<HEADLINE>
HBO, `FRASIER' AND HELEN HUNT WIN EMMYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Will be updated with more winners.)  
(nk) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the sixth year in a row, HBO took the Emmy for
outstanding movie, this time for ``Don King: Only in America.'' The
movie also won for best writing, with a script written by Kario
Salem.
</P>
<P>
   The Emmy for best actor in a movie or mini-series went to Gary
Sinise for ``George Wallace''; the actor had been nominated
previously for his role as Harry Truman in ``Truman.'' The Emmy for
best actress in a movie or mini-series went to Ellen Barkin for her
role in ``Before Women Had Wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the awards had yet to be announced, but the Emmy for
best actress in a comedy series went, for the third consecutive
year, to Helen Hunt of ``Mad About You,'' and the best actor in a
comedy series, for the third time, went to Kelsey Grammer of
``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Late Show with David Letterman'' won for best variety, music
or comedy series.
</P>
<P>
   In an evening noteworthy for the extent to which it reveled in
television's past rather than the immense uncertainty of its
future, Emmy Awards were presented Sunday evening largely to
established shows and a few first-time nominees in the 50th
telecast of the honors.
</P>
<P>
   Camryn Manheim, the earnest lawyer, Ellenor Frutt, in ``The
Practice,'' took the Emmy for best supporting actress in a drama
series. In one of the more memorable acceptance speeches of the
evening, the heavyset Ms. Manheim thanked her friends and
supporters, asked if she could get the autographs of her fellow
nominees, then shouted, ``This is for all the fat girls!''
</P>
<P>
   The Emmy for best supporting actor in a drama went to Gordon
Clapp, Detective Greg Medavoy in ``NYPD Blue.'' It was Ms.
Manheim's first nomination and Clapp's second.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony for the Emmys, given out by the Academy of
Television Arts and Sciences, was held at the Shrine Auditorium in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Kudrow, the sincere, slightly misguided, not always
coherent Phoebe in ``Friends,'' won her first Emmy as best
supporting actress in a comedy series. The best supporting actor in
a comedy went to David Hyde Pierce, the stuffy, emotionally
repressed Miles of ``Frasier.'' It was the second time he has taken
the honor, and he took a moment to particularly note one of his
fellow nominees, Phil Hartman from ``News Radio,'' who was killed
by his wife in late May.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Tolan and Garry Shandling won as best writers in a comedy
series for ``The Larry Sanders Show.'' It was the first Emmy for
Shandling after 19 nominations.
</P>
<P>
   The program was heavier on nostalgia than usual, with a series
of clips and moments commemorating people like the Marx Brothers
and Ed Sullivan and shows like ``Gunsmoke'' and ``Father Knows
Best.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a long standing ovation when Bob Hope, Milton Berle
and Sid Caesar appeared together onstage.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy and television executives were eager to focus on
creative achievements rather than the uncertainty of the future and
squabbles that have taken place behind the scenes for several
years.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, there has been much focus on whether several
records would be set Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
   David Kelley, the writer and producer, has been nominated for
and could win an unprecedented honor by garnering the Emmys for
best comedy, ``Ally McBeal,'' on Fox, and for best drama, ``The
Practice,'' on ABC. No one had previously been nominated in both
categories. These awards were scheduled to be announced late Sunday
evening.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Frasier,'' NBC's highly regarded sitcom, could also break
what many had thought a record as unassailable as Roger Maris' home
run mark by winning a fifth consecutive Emmy as best comedy. That
would mean it had taken the award every year that the series, about
an earnest but fumbling radio therapist, Dr. Frasier Crane, had
been on the air. Last year, ``Frasier'' tied the record of four
Emmys, matching ``Cheers,'' from which ``Frasier'' was spun off.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last year, and even earlier this year, the world of television
was split into bitter factions because of the growing competition
that the cable channels are providing the broadcast networks, which
are struggling financially and losing audience share.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall several network executives suggested that the cable
channels ought to be placed in separate Emmy categories because of
allegations that they can spend far more on things like original
movies than the networks.
</P>
<P>
   This year the dispute took a different form, over whether HBO's
widely acclaimed, 12-part program, ``From the Earth to the Moon,''
about the Apollo space program, qualified as a mini-series.
</P>
<P>
   Meryl Marshall, the Academy's president and an independent
producer, rejected the idea of segregating the cable channels and
then turned down the protest against ``From the Earth to the
Moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did it qualify in the mini-series category, but it
garnered 17 nominations, more than any other program this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
