<HEADLINE>
EARLY UPSETS MAKE COACH-SPEAK SOUND PROPHETIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., Mich., N.Y., Ohio, Texas)  (nk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every college coach utters a version of it early in the season.
How his team has excellent potential, but don't make bowl
reservations yet.
</P>
<P>
   Their teams are young and inexperienced and have holes. They say
it as if they believe it, but when they actually do stumble, they
have a difficult time hiding their surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Since August, Bobby Bowden cautioned that his Florida State
Seminoles were young, with only 10 seniors. His starting
quarterback, the 26-year-old minor league baseball refugee Chris
Weinke, is the first true sophomore he has begun the season with at
the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty stunned,'' Bowden said after North Carolina State
upset his Seminoles by 24-7. Weinke threw a school-record six
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get beat like that, I'm very surprised, surprised how we
fell apart,'' Bowden said. ``Our offense just could not execute at
all. That's the biggest surprise I've got. For some reason, we
couldn't throw the ball and catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame Coach Bob Davie called last week's victory over
Michigan _ one that catapulted the Irish into the top 10 _ a ``big,
big win,'' but he warned that his team was a long way from
contending for a national title. His team did not wait long to
prove the coach right, falling behind by 42-3 in the first half to
an 0-2 Michigan State team on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm embarrassed; this football team's embarrassed,'' Davie
said after Notre Dame's 45-23 loss. ``There's not going to be a
whole lot of talk about it. I think we came in here expecting to
play well, and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan's Lloyd Carr, on the other hand, pretty much kept his
concerns about his defending national co-champion to himself,
allowing only that he voted for Ohio State, his Big Ten rival, as
the nation's No. 1 team. Now his Wolverines are 0-2 after being
shellacked by Syracuse, 38-28, before the largest crowd in college
football history, 111,012, at newly renovated Michigan Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the ship sinks, it goes down fast,'' Wolverines offensive
tackle Jon Jansen said. ``We have to find out where those holes are
and get them patched fast. If you had told me this summer that we'd
be 0-2 at this point, I'd have said there was no way.''
</P>
<P>
   What is not surprising is that Florida State dropped from No. 2
to No. 11 in The Associated Press news media poll. Notre Dame
tumbled from No. 10 to No. 23. And Michigan slid all the way to the
dubious category of ``others receiving votes.''
</P>
<P>
   The upsets make room for some teams not usually tagged as
national-title contenders. In the West, UCLA's 49-31 victory over
Texas, the team's 11th straight victory dating to last season,
showed the Bruins not only have a Heisman Trophy contender in Cade
McNown (339 yards passing and 3 touchdowns), but are also probably
the best team in the region.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, Syracuse's victory over Michigan and near victory
over No. 6 Tennessee last week keep Donovan McNabb alive in the
Heisman race and make the No. 13 Orangemen viable title contenders.
They now settle into their Big East schedule, but their
nonconference schedule suddenly looks pretty good because of an
early October road game against North Carolina State, a newcomer to
the ranking at No. 21.
</P>
<P>
   One of the usual contenders, Nebraska, moved up to No. 3 with a
24-3 victory over California. And it has used its usual soft early
schedule to get over injuries _ five starters are out _ which
threaten its chances of winning its fourth national title in five
years. But how deep are the Cornhuskers?
</P>
<P>
   The starting quarterback, Bobby Newcombe, was sidelined for a
second straight week by a knee injury, and his replacement, Eric
Crouch, left with a hamstring strain after throwing for two
touchdowns. The third-stringer, Monte Christo, however, stepped in
to throw another one.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are banged up; I don't think there is any question about
it,'' said first-year coach Frank Solich. ``I thought the guys that
did play, our backup players, did well. We have some depth on our
team, and it can certainly make us a stronger team as the season
goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Spurrier is also a proponent of soft early scheduling. But
after back-to-back routs of the Citadel and Northeast Louisiana,
his No. 2 Florida Gators head to Knoxville this week to face
Tennessee. In the first year of the Bowl Championship Series,
whichever team loses has a tough climb back to the title game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt if anybody is out yet with one loss,'' Bowden said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
