<SLUG> BC-CLERGY-CLINTON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS LEADERS FACE CONGREGANTS QUESTIONS ON CLINTON SCANDAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``a'' national news file.) 
BY YVETTE CABRERA 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sex scandals aren't usually topics of church
sermons, but clergy across the nation used the Sabbath to focus on
the issue as parishioners struggled to come to terms with a
president who admitted to an extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   Some were faced with questions from church members about how to
explain President Clinton's conduct to children. Some said Clinton
should resign, and a number of religious leaders talked about
atonement.
</P>
<P>
   Pastors such as the Rev. Cecil Murray of the First AME Church in
Los Angeles took the opportunity to teach of sin, repentance and
forgiveness, as Americans continued to reel from details released
Friday about Bill Clinton's sexual affair with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you will find very little if any opposition in the
minority black community to forgiveness,'' Murray said Sunday in a
phone interview from his South Central Los Angeles church.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through his sermon, Murray asked his congregation to
rise. He then spoke of how all should keep in mind that nobody is
without sin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally we have received a request for forgiveness, we have
received a commitment to repentance and our answer is a resounding
yes,'' Murray told his parishioners.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is a good leader who sees people regardless of their
circumstances, said Murray, echoing an opinion voiced by other
leaders in the African-American community.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has made terrible errors in this case and perhaps related
cases, but always on the scale of human values, one weighs the good
against the bad, and only one category fails to regard the good and
that's the total bad,'' Murray said.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Rabbi Elijah Schochet of Shomrei Torah, said much
can be learned from the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal, which is
unfolding during a key period for Jewish synagogues.
</P>
<P>
   Starting next Sunday, Jews will observe the new year, Rosh
Hashana, which begins the Ten Days of Penitence and will end with
Yom Kippur, the Day of Atonement, on Sept. 29.
</P>
<P>
   It is a time of the year when Jewish religious vocabulary is
replete with phrases like sin, repentance and atonement, which make
the Clinton issue all the more salient, Schochet said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very easy for these (phrases) to be abstract concepts,''
Schochet said. ``But all of a sudden there's a real live drama
that's taking place that brings it to the fore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it became a living demonstration of the central human
dilemma that we all face, which would be coming to grips with our
shortcomings, our mistakes in life and what to do about them,''
Schochet said.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous parents in Schochet's suburban synagogue of 750
families have approached him for advice on how to deal with the
questions that their young children have raised about Clinton's
sexual conduct.
</P>
<P>
   It is an issue ``I would say for quite a number of my members,''
Schochet said. ``How does one explain exactly what has
transpired?''
</P>
<P>
   Parents, with children as young as 3 and 4, who are faced with
this same dilemma have approached the Rev. Gary Dickey, pastor of
the First United Methodist Church in the San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a parent who told me, my child wanted to know what oral
sex was,'' said Dickey, who recommends that parents tackle the
touchy subject in a straightforward manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this is the time to talk about these issues with a
child, as young as they may be, because if you don't talk, then
their decisions on what to do is determined by what they hear or
read,'' Dickey said.
</P>
<P>
   Dickey addressed the Clinton scandal in a Sept. 6 sermon but
declined to take sides on the issue of whether Clinton was guilty
or not. Instead, he used the opportunity to discuss morality and
sexual ethics and how this relates to a Christian who has to make
the same kinds of decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to expect from our leadership a good example because
our young people, our society, takes example from that
leadership,'' said Dickey, who did not broach the Clinton issue on
Sunday. ``It wouldn't matter if it was Clinton, Nixon or (Al) Gore.
The person is not the issue here; the issue is the ethics.''
</P>
<P>
   Opinion among Dickey's parishioners on what Clinton should do
now has been varied.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some who say he shouldn't be impeached and others
who say he should,'' Dickey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are willing to forgive Clinton as much as any other
congregation might, but our issue is that forgiveness doesn't
mitigate one's actions. You can be forgiven, but you still have to
take responsibility for your actions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
