<HEADER>
A3152 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DAMATO-ABORTION-NY     09-14 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DAMATO-ABORTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METRO MATTERS: ONE PRIMARY THAT'S NO HELP TO D'AMATO
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ELIZABETH KOLBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas Droleskey is not, he insists, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato's
enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm his adversary,'' he says, pausing to let the distinction
sink in. Still, it is easy to understand how D'Amato might get the
wrong idea.
</P>
<P>
   In each of D'Amato's three previous races for the Senate, he has
had, in addition to the backing of the Republican and Conservative
Parties, the support of the Right to Life Party. Though the party,
with fewer than 50,000 registered voters, is one of the smallest in
the state, it has played an outsized role in the senator's career.
</P>
<P>
   In his last race, D'Amato received 225,000 votes on the Right to
Life line, just enough to carry him to victory over his
Democratic-Liberal opponent, Robert Abrams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without our line,'' said the party's chairwoman, Lena
Harknett, ``he wouldn't be there now.''
</P>
<P>
   This time around, however, Droleskey, a part-time professor of
political science at C.W. Post College on Long Island, is
challenging D'Amato, claiming he is not enough of a true believer
to merit the party's nomination. For the last few months, he has
been using his newsletter, ``Christ or Chaos,'' to criticize the
senator while crisscrossing the state in his Saturn station wagon
urging party members to vote for him instead.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of losing to Droleskey, who received enough votes
at the party's convention in May to automatically win a spot on
Tuesday's primary ballot, has worried D'Amato enough that he has
paid for several mailings to Right to Life voters. But D'Amato has
elected not to stage a full-fledged campaign for the party's
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not that his anti-abortion stand is too weak to
defend; it is that defending it could cost him his seat.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Harknett calls D'Amato's voting record ``excellent,''
saying that ``as far as legislation is concerned, he has been with
us all the time.'' The National Abortion and Reproductive Rights
Action League essentially agrees with this assessment; the senator,
according to its tallies, has voted against abortion rights 91
percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   A pro-D'Amato flier passed out at the Right to Life Party's
convention lists 99 anti-abortion votes the senator has cast,
including 12 to prohibit the use of federal Medicaid funds to
finance abortions, three to ban abortions at U.S. military bases
abroad and one for a constitutional amendment that would have
allowed Congress and the states to outlaw the procedure entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Though often characterized as a legislator whose chief guide to
policy making is a finger to the wind, D'Amato has, with these
votes, clearly defied public opinion. According to a recent
Quinnipiac College poll, half of all New Yorkers believe abortion
should be ``generally available'' to those who want it, while a
third believe it should be available, but under stricter limits.
Only one in six shares D'Amato's view that it should not be
allowed.
</P>
<P>
   It is not D'Amato's voting record on abortion that has attracted
Droleskey's ire. Rather what offends him, he said, are the
political compromises the senator has made with abortion rights
proponents. He points to the senator's votes to confirm judges like
Ruth Bader Ginsburg, the Supreme Court justice, and his support of
politicians like Gov. George Pataki as evidence of the senator's
insufficient commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``D'Amato doesn't care about changing hearts and minds,''
Droleskey declared. ``He cares about winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Droleskey added that D'Amato rarely spoke out about abortion
without being forced to, and generally has sought to say as little
about the issue as possible. Though D'Amato has used various
surrogates to campaign against him, Droleskey said, the senator
himself has refused to be drawn into debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I know,'' Droleskey said, ``he has never even
mentioned my name.'' Numerous calls to D'Amato's campaign
spokesman, Harvey Valentine, seeking a response from the senator to
Droleskey went unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens Tuesday, Droleskey acknowledged that he had no
hope of going on to win a seat in the Senate. When confronted with
the fact that his candidacy could help elect a Democrat favoring
abortion rights, he countered that the Right to Life Party should
not put local victories above the larger cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Third parties,'' he said, ``exist to move issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 0015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
