<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3154 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN--COWBOYS-HNS &LR;      09-14 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN--COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
DENVER _ Troy Aikman's left collarbone cracked, and Chan Gailey's
heart sank. The key to his reworked Cowboys offense was rushed to
an X-ray machine, brought back in jeans and a sling and declared
lost for a month, maybe two.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And as Gailey considered the wreckage of Sunday's 42-23 crash at
Denver, his quarterback's broken bone was, though not the least of
his worries, just one on a long list.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Aikman went down and out, his pain merely added
injury to insult. The Cowboys had been blitzed by the Broncos'
offense enough to remain well off the pace of the NFL's champions.
And a second-half rally to within a chance did little to cheer a
team with a defense as broken as its quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who expected this?'' Aikman said. ``This is the NFL. Nobody
can go into a game saying it's going to be a big shootout.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Cowboys were outgunned from the outset, long before
Aikman was hurt, and Gailey was left with an additional piece to
put back together before heading to New York to face the Giants on
Sept. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Garrett, who played well in Aikman's place Sunday,
throwing for more yards, 113, than in his past two seasons, will
replace Aikman for at least four weeks and as many as eight.
</P>
<P>
   But Aikman's departure Sunday had nothing to do with the
Cowboys' defensive failings.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was hurt, he had contributed nothing to the Cowboys'
pass rush, run defense or pass coverage. And that put him on a par
with much of the Cowboys' defense in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos led 28-14 when Aikman went out, having scored on
each of their first four possessions and with increasing ease.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos showed off both sides of their two-fisted offense as
if back in the Super Bowl, John Elway passing for 268 yards and two
touchdowns and Terrell Davis rushing for 191 yards and three
scores.
</P>
<P>
   Elway also left the game with an injury, but his strained right
hamstring is not expected to keep him out. He compared it to an
injury in 1996 with which he played for four weeks, until a playoff
spot was clinched and he could let it rest.
</P>
<P>
   And if he is given the time he had against the Cowboys' pass
rush Sunday, and could continue to pass against a confused
secondary, he won't need both legs anyway. The Broncos' 35-point
half was the most prolific ever against the Cowboys, as they scored
on all five drives while rolling up 379 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I've ever seen a team go five series and get
five touchdowns in the first half,'' Broncos coach Mike Shanahan
said. ``Any time you score 35 points in a half, five drives, five
touchdowns, you've got to be pleased. Using four wide receivers and
a tight end allowed us to spread the field out and give John some
targets.''
</P>
<P>
   And Elway threw darts. He found tight end Shannon Sharpe flying
past Cowboys safety Darren Woodson for 39 yards and a touchdown on
the Broncos' first possession. He fooled the Cowboys with a play
fake to easily add a 23-yard toss to Sharpe for the fourth score.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Davis sprinted untouched on consecutive plays as if
running wind sprints. He cut left around Dexter Coakley, then
outran the Cowboys' secondary for 63 yards on his first score. And
on the next Denver possession, Davis took a pitch, found a hole up
the middle and took off for 59 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said it all along: Mike Shanahan is an offensive
genius,'' Cowboys cornerback Deion Sanders said. ``He kept us
off-balance. And every time we made adjustments, he just made
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cowboys corner Kevin Smith: ``They spread us out, and we
couldn't match up. They had a great game, a great game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Cowboys stayed within reach. The Cowboys scored on three
consecutive possessions, Aikman passing to Ernie Mills for a
36-yard touchdown and Emmitt Smith scoring on a four-yard run. Even
on the possession in which Aikman was hurt, Garrett passed to
Michael Irvin for 32 yards to set up a Richie Cunningham field
goal.
</P>
<P>
   But each time the Cowboys would make a move, the Broncos'
offense would answer, as if nothing it had previously shown could
offer a clue as to how it could be stopped. Denver rolled 80 yards
to finish the half, Elway completing four of four passes for 71
yards before sneaking in from the one.
</P>
<P>
   And after the Cowboys drove well but settled for two field goals
to move within 35-23 early in the fourth quarter, the Broncos
erased any doubt. Elway began the drive completing three passes,
straining his hamstring on the third. But Bubby Brister came in to
toss a 38-yard pass to Ed McCaffrey, and Davis scored from the
three for a 19-point Broncos lead with 7:33 left.
</P>
<P>
   And as a measure of where the Cowboys stand early in the season
after last year's 6-10 record, the difference between the
rebuilding Cowboys and the teams at the top semed clear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
