<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-TERRORIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT AIDED BY FRENCH INTELLECTUALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ For two decades, the police in Austria and Germany had
searched for the accused terrorist Hans-Joachim Klein, who was
arrested last week as he sipped beer at a cafe in the Norman
village of Ste.-Honorine-la-Guillaume, where he had had been living
for five years under an alias.
</P>
<P>
   But there were others, prominent people in France and Germany,
who knew where he had been all along, kept his true identity secret
and even paid his rent, they acknowledged in a letter published in
Le Monde on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Among them were the French philosopher Andre Glucksmann and
Daniel Cohn-Bendit, who holds dual French and German citizenship.
As ``Danny the Red,'' Cohn-Bendit was a leader of the French
student uprisings in 1968. After being expelled to Germany then, he
met Klein, who is German, in radical student circles of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hans-Joachim Klein was arrested not far from his Norman
domicile only a few days before he planned to surrender,'' said
their letter, which was also signed by four other people, including
the co-author of a book that Klein wrote renouncing terrorism in
1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many of us in France and Germany who helped him by
protecting him against threats of death and vengeance by former
`friends' turned murderers, by giving him a minimum of support,
renting the house he lived in and paying the rent, and by trying to
help keep his spirits up during his long isolation,'' the letter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Klein was wanted by the authorities in Germany and Austria for
taking part in a spectacular kidnapping of OPEC oil ministers in
1975 that left three people dead and was led by Ilich Ramirez
Sanchez, the international terrorist who called himself Carlos.
Ramirez was captured by French police in Sudan in 1994 and was
sentenced to life imprisonment after a trial here last December.
</P>
<P>
   Klein, shot in the stomach during the OPEC attack, declared his
break with terrorism in a 1978 interview with a French journalist,
Jean-Marcel Bouguereau, one of the signers of the letter published
in Le Monde. A year later, he explained himself further in a book
entitled ``Mercenary Death,'' for which Cohn-Bendit wrote the
preface.
</P>
<P>
   ``Klein in fact not only renounced violence, he denounced its
errors and perversions,'' Cohn-Bendit and the others wrote. ``By
his book and through numerous conversations, he revealed the
reality of the distortion of `armed struggle.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cohn-Bendit, who lives in Frankfurt and plans to run on the
German Green Party ticket for a seat in the European Parliament
next year, could not be reached for comment over the weekend. But
last week Cohn-Bendit suggested that the arrest had more to do with
Chancellor Helmut Kohl's struggle for re-election in Germany's
elections on Sept. 27 than with justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The German authorities knew where he was all along,''
Cohn-Bendit said, and a German lawyer for Klein said that he had
been in negotiations with prosecutors in Frankfurt on a surrender
for his client since March.
</P>
<P>
   But the French police, acting on an old warrant from German
authorities, surprised Klein at his usual village cafe on Tuesday
night. He surrendered without a struggle and was arraigned and held
for possible extradition to either Germany or Austria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 0022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3160 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-WALLACE-2NDTAKE-     09-14 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WALLACE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: presidential election. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the 1972 race, he was running even stronger in the Democratic
presidential primaries. He rattled the party's establishment with a
second-place finish in Wisconsin and a rapid ascent in the polls.
He also won primaries in Maryland and Michigan on May 16, but got
the news in a hospital bed, having been shot and paralyzed on the
day before the balloting.
</P>
<P>
   The injury from Bremer's bullet became a ``thorn in my flesh,''
Wallace later said, and the truncated campaign became a thorn in
his psyche. He died believing that had he not been shot, popular
appeal would have forced the Democratic Party to put him on the
ticket in 1972 to keep Nixon from sweeping the Sun Belt and
blue-collar enclaves in the Middle West and Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace ran again in 1976. From the start, aides noticed that
the applause dwindled once crowds saw his shiny wheelchair. Wallace
noticed it, too, and in private he disputed friends who reminded
him that Franklin Roosevelt had won despite crutches and
wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Wallace told his confidant Oscar Adams, ``they elected
Roosevelt, but they didn't watch him on television every night
getting hauled on a plane like he was half-dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The death of Wallace's presidential dream came just before the
Illinois primary, when he dropped out and endorsed a more modern
Southerner with no segregationist baggage, Gov. Jimmy Carter of
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace wanted to be remembered for his shining moment in 1972
and the Main Street themes he brought to prominence. Dan Carter, a
professor of history at Emory University and author of the most
detailed Wallace biography, ``The Politics of Rage,'' supports the
claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to conceive of what American politics of the
1960s, 70s and 80s would be like without George Wallace,'' Carter
said in a 1994 interview. ``I don't think there's a single issue
that Nixon and Reagan talk of in terms of social issues that he
doesn't get to first.''
</P>
<P>
   In this view, Wallace's presidential campaigns prefigured, in an
especially abrasive way, a large portion of the country's politics
of later years. Wallace was the first major political figure in his
generation to exploit the antipathy toward Washington that went on
to be a prime force in politics from coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   He was also surely the first in his generation to galvanize the
white, working-class voters later labeled as Reagan Democrats. And
he was the first nationally known politician of that generation to
put such raucous emphasis on race, crime, welfare and other issues
that still loom large, if less crudely, on the political landscape.
</P>
<P>
   After he retired as governor, Wallace used interviews to push
relentlessly at the theme that he was the real inventor of
Reaganism. Starting in 1979, he also undertook a campaign of
apology and revisionist explanation intended to erase the word
``racist'' from his epitaph.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that his early devotion to segregation was based on
his reading of the Constitution and the Bible and was
misinterpreted as a racist hatred of black people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake in the sense that I should have clarified my
position more,'' he said in his last term as governor. ``I was
never saying anything that reflected upon black people, and I'm
very sorry it was taken that way.''
</P>
<P>
   That Wallace died haunted by race is appropriate to his life
story _ one of Faulknerian perversity embodying the old themes of
guilt and a steady, if clumsy, Snopsian aspiration.
</P>
<P>
   George Corley Wallace Jr. was born on Aug. 25, 1919, in Clio,
Ala., a cotton town in Barbour County, where mule-drawn wagons were
as common as cars on the unpaved main street. His father was the
wastrel son of a beloved local doctor. His mother, Mozelle Smith
Wallace, had survived abandonment by her mother and a depressing
girlhood in an Episcopal orphanage at Mobile.
</P>
<P>
   Like his father, George Jr. was quick with his fists and drawn
to politics. Calling himself the ``Barbour Bantam,'' he won two
Golden Gloves titles while in high school. As a 15-year-old
legislative page at the Capitol in Montgomery, he stood on the gold
star marking the spot where Jefferson Davis was sworn as president
of the Confederacy and where, by tradition, Alabama governors have
taken the oath of office ever since. It was the seminal moment of
his youth. Man and boy, George Wallace revered that spot, so much
so that as governor he ordered state troopers to encircle it so
that a visitor, Attorney General Robert Kennedy, could not put a
desecrating Yankee foot atop it.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1937, on the oak-shaded Tuscaloosa campus of the
University of Alabama, that George Wallace began to define what he
would become politically. He arrived in the same shiny suit he had
worn as a page in Montgomery, but Tuscaloosa was a congenial place
for poor, ambitious country boys. And by tradition, it was a
virtual boot camp for future governors and senators. Young Wallace
won election as president of the freshman class. He never won
another student office, but his campaign to beat the fraternity
machine with a coalition of independents and out-of-state students
whetted his permanent taste for underdog politics.
</P>
<P>
   The other leitmotifs of his Alabama career _ cronyism and
betrayal _ emerged at the university. He acquired the hangers-on
who staffed his later efforts, and he made an unlikely, but
ill-fated friendship with Frank Johnson, a handsome law student
from Winston County, a Unionist stronghold in northern Alabama that
seceded from Alabama when Alabama left the Union. Johnson was a
Republican, Wallace an ardent New Deal Democrat. Johnson joked
about someday being a federal judge and Wallace about being
governor. But the big wheels on campus tended to dismiss Wallace's
ambitions as comical.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 0023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DEMOCRATS-PRIMARY-     09-14 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DEMOCRATS-PRIMARY-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATEWIDE CANDIDATES HITCH RIDES ON LOCAL COATTAILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a suite of offices above a storefront in the Crown
Heights section of Brooklyn, the campaign headquarters of
Assemblyman Clarence Norman Jr. was buzzing Sunday afternoon.
Teen-agers rushed to pick up campaign literature to hand out in the
neighborhood, while another cluster of campaign volunteers worked
the telephones, making sure that the 200 or so Election Day
volunteers had their marching orders.
</P>
<P>
   Norman, who is also the Brooklyn Democratic Party chairman, is
in the thick of a re-election battle, but the bustle at his
campaign headquarters was not only a get-out-the-vote effort for
him in Tuesday's Democratic primary, but for a string of other
candidates, including Charles Hynes, a candidate for governor, and
Eliot Spitzer, who is running for state attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, alliances between such local races as Norman's
re-election effort and a statewide campaign would be considered a
plus. But in this year's Democratic primary, where so many
candidates in statewide races are from New York City, linking one
campaign's get-out-the-vote effort with another's is considered
crucial to the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   In the primary for attorney general, for example, all the
candidates _ state Sen. Catherine Abate, G. Oliver Koppell and Evan
Davis, along with Spitzer _ are from New York City. And that
pattern is similar in the races for governor and U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom for a Democratic primary has been to
focus on New York City and one or two urban centers elsewhere in
the state. But that strategy has been turned upside down because
all the New York City candidates have balkanized the electorate
there. As a result, they have had to scramble for votes wherever
they can get them.
</P>
<P>
   That has made every connection more important than usual,
campaign officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's campaign, with its deep war chest, has been
particularly notable for spending lavishly to win the support of
local Democratic clubs throughout the state. By contributing to the
campaigns of candidates for the Assembly and other local races, he
has earned the support of a host of foot soldiers, like those in
Norman's Thurgood Marshall Democratic Club.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff can be found in Norman's headquarters at the club.
Its ivory walls are filled with Spitzer's red-and-blue posters, and
a team of campaign volunteers marched out Sunday afternoon with
campaign literature bearing the names of Spitzer, a former
prosecutor, and Hynes, the Brooklyn district attorney, along with
Norman's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work together as a team,'' Norman said. ``And it benefits
all of us.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Abate, one of Spitzer's rivals for the attorney general
nomination, has focused her efforts on a combination of telephone
calls to likely voters and door-to-door visits by volunteers,
emphasizing Manhattan residents, women and Italian-American voters,
particularly in upstate areas, according to her Martin Brennan, her
campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they are done right, the get-out-the-vote operation
should be a combination of sophisticated organization and
grass-roots grunt work,'' Brennan said. ``There is not a lot of
thinking, just a lot of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Candidates also have gone out of the way to court unions, whose
support is always considered an important force in a Democratic
primary because of their ability to make mass mailings, organize
telephone banks and turn out the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In the race for the Democratic nomination for Senate, Mark
Green, New York City's public advocate and one of three major
candidates in the race, began courting upstate Democrats more than
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who repeatedly closes his remarks by saying that he
believes the race will be decided by less than 10,000 votes, was
rewarded for his efforts last spring when he was endorsed by the
Democratic Rural Conference, a coalition of Democratic chairmen
from the state's 41 smallest counties.
</P>
<P>
   Well beyond the bragging rights, Green expects the rural
conference members to help him turn out the voters on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the campaign, Peter Vallone, the speaker of the New
York City Council and a candidate for the Democratic gubernatorial
nomination, won the support of the Democratic county organizations
in the Bronx and in his home borough, Queens. Those endorsements
are now bearing fruit, Vallone's campaign strategists said, because
of the large number of highly competitive races in the two
boroughs. There are several heated battles for the Assembly and
state Senate, and in some cases Vallone is supported by candidates
who are competing for the same seat.
</P>
<P>
   Local races also have the involvement of community groups and
established organizations _ an additional attraction for statewide
candidates. In local races where there are no official links with a
gubernatorial or Senate campaign, many of the statewide operations
are focusing their get-out-the-vote effort on areas where highly
competitive races are expected to draw a higher-than-average number
of voters to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Many statewide campaigns are calling voters and distributing
literature in the 9th Congressional District, which stretches from
Forest Hills, Queens, into southern Brooklyn. In that contest, four
Democratic officials _ City Councilmen Anthony Weiner and Noach
Dear and Assembly members Melinda Katz and Daniel Feldman _ are
running for the seat being vacated by Rep. Charles Schumer, who is
running for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Another such campaign is the race for a state Senate seat
representing the West Side of Manhattan. The incumbent, Franz
Leichter, is not running for re-election, and there is a spirited
campaign between Edward Schneiderman, a lawyer and Democratic
district leader and Daniel O'Donnell, a lawyer who is president of
a Democratic club and brother of Rosie O'Donnell, the entertainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statewide candidates hope that they can get some of the heat
given off by the friction of local races,'' said Jeffrey Plaut, a
partner at Global Strategies Group, a political consulting
organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
