<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-PRIMARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NY SENATE RACE PITS THREE DEMOCRATS IN TWO TV DEBATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With less than 48 hours to go until their primary,
the Democratic candidates for Senate met in their first televised
debates of the campaign Sunday, two mannerly encounters in which
they squabbled over fund raising but mostly agreed on both the
shortcomings of Sen. Alfonse D'Amato and how a senator from New
York should vote in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day of smiles and first names as the candidates _
Geraldine Ferraro, Mark Green and Charles Schumer _ offered voters
a generally cordial discussion of politics and policy, interrupted
by only the occasional disagreement. The day precisely reflected
the tone of the entire Senate campaign in New York and left little
doubt that the 1998 contest would be remembered, at least in tone,
as the opposite of the antagonistic Democratic contest of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate debates came on a day packed with politicking. In
another television studio, the Democratic candidates for the
nomination for governor met in their final debate, in which two of
them, Peter Vallone and Betsy McCaughey Ross, argued over Vallone's
commitment to abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, candidates for state attorney general and lieutenant
governor campaigned for support, shaking hands, visiting street
fairs on a warm late-summer afternoon and talking to any television
camera or reporter in sight.
</P>
<P>
   The comparative rush of last-minute politicking signaled the
approach of Tuesday's Democratic primary, the conclusion of what
several Democrats suggested were some of the quietest statewide
primary contests in a generation. As the campaigns went into their
final weekend, the candidates found themselves competing for
attention, and usually without success, with the investigation of
President Clinton. Fittingly, Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton
will come to New York on Monday, the eve of the primary, for a day
of fund raising, in the Clintons' first trip since the release of
the independent counsel's report on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate debates were clearly the most significant events of
the day, both because they offered viewers their first chance to
see the three major Democratic Senate candidates on the same stage
and because the Senate race is one of the few that has attracted
national attention _ D'Amato, a Republican seeking a fourth term,
is seen by some analysts as particularly vulnerable this year.
</P>
<P>
   Until Sunday, the three major Democratic candidates in the race
had only met twice for debate, in both cases upstate and not
televised. Schumer, a congressman from Brooklyn, and Green, the New
York City public advocate, had pushed for additional debates, but
Ms. Ferraro, a former congresswoman from Queens who ran for vice
president in 1984, had declined.
</P>
<P>
   Although the primary remained by all accounts volatile and
competitive, there were indications Sunday that some state
politicians were already looking beyond Tuesday to the general
election ahead. Over the weekend, D'Amato's campaign sent out a
mailing attacking Schumer's voting record, a signal that D'Amato
considered Schumer _ and not Ms. Ferraro, as he once did _ his more
likely opponent.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Schumer, reflecting confidence in his campaign,
quietly changed the tag line on his primary advertisements to a
theme that is intended for general election use if he wins the
primary: ``He'll make New York proud again.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in the debates Sunday, he offered what his aides said
would be a central thrust of his attack on D'Amato should he win.
``Al D'Amato is not a legislator,'' Schumer said during the debate,
which was on WABC-TV and was sponsored by the League of Women
Voters. ``You cannot name a single piece of legislation he's passed
in 18 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer was the target of some of the only attacks of Sunday's
debate. Ms. Ferraro and Green assailed the congressman for the
aggressive fund raising that had allowed him to raise the $13
million that financed a saturation television campaign that both
his opponents said accounted for polls showing Schumer on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer responded by presenting himself as a champion of
restrictions on fund raising, and sought to differentiate himself
from D'Amato, who is also known as a tireless fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fund raising is totally different than Senator D'Amato,''
Schumer said, prompting a burst of laughter from an audience that
was largely made up of political supporters of all three
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer paused for an uncomfortable moment and then pushed
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud of the fund raising we have done,'' he said. ``We
have had 65,000 contributions from all over the country. Our
average contribution was $100.''
</P>
<P>
   At both the WABC debate and a later one with Gabe Pressman on
WNBC-TV, Green and Ms. Ferraro belittled Schumer on that score,
saying that he was a member of the House Banking Committee and thus
the beneficiary of contributions from banks and other financial
institutions with a clear interest in influencing his votes.
``Congressman Schumer is saying that he wants to change the system
that he milks reminds me of Elmer Gantry denouncing sin,'' Green
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ferraro said she would make campaign finance changes a
priority if she is elected to the Senate. ``Is it corrupt?'' she
asked. ``I don't know. But it certainly gives the perception of
corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, there were signs that both Ms. Ferraro and Green,
if scornful of Schumer's financial practices, were also envious of
his success. ``I envy Chuck a little bit,'' said Ms. Ferraro, who
has experienced fund-raising difficulties during her campaign. ``I
wish I had more money''
</P>
<P>
   When Pressman noted to Green that he, too, had received some
money from political action committees, the public advocate grinned
and said, ``I wish I could have gotten more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
