<HEADER>
A3175 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PARADE-SLUR-900(2T     09-14 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PARADE-SLUR-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKFACE INCIDENT LEAVES RESIDENTS WITH MIXED FEELINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wearing blackface and Afro wigs, the men who piled
into a pickup truck for the Labor Day parade in Broad Channel,
Queens, were trying to win a trophy. For decades, parade organizers
have awarded trophies for categories like ``cutest baby'' or ``most
popular pet,'' and the men had won ``funniest float'' for nine
straight years.
</P>
<P>
   Within Broad Channel, a narrow island in Jamaica Bay where
nearly everyone is white, the men had won with past themes like
``Gooks of Hazzard,'' ``Hasidic Park'' and ``Happy Gays.'' This
year's theme _ ``Black to the Future, Broad Channel, 2098'' _
stayed true to their formula of mocking minorities. They bounced
basketballs and tossed slices of watermelon.
</P>
<P>
   Would the formula have worked again? No one will ever know. The
float had not yet reached the judges when the Labor Day storms
suddenly interrupted the parade. Most people in Broad Channel first
saw it the next night when an amateur videotape was broadcast on
television. It showed one of the men mimicking a horrific hate
crime: the June killing of a black man in Texas, dragged behind a
pickup truck by three white men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you,'' said Denise Horan, a Broad Channel
resident, ``it hurt like hell to see that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet after a week of fierce outside condemnation and scrutiny,
there is still ambivalence in Broad Channel. Many residents have
spoken out, expressing shame and horror even as they defend their
``small town'' against charges of racism. On Saturday, a New York
City police officer, suspended for joining the float, publicly
apologized, declaring ``I'm not a racist.'' Four other men also
came forward and apologized.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is sorry. There are people seething with anger,
unapologetic for something they consider a harmless joke. Nearly
everyone is furious that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is trying to
dismiss the police officer and two city firefighters who joined the
float. They are angrier still at the mayor for withdrawing city
money from the volunteer fire department and revoking the sale of
city land for a new firehouse. The ``vollies,'' who sponsored the
Labor Day parade, are the heart of Broad Channel.
</P>
<P>
   ``First time I ever agreed with that Al Sharpton,'' said Tommy
Mink, 67, a retired construction worker. ``He always accuses
Giuliani of overreaching. We have an awful lot of hate for the city
and for Giuliani now. He's playing politics.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was younger, Mink said he rode in a float that lampooned
civil rights advocates in the South. ``Every year they have a
parade and something gets in there,'' he said of the Labor Day
tradition. ``Whether it's a black float or a Jew float. It's all in
fun. They may call it prejudice, but it isn't prejudice. If there's
any town without prejudice, this is it.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad Channel, Mink explained, ``didn't have to have any''
prejudice because it has few, if any, black residents. Instead,
many of the families are Irish, German or Italian, some having
lived on the island for generations. It is isolation from the throb
of the city that many residents seek; Broad Channel is tethered to
New York City by bridge and by politics, but not by spirit. Visible
in the distance beyond Jamaica Bay, the Manhattan skyline rises
above the marshes on clear days, as remote and otherworldly as the
moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a small town in New York City,'' said Dan Tubridy, whose
family has lived on the island since the 1920s. ``We're very proud
of that, very happy about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ethnic roar of the city, the encroaching threat of dark,
unfamiliar faces, was apparently the focus of the group's attempt
at parody. ``What they were spoofing was that in the year 2098
their community, which is all white now, would have to have
blacks,'' said Marvyn Kornberg, a lawyer for four of the men.
``They were spoofing their own community.''
</P>
<P>
   Such fears, and resentments, are not hard to find in Broad
Channel. ``This was a bunch of black guys who were supposed to be
drunk coming back from a basketball game,'' a 43-year-old man said
of the float. ``Where was that racist? That's the whole idea of it
_ to be like `Saturday Night Live.' Chris Rock can do it. Why can't
we?''
</P>
<P>
   The man, a white construction worker who refused to give his
name, said he left Brooklyn for Broad Channel about 15 years ago
when his once-white neighborhood, Cypress Hills, began to change.
His parents, he said, are ``trapped'' there. Now, he fears the same
could happen to Broad Channel. The island's first real-estate
office, Century 21, opened in May, and a sign hanging in the window
promises, ``Houses Bought, All Ca$h, any condition.'' He said
brokers had called residents, searching for sellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever seen blockbusting before?'' asked the man, who
lives on Cross Bay Boulevard, the community's main thoroughfare.
``You pay anything you need to pay to get the neighborhood
moving.'' He wondered aloud whether Century 21 officials had
videotaped the float, an assertion denied by a Century 21 manager,
Francine Hamill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not discriminate,'' she said. ``I think the incident
that happened is in very poor taste.'' She said her office had
called residents to look for dilapidated or undeveloped property.
But she did not mind the publicity. ``Not too many people know
about Broad Channel,'' she said. ``Now it's on everybody's lips.
It's not going to hurt me.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For decades, people on Broad Channel leased their land from the
city, which flirted with the idea of making it a park or a nature
preserve. Only in March 1995 did the city finally sell residents
the last parcels. Until then, many people could not get mortgages
or improvement loans for houses built on land they did not own.
Still, they stayed, many of them city employees who said they were
drawn by the salt air and quiet living.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know everybody,'' said one white resident, a Fordham
University student who refused to give his name. ``You can go over
to your neighbor's house and ask for bread or cheese if you don't
have any. It's nice when you see somebody in the street and they
say hello to you and you say hello to them.''
</P>
<P>
   What infuriates so many people is the harm the parade has
brought to the Broad Channel Volunteer Fire Department and
Ambulance Corps. Ray Holloway, who lives on Cross Bay Boulevard,
said the ``vollies'' have a waiting list. Affixed to many front
doors are small stickers that say, ``We Care, We Gave,'' indicating
a household that contributed to the fire department. With only
sporadic help from city fire trucks, the vollies handle more than
200 calls a year, including many on Labor Day, when Holloway said
they helped him with his collapsed chimney.
</P>
<P>
   To raise money every year, the fire department rotates
sponsorship of the Labor Day parade with officials of the local
youth athletic league. The parade is part of a weekend ``Mardi
Gras'' celebration, replete with parties and dances. Now, Giuliani
has canceled the city's $6,100 contribution to the volunteers and
revoked a deal to sell a piece of city property as a site for a new
firehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents accused the mayor of trying to appease his
critics over the tactics used by police at the end of a Harlem
youth rally on Sept. 5. ``I'm very upset that the firehouse is
taking the fall for it,'' Ms. Horan said. ``They should come down
here when we're in the middle of a bad winter storm and they're on
boats rescuing people out of their houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the volunteer fire department refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the ``Black to the Future'' float, the Broad Channel
parade was benign. Children rode in floats titled ``Little
Rascals'' and ``The Wizard of Oz.'' Some teen-agers wore Spice
Girls costumes. There were bagpipers and school bands and a
procession of babies in strollers. In one float, a woman
masqueraded as Monica Lewinsky while a man impersonating President
Clinton yelled, ``I didn't do it! I didn't do it!''
</P>
<P>
   Then, lastly, came ``Black to the Future.'' The group apparently
registered only minutes before the start of the parade. Kornberg,
the lawyer, said the man who jumped behind the truck as if it were
dragging him did so without telling the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The float was definitely in very poor taste,'' said Kathleen
Holloway, Ray Holloway's wife. ``No one is going to deny that, but
the people involved aren't horrible people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To say that everybody in Broad Channel is racist, and to say
we bring up our children to be prejudiced, is not right,'' she
added. ``Was it a racist act? I don't know. Are they racists? I
don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   One person who did see the ``Black to Future'' float, a
23-year-old white man, had watched the parade in front of Eddie B's
Bar. He said the float ``got out of control'' but called it just a
joke. ``They make fun of the Jews and the gays, and no one
complained about it as far as the city or the media,'' said the
man, who refused to give his name. ``And since they make fun of the
blacks, they make a big deal out of it. How did they hurt
anybody?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 0041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
