<HEADER>
A3180 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-EMMYS-ANALYSIS-LAD     09-14 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-EMMYS-ANALYSIS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMMYS USE COMMAND OF TV TO CELEBRATE MEDIUM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY   KEITH MARDER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The television industry gets together to
congratulate itself in an annual ritual called the Emmy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   It's a wonder there isn't a rash of dislocated shoulders the
morning after.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday at the Shrine Auditorium, the television industry had
reason to celebrate. Its 50th Prime-time Emmy Awards show was a
time to reflect on how it has grown and what it has done best.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Oscars, which bogged down its 70th Award show with a
roll call of past winners, television knows how to do television.
It pulled off its self-tribute with an exciting range of historical
pieces. (Also, unlike the Oscars, the Emmys ended on time.)
</P>
<P>
   We saw whimsy and tragedy, improvements in cultural diversity
and the mushrooming of channels.
</P>
<P>
   If ever the changes in television were in question, consider
that Milton Berle and Katie Holmes (``Dawson's Creek'') appeared on
the same stage, we were reminded that Lesley Ann Warren and R&AMP;B
sensation Brandy both appeared as Cinderella, that the same box
that brought you a man landing on the moon also showed ``Mr. Ed.''
We also learned who shot J.R. and who shot JFK the same way.
</P>
<P>
   And as the country has grown up and acquired a higher tolerance
for racy material, that is what television has delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different world,'' said Sid Caesar, who was honored
along with fellow comedy legends Berle and Bob Hope. ``It's
actually a different universe. We couldn't say `pregnant.' Pregnant
was a dirty word. We could say `with child' or `expecting,' but
`pregnant' was dirty. Today ...'' he laughed.
</P>
<P>
   The record-long, four-hour Emmy broadcast unleashed by executive
producer Don Mischer and director Louis J. Horvitz efficiently and
effectively told the story of television with devices such as the
top 10 television moments of all time, time-line trivia questions
and a performance by percussion/dance troupe STOMP with perfectly
timed television clips running on large screens behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (space shuttle) Challenger disaster and those other great
moments are spectacular,'' said Mark Tinker, who won an Emmy for
outstanding director of a drama series. ``And the goodbyes are very
touching. The 50 years of television gets you right here.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a broadcast runs the risk of being didactic and ponderous,
but the reasonably fast-moving show offered enough eye candy to
keep even the notoriously short-attention-span viewing audience
entertained.
</P>
<P>
   Sure some of the segments fell short. Interviews with ``real
viewers'' were too slickly produced and packaged, losing any
spontaneity.
</P>
<P>
   The top 10 list, which was voted on by television historians and
journalists, left enough area for debate. For instance, the
premiere of ``Hill Street Blues'' ranked third, ahead of the
Kennedy assassination, Johnny Carson's final ``Tonight Show'' and
the Challenger explosion. ``Hill Street'' may have been
cutting-edge television, but that episode is not exactly one of
those events where you knew where you where when you heard the
news.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night's Emmy broadcast may not be remembered as one of
the great moments in television, but its four-hour tour of the
medium's greatest hits was a pleasant trip down memory lane. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
