<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-REDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENES' NO-HIT ATTEMPT FALLS JUST SHORT IN 9TH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ It had been a few days since Mark McGwire came and
went, homerless, and so it was left to Andy Benes to produce some
magic on a field that could tell some stories if it could talk.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the Cincinnati Reds, the Diamondbacks right-hander was on
the brink of a no-hitter, cheered on by a tidy gathering of 17,741
at Cinergy Field, which used to be Riverfront Stadium, which used
to be the home of larger crowds, not to mention legendary
individuals and record-holders, Hall of Famers and collective world
champions.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire didn't come close to hitting home run No. 63 in two
games Wednesday and Thursday, but now here was Benes brushing up
against something special. With retired jerseys and other reminders
of past Reds glory glued to the outfield wall behind him, Benes was
looking in at Sean Casey, a young, hard-hitting first baseman, only
two outs away from what Diamondbacks pitching coach Mark Connor
called ``the pinnacle.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey, savvy for a rookie, worked the count to 3-2. Then he
swung at an inside fastball that Benes meant to throw outside and
lined it to right field for the first _ and only _ Reds' hit. Benes
got a nice hand. Reggie Sanders, the previous hitter who had
walked, went to second. And the hitter after Casey, Barry Larkin,
walked to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Benes had thrown 138 pitches on a broiling afternoon and had to
come out. Gregg Olson came in and threw a double-play ball to end
the Diamondbacks' four-game losing streak with a combined
one-hitter and a 5-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' said Benes, staked to the lead on two-run
homers by Jay Bell and Tony Batista, and Kelly Stinnett's RBI
double. ``You get to the ninth inning, you think you've got a
chance. It was fun to watch the reaction of my teammates. No one
would talk to me. Except Jay Bell. He was making fun of me because
I struck out three times.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell, the Diamondbacks' second baseman, said he doesn't believe
in the superstition of not mentioning a no-hitter or even talking
to the pitcher. But that wasn't it. He simply wasn't aware of what
was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know,'' he said. ``He (Benes) had something like
three walks early. I was walking off the field and we were talking,
and I looked up to see how many hits we had. I saw four, and then I
saw none. I really wasn't paying attention.''
</P>
<P>
   This was about the sixth inning, Bell said, but he kept talking
to Benes, who got through the seventh and then the eighth,
surviving Bret Boone's deep fly ball to center. Benes himself said
he didn't start to seriously think about the circumstances until
the sixth. Then he realized, ``Hey, they don't have any hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Benes conceded he was far from overpowering, although he did
have command of his four pitches _ fastball, slider, curve and
change-up. He struck out six and walked five. There was talk of
plate umpire C.B. Bucknor's inconsistent strike zone, but not from
Benes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like it was anything spectacular,'' he said. ``I
walked a bunch of guys. For the most part, I changed speeds and
threw the ball on both sides of the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey, who had hit three homers in three games prior to being
intentionally walked as a pinch-hitter on Saturday, flew out deep
to center, flied out to left and struck out in his first three
at-bats. On the fly to left, he was jammed on a fastball similar to
the one he hit to break up the no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he jumped on the pitch from Benes, who admitted he
was tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad,'' Manager Buck Showalter said. ``He (Benes) had
a great outing.''
</P>
<P>
   Benes, who is from Evansville, Ind., about 3{ hours away,
reminded Casey about the earlier pitch when the two passed each
other underneath the stands after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice job, man,'' Casey told Benes. ``Great job.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sanders walked before him, Casey thought, ``We might be
going down in history pretty soon.'' This sort of notoriety he
didn't need.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could really feel the fans getting into it,'' Casey said.
``A lot of emotion. But, as the opposing team, you've got to do
your job. . . . The 3-2 pitch, he just left it right over the
plate. I think it was his only mistake of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Benes, who lost a no-hitter while pitching for the San Diego
Padres in 1994 when Rico Brogna of the New York Mets led off the
eighth inning with a double, won his 13th game to tie a record for
victories by an expansion pitcher. Tampa Bay's Rolando Arrojo also
tied the mark and, like Benes, will get a couple more starts.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since getting bombed by the Mets on Aug. 22, Benes has been
outstanding. In his past four starts, he has given up three earned
runs over 31 innings to closely resemble the pitcher the
Diamondbacks thought they were getting when he signed a substantial
free-agent contract in February. Benes already has exceeded 200
innings for the fifth time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been the steady guy we felt we got,'' Connor said. ``He's
our guy, the workhorse of the staff. The No. 1 guy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
