<HEADER>
A3190 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-SEAHAWKS-AZ     09-14 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-SEAHAWKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURTIN' FOR CERTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Only two down, 14 to go, and already the Cardinals are
90 percent scar tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team hurts a lot right now,'' Coach Vince Tobin said.
``We're licking our wounds.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a young team that could respond two ways to two crushing
road losses to open the season, including a 33-14 thumping by
Seattle on Sunday at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody will be saying bad things about us,'' said Pro Bowl
left tackle Lomas Brown, one of the Cardinals offensive captains.
``We have to hang in there. This week is huge. We are a team that
is searching. We want to win badly. Things are just not going right
for us, not right at all. We've got to win this week, point blank.
No ifs, ands, or buts. Have to.''
</P>
<P>
   The season, already on the line, comes down to whether the
Cardinals can put their pain behind and their vision ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Four seemingly winnable games are upcoming in the most
Cardinal-friendly portion of the schedule, beginning with Sunday's
home opener against NFC East foe Philadelphia. Also ahead are St.
Louis, Oakland and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``How good we are will be determined by how well we handle
adversity,'' said Pro Bowl cornerback Aeneas Williams, a defensive
captain. ``That is what's going to decide the rest of our season.
It's to our advantage that we have so many young guys here now
because they're coming from winning college programs. They don't
come with the stigma of, `Here we go again.' I'm hearing guys
saying, `Let's find a way, let's get some wins, let's get something
going here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals veterans agree it is critical that they remember
they are a growing team with talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still do have a chance,'' said outside linebacker Jamir
Miller. ``When it's over, I'll be the first to let you all know
it's over. But it's not. There's not as big a difference in talent
as it has appeared. There can't be any more showings like this,
though. ''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have to begin asking hard questions of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Have they overestimated their talent? The young offensive
linemen are taking a particularly tough beating.
</P>
<P>
   Is the coaching staff getting the job done? Going back to the
6-6 point of the 1996 season, the Cardinals have dropped 17 of
their past 22 games under Tobin and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   Or can a rough start be chalked up to facing two tough foes, on
the road, shorthanded (injured starters Aaron Graham and Tony
McCombs did not suit up)?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, attitude and character are as important as physical
ability,'' said fullback Larry Centers. ``Right now, we need to
lean on our character. Our backs are to the wall already but all is
not lost. We have to realize that.''
</P>
<P>
   Falling behind big, early, is no boost to confidence. It was as
close as 20-0 at halftime only because the Seahawks managed only
three points out of drives to the Cardinals 34 , 12 and 2-yard
lines.
</P>
<P>
   While the Cardinals bristle at the suggestion that they're the
same old team that has given the Valley 10 [ non-winning seasons,
they would be hard-pressed to refute the evidence Sunday pointing
to classic Cardinal malfeasance:
</P>
<P>
   They marched to the Seahawks 30 on their opening possession, and
then suffered two sacks that took them out of field-goal range.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to get a reward on that first drive, a field goal at
the minimum,'' Centers said.
</P>
<P>
   They were in position to down a punt at the 3, but the ball
bounced past the coverage team into the end zone. Then Warren Moon,
the Seahawks 41-year-old quarterback, completed his first five
passes, leading to a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals were set to start a possession on their 27-yard
line, but an illegal-block penalty against Jarius Hayes on the
kickoff return put them back at the 6. Jake Plummer, who was
anything but the quarterback who completed his first 11 passes and
17 of his first 19 while passing for 322 yards against Seattle
three weeks earlier in a preseason game, dropped into the end zone
on the first snap and served up the first of two interceptions
returned for a touchdowns. This one was taken back 28 yards by
Willie Williams for a 10-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   A Cardinals punt appeared to pin the Seahawks at their 13-yard
line _ until Kwamie Lassiter was penalized for interfering with the
fair catch. Three plays into the Seattle drive, the Cardinals'
Williams was called for pass interference against speedy receiver
Joey Galloway at the Cardinals' 6 _ a 41-yard field-position change
_ even though replays showed that Galloway actually grabbed
Williams and pulled him down. Seattle scored to make it 17-0.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer was sacked seven times. And while the final statistics
indicate the Cardinals rushed for 111 yards, 61 of those came in
the fourth quarter after it was 33-7.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, the Cardinals prevented Moon from making the killer
passing plays, but they couldn't stop Ricky Watters, who rushed for
105 yards, the 22nd time he has reached triple figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' Tobin said, ``is our team did not play well
enough to win the game. That's extremely disappointing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
