<HEADLINE>
JAKE PLUMMER CAUGHT IN SEAHAWKS PRESSURE COOKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ First Jake Plummer wobbled. Then his pass did.
Three-plus quarters into the Arizona Cardinals' latest bloody
Sunday, Plummer lost his balance as the Seahawks' Cortez Kennedy
bulled through the line. Plummer's trembling toss found cornerback
Shawn Springs, who found the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   It was Seattle's second interception returned for a touchdown
Sunday, and the Seahawks had one more pick in their pocket. After
stopping the clock at :04 with a spike, Plummer ended the game with
a pass complete to Seahawks safety Mark Collins.
</P>
<P>
   That sealed a 19-point loss for the Cardinals, who fell by 28 in
their opening game at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to start 0-2; that's bad, especially the way we
got beat twice,'' said Plummer, who has three wins in 11 NFL
starts. ``(You can say) it was on the road, on turf, whatever _ we
got beat twice pretty handily. If we want to be winners, we have to
show our mettle, come back next week and be mad. This should really
sting. It stings me right now, just standing here.''
</P>
<P>
   The sting was worse when he was surrounded by Seahawks, not
reporters. Seattle blitzed Plummer often to counter the Cardinals'
West Coast offensive style, and the Cardinals said they knew it was
coming. But that didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of times it was a physical breakdown, a couple of
times we missed reads, a couple of times it was just everything,''
said tackle Lomas Brown. ``It was a whole combination of different
things that contributed to us not being effective.''
</P>
<P>
   For Plummer, it was another session in an ongoing crash course
on life in the NFL. He was a star at Arizona State two years ago
and remains a fan favorite in Phoenix, but if he's really the
Cardinals' answer, he knows he needs time to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was playing me, I'd blitz the hell out of me, every
single play,'' said Plummer, who was 22 of 36 for 204 yards and a
touchdown. ``It's something I have to learn. Once we see how
they're coming, we can work on a few things and become a pretty
lethal team. Right now, I'm struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals were shut out in the first half but came out
strong in the third quarter. Brown said the Cardinals began
recognizing blitzes better, and their plan to run the ball more to
take pressure off Plummer worked.
</P>
<P>
   But that success was fleeting, and by the end the Cardinals were
the Seahawks' opposite, with two blowout losses and deflated
optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll continue to fight and find ways to improve ourselves
individually and as a team,'' said fullback Larry Centers. ``It's
just a matter of going back to the drawing board. We'll get this
thing on track before it's all over.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll have a chance in their home opener this week against
another Seahawk victim, Philadelphia. But Brown isn't expecting a
warm reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans are going to be pretty sour with us,'' he said.
``It's not the homecoming you'd expect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
