<HEADLINE>
TKACHUK SILENCE CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - Although some players might be under the
impression that negotiations will continue with holdout left wing
 &UR; Keith Tkachuk, General Manager  &UR; Bobby Smith said they should not
be so optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got nothing to talk about with Tkachuk,'' Smith said
Sunday, the opening day of training camp. ``It's not like there's
going to be something new every day, because there's ``not'' going
to be anything new.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight day since he was suspended, Tkachuk, the
team's captain and leading scorer, could not be reached for
comment. Neither could his Boston-based agent,  &UR; Bob Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk now has forfeited $20,362 of his $2.8 million salary
since being suspended on Saturday, in accordance with rules in the
NHL's collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed, obviously,'' said Coyotes Coach  &UR; Jim
Schoenfeld, who built up a special relationship with Tkachuk last
season. ``As I've said before, Keith is a player under contract and
we expect all our contracted players to be here. He's decided not
to come, so now it's a situation where our planning for the start
of the regular season has to be done without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``After this point, we're going to talk about the players we
have in uniform. It's a situation between Keith and management.
Historically, these things get resolved, so I really think it's
fruitless for me to get involved one way or another because
everybody is all huggy-kissy after all the negotiations and
everything that's been said in the press.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk's teammates remain hopeful something will be resolved
soon with the power forward, who has two years worth $5.8 million
left on his current contract, but is demanding an extension worth
$8 million a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had every inkling that he wasn't going to come,''
forward &UR; Rick Tocchet said. ``It seemed like they were pretty far
apart for a long time, so I didn't think one side was going to make
that big of concession.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman  &UR; Teppo Numminen and right wing  &UR; Dallas Drake both
said they expect negotiations to continue in hopes of a resolution,
but that doesn't seem to be a likely scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every individual has their own beliefs, but it really doesn't
matter what I believe,'' Tocchet said. ``I know what I would do,
but it's a tough situation.'' &QL; 
Lemieux out indefinitely &QL; 
Veteran wing  &UR; Jocelyn Lemieux suffered a fractured collarbone while
mountain biking in north Scottsdale and will be sidelined 10 to 12
weeks after undergoing surgery this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second major obstacle the 30-year-old Lemieux, the
younger brother of Colorado star  &UR; Claude Lemieux, has had to endure
in the past two seasons. His career nearly was finished in December
1996 after he suffered a severe compound fracture to his forearm
while playing for the Long Beach Ice Dogs in the International
Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things that's extremely unfortunate, and you
really feel bad for the player,'' Schoenfeld said. ``For Jocelyn,
it's just another obstacle he has to overcome.'' &QL; 
Roenick absent &QL; 
Center  &UR; Jeremy Roenick was excused from the first day of training
camp with permission from Smith so he could attend to family
business. Roenick flew to Boston, his hometown, but was back in the
Valley by Sunday afternoon, according to relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick will practice this morning in Scottsdale, according to
Smith, who declined to give details for his absence. There was no
death or serious illness in the family, another relative said. &QL; 
Slap shots &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bruising defenseman  &UR; Sean Gagnon is sidelined day-to-day because
of a hip flexor injury, but he apparently has informed team
officials he plans to practice today.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations between the club and restricted Group II free-agent
defenseman &UR; Keith Carney have hit a wall, but Smith said Sunday he
still hopes to re-sign the U.S. Olympian at some point this week. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
