<HEADLINE>
SHOWALTER `REMINDS' TEAM OF GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Diamondbacks Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter doesn't like
to give speeches. But sometimes, he believes the time is right for
a little one-way conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was one of those times. The Diamondbacks had lost four in
a row. Even more distressing was the manner in which they had
played. Less than stellar pitchers shut them down, and there were
defensive and mental lapses.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's game, a 3-0 loss to the Cincinnati Reds,
Showalter was clearly upset. He woke up Sunday feeling the same
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I still feel passionate the next day, I'll follow up on
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter's pre-game talk lasted only about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reiterated some things I thought they needed to be reminded
of,'' he said. ``It's never pleasant. But I have a lot of trust in
these guys. At the same time, we want to finish strong. I know the
fans want to, and I know the organization wants to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a reminder of what we want to be about.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks then went out and beat the Cincinnati Reds,
5-0, as  &UR; Andy
 &UR; Benes lost a no-hitter with one out in the ninth inning. But
Showalter indicated there are still some things that bother him.
</P>
<P>
   Returning home for a three-game series with San Francisco
starting tonight, the Diamondbacks are 59-91. They need to win four
of their remaining 12 games to avoid 100 losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for us to remember that we're building for
something,'' Benes said, ``and that every time we go out there, we
want to win.'' &QL; 
HR mark &QL; 
 &UR; Tony Batista did it again. The Diamondbacks &QL; 
infielder hit his 18th homer of the season, a two-run shot in the
seventh inning. It was a new professional best for Batista and his
fourth homer in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Batista has just 245 at-bats this year. That's one home run
every 13.3 at-bats, which would have put him among the league
leaders if he had played every day.
</P>
<P>
   Since Aug. 3, Batista has hit 13 home runs. That's one every
nine at-bats. For the sake of comparison,  &UR; Mark McGwire has hit a
home run every 7.5 at-bats, and  &UR; Sammy Sosa one every 9.8 at-bats
prior to Sunday's games.
</P>
<P>
   Batista's previous high was 17 homers for Class A Modesto in
1994. It took him 466 at-bats to get there.
</P>
<P>
   Batista was known to have decent power, but even he is
surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, yeah,'' he said. ``I don't know what I'm doing. All
the balls I hit are deep. It just happens.'' &QL; 
Heat wave &QL; 
It was hot on the AstroTurf at Cinergy Field _ over 100 degrees _
but even hotter in the dugout. How hot was it? For the second day
in a row, Showalter removed his trademark jacket and wore just his
uniform top. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
