<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-OFF-LINE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SACKS QUICKLY ADDING UP FOR CARDINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Do the arithmetic.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals continue to give up 4.5 sacks per game, they
will allow 72 this season, six fewer than last year but still the
third most in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   So after the Seattle Seahawks sacked quarterback Jake Plummer
seven times in their 33-14 victory Sunday, Cardinals offensive
tackle Lomas Brown conceded that opposing defenses will blitz the
second-year pro as soon as they get off the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if you are a 20-year veteran or a two-year
veteran,'' Brown said. ``Until you shut them (blitzers) down, they
are going to keep coming after you week after week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what people say about the Arizona Cardinals. It's all
been written: `The Arizona Cardinals don't have an offensive line,
have a young quarterback and no running game. All you have to do is
put eight men on the line and go after the Cardinals and you will
beat them.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, the Cardinals gave up five sacks for 27 yards
in losses and gained only 27 yards on the ground. Plummer also
threw an interception for a touchdown, one of two he had returned
for scores.
</P>
<P>
   But on their opening drive, they moved from their 30 to
Seattle's 30 before Plummer was sacked on back-to-back plays,
moving the Cardinals out of field-goal range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things were rolling,'' Brown said. ``We're chugging along,
feeling good about ourselves, and then we kill ourselves. We can't
do that against a good team. It's painful.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the off-season, the Cardinals maintained they had
improved their offensive line even though starting right guard
Lester Holmes was the only free-agent addition.
</P>
<P>
   They also have first-year starters in left guard Chris Dishman,
center Aaron Graham and right tackle James Dexter. Dishman was
critical of his performance, Graham was a last-minute scratch
because of a sore calf muscle and Dexter was beaten for two sacks
by Seahawks defensive end Michael Sinclair.
</P>
<P>
   One change could be moving rookie Anthony Clement, a
second-round draft pick from Southwestern Louisiana, into the
starting lineup. Clement, whose progress was slowed by a preseason
knee injury, dressed for the first time on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   If Clement becomes a starter at right tackle, Dexter could be
moved to guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't keep giving up that many sacks,'' Dishman said. ``If
we do stuff like that every week, we won't be around. The Seahawks
brought a lot of people on blitzes, but we knew it was coming. It's
no secret when it's second and 7, second and long, that they are
coming after us. We should have picked them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Mike Devlin, who replaced Graham in the starting lineup,
said the Seahawks didn't fool the Cardinals with any tricks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't do anything differently than the week before,''
Devlin said. ``Sometimes, it was us. We didn't pick up our men.
Sometimes, they brought more guys than we had blockers. But nobody
did a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin refused to put all of the blame on
the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you have seven sacks, there's more to it than just
the offensive line,'' Tobin said. ``It's convenient to lay it all
on their shoulders, but that's just part of the problem. When you
are getting blitzed like that, you have to get rid of the football
and not take those sacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a surprise. Seahawks safety Jay Bellamy thinks the
Philadelphia Eagles, the Cardinals' opponent next week, will try to
pressure Plummer from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   He said that was Seattle's strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every snap he goes back and throws the ball, we're going to
have somebody in his face,'' Bellamy said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 0058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
