<SLUG> BC-LPGA-SAFECO-CLASSIC-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORENSTAM METHODICALLY ROLLS TO FIVE-SHOT VICTORY IN SAFECO
CLASSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENT, Wash. _ Annika Sorenstam visited the media tent almost as
much as the driving range during the 17th Safeco Classic, looking
for statistics, seeking answers. Maybe that explains why four days
at Meridian Valley Country Club turned into a numbers crunch.
</P>
<P>
   Broken down, it went like something this: The No. 1 women's
golfer in the world _ though not the most revered _ Sunday turned
in the tournament's second most-decisive victory (five strokes)
before record-breaking crowds (33,200 on Sunday, 86,700 overall).
</P>
<P>
   Any way you added it up, it was Sorenstam by a lot.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Swede turned Lake Tahoe resident bogeyed just
one hole over the final 44. She shot 15-under-par 273, 68 on the
last day, good for $90,000. She was as methodical as a grocery
store checker, pounding away and tallying up her fourth victory
since June.
</P>
<P>
   Things were so one-sided, Patty Sheehan, who finished tied for
second with Laura Davies, congratulated Sorenstam on her victory _
halfway up the 18th fairway. The winner felt it was a wrap on the
16th hole. The scoreboard indicated as much on the 14th.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just had to walk in the park today, sing a little and do a
little two-step,'' Sheehan said.
</P>
<P>
   Safeco tried something new, then something old, before settling
on the best the LPGA has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie sensation Se Ri Pak, the one largely responsible for the
boost in Safeco attendance (2,000 more on Sunday, 200 more
overall), completed a two-day fade to finish tied for 21st with 10
other players. The South Korean teased local golf followers much
like Tiger Woods did at the PGA Championship, leading for a round
before falling well off the pace.
</P>
<P>
   The 41-year-old Sheehan, the LPGA's answer to Tom Watson, got
everyone a little emotional when she unexpectedly moved into
contention and led by a stroke entering the final round. A victory
would have been her fourth at Meridian Valley.
</P>
<P>
   While all this was going on, Sorenstam, whose game has been
described as ``boring'' at times, diligently positioned herself to
win. Her peers had seen it before.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not an exciting player by any means, but shooting 15- or
17-under (par) each week is exciting in itself,'' Davies pointed
out. ``She keeps it in play. She's got a fabulous putter. She's the
real deal. She's proven it all over again why she is the best
player in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam made regular visits to the media tent, but she was
more interested in finding stat sheets than answering questions.
Each night, she left deep in thought. Admittedly, she's a golf
nerd.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1987, Sorenstam has been loading her tournament details in
a computer, checking tendencies. All kinds of minutia. Not
necessarily how many fairways she hits, but which side of the
fairway her ball landed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty hard on myself,'' she said. ``If I don't hit 18
greens, I strive to hit 18 greens the next time.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam toured the course Sunday with two players, Sheehan and
Juli Inkster, who had five Safeco victories between them.
</P>
<P>
   Easily recognizable by the big black bow in her hair, Sorenstam
smiled on the third hole when a male fan told her to knock one in.
She acknowledged a man who spoke to her in Swedish a few holes
later. She nodded when a man and woman pushing a baby stroller
called her name. She chatted easily with Sheehan during breaks on
several holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might look focused, but I see things and hear things that go
on around me,'' she said. ``I work very hard to stay calm. But the
atmosphere (Sunday) was very relaxed. I felt comfortable with my
playing partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam pulled even with Sheehan on the par-3 third hole,
rolling in a 15-foot putt for birdie. She took the lead for good on
the par-5 No. 5, reaching the hole in two shots and two-putting for
birdie, while Sheehan parred.
</P>
<P>
   At the same, history was being made on the hole ahead _ by Pak.
The first-year player, surrounded by her largest Korean-American
gallery of the year, shocked them by hitting her tee shot into the
right rough, shanking her second shot into the water, taking a drop
and hitting a tree with her next offering. She finally chipped on
and two-putted the 380-yard sixth hole for a triple-bogey seven.
</P>
<P>
   The shank and triple were firsts for her on the LPGA Tour, as
was a string of three consecutive double-bogeys on Saturday.
``Today I feel something not that good,'' she said in her broken
English. ``Other times it is just golf. Maybe from this, I will
learn many things.''
</P>
<P>
   When the last putt dropped, Sorenstam had her 16th LPGA victory
in five seasons, a commanding lead over Pak on the money list and
her first Safeco win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
