<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERFERENCE PENALTY DIDN'T GRAB CARDINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 and STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It's difficult to pin a 33-14 whipping on one play.
But the Cardinals agreed that one back-breaker as they fell to 0-2
Sunday at the Kingdome was a 41-yard pass interference call against
their Pro Bowl cornerback,  &UR; Aeneas Williams, who was covering
speedy Seattle Seahawks receiver  &UR; Joey Galloway.
</P>
<P>
   Replays showed that Galloway actually grabbed Williams and
pulled him down. It took several seconds for an official to throw a
flag.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty moved the Seahawks, who were leading, 10-0, early in
the second quarter, to the Cardinals 6-yard line. Quarterback
 &UR; Warren Moon then fired a 4-yard scoring pass to fullback  &UR; Mack
Strong for a 17-0 lead two plays later.
</P>
<P>
   For all intents and purposes, the Big Red was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made the call,'' Williams said. ``I'll have to go back
and critique it on film. What I've got to do in that situation is
find a way to come up with the interception and not let them make
that call.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin, aware the league fines those who make
critical comments regarding officiating, would say only ``that's a
tough call.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what more Aeneas is supposed to do,'' Tobin said.
``He ran with Galloway and turned inside to make the play. The guy
came over his back and they called (Williams) for interference.
That's what I saw, but I don't know what the official saw.''
</P>
<P>
   That play accounted for nearly half of 88 first-half penalty
yards _ compared with none for the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that we had an inordinate number of penalties,''
Tobin said. ``But that interference call was a big one.'' &QL; 
Quick stop &QL; 
Just as they had in their opening 38-10 loss at Dallas, the
Cardinals moved the ball into scoring position on their opening
drive but were denied the chance to take an early lead.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Jake Plummer took them to the Seahawks 30-yard line
before two sacks gave the Cardinals fourth-and-15 at the 35. It
would have been a 52-yard field-goal attempt by Joe Nedney.
Instead, Tobin ordered a punt.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle then drove to the Cardinals 34, where, faced with a
nearly identical situation, Seattle Coach Dennis Erickson called
for a field goal. Todd Peterson connected from 51 yards for a 3-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said he did not give Nedney, who was erratic last season
beyond 40 yards, the chance because of a previously unreported hip
flexor injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nedney had a hip flexor that bothered him all week,'' Tobin
said. ``We didn't want to risk putting our defense in bad field
position right away if he missed. After he warmed up before the
game he didn't feel like he could make any over 50 yards, so I took
him at his word.'' &QL; 
Restless natives &QL; 
It was a bad weekend for teams that play at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State was upset by Brigham Young, 26-6, on Saturday
night in Provo, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals were routed for the second consecutive week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans are going to be angry all over the state of
Arizona,'' offensive tackle  &UR; Lomas Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown called next week's home opener against the Eagles a
pressure game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Philadelphia is a team we need to beat,'' Brown said. ``We
have to beat them. It's a turning point of our season.'' &QL; 
Disappearing act
</P>
<P>
   Can you name the last time Cardinals defensive end &UR; Simeon Rice
had a sack?
</P>
<P>
   It came last Nov. 2 against the Eagles, meaning he has gone nine
consecutive games without a sack.
</P>
<P>
   He played most of Sunday's game and had only one tackle. &QL; 
Short shots
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals dropped to 3-15 on the road under Tobin.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker  &UR; Ronald McKinnon has 24 tackles in two games. He's on
a pace to finish with 192 tackles, the second most in team history.
</P>
<P>
   Only once last season did  &UR; Larry Centers have more catches than
the seven he had Sunday for 54 yards. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
