</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-CARDINALS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS BLITZ CARDINALS FOR 2-0 START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ On a day when Warren Moon passed for only 146 yards,
the defense collected seven sacks.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when Joey Galloway caught just two passes, the defense
returned two interceptions for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when the big play was missing from the offense, the
defense forced five turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when Ricky Watters did run for 105 yards, the defense
ran Cardinals quarterback Jake Plummer ragged.
</P>
<P>
   The best defensive performance in Dennis Erickson's 50-game
tenure as coach of the Seahawks was more than enough to offset an
inconsistent offense in Sunday's 33-14 thrashing of the Arizona
Cardinals at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   The victory before a home-opener crowd of 57,678 pushed the
Seahawks' record to 2-0, and put them very much within reach of
only the second 3-0 start in franchise history in next week's game
against the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this game showed is that when one side is not playing as
well as it should, the other side can pick up the slack,'' said
Moon, who threw TD passes to Galloway and fullback Mack Strong in
winning the 100th game of his 15-year NFL career.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks' defense didn't just pick up the slack, it
strangled the Cardinals' offense. For the second straight week, the
defense set the tempo by blitzing its way to one big play after
another.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the 38-0 shutout at Philadelphia in last week's season
opener, the Seahawks did not need an array of defensive sets to
rattle Plummer and the Cardinals offense. The Seahawks generated
enough pressure from their base 4-3 defense to wilt a seasoned NFL
passer, let alone one making only his 11th start.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came with it. We knew they were coming, but we just
couldn't quite get all of them blocked,'' Plummer said. ``When we
did get (a pass) off, they were covering the hottest on the
sidelines, so they had a good game plan for us defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks blitzed early. They blitzed often. They blitzed
with devastating results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Total domination is what we strive for, for 60 minutes,'' said
defensive tackle Sam Adams, who did not have a sack but for the
second straight week was almost unblockable. ``We thought we could
get pressure just playing the regular defense. What we wanted to do
was force him to throw and then pressure each and every pass. I
think we were able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer was forced to throw early on a pass to Rob Moore in the
first quarter. The Cardinals' leading receiver never saw the pass
because he had yet to turn around. Instead, Seahawks cornerback
Willie Williams intercepted the pass and returned it 28 yards for a
touchdown that gave the Seahawks a 10-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was mixed up communication between the quarterback
and the receiver,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-9, 180-pound Williams had to leap past Cardinals
center Mike Devlin at the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to dive over. I didn't want to try to run him over. I
probably would have lost that battle,'' Williams said of the
318-pound Devlin.
</P>
<P>
   Another blitz, this one by safety Mark Collins, forced Plummer
to serve up a wobbler of a pass that was picked off by cornerback
Shawn Springs and returned 56 yards for a touchdown to make it 33-7
in the fourth quarter. The combination of Collins blitzing and
Springs intercepting also clicked for a score in last week's win at
Philly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same exact play, the same exact blitz,'' said
Springs, who was playing despite a hip flexor he suffered in
practice last week. ``I think we have something special on defense
this year. We pride ourselves on just completely dominating and not
giving up really anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The interceptions were just the biggest plays in what was an
inferno of an afternoon for Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Darrin Smith had two sacks and also forced a fumble
as part of his 10-tackle effort. Defensive end Michael Sinclair
also got to Plummer twice, and now has 4{ sacks in two games.
Defensive end Matt LaBounty and strong safety Jay Bellamy each had
a sack. Linebacker Chad Brown and defensive end Phillip Daniels
shared a sack.
</P>
<P>
   Seven sacks, from six different players, from a half-dozen
directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like winning is contagious, making big plays is
contagious,'' Sinclair said. ``There was a lot said about Jake
escaping. I thought we kept him in the pocket. We contained him. We
hit him. He just didn't seem comfortable back there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was another dominating performance. But it also was just one
more game against another inexperienced quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's two wins. It's just two wins. There are a lot of rounds
left in this fight,'' Brown said. ``We can't break our arms patting
ourselves on the back and thinking, `Oh, the Seahawks are all this
and all that.' It's two wins in two games against teams with young
quarterbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   With a third set for Sunday against the Redskins and quarterback
Trent Green.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
