<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EYES HAVE IT: REFLECT QB'S ANGER  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE - In the second half, Lomas Brown turned and faced his
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jake,'' he said, ``lemme see your eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the eyes, Lomas?
</P>
<P>
   ``The eyes,'' Brown said, ``tell it all.''
</P>
<P>
   A 14-year NFL veteran, Brown looked deeply into the eyes of No.
16. He studied the eyes of the young face the way a boxing trainer
reads the eyes of a fighter slumped on a stool between rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was concerned. The kid he and his fellow offensive linemen
are paid to protect was taking a physical and mental beating.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals couldn't stop Seattle's pass rush. Between sacks,
seven in all, Plummer threw a terrible pass _ ``a gift'' Vince
Tobin called the ball that cornerback Willie Williams intercepted
and returned 28 yards for a first-quarter touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Plummer would throw another.
</P>
<P>
   The player around whom this offense is built, the kid whom Bill
Walsh has called the next Joe Montana, never saw Shawn Springs pick
off his fluttery pass and prance 56 yards to make the score 33-7.
</P>
<P>
   More frustration. More embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   Jake missed the Seahawks' fourth touchdown. As blood from a turf
burn oozed through an elbow bandage, Plummer lay on the ground,
pinned under 306 pounds of Cortez Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Plummer, who is featured in national magazines and on
ESPN's promotion for Sunday night's Cardinals home opener against
Philadelphia, was suffering through another bad game. Terrible
game.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer, the guy this team is counting on to score points and
win games and shed that ``same old Cardinals'' tag he hates, later
said it best, ``We stunk offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   The game not over _ would it ever end? _ Brown searched
Plummer's eyes. What was he looking for?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see if there was any intensity there,'' the left
tackle said. The old pro checked to see if the kid had that vacant
gaze Brown has seen in quarterbacks whose spirit is broken.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to see Jake's reaction. Measure his resiliency. He
wanted to see if Jake had given up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see that,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   What he saw was a kid who was angry. Angry and upset over the
sorry way this season has started. Mostly, Plummer was angry with
himself.
</P>
<P>
   This is a new offense, one designed to exploit his talents. Jake
would shine. Jake would be the playmaker. He hasn't done that this
year. He spent Sunday dodging rushers, throwing passes he wished he
could pull back like a yo-yo on a string. He spent a long day in
the tomb-like gloom of the Kingdome licking his lips between plays
and looking to the sideline at Marc Trestman, the offensive
coordinator, for answers.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's game plan was simple. Blitz the young quarterback.
Plummer admired the strategy. ``If I were playing me,'' he said,
``I would blitz the hell out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer knows the situation. So does Trestman. Seattle's plan is
a blueprint for every team. Every Cardinals opponent will come
after the quarterback until he proves he can beat them. Can he?
Will he? When?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm young,'' Plummer said, reminding himself, trying to smile.
But he is impatient with himself. He hates to lose. He feels the
burden of high expectation, what center Mike Devlin called `'the
weight of the world'' on his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   So when the game ended, No. 16 didn't linger. As fireworks
exploded overhead, Plummer was the first Cardinals player off the
field, sprinting toward the locker. He didn't stay around to
chit-chat with Jeff Feagles, the former Cardinals punter, or talk
over old times with Springs, the former Ohio State defensive back
whom Jake played against in the Rose Bowl two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``What am I going to say?'' Plummer asked. ``Hi.
Congratulations. You kicked our (. . .).' I can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The eyes are impatient. Angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plum . . . mer! Plum . . . mer!'' they sang out from the first
row of seats behind the Cardinals' bench.
</P>
<P>
   He ignored the catcalls. He didn't check the scoreboard when it
was over. He just wanted to shower and dress and get on the bus and
fly home. The present and future quarterback of 47 men who meet the
``legal'' definition of a ``professional'' football team, but so
far has not performed like one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
