<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3207 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      09-14 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS 2-0, BUT AGAINST NFC LEAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Somebody check to see if the polar caps have melted.
</P>
<P>
   Find out if Steven Seagal made a good movie.
</P>
<P>
   Hey _ maybe the president was honest Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks are 2-0. Assume nothing about the world.
</P>
<P>
   Each season of Dennis Erickson's term as Seahawk coach started
out 0-2. With Sunday's 33-14 home-opener win over the Arizona
Discard-inals, the Seahawks are positively woozy from the heights.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it's a molehill, not a mountain. When one knows nothing
but the valley, any variation in terrain is breathtaking.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawk giddiness is tempered by the fact that Sunday was the
second of three games against opponents from the NFC East, possibly
the worst grouping since fever blisters.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the second encounter with an inexperienced
quarterback, this one Jake Plummer, a starter of 11 NFL games. Last
week Philadelphia's Bobby Hoying made his seventh start against the
Seahawks. Next week, it's Trent Green, who makes his NFL debut in
the Monday night game tonight for the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   These guys are human teething rings. They don't know blitz from
zits. When Seahawk defenders lean across the line of scrimmage and
whisper, ``Boo!'' these QBs get more vertical than Sergei Bubka.
</P>
<P>
   But after a recent history of quarterbacks that included Rick
Mirer, Dan McGwire and Kelly Stouffer, the Seahawks can figure they
are entitled to a few gimmes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the three years and two games I've been here, that's the
best defensive effort we've had,'' said Erickson, his face missing
its usual September torque. A year ago at this point, the Seahawks
allowed 76 points and were on their way to giving back more ground
than Rommel in North Africa.
</P>
<P>
   This year appears to be a new deal, especially for the defense.
Perhaps not as dramatic as the cumulative scores so far indicate,
but the fact is the Seahawk defense has scored three touchdowns and
allowed two, and one of the latter was a fourth-quarter non-event.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blitz _ period,'' said defensive tackle Dan Saleamua, when
asked to explain. ``We're just going after 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   So it would seem, since the Seahawks added seven quarterback
sacks to their nine against the Eagles. Since the NFL team record
is 104, that puts them on a pace to beat not only the record, but
Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire as well.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive backs Shawn Springs and Willie Williams returned
interceptions for touchdowns and the longest play allowed the
Discard-inals from scrimmage was 23 yards. This is the kind of
opportunism combined with stoutness that can make a case for some
serious reckoning from future opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to come here worried about our defense, like
they (worried) about the old Steelers and Raiders,'' said newcomer
linebacker Darrin Smith, whose two sacks were part of his team-high
10 tackles. ``I don't know if there's a better front four in the
league. They allow us linebackers to run around. The secondary is
back there making plays and scoring touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's so excited to be running around that nobody wants
to be caught walking.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all this running around can come to an abrupt halt
against Kansas City or Denver. But that's a ways off, and the
puffball early schedule is allowing the Seahawks to get more
plugged into one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not five new guys out there running into each other,''
said linebacker Chad Brown, one of last year's five new starters
whose collective learning curve was steep, particularly at the
start. The Seahawk defense improved as the season progressed, but
couldn't cover for collapses elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Williams has been here a year with our system of coverages,''
he said. ``Shawn is no longer a rookie. There's 11 guys who can
execute the zone blitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is you can't blow a zone assignment or
it's a big play. If someone is supposed to blitz and doesn't, a guy
like Plummer can make some yards. We blew a few today, but we
played well a lot more than we played bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The obvious Seahawk defensive game plan of Jake-rattle-and-roll
for the second-year quarterback worked so well that Arizona really
had no ability to come back from the 20-0 halftime hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't comfortable back there at all,'' said defensive end
Michael Sinclair. ``He just didn't feel at home back there, and
that's a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   With a year together as a unit, and improvement in last year's
downfall of special teams, the Seahawks seem on the verge of a
developing a swagger. Once they get into the AFC West schedule,
that swagger can turn quickly into a limp. For now, it's fun to
practice it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect,'' said Brown, ``to play well.''
</P>
<P>
   But you expected the same a year ago, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I expected it,'' he said. ``Not pointing fingers, but
after things started turning bad last year, maybe certain people
didn't expect to win. They wanted to win, but did they have it in
their heart they were going to win? I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``This organization hasn't had a lot of winning seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Since it hasn't been tested, it's too early to tell the makeup
of the Seahawk heart. But 2-0 is indisputable, not to mention
hardly recognizable.
</P>
<P>
   Some things in life are supposed to be constants. But yet
another has disappeared. Seahawk fans can only hope to make the
best of the unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
