<HEADER>
A3209 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEKYLL-HYDE-MANIA-ART     09-14 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEKYLL-HYDE-MANIA-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOYAL FANS RETURN TO A MUSICAL AGAIN AND AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sure, Pat Costa had already seen ``Jekyll and Hyde''
66 times, but this was different.
</P>
<P>
   As a successful bidder at a theater group's auction, she had
just been given a backstage tour, including the dressing rooms, wig
rooms and bathrooms, by the show's star Robert Cuccioli. When she
finally made it outside with her friend Connie Cadieux, who had
seen the show a mere 18 times, she was shaking as if near a
meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you verklempt?'' asked Jodi Stevens, a cast member and
Cuccioli's real-life girlfriend, as they left through the stage
door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Verklempt? I'm tres verklempt,'' gasped Ms. Costa, a nurse
from West Islip, whose home answering machine greets callers with
``This Is the Moment,'' the show's big number. ``I feel like my
life is hanging in the balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Reality seems to hang in the balance most nights at the Plymouth
Theater as one of Broadway's oddest obsessions plays out nightly.
``Jekyll and Hyde,'' Frank Wildhorn's hyperbolic musical, came to
New York last year with a built-in following of fans known as
Jekkies, who show up for performances nearly as regularly as some
people show up for work.
</P>
<P>
   In its second year, Jekkiedom shows no signs of dissipating, a
syndrome with implications not just for curious clinicians but
perhaps for other theatrical productions as well.
</P>
<P>
   By all rights, ``Jekyll and Hyde'' should be long gone. The
pallid blurbs culled from mostly underwhelmed reviews on the
theater marquee (```Like ``Phantom,'' it will run forever' _
Gannett Newspapers'') are a reminder that ``Jekyll'' is not exactly
a critic's favorite. In his review in The New York Times, Ben
Brantley called it a ``leaden, solemnly campy musical.'' In
Newsday, Linda Winer called the show ``dreary nonsense'' and ``a
pseudo-serious potboiler.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the Deadheads of Broadway, the hard-core Jekkies have
helped build word of mouth that has made the show a phenomenon. It
had its 500th Broadway performance in July, and plans are set for
productions in Sydney, Australia; Bremen, Germany; Madrid, Spain;
and Scandinavia, with others in the works for London, Mexico City
and Buenos Aires, Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Most people in the Broadway audience each night are
first-timers, of course. But few shows are likely to build a
following as fanatical as the Jekkies. Paul Martin, who saw the
show the same night as Ms. Costa, said he had lost exact count but
figured his 100th trip to ``Jekyll'' coincided with Linda Eder's
epochal last performance on Aug. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Goldman was there for the 41st time. Debbie Krigger of
Houston has seen the show in its nearly endless pre-New York tour
in Houston, Cleveland, St. Louis, Pittsburgh, Dallas, San Antonio,
Orlando, Miami, Baltimore, Washington and Phoenix as well as in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The main Jekkie fan club has about 400 members, and there are
Web sites not just for the show but for Cuccioli; his understudy,
Robert Evan, who performs at Wednesday and Saturday matinees; Ms.
Eder, who played Lucy, the prostitute, and Christiane Noll, who
plays the virginal Emma.
</P>
<P>
   Those who miss each night's show are likely to get a review of
it on the day's Jekkie Internet message board at
www.jekyllhyde.com, which includes fan notes, cast-member sightings
and musings on various Jekkie obsessions like the guy who was
beginning to see a therapist because he thought his Jekkiedom was
getting out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not alone,'' came a reply. ``Many of us feel the same
way as you. Instead of going to a therapist, we talk to each other
about it, since others truly don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jekyll and Hyde'' is not the first show to attract repeat
customers, though it is more likely to happen in critical hits like
``A Chorus Line'' or ``Rent.'' Movies like ``The Rocky Horror
Picture Show'' have long been cult favorites as well.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some of these, which have a young following, ``Jekyll''
draws its faithful from a wide age range, with most from the early
20s to the late 40s.
</P>
<P>
   Regular-price tickets to ``Jekyll'' range from $45 to $75, which
can make becoming a Jekkie an expensive hobby. But to ease the
pain, many repeat offenders rely on $20 tickets available the day
of the show or discount tickets from the TKTS booth.
</P>
<P>
   The faithful, most of whom see other shows as well as ``Jekyll
and Hyde,'' have a little trouble putting their fingers on what
makes them serial customers. But most start with the music, which
is a mixture of high-wattage, Disneyesque Top 40 pop and brassy
Broadway bombast. ``This Is the Moment'' has already become a
staple at events in congenital need of emotional overkill, like the
Miss America contest, the Olympics and the 1996 Democratic National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, without the revenue from ``Jekyll'' albums _ 250,000
copies were sold before the show opened in New York _ it is
doubtful the show would have lasted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a metal-rock musician, and the first time I saw their
commercial on television, I thought, `Hey this guy can sing,'''
said Sal Italiano, who has seen the show 19 times. ``I'll tell you
right now, Frank Wildhorn is going to redefine Broadway. He's just
got a handle on a new genre of fan, a whole new market.''
</P>
<P>
   But, like being a Deadhead, being a fan of ``Jekyll and Hyde''
is about more than the show. Goldman met his girlfriend, Amy Hogge
of Dallas, through the ``Jekyll'' network. When he showed up at the
theater recently, he was guaranteed to find a ready community of
fellow travelers. They included fans and friends like Martin or
Melissa Charwin, who stopped by after the show to see how Ms.
Costa's backstage tour went.
</P>
<P>
   He chatted with Charles Wallace, who had just left the ensemble
and had come to see the show from the audience for the first time,
and he regularly talks with cast members like Ms. Noll after the
show.
</P>
<P>
   Most striking is the way the cast members have come to see the
fans more as parishioners than customers. Even the show's stars
make a point of lingering after the performance to sign autographs,
pose for pictures and chat with the faithful. Some go to Jekkies'
parties or join them for after-show coffee or drinks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``After you see the same faces every day, you get used to them,
and they become almost like family, to some extent,'' said
Cuccioli, who was nominated for a Tony last year for his
performance. ``I never expected anything like this, to be honest,
and I wasn't prepared for it. But they've been very supportive of
us, and I feel a responsibility to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jekkie culture is also a product of the Internet, and the
way it has been able to spread information and bring people
together around a common interest like nothing in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Like all families, Jekkiedom has its own family tree and rites
of passage. The extended family includes Wildhorn's other show on
Broadway, the even more widely panned ``Scarlet Pimpernel.'' And
fans are awaiting his next one, ``The Civil War,'' a recounting of
the war's personal conflicts, based on contemporary accounts. It is
to have its debut in Houston this month, starring Ms. Eder.
</P>
<P>
   And this was a traumatic week when the revered Ms. Eder was
replaced by a newcomer to the cast, Luba Mason.
</P>
<P>
   After the emotional catharsis of Ms. Eder's last performance,
when the theater was packed with the faithful following every
nuance and gesture as if interpreting Scripture, Martin came to a
recent show with a pained expression as if revisiting a favorite
haunt from a faded romance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it four times the last week, and the last show was the
most amazing thing I ever saw in my life,'' he said wistfully.
``Linda has the lungs of a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   So Ms. Mason's performance was like a first dinner with
prospective in-laws. But when it was over, both he and Goldman
proclaimed themselves pleased with the actress, who had an earthier
take on the character but seemed a welcome addition to the family.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if the music, message and community account for the
serial Jekkies, whatever makes someone see a show 100 times may be
a mystery too dense to unravel. Most of the first-timers in the
audience seemed to like the show but were baffled at the notion of
seeing it dozens of times. Even those at Ground Zero don't have a
ready explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're normal people usually,'' said Ms. Costa, who has seen
the show four more times over the past week bringing her total to
71. ``I'm a nurse. She's a bank manager. I never did this for
anything before. But I saw the second preview, March 22, 1997, and
I thought this is what Broadway is supposed to be. So I keep coming
back. Maybe it's a case of arrested development. What I didn't do
at 16, I'm doing at 47.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
