<HEADLINE>
DAVENPORT'S U.S. OPEN TITLE FILLS VOID IN WOMEN'S TENNIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The new U.S. Open singles champion said she walked
into her hotel room late Saturday afternoon and found the message
light bright as Rudolph's nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the most messages,'' Lindsay Davenport said Sunday after
she and Natasha Zvereva lost the women's doubles championship match
to Martina Hingis and Jana Novotna _ although one championship
seemed enough to turn Davenport's world around.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like, `You have 23 messages.' And I said, `Oh, my God.'
The first call I got, I'll never forget it, it was from a guy who
plays on the Tour. His name is Brian McPhie. He called and said `It
is 3:27 and you just won match point,' and he was screaming into
the phone. Those are the ones you remember,'' Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
   One day had passed since the 22-year-old Californian had secured
her most important tennis victory _ a win that puts her in some
pretty rare, pretty good company.
</P>
<P>
   The names Billie Jean King, Chris Evert and Tracey Austin are
also etched on that silver trophy that commemorates all singles
winners of the U.S. Grand Slam since the Open era began in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Now Davenport's name is etched in sterling, too.
</P>
<P>
   What this means is that for a 1998 U.S. Open that did not
produce Pete Sampras' 12th career Grand Slam victory _ Australia's
Patrick Rafter defend his men's title with a win over Mark
Philippousas _ something else was gained here. Something unexpected
but something necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the 20 pounds she lost and because of the new level
of dedication she mustered for the game, Davenport has picked up
where something was left off. For all the American women who have
turned their athletic attention to tennis, the royal lineage
continues. Davenport is now the next American champion.
</P>
<P>
   She is the one who takes the place at the table set for Jennifer
Capriati, who could not ingest all the hype and pressure and who
could not endure the lost childhood that came from a too-much,
too-soon life on the tour.
</P>
<P>
   And Davenport got to that elite place among American tennis
champions before Venus Williams, the awesome 18-year-old whose
tennis mind and tennis patience need more time to develop.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport's arrival, especially because her first slam win came
at the U.S. Open, helps fill a void maybe none of us realized
existed until you look around and see that no American woman has
yet emerged from the deep wake after King and Evert.
</P>
<P>
   Those American women played their best tennis in their 20's and
into their 30's. Because of their persistence, consistency and
force of personality, tennis gained a foothold in the American
sporting consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Now Davenport seems prepared to take up the cause, even if she
continues to battle a perception that she is not a fitting heir to
the legacy of her predecessors' success and even if tennis needs a
much bigger boost (from some sort of comprehensive marketing push)
than one polite, laid-back Californian can supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't put myself in that same category as Billie Jean or
Chris, or even Martina (Navratoliva) or Monica (Seles, who became
U.S. citizens.) Maybe after I've won 10 or 12,'' Davenport said,
understanding this is just a beginning for her.
</P>
<P>
   The computer rankings will keep Davenport at No. 2, behind
Hingis, this week. But Davenport is well-positioned to take over
No. 1, especially since her U.S. Open victory over Hingis gives her
five titles this year and she is playing the best tennis of any
woman on the tour.
</P>
<P>
   This momentum had Davenport's International Management Group
agent licking his lips a bit Sunday. The opportunities are sure to
float Davenport's way now, even if that was the last thing on her
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has obviously proven herself, especially after this Open
victory, to be the best player in the world this year. She's got
big bonuses coming from Wilson and Nike,'' said Tony Godsick,
trying to pose for a picture with Davenport in front of the famous
Atlas on the Worlds Fairgrounds outside the United States Tennis
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport was mobbed by photographers from around the world
Sunday, and fans, too, tried to get a shot of the new champ.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she is very different from some of the other players. She
is as American as, I hate to say this, but apple pie. She is a
Californian. Very laid back. She turns down exhibitions and things
to spend whatever time she has with her mom and her sisters,''
Godsick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing she has ever done is hold up that
silver trophy. She wanted to be the best player she could be.''
</P>
<P>
   And that alone is no small victory.
</P>
<P>
   Time will tell more about Lindsay Davenport, she knows that. But
what she started here at the Open, where she won every set and
seemed to possess a mandate for victory, was pretty impressive.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was Billie Jean King who was one of those 23 callers
who left a message Saturday night, after Davenport added her name
to the illustrious list of American women etched in Grand Slam
sterling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billie called me back and said `I'm really proud of you. You
looked great. You handled yourself great. You should be proud,'''
Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
   Even at 6-foot-2{, Lindsay Davenport knew she could stand
taller.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
