<HEADLINE>
PRETENDERS BE ING IDENTIFIED IN FIESTA RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There is no more fruitless exercise in sports than
trying to come up with a preseason college football ranking. That
has been proven again in the first few weeks this season.
</P>
<P>
   Contenders have become pretenders. One marquee team, Michigan,
has seen its chances of playing in the Fiesta Bowl for a second
straight national title disappear with an 0-2 start.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State, which also harbored some hope of playing for a
national title in Sun Devil Stadium Jan. 4, is also 0-2 and can't
afford to take its next opponent, North Texas, for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Another perennial frontrunner, Florida State, saw its chance of
a national title severely damaged with an upset loss to North
Carolina State on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame, which moved into darkhorse status with a victory
over Michigan a week ago, came back to earth with a loss last
Saturday against Michigan State.
</P>
<P>
   Some of college football's elite have come through the opening
weeks unscathed. No. 1 Ohio State has been impressive. Nebraska is
3-0, despite playing without starting quarterback Bobby Newcombe
the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State, which gave Coach Joe Paterno his 300th victory last
Saturday, looks better than most people expected. Florida will gets
its first serious test this Saturday against Tennessee. UCLA looked
good against a so-so Texas team.
</P>
<P>
   Like Florida, Kansas State is 2-0 thanks to an easy schedule.
The Wildcats' weak nonconference schedule could hurt them later in
the year should they remain a contender for the Fiesta Bowl.
Strength of schedule is one of the criteria used in determing the
participants. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 0110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3215 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-GALLERY-VANDALS-39     09-14 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-GALLERY-VANDALS-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPICIOUS FIRE DESTROYS EXHIBIT ON ULSTER STRIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERSEY CITY, N.J. _ In a suspected act of arson that officials
say may have been politically motivated, an art gallery was set
ablaze early Sunday morning just hours before it was to unveil a
photography exhibition of Catholic children in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   No one was injured in the fire, which broke out at 6:42 a.m. at
the Cooper Gallery, and was contained at 7:02 a.m, said Capt. Brett
Minor of the Jersey City Fire Department. But the gallery, which is
in the basement of a three-story building, was extensively damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Freshly painted white walls had been singed black. Office files
were destroyed. And all 23 of the black-and-white prints in the
exhibition, ``Faces of War: Children of Belfast,'' by Michael
Schwartz, were ruined.
</P>
<P>
   At first, officials suspected that the fire was routine, or
perhaps an act of arson. But after the owners informed
investigators of the nature of the photographs _ which depict,
among other images, the children of members of the Irish Republican
Army _ the police began investigating it as a bias incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire was deliberately set, and we're going to handle it as
a bias incident,'' said Lieut. John Sheyka of the Jersey City
Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   He said investigators had determined that the vandals had broken
into an adjacent gallery that was under construction and gained
access to the Cooper Gallery. There, they disabled the alarm system
and smoke detectors, made a pile of combustible materials in the
director's office and lighted it, Sheyka said. No fingerprints were
found.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it was political or malicious, we're going to have to
find out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To Schwartz and the gallery's owners, though, the motivation was
clearly political.
</P>
<P>
   ``The subject matter obviously antagonized a person or a
group,'' said Schwartz, who works as a freelance photographer for
The Daily News. ``I would say that even though my intent was to try
to show some compassion for these little kids that are victims over
there, and maybe change some people in thinking about the peace
process, all it did was the exact opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Sunday night, no arrests had been made, nor had anyone
claimed responsibility for the fire, Sheyka said. But the police
had arranged to have an officer patrol outside the gallery
overnight, to guard against any more acts of violence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   e The fire caught many by surprise and offered a reminder that
even the most foreign of conflicts can sometimes be felt closer to
home.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday night, it remained a mystery who might have wanted
to make a political statement about Northern Ireland in a small,
sedate New Jersey gallery that, with its two main exhibition spaces
and rear garden, has often been used by the public as an escape
from the city since the gallery opened in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz noted that some of the photographs in the exhibit had
been shown in public before, either in smaller solo shows or in
group shows, and that they had never provoked any protests.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit is the product of 10 years of work and captures
children ages 9 to 16 at rest and play in Belfast in the
British-ruled territory of Northern Ireland, which has been
beleaguered by decades of violence between Catholics and
Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   Irish people in the United States were also puzzled. Niall
O'Dowd, the publisher of The Irish Voice, a weekly newspaper, said
he could not recall an incident in this country in which an exhibit
or event was disrupted for political reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering the tremendous ground swell for peace, when
there's more hope than ever,'' he said, ``something like this is
completely mystifying.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Dowd added that he could not imagine how the fire could have
been related to the topic, which he said was not overly
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures reflect the complicated reality of life in Belfast.
In one, a child makes an obscene gesture at a British paratrooper;
in another, a child smiles at a paratrooper, who returns the
expression. In others, youths play with guns and wear ski masks.
</P>
<P>
   To accentuate the emotional impact, the gallery's window
featured empty bullet casings and an assortment of children's toys
_ a Lego piece, crayons, sneakers, a baseball glove. But like the
photographs, those items, too, were damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Before the opening reception planned for Sunday, the exhibition
had been the subject of articles in several newspapers, including
The Daily News, The Star-Ledger of Newark, The Jersey Journal and
The Hudson Current, a local weekly.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition had attracted more attention, perhaps, because it
was the product of the gallery's first-ever national contest, said
Stephan Shedrowitz, director of exhibitions and an owner of the
gallery.
</P>
<P>
   One grace note Sunday was that the pictures have not been lost
forever; the negatives, Schwartz said, are in a safe-deposit box.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the fire, the gallery went ahead with its previously
scheduled 2 p.m. opening of the show in the garden area, to mark
not only Schwartz's work, but that of the other artists whose
pieces were destroyed in the fire.
</P>
<P>
   There was a touch of bitter irony, too. Guests who had to
negotiate their way past the gallery's broken windows, singed walls
and destroyed photographs were greeted by several signs in front of
the gallery that read: ``Welcome to the War Zone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
