<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAKE DETERMINED TO GET `RIGHT' DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man voted the National Hockey League's best defenseman last
season spent the first day of this year's training camp apart from
his team, burning off energy on an exercise bicycle Sunday and
watching football at his Manhattan Beach home with Kings teammates
Glen Murray and Sean O'Donnell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little different,'' Rob Blake said Sunday afternoon.
``I should be doing something different now. But it's not going to
happen here for a bit, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake, a restricted free agent, has turned down a reported
five-year, $25-million Kings offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's hard to relate and I know (fans) are going to
think whatever,'' said Blake, who earned $3.15 million last year.
``It's difficult. The thing I want to get across is there's going
to be a lot said about the money. But I want to be treated fairly
as a player and until that happens, you're not going to be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the fact that he's eligible for unrestricted free
agency when he turns 31, the 28-year-old Blake said of the Kings'
offer: ``That's for five years, which gives up two years of
(unrestricted) free agency. I'd love to stay here for five years. I
don't want to move. But I'm 28 and this is the biggest contract of
my life. I want to make sure it's the right one.''
</P>
<P>
   Off-ice Berg: Coach Larry Robinson made his strongest statement
to date about an unsigned player, and it wasn't about Blake.
Rather, he is disappointed at the decision by 21-year-old
restricted free-agent defenseman Aki Berg to return to his native
Finland while negotiations proceed. Berg earned $825,000 last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he's getting the right advice,'' Robinson said. ``For a
guy who really hasn't done anything in three years and is ready to
make a statement in the league, he's going about it in the wrong
way. I hope he knows what he's doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is his time to shine and he's not here. When you look at
his statistics, what has he got to base his actions on? He had the
sixth-most minutes played and he had no goals and eight assists.
He's not an offensive star. Do something before you ask for
something. In his case, he's wanting something before he's done
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Berg's agent were unsuccessful and it's not
known whether Berg is considering playing in Finland this season.
But if he were to play even one game there, he would have to clear
NHL waivers before rejoining the Kings this season, an unlikely
scenario for a 21-year-old player chosen third overall in the draft
just three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   On the ice: Two Kings suffered what appeared to be minor
injuries on the first day of practice. Center Jozef Stumpel, the
Kings' leading scorer last season, twisted his right ankle and
might be sidelined for two or three days, and rookie center Eric
Belanger suffered a cut on his nose.
</P>
<P>
   Of the first day's action, Robinson said: ``The pace was pretty
good. But it's not the first day you worry about. It's the second
or third day. That's when the fatigue sets in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
