<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3237 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      09-14 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
An afternoon victory by the Chicago Cubs assured the Astros a
chance to clinch the National League Central Division title on
their own terms.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They took the field Sunday night with a flame in their eyes that
would have sent any fire marshal into a citation-writing frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   False alarm.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Cardinals doused the Astros' plans in
table-turning fashion with a 3-2 come-from-behind victory in the
Astrodome. The Cards' Fernando Tatis entered the game late, but he
was just in time to be a party pooper for the Astros and the 52,338
people on their guest list.
</P>
<P>
   Tatis, who took the field in the fifth inning after Mark McGwire
left because of back spasms, delivered a two-out, two-run double in
the eighth off Astros reliever Doug Henry to put a damper on the
festivities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hung a slider, and (Tatis) tattooed it,'' Henry said. ``It
was a really bad slider. It would have been nice to wrap up the
division today, but it didn't happen. We'll have to come back
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the third time will be the charm. The Astros will take
another crack at locking up the division against the New York Mets
tonight in the first of a four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is disappointed,'' said Jeff Bagwell, who was 4-for-4
to raise his average to .295. ``We wanted to do it today because
there probably won't be a crowd this big tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's crowd saw the Astros' season-high-tying eight-game
winning streak end. Because Atlanta lost, the Astros maintained
sole possession of the NL's best record.
</P>
<P>
   But the only number that seemed to matter Sunday was the ``1''
hanging from the rafters near the left-field foul pole _ the one
representing the Astros' magic number.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're far from panicking,'' Astros catcher Brad Ausmus said.
``This was our first loss in a week. You can't expect us to win
every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals righthander Juan Acevedo survived warning-track fly
balls by pinch hitters Bill Spiers and Dave Clark to earn his ninth
save.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored first on a second-inning single by Ausmus.
Bagwell doubled home Derek Bell to give the Astros a 2-0 lead in
the third.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Astros starter Sean Bergman was doing his best
impersonation of Mike Scott, who pitched a no-hitter the day the
Astros clinched the NL West in 1986. Bergman retired the first nine
batters he faced and took a no-hitter into the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But the early tease ended when Cardinals second baseman Delino
DeShields launched a 1-0 pitch into the right-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of few mistakes by Bergman, who held the Cardinals to
five hits and three runs in 7 innings. Unfortunately for Bergman,
his best outing in about three weeks wasn't enough to help the
Astros lock up their second division title in as many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a tough loss,'' Bergman said. ``I really wanted to be
the guy on the mound at the end of a big game like this. That's
always been a dream of mine. It's too bad we had to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros cranked out seven hits in the first three innings
against Cardinals starter Kent Mercker, but it was quite an
accomplishment to get one runner off the veteran lefty after he
settled into a groove. Mercker retired eight consecutive batters
after Bagwell's RBI double in the third, and he polished off 13 of
the last 14 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' winning rally was ignited by Bergman's only two
walks of the game. He issued free passes to Eli Marrero _ on four
pitches _ and J.D. Drew. Tatis, who was batting in McGwire's spot
in the order, chased both home with a double out of Moises Alou's
reach in left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The four-pitch walk was unacceptable,'' Bergman said.
</P>
<P>
   Alou wasn't much happier with the way he played the ball off
Tatis' bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I should have caught that ball,'' Alou said. ``I
misjudged it. That would have been the game right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Astros seldom go down without at least the threat
of a comeback. The outlook was pretty good in the eighth inning,
but hard-throwing Cardinals reliever Rich Croushore struck out
Alou, who has been the Astros' best clutch hitter all season, with
the tying run at second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come through in that situation a lot of times, but you
can't do it all of the time,'' Alou said. ``I love those
situations. I would have loved to have come through with 50,000
people on their feet, especially after making a mistake in the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't have the best plan up there. I was trying to hit
the ball 10,000 feet instead of just trying to hit it hard
somewhere. I'd love to be in that situation again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're eventually going to clinch it. Whether it's tomorrow or
next week, we will clinch it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 0153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
