<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3239 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     09-14 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DENVER _ It had seemed like such a good idea a week earlier when
Troy Aikman was making like a jackrabbit against the Arizona
Cardinals, darting through the briar patch for 40 yards. Even
rushing for two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   There were plenty of locker-room jokes and chuckles. The Chan
Gailey Era was being ushered in with a new high-tech offensive
weapon, a 31-year-old quarterback with wheels you used to think
belonged up on milk crates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slash,'' they called Troy Aikman after he went in twice for
scores. ``Flash,'' they called him for the way he looked like a
jumbo jet rolling down the runway as he beat the Cardinals
defenders to the outside on one particularly surprising takeoff
into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Aikman can add a new nickname to his collection. Call him
``Crash.''
</P>
<P>
   That's ``Crash'' for the way he turned upfield on a scramble
early in the second quarter in an attempt to squeeze by linebacker
Bill Romanowski and gain an extra two yards.
</P>
<P>
   That's ``Crash'' in the way he slammed hard into the Mile High
Stadium turf, was hit by defensive end Marvin Washington and
suffered a broken collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   With the prognosis Aikman will be sidelined four to eight weeks,
that also might be the sound that describes the Cowboys' season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crash.'' As in the recent Dow Jones averages. Suddenly, it's a
bear market for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to lose to the defending Super Bowl champions.
But it's an entirely different thing to have your defense torched
42-23 and lose the cog to your offense on the same afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what people are going to say, that I did a lot of
running last week and the idea of having me out there is too
risky,'' Aikman said. ``But this wasn't a designed play. It was a
scramble. I saw Romanowski, and I thought I could get an angle on
him for a couple of extra yards. Then I got hurt. It was one of
those freakish things that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Freakish, maybe. But unnecessary and unthinking from a 10-year
veteran who knows what is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   You can understand it and not excuse it at the same time. On the
other side of the field, after 16 years in the NFL, the Broncos'
John Elway has it in his head to take on a linebacker from time to
time. The image from the Super Bowl, when Elway was smashed and
spun around by the Packers, stays in your mind. In Denver's opener
against New England, Elway took off and ran five times. On one
occasion, he had his bell rung louder than a fire alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think I'm going to stop doing that, you're crazy,''
Elway said. ``That's the way I play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is the same macho response Aikman offered up after the
game, while standing there with his left arm in a sling.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in the two quarterbacks is not only Elway's
better speed and mobility but that he is not, like Aikman, the
poster boy for NFL head injuries. Aikman has had more concussions
than Rush Limbaugh has chins, and every time he decides to
challenge a defender he risks his career. Not to mention crippling
the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the offense falls into the hands of Jason Garrett, a nice
Ivy League boy from Princeton with six years as an understudy on
his rsum. He also has a throwing arm that, compared to Aikman's, is
a popgun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Due to his arm strength, there are probably some things that
we won't be able to do with Jason,'' Gailey said. ``But we are
going to ask him to do a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey has to ask for a lot out of his quarterback and his
offense, because his defense has more holes than the one coming out
of the White House. The Broncos scored five touchdowns on their
first five possessions of the first half. Elway completed 16 of 22
passes for 268 yards and two touchdowns. Terrell Davis carried the
ball 23 times for 191 yards and three TDs, including runs of 63 and
59 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody but Sammy Sosa scored against the Cowboys in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not so surprising, considering Dallas gets no defensive
pressure from its front seven and had Darren Woodson, Kevin Smith
and Omar Stoutmire roaming around the secondary looking like Moe,
Larry and Shemp. (Please, don't insult Curly.)
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys had any hope this season, it was to outscore
their opponents. Now, they must do that without their triggerman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a violent game, and there are a lot of big hits,'' Aikman
said with a shrug. ``I believe the league has done all that it can
to prevent the quarterback position from getting hurt too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   After all these years, Crash Aikman can't say the same.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
