<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL QBS ON BOUNTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Streams of unconsciousness while wishing NFL teams would go deep
as often as Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire:
</P>
<P>
   I can see the NFL's future as clearly as Ken Starr can see
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   I see an epidemic of biblical proportions as quarterbacks fall
faster than the Dow. The Big Picture in the NFL is an X-ray. On any
given Sunday, a quarterback's career may come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   For those counting at home, 10 NFL teams have already had to
change quarterbacks because of injuries in two weeks of plays.
That's 33 percent of the teams in the league with an eighth of the
season in the books.
</P>
<P>
   George Blanda and Vince Evans, wherever you are, please suit up.
</P>
<P>
   At this rate of attrition, it is very easy to predict the first
seven picks in the 1999 NFL draft. They will be, in alphabetical
order, Michael Bishop, Tim Couch, Daunte Culpepper, Brock Huard,
Donovan McNabb, Cade McNown and Tim Rattay. The next Big Thing in
sports will be prep All-American quarterbacks skipping college so
they can play in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL, of course, is not a pee wee football league that thinks
safety first. These are well-grown young men playing a physical,
intense game, and its audience does not care to watch flag
football. Insisting the league step in between its quarterbacks and
Warren Sapp is the quickest path to wimp-dom.
</P>
<P>
   But the injury rate does nothing for the growth of the game.
Troy Aikman (fractured collarbone), Brad Johnson (leg) and John
Elway (hamstring) left games Sunday, a week after seven starters
were KO'd from games. It would be a mighty shame if your favorite
team's season swung on the strength of its backup quarterbacks. ...
</P>
<P>
   That's where a few teams are already at. The new Redskins
starter is Trent Green. The Cowboys will start Jason Garrett with
Aikman out for a month or two. Rich Gannon (K.C.), Eric Zeier
(Baltimore) and Danny Wuerffel (New Orleans) are starting now while
the regulars heal.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like the league is flush with 30 good starters, either.
Four starters, all future Hall of Famers, are nearing retirement
age: Warren Moon (41), Elway (38), Dan Marino (37 Tuesday) and
Steve Young (37 in October). Two others, Peyton Manning and Ryan
Leaf, are rookies.
</P>
<P>
   The next tier would be a five-pack of quality starters: Aikman,
Johnson, Drew Bledsoe, Mark Brunell and Brett Favre. They're
followed by a group that still has more promise than performance:
Kordell Stewart, Steve McNair and Rob Johnson. The Jets (Glenn
Foley, 3 interceptions Sunday) and Cardinals (Jake Plummer) hope
their quarterbacks rise to that level.
</P>
<P>
   If they do not, they'll join Jeff George, Chris Chandler, Jim
Harbaugh and Neil O'Donnell as guys good enough to start but not
good enough to win much. Or worse, they'll become the Lions' Scott
Mitchell (15-for-31 and an OT pick returned for a TD) and the Rams'
Tony Banks (four picks), fellows who may soon be demoted.
</P>
<P>
   And for who? Look at the ages of some backups Steve DeBerg (44,
Falcons), Dave Krieg (39, Oilers), Jeff Hostetler (38, Redskins),
Frank Reich (36, Lions), Doug Flutie (35, Bills), Randall
Cunningham (35, Vikes), Steve Beuerlein (33, Panthers) and Rodney
Peete (32, Eagles).
</P>
<P>
   And look at the others, who don't even have age on their side:
Kelly Holcomb (Colts), Jamie Martin (Jags), Scott Zolak (Pats),
Steve Stenstrom (Bears), Rick Mirer (Packers), Kent Graham
(Giants), Steve Bono (Rams), Ty Detmer (49ers) and Steve Walsh
(Bucs). No wonder Vinny Testaverde (Jets) and Mike Tomczak
(Steelers) are still on a roster. ...
</P>
<P>
   With this dearth, it's a wonder NFL coaches haven't junked their
playbook and West Coast offenses and adopted the old single wing or
wishbone.
</P>
<P>
   Some have, sort of. Brunell threw only 18 passes Sunday in the
Jags' win. The Saints (Mike Ditka) and Jets (Bill Parcells) worked
overtime this offseason to upgrade their running game. Denver
finally won a Super Bowl last year when Terrell Davis emerged as a
complement for Elway.
</P>
<P>
   And look at the Fish. Jimmy Johnson is having his way in Miami
with a ground-oriented attack. Dan Marino has attempted just 50
passes in two games. Miami is 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best way to protect your quarterback is not to use
him. ...
</P>
<P>
   Here's one example why college football is so enjoyable. Seven
of the top eight teams in the new AP poll won games Saturday by
margins of 18, 21, 32, 36, 45, 49 and 67. Yet despite those
whackings, there were also major upsets of Florida State, Michigan,
Notre Dame and Arizona State. ...
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State, the co-favorite in the Pac-10 race, is now 0-2.
So much for the Sun Devils hosting the national title game. But
this doesn't mean the Pac-10 is having a down year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Washington looks strong, Arizona and Oregon are much
better than their preseason status indicated, and USC, Cal and
Oregon State seem improved, too. Everyone thought UCLA's
Washington-USC parlay in November would be its their
</P>
<P>
   challenge, but now it may be the back-to-back Arizona-Oregon
games in October. ...
</P>
<P>
   UCLA and Bob Toledo very likely will have to hire a new
offensive coordinator next season, because Al Borges is very likely
to receive offers to be a college head coach or NFL coordinator
next season.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' offense may be the smoothest drive in the nation. It
is both balanced and innovative, and so much more exciting and
sophisticated than the West Coast offense.
</P>
<P>
   That offense is special when you have players like Steve Young
and Jerry Rice. But it has been adopted and co-opted to the point
where it has become a boring cliche. ...
</P>
<P>
   R. Jay Soward's night against San Diego State shows that this
town is plenty big enough for two good teams as opposed to, say the
Rams and Raiders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
