<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPBEAT DUCKS OPEN CAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ After a summer of front-office discontent, the Mighty
Ducks finally turned their attention to the ice Sunday when
training camp opened at Disney Ice.
</P>
<P>
   Former Chicago coach Craig Hartsburg put his new team through
its paces as new president and general manager Pierre Gauthier and
former GM Jack Ferreira, among others, looked on.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a year that goalie Guy Hebert called ``a disaster,''
the Ducks are already one step ahead of the game when compared to
last year at this time _ both Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne are in
camp from day one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time we will be starting the season
together. I think it's really important, and really a good sign,''
said Selanne, who tied the league lead in goals (52) even though
Kariya missed 60 games due to a contract dispute and a
season-ending concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, who missed training camp in 1996 due to an abdominal
injury and was a no-show in '97 when he and the Ducks couldn't
agree on a contract, looked sharp in the opening workout and
admitted a full camp certainly won't hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two times (after missing camp) it took me a while to
get going,'' said Kariya, who scored 17 goals and 31 points in 22
games last year. ``If you've had a full camp you are ready to go in
the first game. It (camp) isn't life or death, but obviously
helps.''
</P>
<P>
   While Kariya and Selanne will provide plenty of offense for the
Ducks, Hartsburg is making defense a priority. And he started
drilling that point home Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal from day one is to improve defensively,'' explained
Hartsburg, who added the Ducks will work especially hard on their
defense in the first three days of workouts. ``Defense is a
commitment thing. You can teach X's and O's, but you can't play
defense without commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, only Vancouver (273) and Tampa Bay (269) allowed more
goals than Anaheim (261).
</P>
<P>
   The opening of camp also marked the return of original Duck Stu
Grimson and defenseman Milos Holan. Holan is attempting to make a
return to hockey, nearly three years after he was diagnosed with
leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   The only significant no-show Sunday was defenseman Fredrik
Olausson, who was found to have an enlarged spleen during his
physical Saturday. He was scheduled to see a specialist today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
