<HEADLINE>
TOP 10 TRIO BOTTOMS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ So much for preseason predictions. Michigan, Florida
State, and Arizona State were all in the Top 10 two weeks ago, each
believing it had a real chance to contend for the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Now they're all gone. Arizona State and Michigan, with 0-2
starts, are history. They're not only out of the Top 10, they're
out of the Top 25. Florida State still can recover, but the
Seminoles' 24-7 loss to North Carolina State Saturday was a
stunner, not so much because FSU lost _ Bobby Bowden's team always
seem to stumble at least once a season _ but because it clearly was
no fluke.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolfpack gave Florida State all it could handle last year in
Tallahassee before getting outscored, 48-35.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm pretty stunned,'' said Bowden, who knows his team
has no margin for error if it hopes to make it to Tempe, Ariz., for
the national championship game in the Fiesta Bowl Jan. 4. ``To get
beat like that, I'm very surprised how we fell apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Falling apart doesn't begin to describe what is happening at
Michigan and Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   After losses to Notre Dame and Syracuse, Michigan is 0-2 for the
first time since 1988, the second time since 1959. The only thing
the Wolverines have going for them is the incentive to upset No.
1-ranked Ohio State in Columbus Nov. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State is an enigma. The Sun Devils lost a heartbreaker
at home against Washington in their opener last week. A letdown was
inevitable. But Saturday night, in a 26-6 loss to Brigham Young,
ASU stunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``They outplayed us,'' said Arizona State coach Bruce Snyder.
``We do need to play a lot better, but I believe in this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is good, since right now no one else does.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week's Give Me a Break Award goes to Kansas State coach
 &UR; Bill Snyder &LR; . Kansas State was leading mighty Northern Illinois,
56-7, with two seconds left in the first half. What did Snyder do?
He sent All-American  &UR; Martin Gramatica  &LR; in to kick a school-record
65-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   To make things worse, Snyder kept in first-string quarterback
 &UR; Michael Bishop  &LR; in the third quarter, and Bishop capped a scoring
drive by throwing a 27-yard pass that made it 66-7.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Illinois has lost its last 20 games.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast this with the class shown by Boston College coach  &UR; Tom
O'Brien &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who in the waning moments of Saturday's 41-14 win over
Rutgers chose to run the ball instead of pass it, even on a third
and 12 from the BC 37.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Florida State quarterback  &UR; Chris Weinke  &LR; is in the Seminoles'
record book only two games into his career as a starter. He threw a
record six interceptions in the loss to North Carolina State ...
When is Prairie View going to catch a break? It had an 8-point
halftime lead against Division 3 Howard Payne Saturday. Final
score? 22-14, Howard Payne. Prairie View's NCAA-record losing
streak is now 79. ``It was a situation we've never been in
before,'' Prairie View coach  &UR; Glen Johnson &LR;  said of the lead. ``And
the kids didn't really know how to respond.'' Prairie View has not
won since Oct. 28, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Give credit to Notre Dame coach  &UR; Bob Davie  &LR; for candor if
nothing else. Following Notre Dame's 45-23 loss to Michigan State,
Davie had no excuses. ``I'm embarrassed, this football team's
embarrassed,'' said Davie, who watched his team fall behind, 42-3,
at the half ... While Notre Dame was down, Illinois was
celebrating. The Illini snapped an 18-game losing streak by beating
Middle Tennessee, 48-20. However, the longest losing streak in
Division 1-A still belongs to a team from Illinois: Northern
Illinois ... Best Name of the Week: Oregon running back  &UR; Herman
Ho-Ching &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who had 117 yards on 13 carries to lead the Ducks to a
33-26 win over Texas-El Paso ... Oregon and Oregon State are a
combined 0-4, and Michigan, Notre Dame, and Arizona State a
combined 1-5 ... Heisman Trophy contenders are putting up some
strong early numbers. Central Florida, a team still looking for a
league, improved to 2-0 as  &UR; Daunte Culpepper  &LR; completed 28 of 33
passes for 406 yards and four touchdowns and ran for three more in
a 48-0 win over Division 1-AA Eastern Illinois. Let's see how
Culpepper does this week, when he meets Purdue in West Lafayette,
Ind. Kentucky's  &UR; Tim Couch  &LR; threw for 372 yards and five TDs in a
52-7 win over Division 1-AA Eastern Kentucky. Kentucky has the No.
1 offense in the nation, while Central Florida is No. 4.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time to start our weekly look at poll glitches. Let's start with
the writer's poll. Michigan and Arizona State are 0-2 and still got
Top 25 votes. If losing games _ and losing them badly _ is a
criterion, maybe Prairie View should get votes next week. And in
the coaches' poll, Notre Dame is ranked 25th, while Michigan State
received only 6 points. And, of course, there's North Carolina
State, with a 2-0 record and a solid win over 1-1 Florida State.
This week's poll: FSU No. 11, N.C. State No. 24. What people seem
to forget is that it's a weekly poll, and the rankings should
reflect that. Is North Carolina State a better team than Florida
State? Probably not. But Saturday it was, and with a better record,
its ranking should reflect that ... Other than Rutgers and Temple,
who clearly are hopeless, the Big East is having a great season.
Boston College, Miami, West Virginia, Virginia Tech, and Syracuse
are all worthy of Top 25 consideration.
</P>
</TEXT>
