<HEADLINE>
BC (2-0) IS JUST GETTING STARTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Two down, two to go.
</P>
<P>
   After winning its first two games of the season, scoring 41
points in each victory, Boston College is halfway to a 4-0
September. The Eagles drew one step closer to that goal by scoring
a 41-14 conference victory over Rutgers Saturday at Alumni Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, though still unranked, continued to better their
showing in the polls, garnering 28 points in the USA Today/ESPN
coaches' poll and 25 in the Associated Press Top 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it, winning is a lot better than losing,''
said senior left guard Doug Brzezinski. ``It's a lot better than
the previous situations we've been in. Hey, right now we're 2-0 and
it's a lot better than being 0-2.''
</P>
<P>
   BC's start, its best since a 7-0-1 beginning in 1992, certainly
is a vast improvement over a year ago, when the Eagles stumbled out
of the blocks, sustaining a 28-21 loss at Temple in Tom O'Brien's
debut as BC coach.
</P>
<P>
   BC next hosts Temple, which will arrive at Chestnut Hill
Saturday for its conference opener with an 0-2 record. After
dropping their season opener at Toledo, 24-12, the Owls bowed to
another Mid-American Conference opponent, Akron, 35-28. But no one
on BC's roster is deceived by Temple's struggles. They all remember
last year's upset in Philly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This week is payback,'' said junior free safety Pedro Cirino,
who must prepare to face an option-oriented Temple offense that
ranks fourth in the nation in rushing, with 298.5 yards per game.
``Option football is so assignment-oriented; it's going to be a
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite several lapses _ one that led to a 56-yard TD pass from
Mike McMahon to Bill Powell for a 7-0 lead; and another that
resulted in a 54-yard catch by Andy Holland on a third-and-8 _ BC's
defense held Rutgers to 271 yards of total offense, 53 rushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we take each game at a time,'' said junior nose guard
Chris Hovan, who was credited with seven tackles and a pair of
sacks for 20 yards in losses. ``We gave up 31 points (in Week 1),
but if we gave up 7 last week and 31 this week, then we're not
getting better. We're making strides to make this a better defense.
As long as we're taking steps forward and not backward, then this
defense is going to be really good.''
</P>
<P>
   For the second consecutive week, after its 41-31 season-opening
triumph at Georgia Tech, BC generated 41 points from a balanced
attack that produced 486 yards of total offense. But when Rutgers
cut BC's lead to 20-14 on a 28-yard interception return by Reggie
Stephens, the Eagles responded with a seven-play, 80-yard scoring
march.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to play up and down and think we can turn it
on,'' O'Brien said. ``I want us to play consistent all the time and
keep working to get better. I don't like this, just turning it on,
because someday when you try to turn it on it ain't going to be
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the drive was, as senior quarterback Scott Mutryn said,
``a telling moment for the team,'' because it sparked a decisive
21-point eruption.
</P>
<P>
   Senior running back Mike Cloud, who had 201 all-purpose yards
(156 rushing, 45 receiving), capped the drive with a 6-yard swan
dive that gave BC a 27-14 lead with 52 seconds left in the third.
Cloud gained 73 yards on the drive, including 67 on the first four
plays: a 1-yard carry, an 18-yard catch, and back-to-back runs of
25 and 23 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we do anything special,'' said Cloud. ``We go
into every game thinking we can play smash-mouth football. We're
going to bring the run and open it up for Scotty to throw some
passes. I think we prepare the same for each team.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Mutryn, ``When the chips were down and we needed to make a
play, we got our composure and we started making plays. There's
just a confidence that the guy next to you is going to be doing his
job and you can count on him from the first snap to the last
whistle. And when you have that kind of confidence in one another,
good things are going to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
