<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEINZE BACK IN BRUINS' FOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Mass. _ The Bruins Sunday practiced as a team for
the first time this preseason at the Ristuccia Center with only one
of their five Group 2 free agents in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Steve Heinze agreed to terms on a two-year deal and
joined his mates for the afternoon scrimmage. The situation before
he settled his contract was a bit chaotic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a miscommunication,'' said Heinze, who signed a pact
that is believed to be worth about $1 million a year. Heinze said
his agent, Steve Mountain, ``agreed to recommend the contract to me
on Friday. He came to me and said, `I think you should take it.' I
said, `Let me think about it.' We had until midnight Saturday.
Steve left (president/general manager) Harry Sinden a message
Saturday night, but he never got it. I came to camp and he didn't
know I had taken it. Sometimes the telephone doesn't work so well.
But it's all agreed to now.''
</P>
<P>
   Free agents Jason Allison, Anson Carter, and Kyle McLaren
remained out of camp. The sides are worlds apart in those
negotiations. Ted Donato is home, too, but not because of money. He
is hoping to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are banking on the 28-year-old Heinze, who had 26
goals in 61 games last season, to provide some scoring punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need his goals,'' said Sinden. ``He plays hard. He can play
either side and the fact he can play left wing is pretty important
to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said confidence is a key issue with Heinze. At times, he
hasn't had enough of it, but Sinden said he thinks the player has
overcome that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not so much the last couple of years, but he's kind of been
his own worst enemy,'' said Sinden. ``He gets down on himself when
things aren't going well and I think it gets worse for him and
that's why he goes into those slumps. As he gets a little older,
you don't notice it as much.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinze has had streaky periods in his career. However, the most
substantial obstacles for him the past two seasons have been
injuries. He had 17 goals in his first 30 games in 1996-97 but then
missed the rest of the season because of abdominal and knee
injuries. Last year he missed seven games with a right ankle sprain
and another 14 with a broken left foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play 80 games and stay consistent for those 80
games,'' said Heinze of 1998-99. ``By doing that, I'm pretty
confident I'll put up some good numbers. My goal going in is
definitely consistency and health.''
</P>
<P>
   In seasons in which the coach has used Heinze in more defensive
roles, he has been healthy. When he's shown offensive flourish,
he's gotten hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``A full year of being relied on, being on the power play, being
on the top two or three lines, that would be great,'' he said.
``That in itself would be a career year for me. The numbers would
probably follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinze is relieved, too, that with a two-year deal he won't have
to spend next summer haggling over a contract, which he's had to do
the last few years. He has other plans. He is scheduled to be
married next offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contract has a little security in it which is something I
haven't had for a while,'' he said. ``I think I'll enjoy next
summer a lot more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 0212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
