<SLUG> BC-SAIL-ETCHELLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETCHELLS WORLD A DREAM FOR CANADIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARBLEHEAD, Mass. _ The names of sailors near the front of the
103-boat fleet were familiar. Star-quality stuff: Dennis Conner,
Dave Curtis, Russell Coutts ... By anyone's standard, a dream
regatta.
</P>
<P>
   But when the gun fired to end Day 1 of the Etchells World
Championships, being raced here this week, it was a lesser-known
Canadian team of Dirk Kneulman, Paul Sustronk, and Allan Harvey who
placed first in the largest and most talented Etchells fleet ever
assembled on a world class race course.
</P>
<P>
   Playing wind shifts to perfection and keeping their air clear in
the huge fleet, the Canadians finished the first leg in the top
five, poured on the coal to take the lead halfway up the second
beat, and then extended to a 40-second lead at the fourth leg, a
run to the leeward mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a fleet this big, you never feel comfortable with a lead,''
said Kneulman, who comes from Oakland, Ontario, and is racing in
his seventh Etchells worlds.
</P>
<P>
   A strong wind had built up big, lumpy seas by the time the fleet
got a start around 1 p.m. And while the seas flattened out later,
the wind held fairly steady until the end of the 10-mile race.
After a general recall in the first start, only four boats were
over 10 minutes later, and the fleet tacked off to the east toward
the windward mark.
</P>
<P>
   In second place was the Chicago team of Ben Atlman and Scheiber
Mahon, who managed to nose Conner into third place, a spot he does
not mind at this point in the regatta. Said Conner, winner of three
of four of the Etchells worlds he has raced, and famed for his
America's Cup exploits, ``If you could take five thirds in this
regatta, you'd win it by 40 points.''
</P>
<P>
   Conner was referring to the talent-laden field, and a fleet so
huge that the start line stretches for three-quarters of a mile and
needs three boats to officiate the start.
</P>
<P>
   Conner said he was ``on a racing holiday'' from his preparation
for the America's Cup next year in Auckland, New Zealand. Defending
Cup champion Coutts placed sixth, about half a minute off Conner's
pace.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the best performances in the closing legs of the race
came from Marblehead's Curtis, a repeat world champion in several
classes, and the sailor many in this regatta regard one of the
heavy favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, who finished just behind the fourth-place team of Carl
Anderson and Moffet Thorpe, from Buzzards Bay, appeared to have
fallen out of the top 10 before putting together a strong finishing
leg to place fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Eastern Yacht Club after his first race of six,
Conner summed up his view of the competition. ``If you can beat
Dave Curtis,'' he said, ``you can win this regatta.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
