<HEADLINE>
ZENGA PROVIDES ZIP FOR REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Revolution lost a significant part of
their playoff hopes during the weekend, but they took steps toward
gaining something more important.
</P>
<P>
   They defeated Columbus, 2-0, Saturday night but remained 6
points behind Miami for the final playoff place in the Eastern
Conference after the Fusion edged D.C. United, 4-3, Sunday. Miami
can clinch a playoff berth with one victory in its final three
matches.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Revolution fail to qualify for the playoffs for the
second time in Major League Soccer's three-year history, they seem
to have discovered a coach/lucky charm in Walter Zenga.
</P>
<P>
   How important has Zenga been to the Revolution? In three years,
they are 15-44-8 without him and 13-9-4 with him as either coach or
player. Next year, Zenga hopes to become the Revolution's
player-coach, which should guarantee at least some success for the
team.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Zenga has displayed a winning touch as a coach. He has
reorganized the team's defense, leading to successive 2-0 victories
over the Metro-Stars and Crew, the Revolution's first back-to-back
shutouts ever. He has made effective, timely substitutions. And he
has added intangible qualities and eliminated some of the pressure
from the players.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga is still in the process of making the transition from the
playing field, but he seems comfortable in the role of authority.
It has been a quick process, starting with the Aug. 22 proposal
that he take over from Thomas Rongen to the 3-2 loss at Miami in
his first game eight days later. In that game, in the South Florida
sun, Zenga seemed more like a player, wearing shorts and a backward
baseball cap. By his third game, he had changed to a dark blue
suit, but kept the cap on backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter is flamboyant and unorthodox,'' general manager Brian
O'Donovan said Sunday. ``But there is no question who is charge of
this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga's flexibility, lankiness, and reactions made him appear to
be a born goalkeeper. But though Zenga sometimes seems an anomaly
as an authority figure, he is also a born leader who is comfortable
instructing players and managing a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is giving us a model for professionalism,'' O'Donovan said.
``Players have to play as a team, and he will not accept anything
less. Everyone knows they are on equal footing. If players are
discontent, he himself has been in that situation and he
understands both sides. It's an epiphany for him to be in charge
and making decisions. He sees himself in the players, in the best-
and the worst-case scenarios.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have regained credibility, a crucial quality
especially with a 35,462 crowd Saturday and another nearly 50,000
expected for the final two regular-season games, against Tampa Bay
next Saturday and the MetroStars Sept. 26. Hope for the future has
been regained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not go overboard one way or the other,'' O'Donovan
said. ``Walter is a very strong personality on a team that has
struggled with its personality without him. We have found our
personality directly through Walter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Walter decided to retire in December, he started seeing
his future and realized his mistake, and now he is really drawn to
the project that is American soccer, and that part of his soul has
been planted here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
