<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-PRESSURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX WOES A PRESSING ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Going on the road may be good for us, you know?'' _ &UR;  &LR; Mo
Vaughn &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We know, Mo. Everyone knows.
</P>
<P>
   You can gauge what kind of afternoon it was Sunday at Fenway
Park when the feel-good events du jour in the Boston clubhouse were
the announcement of a contract extension for Bret Saberhagen and
the distribution of meal money for the week.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox had lost, again, to the, ahem, Tigers, the supposed
September panacea for the struggling team. The Red Sox are now just
three games up on Toronto in the wild-card race and are on the road
this week with games in New York, Baltimore, and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   They will be away from newspapers (unless they're online kinda
guys) and talk radio and the fatalist, Calvinist essence of most
every Red Sox fan. By the time they return, the wild-card race
could be moot or, well, you know.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams, the ever-optimistic manager, already is tired of
all the negative what-ifs. He made several not-so-subtle jabs at
the inevitable reaction to the team's latest misfortune, a 4-1
loss. He's been here less than two years _ this is his first
experience when the team is a playoff threat _ and he's already got
a pretty good read on the vox populi.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not you people,'' he said, unconvincingly, to reporters.
``We all want the same thing, the same goal. We're after the same
thing. It's a mutual admiration society.'' He smiled, the sort of
smile you might see from an IRS agent during an audit.
</P>
<P>
   Any pressure, skip?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not with us. We're basically in the same place we were a week
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he sense any uneasiness among the faithful?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got 20-20 hearing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have lost eight of their last 10 games, including
the last two of this weekend series to the horrible Tigers. They
struggled against a pitching staff not to be confused with the 1954
Indians or the 1971 Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in a good position,'' offered Steve Avery, who
took a no-hitter into the fifth, a shutout into the sixth, and a
shower after getting the hook in the seventh. ``I'd be nervous if I
was a fan. But as long as we're in this situation, we don't have to
worry. The only time we have to worry is if we get behind
(Toronto/-Texas), and I don't think that's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Even using today's trendy whole math, where there is no answer
book, the Red Sox are still in pretty good shape. They have 15
games remaining, seven against the White Sox and Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents and venues never seem to matter in situations like
these. Who could have imagined scuffling in the last two games
against the Tigers? Who could have envisioned Vaughn, Nomar
Garciaparra, and Troy O'Leary all striking out in the ninth? (The
Sox also had three strikeouts in the eighth and one in the seventh,
10 overall.)
</P>
<P>
   Avery said he thinks the Red Sox might be pressing, but he added
that most teams do under similar circumstances. ``There's always a
difference in September,'' he said. ``But Jimy has been through
this and he's the one we feed off. He doesn't panic. We don't
panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought the team was right, Vaughn snorted, ``I
would hope not.'' He added, ``You gotta want to be here. It's when
you lose that gets everyone excited. It's a big panic now. But no
one cared when we were winning earlier in the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn knows better than most about all the inherent angst that
will continue to bubble until the season ends. He still likes the
team's position and its chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the lead and that's the way you have to look at
it,'' he said. ``There's no time for frustration, pressing, getting
down, none of that. It's not how many games you get in by. It's
getting in there that matters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
