</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-TIGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARK HR SENDS RED SOX ON ROAD FOR REFUGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Let's face it, the Red Sox need to get out of town.
Watching a wild-card contender self-destruct at Fenway Park hasn't
been fun.
</P>
<P>
   Fenway certainly wasn't a very happy place Sunday in the wake of
a 4-1 loss to the Detroit Tigers that put the Olde Towne Team on
its heels again and a crowd of 31,255 into a blue funk. The Blue
Jays are within three games in the wild-card race. Boston's next
seven games are on the road, starting Monday night against the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox lost four of six games at home and have lost eight of
their last 10. The lowly Tigers won two straight after losing on
Friday, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing hard,'' said manager Jimy Williams. ``We're
pitching good. We haven't been scoring a lot of runs lately. But we
don't accept losing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get the kind of pitching we've gotten in the last few
days, we're going to win a lot of games. We didn't get this far by
just going out there. We've competed all year long. We're not going
to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers won for the second straight time with a late home
run. Saturday, the Sox lost, 3-2, on a two-run ninth-inning blast
by Joe Randa. Sunday Tony Clark hit a three-run shot off reliever
Greg Swindell to break a 1-1 tie in the eighth. All three runs were
unearned because of shortstop Nomar Garciaparra's 24th error of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Is the party over?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' said first baseman Mo Vaughn. ``This is no time
for frustration. This is no time for pressing. I don't understand
why everybody is getting excited. We're still in first place in the
wild-card race. We've still got an opportunity to do some things.
We have just got to put some wins together. That's the bottom
line.''
</P>
<P>
   If you went by the number of grim faces and tough questions
being asked these days, you'd certainly think the Sox were on the
ropes. The confidence of two weeks ago is missing. The hitting is
off. Boston has scored only three runs in the last 20 innings. The
pitching is just good enough to get beaten. Not a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing to come home and play the way we did,''
said starter Steve Avery, who worked six innings and gave up one
earned run. ``I don't like the fact that we lost four of six after
playing so well all year here. We definitely have to pick it up.
We're not going to be able to back into the playoffs. We have to go
in with some wins.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox started the day with 83 wins. One would think 90 wins is
attainable, and would be good enough for any wild-card team. But it
won't be if Toronto doesn't stop winning. Given the history of
Boston teams, this is a feeling Red Sox fans know too well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to just go out and play,'' said Vaughn. ``Don't try to
do too much. Don't force it. Do it pitch by pitch, at-bat by
at-bat. The game hasn't changed since the time we were playing
well. It's just one of those things that happens, and we've got to
go about it as professionals.''
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the eighth, Garciaparra muffed a routine
grounder by Brian Hunter. Bobby Higginson struck out for what would
have been the third out. But Juan Encarnacion singled to center and
Clark followed with his 32d home run of the year, which cleared the
left-field screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't much to it,'' said Swindell, who blamed himself
rather than Garciaparra. ``One changeup, right into his swing. He
got it. This game is hard and we're all struggling right now. The
team has been through it before. We have to dig down deep and keep
playing. Every game means something. It's time to dig down deep and
see what you got.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for home cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to go on the road and get untracked,'' said
Williams. ``Slump? I don't feel it in the clubhouse. We're putting
some good at-bats up there. We're just not getting hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, said Avery, it comes down to having a little luck.
``We need to get a break here and there and try to get the momentum
going the other way,'' he said. ``We're pressing a little. But
those other teams are pressing, too. I think we just need to relax
and have some fun out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
