</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-ECON (Buenos Aires) _ It has become almost a daily
ritual. President Carlos Saul Menem and his chief economic advisers
take every opportunity to promise they will not retreat from the
government's fixed exchange rate that pegs the value of the
Argentine peso to the American dollar one to one. Such
pronouncements have often preceded huge devaluations in Latin
America. But most Argentine economists and Wall Street analysts are
taking Menem at his word, at least for now, despite concerns that
the currency peg could push up interest rates and unemployment. By
Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
