<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEN TRIUMPH A WALTZ FOR AUSSIE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Waltzing Matilda,'' the Australian national anthem,
came out of Queensland, and so did Patrick Michael Rafter, the
Australian national hero _ waltzing his way to the US Open title
and taking it Down Under once more.
</P>
<P>
   What a dancing master Rafter was _ an Astaire in sneakers _
cakewalking blithely across Arthur's Gulch, the year-old stadium at
Flushing Meadow, to extend his lease on the massive tennis palace
named for the champ of 30 years ago, Arthur Ashe. It takes two to
tangle on a court, and the party of the second part, hulking Mark
Philippoussis, just couldn't keep up as Rafter led, and kept
swirling them faster and faster, 6-3, 3-6, 6-2, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   But 21-year-old Philippoussis, in his major final debut, is an
Aussie, too, and you wondered, sitting there among the sun-draped
mob of 21,447, if a new Down Undertaking plague has been launched.
Sitting there, too, with patriotic smiles on their weathered faces,
were Ken Rosewall and Tony Roche, the champ and runner-up 28 years
ago, the last all-Aussie title-round party of 10 that had concluded
US Championships over 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we may be back in business,'' grinned Australian Davis
Cup captain John Newcombe, the last pre-Rafter US Open champ from
their neighborhood in 1973. ``When we dominated, the tournament was
on grass. It's been hard courts here since 1978, and Patrick and
Mark are real breakthroughs for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Queensland, the huge but lightly populated northeast state, has
produced far more than its share of US Open champs: Mal Anderson,
Roy Emerson (whom Pete Sampras continues to stalk), Rod Laver, and
now Rafter, cutting up seven titles among them.
</P>
<P>
   Way out in the Outback, about a century ago in a dusty cow town
called Winton, the country's favorite poet, A.B. (Banjo) Paterson
wrote the words to ``Waltzing Matilda,'' a bush hymn that lifted
Aussie spirits through two world wars and identifies them wherever
they go. Rafter had his own stringed banjo, a racket on which for
two hours he played an ominous tune such as seldom has been heard
on a tennis court at this level.
</P>
<P>
   It was the twang of doom for the 6-foot-4-inch outsider, No. 22
Philippoussis, who found that prying points from Rafter was like
getting the US to pay its UN debt. Rafter, less charitable than
Scrooge, contributed all of five unforced errors to Philippoussis's
cause. Five of Philippoussis's 85 points was the total of his foe's
generosity. This tightness was reminiscent of John McEnroe's
offering Jimmy Connors but two unforced errors in an airtight 1984
Wimbledon final triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter simply did not give at the office. But he did give his
all in beating Sampras and Philippoussis in succession, and that
``all,'' as we've seen all summer, is merely spectacular. He never
stopped pounding the pavement _ and opponents _ once the hard-court
campaign began in the US following Wimbledon: four titles in six
starts and a 25-2 match record, a 12-straight streak intact.
</P>
<P>
   Over the same stretch Sampras entered four tourneys, won none,
and may have been a victim of the Queensland old boy network, the
Emerson defense force. Sampras, with 11 major titles, came in
expecting to tie Emmo's rec-ord of 12. Rafter, from the copper
mining community of Mt. Isa, made sure Sampras didn't strike gold
at the Meadow.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter and Philippoussis played the kind of in-your-face tennis
that transformed the asphalt rectangle to the grass of Wimbledon.
Serve-and-volley, mate, and let's see who wins the race to the net.
Two points _ that's all _ endured as long as seven strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter always won that race even though Philippoussis had longer
legs. As a couple of song-and-dance men, Rafter, the tenor released
``Hehhh!'' notes as he served, generally winning the duets with
Philippoussis's bass ``Wuuuuhh!''
</P>
<P>
   But it was his footwork that left young Philippoussis feeling
like a wallflower at the prom. Call it the Rafter Rhumba _ serve,
four quick steps covering 7 yards, bend, and volley. All afternoon.
Only twice did Rafter forget to charge behind his serve. ``Just
trying to mix things up,'' he said with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know how I'd come up after Sampras. But I was even
stronger, really fit for this kind of tennis. The adrenaline was
flowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Philippoussis found himself constantly repeating the infantile
drill, trying to deal with Rafter's low, troubling returns. ``Too
many volleys at my shoelaces,'' he sighed.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``Waltzing Matilda'' time again in New York, and Matilda
could have only one love this time: Patrick Michael Rafter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
