<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIPPOUSSIS DOWN, UNDER RAFTER BLITZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ And then there were nine.
</P>
<P>
   A gap of nine championships in major tennis tournaments between
Patrick Rafter and Pete Sampras, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter won his second straight US Open by keeping the pressure
on and finally cracking fellow Australian Mark Philippoussis, 6-3,
3-6, 6-2, 6-0, Sunday. Rafter, the No. 2 seed, earned $700,000 for
the win and Philippoussis, who was unseeded and in his first Grand
Slam final, collected $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras recently was asked the difference between his game and
Rafter's: ``Ten Grand Slams,'' joked Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   Make it nine. Rafter made sure Sampras remained stalled at 11
major singles titles _ one short of Roy Emerson's record _ when he
sent Sampras out in Saturday's semifinals after the four-time
champion had hurt his leg.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras left here saying it would take some time to see if his
rivalry with Rafter could develop into something special.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Rafter _ still with a long way to go before reaching the
Sampras level of longevity _ rallied in the third set to steal the
momentum from Philippoussis. He roared from there to his second
major title, solidifying a claim to his role as rival and
contender.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Rafter leaped into a courtside box to celebrate his
victory over Greg Rusedski. This year, partly because he was
playing a fellow Australian, partly because he had been here
before, and partly because of the way the match ended, he was a
little more subdued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the initial feeling was not quite as exciting as
last year,'' Rafter said. ``Don't get me wrong, take nothing away
from this title, but last year I think was a little more
nerve-racking.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter played nearly flawless tennis. He had two unforced errors
in the final two sets and five for the match to the 29 of his
countryman.
</P>
<P>
   Philippoussis had only three break points on Rafter's serve in
the match and won only one. Rafter's attacking style helped make
sure Philippoussis, often a serving machine, struggled on serve.
Philippoussis had 13 double faults in the match and only five aces.
Rafter had six aces and one double fault.
</P>
<P>
   Still, things did not look that great for Rafter in the second
set. He was down a break and Philippoussis was serving to even the
match when he got himself in a huge hole at 15-40 with three
straight double faults. But Philippoussis escaped and took the set.
</P>
<P>
   On to the third set where Philippoussis again wiggled free from
15-40. Finally, Rafter, on his fourth break point of the sixth
game, converted one. It was deuce when Rafter won the point of the
match. Philippoussis had gotten back to deuce the point before with
a nice overhead. This time, Philippoussis had another overhead and
couldn't put it away and Rafter, hustling from side to side,
punched a forehand over the net and Philippoussis netted a volley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that was a bit disappointing,'' Philippoussis said. ``It
was a bad choice of shot for myself. You know, Pat is very quick
around the court.''
</P>
<P>
   The rout was on.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter won 22 of the next 26 points, including 12 straight, and
was on his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started making a lot of passing shots, a lot of returns, a
lot of tough shots for him,'' Rafter said. ``Just a combination of
him losing maybe a bit of spirit, intensity, and myself making him
play very tough shots.''
</P>
<P>
   The turnaround, Rafter said, was fueled a game earlier. Ahead,
40-0, on his serve, he nearly squandered his advantage. A forehand
volley into the net got it to deuce and Rafter angrily threw his
racket to the ground. On the next point, Philippoussis hit a
forehand into the net and Rafter, at the net, let out a sigh.
Philippoussis then put a backhand into the net and Rafter clenched
his fist and went on to his big break.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, it was over.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter, whose Open title last year was only his second
championship of any kind, had taken another major step.
</P>
<P>
   And Rafter, who scrambled from two sets down just to survive a
first-round match with Hicham Arazi, was feeling pretty good about
things.
</P>
<P>
   He still has a long way to go to match the accomplishments of
Sampras, of course. But Rafter is 25, Sampras 27, and Rafter has
beaten the world's No. 1 player twice in a row. And it's quite
obvious that future winners of major championships _ at least this
major championship _ must deal with him.
</P>
<P>
   He proved something to himself, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year I feel I've consolidated,'' Rafter said. ``Maybe I
can kick on and have another great next six months whereas last
year, the last six months weren't quite as advantageous for me as
far as gaining points. I was sort of struggling, I guess, with
maybe if people respected me for what I'd done or, again, if it was
just a fluke.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
