</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COLTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS WISE TO COLTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The game plan was executed.
</P>
<P>
   Make Peyton Manning, the NFL's top draft pick, shoot himself in
the foot. Take advantage of his miscues and move on to next week's
game against the Tennessee Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots broke into the win column Sunday night by
flawlessly executing that game plan. They forced four Manning
turnovers and turned them into points, defeating the Indianapolis
Colts, 29-6, before a sellout crowd of 60,068 at Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defensive line did a great job,'' said Ty Law, who picked
off two passes. Chris Canty had the other. ``They pressured Peyton
into having to throw off his back foot. When that happens, it gives
the secondary a chance to break on the ball better. I figured
Peyton had to throw the ball to my side because his favorite
target, Marvin Harrison, was my responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just took advantage of a rookie quarterback,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots improved to 1-1, winning their first divisional
game with a great defensive performance _ with a big assist to
Manning.
</P>
<P>
   Manning actually passed the ball well most of the night,
completing 21 of 33 for 188 yards. But there were two crucial Law
pickoffs, one of which the cornerback ran back 59 yards for a
score, and another that ruined the Colts' chances of scoring in the
second quarter when Law picked off a pass in the end zone. The
Canty pickoff came after the Patriots had built a comfortable lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots built a 16-0 lead at the half mostly with defense
and Manning mistakes. The New England offense finally cranked it up
in the second half, scoring two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to get up for a team like Denver on Monday night
against the champions,'' said Patriots quarterback Drew Bledsoe.
``But to come back in a short week against a team like this could
be a little dangerous. But we have the maturity now to approach a
game like this and win it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots amassed 321 yards, 218 in the air.
</P>
<P>
   One area that wasn't an artistic success for the Patriots was
the running game. It was never established, with rookie Robert
Edwards gaining 36 yards on 18 carries. Sedrick Shaw broke a
51-yarder in the fourth quarter, but Edwards was more useful in
receiving the ball _ three catches for 71 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The key for the Patriots was that they didn't turn the ball
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been able to play keep-away with the defense,'' said
Bledsoe. ``I've been putting the ball where only our guys can catch
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense was ignited by end Willie McGinest, who set up the
first of Adam Vinatieri's three field goals, a 19-yarder in the
first quarter that came after Edwards was stuffed three times at
the 2-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Manning's arm was hit by McGinest as he attempted to throw,
forcing a loose ball that was picked up briefly by Chris Slade. He
bobbled it, but Willie Clay recovered at the 2.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later Manning underthrew receiver Marcus Pollard on
third and 3 at his 41. Law leaped for the ball, came down with it,
and proceeded 59 yards on some nifty moves to give the Patriots
their first touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   It was Law's second interception return for a touchdown, the
first coming last Dec. 8 against Bill Parcells's New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter, the Colts moved the ball down the field,
but once again Manning made a rookie mistake and threw right into
the hands of Law in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   When the Patriots took over, the offense actually looked OK.
Bledsoe had his finest moment by hitting Shawn Jefferson for a
38-yard gain to the Colt 34. Jefferson made a nice move on Jeff
Burris to break to the sideline and open up enough daylight to make
the play.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe then hit Terry Glenn for a 14-yard gain. But the drive
stalled there. Bledsoe threw to goal line on third and 6 to third
tight end Mike Bartrum, but cornerback Monty Montgomery broke up
the play from behind to force the Patriots into a 23-yard field
goal by Vinatieri, making it 13-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots worked their two-minute offense fairly well after
they took over at their 10 with 1:49 remaining in the second.
Bledsoe hit Lovett Purnell for a 22-yard gain, Glenn for 12, and
Troy Brown for 15. The Patriots got to the Colt 36 before the drive
stalled and Vinatieri booted a 52-yard field goal, tying a career
high. It went over the goalpost, banged off the goalpost camera,
and came back onto the field, one of the most unusual field goals
in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   The offense finally got one in the end zone early in the third
quarter, mounting a 46-yard drive that concluded with a 3-yard pass
from Bledsoe to Glenn with Burris draped all over him. Bledsoe put
the ball low, in a spot where Burris couldn't get to it.
</P>
<P>
   The rest was garbage time. The Colts scored once, on a Manning
3-yard pass to Torrance Small. But the Patriots had this well in
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough when you play a good team like the Patriots,'' said
Manning, who did get help from Marshall Faulk, who gained 127 yards
on 29 carries and had seven receptions for 60 yards. ``I feel I'm
making bad decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   All of them helped the Patriots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
