<HEADER>
A3265 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     09-14 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL BUT ONE PROBLEM SOLVED BY PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ They did what they had to do Sunday night.
They destroyed a sacrificial lamb. Or, in this case, 53 sacrificial
Colts.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots were not in a no-win situation when they trotted
onto the field at Foxboro Stadium to meet the futile Indianapolis
Colts and they knew it. Barring a tornado or some other act of God,
they were in a win situation. The only issue then was, would they
just win or would they really win.
</P>
<P>
   The former would be good enough, since a win is a win in the NFL
these days, but that would answer none of the questions about them
that had resurfaced last Monday night in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The latter would be better because the latter would say
something about them that needed to be said now, before questions
began to creep into their minds and those of their supporters over
just who, exactly, they are.
</P>
<P>
   By halftime the just-win half of the equation had been solved
and by early in the fourth quarter the score was 29-0, the Colts
had converted only 23 percent of their third down attempts, and any
concerns that the Patriots might suffer some sort of letdown after
the disappointment of losing in Denver seemed so silly as to be
absurd. What the Patriots needed to show Sunday night against the
lowly Colts they had shown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team ... we know what we are,'' quarterback Drew Bledsoe
said after the 29-6 victory. ``We know we're a good football team.
We were playing a team we should beat and we beat them
convincingly. It was an affirmation of who we are. We know we're a
good team and we played like it.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Patriots succeeded in doing was to send their fans home
early, giving them a Sunday night break with a work day coming up
this morning. When they pushed the score to 29-0 with 14:21 still
to play in the fourth quarter, red tailights began to light up
Route 1, and within minutes those lights were moving slowly because
the Patriots had moved quickly to destroy the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, they took control of the game early despite the
running of Indianapolis' Marshall Faulk (127 yards). They sacked
rookie quarterback Peyton Manning, forcing him to fumble, and the
ball was recovered by Willie Clay at the 2 to set up the first of
Adam Vinatieri's three field goals just eight minutes into the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Five plays later, Ty Law made the first of his two interceptions
and returned it 59 yards for a touchdown by weaving so effectively
through his pursuers that it gave one reason to ask if maybe New
England's brain trust should try him at running back instead of the
current crew of 2.2 yards-per-carry operatives.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Law would have a second interception to set up another
field goal, and then Vinatieri would hit a third one from 52 yards
as the first half closed. And the Patriots nearly had acheived
their unstated but very real goal: to destroy an inferior opponent
and thus put the rest of the AFC on notice that just because they
can't beat the Denver Broncos doesn't mean the rest of the
conference was safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``A game like this we wanted to go out and dominate,'' Clay
said. ``We know we're a pretty good team but we had to jump out on
them.''
</P>
<P>
   They did that at two critical times, early in the first quarter
and again early in the third quarter, thus establishing who was the
boss on this night. Perhaps the most important moment came on the
first two possessions of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   First Clay's defense again slapped down Manning and the Colts,
forcing them to open the second half by going three-and-out. Then
Bledsoe's offense took over at the Colts' 46 and finally got in
gear, needing just eight plays to culminate the drive with Terry
Glenn's first touchdown catch since Nov. 2, 1997, a 3-yard
reception that made it 22-0 with 9:34 to play in the third quarter
and effectively sent the fans home for the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're becoming a more veteran football team,'' Bledsoe said.
``We understand different types of games. It's easy to get up for
Denver. But now we have enough discipline and maturity to prepare
for a game like this and win it.''
</P>
<P>
   They won it as they should have, by making a rookie quarterback
look like a rookie quarterback and by making an average defense
look below average and by giving a young opponent with many holes
on offense and defense no reason to believe it could win.
</P>
<P>
   They choked the life out of the Colts with a defense that forced
four turnovers and then finished them off with an offense that made
none. But most of all, they played like the team they believe they
are, which is a team that concedes you nothing when you have the
ball and threatens you every time it has it.
</P>
<P>
   That may not have impressed the Broncos, watching back home in
Denver, but what it told the rest of the AFC is that these Patriots
will not be an easy team to beat this season in places other than
Mile High Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if they could just figure out how to run the ball ... well,
we'll leave that for another day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
