<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3269 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MCDONOUGHCOLUMN-B     09-14 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLTS' STAR PUPIL TAKEN TO SCHOOL BY DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Night school.
</P>
<P>
   Course: Educating a Quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Professor: Steve Sidwell.
</P>
<P>
   His daddy, Archie, told young Peyton Manning there would be
nights like Sunday night, during which all a struggling first-year
QB in the National Football League could get for a grade is an A
for effort.
</P>
<P>
   This test, the second of the semester, was just too much to
handle, the Patriots beating the Colts, 29-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the education of a quarterback,'' said Indianapolis
general manager Bill Polian, who decided Manning was going to be
his prize pupil when the Colts had the first pick of the NFL draft
last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what has to happen to him,'' Polian said evenly, after
Manning struggled against the sophisticated Patriot schemes drawn
up by defensive coordinator Sidwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew coming into this game he would see some things he
hadn't seen before,'' said Polian. ``New England is very good on
defense. They do a lot of different things and they do them well.
He made some good plays, but he had some he wished he had back. But
this is all part of the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to see all of these things and learn from them. When he
does, then the ball will come out of his hand at the right time and
to the right person. Then he can go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   The first priority of the Colts offense Sunday night was to run
the ball, leading to the second priority, not getting Manning into
certain passing situations where the Patriots could throw a lot of
looks at him, confusing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``On his first interception (which Ty Law returned for a
touchdown), Law just made a terrific play,'' said Polian. ``He left
his coverage and got himself back into the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the second interception (again by Law), Manning was
confused. He pump-faked and then threw it deep. He was not supposed
to do that against the coverage the Patriots had. They gave him one
look, and then Law dropped back into the end zone in zone coverage,
and Manning threw the ball right to him. Manning should have thrown
the ball to the other side of the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The game plan was to stay away from Law. The Colts respect him
as one of the best cornerbacks in the conference. However, the
Patriots swung their double coverage toward Chris Canty, who was
burned often by John Elway in Denver last Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Manning had a dilemma. Go toward Law in man-to-man, or throw
into double coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give the Patriots credit,'' said Polian. ``They kept bringing
a safety up to the line of scrimmage, and then dropped him off.
This confused him.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for Manning's inexperience, the Colts played a solid
first half. They trailed, 16-0, but 10 of those points were
directly attributable to Manning. He fumbled deep in his own end,
when Willie McGinest beat tight end Ken Dilger to the outside with
a speed rush. McGinest hit Manning from the blind side, and he
fumbled, setting up an Adam Vinatieri field goal.
</P>
<P>
   With less than five minutes left in the first period, Manning
had a third-and-3 at his 42 when he made another critical error in
judgment. Instead of throwing short, trying to get a first down, he
looked away from Dilger in the right flat and focused on Marcus
Pollard running a crossing pattern 20 yards deep across the field
left to right. Law left Dilger and stepped in front of Pollard to
make the interception and return it 59 yards for the score.
</P>
<P>
   But Manning's most embarrassing moment was yet to come, and cost
his team more points. With a second-and-10 at the Patriots 15 in
the second period, Manning threw a pump fake toward Marvin Harrison
running a slant, then brought the ball back down and lobbed it
toward the corner of the end zone. Law, who again had dropped into
coverage, just stood there and waited for it to drop in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Before his miserable night would end, Manning tallied four
turnovers, with three interceptions and a fumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we did some good things,'' Manning said. ``We ran
the ball really well. I feel I'm making some bad decisions. All of
them (interceptions) were poor decisions on my part.''
</P>
<P>
   Patriot quarterback Drew Bledsoe, asked if he empathized with
Manning, said, ``I sure do. But he's going to be a very good
quarterback. This is something when you're a rookie that's going to
happen, but he'll come back and play well.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Manning finished with 21 completions in 33 attempts, but for
only 188 yards. Generally, a passer with that many completions
should end up with more than 250 yards, but most of his completions
were for less than 10 yards, as the Colts tried not to expose him
to the Patriots' rush.
</P>
<P>
   He failed this test. But there will be 14 more before the end of
the marking period, and a final grade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
