<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-RUNNING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS GROUND GAME STILL AT STANDSTILL 
</HEADLINE>
 BACKS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ There is cause for concern but not alarm.
Sunday night Patriots running backs combined for 103 yards on 33
carries against the Indianapolis Colts _ and 51 of those yards came
on a scamper by backup tailback Sedrick Shaw. New England finished
the first half with 28 yards on 14 carries and was stopped on
short-yardage situations throughout the contest.
</P>
<P>
   Many Patriots fans were too busy singing the praises of
defensive back Ty Law (two interceptions) and defensive end Willie
McGinest (eight tackles, a sack, a forced fumble) to raise eyebrows
about the running backs' futility. But the ground game soon will be
a focal point.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with their season-opening effort against Denver, the
Patriots have just 184 yards rushing in two games. That will need
to improve, particuarly in outings in which the defense isn't in
sync and the receivers are well-covered.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the fact that few teams go far in the NFL without
a solid running game. The New England attack has shown flashes. How
far it is from consistency is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not frustrated (with the running game). There are going to
be games like this,'' said running back Robert Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   The first-round draft picked charged with making fans forget
about the departure of Curtis Martin had 36 yards on 18 carries,
including 8 yards in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   He did, however, score the team's only rushing touchdown on a
1-yard run on third down in the fourth quarter _ after a 1-yard run
on second down went for no gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won the game, and that's all that matters. I'm just trying
to take what the defense is giving me. Indianapolis did a great job
tonight,'' said Edwards, who gained 50 yards on 13 carries in the
opener against Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a few good plays, but you're going to have bad plays
along with the good. We're going to go and look at the film this
week and see what we need to work on. There's a lot of improvement
that needs to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, who missed much of the exhibition season because of
injury, said he is becoming more comfortable with the offense.
Right now, it's showing most with his receiving, as the former
University of Georgia standout is living up to his reputation as a
reliable threat out of the backfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be a good receiver,'' said quarterback Drew
Bledsoe, who completed three passes to Edwards for 71 yards. ``He
made a nice catch on the one crossing pattern to him. The ball
wasn't particularly well thrown and he caught it down at his feet.
It's nice to have a back who can catch the ball when the ball's not
thrown well.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards was most effective Sunday night running cutbacks and
sweeps, plays on which he made the first tackler miss. He was often
stuffed at the line of scrimmage or behind it on runs up the
middle. Yet the rookie said Indianapolis deserves much credit, too,
for stopping the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indy did a great job on defense as far as slow-playing a lot
of stuff,'' he said. ``The cutbacks weren't there as they have
been. They really studied their film and they just waited for stuff
to happen and just attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always a man unaccounted for, and that's my man. I
tried to give a little something and give a little extra effort to
get yardage, but sometimes it doesn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't think coach Pete Carroll isn't aware of that. After Shaw's
big gain, no other back had a run of more than 8 yards. Even Shaw
wasn't effective past his big gain, with just 4 more yards on four
carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a good, clean night for us in the running game,''
Carroll said. ``By halftime we were not running the football well
at all. Our stats are a little misleading because of that run with
Sedrick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
