<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3298 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-     09-14 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE STILL IN THE RUNNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ With Week 2 of the National Football
League season still to be completed, nearly half of the starting
quarterbacks have been injured.
</P>
<P>
   Opening week, eight went down. Sunday Troy Aikman, John Elway,
and Brad Johnson could not finish games.
</P>
<P>
   And some Patriot fans would like to see Drew Bledsoe run more.
</P>
<P>
   That shows how much they know, cerainly not much about the value
of keeping your starting quarterback in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   As much as they moan about Bledsoe and his alleged lack of
toughness and mobility, he has not missed a game in more than 2 1/2
seasons, and only one in the last four years, after he separated
his shoulder in San Francisco when he was planted into the ground
by linebacker Ken Norton.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, who is not a runner to begin with, must have been
feeling his oats. He ran for two touchdowns last week in the opener
against Arizona. And in Denver Sunday he scrambled on two plays in
succession. The problem was, he never got up after the second one.
On the way down, two defenders landed on Aikman, hammering his left
shoulder into the turf. He sustained a fractured left clavicle and
is expected to be out 4-8 weeks. That just might kill any playoff
hopes the Cowboys have this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday night, during the Patriots' loss in Denver, Bledsoe
was forced out of the pocket and ran as fast as he could, which is
not very fast, for the sideline. He gained 9 yards on the play, but
it was called back because of a penalty.
</P>
<P>
   During the week, talk show types and some writers discussed how
Bledsoe showed leadership on the play, and how great that was for
the team.
</P>
<P>
   They had the same reaction two years ago, in the third game of
the season, and the first in Foxboro Stadium. The Patriots had lost
the first two on the road, and Bledsoe was widely criticized for
his lack of mobility. Toward the end of a close game in Buffalo, he
had a chance to run in for a score that would have won the game,
and didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The next week, on a meaningless play early in the game, he ran
to his right for a first down, leaped in the air over a tackler,
and landed on his head. The crowd went wild. Bledsoe had showed he
was one of the boys. He was lucky he didn't end up in Massachusetts
General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Before this season started, Miami coach Jimmy Johnson was asked
to assess the Eastern Division of the AFC. He said that the
Patriots had the best team but added: ``If anything happens to
Bledsoe, then we are the team to beat. We go right by them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he is not mobile, is not a talented runner, and
cannot slide in the pocket to make rushers miss like the great ones
can, Bledsoe is resilient. He has been hit with some hellacious
shots over the last couple of years and bounced back to play.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, he does not get beat up like other quarterbacks.
In fact, he is hit probably less than any other starting passer.
</P>
<P>
   Though some Patriots followers like to complain about the lack
of a running game, and the lack of solid blocking by the offensive
line for those runs, this unit has been one of the best in the NFL
at protecting he passer. Also, Patriots offensive coordinators have
not put Bledsoe at risk.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there were at least a dozen times last Monday night
that Elway rolled outside the end on a semi-bootleg to throw and
exposed himself to hits by rushers, especially Willie McGinest.
There was a point in the game that he obviously was not happy with
the calls that put him in those positions. Once he even took a
dive, throwing the ball away and ducking, before the rusher got a
clear shot. That was the smart thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you like him or not, as Johnson indicates, Bledsoe is
the Patriots offense. Without him, every opposing team would stack
the line of scrimmage. With him, they back off and play pass
defense, which is why the Patriots should be able to run the ball
better this year, especially with the nice, easy schedule they
play.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City, in Week 5, was supposed to be the first big test
after Denver. But starting quarterback Elvis Grbac is out with a
bad shoulder, and may not play. The Chiefs had more players on the
injured list Sunday than at any other time in recent memory, and
they lost in Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Polian, the highly regarded general manager of the Colts,
pinpointed the reason for the rash of early-season injuries. ``It's
these zone blitzes and zone dogs,'' said Polian, just before
kickoff Sunday night. ``They are giving these defensive people
clean shots at the passer. And these defensive blitzers are getting
bigger and faster all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of these zone dogs, your offense has to practice more
11 on 11, and when this happens, you get more injuries in practice,
because you have to practice at a faster pace to simulate what
happens when a zone dog comes. It's a real problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, at the league meeting, Well Mara (owner of the
Giants) proposed that we make intentional grounding legal, that it
not be a penalty. This might be something we look at to help save
these quarterbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Including Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
