A3457 &Cx1f; var-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      09-14 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Sept. 13, moved Saturday in the `a' category and are
repeated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CENSURE-REVIEW _ Andrew Johnson was the only president
ever impeached, and Andrew Jackson was the only president ever
censured. The historical auguries may not bode well for high-minded
nonpartisanship. The records of the two big presidential crises of
the 19th century show that when Congress acted to remove or
sanction a president, raw politics prevailed. Here are excerpts.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-CLINTON-REVIEW _ Kenneth W. Starr's report became
public so suddenly last week that Americans are still digesting its
charges and tawdriness and weighing their significance. But already
potentially seismic attitudes are taking shape. The politicians,
strategists and scholars trying to gauge them are certain of little
except that much is at stake, regardless of whether Bill Clinton
survives as president. By David E. Rosenbaum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-MARKETS-REVIEW _ As more of the world's markets come
unhinged _ last week the contagion hit Brazil full force, and many
now worry that the rest of Latin America could succumb as well _
there is a modest revolt under way against one of the biggest
trends of the 1980s and 1990s, the view that money should move
unimpeded around the world, to the places where it can be used most
efficiently. By David E. Sanger. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-VOLUNTEERS-REVIEW _ Nowadays, volunteerism is the most
popular prescription for improving young people and it has the
added virtue of saving the world. But since this is America,
there's a group or two somewhere voluntarily opposed to it. To
instill a sense of civic duty in teen-agers, the Chicago public
school system has enacted a policy requiring its students to
perform 40 hours of public service to earn a high school diploma.
By Dirk Johnson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STARR-CLINTON-REVIEW _ Historians will, no doubt, analyze the
blood feud nearing its denouemont between Bill Clinton and Kenneth
W. Starr in lots of ways _ as a showdown over politics and law, of
constitutional issues and human ones. But a look at where both men
came from suggests another possible prism _ a battle of dueling
Southerners, each of them summing up the competing instincts of the
South in which issues of politics, morals and religion have become
personalized at a deep, visceral level. By Peter Applebome. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-ASSEMBLY-REVIEW _ When the annual limousine-and-sirens
season opens at the United Nations on Sept. 21 with high-level
speeches in the General Assembly, a lot of the world's bad boys
won't be anywhere near the podium. They always stay home. By
Barbara Crossette. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERS-REVIEW _ How do you measure the talent to teach? And
how do you turn knowledgeable people into talented educators? Is an
exam like the one in Massachusetts a tool to raise standards or
does it represent the long, stultifying reach of an educational
bureaucracy? As states raise academic standards for students, New
York and others are moving to stiffen their credentialing
requirements to make sure that teachers can teach more rigorous
curriculum. By Randal C. Archibold. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-HEROES-REVIEW _ Although baseball's charming 129-year
history is a unique asset that distinguishes it from younger
sports, it has also become an undertow from which the sport has
struggled to escape. Today's sports fans aren't preoccupied with
history; they focus on the next this, the next that. Figures from
the past often get mistaken as curiosities rather than as cherished
legends. By Alan Schwarz. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-VOTE-REVIEW _ Germany's most important election in
decades will take place two weeks from Sunday and the striking
thing is this: Whoever wins will inherit a land where the pace has
already been set for them, not so much by politicians as by the
barons of big business. Almost nine years after the fall of the
Berlin Wall, that is not entirely a surprise: As in the United
States or Britain, ideology has lost its primacy, yielding to a
contest among rival politicians to define and capture the
post-ideological center. By Alan Cowell. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ATROCITIES-SUITS-REVIEW _ In the wake of the settlement between
Holocaust survivors and Swiss banks accused of profiting from
looted Jewish assets, some experts fear that opportunistic lawyers
may see a potential gold mine in the precedent, and will seek every
opportunity to file suits on behalf of victims of past atrocities.
By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   CIA-CHILE-REVIEW _ Excerpts from newly declassified documents on
how the CIA under President Richard M. Nixon targeted Chilean
President Salvadore Allende in the early 1970s. Allende was ousted
in a coup 25 years ago this month.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW YORK TIMES NEWS SERVICE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
