<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 08:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3489 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-ART     09-14 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
 
 (Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday,
September 12.) 
 (The Week in Review) 
(ART ADV: Graphic with stock market story is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reno Announces Review of Clinton Campaign Ads
</P>
<P>
   As if the White House did not have enough problems, Attorney
General Janet Reno moved an important step closer to seeking an
independent prosecutor to investigate whether President Clinton
violated federal election laws during his 1996 re-election
campaign. Reno ordered a 90-day review of whether the $42 million
the Democrats split among state party organizations for general
advertising was actually an illegal scheme to finance an ad
campaign for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's decision marked the third time in two weeks that she
opened campaign finance inquiries that could lead to independent
prosecutors: The others involve fund-raising calls made by Vice
President Al Gore and possible perjury by Harold M. Ickes, the
former deputy White House chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   Campaign Finance Bill Dies
</P>
<P>
   The Senate effectively buried an overhaul of campaign finance
laws for this year. Senators voted 52-48 to cut off debate and vote
on a bill to ban unlimited, unregulated donations, called soft
money, to political parties. But supporters failed to muster the 60
votes needed to end a Republican filibuster, so the bill was
withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's supporters had hoped to build new momentum from the
House's strong vote last month for a similar bill.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ERIC SCHMITT
</P>
<P>
   Relief for North Korea
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said they were readying a large humanitarian food
shipment to North Korea. The move was part of an effort to keep the
secretive country talking about its nuclear program, which includes
a large underground site that American intelligence agencies
believe could be part of a new nuclear complex.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement to provide aid was made despite North Korea's
recent launching of a multistage missile over Japan two weeks ago.
The North was condemned for the act, but insisted that it had
merely launched a small satellite to broadcast praise for the late
dictator Kim Il Sung. Now it appears that there really was a tiny
satellite, but that it failed to get into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
<P>
   Method to Pick Baby's Sex
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in the millennia that humans have tried to
select the sex of their baby, success may be at hand. Doctors at
the Genetics &AMP; IVF Institute in Fairfax, Va., reported that they
can sort sperm by exploiting the one difference between sperm that
produce a male and those that produce a female: Sperm that produce
a male have 2.8 percent less DNA.
</P>
<P>
   The method does not guarantee couples a baby with the sex of
their choice _ it merely stacks the odds. But already questions are
being raised. Is society ready to go down this path? And how safe
is the method?
</P>
<P>
   _ By GINA KOLATA
</P>
<P>
   Congo Peace Talks End
</P>
<P>
   A summit meeting of African leaders to negotiate a peace
settlement for the Congo ended with little more than a joint
statement endorsing peace as an ultimate goal. All the parties
involved in the conflict got together, but they had little to show
for their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting broke out in Congo in July as rebel forces backed by
Rwanda and Uganda attacked the government of Laurent Kabila, who
had been in power less than 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Progress Toward Safer Beef
</P>
<P>
   One way to avoid most deadly E. coli bacteria is to tinker with
your diet _ by avoiding hamburgers. Now researchers at Cornell
University have come up with another solution: First tinker with
your diet's diet.
</P>
<P>
   Feeding grain to cattle in the days before slaughter, they
found, can foster the growth of E. coli, but if the cattle switch
to hay and grass in those crucial days, the bacteria have only a
slim chance of surviving.
</P>
<P>
   If further research backs up the Cornell findings, the
Agriculture Department could recommend changes in cattle feeding.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Justices to Hear Census Case
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional mandate to conduct a national headcount every
10 years sounds simple enough, and once it was. But a highly
charged debate over how to run the census has reached the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   The justices agreed to decide whether the Clinton
administration's plan to have the Census Bureau use statistical
sampling as part of the census for the year 2000, to correct for an
anticipated undercount of some 4 million people using traditional
door-to-door and mailed survey methods, is permissible. Poor people
and members of minorities are missed disproportionately in the
traditional census.
</P>
<P>
   A special three-judge U.S. District Court ruled last month, in a
suit brought by the House of Representatives, that the sampling
proposal violated federal law. The Supreme Court will hear
arguments Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LINDA GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Extends Iraq Sanctions
</P>
<P>
   After dithering for more than a month in the wake of Iraq's
decision Aug. 5 to stop weapons inspections, the U.N. Security
Council pulled together in surprising strength and voted
unanimously to deprive Baghdad of any chance of having sanctions
lifted until the inspectors were allowed to resume their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, which freezes future sanctions reviews, also
dangles the carrot of a complete look at Iraq's relations with the
United Nations, which imposed sanctions after the 1990 invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq, arguing that it has already disarmed, says no more
inspections are needed.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARBARA CROSSETTE
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hope in Swissair Crash
</P>
<P>
   In a case of deja vu, The U.S. Navy salvage ship Grapple is once
again preparing to raise airplane parts from the ocean. It almost
seems as if the crash of TWA Flight 800 off New York in July 1996
had repeated itself Sept. 2 when Swissair Flight 111 crashed in the
Atlantic Ocean off Nova Scotia, killing all 229 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   But it is already clear that the crew of the Swissair MD-11 had
at least 16 minutes to struggle for survival, while the TWA Boeing
747 exploded without warning. And while the TWA crash is still
unsolved, the Swissair plane carried an advanced flight data
recorder; combined with evidence from the cockpit, investigators
believe they will eventually find the cause of the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MATTHEW L. WALD
</P>
<P>
   Big-Time Sports, Big-Time Bids
</P>
<P>
   If you thought Mark McGwire set the only sports record by
swatting his 62nd home run Tuesday, you'd be wrong. The record
price paid for a sports franchise tumbled twice in two days, making
the $311 million paid by Rupert Murdoch for the Los Angeles Dodgers
last January look like a Filene's Basement bargain.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the National Football League accepted $530 million
for the new Cleveland Browns from Alfred Lerner, chairman of MBNA
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   One day later, BSkyB, Murdoch's British satellite TV company,
agreed to pay $1 billion in cash and stock for Manchester United,
Britain's richest soccer club with $45 million in profits last
year. The team is central to the English Premier League, BSkyB's
prized attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch is accustomed to paying outlandish prices for sports
properties to enhance his global media empire. The Dodgers'
acquisition secured the team's presence on Fox Sports West,
Murdoch's regional sports channel in southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Buying Manchester United means Murdoch will have a team owner's
role in the future of the Premier League, especially when TV rights
are renegotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner, who is not in the media business, offered this
perspective on buying the successors to the original Browns
franchise, which moved to Baltimore in 1996. ``If you ask me how it
feels to write a check for a pair of shoes, I could tell you,'' he
said. ``But at this level, it's a unique experience.''
</P>
<P>
   It makes one wonder what owners who bought their teams on the
cheap are thinking. What, after all, could George Steinbrenner and
his partners get for the Yankees, which cost them only $10 million
in 1973?
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD SANDOMIR &QR;
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Feels the Yo-Yo Effect
</P>
<P>
   The stock market has given investors more than a few jolts
lately, but some bumps aren't what they used to be.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell nearly 100
points in the first 15 minutes of trading, then turned on a dime
and in the next 20 minutes shot up more than 200 points from its
low. The turnaround came as President Clinton, appearing at a
televised prayer breakfast, asked Monica Lewinsky and her family
for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow finished up 179.96 points, at 7,795.50. It was the
fourth consecutive trading session _ and eighth in the last 10
trading days _ in which the Dow rose or fell by more than 100
points.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly the stock market is in turmoil. But is the market's
recent volatility any worse than at other times of political and
economic uncertainty?
</P>
<P>
   By one measure of volatility _ how often the Dow has risen or
fallen by more than 1 percent in a single day _ the year so far is
the market's most volatile in more than a decade. In fact, 1998
isn't out of line with previous periods of extreme ups and downs _
like 1987, when the stock market crashed, or 1980, when the silver
market crashed.
</P>
<P>
   There is no shortage of causes for the recent swings in the Dow.
Faltering economies in Asia, Eastern Europe and Latin America have
begun to put a squeeze on the profits of U.S. companies, causing
investors to fear that the seven-year economic boom could be coming
to an end. In addition, uncertainty about Clinton's problems has
caused big market gyrations.
</P>
<P>
   But there's also a psychological dimension: Many investors are
only beginning to get used to triple-digit fluctuations in the
Dow's close. In 1987, a swing of 100 points equaled 4 percent of
the Dow. When the index peaked above 9,000 in July, the same
100-point move represented little more than 1 percent. Still a bit
unnerving, but hardly cause for panic.
</P>
<P>
   _ By EDWARD WYATT &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
