<HEADER>
A3492 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-ATROCITIES-SUITS-RE     09-14 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-ATROCITIES-SUITS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
12.) 
 THE LAWSUITS PILE UP, MATCHING THE LIST OF ATROCITIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, September (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifty-three years after it ended, the Second World War is
spawning a new form of international justice that victims hail as
long overdue. But some of its targets decry it as a dubious new
legal cottage industry, in which some lawyers seize upon human
rights abuses as the basis for emotionally charged class-action
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of last month's $1.25 billion settlement between
Holocaust survivors and Swiss banks that were accused of profiting
from looted Jewish assets, some officials and lawyers involved in
the Holocaust cases say they fear that opportunistic lawyers may
see a potential gold mine in the precedent, and will seek every
opportunity to file suits on behalf of victims of past atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about an explosion of these kind of suits,'' said Bert
Neuborne, a New York University law professor working without fee
on the Holocaust cases. ``That a lot of people will see a potential
for what they think is a fast buck.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not the only thorny question being raised. More tricky,
perhaps, is the question of where it will all end. If Holocaust
victims are compensated now, as native American tribes were
compensated for past wrongs over the previous two decades, who
might be next? African-Americans because their ancestors were
slaves? Bosnians who consider the United Nations accountable for
breaking promises to protect them?
</P>
<P>
   These are, of course, genuine victims with genuine grievances.
The problem is that sometimes sincere efforts to right clear moral
wrongs can be seized upon by people with less-than-noble motives.
And under legal standards, it is easier to demonstrate damage from
some historical wrongs than from others.
</P>
<P>
   The number of suits keeps growing. On Friday, Melvin Weiss, a
nationally known class-action lawyer, filed in federal court in
Newark, N.J., against the German conglomerate Krupp, charging that
it had profited from slave labor during World War II. Two weeks
ago, another group of lawyers filed another class action suit in
federal court in Brooklyn against more than a dozen German
companies, including Krupp.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, suits have also been filed against Ford
Motor Co., Italian and German insurance companies and French banks
accused of profiting from the cruelties of Hitler's Germany. Banks
in Sweden, Spain, Portugal and Argentina could be next, Neuborne
said.
</P>
<P>
   Asian-American groups, meanwhile, have been scouring the United
States for victims of the Nanking Massacre and the use of forced
labor by wartime Japan. They hope to file class-action lawsuits in
U.S. courts against Japanese corporations, such as Mitsubishi, as
well as the Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
   And some black leaders have repeatedly called for reparations to
be paid for slave labor in the United States. ``If the descendants
of Nazi-era slave laborers deserve some compensation, why don't the
descendants of the victims of 250 years of American slave labor
deserve compensation?'' asked Eric Foner, a Columbia University
history professor.
</P>
<P>
   But Foner also said it was a difficult question: ``How far back
do you go? If we want to go all the way back, all the land would go
back to the Indians.''
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts warn that suits involving other historic
grievances may not lead to settlements as quickly as some of the
Holocaust cases. Kent Syverud, dean of the Vanderbilt University
law school, said suing for damages based on slave labor in the
United States would be difficult. He said few records exist that
define exactly who was a slave, who is a descendant of a specific
slave, and how much the slave-owner benefited from the slave's
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Holocaust suits are different in that they involve much
more concrete and identifiable events and records,'' he said. ``The
events of slavery are very hard to link it to a specific bank
account.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by groups to sue the American government for damages
have achieved mixed results. In the 1970s, Native American tribes
successfully sued for the rights to control and profit from vast
amounts of land. But legal actions by Japanese-Americans interned
during World War II were less successful, and they had to wait
until Congress awarded them $20,000 each in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Among the newer Holocaust suits, the Ford case may provide the
clearest indication of difficulties ahead for claimants. While some
German companies, for example Volkswagen, have already agreed to
create some form of fund to compensate former slave laborers, Ford
is vowing to fight.
</P>
<P>
   In the suit, Weiss' team argues that Henry Ford's anti-Semitic
remarks in the 1920s and alleged close relationship with Hitler
resulted in Ford's subsidiary in Germany never being taken over by
the Nazis. But Ian Slater, a Ford spokesman in the United States,
said the company lost control of its subsidiary during the war and
the factory was badly damaged when Ford regained control of it. He
said the suit was an unfair attempt to use bad publicity to force
the company to settle.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the question of lawyers' fees. Weiss said he would
request minimal fees. Ed Fagan, who is working on the Swiss bank
and German slave labor cases and said he hoped to represent victims
of Japanese slave labor practices, said he expected a standard
share of settlements. The World Jewish Congress and other Jewish
groups that support such legal claims are calling for all lawyers
involved in the Holocaust cases to work free.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe that the Holocaust is an area anyone should
be profiting from,'' said Elan Steinberg, the organization's
executive director.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 0842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 09:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3517 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALLACE-OBIT-COX     09-14 1713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLACE-OBIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    George Wallace, paradox of Southern politics
 &HT;    By Tom Bennett and Jim Yardley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Wallace was a Southern populist and opportunist. He
embodied Southern racism in the tumultuous 1960s, grew more
moderate in the 1970s and asked for forgiveness _ and black votes _
in the 1980s. He was despised and admired _ and not necessarily
along racial lines.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who served four terms as governor of Alabama, died of
cardiac arrest Sunday night in Montgomery while suffering from a
blood infection. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, where he was a folk hero, a generation grew up
having known only brief periods when the governor's mansion was not
occupied by a Wallace _ George or his first wife, Lurleen. He was
governor from 1963-67, 1971-79 and 1983-87. She served a partial
term as governor in 1967-68 when by law he could not succeed
himself. Lurleen Wallace died in office.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his political career, in the 1940s, Wallace was labeled
``liberal'' when he backed populist Gov. James E. ``Big Jim''
Folsom. But Folsom's popularity dimmed after the Supreme Court
outlawed school segregation, and Wallace dropped him cold. Wallace
won the governorship in 1962 and declared in his 1963 inaugural
address, ``Segregation now! Segregation tomorrow! Segregation
forever!''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace ran for president four times, including in 1972 when
Arthur Bremer shot him during a campaign stop in Laurel, Md.
Wallace was left paralyzed, and his national influence gradually
faded. But future presidents from Richard Nixon to Bill Clinton
would adopt many of his themes, including welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace toned down his racial views in the 1974 governor's race,
then came full circle in 1982, winning the governorship for the
fourth and final time with 90 percent of the black vote after he
declared segregation to be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   George Corley Wallace Jr. was born Aug. 25, 1919, in the tiny
southeast Alabama town of Clio. His home county, Barbour, was known
as ``the Home of the Governors,'' having produced seven. He was the
oldest son of George C. ``Sag'' Wallace Sr., a farmer, and Mozelle
Smith Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   The young Wallace began his political career at 16 as a page in
the state Senate. At the University of Alabama, he was freshman
class president and two-time state bantamweight boxing champion. He
received a law degree in 1942. To make ends meet, he worked as a
busboy, taxi driver, dogcatcher and magazine salesman.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, he enlisted in the Army Air Forces, but
washed out of pilots' school after contracting spinal meningitis.
On furlough in 1943, he married Lurleen Burns, a clerk at the
Kresge's store in Tuscaloosa.
</P>
<P>
   Aboard a B-29 superfortress, Wallace flew 19 often-harrowing
bombing missions over Japan. He was discharged after the war with a
10 percent disability related to ``a nervous condition resulting
from combat fatigue.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace was known as a ``liberal'' after his 1946 election in
Barbour County to the state House of Representatives. In 1948, at
the Democratic Convention, he was one of the few Southerners not to
walk out with the ``Dixiecrats'' protesting a civil rights plank in
the platform.
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, he was elected a judge of the 3rd Judicial District _
Barbour, Dale and Bullock counties. Two years later, the political
winds changed with the Supreme Court's landmark Brown desegregation
ruling. Wallace changed, too. Folsom as governor invited Harlem
attorney Adam Clayton Powell to the governor's mansion for a drink.
Wallace and others became segregationists.
</P>
<P>
   The only governor's race Wallace would lose would be his first
in 1958. All 13 candidates were segregationists, but Attorney
General John Patterson emerged as the most irreconcilable of all.
Patterson and Wallace led the Democratic primary and met in a
runoff where Wallace labeled Patterson the Ku Klux Klan candidate.
Patterson crushed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patterson out-niggered me,'' Wallace said in defeat, ``and,
boys, I'm not going to be out-niggered again.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace entered the 1962 governor's race pledging to ``stand in
the door'' to prevent integration. His newfound intransigence
carried him to victory. At his swearing-in, Wallace stood on a star
on the Capitol steps in Montgomery marking the spot where Jefferson
Davis had been sworn in as Confederate president.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most infamous declarations in Southern demagoguery
followed. Wallace said: ``In the name of the greatest people that
have ever trod this Earth, I draw the line in the dust and toss the
gauntlet before the feet of tyranny and I say, Segregation now!
Segregation tomorrow! Segregation forever!''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's defining moment came only months later when a federal
judge ordered the University of Alabama to admit two black
students, Jimmy Hood and Vivian Malone. Hood and Malone arrived on
the Tuscaloosa campus June 11, 1963. Wallace and federal officials
played out a drama fulfilling Wallace's ``stand'' pledge, and
saving face for all while avoiding violence.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace stood in front of a door as U.S. Assistant Attorney
General Nicholas Katzenbach and the students approached. Wallace
threw up a hand. Katzenbach handed him a cease-and-desist order,
and Wallace read a statement berating the federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenbach withdrew. The students were taken to dorm rooms. The
Alabama National Guard was federalized. The students later
registered without incident as Wallace returned to Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, on Sept. 15, 1963, the Sixteenth Street
Baptist Church in Birmingham was bombed; four young girls were
killed. Wallace denounced the bombing. But President John F.
Kennedy implied some culpability on the part of Wallace when he
said that it was ``regrettable that public disparagement of law and
order had encouraged violence which had fallen on the innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's ``stand'' vaulted him onto the national stage. He made
his first run for president in 1964 as a Democrat, challenging
President Lyndon Johnson. Wallace earned large support in primaries
in Wisconsin, Indiana and Maryland, but supporters failed to place
him on the ballots in Georgia, Mississippi and South Carolina. The
death blow to his candidacy was the Republicans' nomination of
conservative Sen. Barry Goldwater. Wallace withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, the increasingly bloody civil rights struggle
continued to dominate politics. In the historic 1965 Selma Voting
Rights March, state troopers beat and tear-gassed 700 blacks and
whites attempting to march to Montgomery. Wallace, who said the
march ``will not be tolerated,'' was blamed for the brutality. Two
months later, Atlanta's Martin Luther King Jr. led marchers to
Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   Forbidden by the state constitution to seek re-election, Wallace
ran his wife in 1966. Lurleen Wallace swept the Democratic primary
and the general election. Wallace openly ran the state from an
office across from his wife's office until her death from cancer in
May 1968. Lt. Gov. Albert Brewer succeeded her.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, meanwhile, launched his most successful and sustained
presidential run in 1968 as a third-party candidate. He collected 3
million signatures and made the ballot in all 50 states. Wallace
won 9,90l,151 popular votes, finished third behind Richard Nixon
and Hubert Humphrey, and carried Georgia, Alabama, Arkansas,
Louisiana and Mississippi. A politician without an office, Wallace
ran for governor again in 1970. After a bitter Democratic primary,
Wallace trailed the incumbent Brewer. But he won the runoff,
559,832 to 525,951, and easily took the general election.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1971, Wallace married Cornelia Ellis Snively, 19
years his junior. She was a beautiful divorcee who was Folsom's
niece and who once had performed in the water-ski show at Florida's
Cypress Gardens. They would divorce in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace became a Democrat again for his third presidential run
in 1972. He reeled off primary victories in Florida, Alabama,
Tennessee and North Carolina, and finished second in Wisconsin,
Pennsylvania and Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   On May 15, 1972, Wallace was walking among supporters at a
Laurel, Md., shopping center when Bremer, a young drifter, shot him
several times, leaving him critically wounded. The next day, the
hospitalized Wallace won the Maryland and Michigan primaries.
</P>
<P>
   But he was in a hospital bed for seven weeks, and eventually
underwent four major operations, several minor surgical procedures,
and suffered various complications. He tried acupuncture and DMSO.
He suffered a progressive loss of hearing. The days before the
assassination attempt would mark the zenith of Wallace's national
popularity. Afterward, he gradually faded from the national scene.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, with a rewritten Alabama constitution permitting
re-election, Wallace was elected governor for the third time in a
landslide. Two years later, he again sought the presidency but
eventually bowed out in favor of another Southerner, Jimmy Carter
of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Forbidden to seek a third straight term, Wallace left the
governor's mansion in January 1979 with his political career
seemingly over. Two years later, he was married for the third time,
to Linda Lee Taylor, 29 years his junior. She was a divorcee and
country music singer who had been ``Lisa'' in a singing duo, ``Mona
and Lisa,'' that performed during his political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   His final political two-step came in 1982, when Wallace returned
and openly courted black voters in the governor's race. Segregation
is wrong, he now said. Facing Republican Emory Folmar in the
general election, Wallace received 90 percent of the black vote to
win easily.
</P>
<P>
   He left office for the last time in 1987 and lived in a
ranch-style house in Montgomery until his death. He and Taylor
divorced that year.
</P>
<P>
   Tuskegee University awarded him an honorary degree in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Surviving are a son by his first marriage, George Wallace Jr. of
Montgomery; three daughters by his first marriage, Peggy Sue
Kennedy of Montgomery and Bobbi Jo Parsons and Janie Lee Dye, both
of Birmingham; a brother, Jack Wallace of Clayton, Ala.; a sister,
Marianne Dauphin of Montgomery; and eight grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
