<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLACE-TIMELINE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Key dates in the life of George Wallace
 &HT;    Staff report
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ 1919 Born in Clio, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1942 Graduated from University of Alabama with law degree.
</P>
<P>
   _ 1942-45 Served in Army Air Corps in World War II, discharged
with disability
</P>
<P>
   _ 1946 Elected to Alabama House of Representatives
</P>
<P>
   _ 1948 Refused to join ``Dixiecrats'' who walked out of
Democratic Convention
</P>
<P>
   _ 1950 Re-elected to Alabama House of Representatives
</P>
<P>
   _ 1952 Elected a circuit judge
</P>
<P>
   _ 1954 Quit as campaign manager of moderate Gov. James E. ``Big
Jim'' Folsom
</P>
<P>
   _ 1958 Lost his first race for governor
</P>
<P>
   _ 1959 Cited for contempt for refusing to turn over his
circuit's voting records to U.S. Civil Rights Commission, was
dubbed ``The Fighting Little Judge''
</P>
<P>
   _ 1962 Elected governor
</P>
<P>
   _ 1963 Vowed in his first inaugural address, ``Segregation now!
Segregation tomorrow! Segregation forever!''
</P>
<P>
   _ 1963 ``Stood in courthouse door'' briefly delaying integration
of University of Alabama
</P>
<P>
   _ 1964 Ran for president as a Democrat, scored well in three
primaries, withdrew after Republicans nominated Barry Goldwater
</P>
<P>
   _ 1966 Could not succeed himself as Alabama governor and ran his
first wife, Lurleen Burns Wallace, for the post. She became
Alabama's first woman governor
</P>
<P>
   _ 1968 Lurleen Wallace died of cancer
</P>
<P>
   _ 1968 Ran for president as American Independent Party
candidate. Received 13.5 percent of popular vote, most by
third-party nominee since 1924, and 46 electoral votes, most by any
minor candidate in U.S. history. Carried Georgia, four other states
</P>
<P>
   _ 1970 Elected governor for second time
</P>
<P>
   _ 1972 Ran for president as a Democrat, won or came in second in
several primaries. On the eve of victories in Maryland and
Michigan, was crippled by an assassination attempt that left him
paralyzed from the waist down. His burgeoning campaign was over.
Eight weeks later he addressed Democratic National Convention from
his wheelchair
</P>
<P>
   _ 1974 Re-elected governor (Alabama law permitted successive
terms)
</P>
<P>
   _ 1976 Ran for president third time, withdrew and endorsed
Georgia's Jimmy Carter
</P>
<P>
   _ 1979 Forbidden by law to seek a third consecutive term as
governor
</P>
<P>
   _ 1982 Elected governor for fourth time with 90 percent of the
black vote
</P>
<P>
   _ 1986 Decided not to seek a fifth term as governor
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
