<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TEEN-VOLUNTEERS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
12.) 
 VOLUNTEER: THAT'S AN ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, September (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ They just don't make young people the way they used
to. Nary a generation has looked upon its callow successors without
finding them soft, spoiled and self-centered.
</P>
<P>
   The old remedy, a good swift kick in the pants, is obsolete,
even illegal. Nowadays, volunteerism is the most popular
prescription for improving young people and it has the added virtue
of saving the world. But since this is America, there's a group or
two somewhere voluntarily opposed to it.
</P>
<P>
   To instill a sense of civic duty in teen-agers, the Chicago
public school system has enacted a policy requiring its students to
perform 40 hours of public service to earn a high school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want students to learn the importance of community,'' said
Bruce Marchiafava, a spokesman for the Chicago schools, the
nation's third-largest system behind New York and Los Angeles.
``They need to know that community is about giving, not just
getting.''
</P>
<P>
   While Chicago is the nation's biggest school system to make
public service a requirement, experts on volunteerism say thousands
of American schools demand that their students get out and help a
good cause. Every student in Maryland's public schools must fulfill
a public service requirement. Many prep schools routinely bus
students to soup kitchens, mentoring programs, children-in-crisis
and elder-care centers and literacy tutorials.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of public service and self-sacrifice has been a
cherished American value long before John F. Kennedy's exhortation
to ``ask what you can do for your country.'' But never before in
peacetime has there been so much emphasis on volunteering. ``Every
young American,'' President Clinton has said, ``should be taught
the joy and the duty of serving.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the president's summit on volunteerism in Philadelphia
last year, Colin Powell has been traveling the country encouraging
young people to give of themselves. And every teen-ager applying to
a top college knows that high test scores and grades can be a
two-legged stool without some evidence of good works.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of making young people more useful, though, has
provoked some criticism, especially when such volunteerism is
mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   On a practical level, requiring public service can be an
administrative and legal nightmare. Is the school district liable
if a child is hurt while fulfilling the requirement. And who
decides which charitable organizations are acceptable?
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's school administrators, who are still working on its
new policy, are aware of the quandaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you let students work for an anti-handgun group, do you
also let them work for the NRA?'' Marchiafava asked, referring to
the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   Those very problems have stopped other big city districts like
Los Angeles from requiring volunteerism. Though the idea has been
raised in New York, J.D. LaRock, a spokesman for New York City
Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew, said officials had no plans to
consider such a requirement. Mandatory volunteerism was a
contradiction in terms, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The courts have upheld the rights of school districts to require
public service, rejecting claims that it amounted to involuntary
servitude and violated the Constitution. One of the unsuccessful
suits filed by the Institute for Justice argued that the 13th
Amendment forbids involuntary servitude. The group also argued in
the case of one Long Island, N.Y., teen-ager that the high &UR;  &LR; school
student came from a working-class family and needed to earn money
to contribute to the family's coffers.
</P>
<P>
   John Kramer, a spokesman for the Institute for Justice, a
Washington-based research organization with a libertarian bent,
said that surveys indicate that between 4 percent and 15 percent of
all schools now require some sort of public service, a form of
learning that some educators call ``infusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Kramer said many districts have backed away from mandatory
volunteerism. One of the rubs with such programs, he said, is that
parents are roped in as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who do you think is going to do all the driving to and from
these volunteer activities?'' Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   For students who bristle at the notion of required public
service, the Ayn Rand Institute has offered an internship designed
to allow them to fulfill the requirement by protesting
volunteerism.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteerism has become ``the most explicit moral crusade this
country has seen in some time,'' said Michael Berliner, the
executive director of the research organization founded by an heir
of Ayn Rand, the late philosopher who argued that people should be
guided by self-interest and reject the notion of charity as a moral
virtue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We disagree with this idea that service to the community is
the ultimate good,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
