u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-TEACHERS-REVIEW-2TA     09-14 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TEACHERS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
12.)
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Originally filed on Saturday, September (ATTN: Mass.)  
 HOW SCHOOLS MEASURE THE TALENT TO TEACH  
 (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Massachusetts Board of Education chairman John Silber recently
berated deans of education schools for standards so low that nearly
six of every 10 prospects who took the state's new basic skills
exam for teachers failed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A high school senior should have been able to pass this,''
said Silber, who helped develop the test. ``Something ought to be
done to bring talented people in.''
</P>
<P>
   But how do you measure the talent to teach? And how do you turn
knowledgeable people into talented educators? Is an exam like
Massachusetts' a tool to raise standards or does it represent the
long, stultifying reach of an educational bureaucracy?
</P>
<P>
   As states raise academic standards for students, New York and
others are moving to stiffen their credentialing requirements to
make sure that teachers can teach a more rigorous curriculum.
Meanwhile, teacher shortages are requiring many states and
localities to hire personnel who don't meet the requirements. Among
the latest crop of 5,000 hired in New York City, one in four isn't
fully certified, which is an improvement over the one in two of 10
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Some states are reassessing the effectiveness of written exams
in gauging how well a person will perform in the classroom. At
least two, Ohio and California, are conducting pilot programs
involving intensive review of beginning teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio program involves interviewing and observing the new
teachers on their curriculum and methods, observing them in class
for a day or more and then reinterviewing them. Assessors also
examine lesson plans and students' work before deciding on a score
or a recommendation on certification.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really ensuring the performance is successful and holding
the individual accountable for how they do in classes,'' said Mary
Troyer, the director of the program. ``I wouldn't say we had a
large number of teachers who were miserable failures in the past.
It's just an extra accountability piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio's program is modeled on an updated teacher certification
exam developed five years ago by the Educational Testing Service of
Princeton, N.J., which is now used by 31 states.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the test includes an assessment of the teacher in the
classroom, which reflects the idea that written exams do not fully
detect how well a fresh recruit will do in the classroom. So far no
state has yet adopted this kind of review of rookie teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do performance assessment is very expensive,'' said Mari
Pearlman, vice president of teaching and learning at the
Educational Testing Service. ``People who have to do the evaluation
must be practitioners themselves. You need to train people to
actually observe.''
</P>
<P>
   After the famous 1983 report ``A Nation at Risk,'' by the
National Commission on Excellence in Education, warned that the
poor level of teaching college graduates was hindering American
children from competing academically with peers around the globe, a
follow-up study in 1986 by Carnegie Corp.'s Task Force on Teaching
as a Profession recommended the creation in 1987 of the nonprofit
National Board for Professional Teaching Standards, a rigorous
voluntary national certification program.
</P>
<P>
   So far 912 teachers from 41 states and the District of Columbia
have won certification, or 45 percent of those who tried.
Applicants must successfully complete an arduous year-long
examination of lesson plans, student work samples, and videotapes
and analyses of classroom instruction.
</P>
<P>
   But drawbacks include a $2,000 exam fee (some states now pay all
or part of the cost). And the test is not recommended for those
with less than three years of teaching experience. Only recently
have any states begun to recognize the board certification in place
of their own exams.
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Mary-Dean Barringer, vice president for teacher
programs at the board, ``we would hope there is enough incentive
for teachers to publicly affirm their teaching at this high level.
Our goal is to drive the standard of teaching quality by getting
states to embrace the high standards.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS in 2nd TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Test for Beginners Only
</P>
<P>
   The following sample questions, and the two brief essays on
which they are based, are from the Praxis Series, an exam devised
by the Educational Testing Service of Princeton, N.J. The questions
are designed to evaluate beginning teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lyndon Johnson's father once told him that he did not belong
in politics unless he could walk into a roomful of people and tell
immediately who was for him and who was against him. In fact, even
the shrewd Johnson had not quite such occult power, but his liking
for this story tells us something useful about him: he set much
store by instinct. No wonder, then, that it would be to his
instincts _ honed in the Texas hill country, sharpened in a life of
politics, confirmed in a long and respected congressional career _
that he would often turn while in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   This reliance on instinct enabled Johnson to put on the
presidency like a suit of comfortable old clothes. John Kennedy, on
the other hand, came to it with a historical, nearly theoretical
view of what was required of a strong president _ he knew exactly
what Woodrow Wilson had said about the office and he had read
Corwin and Neustadt. With eager confidence, Kennedy acquired a
presidential suit off the rack and put on a little weight to make
himself fit it.''
</P>
<P>
   1. In the passage, the author is primarily concerned with
</P>
<P>
   (A) explaining an event
</P>
<P>
   (B) making a comparison
</P>
<P>
   (C) listing facts
</P>
<P>
   (D) retelling a story
</P>
<P>
   (E) refuting an argument
</P>
<P>
   2. Which of the following words, if substituted for the word
``occult'' ... would introduce the least change in the meaning of
the sentence?
</P>
<P>
   (A) legendary
</P>
<P>
   (B) subtle
</P>
<P>
   (C) invisible
</P>
<P>
   (D) persuasive
</P>
<P>
   (E) supernatural
</P>
<P>
   ``With the influx of Cuban citizens into Miami in 1959,
thousands of Spanish-speaking children enrolled in Florida's public
schools. Since teachers had been among the professional groups that
left Cuba, Florida schools had access to teachers who shared the
language and culture of the new students. The school boards had to
decide whether the children should learn English before entering
school or whether education in both languages should be tried.
Fortunately, the latter method was chosen. This event had a
significant influence on the acceptance and growth of bilingual
education in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   3. Which of the following statements best expresses the author's
main point in the passage?
</P>
<P>
   (A) Florida's public schools were among the first in the country
to offer bilingual education to Spanish-speaking children.
</P>
<P>
   (B) School systems considering bilingual education programs
would do well to model their programs after those used in Miami
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   (C) Bilingual education programs in Florida schools have been
very successful and deserve more national recognition.
</P>
<P>
   (D) Florida school boards made the right choice when they
decided in 1959 to offer bilingual education to Spanish-speaking
children.
</P>
<P>
   (E) Bilingual education was revived in Florida in the 1960s
because of an influx of Spanish-speaking students into the public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Answers
</P>
<P>
   (1.) The passage is about the different approaches of Johnson
and Kennedy to the presidency. In explaining how each approached
the office and how they differed in this respect, the author is
necessarily making a comparison. The correct answer is B.
</P>
<P>
   (2.) The ``occult'' power described in the first sentence is
clearly not a power that people ordinarily have. It could,
therefore, best be described as ``supernatural.'' Choice E is the
best answer.
</P>
<P>
   (3.) The author presents an educational problem that confronted
Florida schools in 1959 _ the need to make an important decision
about whether to require Spanish-speaking children to learn English
before entering school. However, in addition to conveying this
information, the author wishes to convey approval of the decision
made by the Florida school boards because of its positive influence
on the acceptance of bilingual education. The last two sentences of
the passage demonstrate the author's positive attitude toward the
school boards' decision. This attitude toward the decision is
reflected in choice D, the correct answer.
</P>
</TEXT>
