<HEADER>
A3538 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-BASEBALL-HEROES-REV     09-14 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BASEBALL-HEROES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
12.) 
 BIG-BANG THEORY: A BLAST FROM THE PAST MAKES BASEBALL A CURRENT
EVENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing. Origianlly filed on Saturday, September (The Week in Review)  
 (duplication warning: also sent with `s' code)  
 Alan Schwarz is a columnist for Baseball America magazine.  
 (bl)  
 By ALAN SCHWARZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shortly after Fox Television bought the broadcasting rights to
major-league baseball games three years ago, Fox Sports president
David Hill issued a simple dictum to his newly assembled producers
and announcers: ``I don't want to hear about dead guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill, a native Australian, rankled a few people by seemingly
thumbing his nose at baseball's cherished memories of Babe Ruth,
Mickey Mantle and countless others. But he had decided that the
sport needed to lose some of its past to move into the future. How
fitting, then, that Fox wound up broadcasting Mark McGwire's
record-breaking 62nd home run Tuesday night: when one swing,
witnessed by more than 50 million people in living rooms, bars and
airport waiting lounges around the world, helped vault baseball
into the modern age.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, baseball has been haunted by its past. Other sports
(and the news media that cover them) have always embraced
evolution, capitalizing on gradual appreciation of fans for
end-zone dances and monster dunks, and hailing contemporary players
like Michael Jordan and Joe Montana as the best of all time.
Baseball, though, has remained beholden to its halcyon days of
Ruth, Joe DiMaggio and the Brooklyn Dodgers' Boys of Summer,
suggesting that the sport's best days are behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Mention to many fans that the Seattle Mariners slugger Ken
Griffey Jr. could be a better all-around player than Willie Mays
and they gasp as if you're burning baseball's flag. No other sport
makes such a killing off old-time uniforms that sob ``Remember
when?'' And as the new economics of professional sports spawn
viruses ranging from free-agent hopscotch to player strikes,
baseball's mantra has become ``Where have you gone, Joe DiMaggio?''
</P>
<P>
   Although baseball's charming 129-year history is a unique asset
that distinguishes it from younger sports, it has also become an
undertow from which the sport has struggled to escape. Today's
sports fans aren't preoccupied with history; they focus on the next
this, the next that. Figures from the past often get mistaken as
curiosities rather than as cherished legends.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's home run threw baseball a lifeline in that regard. In
the past 20 years no player's pursuit of history has evoked such
widespread intrigue and excitement. (The breaking of Lou Gehrig's
consecutive-game record by Cal Ripken Jr. in 1995 was enjoyed more
as an antidote to the bitterness left by the recent strike than
with the sheer giddiness surrounding McGwire.) At last, a modern
star moved past the black-and-white ghosts of the past to wrest
away baseball's most prestigious record. Today's era now has its
own bona-fide hero, one that has joined the towering figures of
old.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the only sport with a history, with players like Babe
Ruth, Lou Gehrig and Ty Cobb,'' said major-league baseball
president Paul Beeston. ``Now we've got a guy at the close of the
century you can mention in the same breath.''
</P>
<P>
   After McGwire swatted No. 62 to break Roger Maris' 37-year-old
record, the new generation of fans said they were tired of hearing
how great the old-timers were, and felt empowered to stick up for
their era. ``I think that today's players are as good as anyone,''
said Adam Modesto, a 13-year-old St. Louis eighth-grader. ``Just
because the older ones did it first doesn't mean they're the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if previous generations of players were better than those
playing today, Ken Caver, a 19-year-old sophomore at Austin Peay
University in Clarksville, Tenn., smiled. ``I thought they were,''
he said. ``Until now.''
</P>
<P>
   Modern players share the frustration at how their sport's rich
history obscures the present. ``Baseball is a good-ol'-boy club,''
said Barry Larkin, the Cincinnati Reds shortstop. ``It's so
conservative and so slow to change. The tradition of baseball _ you
hear about that all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   All-time all-star teams usually pay tribute to legends like
Jimmie Foxx, Ted Williams and Honus Wagner and include few, if any,
players who played in the last 20 years. Will McGwire now get some
consideration over Gehrig at first base? Will that start
conversation about other current players? What is heresy today
could be history tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire himself saw a subtle shift toward appreciating the
modern game during his chase. ``Hopefully it continues with not
just me, but with the other great players in the game,'' he said,
giving a nod to his fellow sluggers Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs
and Griffey. ``There is unbelievable talent right now in the game
of baseball. I think everybody across America is seeing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before McGwire, whose summer-long pursuit of the home-run record
inspired celebratory national commercials from the likes of
Mastercard and Pepsi, companies involved with baseball often played
off the sport's grip on its past. To promote its ``Sunday Night
Baseball'' games three years ago, ESPN stuck two crotchety
Brooklynites in a bar and had them complain about everything from
the Dodgers' defection to how they couldn't set the clock on their
VCR.
</P>
<P>
   A commercial for Sports Illustrated, with elegiac music in the
background, offered a free baseball video titled ``When It Was a
Game.'' A TV ad for Franklin batting gloves captured baseball's
discomfort with changing times perfectly: It had Barry Bonds (the
me-first modern athlete) teasing Ripken (the treasured throwback)
that he needed an earring. As Ripken looked in the mirror, he
sighed, ``I wonder what Dad would say.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, meanwhile, has been embraced by both fathers and sons.
(Grandfathers? Let's not get greedy.) Surveys showed that up to 90
percent of fans, both young and old, wanted the brawny Cardinal
first baseman to break the record. Their fascination with the
slugger helped unify generations of fans.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one reason why McGwire's chase enthralled the nation
was that baseball, by virtue of its age and history, has hallowed
records and legends (and dead guys) that capture the imagination
the way few other sports can match.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine there will be daily countdowns and live
cut-ins when a football quarterback approaches the touchdown-pass
record, or when a basketball guard scores the most points ever in a
season. Baseball records have evolved over so much time that they
evoke a public respect and loyalty unmatched in American sports.
</P>
<P>
   That loyalty, however, has often held baseball back as the rest
of the sports world has evolved. Ask fans over the age of 40 what
image most symbolizes baseball and many would say Mantle's
ferocious swing, or Mays playing stick ball in the streets. It was
so much simpler then.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's blast showed that baseball still provides its simple
thrills. And maybe, just maybe, these can be the good old days,
too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 0927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
