<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3586 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN16-CO     09-14 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Looking beyond Clinton, to America
 &HT;    (For release, Wednesday, Sept. 16, 1998)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   And, so, we again are about to send out Diogenes and his lantern
in search of a person who can lead a life of self-control and,
although probably too much to ask, free of all desire for material
things and pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how our presidential crisis comes out _ impeachment,
censure, resignation, continuance _ there's going to be a new
president. If not next week, certainly by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The office of the presidency has been eroded by Bill Clinton's
lies, betrayals and libido; the institution is severely damaged and
badly in need of repair.
</P>
<P>
   When Richard Nixon was forced to resign, he was replaced by a
man, Gerald Ford, whose integrity few would question. Although his
pardon of Nixon did raise some questions, Ford nevertheless served
this country best by calming it down from the divisiveness of the
Watergate investigation and subsequent findings.
</P>
<P>
   We are at that point again. Who shall succeed Clinton? For the
next few years, that would be Al Gore, but you don't have to read
tea leaves to know that he already has been targeted for illegal
fund-raising, and his ascension to the presidency only will
accelerate that issue.
</P>
<P>
   Looking out on the American scene is dispiriting; few are out
there who command the respect of the entire nation. Too much has
the U.S. been politically polarized.
</P>
<P>
   It is interesting, therefore, to look back at Colin Powell, the
reluctant candidate with Republican credentials. All through this
continuing Clinton tragedy, Powell has kept clear of the mob, on a
high plane, dealing with matters free of taint or partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   Others who would be president _ Gore, Dan Quayle, Newt Gingrich,
Dick Gephardt, Steve Forbes, et al. _ hardly are universally loved,
or respected.
</P>
<P>
   America looks for the same person sought by Diogenes. Whether or
not he (or she) exists is questionable, as no one is safe from the
deepest scrutiny of muckrakers _ whether in the media or on ugly
political expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   Diogenes never found what he was looking for, nor will we. There
is no perfect person. But next best will do quite well. And I don't
see ``next best'' stoking up the coals for a mid-winter visit to
New Hampshire and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Through all this, Powell has been quiet, a nonparticipant in the
filth that is covering Washington, D.C., these days. I am loath to
proclaim that the former Army general has gone through life without
fault, because we have re-created and expanded our interpretations
of public fault.
</P>
<P>
   His wife fears a presidential run; she said so several years
ago. But, she said, she feared it more for whatever racial tremors
it might stir. We still don't know if Colin Powell is a choirboy
because the cutthroats haven't been set loose on him yet.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day, when most of us were basking in the aura of
the Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa accomplishments in baseball, saying
to ourselves how wonderful it was to happen at a time like this, my
cynical genes caused me to remark that after the glow of the
baseball glory wears off, someone is going to look for and possibly
find some dark secret lurking in McGwire's or Sosa's pasts to tear
them down from their pedestals.
</P>
<P>
   It's the way we do things.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton wasn't solely responsible for improving the U.S.
economy any more than Ronald Reagan and George Bush were
responsible for the collapse of the Soviet Union. Those things just
happened to happen on their watch.
</P>
<P>
   What we seek most in a president is to respect and revere him.
Our Constitution wisely has separated the powers of the nation into
three branches, the executive being only one _ and, to my thinking,
the least powerful.
</P>
<P>
   This nation needs a leader who can restore our confidence in the
presidency. I don't see any of the prominent pretenders as having
that ability. And unless or until someone finds something deep in
Colin Powell's closet, he would appear to be, however reluctant he
is, a man we might need at this time.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
