<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3587 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN16-COX     09-14 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: No case for impeachment
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, so sometimes a cigar isn't just a cigar, but even so, if
anything can rehabilitate the Clinton presidency, the Starr
report's excesses and flimsy charges may do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ought to resign for ethical reasons, out of chagrin at
the human wreckage caused by his misbehaviors and, pragmatically,
in recognition that even if he can manage to stick, he'll be the
captain of a grounded ship of state.
</P>
<P>
   But if the president does try to gut this thing out, his
impeachment on the evidence of the Starr report would set a
precedent that could start a cycle of political attacks and
presidential collapses that would amount to coups in legal
trimmings.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr never should have been in the Paula Jones/Monica
Lewinsky business in the first place. His presence there is an
insupportable extrusion from his original charter to investigate
land deals from the 1980s in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, a conservative Republican and long-laboring water carrier
for his party, has functioned as the de facto legal arm of lavishly
funded right-wing efforts to undo Clinton's elections. The
prosecutor has acted _ not overtly but surely not unwittingly
either _ as a facilitator for Jones's private lawyers, who were
outrageously demanding that the president name every woman he had
sex with while he was attorney general and governor of Arkansas and
as president.
</P>
<P>
   In was in furtherance of that sort of get-Clinton trolling that
Starr perked up at Linda Tripp's sexual tattling when he should
have dismissed it out of hand as having no legitimate bearing on
his charge. The result is a report that for all its huffing and
puffing presents a case for impeachment that is very thin gruel.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear the president lied, in the common meaning of the
word, about not having had sex with Lewinsky, though he may have
been dodgy enough in his testimony to fishtail through the narrow
definition of sex that had been established for the Jones case.
Either way, few of us would have a president impeached for lying
about sex in a private lawsuit that was itself politically
inspired.
</P>
<P>
   Starr charges obstruction of justice in the prior understanding
Lewinsky and Clinton had to deny their affair, but how many illicit
lovers don't have such an understanding? The back-and-forth over
the president's gifts to Lewinsky is muddled and inconclusive.
Clinton's efforts to land Lewinsky a new job preceded her subpoena
and Starr doesn't tie them to her testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The scariest part of the report _ with grave implications for
everyone's civil liberties should it prevail _ is its charge that
the president abused his power by lying to associates who were then
unable to rat him out to the grand jury, by putting off his own
testimony as long as he could and by filing bothersome lawsuits _
in short, by defending himself from Starr. There are the makings of
megalomania in that weird construction of abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   In its needlessly extensive rehearsal of sexual particulars and
in its leering prurience _ so like the anti-smut crusaders who
collect pornography to decry it _ the Starr report suggests that
this business really is just about sex, even, and maybe especially,
in Starr's own mind.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
