<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-WALLACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-ALABAMA GOVERNOR GEORGE WALLACE DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WIL HAYGOOD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Wallace, the feisty and mercurial Alabama governor who
ran for president four times and enshrined himself in US political
history when he challenged the Kennedy administration over the
issue of integration at the University of Alabama in 1963, died
Sunday in a Montgomery, Ala., hospital. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Wallace entered the hospital Thursday, suffering from
breathing problems and septic shock caused by a severe bacterial
infection. He also had been hospitalized this summer with similar
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Wallace's health had been failing since 1972, when he was
shot five times by a would-be assassin in a parking lot in Laurel,
Md., during a presidential campaign rally.
</P>
<P>
   The shooting paralyzed Mr. Wallace from the waist down and left
him in perpetual pain, according to his doctors. But those who
thought the shooting would end Mr. Wallace's political career were
premature in their thinking: He went on to serve two additional
terms as Alabama's governor.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Wallace in recent years had battled Parkinson's disease as
well as the lingering effects of his wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Wallace's death ends one of the more storied and volatile
careers in American political history, which saw Mr. Wallace assail
blacks, liberals, presidents, and ``pinko communists.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a career that began in Mr. Wallace's native Barbour
County, Ala., when he returned home from World War II. As a state
judicial candidate, Mr. Wallace shamelessly appealed to racist
tactics, at times drawing Ku Klux Klan support, which he utilized
during future campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   But during the last decade of his life, Mr. Wallace had begged
forgiveness for his onetime racist appeals, crying from the pulpit
of black churches across Alabama, giving his political life an
unexpected _ and sometimes touching _ twist as it ended.
</P>
<P>
   George Corley Wallace was born in the small town of Clio, Ala.,
on Aug. 25, 1919.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Wallace would ricochet onto the national political scene in
a riveting showdown with the Kennedy Justice Department. On June
11, 1963, Mr. Wallace stood in the schoolhouse door on the
University of Alabama campus in Tuscaloosa and tried to block two
blacks from entering. Mr. Wallace, who stepped aside with the show
of federal troops, called the federal action an ``illegal
usurpation of power by the central government.''
</P>
<P>
   To many of his fellow Southerners, Mr. Wallace rose as icon and
near-mythic figure.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Wallace's Jan. 14, 1963, inauguration speech seemed a brutal
and nostalgic reach for Southern gallantry during the Civil War.
Mr. Wallace wrapped himself in Old Confederacy rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the name of the greatest people that ever trod this earth,
I draw the line in the dust and toss the gauntlet before the feet
of tyranny. And I say: Segregation now! Segregation tomorrow!
Segregation forever!''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Wallace's political rise coincided with the modern American
civil rights movement. A mere two blocks from the Montgomery
statehouse sat the Dexter Avenue Baptist church. In its pulpit
stood the young Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   On March 21, 1965, one of the more dramatic civil rights
demonstrations was staged in Alabama: the Selma-to-Montgomery
march, a 50-mile trek on behalf of voting rights. When the 50,000
marchers reached the Alabama statehouse, Mr. Wallace ignored them.
Mr. Wallace had earlier tried to stop the march but was overruled
by Judge Johnson. On the night the march ended, March 25, a civil
rights worker from Detroit named Viola Liuzzo was murdered on a
Lowndes County highway by racists.
</P>
<P>
   President Johnson, a short time later, signed the 1965 Voting
Rights Act into law. ``At times history and fate meet in a single
time in a single place to shape a turning point in man's unending
search for freedom,'' Johnson said. ``So it was at Lexington and
Concord. So it was a century ago at Appomattox. So it was last week
in Selma, Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   In his presidential campaigns Mr. Wallace painted himself as a
little man against the tyranny of the big federal government. Mr.
Wallace waged all-out verbal assaults against hippies, Vietnam War
protesters, and those engaged in acts of civil disobedience. ``Any
anarchist scum who lies down in front of our car when we get to be
president, it'll be the last car he'll ever lie down in front of,''
Mr. Wallace remarked.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Wallace first ran for president on the American Independent
Party ticket in 1964. He registered a stunning 43 percent showing
in a Maryland primary. Northern Democratic operatives feared his
appeal to angry voters. Mr. Wallace's campaign eventually fizzled,
but he ran again, in 1968. At times Mr. Wallace approached the
totals of Democratic nominee Hubert Humphrey in early fall opinion
polls. However, in the end, Mr. Wallace won only five states and
Richard Nixon was elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Wallace's digs at bigtime Washington political figures
endeared him to poor Southern whites and disgruntled voters
elsewhere. ``The instincts of a common-sense Alabamian are better
than the brains of a New York intellectual moron,'' Mr. Wallace
once remarked.
</P>
<P>
   On May 15, 1972, a onetime Milwaukee busboy named Arthur Bremer
trailed presidential candidate George Wallace to a campaign rally
at a Maryland shopping center. Bremer fired five bullets into Mr.
Wallace, paralyzing him from the waist down. Mr. Wallace believed
the assasination attempt was a conspiracy, without offering proof.
Bremer received a 60-year prison sentence and refused to talk about
his motives.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Wallace had several operations to ease the pain over the
years, but remained on heavy doses of pain-killing medication the
rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his confinement to a wheelchair, Mr. Wallace won
reelection for governor again in 1974. By that time, the South had
begun to change perceptibly, especially in statehouses. Georgia
Gov. Governor Jimmy Carter, for example, had gained national
attention for espousing progressive attitudes toward race. It was
the success of Carter's 1976 presidential run that thwarted Mr.
Wallace's final attempt to reach the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the more dramatic aspects of his waning political
life, Mr. Wallace sought to make amends with blacks. Appearing
before groups of black elected officials, Mr. Wallace apologized
for his stance against integration. During his last stint as
governor, from 1983 to 1987, Mr. Wallace made significant black
appointments, and was also credited with funding black junior
colleges in the state of Alabama. Often, appearing before black
groups, he became teary-eyed and emotional.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1993 interview in his Montgomery law office with The Boston
Globe, Mr. Wallace said, ``I'm not a bad man.'' And as he pondered
death, he said, ``I'm all right with the Lord.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
