<P>
   1. THE SWOON OF THE SWOOSH The coolest kids now think Nike's
logo is decidedly uncool. Liberals think it means ``exploits Asian
workers.'' The only thing that still works for Nike is Michael
Jordan - and he's about to retire. Has branding given Nike a bad
name? By Timothy Egan. From The New York Times Magazine. 2,000
words. Full-length article (3,800 words) available on request. 2.
WINNING THE DRUG WAR ISN'T SO HARD AFTER ALL For nearly 20 years,
the United States has waged a relentless war on drugs, with
treatment discounted as a weak weapon. Instead, the government has
sent spy planes flying over the Caribbean, built a paramilitary
base in Peru, mounted coca-eradication programs in Bolivia - and
invaded Panama. But this punitive approach has failed. By Michael
Massing. From The New York Times Magazine. 2,000 words. Full-length
article (3,000 words) available on request. 3. LABYRINTH OF
SOLITUDE Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, the mayor of Mexico City, is the
second most prominent man in his country, the son of one of its
most beloved presidents and Mexico's best hope for reform. Then why
does he seem so alone and helpless? Cardenas needed what every
left-winger is looking for in Latin America today : a novel and
convincing way to stand for a better future without seeming to
stand for the failures of the past. But no such formula was at
hand. By Paul Berman. From The New York Times Magazine. 7,500
words. 4. AMERICANS FEAR SNOOPS MORE THAN GERMS ``While deploring
the loss of his own privacy this summer, President Clinton set out
boldly to invade mine,'' writes Max Frankel. ``His administration
promised me a healthier life if I would accept assignment of a
computer code - a number or thumb print or retina marker or other
electronic gizmo to be called a UHI, a unique health identifier. It
would instantly disclose my medical record to anyone needing to
treat me anywhere ... Shouts of protest forced the president to
retreat. Americans, it seems, fear snoops even more than they fear
germs.'' From The New York Times Magazine. 1,000 words. 5. THE
EUROPEAN VIEW OF CLINTON'S TRAUMA German journalist Josef Joffe
observes that Europeans find the charges of sexual misconduct
against Clinton to be frivolous, but take seriously his pattern of
lies. New York Times Op-Ed. 800 words. 6. THE BABY WHO STOPPED
EATING Pediatrics professor Robert Marion reports on his treatment
of an infant patient who, for no apparent reason, stopped nursing.
(The answer was found in a jar of honey ... infected with
botulism.) From Discover magazine. 1,600 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
THE SURREALISTS MEET THE HOPI PEOPLE Kachina dolls, which represent
the mythical ancestors of Hopi Pueblo Indians in Arizona and New
Mexico, are the subject of a new exhibition in Paris until October
25. (In the 1940s, Andre Breton, founder of the Surrealist
movement, noted that black sculpture had already been used in
spectacular fashion to inspire artists. ``It is the visual art of
the Red Indian race, in particular, that today enables us to accede
to a new system of knowledge and relationships.'') By Emmanuel de
Roux. From Le Monde. 900 words. English translation available.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
THE DEAD BABY MYSTERY Sudden Infant Death Syndrome is not really a
disease but rather the name we've given to one of the great medical
mysteries of our time. By Atul Gawande. From SLATE (the premier
online magazine of politics and culture.). 1,200 words. 9. MY
PERSONAL SEARCH FOR FAMILY Andrew Blum is adopted. He writes: ``For
me, no matter how much I loved my family, I never knew my roots.
Even now, in 1998, after having found two-thirds of my biological
family, I can't find my father.'' 1,300 words. 10. EXERCISE BUILT
FOR TWO Tandem bicycles are no longer clunky things piloted by
sunburnt tourists lacking the motor skills necessary to ride a bike
on their own. Riding a tandem can be a process of discovery ... By
Ken McAlpine. From Cooking Light Magazine. 1,200 words + photo.
