<SLUG> BC-TV-EMMYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FRASIER' WINS FOR FIFTH TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``No one should complain that the Oscars are the longest show on
TV again,'' announced Billy Crystal Sunday night, picking up his
second Emmy for hosting the Academy Awards show.
</P>
<P>
   But after NBC's enjoyably epic Emmy telecast, we can still
complain that the Oscars remain the most tedious. The four-hour
Emmy presentation was a fast-paced night of TV that paid tribute to
a half-century of itself without an excess of vanity, tedium, or
stuffiness. Filled with vintage, emotion-packed footage and
appearances by faces from TV's past, it was as swift and engaging
as 240 electronic minutes can be. So what if the awards themselves
sometimes seemed like an afterthought, punctuation for the run-on
sentence of clips and reminiscences?
</P>
<P>
   As on most awards shows, the winners ranged from the expected
(HBO's ``From the Earth to the Moon'' for best miniseries) to the
delightful (``The Practice'' for best drama series) to the strange
and outrageous (Helen Hunt's third consecutive Emmy, over Calista
Flockhart and Jenna Elfman, for her notably wan season of ``Mad
About You''). If there was a trend, it belonged to ``Frasier,''
which won three major awards only two weeks before its high-profile
move into the Thursday night ``Seinfeld'' timeslot. The show _
certainly the most consistently funny series _ took its fifth
consecutive Emmy (a record) for outstanding comedy, Kelsey Grammer
won his third Emmy as lead actor in a comedy, and David Hyde Pierce
had his second win as a supporting player, a surprise as he was up
against a sentimental favorite, the late Phil Hartman.
</P>
<P>
   While David E. Kelley's ``Ally McBeal'' did not win in any of
its categories, the writer-producer's other celebrated show, ``The
Practice,'' won not only best dramatic series but best supporting
actress, for Camryn Manheim, who gave the show its strongest
subplot last season. Andre Braugher of ``Homicide'' took home a
long-deserved Emmy for his final season on ``Homicide,'' TV's best
cop show in spite of the fact that it has never been nominated as a
series. ``NYPD Blue,'' meanwhile, took home three statues despite
its weakest season so far. Gordon Clapp won for his supporting
work, against the more heavy-duty performances of ``ER'' actors
Noah Wyle and Eriq La Salle. ``NYPD'' also won awards for writing
and directing. Christine Lahti of `Chicago Hope' was named best
actress in a dramatic series, and, against the more formidable
comedy of Julia Louis-Dreyfus, Lisa Kudrow won as supporting
actress in a comedy series for ``Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   In an odd coincidence, Gary Sinese won for best actor in a
miniseries for ``George Wallace,'' on the day the former governor
died.
</P>
<P>
   As entertainment, the Emmy show had it all _ moments of real
sentiment, triumph, injustice, and nostalgia. There were the
fashion wonders of the world, including a radiant Julianna
Margulies, a regal Camryn Manheim, and Gillian Anderson in black
lace, and there were the requisite Clinton-Lewinski jokes, with
Chris Rock producing a cigar and Dennis Miller thanking Vernon
Jordan for his job. After a barrage of clips of TV's original
comedians, Milton Berle, Bob Hope, and Sid Ceasar appeared on stage
to a wonderfully endless standing ovation. The trio said nothing,
and that was enough.
</P>
<P>
   Most winners kept their acceptances short and sweet, some of
them genuinely emotional. ``Frasier's'' Pierce honored Hartman,
saying ``You all know how great he is,'' and Grammer referred to
his sobriety, thanking those who helped him ``at a very dark time
in my life and told me there was a way out.'' The happiest moment
came courtesy of Manheim. ``This is for all the fat girls,'' she
screamed in triumph.
</P>
<P>
   There were clever presenter pairings _ Garry Shandling and David
Duchovny, who showed their comic chemistry in the last episode of
``The Larry Sanders Show'' and again Sunday night _ and a reunion
of the living members of the ``Hill Street Blues'' premiere. The
ubiquitous clips also produced touching moments _ from John
Travolta tearfully accepting an Emmy for his late love, Diana
Hyland, to the always potent newscasts of the death of President
John F. Kennedy, presented as one of 10 TV milestones.
</P>
<P>
   The show's misteps were a trivia game before and after
commercials, and an opening sequence hosted by Bill Costas outside
the LA Shrine Auditorium, as guests arrived. Stiffly, Costas asked
questions to stars like Jenna Elfman, who talked about how being
nominated is like winning. Blah blah blah. Aside from these bits,
the night was golden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
