<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3641 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIRCH-INTERVIEWS15-CO     09-14 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRCH-INTERVIEWS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Experience separates 'Birch' boys
 &HT;    By Alison Macor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Although he's only a few weeks shy of his 15th
birthday, Joseph Mazzello is no stranger to the endless parade of
print and television interviews that make up the publicity machine
for a major motion picture such as Disney's ``Simon Birch,'' a
loose adaptation by Mark Steven Johnson of John Irving's much-loved
novel, ``A Prayer for Owen Meany.''
</P>
<P>
   A veteran of more than 10 films, including ``Jurassic Park'' and
``The River Wild,'' Mazzello speaks with authority about his role
in ``Simon Birch'' from the back seat of a limousine spiriting him
from a Houston television station to theairport.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks later, another interview takes place by phone. This time,
however, the interviewee is Ian Michael Smith, the 11-year-old
sixth-grader who plays the title role in ``Simon Birch.'' Ensconced
in his father's Ill- inois office, far from studio-rented
limousines, Smith talks about his first acting experience as his
father, Steve, remains unobtrusively in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Separated by four years, many movie roles and perhaps even
vastly different perceptions of Hollywood moviemaking, Mazzello's
and Smith's comments about the making of ``Simon Birch'' reflect
their individual approaches to acting as much as they reveal
Mazzello's veteran status in Hollywood and Smith's role as the
enthusiastic newcomer.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzello hasn't read Irving's novel but says he chose the script
because it represented an acting challenge for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really liked the character of Joe,'' says Mazzello,
referring to Simon Birch's best friend. ``I thought that he had a
lot of emotion in the movie, and he had a long range of things that
he had to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that (the role of Joe) showed my talent and what I
could do,'' says Mazzello, revealing the thoughtful choosiness that
has led to his well-received and varied screen performances.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Smith's reasons for starring in ``Simon Birch'' are
less goal-oriented. ``It might be something fun'' is what he
remembers thinking when approached to audition for the film. He
thought Johnson's script about a small boy seeking his destiny was
a ``great story'' and read half of Irving's novel before production
began last fall.
</P>
<P>
   He finished the book after shooting wrapped, and while Smith
likes the witty and sprawling novel that chronicles the fated life
of a small boy with a wrecked voice, he admits that he thought it
was a dense read. ``Too much to process,'' says the young actor,
who is a voracious reader currently plowing through Dilbert creator
Scott Adams' ``Dogbert's Top Secret Management Handbook'' and a
do-it-yourself computer programming book. Toned-down emotions
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who suffers from a rare enzyme disorder called Morquio
syndrome (symptoms include dwarfism and constant fatigue), was
given two acting coaches to help him prepare for his first film
role. Steve Smith, who acted throughout high school and college,
also worked with his son as they read the script many times to
process the film's themes. Mazzello's experience provided another
source of inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something Joe said is really right,'' says Ian Michael Smith
as he talks about getting in and out of character. ``You have to
put yourself in the character's place.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Mazzello was able to offer more input into the film
and his role because of his years of acting experience. He credits
the director for letting him decide how to handle his character.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did talk about how there were so many emotional themes,''
he says. ``We kind of toned down some of them and made them not so
sad. We didn't want this movie to be overly sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ``Simon Birch'' has its poignant moments but some
hilariously chaotic scenes as well. Such Disney-esque mirth may
rankle fans of the Irving book, but it allows ``Simon Birch'' to
stand apart from its source and, from a marketing standpoint, to
appeal to the widest possible audience. As Mazzello says, ``We
didn't want (the movie) to be too much, for people to say, `Oh, I
can't see this movie again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Both boys have favorite scenes from the film, and Mazzello
sounds delighted when he is told his interviewer likes the
Christmas pageant sequence and the scenes in which Simon and Joe
race through the woods in a symbolic gesture of friendship. These
also are Mazzello's favorites.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most affecting scene to him is one in which Joe,
Simon and Joe's mother Rebecca (Ashley Judd) walk down a church
aisle, beautifully backlit. ``I like how that's set up, in between
the pews and (with) the light coming through the doors,'' Mazzello
says.
</P>
<P>
   His awareness of the metaphoric power of a shot's mise-en-scene
not only suggests a veteran's sense of composition but also reveals
Mazzello's desire to direct movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going to like the behind-the-scenes things,'' he
says. ``I've always wanted'' to direct films.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see how it is when you're actually picking the
people instead of getting picked,'' he adds, and his ability to
realize where the power lies on a film set reminds one that he's
been acting in films for most of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also likes the Christmas pageant sequence, but for reasons
that go beyond its hilarity. Shot over the course of two to three
weeks, the sequence allowed the actors to get to know each other
and the children who played supporting characters Without a trace
of disingenuousness, Smith says, ``We really got to know all the
shepherds and the sheep on the set.'' Star personas
</P>
<P>
   While Mazzello hopes to attend college and direct movies, Smith
isn't entirely ready to commit to an acting career. Although he
says he'll continue to act in school plays whether or not other
movie offers materialize, Smith's plans may include practicing law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been attracted to being a lawyer ever since the
second grade,'' he says. ``We had a mock trial over a book called
`Superfudge' (by Judy Blume). We were arguing over whose fault it
was that Fudge lost his two front teeth, and I won!''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the two actors hope only that their film appeals to a
wide range of viewers. Like many of their comments, their
interpretations of the film reflect their ages and their appealing
_ and in the case of Smith, slowly emerging _ star personas.
</P>
<P>
   Mazzello articulately describes ``Simon Birch'' as being ``about
two boys looking for something: One's trying to find his father and
the other (is trying to find) his destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real family movie,'' he says. ``I think everyone's
gonna like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith offers his own description of the film, one that is sweet
without being precious, much like the character he plays in the
film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for all kinds of people who like all kinds of movies,''
he says, ``because it's got some stuff for the people who like sad
drama, stuff for the people who like excitement, and it's got some
funny parts, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon Birch himself couldn't have said it any better.
</P>
<P>
   Alison Macor is a freelancer for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
