<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ Every now and again people are seized
with the passion to scour entire libraries and throw out the dirty
parts. The censorship crowd usually loses, since it has an unerring
instinct for quality, but don't think there is some filth, as
Winston Churchill said, up with which I will not put. My nomination
is Kenneth Starr's official report on the Lewinksy affair.
(Rosenfeld, Cox News Service) MOVED FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio. The woolly worms have begun
wiggling their way across our country roads, signaling winter's
imminence with its pall of short, gray days and serious lack of
things to do once the ironing is finished and the soaps have lost
their suds. Vistas of bleak and aimless lives loom ahead. Soon
it'll be cabin fever time. But there's hope on the horizon.
(Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Gov. George Bush, with his
background as a baseball owner, should understand. If you want to
compete you have to pony up. If all that matters to you is keeping
your payroll down, if you look at players as expendable and
interchangeable, you can watch your franchise make a beeline for
the basement. You can watch your star players bolt for free agency.
(Young, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEEWAX-COLUMN _ With his record-breaking home runs last week,
St. Louis Cardinal Mark McGwire not only changed baseball history
but may have shifted economic history a little, too. He reminded us
that by keeping an eye on the ball, instead of the dollar signs, we
can come out winners. (Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (k, f)
