<HEADER>
A3645 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONGHORNS-BRUINS15-CO     09-14 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONGHORNS-BRUINS15-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   AUS-LONGHORNS-BRUINS-SH
</P>
<P>
   Bruins wary of UT, 'ludicrous' 66-3
</P>
<P>
   By Kirk Bohls
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Mike Meyers has always been a huge college
football fan. Every Saturday afternoon, a satellite dish brought to
the Southern California home of the Fortune 500 distributor many of
the nation's elite programs. Notre Dame. Alabama. USC. And Texas.
Yes, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Meyers would sit at his father's knee and be educated.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad loves all the old teams,'' the freckle-faced giant of
an offensive guard was saying after UCLA's practice. ``Texas
football is big-time, he'd say. He used to root for Texas all the
time, but I don't think he will on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Allegiances change, the same as power structures and kids so
skinny they were nicknamed ``Bones.'' Andy Meyers has grown up, and
so has the game he plays. Scholarship limitations, gender equity,
the advent of pro-style offenses, better athletes, and yes, even
satellite dishes that have shrunk college football's global village
have shifted at least part of the game's power base away from
programs like Texas and UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   That's why in the '90s Colorado State and Kansas State can
finagle their way into the Top 25, why Arizona State crowds into
the traditional Pac-10 conflict along with the USC, UCLA and
Washington, why Miami of Ohio can be ranked ahead of that other
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in this class struggle with a radically altered football
landscape, Texas' image curiously remains unsoiled. How else can
Texas whip up on a hapless New Mexico State 66-36 and find itself
ranked? How else can one explain the Bruins' deferential respect
for a program they obliterated by 63 points just a year ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't show us Texas football,'' UCLA linebacker Brendon
Ayanbadejo says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an automatic respect for Texas,'' center Shawn Stuart
says. ``They're Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Or they were. Since Darrell Royal coached his last season in
1976, the Longhorns have finished in the Top 10 only four times.
Texas has won only two minor bowls since 1981, one of which
(Bluebonnet) no longer even exists. Of the school's 12 losing
seasons in 105 years, five have come since 1985. Saturday's game
with UCLA would be a good place for the new coach, Mack Brown, to
start reclaiming Texas' place.
</P>
<P>
   ``They scored 66 points last week,'' UCLA Coach Bob Toledo says.
``That got our attention. Last year was just a crazy game.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Texas handed out turnovers like they were campaign
literature, and UCLA took them. And, sure, Ricky Williams was
limited to 36 yards as much by the Longhorns wanting to spare him
as the Bruins wanting to deny him. But Texas allowed it to totally
defrock part of college football royalty. Great programs do not
lose 66-3 at home. To anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect the University of Texas,'' says Ayanbadejo, one of
only four returning starters on the UCLA defense. ``But I'd have to
say they gave up last year. They put their heads down. I was
definitely surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some Horns haven't disputed it.
</P>
<P>
   Texas offensive guard Ben Adams, a Californian by birth but
Longhorn by position, called it ``the worst four hours in my entire
life. They came into our house and beat us 66-3. The one thing that
broke my heart was halfway through the third (second actually)
quarter, our fans were leaving. I don't blame 'em, but it's just so
sad.''
</P>
<P>
   The question that remains revolves around these two teams'
reaction to last year's disaster. The Bruins minimize the revenge
factor. ``That'll wear off, that initial hatred,'' Ayanbadejo
notes. ``They have a lot of tendencies. I think they're somewhat
predictable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be out for blood, but we're going to be
motivated, too,'' Stuart adds. ``They've got some burning, but
they're by no means walking into a scared football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's win snapped an 0-2 slump and propelled the Bruins to
10 consecutive wins, including a victory over Texas A&AMP;M in the
Cotton Bowl, and a preseason No. 7 ranking. Despite the loss of two
offensive players who scored 37 of the team's 60 touchdowns, the
bulk of the defense and its coordinator, UCLA is a legitimate
contender to win its second national title and first since 1954.
The Bruins have rising stars in redshirt freshman wideout Freddie
Mitchell and rookie tailback DeShaun Foster and think the team's
better than last year.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is trying to become respected again. UCLA is already
giving them that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've practiced so hard that the coaches have had to calm us
down,'' Meyers says. ``Last year's score was absolutely ludicrous.
We just caught them off guard. Hey, they probably overlooked New
Mexico State last week, but we're definitely not New Mexico
State.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
