NYT-09-14-98 1040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3646 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLINS-INTERVIEW15-C     09-14 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-INTERVIEW15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Collins memoirs were matter of survival
 &HT;    By Anne Morris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Judy Collins always looks peaceful on stage
singing intricate folksongs in her pure, clear voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm peaceful,'' she says, ``but my legs are really moving
under water.'' Her voice is cheerful, familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, somehow her life has always been more difficult than it
looked from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed by phone from her home in New York City, Collins
talked about the pain that produced ``Singing Lessons: A Memoir of
Love, Loss, Hope and Healing,'' and the accompanying CD of four
original songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upon my son's death it seemed clear that I had to write about
it,'' she said. ``It really was the only way I could get through
the personal recovery.'' Clark, her son and only child, committed
suicide in 1992, leaving a wife and child. He had been troubled for
years with drug and alcohol addiction, but appeared to be doing
better.
</P>
<P>
   Devastated by Clark's death, Collins looked for ways to live
afterward . Always a reader, she tried to find books on suicide
survival. There was none that spoke to her. She kept a journal,
writing daily meditations, and began writing the story of her life
and her son's. ``Singing Lessons'' includes what she learned about
suicide, addictions and survival through therapy, through friends,
through books. In the end, she learned to live again, even to allow
herself to experience joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was an important story to tell,'' she said. ``I
was determined to get this story out.''
</P>
<P>
   No one wanted a book about suicide, but as a memoir, it could be
published.
</P>
<P>
   Since she had earlier written an autobiography, this book does
not go into as much detail about all parts of her life as it might.
There is a fair amount about her much-adored father, a radio
performer sightless since he was a child and unpredictable when he
drank; a description of her bouts with polio and tuberculosis and
of her recovery from alcoholism; stories of her demanding music
teachers, her developing career. But sometimes, the book leaves you
wanting more.
</P>
<P>
   For example, you'll be reading along about her musical history
and run into a sentence like: ``I had become friends with John
Phillips, with whom I had taken my first acid trip, and who...would
put together the Mamas and Papas.'' In the next paragraph she's
talking about using a cello on an album for the first time. It's
all straightforward and matter-of-fact, yet strangely warm and
open. You learn her family was, and is, important to her. You learn
how hard she worked and what social issues she cared about. In some
ways she was highly disciplined; in others, not at all. She came to
fame in the '60s, after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted you to know the context of my life, but I wanted to
not go into detail with things that would take away from the
flow.''
</P>
<P>
   The main story is about Clark. Her meditations about his loss
alternate with the chapters. As a teen-ager she married his father,
a graduate student in English literature. At first, her singing
largely supported their lives. But as it took her away more and
more, they grew apart. With the divorce she lost custody of her
son. When he was 9, and his father had remarried, Clark came back
to her.
</P>
<P>
   The book describes her therapy, her son's therapy _ successes
and failures. ``I think that a 28-day program and a recovery
program for addictions can work,'' she said. ``Most of us have some
addiction _ something we'd like to change in our lives. Although it
has its benefits, I'm not sure therapy is terribly helpful for
those things. In my therapy I ran into a bunch of people that I
don't think were very helpful in the long run for me, but I don't
know how I would've managed to live if I hadn't found them in the
first place.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Collins turns to short-term therapy. Living day by
day, she exercises, meditates and, of course, sings. Such things
have saved her life.
</P>
<P>
   A fan of President Bill Clinton, who along with Hillary is a fan
of hers, Collins gives a chapter to her performances in Washington,
D.C., and her night spent in the Lincoln bedroom, after which she
got up and jogged with the president.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the wake of the Monica Lewinsky affair, Collins is
worried about her friend. She called him recently on Martha's
Vineyard to wish him a happy birthday. ``In the midst of it, I
think he was stunned that anybody was on the phone to him,''
Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   She sees Clinton now as having a serious problem but hopes the
presidency can be salvaged. ``You and I hired this guy,'' she said.
``What do you do with somebody who's an employee who's got
problems, but who's also got tremendous strengths? Do you want to
throw away all the good things? Do you only focus on the negative?
I must say, though, that it's essential in a personal crisis of
this kind where there's some kind of dysfunction or illness going
on that it be confronted. I have no doubt about that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the happy part of Collins' book, she marries the man she has
been with for 17 years and embraces the future as embodied by her
work, her granddaughter. At 59, the singer is doing more concerts
than ever and continuing to write songs and books. ``Sixty? It's
there and I don't feel any particular way about it...I have no
intention of retiring. Anybody who has the kind of life that I've
had knows that's not in the cards. I'll probably do a novel next.''
</P>
<P>
   She reads constantly. This past summer it was mostly
biographies, though she also had ``Memoirs of a Geisha'' and Iris
Murdoch's ``Jackson's Dilemma'' on her stack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've found through my writing the kind of voice that I
needed to find that singing could not provide for me,'' Collins
said. ``It's essential for me to continue to write prose ...
there's more freedom in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Morris is a book editor for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
