<P>
   TV-RATINGS _ Checking on over-the-weekend TV ratings for Clinton
coverage. (Harris, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURFER _ PBS airs ``Family Name,'' an excellent film about a
white man discovering his connections to black families with his
same last name; plus reminder that ``King of the Hill'' and
``Costello'' start their seasons this night. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-SHULER _ LONDON _ Interview with actor Shuler Hensley,
the Georgia native who has become the toast of London theater for
his performance as Jud in the Royal National Theatre production of
``Oklahoma!'' (Campbell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-GODOT _ The first black U.S. production of ``Waiting for
Godot,'' featuring actors from Jomandi Productions in Atlanta.
(Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   NEWSSTAND _ Periodicals on the newsstands this week. (O'Briant,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-JENKINS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The good news is that even
though Dan Jenkins has sworn off all the fun stuff that's bad for
you, his fictional characters have not. The usual suspects in his
new novel, ``Rude Behavior,'' have been with him since 1972's
``Semi-Tough.'' And although they're older, they're unrepentant in
their personal habits. (Beach, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-INTERVIEW _ AUSTIN _ Judy Collins always looks peaceful
on stage singing intricate folksongs in her pure, clear voice. Yet,
somehow her life has always been more difficult than it looked from
the outside. Interviewed by phone from her home in New York City,
Collins talked about the pain that produced ``Singing Lessons: A
Memoir of Love, Loss, Hope and Healing,'' and the accompanying CD
of four original songs. (Morris, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BIRCH-INTERVIEWS _ Separated by four years, many movie roles and
perhaps even vastly different perceptions of Hollywood moviemaking,
Mazzello's and Smith's comments about the making of ``Simon Birch''
reflect their individual approaches to acting as much as they
reveal Mazzello's veteran status in Hollywood and Smith's role as
the enthusiastic newcomer. (Macor, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GAMESHOW _ To celebrate America's facination with game shows
(there's even an entire cable TV channel dedicated to game shows!)
join us for our own game and take a peek at their kooky past.
(Houck, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
