<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REALLIFE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Going outside always beats going online
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are you tired?
</P>
<P>
   Does your back hurt?
</P>
<P>
   Feel like you're in a funk?
</P>
<P>
   Well, it might be more than just the Monday morning blues.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you spent hour upon hour at the computer over the
weekend _ and which one of us out there didn't? _ you could have a
bigger problem than just wishing it were still Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking about the latest rage and, no, it has nothing to do
with Bill Clinton's feelings for Ken Starr.
</P>
<P>
   It's Internet depression. And, in case you think I'm lying,
there's a $1.5 million study out there to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   About four years ago, researchers at Carnegie Mellon University
selected 98 families from the Pittsburgh area, families that had
never used the Internet. Or at least not very much.
</P>
<P>
   The study paid for a computer, an extra phone line and Internet
connection in each of these homes. And then they sat back for three
years and watched the families' on-line wanderings.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the researchers measured everyone's mental
standings through a variety of psychological tests. And guess what?
</P>
<P>
   People who use the computer a lot have an increased amount of
depression.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a horrid depression. We're not saying you'll be fine
one day, suicidal the next. But people who day after day, year
after year, used the Internet felt sad and isolated. They were in a
funk.
</P>
<P>
   Now, sometimes people forget about a little something I like to
call common sense and I think that's what happened with the folks
who just got done spending $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   See, I am the mother of a computer-loving 7-year-old. And I
could have given you similar results for a lot less money.
</P>
<P>
   My findings?
</P>
<P>
   Kids who use the computer have a glazed look. They practically
forget to use the bathroom. They throw a fit when you tell them to
turn off the computer, now, and do homework. And at the dinner
table, they talk about that little Pac-Man guy instead of the cool
fort they built out back after school.
</P>
<P>
   A Virginia psychologist who specializes in on-line mental health
_ I love that _ has this to say about the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Internet has the potential to imbalance people's
lives in ways they don't expect,'' says Dr. Leonard Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes' job is fascinating. He watches the effects of computers
on humans. And here's what worries the doctor:
</P>
<P>
   When you're with someone in real life, you can naturally take a
little break from that someone. It kind of happens innately, like
when your husband's on your nerves. You leave the room.
</P>
<P>
   That's the real world.
</P>
<P>
   But in the virtual world, you can have solitude and contact at
the same time. When someone's on your nerves _ say, your virtual
lover _ you don't have to leave the room. You're already alone! And
that's a bizarre interpersonal thing (``thing'' being the true
medical term) that people like Dr. Holmes are studying.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get caught up in all that clinical mumbo-jumbo. Just
remember.
</P>
<P>
   Balance is good.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the room when your husband is on your nerves is better.
</P>
<P>
   And building a fort outdoors after school is best.
</P>
<P>
   Now give me my $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
