r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN15-COX     09-14 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``Silent strike''
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Gov. George Bush, with his background as a
baseball owner, should understand. If you want to compete you have
to pony up.
</P>
<P>
   If all that matters to you is keeping your payroll down, if you
look at players as expendable and interchangeable, you can watch
your franchise make a beeline for the basement. You can watch your
star players bolt for free agency.
</P>
<P>
   That's what's happening in Texas schools, in a development
framed in terms that a baseball team owner in the '90s should
appreciate: The Texas State Teachers Association calls it a
``silent strike.''
</P>
<P>
   No, this isn't guys with in gold chains around their big necks
driving off in their BMWs to tough it out on the hundred thousand
in that last paycheck. This is teachers saying goodbye to their
chosen profession, or at least to pursuing it in Texas public
schools. Unprecedented numbers of teachers are reported to be
declaring free agency or retiring outright.
</P>
<P>
   What's a school to do? In lingo a '90s baseball owner should
understand, schools are having to turn to what the strike-torn
major leagues got to know as ``replacement players'' _
non-certified teachers in classes they aren't qualified to teach.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, ya bums. You get the slop you pay for. You expect a scab
pitcher to throw 94 mph fastballs?
</P>
<P>
   With an election approaching, you need a radar gun to clock
candidates in their zest to demonstrate their claim on education as
an issue. Bush is one of those on the campaign trail talking about
increasing teachers' pay with some of the projected $3.7 billion
state surplus.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting to hear this now. During the 75th Legislature,
way back in 1997, you heard no such urgency about teacher pay from
Bush _ or John Sharp, or Rick Perry, or just about anyone else _
though the issue was no less urgent.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the modest teacher pay raise that did emerge in '97
came only after someone influential and with backbone, someone like
state Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant, pointed out that
lawmakers were about to renege on a 1995 promise to teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In the '95 session the legislature dropped the state's merit pay
plan for teachers and agreed to implement a teacher-pay ``escalator
clause'' _ meaning that if the state increased spending on
education, it had to increase its salary base accordingly. Leaders
like State Sen. Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo, chair of the Senate
Education Committee, tried to weasel out of any raise by saying
that no additional dollars were being spent on education, hence no
escalation.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though it appeared as excruciating as yielding a
kidney stone, our lawmakers did raise the state base pay for
teachers. This little flashback should put today's ``urgency'' in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's opponent for governor, Garry Mauro, is saying he would
give Texas teachers a $6,000 across-the-board raise to bring the
state up from its rank of 38th nationally in average pay up to the
middle of the pack, costing about $3.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says he'd send $1 billion to school districts to spend as
they wish on teacher pay or class sizes, and would reduce property
taxes for school districts to the tune of $2 billion. The
assumption with the latter move is that school districts would have
more wiggle room to raise revenue to meet their needs.
</P>
<P>
   Under his proposal, the onus would be on local school boards to
raise the money the state otherwise might spend on schools, and to
take the subsequent heat.
</P>
<P>
   One must ask whether the property-tax wrinkle is meant to
benefit the players on the field, the educators, or if it's
something ultimately to comfort those in the luxury boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Would Texas be anywhere close to the national average in teacher
pay with this proposal? Bet you a McGwire home run ball it
wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
