<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMESHOW15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Come on down! You're the next contestant on . . . name that game
show
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 30 years after it first arrived on TV, Hollywood
Squares is making a comeback. The show, which begins airing tonight
in syndication (7:30 p.m., WPTV-Channel 5), will follow the
familiar format of contestants playing tick-tack-toe as they try to
figure out whether celebrities are giving them the correct answer
to trivia questions, or whether they are lying through their teeth.
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate America's facination with game shows (there's even
an entire cable TV channel dedicated to game shows!) join us for
our own game and take a peek at their kooky past.
</P>
<P>
   TO PLAY OUR GAME
</P>
<P>
   RULES:
</P>
<P>
   1. At least two enthusiastic players are required, along with
one additional person to act as the all-knowing game show host
(polyester suit and hairpiece not included).
</P>
<P>
   2. Before the host reads a question, each player chooses a game
piece (either the head of Monty or Wink) and takes turns flipping a
coin to advance around the board. Flip heads, move one space. Flip
tails, move two spaces. Give an incorrect answer, move one space
back.
</P>
<P>
   3. The first person to the end wins a glorious vacation for two
to ACAPULCO, MEXICO!!!! (Okay, not really. But you're welcome to
eat some salsa and nacho chips while you play . . . )
</P>
<P>
   1. This hit game show's title was supposed to be What's the
Question? 2. This snowy-haired game show host attended college on a
basketball scholarship and was a radio announcer at WWPG in West
Palm Beach. 3. Which rugged Oscar winner was once caught napping in
his chair during a taping of Hollywood Squares?
</P>
<P>
   4. Vanna White was a contestant on what game show in 1980, one
year before she became Wheel of Fortune's letter turner? 5. What
1967 game show was shot at the Colonnades Beach Hotel in Palm Beach
Shores?
</P>
<P>
   6. What is the longest running daytime game show in television
history?
</P>
<P>
   7. Mathematically speaking, what is the most a contestant could
win on one episode of Jeopardy!? 8. Who hosted the most TV game
shows?
</P>
<P>
   9. What amorous show featured Karen Carpenter, Michael Jackson,
Steve Martin, Willie Nelson, Groucho Marx and Tom Selleck as
contestants?
</P>
<P>
   10. Lucille Ball used to visit the set of this dice-tossing game
show.
</P>
<P>
   11. Who was Name That Tune's vocalist before she starred on Hee
Haw Honies and her own morning talk show?
</P>
<P>
   12. What kissy-faced Brit starred as a futuristic game show host
in the 1987 film The Running Man?
</P>
<P>
   13. What game show's set was modeled after Burt Reynolds' living
room?
</P>
<P>
   14. How much would a year's supply of Rice-a-Roni cost?
</P>
<P>
   15. This big-mouthed comedian was a contestant on the $1.98
Beauty Show. She didn't win.
</P>
<P>
   1. Jeopardy!
</P>
<P>
   2. Bob Barker
</P>
<P>
   3. Actor Jack Palance
</P>
<P>
   4. The Price is Right
</P>
<P>
   5. Treasure Isle. The game had three couples who competed by
answering questions, solving puzzles and completing stunts in the
hopes of reaching a specially constructed island, where they hunted
for buried treasure.
</P>
<P>
   6. The Price is Right 7. $283,200. The highest one-day total in
the show's history is $34,000. 8. Bill Cullen, 22 shows 9. The
Dating Game 10. High Rollers, with host Alex Trebek 11. Kathie Lee
Johnson, who later became Kathie Lee Gifford and co-star of Live
With Regis and Kathie Lee 12. Richard Dawson, former host of Family
Feud
</P>
<P>
   13. Win, Lose or Draw. Reynolds was executive director of the
show, along with host Burt Convy.
</P>
<P>
   14. The staple prize of many a game show, the ``San Francisco
Treat'' became a household name from its association with Hollywood
Squares, Jeopardy! and Concentration. Assuming you ate a box a day
for a year, a year's supply would cost $352.44.
</P>
<P>
   15. Sandra Bernhard
</P>
<P>
   `WE WERE THE SHOW FOR THE CELEBS TO DO'
</P>
<P>
   A new version of Hollywood Squares is about to hit the air this
week. Peter Marshall, the show's host during its original 15-year
run, says he's a little apprehensive about his baby. He wasn't too
crazy about the show's second run from 1986 to 1989 with John
Davidson as host.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's going to be OK,'' Marshall said. ``I didn't like
the second one too much. Instead of making it a game show with some
humor, they made it a comedy show with some questions.''
</P>
<P>
   He does, however, like Squares' new host, Tom Bergeron. (The new
show begins airing at 7:30 p.m. today on WPTV-Channel 5 in West
Palm Beach and on WFOR-Channel 4 in Miami.)
</P>
<P>
   And if anyone knows about hosting a game show, it's Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   He's back on the air hosting the movie-trivia game show The Reel
to Reel Picture Show on the newly launched PAX TV network, but from
1966 to 1981, Marshall was at the helm of Squares, one of the most
successful daytime shows in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the show for the celebs to do during that time. Us and
the Tonight show,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At its core, the show answered the question: What would happen
if you combined a 40-foot-tall tic-tac-toe game with the atmosphere
of a cocktail party? Contestants would try to decide if a celebrity
was answering a trivia question correctly or trying to bluff.
</P>
<P>
   A correct guess would grant them a square on the tic-tac-toe
board.
</P>
<P>
   The guests _ from the snide Paul Lynde in the center square to
regulars Wally Cox, George Gobel, Charley Weaver and Rose Marie _
were usually witty with their comebacks and their answers to
Marshall's trivia questions. And often the contestants couldn't
tell if the answers they heard were gospel truth or a
straight-faced bluff.
</P>
<P>
   The show wound up turning B-grade Hollywood castaways and
character actors into household names before it eventually
attracted the big stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``My philosophy was that we should build the stars,'' Marshall
said. ``Some of the biggest stars were the dullest guests. Groucho
Marx didn't understand the show's function. He thought he had to do
a monologue. He didn't get that it should be the question, the joke
or the answer, and get out in less than 45 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   There were some classic moments. Like the time actor Jack
Palance fell asleep during the game.
</P>
<P>
   And when an earthquake hit during the middle of a taping.
Everyone fled from the studio except Paul Lynde, who stayed seated
in his square on the set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a cameraman to my right who stood up on a riser,''
Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the quake hit, he jumped off the riser, ran off the set,
out of the studio and we never saw him again.''
</P>
<P>
   `PRICE' WAS RIGHT FOR STAMBAUGH, ONE OF FIRST TV GAME SHOW
MODELS
</P>
<P>
   The irony isn't lost on Carolyn Stambaugh.
</P>
<P>
   Living in a small apartment on New York City's East Side in
1956, she'd hop on a crosstown bus to get to the Hudson Theater on
West 48th. Once there, she'd spend the entire day as a model on The
Price is Right, wearing luxurious mink coats and diamond jewelry,
lounging on expensive furniture and showing off swanky cars and
boats.
</P>
<P>
   Then at the end of the day she'd get back on a bus or in a cab
and go back to her little apartment. The job earned her $12,000 a
year _ not bad for the time, but nothing like today's huge
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a high-profile job tacked on to the top of a resume
filled with modeling and beauty pageant achievements that ranged
from the cover of Ladies Home Journal to being crowned Orange Bowl
queen.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Charlotte, N.C., she moved to the Palm Beaches when she
was 12 and has lived here on and off ever since. She started her
career after studying at the Palm Beach School of Modeling, showing
Worth Avenue fashions at the Everglades Club. Now, she lives in
Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   From there, her agent got her the TV job in New York that would
elevate her career. (She was Carolyn Stroupe back then, but later
married Palm Beach dentist Dr. Reginald Stambaugh.) For that first
year of The Price is Right, she was a television pioneer of sorts,
along with fellow model Beverly Bentley. They were the Vanna Whites
of their time, posing gracefully and elegantly running their hands
over the merchandise. Every game show hostess since has been using
that same technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``The director gave us a great piece of advice,'' she said. ``He
told us to move as if we were moving through oil. That way, the
camera could follow us and it would look nice and smooth. And, you
know, he was right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Price is Right went on to become the longest-running daytime
game show in television history, first with the likable Bill Cullen
as host and then with dapper Bob Barker.
</P>
<P>
   The big difference between the early days of the show and
Barker's version, says Stambaugh, is that her show was live every
day on NBC. You couldn't just stop the tape machine when something
went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stage hands would, for example, roll out a stove on a
dolly and they'd walk away,'' she remembered. ``You'd go to show it
and sometimes the merchandise would fall down cockeyed and you'd
still have to go on showing it as if nothing happened. The audience
loved that.''
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the Price is Right models today who think nothing of
posing in tiny bathing suits, Stambaugh says she refused to pose in
lingerie or anything skimpy. ``I felt it was important to keep my
dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   Stambaugh left the show before the end of 1957 to do other
modeling work, including some for a beer company. After modeling,
she got her master's degree in mental health counseling.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of four children, Stambaugh, 65, said she's been
blessed with success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any good things that have come to me have done so because God
has been very good to me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   HOW WINSTON MARTINDALE BECAME `WINK'
</P>
<P>
   Of all the arcane facts about game shows crammed into David
Schwartz's brain, perhaps the most valuable is the answer to this
long-pondered question: How does a guy get a name like Wink
Martindale?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the Winkster was hosting a show in 1964 for NBC
called What's This Song? Then known around Los Angeles as Winston
Martindale, or Win for short, he tweaked it a little bit more. As a
kid, he'd been known as Wink, so he picked it up for a professional
moniker as well.
</P>
<P>
   It's this kind of minutiae that has made Schwartz a human
Smithsonian of game show trivia. His book The Encyclopedia of TV
Game Shows, co-written with Steve Ryan and Fred Wostbrock, is a
must read for anyone obsessed with the details of The Dating Game
or the nuttiness of The Newlywed Game. The book, filled with gobs
of information on more than 500 shows, is set to be updated in a
third edition early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz, who has parlayed his knowledge into a job as a
librarian and historian for The Game Show Network, says the lure is
powerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always love to play games, whether it's Hollywood
Squares or Jeopardy!. People keep coming back because they are so
very simple to play, and they can become instantly involved with
them. I mean, Wheel of Fortune is nothing more than an elaborate
game of hangman.''
</P>
<P>
   So with all this flotsam floating through his head, there have
to be some favorites, right?
</P>
<P>
   Favorite host: Nobody in particular, but Bill Cullen of To Tell
The Truth and The Price is Right fame is at the top. He hosted more
than 20 shows, more than any other star. ``He could do any kind of
game show and make it work. He was the great, common, everyday
host.''
</P>
<P>
   Favorite show: Concentration. ``I had all the home games and I
watched it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Favorite game show moment: ``I remember a time on Classic
Concentration when Alex Trebek (the host) let his hair down when
they were doing a `Summer of Love' week, saluting Woodstock and all
that. They had Alex in his long hair and love beads and giving away
classic cars on the show. It was definitely a different side of
Alex than what we see on Jeopardy!.''
</P>
<P>
   `PICTURE' SO BAD, GLEASON APOLOGIZED
</P>
<P>
   For every wildly successful show like Jeopardy! and Wheel of
Fortune, there are dozens of stinkers like You're in the Picture.
</P>
<P>
   That show involved four celebrities sitting behind a picture in
a frame 7 feet high and 10 feet wide. They would then put their
heads through porthole cutouts and try to guess what actions their
characters were performing in the picture.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Jackie Gleason as host, the 1961 show tanked
miserably, lasting only one day.
</P>
<P>
   One day.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Gleason sat on a chair on an empty stage,
apologized for the first broadcast and spent the program just
talking to the audience. It was one of the biggest bombs in TV
history.
</P>
<P>
   If a Museum of Bad Television ever opens, Picture could join
these less than stellar efforts:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gaters _ ESPN's outdoor show had participants performing gags
such as catching oversized pretzels on a plunger and using a
slingshot with plastic balls to hit paper plates in the air.
Winners received T-shirts and caps.
</P>
<P>
   _ Made in America _ Hans Conreid, the voice of Snidely Whiplash
in the Dudley Do-Right cartoons, hosted this 1964 bomb. A celebrity
panel tried to guess how the guests, who were all millionaires,
made their fortunes. If the guest stumped the panel, the $600 prize
was donated to charity. The show lasted a month.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bedroom Buddies _ Three couples, either married, engaged or
just living together, competed in this adult-oriented game. On the
program, couples had to prove how well they knew their mate. One
round of ``romantic choices'' was played, in which each couple was
given a question like, ``What was your most exciting encounter?''
One mate had to guess what his or her partner said from between two
choices. The show lasted four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
