<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Families saving for college will findthe '529 plan' has both
pros and cons
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not many people have noticed a new kind of investment account
that gives families a way to save big chunks of money for college
and to defer paying taxes on the earnings.
</P>
<P>
   It looks like a sweetheart of a deal, but is it? It turns out
that this is a decision each family will have to make for itself.
</P>
<P>
   The new accounts are called savings trusts or ``529 plans,''
after the section of the federal tax law that set them up.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how they work: A parent, grandparent or even a friend can
set up an account for a child. There are no income limitations on
who can participate. You can put up to $50,000 a year in some of
the plans, although anything over $10,000 a year will force you to
consider the possibility of paying gift taxes. The maximum an
account can accumulate is slightly over $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   You have to pay current income taxes on the amount you
contribute. But earnings are sheltered until you withdraw them for
college expenses. Then they are taxed at the child's rate, not the
contributor's. You can use the money for expenses _ including room
and board _ at any accredited post-secondary institution in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   States like the plans because the program is likely to be
popular and because at least some of these savings will end up
benefiting public colleges in the state that sponsors a given plan.
</P>
<P>
   But many financial advisers advise families to think carefully
before pouring their savings into a 529. Here are some potential
problem areas:
</P>
<P>
   -- You can't control your own investments. These plans are
managed by state governments, and the government picks both the
managers and the investment products your money will go into. It
could be certificates of deposit, bonds, stocks or some mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Investing in the most conservative investments could be a major
mistake, said Alan McKnight, a certified financial planner in
Atlanta. ``Obviously you need an investment that is going to beat
the inflation in college costs,'' he said. ``If you are in CDs or
something else with low returns, you are not necessarily going to
make any headway with your savings.''
</P>
<P>
   -- You might be able to do better on your own. Index or
tax-managed mutual funds, for example, might give you a competitive
return without too great a tax penalty.
</P>
<P>
   -- If your child doesn't go to college, or if you take the money
out for any reason other than college expenses, you will have to
pay both income tax and a penalty. ``It really sort of handcuffs
people,'' McKnight said.
</P>
<P>
   -- This is a new product line, so the plans have little or no
track record to examine.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons why 529 plans have not gotten much
attention until now. One is that they are new _ made possible in
the 1997 Taxpayer Relief Act and made more attractive by subsequent
rule-making.
</P>
<P>
   Another is that Georgia doesn't have one. But more than 20 other
states do, and at least four of them will open accounts for
out-of-state residents. They are Montana, New Hampshire, New York
and Utah.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to look into 529 plans, the best place to start is
on the Internet. Start at www
</P>
<P>
   .collegesavings.org/online.htm, where you will find a nearly
up-to-date listing of state-sponsored savings plans, and links to
them. The link ``information clearinghouse'' gives more resources.
</P>
<P>
   Look over several of the plans, and call or write for more
information. Note that the details in each of these plans vary. The
minimum contribution may be different, for example. You may want to
check out which state agencies are involved in setting up the plan,
and you certainly will want to know something about the money
manager.
</P>
<P>
   A crucial difference will be the kinds of investments allowed in
each state's plans. As with any other major investment, you need to
be sure you're getting what you want.
</P>
<P>
   On the conservative end, the Montana plan puts your money into
something called CollegeSure certificates of deposit, which are
issued by a bank in Helena, Mont.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire accounts will be managed by Fidelity Investments,
the giant mutual fund company. The money goes into one of seven
investment portfolios. Each will hold a mix of stocks, bonds and
money market investments, and the mix will become more conservative
as the child nears college age.
</P>
<P>
   New York picked TIAA-CREF as its manager, and the investment
rationale is similar to Fidelity's.
</P>
<P>
   Utah's selections include a Vanguard bond fund and the Vanguard
Index 500 fund.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell's e-mail: ezell(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
