<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: The time of year when subs get eaten alive
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The woolly worms have begun wiggling their
way across our country roads, signaling winter's imminence with its
pall of short, gray days and serious lack of things to do once the
ironing is finished and the soaps have lost their suds. Vistas of
bleak and aimless lives loom ahead. Soon it'll be cabin fever time.
</P>
<P>
   But there's hope on the horizon. How about a change of pace this
winter? Why not consider being a sub? No, not the kind with salami,
cheese and special sauce; I'm talking about the kind that surfaces
in the principal's office about 7:30 on Monday morning looking
dazed but determined.
</P>
<P>
   School districts everywhere are hurting for substitute teachers.
The pay's not bad and there are no papers to grade. All you have to
do is show up, decipher the absent teacher's lesson plan, and
locate the nearest restroom. Piece of cake.
</P>
<P>
   But it takes some preparation. Here's what you do:
</P>
<P>
   First, drive around your district and check out the schools to
kind of get an idea what you might be getting into. If the grass is
over the tops of the kids' combat boots and the bulletin board out
front is advertising flak jackets instead of sock hops, skip it.
Same with barred windows. Graffiti on the doors, particularly if
it's misspelled, is not a good sign either. And if more than a
third of the cars in the parking lot lack wheels, keep moving.
</P>
<P>
   However, don't let rows of BMWs with an occasional Range Rover
thrown in fool you. They are not an indication of the caliber of
staff you'll be working with. Those belong to the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have reconnoitered and lined up a few possibles, call
the school and find out what they pay. If their first offer makes
you laugh out loud, go ahead and cross them off your list, because
schools aren't big on haggling. Remember, though, a school that
let's teachers drink coffee in the classroom is worth a couple of
bucks less than what you might have been expecting.
</P>
<P>
   Next you have to decide whether you want to limit your duty to
the elementary or the high schools. There's a big difference.
</P>
<P>
   Elementary scenario: Timmy screams, ``Teacher! Teacher! Johnny
just threw my Mighty Mouse lunchbox out the window.'' Teacher asks
Johnny why he did that. Johnny says, ``Because.'' Teacher tells
Johnny he's going to have to go to the principal's office. Johnny
bursts into tears and wets his pants.
</P>
<P>
   High school scenario: Frangipani points to a tattooed kid
nicknamed ``Bad Bubba'' and yells, ``Hey teach! Bubba just threw
Elwood out the window.'' Teacher asks Bad Bubba why he did that.
Bubba tells teacher to mind her own business because he knows where
she lives.
</P>
<P>
   Before I hired on as a full-time middle school English teacher,
I did some subbing. It was OK_ particularly in my home district. A
good bunch of kids with only the expected one or two who would do
their best to act like the lead ape in a sequel to ``Godzilla Goes
to School'' and try the patience of the saintliest of subs.
</P>
<P>
   But subbing is not something the uninitiated would want to
blunder into without a few tips from the pros. Here goes:
</P>
<P>
   1. Let the kids pass notes as long as it doesn't interfere with
the lesson. Should you feel obliged to intercept one, for heaven's
sakes don't read it. It'll curl your hair and even the four-letter
words will be misspelled.
</P>
<P>
   2. No matter how persuasive the argument, do not allow the kids
to convince you it's OK to leave for lunch 15 minutes early _ even
on pizza day.
</P>
<P>
   3. Only one at a time in the restroom because the next thing you
know, you'll be reading ``Moby Dick'' to an empty classroom.
</P>
<P>
   4. Don't believe the stories of what they did to their last sub.
</P>
<P>
   5. And for pity sakes don't mess with a seating chart. No one is
going to answer to the right name anyway. Take a headcount and if a
few are missing don't make a big deal of it. Enjoy. The old adage
``the more the merrier'' does not apply in classrooms _ at least
not for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   6. Don't aim for the impossible. If Freddy insists he always
lies on the floor when he writes, let him. Efforts to whip him into
shape would be pointless. Just be sure he's not where you have to
step over him at any time. Particularly if you happen to be wearing
a dress.
</P>
<P>
   There's more, but you'll figure it out on your own. Meanwhile,
ditch those wintertime blahs.
</P>
<P>
   Get out there and be a sub!
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett, a writer and teacher in Gibsonburg, Ohio,
writes for Cox News Service. Her e-mail address is
eschuett(at)nwonline.net.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
