<SLUG> BC-TIMELEAP15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Planetary rotation confounds clocks
 &HT;    By Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ University of Texas astronomers want you to know
exactly why time will linger for a second _ but only for a second _
on the last second of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   It galls these scientists whenever they hear or read that the
standstill is necessary to compensate for tidal forces that are
slowing down the Earth's rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety-nine articles out of 100 will say that, and it's wrong,
wrong, wrong, wrong,'' said Peter Shelus, a research astronomer at
UT's McDonald Observatory in West Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Shelus particularly worries about this because he specializes in
time. He manages the observatory's Laser Ranging Operations, and he
will be attentive on the last second of Dec. 31 when time stands
still long enough for the world's official timekeepers to insert an
extra second into the year. They'll do it to get their precise
atomic clocks into sync with the planet's somewhat unreliable
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   One extra second is all that the ominous-sounding Directorate of
Time _ actually a division of the U.S. Naval Observatory in
Washington _ needs to get the Coordinated Universal Time clocks up
to snuff.
</P>
<P>
   This leap second, as it is called, is similar to the day added
during leap years to get the calendar in line with the planet's
journey around the sun. This year's leap second will be the 22nd
extra-second adjustment decreed by the International Bureau of
Weights and Measures in Paris, France, under international
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The last leap second was added on June 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Leap seconds are necessary because the atomic timepieces are far
more precise than the roughly 24-hour day dictated by the planet's
rotation. Traditionally, time was set by the rotation of the planet
because people became accustomed to the passage of the sun across
the sky. Early clock makers used pendulums to set time's rate, but
they are affected by humidity and faulty mechanisms. But the
planet's rotation, which is affected by the tides and such things
as the globe's friction with its atmosphere and the sloshing of the
liquid metal at its core, is consistent to only a mere few
thousandths of a second per day.
</P>
<P>
   To be more precise, scientists arbitrarily chose to mark time by
the reliable vibrations of cesium atoms. They defined the solar
second as 9.162770 billion atomic vibrations. Atomic clocks
calculate the passage of time by measuring the vibration of cesium
atoms, which are accurate to within a few billionths of a second
per day.
</P>
<P>
   Most people wouldn't miss a second, or even two, but Shelus said
the world's space agencies, for example, would quickly notice the
loss. When a satellite is moving through its orbit at several miles
a second, a second can go a long way. Complicating things is the
Earth's movement around the sun at 14 miles a second.
</P>
<P>
   But the leap second is something of a dinosaur and may
eventually be discarded. Increasingly, jetliners, ships and even
sport fishermen navigate the planet with electronic instruments
taking signals from a constellation of satellites called the Global
Positioning System. Each satellite carries its own cesium atomic
clock.
</P>
<P>
   So enjoy this year's extra second. There may not be a second
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
