<HEADER>
A3657 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMERWATCH15-COX     09-14 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERWATCH15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Detroit bank has married home equity and credit card debt
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will you, credit card, take this home equity line as your legal
debt to hold and pay?
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Americans owe billions of dollars to credit cards
and home equity lines. Now, a Detroit-based bank has married the
two types of debts.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan National Bank last month announced its Equi-Money VISA
Gold, a credit card secured by the cardholder's equity in his or
her home.
</P>
<P>
   That means the card's credit limit is determined by the home
equity amount, which could be $10,000, $25,000 or more _ money
that's quickly available to the cardholder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The customer reaction has been overwhelming,'' said Robert
Darmanin, a bank spokesman. But Gerri Detweiler, author of ``The
Ultimate Credit Handbook,'' warns that consumers should be ``very,
very careful'' in using such a card.
</P>
<P>
   The credit/equity card, which is currently available only to
Michigan residents, comes with certain advantages, but one very big
disadvantage: You could lose your home.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike regular bank cards or credit cards secured by savings
accounts, fail to pay your bills on this card and the bank could
foreclose on your home.
</P>
<P>
   With bank cards, if you fail to pay, the lender can cut off your
credit, employ debt collectors to seek payment, and report you to
credit bureaus, but they cannot foreclose on your home. With
secured cards, they can keep the savings you posted as collateral,
but not your home.
</P>
<P>
   Darmanin, however, says home foreclosure is not likely to be a
danger for people who are issued the credit/equity cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not offering these cards to just anyone,'' he said.
``They will be offered to people who have bought homes, have built
up equity, and have demonstrated they can handle credit
responsibily.''
</P>
<P>
   The cards' two major advantages are that the interest will
generally be tax-deductible, and the interest rates, depending on
the amount of credit, will range from prime to prime plus 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Detweiler, formerly director of Bankcard Holders of America, a
consumer group, said the tax deductibility of the interest would be
limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, you would have to itemize deductions on your tax return
to claim the interest, and then you would need total deductions
above the standard deduction to claim any of the interest,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely would not use the card to pay for shopping or
meals or anything except perhaps a well-thought-out purchase, such
as improvement to boost the value of your home.''
</P>
<P>
   Detweiler said she had heard that some other banks were thinking
about issuing credit(backslash)equity cards, but she did not know
which banks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
