<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3660 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERSCENE15-COX     09-14 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shopping for cars made easy on InternetBy John Ghirardini
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most unpleasant tasks known to man is shopping for a
car. For most of us, this endeavor ranks only slightly above root
canals.
</P>
<P>
   Some studies have shown more than 60 percent of consumers
flat-out hate the car shopping and buying process. First there's
all the schlepping around to various dealers spread all over the
metro area. Then there's the compromise on a model that doesn't
have quite all the features or options you'd like. Last, there's
the negotiations with the smooth salesperson who often could make a
shark feel uncomfortable _ at least during the times your offer
isn't being ``taken to my manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you've signed on the dotted line, there's always the
nagging feeling you've been taken anyway.
</P>
<P>
   That's been eased some by the car dealers who maintain a
no-haggle set price, but what if you don't want a Saturn?
</P>
<P>
   Next time, let your mouse do the shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Several sites on the World Wide Web are devoted to helping
consumers with everything from negotiating a price to actually
completing the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   As the average price for new vehicles has hit $20,000 over the
last few years, the used-car market has mushroomed into a $365
billion behemoth. More than 40 million used cars changed hands last
year; new-car sales were about 15 million, according to a study
done this year by Leiberman Research Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   AutoConnect (http://www.autoconnect.com) is one of the new breed
of ``cyber middlemen'' _ online retail portals that connect buyers
and sellers. In the case of AutoConnect, the service is free to
both.
</P>
<P>
   The site features a comprehensive and detailed database of
nearly 500,000 used vehicles, searchable by make, model, type
(truck, car or van, for instance), price, Blue Book value and
geographic proximity. When a shopper finds the '39 Nash or '92
Mercedes of his or her dreams, AutoConnect gives them several ways
to contact the dealer or private seller directly. The site also
features photos of many of the vehicles, side-by-side comparisons,
articles on insurance and maintenance, and calculators for figuring
out loan payments or comparing loan vs. lease.
</P>
<P>
   AutoConnect's primary focus is on used vehicles, but comparison
information and dealer lists are available for new-car shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   If you've got a yen for a brand-new set of wheels, here are a
couple of other sites to check out:
</P>
<P>
   AutoVantage (http://www.cuc.com/ctg/cgi-bin/AutoSavings
</P>
<P>
   /home?ref &QC; ). The site maintains information from a network of
2,300 dealers, and can steer you to the best deal for buying or
leasing in your neck of the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Auto BuySmart (http://www.autobuysmart.com/howitwrk
</P>
<P>
   .htm) is a new-car buying service that basically does all the
work and haggling for a $295 fee _ cheap compared with the price of
a car and reduction of wear and tear on your psyche.
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to fight the good fight yourself, go into the
battle forearmed. Take a look at the Beat the Car Salesman site
(http://www.beat-the.com
</P>
<P>
   /beat-the-car-salesman/), which bills itself as ``the car
salesman's worst nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   The site is actually the online companion to a book by the same
name, but contains valuable information in its own right.
</P>
<P>
   Ladies and gentlemen, start your engines.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
