u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     09-14 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
  
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, Sept. 14, 1998
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COSMETIC-SURGERY (San Francisco) _ Cosmetic surgery has become
the medical growth industry of the 1990s, as thousands of baby
boomers undergo face lifts, breast implants, liposuction and other
procedures in hopes of fending off the wrinkles and sag of middle
age. Many get what they want but an San Francisco Examiner
investigation shows a growing number of patients suffer
disappointment, disfigurement and even death from what are billed
as simple, low-risk procedures. By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ and LANCE
WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   SURGERY-GAYNOR (San Francisco) _ The state Medical Board accuses
Dr. Alan Gaynor of incompetence, gross negligence and dishonesty.
But on talk TV, Gaynor has become an emblem for the idea that, with
little pain or risk, modern medicine can reverse the aging process.
By LANCE WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PROSTITUTE-MURDERS (Poughkeepsie, N.Y.) _ Eight women, believed
to be prostitutes, have been killed over a two-year period in this
Hudson Valley town. Talk about the crime has been ceaseless. By
ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   ZIP-CODES (Dryden, Texas) _ As the crow flies, this tiny West
Texas town, population 8, is just 20 miles east of Sanderson, the
Terrell County seat. But for a crow _ or anyone else _ mailing a
letter from Sanderson to here, Dryden is nearly 1,200 miles away.
The reason for this postal oddity lies in ZIP code boundaries. By
JOHN MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINE-BELLS (San Francisco) _ At an Air Force base in
Cheyenne, Wyo., sit two bronze church bells at the center of a
trans-Pacific dispute. Taken by American soldiers as a war trophy
in 1901 from a Philippine island, the bells symbolize the
Philippine Insurrection. The Philippines asked for them back but
U.S. officials decline. By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   UNABOMBER (San Francisco) _ When he was in graduate school,
Theodore John Kaczynski became frustrated with his inability to
form relationships with women, and considered getting a sex-change
operation. When his attempt to seek counseling ended in
humiliation, he thought of killing. This is part of a 47-page
psychiatric study that was a key factor in his January plea to
being the Unabomber. By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   SEX-DEFINITION (San Francisco) _ What constitutes sex? As the
nation reacts to the Starr report's excruciating detail of the
president's 16-month affair, it appears that Clinton's very
particular definition of sex is more widely held than Americans
might think. By CRAIG MARINE.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-CLINTON (San Francisco) _ Not only did the Web serve as
an ultrafast method of conveying information about President
Clinton's sex scandal, it also offered users a chance to vent. By
ERIN McCORMICK.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-SEX (San Francisco) _ Psychologists and experts in child
development say the latest rush of media attention to President
Clinton's sex scandal may expose children to more than they can
digest, but can also be used as a valuable learning experience. By
KATHERINE SELIGMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SILICON-VALLEY (San Francisco) _ Silicon Valley's economy could
crash like a burned-out computer system, falling into recession by
next year from the effects of the 14-month-old Asian fiscal crisis,
according to a study by the Santa Monica-based Milken Institute.
The study, ``The Asian Crisis Tsunami,'' says that San Jose will be
hit hardest of any metropolitan area in California. By DAVID
ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Future opportunities to go
hiking, biking, fishing, canoeing or horseback riding at the
Peninsula's Crystal Springs watershed are being quietly destroyed
in a series of maneuvers by the San Francisco Planning Department.
By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Never mind high crimes,
misdemeanors and cigars that sometimes aren't just cigars. These
are my eight grounds for the impeachment of Bill Clinton, one of
which is saying ``I have sinned'' with tears in his eyes at a
prayer breakfast with such ``pastoral counselors'' as the Rev.
Jesse Jackson. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I was 23 before I saw my first
live opera _ Verdi's ``La Traviata'' at the New York City Opera _
and I walked out at the first intermission. Twenty-five years
later, you would need a large cruise missile to keep me from my
seat. How does a person make such a 180-degree turn? By STEPHANIE
SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-AMERICANIZATION (Jerusalem) _ The signs of Israel's rapid
Americanization stand in sharp contrast to the images shown on
television news _ Jewish settlers rampaging through the Arab
markets of Hebron and black-coated ultra-Orthodox politicians
passing judgment in religious-secular disputes. By ELAINE RUTH
FLETCHER.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3746 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      09-14 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET AWASH WITH SPECULATION ABOUT CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIN McCORMICK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The release of the Whitewater independent
counsel's report on President Clinton has the Internet buzzing with
sordid discussions, lurid speculation and debate about the merits
of punishing a public figure for a private sexual affair.
</P>
<P>
   One Internet betting pool has offered up to $5,000 to the person
who can correctly guess the date on which President Clinton might
leave office.
</P>
<P>
   An on-line chat group encouraged users to vote on which of 27
outcomes would seal the president's future, offering choices that
included impeachment and Clinton suffering a heart attack, and thus
gaining public sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   And members of an on-line support group for people suffering
from depression frantically exchanged messages about where they
could find Kenneth Starr's report on Clinton's sexual adventures.
</P>
<P>
   As the scathing report hit the World Wide Web Friday, thousands
of Internet users responded by pouring their outrage, their
anguish, their support and, more prevalently, their cynicism onto
the information superhighway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having just read it, Clinton should resign immediately,'' one
user said in a message posted to a discussion group on current
news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looks to me like Starr's a Rush Limbaugh type, who thinks the
prez is a naturally evil person who can be brought down with
unsubstantial allegations,'' another Internet user wrote to a stock
investors newsgroup.
</P>
<P>
   And then there were the smart alecks, who seemed to outnumber
those with serious comments 10-1.
</P>
<P>
   One member of a discussion group suggested Clinton try to
portray his sexual promiscuity as an illness that might fall under
the Americans with Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can NOT impeach Clinton. It's very simple,'' the pundit
wrote in a newsgroup on politics. ``Clinton clearly has a sexual
addiction. That is a psychological disorder, and therefore a
disability. ... And you can not fire someone for having a
disability.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Web serve as an ultrafast method of conveying
information about the Clinton scandal, said Internet journalist
David Weir, it also offered users a chance to vent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is a place where people feel they can talk,''
said Weir, managing editor of the on-line magazine Salon. ``It's a
way for people to process their emotional response to big stories.
We saw that when Princess Diana died, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet also abounds with chances to bet on Clinton's
future, although White House advisers have said Clinton would never
resign because of the Monica Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Judgement Day Betting Pool'' invites bets of $10 on which
day will be the president's last day in office and get a chance to
win up to $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Directions for the Internet pool, sponsored by a group called
the New Irish Sweepstakes, explained that, if Clinton ``gets off
scot-free'' and remains in office, his entire term, anyone who
picked the date Jan. 20, 2001, would win $27.
</P>
<P>
   If he left office earlier, winners would get more.
</P>
<P>
   Another Web pool _ Clinton's Last Day Contest _ costs nothing
and offers a plaque for the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Mr. Clinton stays till the normal end, all the names that
predicted (this) will be put in a dark blue beret and one name will
be chosen (to) get the plaque,'' the site's instructions say.
</P>
<P>
   One political newsgroup asked readers to pick one of 27
scenarios for how Clinton's term will end. These ranged from
impeachment, to Clinton suffering no repercussions whatsoever, to
bizarre possibilities like diversionary attacks on foreign nations.
</P>
<P>
   Choice No. 26 posed a scenario in which news anchor Katie Couric
interviews Chelsea Clinton on the ``Today Show,'' makes Chelsea cry
on camera and then the ``public sympathy saves Clinton.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
