<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 12:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3767 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEX-DEFINITION-HNS &LR;      09-14 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEX-DEFINITION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDIES INDICATE CLINTON'S VIEWS ON SEX FAR FROM UNIQUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CRAIG MARINE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As the nation reacts to the Whitewater
independent counsel's excruciating details of the president's
16-month sexual affair, it appears that Bill Clinton's definition
of sex is more widely held than Americans might think.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before a federal grand jury, the president
``maintained that there can be no sexual relationship without
sexual intercourse, regardless of what other sexual activities may
transpire. (Clinton) stated that `most ordinary Americans' would
embrace this distinction.''
</P>
<P>
   While that may strike some people as absurd, two surveys at
least partially bear him out. Dr. Stephanie Sanders, associate
director of the renowned Kinsey Institute in Indiana, cited some
relevant information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We conducted a survey in 1991 that specifically asked that
question, whether people would say they had `had sex' with someone
if the most intimate behavior was oral-genital contact. Sixty
percent of the people answered `no.'''
</P>
<P>
   A survey of college students conducted by Playboy magazine and
published in its October 1996 issue showed that 54 percent of the
women responding did not view oral sex as ``real'' sex, although 52
percent of men did.
</P>
<P>
   Determining where the sexual relationship between Clinton and
Monica Lewinsky falls in relation to the sexual practices of most
Americans is tricky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Social Organization of Sexuality: Sexual Practices in the
United States,'' a landmark study released in 1994 by researchers
from the University of Chicago and State University of New York at
Stony Brook, found that white educated people who identify
themselves as liberals are the most likely to masturbate and have
oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   As to what was ``appealing,'' heterosexuals overwhelmingly
preferred intercourse. Watching a partner undress was a distant
second, followed by oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who are married, 75 percent of men said they had
been faithful to their spouses.
</P>
<P>
   Of those in short-term relationships, 29 percent of men and 23
percent of women report fellatio usually or always.
</P>
<P>
   Vibrators were used by 2 percent of both men and women, while
``other sex toys'' were used by 1 percent of men and 2 percent of
women.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, it is the ``other sex toy'' that is likely to ruffle
the most feathers. Yet Dr. Bernie Zilbergeld, an Oakland-based sex
therapist and author of ``The New Male Sexuality,'' has a different
take on Clinton's use of his cigar as a sex prop, as reported in
the independent counsel's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was an incredibly loving and sensitive thing to
do,'' Zilbergeld said. ``He was showing her he cared about her and
valued her essence. I didn't know he had it in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Zilbergeld said he knew his opinion may be in the minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (San Francisco) Bay area has always been at the forefront
of sexual liberalism,'' he said. ``This is a long way from Kansas
or Arkansas. A lot of people, if they don't engage in a particular
practice themselves, react to it with outrage. At the same time,
they are excited by the details. They may have been on the computer
in their barn saying, `Oh my God, isn't that horrible? Scroll
faster!'''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Louanne Cole Weston, a therapist, concurs _ to a degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still a lot of people out there whose idea of sex
involves a little kissing, maybe some fondling, the man gets on top
and it's over when he's done,'' she said. ``These people are going
to be genuinely shocked by the oral sex aspects of the
relationship, let alone the cigar.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it is also true that people engage in all sorts of sexual
behaviors everywhere in this country. I know sex therapists in Des
Moines who have people lined up around the block, who are doing
everything imaginable,'' Weston said. ``The difference is in the
community standards, the freedom people have to speak openly about
their behavior without being ostracized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
