</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURFING-THE-WEB-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURFING THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files. Also, the word
TILDE in parentheses has been used in a Web address instead of the
symbol, which can't be interpreted by many newspapers' computer
systems.)  
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The Internet is finally a viable tool for enthusiasts who like
to plan their own travel. Many Web-based services are now capable
of accepting credit cards for purchases, and the proliferation of
faster modems has meant that glacial waits for downloads are now
largely a thing of the past.
 &HT;    Here are some of the better sites around for those who want to
get somewhere fast.
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    There's been a proliferation of Web-based travel agencies, many
of which are now routinely used by business travelers. But leisure
travelers who are savvy enough can use them to their own advantage
and sidestep airline reservationists and conventional travel
agents.
 &HT;    Virtually all of them have some sort of fare-finder that enables
the traveler to enter flights and come up with fare and carrier
options in short order. In addition to airfare, the following sites
allow the traveler to book a car rental and a hotel as well.
 &HT;    Start with BizTravel.com (www.biztravel.com), which has become a
favorite of business travelers. It allows user to create very
detailed traveling profiles of themselves and manage their
frequent-flier programs. It has a good, fast fare-finder and has a
wide-ranging data base of hotels and car-rental agencies as well.
 &HT;    Microsoft Expedia (www.expedia.com) is one of the best-known
on-line travel agencies around, with a good fare finder and a
pretty sophisticated search engine that allows users to look for
the best-priced flights and scroll through scheduled flights
easily.
 &HT;    Flifo (www.flifo.com) makes it easy to set up a detailed
itinerary. The fare-finder is speedy and the free ticket delivery
is a bonus.
 &HT;    Preview Travel (www.previewtravel.com), the preferred travel
service for America On-Line (AOL) members, is also one of the best
and the fastest for leisure travelers. Users have access to a
responsive fare-finder that ranks flights not only by price but
also provides aircraft model and up-to-the-minute availability of
seats in all classes.
 &HT;    The Trip.com (www.thetrip.com) is an all-purpose travel site
that allows users to not only book flights but to track them as
well. Waiting for someone to arrive at the local airport? This site
gives real-time locations of flights enroute, something no airline
toll-free number can do.
 &HT;    Travelocity (www.travelocity.com) was one of the first on-line
travel agencies and is linked to SABRE, one of the systems used by
professional travel agents. But it's easier to use than its parent
and is quite good at finding low fares.
 &HT;    There's also 1travel.com (1travel.com), which has a somewhat
less sophisticated fare-finder than the others and still requires a
phone call to complete a transaction. What makes this site
noteworthy is that it provides consolidator flights, a boon for
anyone looking for discounted airfares to Europe and Asia.
 &HT;    For hotels alone, two discount hotel brokers who can help
travelers ease the sting of big-city hotel prices are Hotel
Reservations Network (www.180096hotel.com) and Quikbook
(www.quikbook.com).
 &HT;    Some of the airline's own Web sites are useful for rooting out
deals. The leading site must be American Airlines' (www.aa.com),
which began offering Net SAAver fares a couple of years ago. These
are last-minute, round-trip deals that are posted every week to
subscribers via e-mail. International deals are listed on Mondays,
domestic deals on Wednesdays. The e-mail subscription is free.
 &HT;    This site is a clearinghouse for unsold tickets, most of which
originate at the airline's hub cities of Chicago, Dallas and Miami.
These deals are good for long weekend travel from either Thursday
to Monday or Friday to Monday or Tuesday.
 &HT;    American also offers discounted first-class fares every week and
usually has additional short-lived deals from American Airlines
Vacations.
 &HT;    Other airline sites worth a look are U.S. Airways
(www.airways.com) and Continental (www.flycontinental.com) for
weekly e-mail specials.
 &HT;    Both TWA (www.twa.com) and Cathay Pacific
(www.cathaypacific(TILDE)air.com) send them out periodically. The
latter, of course, still has what is probably the greatest airfare
deal of the year, an $899 Asia Pass that includes round-trip
airfare from New York to Hong Kong and unlimited travel to the 18
cities that Cathay serves within a 30-day period, including Bali
(Indonesia), Bangkok (Thailand) and Seoul (Korea).
 &HT;    For anyone who's contemplating mountain biking in the Lake
Geneva region of Switzerland or hiking in the Rockies, there's
GORP, the Great Outdoors Recreation Pages (www.gorp.com), with
traveler's tales about biking, hiking and fishing and listings of
dozens of adventure-travel companies.
 &HT;    Thinking about going around the world? High Adventure Travel
(www.highadv.com) offers dozens of sample itineraries and allows
users to plan their own world jaunt on-line.
 &HT;    Council Travel (www.ciee.org) and Air Brokers International
(www.airbrokers.com) are also good sources for would-be
round-the-world travelers _ or for anyone who'd like to dream about
such a trip.
 ---- 
 &HT;     (Everett Potter is a New York-based free-lance writer.)  
 &HT;     c.1998 Everett Potter  
