<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3782 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-WALLACE-1000&AMP;ADD     09-14 2479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WALLACE-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE WALLACE, 79; LED OPPOSITION TO SEGREGATION
</HEADLINE>
  By TOM BENNETT 
 c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Wallace, the four-term governor of Alabama who dominated
its politics for a quarter-century and waged a historic third-party
presidential campaign in 1968, died of respiratory and cardiac
arrest Sunday night at Jackson Hospital in Montgomery. He was 79
and lived in Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace was a Southern populist and opportunist. When millions
still despised or admired him for his 1963 segregationist stand at
the University of Alabama, he had long since discarded that
political stance, and moved on.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, where he was a folk hero, a generation grew up
having known only brief periods when the governor's mansion was not
occupied by a Wallace _ George or his first wife Lurleen. He was
governor in 1963-67, 1971-79 and 1983-87. She served a partial term
as governor in 1967-68 when by law he could not succeed himself.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his political career, in the 1940s, Wallace was labeled
liberal when he backed Gov. James E. ``Big Jim'' Folsom, who sought
more opportunities for blacks a decade before the civil rights
movement. But Folsom's popularity dimmed after the U.S. Supreme
Court outlawed school segregation, and Wallace dropped him cold.
Wallace went on to win the governorship in 1962 and declare in his
1963 inaugural address, ``Segregation now! Segregation tomorrow!
Segregation forever!''
</P>
<P>
   He reversed again to espouse moderate views in 1974, then came
full circle in 1982, winning the governorship for the fourth and
last time with 90 percent of the black vote and declaring
segregation to be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Age and lingering pain from a 1972 assassination attempt kept
Wallace from seeking a fifth term as governor in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   George Corley Wallace Jr. was born Aug. 25, 1919, in the Barbour
County town of Clio in the black belt of southeast Alabama. He was
the oldest son of George C. ``Sag'' Wallace Sr., a farmer, and
Mozelle Smith Wallace. Barbour County has the nickname ``Home of
Governors,'' having produced seven.
</P>
<P>
   The young Wallace was a state Senate page at 16. At the
University of Alabama, he was freshman class president and two-time
state bantamweight boxing champion. To make ends meet, he worked at
various times as a busboy, taxi driver, dogcatcher and magazine
salesman, and received a law degree in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   He enlisted in the Army Air Force, but washed out of pilot
school after contracting spinal meningitis. On furlough, he married
Lurleen Burns, a clerk at the Kresge's store in Tuscaloosa. While
in flight engineer school, they lived in a converted chicken house
in Alamagordo, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Stationed in the Mariana Islands, Wallace plotted a political
career. From that far western Pacific outpost, he wrote letters to
Alabama Gov. Chauncey Sparks, and sent Christmas cards to surprised
Barbour County voters.
</P>
<P>
   Aboard a B-29 superfortress, Wallace flew 19 bombing missions
over Japan. He was discharged from the Air Corps in 1945 with a 10
percent disability related to a nervous condition resulting from
combat fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Stateside, he hitchhiked to Montgomery to see Sparks, and got a
job as an assistant attorney general. Wallace ran for and won a
seat in the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   As an alternate delegate to the 1948 Democratic Convention,
Wallace, then in his first liberal period, did not join the
Dixiecrat walkout protesting a civil rights plank in the platform.
</P>
<P>
   He was reelected to the statehouse in 1950, but later quit,
complaining that he was not allowed to play a strong enough role in
guiding the legislative program. In 1952, he was elected a judge of
the Third Judicial District serving Barbour, Dale and Bullock
counties.
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, Wallace, still a judge, was his mentor Jim Folsom's
south Alabama campaign manager. But with that year's decision by
the U.S. Supreme Court in Brown v. Board of Education, all other
matters shrunk in importance, and race became the only political
issue in the South. Folsom as governor invited Harlem attorney Adam
Clayton Powell to the governor's mansion for a drink. Wallace and
others deserted Folsom.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace entered the 1958 gubernatorial race along with Folsom,
state Attorney General John Patterson and 11 others. Borrowing from
a boyhood hero, Gov. Bibb Graves, who had styled himself ``The
Little Colonel,'' Wallace called himself ``The Little Judge'' and
still later improved it to ``The Fighting Little Judge.''
</P>
<P>
   All 13 candidates were segregationists, but Patterson gained an
edge as the most irreconcilable of all. He led Wallace in the
primary, 196,859 to 162,435. A run-off followed, and Wallace
labeled Patterson the Ku Klux Klan candidate. Wallace's gambit
failed: Patterson crushed him, 315,353 to 250,451, and went on win
general election.
</P>
<P>
   In a dubious hallmark of Alabama history, Wallace said in his
election postmortem: ``Patterson out-niggered me, and, boys, I'm
not going to be out-niggered again.''
</P>
<P>
   In January 1959, events played into Wallace's hands. The U.S.
Civil Rights Commission demanded to see voting records of his
judicial district, and he refused to release them.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Frank M. Johnson Jr., Wallace's former law
school classmate, ordered Wallace to release the voting records.
Wallace refused and was cited for contempt. When he said he would
turn over the records only to a grand jury, Johnson cited him for
criminal contempt. Wallace made a secret night visit to Johnson's
Montgomery home, entering through the back door, and attempted to
negotiate, but Johnson refused.
</P>
<P>
   In court, Wallace's lawyers pled him guilty. Johnson upstaged
them, ruling that Wallace had complied and turned over voter
records, and acquitted him. Their one-upmanship continued as
Wallace now insisted he was guilty, and stumped the state calling
Johnson a liar.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace entered the 1962 governor's race pledging to stand in
the schoolhouse door before permitting integration. He out-polled
state Sen. Ryan De Graffenreid in the primary, 207,062 to 160,704,
and in a run-off won, 340,730 to 269,122. He swamped independent
Frank P. Walls in the general election by a 50-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-OBIT-WALLACE-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; (UNDATED: 50-1 margin.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At his swearing-in, Wallace stood on a star on the Capitol steps
marking the spot where Jefferson Davis had been sworn in as
Confederate president. One of the most infamous declarations in
Southern demagoguery followed. Wallace said: ``In the name of the
greatest people that have ever trod this earth, I draw the line in
the dust and toss the gauntlet before the feet of tyranny and I
say, Segregation now! Segregation tomorrow! Segregation forever!''
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ordered the University of Alabama to admit
blacks Jimmy Hood and Vivian Malone. Earlier, there had been
violence at the University of Mississippi when James Meredith
enrolled. U.S. Attorney General Robert F. Kennedy came to
Montgomery hoping to stave off further violence. Wallace met
Kennedy, but not before ordering a wreath placed over the Jefferson
Davis star to keep Kennedy from walking on it.
</P>
<P>
   Hood and Malone arrived on the Tuscaloosa campus June 11, 1963.
Wallace and federal officials played out a drama fulfilling
Wallace's stand pledge, and saving face for all while avoiding
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace selected a door and stood there behind a lectern. U.S.
Assistant Attorney General Nicholas Katzenbach and the students
approached. Wallace threw up a hand. Katzenbach handed him a
cease-and-desist order, and started to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need your speech,'' Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenbach withdrew. The students were taken to dorm rooms. The
Alabama National Guard was federalized. A second confrontation
occurred later, this time at the registration center. Wallace again
stood in a door. A National Guard officer asked him to step aside;
he did. By the time the blacks were registered, Wallace was being
driven back to Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   (Hood dropped out after six weeks. Malone graduated, and later
headed the Atlanta-based Voter Education Project.)
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1963, Wallace delayed the openings of schools in
four cities which had been ordered desegregated. Wallace used the
National Guard to prevent registration of blacks. President Kennedy
responded by federalizing the guardsmen and ordering them to their
barracks. The schools were desegregated.
</P>
<P>
   As this was occurring, on Sept. 15, 1963, the 16th Street
Baptist Church in Birmingham was bombed. Four black children died.
Wallace denounced the bombing, but Kennedy implied some culpability
on the part of Wallace when he said that it was regrettable that
public disparagement of law and order had encouraged violence which
had fallen on the innocent.
</P>
<P>
   His stand had made Wallace a national figure. He entered the
1964 presidential race as a Democrat, challenging President Lyndon
Johnson and hoping to win enough electoral votes to throw the
election into the House of Representatives. There, he hoped, he
would gain concessions on civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace won 33.8 percent in the Wisconsin primary, 29.8 percent
in Indiana, and 42.7 percent in Maryland. But supporters failed to
place Wallace electors on the Georgia, Mississippi and South
Carolina ballots. The death blow to his candidacy was the
Republicans' nomination of conservative Sen. Barry Goldwater.
Wallace withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   His role in the historic 1965 Selma March was largely as a
symbol of all that the marchers despised in their campaign for the
right to vote. Blacks launched a voter registration drive in Selma
in January of that year, and Atlanta's Martin Luther King Jr.
announced plans to march to Montgomery. Wallace said the march will
not be tolerated, and troopers turned back 700 blacks March 7. But
a federal judge enjoined state officials from interfering, and the
historic march occurred March 21-25.
</P>
<P>
   The state Constitution forbade a governor to succeed himself.
Wallace ran Lurleen and she won the primary in June 1966 with
480,841 votes, more than nine opponents combined. She crushed
Republican Jim Martin in the general election, 537,505 to 262,943.
</P>
<P>
   Her election eliminated the last vestige of opposition to the
Wallaces. At the Capitol, he ran the state from an office across
the hall from hers. But their reign was halted when Lurleen died of
cancer in May 1968 after 18 months in office, and Lt. Gov. Albert
Brewer became governor.
</P>
<P>
   George Wallace sought the presidency again in 1968, this time as
a third-party candidate. He collected 3 million signatures and got
on the ballot in all 50 states under varying party names American
Independent, Georgia Wallace, American, Conservative, George C.
Wallace and Courage Parties. Former Georgia Gov. Marvin Griffin was
a stand-in vice-presidential candidate to meet requirements in four
states, then was replaced by former Air Force Gen. Curtis E. LeMay.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic candidate Humphrey and labor attacked Wallace, and he
also was hurt when it was revealed that, before he was added to the
ticket, LeMay had advocated bombing the North Vietnamese ``back
into the stone age.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace got 9,90l,151 popular votes, finished third behind
Richard Nixon and Humphrey and carried Georgia, Alabama, Arkansas,
Louisiana and Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   He met the incumbent, Brewer, in a bitter 1970 primary campaign
for governor. Wallace trailed, 428,146 to 416,443, but won a
run-off, 559,832 to 525,951. He buried John Cashin of the black
National Democratic Party of Alabama in the general election,
637,046 to 125,491.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1971, Wallace married Cornelia Ellis Snively, 19
years his junior, a beautiful divorcee who was Folsom's niece and
who once had performed in the water-ski show at Florida's Cypress
Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace became a Democrat again to run for president in 1972. He
reeled off primary victories in Florida, Alabama, Tennessee and
North Carolina, and finished second in Wisconsin, Pennsylvania and
Indiana. Maryland was next.
</P>
<P>
   On May 15, 1972, Wallace was walking among supporters at a
Laurel, Md., shopping center when he was shot several times and
critically wounded. Secret Service agents seized Arthur Bremer, a
young drifter who was later tried, convicted and sentenced to
prison.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the hospitalized Wallace won the Maryland and
Michigan primaries. But he was in a hospital bed for seven weeks,
and eventually underwent four major operations, several minor
surgical procedures and suffered various complications. Confined to
a wheelchair, he went to Miami and addressed the Democratic
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later he won the governorship of Alabama in a
landslide victory. (The state constitution now permitted him to
succeed himself.) Wallace, courting the black vote, defeated Gene
McLain in the Democratic primary, 536,235 to 249,695, and
overwhelmed Republican Elvin McCary in the general election,
497,574 to 88,381.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, Wallace decided on one more presidential race and
faced, among others, Georgia's Jimmy Carter. The major test was the
Florida primary. Wallace's longtime slogan had been ``Send a
message to Washington,'' but Carter urged voters to ``Send a
president, not a message.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter won in Florida and later defeated Wallace in North
Carolina. Wallace withdrew, and stunned his old backers by
endorsing Carter. Former Georgia Gov. Lester Maddox ran for
president under the American Independent Party banner, and won
170,531 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's seven-year marriage to Cornelia ended in divorce in
January 1978.
</P>
<P>
   He could not run for a third term and left office in January
1979. The law forbade a pension but he was awarded an
$18,000-per-year honorarium.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1981, Wallace married Linda Lee Taylor, 29 years his
junior, a divorcee and country music singer who had been Lisa in a
singing duo, Mona and Lisa, that performed during his political
campaigns. (They divorced in 1987.)
</P>
<P>
   Wallace put on a new face to run for governor once again in
1982. ``Segregation is wrong,'' he said. Montgomery black leader
E.D. Nixon said Wallace ``has done more for black folks than any
other governor in the last 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace topped George McMillian in the 1982 primary, 425,469 to
296,271, and won a run-off, 512,203 to 488,444. In the general
election, Wallace received 90 percent of the black vote as he
defeated Montgomery mayor Emory Folmar, 650,538 to 440,815.
</P>
<P>
   He was inaugurated a fourth time and the official program for
the event called him a lifelong champion of the less fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   Tuskegee University awarded him an honorary degree in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
