<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONG-KONG-SCHOOLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGLISH LOSES HOLD ON HONG KONG SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ The last major bastion of English dominance in this
former colony crumbled last week, when the new school year began.
For the first time in this overwhelmingly Chinese city, the vast
majority of students will now be educated in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching students in their native language is hardly novel. But
in a city whose colonial history shaped it as an international
entrepot, the switch has sparked emotional hand-wringing and
politicized debate.
</P>
<P>
   The Education Department says most of Hong Kong's 57,000
teachers are not qualified to teach in English, and that switching
to Chinese is a pragmatic response to declining academic standards.
Proponents say it is logical that children will develop better
academically and socially if they learn in their mother tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the local government is making the change to prove
its patriotism and kowtow to Beijing, which regained sovereignty of
Hong Kong in July 1997. The demise of English in schools, they say,
will undermine students' job prospects and Hong Kong's role as an
international center of commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But advocates of the switch note that while teaching in Chinese
is being mandated only now, the movement began a decade ago under
British rule.
</P>
<P>
   In the period since the handover, observers have watched
anxiously for changes to the legal system and civil liberties and
signs of meddling by Beijing, but few have emerged. Instead,
language _ perhaps more than any other issue _ has polarized a
community that prides itself on how little has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the educational arguments, how people view
``mother-tongue teaching'' depends largely on whether they think
Hong Kong's key to success lies within its bicultural past or its
future as a Chinese city.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, English was important because Hong Kong was a
colony, but now we are a part of China and we must know Chinese,''
said Charles Yip, 40, whose daughter is enrolled at Pui Ching
Middle School, one of only 26 schools here that has always taught
in Chinese. ``China is getting more important in the world, and if
we act as a bridge between China and the West, we must know China
better.''
</P>
<P>
   English will still be taught, but as a foreign language. Critics
say that once English is used less, it will fade, and Hong Kong
will lose its edge as a bridge to the West and a regional base for
multinationals.
</P>
<P>
   When the government announced last spring that only 114 of Hong
Kong's 400 secondary schools _ those with the best-scoring students
_ could continue to teach in English, angry callers flooded radio
talk shows, denouncing the creation of a ``two-tiered'' educational
system. Students at schools that ``lost out'' wept openly on
campuses.
</P>
<P>
   A recent survey by Caritas Community Center found only 4 percent
of parents polled preferred their children to study in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Schools that were forced to switch have seen their enrollment
drop, and some parents are opting for private schools rather than
public and state-funded religious schools that now must teach in
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   After 156 years of colonial rule, it's easy to see why parents
think children must know English to succeed. Although 98 percent of
the population speaks the local Cantonese dialect and almost no one
uses English at home, English has been the language of law,
government, and business. Local universities teach in English, and
the best jobs require English.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, however, the territory's laws have been
translated into Chinese, and judges have started hearing some cases
in Cantonese. Chinese is now the official language, and civil
servants and legislators are using Chinese more, even though the
law says English can still be used.
</P>
<P>
   Yet schools have clung to teaching in English, even though for
years, only about 7 percent of high school students have scored a C
or better in English on the standardized exams. In the exams graded
last month, only 44 percent of students who took the easier English
test passed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Yeung Yok-wah, principal of Concordia Lutheran School at
North Point, which is being forced to switch this year, laments
that ``two different status of people are being created by the
government.'' In the past, his students, who are among the
lower-scoring pupils in the district, have managed to get jobs as
branch managers for international banks or English-speaking tour
guides. ``If we're only using Chinese, we cannot create these kinds
of people for the community. And students from elite schools won't
accept those jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann Yeung, 39, says her son Toby cried for a week when he found
out that his campus, St. Francis Xavier's School in Tsuen Wan,
would be forced to use Chinese. She worries he'll have a harder
time getting into college, or adjusting to coursework in English if
he does attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't even want to tell others where he's going to
school, because he's afraid of being laughed at as a second-class
citizen,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior education officer, P.K. Chiu, acknowledges that many
parents share Yeung's view, but says that on the contrary, the new
system will raise the lot of low-achieving pupils. ``Imagine a
student who can't write a complete sentence. English is a foreign
language for us. Children speak Cantonese at home, with friends, in
stores. ... How can they listen and communicate in English
effectively?
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are taught in Chinese, teaching and learning are more
enjoyable. And they'll have more spare time to put into efforts in
learning English as a second language,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yip Bun-bun, 15, a fourth-year student at Hong Kong Sam Yuk
Secondary School, hates learning in English because she barely
understands what teachers say and can't read her textbooks. ``It's
a waste of time to teach in English, because teachers always have
to repeat themselves in Chinese. ... I just memorize terms without
knowing their pronunciation or meaning, and I forget them very
easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Her principal, Kavin Yeung, agrees. Over the past five years,
his school has been making the transition to mother-tongue
education by choice. Last year, all his first-year secondary school
pupils learned in Chinese, and their marks in Chinese, English, and
math rose 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he acknowledges the transition has been difficult.
Educators who have taught in English for years say one summer is
too little time to learn a specialized vocabulary, plan lessons,
and read new texts in a new language. The Education Department says
it has published glossaries and held retraining courses, and faults
schools for not preparing for the transition.
</P>
<P>
   At Pui Ching, where Chinese has been used since the school was
founded in 1889, principal Cheng Sing Yip says the idea that
learning Chinese holds back high-achieving students is a myth. His
school is one of the best on Hong Kong; graduates have attended
Harvard, Yale, and Oxford universities, and 99 percent of his
students passed their five best subjects in this year's Certificate
of Education exam. But he admits that only 71.5 percent passed the
English exam, and only 13 students scored a C or above.
</P>
<P>
   Yeung Sik-wing, 16, one of Pui Ching's top students, scored A's
in seven subjects but received a D in English. ``We don't have
enough opportunity to talk English, listen English, and writing,''
she said, stumbling over her grammar before switching to Chinese.
``If I had a chance to choose again, I might choose an
English-medium school. ... (But) after the return to China, the
Hong Kong government is making us resemble China more.''
</P>
<P>
   Her principal agrees that there are political overtones to the
new policy, but he sees the change as positive. ``The British tried
to create the belief that only English is important, and that
influenced students, parents, and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget,'' he added, ``in the future, Chinese will be the
language of business here and throughout Asia. This is only 1998.
Give it time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
