<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-CAPTIVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LAWLESS LAND, LONE CRUSADER FINDS THE MISSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Yury Chudakov got kidnapped in the usual way. The
police sergeant was manning a roadblock in southern Russia's
strife-torn and crime-ridden Caucasus badlands when a car stopped
and the driver asked him for help.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Chudakov was overwhelmed and hustled into the car
by several gunmen. They drove him over the border into separatist
Chechnya, a breakaway republic still reeling from Russia's failed
and bloody campaign to end an armed rebellion. It is a
poverty-stricken and lawless place 1,000 miles south of Moscow
where taking hostages for ransom has become a profitable business.
A ransom note followed, demanding a sum none of Chudakov's friends
or loved ones could pay.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people have disappeared in recent months in southern
Russia, and neither the Kremlin, which has all but lost control of
Chechnya and neighboring regions, nor squabbling local authorities,
who never really had control, have been able to do anything about
it. Chudakov was just one more prisoner of the Caucasus whom no one
expected to see again.
</P>
<P>
   No one, that is, except Vyacheslav Izmailov, a former army major
who has made freeing hostages and prisoners of war his business.
</P>
<P>
   One day recently, Izmailov left his Moscow office and headed
down to the hardscrabble villages just across Chechnya's eastern
border, a place where most Russians would never go. Five days
later, Izmailov emerged with Chudakov. As usual with the dozens of
people Izmailov has freed _ he lost count after 60 last year _ no
ransom was paid.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that this Russian Rambo is no muscle-bound
fighting machine, nor does he free hostages by means of brute force
and derring-do. Izmailov, 43, balding and somewhat pudgy, holds
negotiations with kidnappers and makes deals with Chechen families
whose relatives are being held prisoner in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are Russian authorities particularly grateful for what
Izmailov does. In June, Russia's Defense Ministry forced him to
resign from the army. In July, one of President Boris Yeltsin's
senior aides, deputy chief of staff Yevgeny Savostyanov, said
Izmailov should be ``flogged'' for what he has done.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that over 1,200 Russian servicemen are still
officially listed as missing in action in Chechnya, and hundreds
more Russian troops, police and civilians, including Yeltsin's
personal representative to Chechnya, have been kidnapped in the
region since the war ended in 1996, the Kremlin's hostility toward
someone who is trying to find these people may seem strange.
</P>
<P>
   But Izmailov long ago earned the Kremlin's wrath with his frank
criticism of the way Moscow prosecuted the war. His column in the
local weekly Novaya Gazeta, appearing under the headline ``The
Forgotten Brigade,'' contained often scathing commentary of
atrocities committed by the Russian military against civilians.
When Russian troops withdrew from Chechnya in early 1997, Izmailov
began writing about the missing servicemen written off and
forgotten by the army like so many lost tanks.
</P>
<P>
   In a society that has shown remarkably little public concern for
the ongoing tragedy on its southern borders, Izmailov stands out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia's constitution says individuals have priority over the
state,'' Izmailov said in a recent interview. ``That provision is
not observed. I see my job as demonstrating that this country is
made up of people with rights.''
</P>
<P>
   A 27-year veteran who served in Afghanistan, Izmailov was
working at a draft board in 1994 when the fighting in Chechnya
broke out. When news of the first casualties of soldiers he had
helped induct started coming in, Izmailov put in for a transfer to
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided I couldn't serve that way anymore, sending boys to
their death,'' Izmailov said. In March, 1995, at the height of the
fighting, Izmailov got his wish and was transferred to Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the Russian Army was trying to isolate the Chechen
rebel fighters by signing ``peace accords'' with civilians in
Chechen villages. Despite the accords, the villages would come
under fire by Russian troops. The Russian Army promised to punish
those responsible, but investigating officers rarely treated the
inquiries seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Izmailov did. The Chechens were amazed when Izmailov sent in
reports detailing atrocities by Russian units and naming the guilty
Russian servicemen.
</P>
<P>
   As a gesture of gratitude, the Chechens helped Izmailov secure
the release of Russian prisoners. After that, Izmailov gained the
reputation among the Chechens as a Russian officer who could be
trusted. During the final battle for Grozny, the Chechen capital,
in August 1996, Izmailov drove around in a tank with no helmet, so
that Chechen commanders could recognize him, picking up the wounded
and dead of surrounded Russian units.
</P>
<P>
   That trust has served Izmailov after the war. Chechens with
family members being held prisoner in Russia supply him information
concerning the whereabouts of Russian hostages in the
Connecticut-sized region. In return, Izmailov works with
prosecutors to try to secure more lenient treatment for the Chechen
prisoners, in some cases securing prisoners' release.
</P>
<P>
   Some have criticized Izmailov, suggesting that his deal-making
encourages Chechens with relatives in Russia accused of criminal
offenses to take hostages as a bargaining chip to secure their
release.
</P>
<P>
   Izmailov admits that in some cases, Chechen families with
relatives in Russian prisons have purchased hostages from
professional kidnappers. He recently helped free a 13-year-old
orphan from one such family, in return for a promise to help
release a Chechen accused of extortion in the Siberian city of
Omsk.
</P>
<P>
   The strain of three straight years in the business of freeing
prisoners is starting to take its toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are thousands of hostages, and no one is doing
anything,'' Ismailov said. ``I'm trying to show our authorities
that we and the Chechens have to work together. But they didn't
understand it before, and they haven't figured it out yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
