<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAHUNT'S MISSION ON JUDICIARY COMMITTEE: FAIRNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Delahunt is one of my favorite freshman
congressmen mostly because, at 57, he's like a freshman in college
who has already done a tour in the Marines and spent a couple of
years working construction.
</P>
<P>
   In short, he's fresh but he's been around, as a legislator but
more important as the veteran district attorney from Norfolk
County, Mass, adjacent to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The other reason is that he doesn't say a whole lot _ not
because he doesn't have anything to say, but because he seems to be
a public official more inclined to pick his spots than chase every
microphone he sees. The result is that when he does talk the
natural reaction is to listen.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, it's worth noting that as a freshman member of the
House Judiciary Committee, Delahunt has become something of a pal
to another _ but far less in shape _ member with white hair _ the
committee's chairman, Henry Hyde, Republican of Illinois. That
makes the few things Delahunt has to say in public about
you-know-what especially worth paying attention to. Everybody
knows, but hardly anybody says it often enough, that something as
solemn as impeachment is never going to move forward much more than
an inch without some block of President Clinton's own partisans
going along; Delahunt will be one of the Democrats to watch.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, he spoke up more than he has of late as the House
prepared to vote to dump nearly 500 pages of independent counsel
Kenneth Starr's narrative material on its membership and, more
important, the public, and to begin reviewing some 2,000 more pages
of raw material for similar distribution over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth _ much more than a little _ Delahunt did not
think a necessarily nonpartisan process had gotten off to a smooth
start.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he did not like what amounted to an abdication of
congressional responsibility to Starr in the decision to instantly
release, on his say-so, his report, but to agree to treat at least
some of the raw evidence that accompanied it as confidential, also
on his say-so alone.
</P>
<P>
   For another, he joined with many of his Democratic colleagues in
protesting the absence of notice and time to respond to the
president and his lawyers, citing the provision made as courtesies
to such investigative targets of the past as Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   And that, he said, tends to exacerbate the third, and
inevitable, impact of Starr's referral _ which as a former
prosecutor Delahunt is greatly experienced in dealing with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will clearly be prejudicial to the president's defense,''
he said. ``If the independent counsel has done his job, the case he
has constructed will be a persuasive one ... And, at least at the
federal level, they have no obligation to apprise the jurors of
exculpatory evidence. The case will seem airtight, yet until the
evidence has withstood cross-examination and the allegations have
been proven, they remain nothing more than allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   Delahunt was not arguing that Starr's report should be
repressed; no one was. The only question, he said, ``is when and
how it should be done,'' which is where the question of
``fundamental fairness'' becomes relevant.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so bad, in Delahunt's view.
</P>
<P>
   And from here on, there is a danger that all this will become
worse.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment there is a great frenzy here _ primarily over the
sexual details in the Starr document. But after a few weeks, and
assuming Clinton can politically survive the initial avalanche of
disclosure, there will be questions about what the Judiciary
Committee is going to do.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is that after all this posturing about how serious
everything is, how solemnly obligations are being undertaken,
Hyde's committee intends to do _ nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Delahunt told me that there simply isn't time to go through an
impeachment inquiry between now and when a new Congress takes
office after the new year and the current Congress leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   However, he did say that Hyde intends to try to decide in the
time left this year the threshhold question of whether there should
be an inquiry, based on study of and debate over the Starr document
and the president's detailed response to it.
</P>
<P>
   One would hope that at the very least the committee would do
that. Otherwise, the judicious reticence of Republicans like Hyde
and Democrats like Delahunt risks appearing pointless.
</P>
<P>
   After all, how can this be a terribly serious, pressing matter _
whether the president is fit to continue in office _ and then have
nothing at all done about for four months?
</P>
<P>
   Answers yet to come.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
