<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3812 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS-SEX-HNS &LR;      09-14 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-SEX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS FACE UNEASY TASK OF EXPLAINING CLINTON AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHERINE SELIGMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Thanks to President Clinton's affair and a
special prosecutor's detailed report about it, parents may face
unsettling, precocious questions about sexual situations from young
children.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologists and experts in child development say the rush of
media attention may expose children to more than they can digest,
but can also be used as a valuable learning experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good opportunity for parents to talk about their
values,'' said Anne Bernstein, a family psychologist in Berkeley,
Calif., and author of ``Flight of the Stork: What Children Think
(And When) About Sex and Family Building.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things you do when you talk about sex is you give
information, and you discuss values,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   William Damon, head of Stanford University's Center on
Adolescence, said the issues that emerged from the Clinton scandal
gave parents a chance to talk not just about sexuality but also
about honesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funny thing about these kinds of events is that they're
wonderful learning opportunities if adults handle them the right
way,'' he said. ``This is how moral learning happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that it's important to pay attention to a child's
level of knowledge before attempting explanations. None interviewed
said censoring the news would be advisable or useful, even if it
were possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think just pretending it's not going on is a way to
deal with it,'' said Tom Spencer, head of the Child Study Center at
San Francisco State University. ``Some of their friends will talk
about it. I always believe they should get the truth at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer advises parents to be careful listeners and give
age-appropriate answers to questions. Children under age 9 probably
won't be aware of the lurid details contained in the report, but
they may have general questions, psychologists say. Most said to
meet the questions directly, without giving unsolicited information
or details.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you're not going to talk to an 8-year-old about
oral sex, and he won't ask questions about it,'' Damon said. ``If
he does, it's because he's heard the phrase somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, you might talk to a child that young about loyalty in
marriage, honesty and the importance of telling the truth in a
relationship, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Mills, who writes a nationally syndicated column ``Child
Life,'' said she and her husband had decided to start a discussion
with their two children, 7 and 9, by saying at the dinner table,
``It seems like the president is having a lot of trouble now.''
</P>
<P>
   Her 9 year-old son wanted to know ``what does it mean?''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband responded that ``the president has made some
inappropriate choices, and he apparently has lied. You're really
not supposed to lie, and he's in a lot of trouble now.''
</P>
<P>
   For her two children that was enough, though Mills said her
husband had ``the complete discussion'' about sex with their
9-year-old this year probably because of ``the Monica Lewinsky
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of kids will know the details of sex sooner thanks to
President Clinton,'' she said. ``It's unfortunate, but I think it
still needs to come from the parents and not from the kids on the
playground. And it doesn't necessarily have to be as graphic as you
think it does.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's important, Mills said, is to build a foundation with
children, to have them understand they can bring up any issue,
whether it's sexuality or honesty, so that when ``the big oral sex
discussion'' surfaces, it won't be as difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Middle-school children are probably the ones who'll find the
latest details most embarrassing and difficult to talk about,
psychologists say. Their discomfort might show up in the form of
jokes or laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Glen Elliott, head of child and adolescent psychiatry at the
University of California at San Francisco, said parents might steer
the discussion into one about ``how public figures get into this
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A 13-year-old will like to talk about this and will have
strong feelings,'' he said. ``I don't think one needs to go into
great detail about sex. The topic has more to do with what happens
when someone does something they're not supposed to have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Krikorian, a school district psychologist in Palo Alto,
Calif., said it was fortunate that the report on Clinton, presented
to Congress by Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth Starr, had
come out on Friday so children could hear about it at home.
</P>
<P>
   Older teens, Elliott said, may be the ones most likely to refuse
to talk about the developments in the White House affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're more likely to respond cynically,'' he said. ``They're
beginning to disrespect adults anyway, and it's an opportunity to
show that.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the news shaking their view of government, Damon doesn't
think most teens revere the president regardless of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Presidents don't have that kind of cache anymore,'' he said.
``Kids don't think of the president as a hero. They pick someone
from sports or entertainment. ... The presidential link (to the
scandal) isn't adding a lot of sauciness to this. That's why I
think a lot of kids won't look it up on the Internet. If they do,
they won't find anything they don't know about or can't find on 10
zillion other Web sites.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
