<HEADLINE>
LEARNING FROM JOHN GLENN'S `EXPERIMENT OF ONE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 77, Sen. John Glenn still has the military bearing, piercing
gaze, and even the boyish grin that Americans of a certain age
recall from 1962, when he became the nation's first space hero. But
next month he will assume a less exalted role: by his own
description, he'll be the first guinea pig in a pioneering venture
that might be called space gerontology.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 29, Glenn is scheduled to blast off with eight other
humans in the space shuttle Discovery for nine days of experiments.
Some of them, he notes, may shed light on the curious similarities
between aging and the physiologic effects of space travel _ muscle
wasting, bone deterioration, sleep disturbances, balance problems,
immune system decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we determine in the human body what turns these systems on
and off, not only will we benefit future astronauts but we will
have made a great step forward in benefitting the old and frail
here on Earth,'' says the once and future astronaut.
</P>
<P>
   Really? Can Earthbound elders expect to benefit from this
brand-new field? Will we indeed learn, as Glenn and the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration promise, about the mechanisms
of aging and how to counteract them?
</P>
<P>
   Scientists, including those involved in the experiments on Glenn
and his colleagues, have much more modest expectations of the
gerontologic yield of STS-95, as NASA terms this fall's mission.
Tellingly, NASA has ``no specific plans to fly other older
astronauts'' to build on the data Glenn will provide, says David
Liskowsky, chief life sciences program scientist for the mission.
</P>
<P>
   However, scientists and nonscientists are unanimous when it
comes to the symbolic value of sending a 77-year-old human into
space.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some feeling this is being done purely for PR
reasons, but I think that's unfair,'' says Dr. Reubin Andres of the
National Institute on Aging's gerontology research center in
Baltimore. ``Clearly we're not going to be able to calculate a mean
value and a standard deviation from an experiment of one, but that
doesn't mean anecdotal information is useless. The fact that he's
77 is simply a plus and adds an interesting dimension to the whole
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The real value of Glenn's venture, many observe, is to bring
home the point that some septuagenarians (and those even older) are
capable of extraordinary feats. ``This is one more step in
challenging the stereotypes about aging,'' says Frank Bailey,
northeast regional director of the American Association of Retired
People. ``It instills a renewed sense of excitement about the
possibilities for folks his age.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is not whether you're going to get scientific data
on the effects of microgravity on the processes of aging _ you
ain't,'' Andres adds. ``But nature is providing us with Sen.
Glenns. We want to study them, and if we're lucky and we design our
experiments carefully, we may learn something.''
</P>
<P>
   The experiments Glenn and his fellow crew will carry out aboard
STS-95 are not specifically designed to test the effects of aging,
but the scientists hope Glenn's age will at least provide glimmers
of how an elder responds to conditions of space.
</P>
<P>
   ``The participation of one elderly individual has limited
scientific value,'' says Dr. Linda Shackelford, an orthopedic
surgeon at NASA's Johnson Space Center in Houston who is measuring
changes in bone metabolism among the STS-95 astronauts. ``But it
may lead the way for more studies like this one, not only in space
but on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Shackelford is trying to develop, for instance, specific
exercise prescriptions that maintain and even build bone among
bedridden individuals on Earth, a project with obvious relevance to
astronauts on long-duration space station missions of the next
decade as well as to millions of frail elders.
</P>
<P>
   The two major human experiments on the mission _ NASA calls them
``primary payload experiments'' _ concern muscle wasting and
changes in sleep patterns, two problems that plague all astronauts
and most if not all elders on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When humans go into space they lose about 10 percent of body
weight, even on short flights, and it's much more than water
weight,'' reports Arny A. Ferrando of the University of Texas
Medical Branch at Galveston, who is running the muscle wasting
study. Microgravity, or weightlessness, ``is only a partial
explanation,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrando's hypothesis is that the stress of space flight
contributes to muscle wasting, mediated by hormones such as
cortisol and insulin. ``Under conditions of stress, the body
mobilizes all its resources to survive, and the breakdown of muscle
protein as an energy source is one of the primary survival
mechanisms,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   During STS-95, Ferrando will track protein ``turnover,'' as the
process of muscle building and breakdown is called, in Glenn and
fellow crew member Pedro Duque of Spain. They will ingest pills of
a distinctive isotope of the amino acid alanine and inject
themselves with another protein building block called 3-methyl
histidine. Ferrando will track the amino acid levels in the
astronauts' blood and urine and correlate it with their hormone
levels. The astronauts' strength levels and muscle mass will also
be measured before and after the flight.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrando expects that Glenn's results will be different from the
35-year-old Duque's. ``Even though John Glenn is in fantastic
shape, I think the stress will probably affect him more, and it
will take longer for him to recover from it,'' Ferrando predicts.
``But you never know. His physiology may not act like a typical
elder's physiology.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in the sleep experiment, Glenn may not turn out to be
typical. Unlike many older individuals, Glenn says, he has never
had trouble sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Charles A. Czeisler of Boston's Brigham and Women's
Hospital, who is running the sleep study, says its primary purpose
``is to find out how sleep is different in space and on the
ground,'' not to investigate how elders respond in space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know sleep disruption becomes more common as people get
older, and disturbed sleep is very common in space flight. We don't
know if the two will be additive,'' Czeisler says. Specifically,
scientists already know that astronauts' breathing patterns change
in conditions of weightlessness, ``and breathing abnormalities are
one of the most common causes of sleep disorders among the
elderly.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most potentially useful aspect of the sleep studies
is to see if melatonin _ a much-touted but largely unproven
hormonal sleep aid _ improves the astronauts' sleep, a continuation
of an experiment begun in April on the Neurolab shuttle mission.
``If melatonin improves sleep they will sleep longer and better,
and that should hopefully translate into better cognitive
performance,'' says NASA's Liskowsky.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting if Glenn responds differently to
melatonin than the other crew member in that experiment, Dr. Chaiki
Mukai, 46. But ``whether or not we can learn anything about
melatonin from one older person is a question,'' Czeisler cautions.
</P>
<P>
   Other STS-95 experiments will measure changes in heart rate and
blood pressure, immune function, and recovery of normal balance
mechanisms, during and after the flight. Everyone will be
interested to see if Glenn differs on any of these measures from
younger astronauts, even if the results can't be generalized to
less typical 77-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the results, they're sure to be overshadowed by the
mere fact of Glenn's return to space at such an advanced age. As
Andres put it: ``He's a genuine American hero _ and we need them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Richard A. Knox is a member of the Globe staff. His e-mail
address is: knox(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
