<HEADLINE>
IN FASHION RACE, US SCORES ONE OVER EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the fashion industry, no matter how heated the rivalries, one
thing has remained constant: European designers without exception
are the first to unveil their seasonal collections, followed by the
Americans. It's an almost sacred tradition, but a lot of US
designers hate it.
</P>
<P>
   That's why starting Monday, , in a history-making shakeup in the
industry, a group of renegade New York-based designers, led by the
likes of Helmut Lang, Calvin Klein, and Donna Karan, has decided to
defy tradition and unveil their spring collections first _ weeks
ahead of Versace, Armani, and Chanel.
</P>
<P>
   The in-your-face move could generate more global respect for New
York, as industry insiders for years have contended that many
American designers don't create women's clothing trends, they copy
them _ from the Europeans. By showing first in New York this week,
said Debra Greenberg, president of Louis, Boston, ``Now they have
to stand on their own. ... They'll be taken more seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, the change will likely have little effect, other
than providing an earlier signal of what to expect when spring
clothes appear in stores in February.
</P>
<P>
   But the breakaway fashion week is opening a huge rift within the
American design community, mostly because it was organized at the
last minute in July and August. While more than 15 designers will
present their women's spring collections over the next few days,
including Nicole Miller, Mark Eisen, and Vivienne Tam, more than 40
others, like Ralph Lauren, Bill Blass, and Oscar de la Renta, are
waiting _ for logistical reasons _ until the traditional New York
fashion week, this year Nov. 2-6.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these designers say they aren't opposed to showing
before Europe in theory. But in reality, with a month's notice or
so, they couldn't cut short their production schedules by seven
weeks. They're irritated, they say, because designers like Klein
didn't wait until the next season so the industry could present a
unified front.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a catastrophe. It's an absolute mess,'' said Boston
designer Alfred Fiandaca, who plans to present his collection in
his Manhattan store during the last week of October. ``This is not
a time for us to be pulling shenanigans. The fashion market hasn't
been that strong. (Buyers and the press) have other priorities. ...
They don't have the budgets to come into New York and put
themselves up at hotels twice in one season.''
</P>
<P>
   Said New York designer Donald Deal, who plans to show in early
November, ``I'm a real practical guy. Literally, when you change a
calendar, it requires preparation. We were not able to secure our
fabrics and embroideries and mount a show in such short notice. ...
It was just not possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some designers contend the move to show their lines earlier has
nothing to do with reputation _ it's all strictly business. Because
designers are selling in more markets globally, they have more
goods they need to produce for spring, and thus they need more time
to do it, they say. What's more, by the time retailers return from
Europe in November, they say, the stores have already seen the
season's trends and many have committed much of their budgets to
the likes of Prada, Chanel, and Missoni.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we wait (till November), it's very difficult to get the
goods into the store on time (for February),'' said Patti Cohen, a
senior vice president for Donna Karan International. ``We've been
having trouble with deliveries, like a lot of companies,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of critics believe ego has more to do with the early
shows than anything else. ``It's ridiculous,'' said Boston designer
David Josef, whose clothes are sold in Saks Fifth Avenue and Neiman
Marcus. ``We're (hardly) done with summer and here they are
presenting spring clothes. ... I think they're doing it for the
press. I've never heard of a retailer who came back (from Europe)
and said `I spent all my money.'''
</P>
<P>
   Josef plans to unveil portions of his spring collection in
November and later, in January. He expects stores to stock it by
February.
</P>
<P>
   The Council of Fashion Designers of America, which organizes the
semi-annual New York shows, said it has tentatively moved up the
fall shows to mid-February, instead of late March _ thus unifying
the US industry once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great idea to show before the Europeans. It just needs
to be planned so we don't all look like fools scurrying around,''
said Deal, who believes this time he'll be ready to show earlier
than the traditional March time frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be a great way for us to hit our stride and show
that this is what we are, this is what we're doing. ... As a
community, to be able to hit the world first with our ideas, has a
bigger bang than at the end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
