<HEADLINE>
BEWARD `NEGATIVE-OPTION' MAILINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA WEN AND BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Companies offering products in the mail always want you
to accept and pay. And in an effort to maximize their success, they
are increasingly using dubious methods to convince themselves that
you wanted what they sent.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, if you say yes, you want it; and if you say no, you
don't. But if you do nothing _ because you were too busy to respond
or chucked the notice in the trash _ some aggressive marketers read
the inaction as a ``yes.''
</P>
<P>
   It's called ``negative option'' mailings, and it assumes you
want something unless you negate or stop it. And when the company
simply gets silence, they start sending you the unwanted products
and the bills. The first offer is often presented as free, when
there are strings attached.
</P>
<P>
   ``This marketing ploy is gaining in popularity,'' said Leslie
Davies, managing attorney for consumer protection at the state
attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   It's illegal for someone to expect you to buy something simply
because they didn't hear from you. Any purchase contract has to be
two-way, with an offer from the company and your actual acceptance
of it. So next time you get an unsolicited product, consider it a
gift; you don't have to pay or return it.
</P>
<P>
   Negative-option mailings are acceptable, however, if you agree
to this setup as part of an ongoing relationship. For example, you
join a book club in which you agree to buy a certain number of
books unless you stop the orders. Or you agree to automatic annual
renewals of an auto club unless you stop it.
</P>
<P>
   A negative-option system, consumer advocate Edgar Dworsky said,
must be disclosed in ``clear and conspicuous'' language. Clever
marketers, however, are finding ways to make it seem like you
agreed to something long term.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Jack Hurley, a computer executive in the South
End who is finding himself the confused _ and now angry _ recipient
of several CDs he never ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Last February, Reader's Digest got Hurley's name from an outside
mailing list and sent him a ``complimentary'' CD called ``Stardust
Moods'' and a coin set, according to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Hurley's initial mailing came with a notice saying that Hurley
could keep it as a gift, and ``if you don't send anything back to
us, we'll send you the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, having not heard form Hurley, Reader's Digest sent him a
``Candlelight Classics'' CD, with a bill for $21.
</P>
<P>
   Hurley couldn't remember ordering the CD, but, afraid it was
just a memory lapse, he sent them a check. Last July, Reader's
Digest sent him another CD and another bill.
</P>
<P>
   By now, Hurley was getting upset. When we inquired, Reader's
Digest spokeswoman Donna Pierpont acknowledged that Hurley never
agreed to enter into a long-term relationship to receive these
products. The company, based in Pleasantville, N.Y., simply assumed
he would indicate if he didn't want them anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Pierpont said of consumers, ``You need to let us know if you
don't want to continue with these services.''
</P>
<P>
   Davies of the attorney general's office said in cases such as
these, Hurley would have been wise to simply keep all the things
coming his way, and, to stop future mailings, inform Reader's
Digest that he wants off this list.
</P>
<P>
   He would have been under no obligation to pay, because he never
asked to receive the CDs.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of James and Bernice Johnson of Reading, they
apparently didn't read the fine print from American Family
Publishers, which said their purchase of one cookbook amounted to
being part of a ``continuity product.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple started receiving notices that a cookbook was waiting
for them and would be sent, unless they sent back the post card
within a month stating they didn't want it. ``Quickly, I wrote on
each side of the card `I DON'T WANT THIS!''' James Johnson said in
his letter to us.
</P>
<P>
   These tactics prey on those who may easily feel intimidated into
paying a bill, partly out of fear it may affect their credit
rating. Davies said the state takes seriously all cases in which
consumers are duped into giving up money and can prosecute any
``unfair and deceptive'' practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies may be trying to trick someone into thinking
they bought something,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Unwanted loan checks &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After reading our column last month about the illegality of
sending unsolicited credit cards in the mail, Ann Grace of Pelham,
N.H., asked whether unsolicited loan checks might also violate
federal law.
</P>
<P>
   She had just received a $5,000 loan check from Fleet Bank, and
said she was ``beyond furious'' because she sees these checks as
gimmicks that prey on the financial vulnerable. (People get instant
cash by depositing them in any bank, then get a coupon book later
to repay the loan.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's crazy,'' she said. ``It gets people into
financial trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   While he can understand consumer concerns, Anthony Ricko, head
of compliance with the Federal Reserve Bank in Boston, said the
loan checks are considered legal as long as the solicitation states
in ``clear and conspicuous'' language its financial terms, such as
the annual percentage rate and payment rules. He said the rules
prohibiting unsolicited credit cards in the mail do not apply to
loan checks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Deirdre Cummings, consumer program director for the
Massachusetts Public Interest Research Group, said federal
regulations should be revised to ban these loan checks. She said
the regulations were written at a time when this marketing tactic
didn't exist.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The pork price was too fat &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 72-year-old Boxford man won a personal consumer victory in his
battle with the meat scales at the Stop &AMP; Shop in Danvers. He said
he was ``mad as a hornet'' after discovering that the 10 pounds of
pork loins he bought from the Stop &AMP; Shop in Danvers on July 31
actually weighed 33 percent less than the package indicated _ and
that he was overcharged.
</P>
<P>
   The man's complaint that day brought in Norman St. Hilaire,
Danvers' sealer of weights and measures. The inspector found that a
random selection of meat indicated the store's scales were off.
Most packages weighed 33 percent less than the store's price/weight
sticker indicated.
</P>
<P>
   After conducting an investigation, St. Hilaire concluded that
the meat workers were allowing a meat tray to come into contact
with the scale, causing what he called ``an accidental
overweighing.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a new law signed by Acting Governor Paul Cellucci last
month, portions of which go into effect in mid-November, inspectors
such as St. Hilaire would have the power to issue traffic
ticket-like fines to stores that are found with inaccurate scales.
</P>
<P>
   St. Hilaire said he subsequently conducted two surprise checks
of the scales last month and found them to be accurate. Regina
Harrington, Stop &AMP; Shop acting manager in Danvers, said the meat
scales were ``corrected immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Boxford man, who asked to remain anonymos, he
demanded a full refund and wondered how many other consumers were
overcharged.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't know this unless you're a suspicious, cheap man
like me,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
