<HEADLINE>
THE NEW LOOK: FROM LUMPY TO FRUMPY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Here I am in a store dressing room trying on a gray pleated
skirt that falls almost to my ankles. The effect is strange.
</P>
<P>
   I'm reminded of one of those crocheted toilet-paper holders, the
kind with the doll torso in the middle and a huge skirt sticking
out horizontally all around. I brace myself for the rear reflection
in the three-way mirror. I look like I'm trying to bring back the
farthingale.
</P>
<P>
   This season fashion is giving us longer skirts, baggy tops, flat
shoes. I was thrilled when I first heard the news. ``The frumpy
look is in!'' I thought. I always knew (I told myself) that if I
waited long enough, fashion would double back and meet me halfway.
What a fool I am. Why do I bother? Why not just wear sackcloth and
ashes? Actually, this season no one would notice the difference if
I did just that. That's how ugly these new clothes are.
</P>
<P>
   The arbiters of fashion don't call the new look ``frumpy.''
Depending upon which magazine you read, it's ``sumptuous,''
``luxe,'' ``voluminous,'' ``carefree,'' ``comfortable,''
``insouciant,'' ``body-skimming,'' ``dressed down,'' ``relaxed,''
even ``chunky.'' But never ``frumpy.'' It doesn't sell.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's no denying that's what I look like in this skirt.
Frumpy. Actually, much worse than frumpy. Dumpy. Frumpy and Dumpy,
the eighth and ninth dwarfs could have been hiding out just below
my waistline, judging by my reflection in the mirror. Hips are my
problem, but when are they not? To wear the new longer skirts it
helps to have no hips. For that matter, to wear the old shorter
skirts it helps to have no hips. Let's face it, to wear anything at
all, it helps to have no hips.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, the new longer, fuller skirts should hide all
those unsightly lumps. But, as every woman knows, when it comes to
fashion, there's a chasm between theory and practice. Someone like
me, who'd hoped to send her hips into hibernation under longer
skirts, may find the style only emphasizes the breadth of her
bottom. Flat shoes, de rigeur with the new length, don't help.
</P>
<P>
   There are certain advantages to wearing long skirts. They're
warmer. You don't have to shave your legs so often. Stockings or
pantyhose aren't an absolute must. On the minus side, you run the
risk of tripping on the hem and killing yourself. But the biggest
drawback of all to the new long skirts is that you have to buy
them. And then you have to buy all the other new stuff that goes
with them.
</P>
<P>
   Gray is this season's color. In the stores, ranks of gray
garments dominate. Every shade of gray. Dove gray. Gunmetal gray.
Masterpiece Theatre governess gray. Charcoal gray. Granite gray.
Airstream gray. Russian Blue gray. Gray is the new black. Or maybe
it's the new brown, because brown was the new black last year.
</P>
<P>
   What's the fascination with gray? Fashion has decreed that gray
is the must-have color, probably because consumers don't have
anything gray in their closets. In her book, ``The Language of
Clothes,'' Alison Lurie observes that gray clothing can ``suggest
that one is mysterious, ambiguous, puzzling.'' Maybe gray reflects
the New Ambiguity, which seems to be our national mood these days.
</P>
<P>
   I am in the dressing room again, hiding in a huge,
hip-concealing mottled-gray sweater, an alleged bargain at $280.
``Gray is a hard color to wear,'' the saleswoman says.
</P>
<P>
   She stares at my face intently. ``You need to adjust your
makeup,'' she says. ``Go brighter.''
</P>
<P>
   It comes as a relief to know that I'm not bright enough to wear
this hideous, overpriced sweater. (Memo to self: Stop reading
fashion magazines. It only confuses you.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
