<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3833 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TOMCAT-BOS &LR;      09-14 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TOMCAT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING AFTER LORNA SUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
TOMCAT IN LOVE 
By Tim O'Brien. Broadway Books. 347 pp. $26. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Thomas Henry Chippering is the kind of smooth talker who
politely asks you a question about yourself, then interrupts 30
seconds in to tell you his life story. His intellect is vast but
untamed and deluded; his self-image waffles between grandiosity and
whiny despair. He stands 6 feet 6 inches and, at age 49, has
achieved the status of full professor of linguistics, but neither
dimension has helped him to stand tall in his own life. The tics
and neuroses that sustain him are considerable. Each morning he
shaves all over (``Thomas H. Chippering, a la buff, is a sight not
soon forgotten,'' he informs us); he enjoys waxing semiotic about
almost everything, and he thinks of women as either delectable
takeout items or predators (one of his seminars is entitled
``Methodologies of Misogyny''). Oh, and he's a war hero, at least
on paper. During a year in Vietnam in 1969, his job was to process
citations for valor in action _ and by the end of his tour, he had
himself a Silver Star.
</P>
<P>
   A comic-obsessive, in other words, and Tim O'Brien's answer to
Humbert Humbert, mad and talented and loathsome and sometimes
demonically engaging. As the increasingly unreliable narrator of
``Tomcat in Love,'' Chippering has the challenging task of
remaining compelling (as a voice, anyway) throughout the story of
his own foibles and noisome acts. In large part he fulfills that
promise, if for no other reason than O'Brien's singular ability to
scan for truth on the most pocked horizon. The author has also
distanced himself from Chippering enough to make our antihero
bombastic and even ludicrous, revealing the gritty insights of this
novel by the professor's error rather than example.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of most of his wayward acts lies Chippering's love
for Lorna Sue, his childhood sweetheart and recently divorced wife
who has remarried and moved to Tampa. Through the (allegedly)
cuckolded voice that opens this tale, we start to gather the shards
of anguish that have led to his demise: the young love that began
in Owago, Minn., in the 1950s; the looney Zylstra family that
spawned both Lorna Sue and her zealously protective brother,
Herbie; the shadowy hint of church burnings and other early
violence that underscore what Chippering might call the pathology
of attachment. There's also that tour of duty in Vietnam, which is
woven throughout the novel with coy but successful manipulation: We
will bear Chippering's insufferable rationales for as long as we
must, if only to find out what happened three decades ago at a
firebase in Quang Ngai.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the narrative genius of Tim O'Brien, who told us how to
tell a true war story with his 1990 work, ``The Things They
Carried.'' ``Tomcat in Love'' bears hints of this mastery _ nobody
but O'Brien could have written some of the opening vortexes about
passion and meaning _ but the novel hasn't the depth or stylistic
beauty of ``The Things They Carried,'' or even the spooky range of
his last novel, ``The Lake in the Woods.'' It's an eminently
readable novel (Chippering's carefully chronicled descent into
mayhem ensures that), but a disturbing one, even when it's meant to
be funny. O'Brien's humor is often a manic, knife-at-the-throat
humor, and it's a little like listening to Lenny Bruce in his last
years. Worse is the occasional feeling of contrivance in the
authorial distance between O'Brien and his character. One minute
Chippering is being mercilessly lampooned, then he starts fondling
an undergraduate during office hours, and you feel you're reading
soft porn over his shoulder. The creative compassion is just a
little too close.
</P>
<P>
   So: Thomas Chippering, c'est moi, and all that. ``Tomcat in
Love'' does succeed in getting to you: O'Brien knows cold the
spiraling insularity of obsession, and he drives home the
universality of an unhinged heart with a long footnote, or literary
aside, from Chippering to a fictional second-person (and female)
reader. If a middle-aged, love-starved lech can go to such lengths
to wreak vengeance on an old flame _ well, watch out, honey, and
don't take the high road just yet. It could, and may, happen to
you.
</P>
<P>
   This stance waffles between structural finery and tiresome high
jinks; even as I admired O'Brien's highwire acts, I grew
exasperated with the indulgences visited upon Chippering, whose
speculations about language and symbolism too soon become an
embarrassment of riches. His voice is perfectly modulated, roaming
the nightlands between love and madness, but the women who cavort
into his path are cardboard creations _ either perky young vultures
with ponytails or Viking earth-moms with firm mattresses and hot
oatmeal. They exist, in other words, to serve Chippering, or rather
to serve O'Brien's plot advancement of our modern anti-hero's
tilting at windmills. Even Lorna Sue, the ice queen at the end of
the journey, is more fantasy than fact, poised between reptilian
gloom and the sum of her own pathologies. Within the guise of
paranoid slapstick, which ``Tomcat in Love'' often suggests, this
is probably acceptable, but not very enticing.
</P>
<P>
   What Chippering and his creator share is an admiration for ``the
looping circuitry of a well-told tale,'' and here ``Tomcat in
Love'' follows the narrative mountain path that O'Brien has claimed
as his home terrain. Roaming between Minnesota in the 1950s and the
jungles of Vietnam, between a broken man's efforts at vengeance and
the unsullied memories that preceded them, Chippering's confession
propels you, even unwillingly, into its comi-tragic darkness. This
momentum is achieved not by empathic concern or even suspense (the
story's giveaway is fairly obvious, 50 pages in) but by the
splendidly controlled orator who holds us captive. Thomas
Chippering may be ``imperious, vain, cruel, thoughtless, pious,
glacial, sullen, short-tempered, narcissistic, sarcastic, callous,
unfaithful, and unloving'' _ all of which he calls Lorna Sue _ but
he is wickedly realized. The agility and intelligence that created
this pathos-ridden romantic make one marvel at Tim O'Brien's gifts,
even as you roll your eyes at his excesses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Gail Caldwell is chief book critic of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
