<HEADER>
A3835 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-PATTERSON-ART-     09-14 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-PATTERSON-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATTERSON'S LATEST NOVEL MIMICS LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``A constitutional crisis is one of the less-desirable methods
of promoting a novel,'' says novelist Richard North Patterson with
only the slightest hint of displeasure.
</P>
<P>
   So far _ at least _ Patterson's publisher isn't using the
independent prosecutor's report on the Clinton-Lewinsky affair to
promote ``No Safe Place,'' but it wouldn't be much of a reach.
</P>
<P>
   In the just-published novel, a young senator is challenging the
incumbent vice president in the year 2000 California presidential
primary. In the final week of the campaign, a newsmagazine learns
that, several years before, the then-married senator had an affair
with a young reporter. By an unfortunate chance, she has now been
assigned to cover the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Although the main action takes place in California, the book
opens with a series of shootings at a Boston abortion clinic and
includes a romantic tryst on Martha's Vineyard (where Patterson has
a summer house).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather not have the constitutional crisis,'' said
Patterson while in Boston this month, ``but seeing that we are in
this situation, I'm glad I wrote it.''
</P>
<P>
   Published by Knopf barely two weeks ago, the novel landed in the
No.10 spot on yesterday's New York Times bestseller list and is
expected to climb to No.5 on next Sunday's list, with 400,000
copies already in print.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Safe Place'' is Patterson's ninth novel, but a departure
from his trademark legal thrillers.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson is a laid-back 51, well-tanned after a summer on the
Vineyard, where the embattled President Clinton also summers.
During his Vineyard stay, Clinton received a copy of Patterson's
book from a mutual friend.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson turned to writing some 20 years ago to escape from the
too-many-nights-away grind as a securities lawyer in Birmingham,
Ala. Home after his third business trip in a week, he roughed out a
legal thriller that was published as ``The Lasko Tangent,'' winning
the Edgar award as the best first suspense novel in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   But when his fourth novel, ``Private Screening,'' in 1985 turned
out to be a publishing disappointment, Patterson went back to
lawyering.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, transplanted to San Francisco, he took up
writing again, partly as a matter of pride, he says. And with a new
publisher, Knopf, the result, ``Degree of Guilt,'' was a solid
success, with a first printing of 250,000 copies _ 241,500 more,
Patterson joked at the time, than any of his four previous books.
</P>
<P>
   But after a string of successes with legal thrillers in the John
Grisham and Scott Turow mode _ most recently ``Silent Witness'' in
1997 _ Patterson decided to try a political thriller, using as a
model ``Advise and Consent,'' the classic political novel by the
late Allen Drury.
</P>
<P>
   It was to be about ``politics in the post-Clinton era,''
Patterson said _ not realizing that what he thought would be the
``post-Clinton'' era in which ``everybody will know everything''
may already have arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson researched ``No Safe Place'' as the latest political
era was dawning. Former President George Bush had written to
Patterson after reading ``Degree of Guilt,'' and Patterson traded
on that to ask his help.
</P>
<P>
   Bush not only invited Patterson _ with his wife, Laurie
Anderson, and their 4-year-old son, Chase _ for a weekend at Bush's
summer home in Kennebunkport, Maine, but introduced the author to
Republican political insiders such as Ron Kaufman. Through Kaufman
and others, Patterson attended the 1996 GOP national convention and
spent several days traveling with Bob Dole's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually,'' he laughed, ``my Democratic friends said, `Hey,
time for some equal time here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Patterson is already well into his next book. It will be set in
his native Midwest _ he grew up around Cleveland and got his law
degree at Case Western University there _ and involves a group of
powerful developers trying to build a baseball park in an
inner-city neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson has talked with developers, economists, proponents,
and opponents of ballpark projects. Maybe more to the point, he
said, ``We've had three grisly ballpark fights in San Francisco.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
