<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3837 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWINSKY-JOB-BOS &LR;      09-14 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-JOB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT SAYS LEWINSKY SOUGHT `DREAM JOB' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER
 &HT;    c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the end, when all that remained of their secret
affair were memories of steamy phone calls and hushed rendezvous
near the Oval Office, Monica S. Lewinsky is said to have insisted
President Clinton grant her a final wish as consolation: her
``dream'' job in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, allegedly wary of a jilted paramour revealing their
potentially explosive affair, enlisted officials at the highest
levels of government and a trusted personal adviser, Vernon Jordan,
to meet the former White House intern's requests, according to
independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   To Starr, the effort constitutes obstruction of justice, a
possibly impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   But to Lewinsky, the job search was something the president owed
her, and it never seemed to be enough. Even as Clinton prepared for
a summit last November with Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo,
Lewinsky sent Clinton a note by courier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a moron,'' she wrote. ``I know that what is going on
in the world takes precedence, but I don't think what I have asked
you for is unreasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``This is so hard for me. ... I need you right now
not as president, but as a man. PLEASE be my friend.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the public attention to their alleged sexual dalliances,
Clinton and Lewinsky exhausted much of their time together, in
personal encounters and dozens of phone calls, focusing on
Lewinsky's employment status, which gradually deteriorated with
their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Yet through it all, Clinton allegedly played an active role in
trying to keep Lewinsky happy, an extraordinary distraction for a
chief executive on behalf of an entry-level worker.
</P>
<P>
   The effort could smack of sexual harassment if Lewinsky, by her
own testimony and correspondence, were not so aggressive in
launching the relationship and trying to sustain it.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's workplace woes began not long ago after her affair
with Clinton began in November 1995. She had ascended from an
internship to a paid position dealing with correspondence in the
White House office of legislative affairs the same month.
</P>
<P>
   But by April 1996, as complaints from the Secret Service about
her frequent visits to the Oval Office created suspicions among
senior staffers about her relationship with Clinton, Lewinsky was
transferred to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   When Lewinsky informed him of her transfer on Easter Sunday, the
president became upset, according to Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   The report alleges that Clinton told Lewinsky she could have a
job on his 1996 campaign if she did not like the Pentagon job, then
any position she wanted after the election.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter that Lewinsky never sent, Starr's report said, she
wrote to Clinton: ``I was so sure that the weekend after the
election you would call me to come visit and you would kiss me
passionately and tell me you couldn't wait to have me back. You'd
ask me where I wanted to work and say something akin to `Consider
it done,' and it would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton allegedly had no physical contact with Lewinsky for
nearly a year, but he repeatedly called at her home. And she
testified that she told him before and after several episodes of
phone sex that she hated her Pentagon job.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the runup to their last alleged sexual encounter in
March 1997, Lewinsky pressed Clinton for a White House job. And he
allegedly dispatched several staffers to work on it. According to
Clinton's secretary, Betty Currie, the president ``was pushing us
hard.'' She testified it was the only time he instructed her to try
to get someone a White House job.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Currie and other aides resisted. And on July 3, 1997,
Lewinsky sent him a note that chastised him for breaking his
promise to get her a White House job and, for the first time,
``obliquely threatened to disclose their relationship,'' according
to Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton testified he took the threat seriously.
</P>
<P>
   By last September, Lewinsky was asking Clinton for work at the
United Nations in New York. Currie quoted Clinton as saying: ``Oh,
that's no problem. We can place her in the UN like that.'' UN
Ambassador Bill Richardson interviewed Lewinsky at her Watergate
apartment, and he offered her a job in October.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewinsky rejected the idea, gave Clinton a wish list of
public-relations firms she hoped to join in New York, and suggested
he recruit Jordan, a Washington power broker, to help.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky showed Jordan the wish list several days later. ``Mr.
Jordan said that he had spoken with the President about her and
that she came `highly recommended,''' according to Starr's report.
``Concerning her job search, Mr. Jordan said: `We're in
business.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan arranged interviews with Lewinsky at three companies in
New York. And Jordan, who has said publicly that he was helping
Lewinsky as he had many other young people, kept Clinton updated on
her progress. She interviewed at two firms Dec. 18, but the next
day she received a subpoena to testify in Paula Jones's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's legal woes soon multiplied. And a new job never again
seemed to be a top priority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3838 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-EFFECT-BOS &LR;      09-14 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EFFECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL FAULT LINES SHIFT AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It changed when the farmers, landowners,
shopkeepers, and dreamers rebelled against their British rulers. It
changed when it dedicated itself to social justice during the Civil
War and, again, during the civil rights movement. It changed when
it grasped for economic justice during the Great Depression and the
New Deal. And it changed when it confronted grave constitutional
questions during the Watergate scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the long-awaited, long-dreaded _ and notably lurid _
report by independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr finally available on
both Capitol Hill and in every living room in the land, with the
wheels of impeachment ready to be set in motion, America is
changing again.
</P>
<P>
   Of these latest alterations, many will be stark, some will be
subtle. Many are utterly predictable, some wildly not. But a number
of them are already apparent _ even amid the frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   The changes involve the relationship between the Democrats and
the Republicans, as well as what we expect of a president. The
rules for judging character are being rewritten. So, too, the rules
governing just how far we will allow our leaders to stray from what
most of the body politic believes is right. Changed, too, is how
and how much the populace will be told about the underside of
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how the great capital drama turns out _ will
Congress rise to the institutional challenge, will President
Clinton survive, will the Republicans increase their majorities in
the House and Senate _ the scandal is bound to be a political and
cultural touchstone, a marker in America's story, an episode, like
Watergate, where the rhythms of national life, and, certainly
national political life, are altered.
</P>
<P>
   True, a sex scandal may not seem as momentous as war and
revolution. But watch for the terrain to shift along these lines:
</P>
<P>
   The nature of partisanship. &UR;  &LR; In political folklore, the
Watergate years that culminated in the resignation of President
Nixon were an era of wild, strident partisanship. It is true that
Nixon inspired unusual passion from his critics, but the Watergate
period was in many ways much less partisan than this decade, when
members of Congress have grown far more partisan even as the public
has grown far less so.
</P>
<P>
   Now this faction-riven Congress faces its ultimate test: Can it
approach the impeachment question with dispassion and
nonpartisanship? Even the president's most virulent critics in the
GOP acknowledge that they cannot permit the House decision on
whether to impeach the president to appear partisan. This episode
has the potential of ripping apart an already divided Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The role of the presidency. &UR;  &LR; More than in any other democratic
nation, the president is the central figure in American national
life. Clinton Rossiter, the presidential scholar, called him ``the
one-man distillation of the American people,'' a notion Democratic
Senator Joseph I. Lieberman cited when he delivered his reproach to
Clinton on the Senate floor Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The growth of American influence abroad, the growth of the
federal government, and the growth of the mass media all have
served to enhance the presidency in the 20th century. Now that the
most intimate details of the private sexual comportment of the
president have been made public, there is danger that the office
itself, so often put on a pedestal by Americans, may tumble to
earth.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Burke called society the ``decent drapery of life,'' and
even in our time it has been a leader's responsibility to keep that
drapery on. Now that the whole world has a mental image of the
president undraped, there is the real possibility that the
presidency might shed some of its mystery and, along with it, its
power.
</P>
<P>
   The endurance of elections. &UR;  &LR; Americans elected Clinton to the
White House not once but twice, the first time after he had
acknowledged, in a celebrated television interview, that his
marriage had not been perfect. His wandering eye, moreover, has
been a staple of late-night television comedians for years.
</P>
<P>
   Now Congress is contemplating starting the impeachment process,
which finishes with a trial in the Senate and a vote on the
president's survival. Implicit in that process is the premature
ending of a president's term. Democrats and some Republicans
already are having second thoughts about that, arguing that a
legislative process such as impeachment should be averted except in
the most extreme examples of presidential misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of this argument will determine whether we, as a
country, are ready to allow the findings of an independent counsel
to remove from office a president who was put there by the votes of
millions of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The question of character. &UR;  &LR; The great unresolved question in
American civic life is the relationship between private conduct and
public character. It wasn't resolved in 1987, when Gary Hart, the
former Democratic senator from Colorado, was forced to abandon his
presidential campaign after reporters staked out a condominium
where he visited with a young model. Nor was it resolved in 1991,
when Clinton, in a breakfast with Washington reporters, sought to
ameliorate his reputation as a womanizer.
</P>
<P>
   Now the question, which has been a flashpoint in various
campaigns, will get its full airing in relation to a sitting
president whose policies are immensely popular with the public. In
philosophy and literature, the connection between the private and
the public may have a poetic appeal. In political science, we may
find it does not.
</P>
<P>
   The wiring of politics. &UR;  &LR; On Friday, for the first time ever, an
important document of state was available to the general public at
the very same instant it was provided to the press. In Watergate
and Iran-Contra, the last two big Washington scandals, important
reports were provided to reporters who, in turn, prepared their
summaries and, in a few cases, reprinted edited excerpts.
</P>
<P>
   Not this time. The Starr report flew onto the Internet, and
though there were monumental inconveniences, any American who
wanted to see what reporters were seeing had a chance to do so. In
the past, the press played a mediating role between the public and
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Now a citizen may feel less need for the filter that reporters
and editors provide. Or, depending on one's experience in trying to
download a huge government document and then synthesizing the
material, there might be new appreciation for journalists.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton scandals have convulsed Washington and mostly bored
the rest of the country, a vivid display of the distance between
the capital and the people.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, politics is the leading industry, if you don't
count punditry. In the rest of the country, it is only one of many
conversation topics, and almost certainly not as compelling as Mark
McGwire or the new advances in gender selection or the effort to
move the killer whale or even the beginning of the school year.
</P>
<P>
   But, as summer ends, a Washington obsession has become a
constitutional crisis. The furor may be a test of Clinton, or of
the Congress, or of the special-prosecutor law, but it is also a
test of the public's interest in what used to be called public
affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
