<SLUG> BC-SCI-OLDER-COBB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 67, SHE HASN'T GIVEN UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former astronaut Jerrie Cobb didn't know her friend Sen. John
Glenn was going back into space until March, when she returned to
the United States to get her bush plane tuned up. ``We don't get
much news in the Amazon,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   The news gave her heart. Cobb hopes it may reopen a door that
slammed shut in 1962, when NASA cancelled its female astronaut
program. Cobb was the first female recruit or, as Time magazine
called her in 1960, ``the first astronautrix (measurements:
36-27-34).''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there's hope for me to go up at the age of 67,'' Cobb
said last week before returning to her life's work _ flying
medicines, seeds, and supplies to indigenous Amazon tribes. ``You
never give up a dream. In the back of my mind, I always felt it was
my destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a discouraging meeting last week with NASA administrator
Daniel S. Goldin has not deterred her. ``He was very gracious,''
she reports. ``But the answer was a very definite no. But that
doesn't mean I'm going to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Cobb has impressive support: the National Organization of Women,
American Association of University Women, women pilots' groups,
senators and congressmen, former Apollo astronaut Buzz Aldrin,
21,000 citizens who have signed petitions to NASA.
</P>
<P>
   Her qualifications have never been in doubt. When NASA recruited
her in 1959, she had logged twice as many flight hours as John
Glenn and set four world aviation records for speed, distance, and
altitude. She had passed astronaut screening tests and recruited 25
other women for the program when NASA appointed her a
``consultant'' and cancelled the program.
</P>
<P>
   A congressional hearing on the cancellation went well the first
two days, but then John Glenn and fellow astronaut Scott Carpenter
took the stand. ``The men go off and fight the wars and fly the
airplanes and come back and help design and build and test them,''
Glenn testified. ``The fact that women are not in this field is a
fact of our social order.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Glenn's testimony effectively killed Cobb's chances
of following him into space, she still considers him ``a friend of
mine.'' She recently appealed to him for support (so far without a
response) in her campaign to follow him this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can learn anything from sending any one
person up,'' Cobb says. ``And face it, most older people are women
anyway. It would make better sense and better science to send a
woman up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
