<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3845 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHERS-SPEECH-2TAKE     09-14 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-SPEECH-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, TEACHER, WATCH WHAT YOU SAY! 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the school year begins, forgive teachers if they have their
minds on the courtroom instead of the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, recent legal rulings have had a chilling
effect on teachers' ability to speak freely to their students.
</P>
<P>
   There is always a tension between school boards' and
administators' need, on the one hand, to set the curriculum and, on
the other, teachers' ability to chose the method they find best to
make a point, answer a question, or illuminate a world. But now,
many teachers and education specialists say several recent court
decisions increase that tension by stifling innovative classroom
efforts at a time when a national debate on the quality of our
schools _ and their need to be more creative _ is being waged.
</P>
<P>
   In North Carolina, for example, a high school drama teacher was
transferred after producing a play in which one character is a
lesbian and another is pregnant out of wedlock; in St. Louis, a
high school writing teacher was fired for letting students write
and perform plays laced with expletives; and in Colorado, a high
school teacher was fired for showing his class Bernardo
Bertolucci's film ``1900.''
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the most recent decisions _ including two of them
in federal appelate courts _ have gone against the teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At bottom is a question about what kind of teachers we want _
those who are confident and experimental, or those who avoid
anything that could conceivably offend,'' says Jay Heubert,
associate professor of education at Teachers College at Columbia
University, and an adjunct professor of law. ``If we are looking
for dynamic teachers, we can't expect them to act like sheep. There
just aren't too many dynamic sheep around.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, there is no US Supreme Court decision that
clearly defines the free speech rights of teachers in the
classroom, but that may change soon. The high court could decide as
early as next month whether to take the case of Peggy Boring, the
North Carolina drama teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Boring's situation: She was the drama teacher at the
Charles D. Owen High School in Asheville, when, in fall 1991, she
selected the play ``Independence'' by Lee Blessing for four
advanced students to perform in a statewide competition. The play
centers on a dysfunctional, single-parent family _ a divorced
mother and her three daughters, of which one is a lesbian and one
pregnant out of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   The school had a policy that generally required advance parental
approval before ``controversial materials'' were used. Boring
sought and received parental consent and notified the principal
that the group would perform ``Independence.''
</P>
<P>
   The play won 17 of a possible 21 regional awards, but when it
was performed in front of an English class (where consent forms had
been previously distributed) at the student actors' own school, a
parent complained to principal Fred Ivey. After reading the play,
Ivey said the group could not perform it. The parents of the four
students pleaded with Ivey and he agreed the play could be
performed in the finals. It won second place. But, at the end of
year, Boring was transferred to a junior high school.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy erupted into the local newspaper. A group of
ministers took out an advertisement condemning the selection of the
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was dumbfounded,'' Boring says, ``I felt I had followed what
I thought was a judicious and prudent process. ... I lived in the
community for years and they had dealt with me for years _ and then
to claim I am immoral and corrupting students.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Buncombe County Board of Education upheld her transfer,
Boring sued, lost, appealed, and eventually had the lower court
overturned. Then the school board appealed and won, both before a
panel of three judges from the US Court of Appeals for the Fourth
Circuit, and in a 7-to-6 decision before the full circuit, located
in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so important for teachers and that is why I am
perservering in this,'' Boring said. ``I know what it is like to be
a pariah. You hear among colleagues that they are afraid to do
anything. Certainly, it is better to err on the side of safety than
controversy, but if you draw the line too far on the side of
safety, you end up with materials that are not conducive to
discussion or abstract thinking skills.''
</P>
<P>
   In St. Louis, veteran teacher Cecilia Lacks was fired for
permitting students to use profanities in creative writing
assignments. She went to court and won, but the school district
appealed to US Court of Appeals for the Eighth Circuit, which
reversed the decision and dismissed the case in June, saying, ``A
school district does not violate the First Amendment when it
disciplines a teacher for allowing students to use profanity
repetitiously and egregiously in their written work.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacks argued that she thought the ``no profanity'' policy in the
school applied to student conversations, not graded work. And to
restrict the students' writing would run counter to the district's
teaching style, she argued. Indeed, according to court documents,
``The Ferguson-Florissant District serves as a national center for
the dissemination of literature supporting the `student-centered'
method, which admonishes teachers to avoid stifling students'
natural voices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guidelines distributed to teachers by the district stated:
`Don't tell writers what should be in their (creative) writing or
worse, write on their pieces. ... Resist making judgments about the
writing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lacks, who is white, in a school where most of her students, the
principal, and the assistant superintendent are black, claims she
also was a victim of racial discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The Appeals Court, however, found that the ``no profanity''
policy did not have an exemption for creative writing, and Lacks
could be fired.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3849 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHERS-SPEECH-2ND &LR;  &UR;      09-14 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-SPEECH-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... could be fired.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lacks is appealing the ruling to the full Eighth Circuit Court.
</P>
<P>
   Because there is no Supreme Court decision on the free speech
rights of teachers in classrooms, says Heubert, ``lower courts have
been trying to interpret what the First Amendment means in the
classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, they are relying on a 1988 Supreme Court
decision that addressed the issue of students' free speech rights
in school. The court found that the Hazelwood School District in
Missouri acted appropriately in censoring two articles from a
student newspaper which nevertheless had a front-page disclaimer
saying the articles reflected the opinion of students and not the
school.
</P>
<P>
   But the high court, in a 5-to-3 decision, found that the
newspaper could be perceived to ``bear the imprimatur of the
school'' and administrators could act to regulate student speech,
``so long as their actions are reasonably related to legitimate
pedagogical concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Boring case, the majority of the Fourth Circuit Court
found that any decision by school officials that relates to the
curriculum ``is by definition a legitimate pedagogical concern.''
</P>
<P>
   State courts are also coming down hard against teachers who
stray from the strict confines of their curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   In Colorado, the state's highest court in June reversed an
appeals court decision and, by a 4-to-3 margin, found that Alfred
Wilder could be fired for showing ``1900'' to his logic and debate
class of 17- and 18-year-olds in spring 1995. The 1976 film, at 255
minutes long, covers 45 (according to court documents) years of
life and social conflict in the Emilia region of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The majority found that Wilder was required to obtain approval
before showing the film ``due to its controversial matter ...
extensive nudity, oral sex, masturbation, profanity, cocaine abuse,
and graphic violence.'' The dissenting opinion called Wilder's
firing ``arbitrary, capricious, and legally impermissible.'' As to
the film, the minority found it ``generational, epic, artful.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilder, out of his teaching job and living in New Hampshire, has
yet to appeal further.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Edwin Delattre, a member of the state Board of Education and
dean of the Boston University School of Education, says teachers
should expect oversight of their classrooms and their methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any sound school department draws teachers to a conception
that they have a place in a community of learners, where if you go
on your own, or pander to students, you will make a buffoon of
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Academic freedom and the First Amendment does not protect
people from unprofessional behavior. The field is replete with
high-quality materials that can be used, and you don't have to be
on the borderline and inflame. Why do things that distract when you
have so much material that doesn't?''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of what teachers can do in the classroom has hit close
to home.
</P>
<P>
   Toby Kling Ward, a high school teacher in Belmont, was not given
tenure after she engaged biology students in a discussion about the
abortion of fetusus that had been diagnosed with Down syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1993 decision, the US Court of Appeals for the First
Circuit found that teachers could have their speech restricted if
it related to pedagogical concerns _ as in the Hazelwood case about
students' rights. But the court, which is located in Boston, found
that Hazelwood must be viewed considering the students' age and
sophistication, the context and manner of the presentation, and a
teacher must be given notice of what conduct is prohibited.
Teachers cannot be punished by the school board for ``speech that
it never prohibited. ... Few subjects lack controversy. If teachers
fear retaliation for every utterance, they will fear teaching,''
the court said.
</P>
<P>
   That ruling stands in stark contrast to the Boring case, where
the appeals court took a much narrower approach to what is allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very wise for teachers, administrators, school
boards, and even communitities to discuss the question'' of
teachers' free speech rights, says Heubert.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be an appropriate topic for collective bargaining
because it bears very heavily on what teachers can and cannot do.
Teachers are walking around not knowing what they can say and what
they can't, and the uncertainty is educationally
counterproductive.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the few recent rulings that supported the rights of
teachers, the Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court ruled in 1996
that Joyce T. Hosford was unfairly suspended by Sandwich school
officials and not rehired because she explained the meanings of
certain vulgarities.
</P>
<P>
   Hosford, then a special-needs teacher of seventh-graders, was
talking about idioms and words with double meanings when a student
asked about certain swear words. She gave their definitions and
admonished the students not to use them.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision by Charles Fried, the SJC found, ``that the
discussion she led was designed precisely to bring out into the
open the reasons why such language is immature and inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hosford, now working elsewhere as a speech pathologist, says,
``The fact that I was really quite sure that what I had done was
appropriate, given the students and the situation, doesn't mean I
didn't second-guess myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear that it instills can really limit your ability to
deal well in a classroom situation,'' Hosford says. ``Teachers are
on the front lines in the classroom every day and you never know
what is going to come up. If you can't address it in a
constructive, educational way because you afraid, then you are
doing a disservice to the students.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
