<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3883 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-UNLOVED-SPECIES-A     09-14 1765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-UNLOVED-SPECIES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW PEOPLE CARE ABOUT `UNCUDDLY' CREATURES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pity the freshwater mussel, a drab, mud-colored shellfish that
can't get away when its watery home gets polluted. Mussels are the
most endangered of all the animal families in North America, but
most people don't have a clue.
</P>
<P>
   How about the Puritan tiger beetle? The vicious little predator
has been driven from 98 percent of its waterfront habitat in New
England, mostly by people who had no idea they were destroying
beetle burrows underfoot.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget dragonflies, those prehistoric-looking insects
whose bogs we are increasingly squeezing. Interest in dragonflies
is so low that biologists don't even know how much their numbers
have fallen.
</P>
<P>
   These are some of the unloved endangered species, the slimy, the
inanimate, the repulsive, creatures that don't attract a fan club
the way bald eagles or tigers or panda bears do. Politicians seldom
seek extra money to help such creatures, and when species such as
Sampson's pearly mussel or the blue pike go extinct _ few even know
it.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists believe the public bias toward ``charismatic
megafauna'' _ those popular, often large, warm-blooded animals that
get most of the attention _ is handicapping efforts to stop what
renowned naturalist E.O. Wilson at Harvard University calls the
largest spasm of extinction since the dinosaurs vanished.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's embarrassing,'' says Tim Simmons of the Massachusetts
Natural Heritage and Endangered Species Program, who has only two
part-time employees helping to protect endangered beetles, a
fraction of the 40 staff and volunteers working with the
Massachusetts Audubon Society to protect the much-cuter piping
plovers this summer. He adds:
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger beetles are considerably more threatened than plovers
and eagles. They're not less important, but from a public
perspective, sure they're less important.''
</P>
<P>
   Biologists go back and forth as to which species are most
``important.'' Big predators such as the wolf can serve as a symbol
for a whole landscape, but humble creatures provide nature's
essential services, cleaning up waste and getting eaten by the big
predators. Freshwater mussels, in particular, may be nature's best
barometer of water quality.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing is certain: The vast majority of the 1,082
federally endangered species are more like mussels than wolves,
lacking both a backbone and the ability to move. Moreover, the
uncharismatic species are more likely to vanish: Five of the seven
US extinctions since 1973 are of plants, fish or mussels.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, star power is becoming even more important as the
congressional debate over renewing the controversial Endangered
Species Act drags on. Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, hoping to
fend off efforts to to weaken the law, has begun stressing major
success stories, mostly involving popular endangered species such
as eagles and alligators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have proved that a strong Endangered Species Act can make a
difference. We don't have to stand by idly and watch our wildlife
go extinct,'' said Babbitt last month in announcing plans to drop
the peregrine falcon from the endangered list.
</P>
<P>
   But the recovery of the falcon, the result of a multi-year,
multi-million dollar campaign that included artificial nests on top
of the Tobin Bridge and the Custom House tower in Boston, is by no
means typical.
</P>
<P>
   The 635 endangered plant species, for example, aren't protected
on private land under the Endangered Species Act, and the US Fish
and Wildlife Service increasingly cuts deals with private land
owners, called habitat conservation plans, to allow building on
some endangered species habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists long ago learned the public's preference for
charismatic animals and have tried to use it to advantage, hoping
that efforts to protect, say, the bison, would help other species
by saving the plains where the buffalo roam.
</P>
<P>
   Activists ``will stick a real tiger in front of you because they
are a magnificent beast and you have a sense that the world is
poorer without them,'' says Chris Leahy, director of the Center for
Biological Conservation at the Massachusetts Audubon Society. ``No
matter what you did to a freshwater mussel, you would have trouble
viewing it as impressive in a physical way. They are pretty
sedentary, pretty brown.''
</P>
<P>
   The piping plover, a small nut-colored shorebird that nests on
popular beaches, may be New England's best example of the virtue of
being cuddly. The plover has come back dramatically through a
massive investment of public and private resources, bringing other
animals along in its wake.
</P>
<P>
   Though off-road vehicle owners objected to the closing of beach
sections while the birds nested, they were no match for the piping
plover in the court of public opinion, says Scott Hecker, director
of the coastal shorebirds program for Audubon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing more horrifying than the thought of these cute
little piping plovers being run over by a vehicle. They are a
classic charismatic species when presented to the public,'' Hecker
says.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the sustained effort, the number of nesting plovers
has risen from 252 in 1987 to nearly 1,000 this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The success with plovers, in turn, allows Hecker to protect less
charismatic creatures, such as terns, that also need beach space.
Efforts to save the plover even help the tiger beetles by reducing
traffic over their burrows for a few weeks in the spring and early
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortuntely, the plovers fly away, and the beetles are stuck
there in the sand,'' says Simmons, beetle specialist at the state
Natural Heritage Program. New England's only remaining Northeastern
beach tiger beetles are found in one section of Cape Cod, and the
Puritan tiger beetles are found in only two places in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Still, biologists have by no means given up hope as the concept
of ``biodiversity'' gains currency. Though an individual snail may
not inspire awe, people and government agencies are beginning to
appreciate the need to preserve all parts of nature's system,
because each makes a unique contribution to life.
</P>
<P>
   State biologist Pat Huckery, up to her neck in the waters of the
Nissitissit River in Pepperell, pulls out a two-inch-long clam
that, all by itself, tells her she is in an unspoiled place. There
are other indicators, from the graceful overhanging trees to the
colorful wildflowers on the bank, but the presence of this rare
``bog floater'' proves the water is clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain freshwater mussels seem to be much more sensitive to
water quality, and they are the ones to end up'' on the endangered
species lists, says Huckery, the mussel specialist at the state
Natural Heritage and Endangered Species Program.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their name, bog floaters, one of nearly 300 species of
freshwater mussels in North America, actually spend their adult
lives anchored in the mud, their shells open enough to filter tiny
food particles from the water. Dams, acid rain, sewage run-off,
fertilizer from lawns and farms _ anything that can change the
water's chemistry _ can, and often do, imperil the bog floaters.
</P>
<P>
   With 55 percent of North America's freshwater shellfish species
endangered and at least three already extinct, state and federal
governments have launched a concerted effort to turn the tide. In
July, federal and state officials fined the Tennessee Shell Company
$1 million for illegally purchasing thousands of pounds of
shellfish in Michigan, Ohio, Kentucky, and West Virginia for sale
on the export market.
</P>
<P>
   ``While freshwater mussels are not cuddly creatures with
eyelashes, they are hugely important in the biological scheme of
things,'' says H. Dale Hall, acting regional director of the US
Fish and Wildlife Service in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, with the help of a federal grant, Huckery's
team has been studying ways to save freshwater mussels in the
Connecticut River Valley. Unfortunately, the mussel news is not
good: Only nine individual clams of the dwarf wedgemussel species
are known to remain in Massachusetts, and 18 of the 21 freshwater
shellfish species are declining.
</P>
<P>
   But Huckery believes the future of unpopular creatures such as
mussels and dragonflies would brighten if more people appreciated
their subtle charms, such as the way immature mussels hitch a ride
on fish to colonize new areas.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Huckery believes that dragonflies, descended from
ancient insects that had two-foot wingspans, have more star power
than people realize. Stepping gingerly across a thick mat of moss
that has grown on the surface a Gardner pond, she snares a blue
darner dragonfly in her net. Its luminous green eyes can see
virtually 360 degrees at once, she says, watching as its abdomen
swells and shrinks with its breathing.
</P>
<P>
   The sex life of these animals alone ought to inspire some
interest, Huckery says. In the carnal world of dragonflies and
their cousins, the damselflies, partners pinwheel through the air
in tandem, genitals locked, as the male attempts to rid the female
of any rivals' sperm before depositing his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing it all the time,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But the sex appeal of dragonflies, like the wonder of freshwater
mussels, is a tough sell in a national debate in which critics of
the Endangered Species Act are quick to highlight aggressive
efforts to help obscure species. The snail darter, a little fish
whose presence helped stop a big dam project in Tennessee, is often
held up by critics as evidence of regulators run amok.
</P>
<P>
   And environmentalists charge that fear of such criticism has led
the US Fish and Wildlife Service to adopt a highly destructive
policy that promises landowners ``no surprises'' if they take steps
to protect known endangered species. Under the policy, officials
promise not to ask for more protections should other endangered
species turn up on the land in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you move on to these less charismatic species where less is
known about the biology, they are really being set up for a huge
fall,'' says Daniel Hall of the Oregon-based American Lands
Alliance, an environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with such complaints, the Fish and Wildlife Service is
revising the ``no surprises'' rule.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the uncharismatic animals and plants, says
Hall, that balancing may be at their expense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
