<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BERGERON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERGERON IS TALKING IN BOSTON AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In the five years since he left Boston, Tom Bergeron
has led a classic now-you-see-him, now-you-don't television
existence.
</P>
<P>
   Bergeron's agile wit enlivened the old ``People Are Talking'' on
WBZ-Ch. 4 as well as ``Fox After Breakfast'' on the Fox network,
but it was not enough to keep those shows from being canceled, nor
to land him the permanent anchor job on ABC's ``Good Morning
America,'' where he was aced out by Kevin Newman.
</P>
<P>
   Bergeron has bounced back, however, and tonight will resurface
on television as the host of a new syndicated version of
``Hollywood Squares.''
</P>
<P>
   Characteristically, the 43-year-old Bergeron is rather jovial
about his odyssey through the network wilderness. ``I call my
post-Boston years my `Serendipity Tour,''' he said. ``I'm just sort
of floating happily from one adventure to another.''
</P>
<P>
   Bergeron's latest ``adventure'' pairs him with executive
producer Whoopi Goldberg, who also will occupy the center square
made famous in the original show by Paul Lynde. In tonight's
premiere, some of the other celebrity players include Rosie
O'Donnell, Jeffrey Tambor, Rita Rudner, and Kathy Najimy. Such
celebrities as Sting, Whitney Houston, Garth Brooks, and Penn &AMP;
Teller are lined up for future guest stints.
</P>
<P>
   To judge by the premiere, though, Bergeron's breezily irreverent
persona will command its own share of the spotlight. However, in
presiding over what he calls ``a star-studded tic-tac-toe game,''
he is aware that he must serve more as ringmaster than entertainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to me to be the `dad' if the contestants start goofing
around,'' said Bergeron. ``I have to draw a line between getting in
the sandbox to play and being the sandbox supervisor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood Squares'' arrived for Bergeron after a highly
publicized setback. A longtime fill-in anchor on ABC's ``Good
Morning America,'' Bergeron was considered a strong candidate to
succeed Charles Gibson. But he was passed over for Newman, the
``Good Morning America'' newsreader. The New York Post headline
hooted: ```GMA to Tom: You're Out!'''
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty, I was not at all disappointed,'' said Bergeron
equably. ``It was clear to me that Lisa (McRee) and I didn't have
much chemistry. A show like that needs chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Bergeron seems ideally suited to a game show, he
insists he never had ``game-show aspirations.'' That changed when
representatives of King World Productions called and said ``We want
to test you with Whoopi'' for a new, ``hip'' version of ``Hollywood
Squares.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg and Bergeron had hit it off when she was a guest on
``Fox After Breakfast,'' and they easily recaptured that chemistry
while taping ``Hollywood Squares,'' according to Bergeron.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a ball together,'' he said. ``With her on board, and
such a strong comedy element, it was a real attractive package.''
</P>
<P>
   The new incarnation of ``Hollywood Squares'' seems like a good
showcase for Bergeron's quick-on-his-feet style. When tonight's
contestant tells him she works as a mobile disc jockey, Bergeron
cracks, ``I was a mobile disc jockey too. I couldn't hold down a
job in any one place.''
</P>
<P>
   Bergeron did begin his career as a disc jockey in 1972 at WHAV
in his hometown of Haverhill, where he was the station's youngest
disc jockey ever. His Boston TV career blossomed in 1982 when he
joined Channel 4 and became host of ``4 Today'' and a pair of
children's shows, ``Rap Around'' and ``Super Kids.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is perhaps best-known locally for his stint as the host
of ``People Are Talking'' from 1987 to 1993 (during which time he
also hosted radio shows on WBZ and WMJX). Glib without being
smarmy, smoothly ranging from substance to fluff and back to
substance again, Bergeron emerged as one of the easiest-to-take TV
personalities Boston has ever had.
</P>
<P>
   When ``People Are Talking'' was canceled, Bergeron went national
with ``Breakfast Time'' on the FX cable channel, which later
migrated to the Fox broadcast network and was renamed ``Fox After
Breakfast.'' But that show was also canceled. Bergeron rebounded
with the guest-host stints at ``Good Morning America'' until Newman
bested him for the role of permanent anchor.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bergeron is pinning his hopes on ``Hollyood Squares.''
(Coincidentally, as Bergeron tries to fill the shoes of Peter
Marshall, host of the old ``Hollywood Squares,'' Marshall has just
had his debut as host of a new game show, ``The Reel to Reel
Picture Show,'' on Pax TV.)
</P>
<P>
   Bergeron says he's pleased he will be back on Channel 4, albeit
in a syndicated show, and says he still misses Boston, recalling
such local touches as the quilt with a ``People Are Talking'' logo
sent to him by a viewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching `Good Will Hunting' and getting homesick,'' he
said. ``If you're accepted by Boston, it's a close, warm, personal
relationship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
