<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-DEADLY-SLEEP-AND-MORE-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following two articles, which have been excerpted from
recent issues of Discover magazine, are available for one-shot
purchase from The New York Times Syndicate. ALL THE ART IS FREE OF
CHARGE!
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   ASK OUR SALES STAFF ABOUT SUBSCRIBING TO DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE.
Each week, clients receive two articles -- in both Spanish and
English -- plus eye-catching art to brighten their pages.
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A SLEEPING STORM &QL; 
 &UR; (1,700 words) &QL; 
 &UR; FOUR COLOR SLIDES &QL; 
 &UR; By CARL ZIMMER &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Sleeping sickness _ once thought to be vanquished _ is raging
back across Africa. At the center of the epidemic, an American
doctor is trying to clear a small patch of good health. Carl
Zimmer, a senior editor of Discover magazine and the winner of the
1997 American Institute of Biological Sciences Media Award,
reports.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-SLEEPING-SICKNESS-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   SENT TO: category codes ``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general
news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BABY WHO STOPPED EATING &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,600 words) &QL; 
 &UR; ONE COLOR ILLUSTRATION &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT MARION &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Robert Marion, a professor of pediatrics at Albert Einstein
Medical College and director of the Center for Congenital Disorders
at Montefiore Medical Center in New York, reports on his treatment
of an infant patient who one day for no apparent reason stopped
nursing. The answer was found in a jar of honey.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-BABY-WON'T-EAT-NYTSF
</P>
