GLOBE CRITICS RATE FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 ! poor, !! fair, !!! good, !!!! excellent  
 
 !!! ``All the Rage''  Set in Boston's boy-beautiful South End,
Roland Tec's smart, provocative feature looks at the life of a
handsome young lawyer whose good looks and desirability make it
difficult for him to choose between tricking and true love. (R)
(Renee Graham)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! 1/2 ``Hollywoodism: Jews, Movies and the American Dream''
 &LR; Simcha Jacobovici's documentary persuasively makes the case for
Hollywood as the idealized creation of Jews excluded from the WASP
establishment. The ultimate irony, as various talking heads spell
out, was that the children of the establishment bought into the
dream images. (Unrated)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ! ``Let's Talk About Sex''  &LR; Somewhere in the middle of this tired
little mess of a movie there's an intriguingly bawdy film about
women's sexual attitudes _ but it's awfully tedious trying to spot
it. Writer-director-star Troy Beyer has done the impossible: She's
made a film about sex unbelievably boring. (R) (Renee Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; !!! ``Rounders''  &LR; Another juicy Matt Damon movie, conventional but
smoothly and tensely managed. It plunges us into the underground
world of high-stakes poker played in dark caves where nobody shares
the winnings with the IRS. Damon's poker wizard, trying to go
straight as a law student, is sucked back into the game after his
buddy, Edward Norton, plays a few bad hands with some bad-news
heavies. (R)
</P>
