<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH CRIMES AND SLEAZY DEMEANOR 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Never mind high crimes, misdemeanors and cigars
that sometimes aren't just cigars. These are my eight grounds for
the impeachment of Bill Clinton:
</P>
<P>
   1) For saying ``I have sinned'' with tears in his eyes at a
prayer breakfast with such ``pastoral counselors'' as the Rev.
Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   2) For writing his own sappy prayer, which ended: ``Let the
words of my mouth and the meditations of my heart and, in the end,
the work of my hands, be pleasing.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeeech. He should just sit on his hands, shut up and talk to God
silently.
</P>
<P>
   3) For forgetting Monica Lewinsky's name after a brief breakup.
Never call a woman ``Kiddo'' unless you're Humphrey Bogart.
</P>
<P>
   4) For telling Monica, after she asked coyly where he got a
certain necktie, ``Some girl with style gave it to me.''
</P>
<P>
   With lines like that, a guy could cut a swathe through a trailer
park like an Arkansas tornado.
</P>
<P>
   5) For giving a speech to some Irish folks and Democratic
bigwigs right after the Starr report appeared and acting like
nothing had happened _ and then quoting Ted Kennedy and saying, ``I
like to borrow Senator Kennedy's lines whenever I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Like what? ``She was driving?''
</P>
<P>
   6) For celebrating holidays like New Year's Eve, Presidents Day
and Easter Sunday with Monica moments. Easter? Aren't there a bunch
of kids rolling eggs on the lawn right outside the window?
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Clinton and Lewinsky began their affair on the
second day of Newt Gingrich's government shutdown. Hey, there was
nothing else to do.
</P>
<P>
   7) For sticking to that ridiculous argument that oral sex isn't
sex. The president even testified that he thought ``any person, any
reasonable person'' would think the same thing. Yeah, it's just
Beltway call-waiting.
</P>
<P>
   8) For talking on the phone with members of Congress while
Monica was servicing him. One conversation was about deploying
troops to Bosnia. This guy is such a policy wonk he can talk
foreign affairs right in the middle of a domestic affair.
</P>
<P>
   Bosnia is lucky it didn't get a sudden launch of cruise
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   There's more to my bill of particulars against unparticular
Bill, but let's talk about the other jerks who have helped set a
team record in American tackiness.
</P>
<P>
   Is stupidity a high crime or a misdemeanor? Either way, this is
the case against Monica:
</P>
<P>
   1) For telling 11 people about her relationship with the
president. Didn't Bill brief her on the don't ask, don't tell
policy?
</P>
<P>
   2) For asking the president: ``Is this just about sex ... or do
you have some interest in trying to get to know me as a person?''
</P>
<P>
   3) For falling in love with Bill Clinton. But then, we can't
fault her for an irrational attachment shared by so many voters.
</P>
<P>
   4) For thinking she might become his wife. Did she have any idea
who she'd be up against?
</P>
<P>
   And now for Kenneth Starr, that righteous avatar of traditional
values who dumped salacious material all over the Internet and the
news media. What a guy. These are my articles of impeachment for
his smug little butt:
</P>
<P>
   1) For sprinkling more sex scenes in his report than you can
find in a whole shelf of paperbacks at a wanker bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   2) For presenting those sex scenes in a style colder than
clinical. Legalese meets sleaze. It's ugly, ugly stuff. I don't
know about you, but I have to purify my system by reading
``Candy.''
</P>
<P>
   3) For making us think about what our sex lives would look like
in a report to Congress. Well, some of our sex lives might look
like a blank piece of paper. That's even worse than being portrayed
sucking on incriminating Tiparillos.
</P>
<P>
   4) For describing encounters between Bill and Monica, and then
tacking on things like ``Mrs. Clinton was in Athens, Greece.''
That's rubbing it in a bit, don't you think?
</P>
<P>
   5) For spending four years and about $50 million on this. A
couple of sailors could do better on weekend liberty with $50.
</P>
<P>
   6) For trying to kill my mother. She shouldn't read this stuff.
</P>
<P>
   As you can see, I am leaving the issue of high crimes and
misdemeanors to the high criminal experts in Congress. The scandal
has come down to low slime and misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before I read Starr's report to Congress and was overwhelmed by
his multimillion-dollar peep show, I fully intended to write a
high-road column. I wandered around the campus at the University of
California at Berkeley talking to students. In teacher Lydia
Chavez's journalism class, I found young grad students wondering
how some tawdry sex and lies led to talk of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Queena Kim said that a professor had asked, ``Aren't you excited
to wake up and read the news? And the students are like, `Not
really.'''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Roller said that she had watched tapes of the Watergate
hearings, and had been moved by the gravity and power of those
events. ``It was so exciting to watch it unfold,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Every age gets the scandal it deserves, I guess. This isn't the
age of Walter Cronkite anymore, but the age of Jerry Springer.
</P>
<P>
   Once we had Watergate. Now we have a scandal better covered by
Penthouse and Cigar Aficionado than Woodward and Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
