<HEADLINE>
AFTER THE POPCORN SEASON, FALL'S ANNUAL DELUGE OF MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, OK. We see you staggering back, hand to head, yelling ``Too
much information!'' Still, a handful of titles do jump out from the
150 or so films due between now and Christmas. So do a handful of
stars from among the usual suspects. Not all the pairings will
involve the usual man-woman duets. Take ``Stepmom,'' the rueful
comedy starring Susan Sarandon and Julia Roberts, due at Christmas.
Sarandon will play the disapproving ex-wife of Ed Harris, who has
remarried the younger but less domestically adept Roberts. Another
pair of high-profile actresses, Sandra Bullock and Nicole Kidman,
are on the same side in ``Practical Magic'' (Oct. 9), playing
sisters who not only are witchy, but are witches.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Meryl Streep, twice. In ``One True Thing''
(Friday), based on Anna Quindlen's novel, she'll play a mom dying
of cancer trying to live with an ambitious journalist daughter
(Renee Zellweger) caring for her and a selfish academic husband
(William Hurt). Later, we'll see her as the eldest sister in the
'30s Irish family in ``Dancing at Lughnasa,'' drawn from Brian
Friel's play.
</P>
<P>
   You will have noted the n-word _ novel _ already. It's the
source, as usual, of most of the fall's high-profile entries.
</P>
<P>
   Several have been simmering for years, starting with Toni
Morrison's ``Beloved'' (Oct. 16), starring Oprah Winfrey as an
escaped slave alongside Danny Glover, under Jonathan Demme's
direction. ``The Thin Red Line'' (Dec. 25) finds Terrence Malick
ending a few decades of seclusion to guide Sean Penn, John
Travolta, Aidan Brody, Nick Nolte, George Clooney, and a bunch of
other A-list grunts through James Jones's story about GIs battling
to take Guadalcanal from the Japanese. Jones himself will be a
major presence in ``A Soldier's Daughter Never Cries,'' based on
the autobiographical novel by his daughter, Kaylie, starring Kris
Kristofferson as it keeps up with the Joneses in Paris and the
United States (Sept. 25).
</P>
<P>
   ``A Civil Action'' (Dec. 25), filmed in Massachusetts and based
on Jonathan Harr's nonfiction bestseller, toplines Travolta as the
lawyer fighting two corporations accused of toxic pollution by
eight Woburn families stricken with leukemia. Nolte will be seen as
a rural cop cursed with a history of family violence in
``Affliction,'' based on Russell Banks's novel (late December or
January). ``A Simple Plan'' (Oct. 9) adapts Scott Smith's dark
novel about brothers (Bill Paxton and Billy Bob Thornton) finding a
crashed plane stuffed with drug money.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Dreams May Come'' (Oct. 2), from Richard Matheson's New
Age novel, finds Robin Williams literally going through heaven and
hell to rejoin his wife, played by Annabella Sciorra, in the
afterlife. Williams plays a doctor for the fifth time in ``What
Dreams May Come,'' and for the sixth time in ``Patch Adams'' (Dec.
25), the twist this time being that he's a former suicidal mental
patient who, upon being healed, heads for med school. It wouldn't
be a new season without a new movie stemming from Stephen King.
``Apt Pupil'' (Oct. 23) finds Ian McKellen's Nazi war criminal
teaching naive teen Brad Renfro all the wrong things. McKellen will
also be seen next month in ``Gods and Monsters'' as James Whale,
the British director of ``Frankenstein'' and ``The Invisible Man.''
Penn also has a second film, portraying a Hollywood player
alongside Kevin Spacey in the long-delayed film of David Rabe's
``Hurlyburly'' (Dec. 25).
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Branagh will be busy, too, as he heads (by alphabetical
fortune) the cast of the new Woody Allen movie ``Celebrity''
(November). Allen presciently signed Leonardo DiCaprio to play a
Hollywood flavor of the month before DiCaprio broke out in
``Titanic.'' Famous people playing famous people is nothing new to
Allen, but this time he expands the concept by casting NBA star
Anthony Mason to play an NBA star. Bra-nagh's other outing will be
``Theory of Flight,'' in which he plays an offender sentenced to
community service, helping Helena Bonham Carter cope with a
neurological disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Predictable star-casting peaks as Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan follow
``Sleepless in Seattle'' with another romantic comedy, ``You've Got
Mail'' (Dec. 18), a version of the Ernst Lubitsch classic ``The
Shop Around the Corner,'' but with an Internet twist. He's a
chain-bookstore marketer squeezing her one-woman bookshop, and they
fall in love on the Web. Val Kilmer and Mira Sorvino take on a more
unorthodox concept in ``At First Sight'' (Nov. 20), as he plays a
blind man and she plays his sighted lover. The relationship genre
also yields the season's most intriguing title, ``Dancing About
Architecture'' (Dec. 18) _ as in the adage ``Talking about music is
like dancing about architecture.'' Its offbeat casting stars Gena
Rowlands and Sean Connery as a long-married couple facing a crisis.
We can't leave ``Shakespeare in Love'' (Dec. 25) off the
relationship-movie list. It stars Joseph Fiennes, Gwyneth Paltrow,
Ben Affleck, Geoffrey Rush, and Judi Dench.
</P>
<P>
   Mayhem of the non-domestic kind will be plentiful, too. But
first, perhaps, we ought to call attention to Brad Pitt's role in
``Meet Joe Black'' (Nov. 13), in which he plays Death. Not the grim
reaper, but the party animal as first depicted in the film of which
this is a remake, ``Death Takes a Holiday.'' Death won't take a
holiday in the season's other eagerly awaited remake, ``Psycho''
(Dec. 4), with Vince Vaughn and Anne Heche in the Tony Perkins and
Janet Leigh roles and Gus Van Sant standing in for Alfred
Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   On the theory that there's something about Cameron Diaz, big
plans are being made for ``Very Bad Things'' (Nov. 20) with its
gruesome party-from-hell theme. ``John Carpenter's Vampires'' (Oct.
30) will add you know what to the Halloween season. The gore level
will be maintained by ``I Still Know What You Did Last Summer''
(Nov. 20), in which the traumatized high-schoolers are stalked on a
tropical island.
</P>
<P>
   Will Smith will return opposite Gene Hackman in the
spy-intrigue-laden ``Enemy of the State'' (Nov. 25). In ``Ronin''
(Sept. 25), Robert De Niro, Stellan Skarsgard, Jonathan Pryce, and
Jean Reno play big guns on the loose in Paris with only a script by
David Mamet and direction by John Frankenheimer. ``Soldier'' (Oct.
22) gives Kurt Russell the sci-fi Western field all to himself.
Stephen Frears has set his Western, ``The Hi-Lo Country'' (Dec. 18)
in postwar New Mexico, as he charts the decline of the Western
frontier against a story involving Woody Harrelson and Billy Crudup
competing for the favors of Patricia Arquette.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Hollywood won't be making nice with a spate of
family-themed movies. New family-film icon Eddie Murphy will return
in ``Holy Man'' (Oct. 9), about a merger between religion and a
home shopping network. DreamWorks and Disney will square off with
dueling insects. DreamWorks promises ``Antz'' (Oct. 2), with Woody
Allen as the voice of a lowly drone wooing queen Sharon Stone.
Disney's ``A Bug's Life'' (Nov. 20), from the ``Toy Story'' wizards
at Pixar, rallies the voices of Kevin Spacey, Julia Louis-Dreyfus,
and Denis Leary in a rebellion by ants against grasshoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Later (Dec. 18), DreamWorks will unveil its ambitious ``Prince
of Egypt,'' the Moses story, with animated influences ranging from
the Book of Exodus to Cecil B. DeMille. Also due: ``Babe: Pig in
the City'' (Nov. 20), in which the popular animatronic porker goes
urban to save the farm. Touchy-feely creature comfort is promised
in the ``Mighty Joe Young'' remake (Dec. 18). The eco-friendly ape
is no ``Godzilla,'' promise the producers. On the other hand, the
hope is for at least a mini-rampage in ``Bride of Chucky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
