<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIREE SHOULD AVOID TEMPTATION FOR BIG CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. In a column earlier this month you suggested a portfolio
consisting of Vanguard GNMA, Vanguard Short-Term Bond, and Vanguard
Corporate High-Yield funds.
</P>
<P>
   I am 80 and keep physically active. My wife and I own our home
and thoroughly enjoy our life here on Cape Cod, after moving here
26 years ago. My investment holdings are $110,000 in Vanguard GNMA,
$33,000 in Vanguard Intermediate-Term U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury, $20,000 in Vanguard Wellington, $40,000 in Van Kampen
Merritt Municipal Trust, $30,000 in Stratton Monthly Dividend REIT
(which I am in the process of closing) and $20,000 in a 7.5 percent
U.S. Treasury Bill. I am interested in the portfolio you outlined.
</P>
<P>
   In view of my holdings, which provide revenue for our living
expenses, would you suggest that I move to the three Vanguard
funds?
</P>
<P>
   R.H., Osterville
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Speaking broadly, your portfolio is already designed pretty
much along the lines I suggested in that previous column -- a core
holding in Ginnie Maes, balanced at either end by holdings that
offer greater and lesser risk. Using an assumption that the money
that came out of Stratton Monthly Dividend has been parked in a
money market fund, I estimate your overall portfolio average yield
at 5.91 percent. That's less than the 6.5 percent-plus target for
the portfolio I wrote about before, but your portfolio has some
compensating advantages -- the tax-free status of the municipals
(which I have assumed are in the Van Kampen American Capital
Municipal Income fund) and the principal growth potential of
Vanguard Wellington.
</P>
<P>
   First off, I have a question: are you sure your tax status makes
the municipal bond fund an advantageous holding. With a 5.4 percent
tax-free yield, it's not providing much of a drain on the overall
yield, but it achieves this high yield -- high for a municipal bond
fund anyway -- by holding a long-term portfolio and by holding a
higher-than-average position (22 percent as of the last Morningstar
Mutual Funds report) in non-rated, or junk munis.
</P>
<P>
   You might analyze your tax situation and determine whether you
might put this money in a taxable bond fund with a higher yield,
ending up ahead even after paying the tax liability.
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio to which you refer was suggested in response to a
person who sought the highest possible yield consistent with a
reasonable risk level. From the tone of your letter, it sounds to
me as though you're fairly comfortable with your income stream as
it is, so I don't think wholesale changes are in order. Even with
this year's disappointing results (up 2.7 percent year-to-date as
this is written) Vanguard Wellington should produce some capital
growth, which was not a realistic feature of the portfolio I
suggested in the previous column.
</P>
<P>
   So unless you find that the tax-free holding isn't doing all
that much for you, my only suggestion involves that $30,000 that is
coming out of the Stratton Monthly Dividend REIT holding. If you
were to add that money to the Vanguard GNMA position, it would
bring the overall portfolio yield up to 6.09 percent; if you were
to put it in Vanguard Corporate High-Yield, the portfolio average
yield would advance to 6.39 percent. If you're considering the
latter option, you should note that high-yield bonds tend to
reflect movements in both the stock and bond markets. Like all bond
funds, they will gain or lose value inversely with changes in
interest rates; like stocks, they will lose value quickly when the
stock market goes into a tailspin. During August Vanguard
High-Yield Corporate Bond fund lost 3.9 percent, and as this is
written it has fallen to the point that its year-to-date total
return is but .8 percent. So making that move will broaden your
exposure to stock market swings beyond the 62 percent of the
Vanguard Wellington portfolio that's in equities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I would like to have $25,000 a year income when I retire at
age 65 in three and a half years. I anticipate $850 monthly from
Social Security and a pension with $528 a month for life or a
$67,332 lump sum. I have a total of $233,020 saved, of which
$158,598 is in IRAs and a 401(k) account. Of this, all but $23,227
is in stocks or stock funds. In addition, I have $36,832 in common
stocks in taxable accounts. The balance of my savings is in bank
savings and U.S. Savings bonds. My only debt is $6,200 on my house,
which is worth about $90,000 with a 7 percent interest rate. Should
I pay this off or keep paying it monthly? Should I sell it and
invest the money?
</P>
<P>
   B.R., Cedar Park, Texas
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I know absolutely nothing about the Texas real estate market,
but my suspicion is that you'd be best off keeping the house.
Consider this math: If you sold the house and paid a typical
Realtor's fee, it would bring in $84,600. After paying off the
mortgage balance, and ignoring your other closing costs, you would
have $78,400. If there were no tax liability and that sum were
invested in a bond fund yielding 6.5 percent, it would bring you
$424 a month. Is such a sum sufficient to pay the rentals of a
similar lodging, even adding in the amount you are paying each
month on real estate taxes, insurance and maintenance? My suspicion
is that the answer is no. Moreover, as a homeowner, you would not
have to worry about the prospect of rent increases.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, I suggest you not only keep the house, but also prepay
the mortgage. You have in excess of $20,000 in low-interest money
market funds at banks and credit unions, which would certainly be
well placed in replacing a 7 percent mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   But my more pressing advice is a response to a question you
didn't ask: Is yours a good portfolio for a person 42 months away
from retirement? I think the answer is no. You have a total of 71.6
percent of your total savings in stocks and stock funds, which
strikes me as a very high percentage. I suggest you reduce your
stock market exposure to a maximum 50 percent of your total
savings, and I would be more comfortable if you were to cut it to
40 percent. This could be achieved without immediate tax effects by
simply transferring many of the tax-deferred holdings into
fixed-income holdings. A typical fixed-income portfolio I often
recommend ( discussed in the letter above) consists of 50 percent
in a good GNMA fund, with the remaining funds evenly divided
between a short-term bond fund and a high- yield bond fund. If you
were to follow my suggestion of a total 40 percent stock position,
you would reduce the equity position in the tax-deferred accounts
to $56,376; if you chose to keep half the funds in stocks, the
figure would be $79,678.
</P>
<P>
   Finally another question you didn't ask: Would I get better
returns from money market fund in a mutual fund family than I'm
getting at the bank and credit union? You bet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Since April of 1995 I have invested $4,750 in American Funds'
Investment Company of America for my eight-year-old grandson.
June's quarterly statement shows the account's value to be $6,608.
I purchased the first shares through a Pittsburgh bank while on
vacation, and did not realize that there is a 5.75 percent sales
charge deducted every time a deposit is made. What is your opinion
of withdrawing these funds and depositing them in the Stein Roe
Young Investor fund?
</P>
<P>
   D.S., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. If the sales charge, or ``load'' is your primary motivation
for making a switch, there's nothing to gain by switching. As you
noted, the 5.75 percent load on Investment Company of America is
charged at the front end, so the money has already been spent, and
you wouldn't recover it by selling. So it would seem to me that
your better move, if you are convinced you don't want to pay any
more sales charges, is to leave the current holdings in Investment
Company of America and begin a second account with Stein Roe Young
Investor.
</P>
<P>
   There are other reasons, in my opinion, to stick with the fund
you have -- as a value- oriented large-cap fund, it provides more
stability in a shaky market than Stein Roe Young Investor. For
example, year-to-date it has a 3.9 percent total return as this is
written; Young Investor shows a 1.5 percent year-to-date loss. The
latter fund's portfolio is dominated by growth-oriented large cap
funds. Over a three-tear period it has nicely outstripped
Investment Company of America, with average annual returns of 18.61
percent compared to 15.33 percent, according to Morningstar's
latest figures. But since I anticipate no return to the frothy
growth markets of 1996 and 1997, I would be more comfortable with
Investment Company of America.
</P>
<P>
   Although Stein Roe Young Investor fund has a $2,500 minimum
initial investment for most accounts, the level is reduced to
$1,000 for uniform gift to minors accounts, and further reduced to
$100 if you sign up for an automatic investment plan into which at
least $50 an month will flow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass.
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
