A3926 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REEVES-TEX     09-14 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IT COMES TO DEFENSIVE WOES, SEVERAL ARE TO BLAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Dallas Cowboys safety Darren Woodson said it was the
players' fault, plain and simple.
</P>
<P>
   Secondary coach Mike Zimmer, in no uncertain terms, blamed
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials were overheard muttering words such as
``embarrassing'' and ``pitiful'' under their breath and that was
``before'' quarterback Troy Aikman was knocked out with a broken
left collar bone.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what: Each and every one of them was right on the money.
</P>
<P>
   Total defensive ineptitude in the first half allowed the Broncos
to make a mockery of the ``Team of the '90s'' Sunday at Mile High
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, by sending Aikman to the sidelines with his arm in a
sling for the next four to six weeks, the Broncos might have put
the Cowboys six feet under for the season as well.
</P>
<P>
   If this was Dallas' first real test of 1998, consider it an
abject and total failure.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the offense, even under backup Jason Garrett, wasn't
shabby, but let head coach Chan Gailey's own words spell out the
grim reality for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't score enough points to win,'' Gailey said tersely
after his first loss as an NFL head coach. ``If your defense isn't
stopping them, you have to score more points than they do. That's
the objective of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You win as a team and you lose as a team. You don't shuffle
the blame to one side or the other; you accept it and go on to the
next one.''
</P>
<P>
   While the loss of Aikman, injured at the end of another
happy-feet scramble _ what are you gonna do, he's a competitor _
loomed as potentially devastating in the long term, the irony was
his departure midway in the second quarter had very little to do
with the final outcome on a balmy Colorado Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Not unless he could have tackled Denver tailback Terrell Davis
or covered tight end Shannon Sharpe.
</P>
<P>
   He shouldn't feel bad. Nobody else could either.
</P>
<P>
   Davis broke open a 7-7 game with stunning back-to-back
first-quarter touchdown runs of 63 and 59 yards and Broncos
quarterback John Elway, toying with the Cowboys' defense, hit
Sharpe with touchdown passes of 39 and 23 yards as the Broncos
scored five touchdowns in five first-half possessions.
</P>
<P>
   The 35 points was the most ever surrendered by a Cowboys' team
in a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised they moved the ball on our defense as well as
they did today,'' Gailey said. ``I thought they did a good job of
spreading us out and creating a lot of one-on-one matchups. John's
got a great vision of the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let'em break two big runs. That really is something we have
not done too much of and you try to keep that from happening. Long
runs are what get you. You at least want to make them work their
way down the field in those situations to give yourself a better
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Broncos had put up 35 first-half points, the Cowboys
had no chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my fault. The whole deal's my fault,'' a flushed Zimmer
declared in the postgame locker room. ``I take all the blame on
this one. It's not (defensive coordinator Dave) Campo and it's not
the players. It's me. The players did what they were supposed to
do. I just didn't put them in the right situation to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Easy, Zim. There's plenty of blame to go around here.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd seen that set they lined up against us, we'd practiced
it, but we lost our composure,'' Zimmer said. ``We outsmarted
ourselves because they got in one set in a bunch of different ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got Sharpe down the middle on that (first touchdown) when
we had a guy bust an assignment, and then we completely lost our
composure after that and couldn't get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   In the hectic bedlam of Mile High, Zimmer said he couldn't
settle his secondary down until the team got into the locker room
at halftime. And by then, the game was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got nervous because we wanted to shut'em down,'' Zimmer
said. ``They had us totally out of sync and completely flustered.
</P>
<P>
   ``When guys are unsure about what's going on, they start to
think and you can't think when you're playing football. It's a
reaction game. They're out there thinking, `What if they do this
and what if they do that?' In the second half we made a couple of
other adjustments and added one more check and we did better, but
it was too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo said the halftime changes were minimal. It was more a case
of getting the players calmed down and refocused.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do a whole lot different,'' he said. ``In the first
half we were doing stuff out there that we hadn't done all training
camp. We just got flustered and that surprised me because I didn't
think another team could do that to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just Mike personality, wanting to take all the blame,
but this is a team game.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodson couldn't have agreed more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the coaches, it's the players,'' he said. ``I give
all the credit to the Broncos.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd give the man a cigar except the way the Cowboys played
defense Sunday, it would probably slip through his fingers and
score.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
