<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPERA HITS THE HIGH NOTE WITH KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Because I have subscribed to the San Francisco
Opera each season since 1981 and always attend the annual Examiner
Opera in the Park concerts, many of my friends and colleagues
assume I've been an opera fan all my life.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, I was 23 before I saw my first live opera _ Verdi's
``La Traviata'' at the New York City Opera _ and I walked out at
the first intermission.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't a clue what was going on onstage, I found the music
brittle and alienating and I was ... bored. Twenty-five years
later, you would need a large cruise missile to keep me from my
seat in the War Memorial Opera House or from the lawn in front of
the stage Sunday in Golden Gate Park.
</P>
<P>
   How does a person make such a 180-degree turn? Well, I believe
that opera _ like great jazz and poetry _ is imbued with magical
properties. Expose yourself to it (the right way), put out just a
little effort, allow yourself to truly open to its mystical powers,
and the odds are you will understand what all those centuries of
shouting have been about.
</P>
<P>
   Since '81, I have compared opera to sports, religion, drugs and
love. Sometimes it's like all four rolled into one. Also, I am fond
of ``explaining'' operaphilia with this Gustav Mahler observation:
``All theater is an insane asylum; opera is the ward for the
incurables.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is ``the right way'' to expose yourself to opera? Not
the way I chose when I was 23, which was to drink too much scotch
before dinner and walk in cold, as if I were about to plop down and
turn on a TV.
</P>
<P>
   The best and easiest way to enter the transcendental realm is to
ask someone who loves opera to open the door and switch on the
lights for you. (If you happen to be in love with that person, the
process will be a cakewalk. Remember, ``If music be the language of
love, play on.'')
</P>
<P>
   For young people who are fortunate enough to live in the age of
supertitles and in the San Francisco Bay area, there is a totally
painless (and pretty cool) way to begin to explore opera. Thanks to
the San Francisco Opera Guild, the Opera Center and the opera's
education director, Ernest Garcia, about 37,000 students from
grades 3 through 12 are introduced to opera each year.
</P>
<P>
   Programs range from Interactive Opera, in which grade school
kids create their own opera with the help of a professional singer,
to High School Night, where teen-agers doll up and attend a full,
final dress rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   One recent night, some 1,700 high school kids filled the Opera
House's grand tier and dress circle. At least three wore rhinestone
tiaras and one his father's tux. For more than three hours they
watched Puccini's action-packed story of a Chinese princess named
``Turandot.''
</P>
<P>
   More accustomed to the sounds of Sublime and Third Eye Blind,
the students applauded in all the right places _ including the
moment when the hero melts the angry ice princess with a kiss _ and
cheered like opera vets when the final glorious notes sounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent my career in arts education, and what I saw the
other night was the most massive conversion I've ever seen,'' said
Susan Stauter, the artistic director for high schools in the San
Francisco Unified School District. ``The phone has not stopped
ringing and kids keep coming up to teachers in the halls saying, `I
didn't know I liked the opera!' It was an epiphanous evening.''
</P>
<P>
   Stauter said teen-agers were ``still discussing `Turandot' in
intense terms'' as the week wound down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They related to all of it,'' she said. ``They understand the
importance of a first kiss, they liked that he (Richard Margison)
got the girl (Gabriele Schnaut). And little Liu (Svetla Vassileva)
_ they related on a very emotional level to her.
</P>
<P>
   One boy said, `Hey, this is a multicultural experience.' He got
that this was an Italian opera about China'' _ with Germans,
Canadians, Italians, Russians and Americans singing.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Stauter said, the students are clamoring to learn more
about Puccini, production designer David Hockney's art _ and opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been on a natural high for days now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Massive conversion? A natural high? The profundity of a first
kiss? Didn't I tell you opera is like religion, drugs and love? As
for sports, I don't want to gloat but, the night those 1,700 teens
were getting lost in ``Turandot,'' guess what Mark McGwire was
doing in St. Louis?
</P>
<P>
   So, kids. Welcome to the insane asylum. You're gonna love this
ward.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
