<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans a three-page package of stories on
Clinton and the fallout from the Starr report now in the hands of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Lede on Capitol Hill action,
including Rep. Hyde's possible push for a wider inquiry and
continued partisan fighting over rules for the way the Judiciary
Committee will proceed. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONSTITUENTS (Washington) _ What lawmakers heard while
they were back home for the weekend. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-REPORT-SCENE (Washington) _ What is going on inside the
room where Members and aides review the boxes and boxes of
information given Congress with the Starr report. By Francis X.
Clines.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DEFENSE (Washington) _ The White House continues to pull
together a defense strategy. By David Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Developments on Clinton from the
independent counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLICY (Washington) _ A look at the effect of the Starr
report crisis on the policy agenda. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PERJURY (Washington) _ Why can't the president say he
didn't tell the truth to the grand jury? Is it ego, pride, or fear
of legal consequences that keeps him from changing the story almost
nobody believes about how he had oral sex with Monica? By James
Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CLINTON (New York) _ How the president is received in his
visit to New York today for addresses to the Council on Foreign
Relations and a fundraiser tonight. By N.R. Kleinfield.
</P>
<P>
   Eds, see also CLINTON-ECON, under Financial, and NY-ELECT, under
National-General.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ECON (New York) _ President Clinton on Monday called for
a meeting of the finance ministers and central bankers from the G7
and key emerging economies to discuss the spreading global economic
crisis. Urging top economies to boost growth, Clinton also
instructed Treasury Secretary Rubin and Fed Chairman Greenspan to
convene a meeting within 30 days on global financial institutions.
By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:30 p.m., the industrial average was up
219 points. Overseas, prices increased 2.2 percent in Tokyo and 1.1
percent in Hong Kong. They gained 2.9 percent in Frankfurt and 2
percent in London. On the American debt market, the long bond was
down 10/32 point at midday, with the yield at 5.25 percent. By
Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   With a separate:
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   TELLABS-CIENA (New York) _ Not unexpectedly, Tellabs cancels its
agreement to acquire Ciena, whose stock has dropped more than 80
percent from its July high. Ciena's shares fall 16 percent;
Tellabs' stock rises. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   GM-SMITH (Detroit) _ General Motors' Smith calls for lower
interest rates and says Asia and Latin America continue to bite. By
Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   ALLIED-AMP (New York) _ Allied Signal says AMP holders owning 72
percent of the stock have agreed to sell their shares to Allied
Signal. It now will buy as many as 40 million AMP shares, an amount
that would fall short of triggering an AMP anti-takeover provision.
By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   KAZAKHSTAN-OIL (Almaty, Kazakhstan) _ An American and a Japanese
company sign oil deals with Kazakhstan amounting to $4 billion, the
biggest deal cemented since the tide of capital flight from the
former Soviet Union began. By Steve LeVine.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   We are also monitoring for a possible verdict in the Archer
Daniels Midland price-fixing case.
</P>
