<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUZZ15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forgiveness ``too late'' for Clinton?
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As graphic details of President Clinton's indiscretions became
public Sept. 11, his supporters and detractors found themselves
joined in disappointment over what they were learning.
</P>
<P>
   Some tried to forgive, but for others it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our responsibility as Christians is to restore him as soon as
possible,'' said Rev. Reuben Jackson of the Mount Carmel Missionary
Baptist Church in Jupiter. ``This is a terrible thing, but then sin
is a terrible thing. We look at him as a president, but we also
must look at him as a human being. We must forgive.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Leonid Feldman of Temple Emanu-El in Palm Beach believes
the nation must repent as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sickened by the stickers that said, `It's the Economy,
Stupid,' '' he said, referring to Clinton's 1992 campaign platform.
``We have all sinned because we have lost our values. We chose a
president we knew was a liar and not a moral man. In Judaism we
definitely believe in forgiveness. But we all need to be forgiven.
We need to be concerned about much more than the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   At Howley's restaurant in West Palm Beach, Anna McIntosh is a
ranking member of the retirees' breakfast club that has met there
for nearly two decades, attempting to solve the world's problems.
The consensus at Howley's rear table is that Clinton should go.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had any guts, he'd retire,'' McIntosh said. ``How can we
believe him about anything anymore? I think what's disappointing is
that people don't seem to care about morals any more as long as
they're making money.''
</P>
<P>
   At Rooney's Public House on Clematis Street in West Palm Beach,
bartender Mike Griffin, born in County Mayo, uses a measure of
Irish wisdom to sort through the turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say that to confess a fault freely is the next thing to
being innocent of it,'' Griffin said. ``He has not done that. He
has not been fo
</P>
</TEXT>
