<P>
   THE CLINTON CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ NEW YORK _ President Clinton today addresses the two
main threats to his presidency. In a speech on the world financial
crisis to the Council on Foreign Relations, he will try to show
that he remains a respected world leader. During the rest of his
day, at a series of Democratic fund-raising events, he'll work on
shoring up his political support among his allies. (Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Clinton fund-raiser remarks scheduled to end at about 7
p.m. and 11 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-WOMEN _ WASHINGTON _ After the Starr report's narration
about President Clinton's treatment of women, why are many women
still in his corner? (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LATAM _ MIAMI _ Sure, lurid details of President
Clinton's alleged sexual exploits have riveted much of the world
this past week. But no one can amuse _ or bemuse _ the masses like
Latin American presidents when it comes to affairs of the heart.
Argentine President Carlos Menem once locked his wife out of the
presidential palace. Peru's Alberto Fujimori once locked his in.
(Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by noon EDT in both the (i) International and (w)
Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MILLER _ ATLANTA _ Georgia Gov. Zell Miller, a friend of
the president's, is the latest ally to take Clinton to task,
although he stops short of recommending what action should result
from his actions. Clinton has shattered his credibility, Miller
said, ``and I don't know how a president operates with his
credibility in ruins.'' (Saporta, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-G8 _ LONDON _ The Group of seven (plus one) industrial
nations is meeting in London on Monday to discuss the dire
condition of the world's economy; namely what to do about Russia;
and clouds gathering over Latin America. (Roughton, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 4 p.m. EDT in both the (i) International and (f)
Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SENIOR-CARE _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate Special Aging Committee
holds a hearing titled, ``Crooks Caring for Seniors: the Case for
Criminal Background Checks.'' (Monroe, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   WALLACE-Q&AMP;A _ Interview on George Wallace's legacy with Dan T.
Carter, author of ``The Politics of Rage: George Wallace, the
Origins of the New Conservatism and the Transformation of American
Politics.'' (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   WALLACE-BAXTER-COLUMN _ Commentary on a Herculean figure in
Alabama politics, for good or ill. (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH _ ANDREWS, N.C. _ Authorities still searching for
Birmingham clinic bombing suspect Eric Robert Rudolph plan to
display the types of food and supplies they believe he has used to
survive in rugged mountains. FBI spokesman Craig Dahle said a news
conference is scheduled today in Andrews to display the materials.
(Scruggs, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINORTY-ENROLLMENT _ The University of Texas plans to release
its official fall enrollment figures today, which are expected to
show an uptick in minority enrollments over last year. We'll
include official figures from other Texas universities, however,
because A&AMP;M started later, that school's data won't be available
until later this week. (Roser, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   FALL-LEAVES _ The dry weather is good for some things. Fall leaf
color will be exceptional in the Southeast mountains this year, say
experts, or the best in 10 years. (Harmon, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GA-PRISONS _ ATLANTA _ Again, the private company planning to
open Georgia's first private prison is scheduled to start taking
inmates on Tuesday, Sept. 15. (Cook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TIMELEAP _ AUSTIN, Texas _ University of Texas astronomers want
you to know exactly why time will linger for a second _ but only
for a second _ on the last second of 1998. It galls these
scientists whenever they hear or read that the standstill is
necessary to compensate for tidal forces that are slowing down the
Earth's rotation. (Stanley, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
