<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3976 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-AMERICANIZATIO     09-14 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-AMERICANIZATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. COMPANIES COULD DO MORE TO PROMOTE MIDEAST PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELAINE RUTH FLETCHER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli youths watch more MTV than any other group
of teen-agers in the world. McDonald's has opened 56 outlets in the
country, with more on the way. Superstores like Toys R Us, Ace
Hardware and Tower Records are swallowing up orange groves and
kibbutzim that were once the visual trademarks of the young state.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the Mediterranean climate, more and more Israeli
execs are aping the dress habits and work styles of the American
corporate world _ forgoing the traditional afternoon siestas and
demanding that shirt-sleeved employees don business suits.
</P>
<P>
   The signs of Israel's rapid Americanization stand in sharp
contrast to the images shown on television news _ Jewish settlers
rampaging through the Arab markets of Hebron and black-coated
ultra-Orthodox politicians passing judgment in religious-secular
disputes. For many Israelis, the new American corporate presence is
a welcome symbol of Israel's own aspirations to achieve the
American dream of individual freedom, material success, economic
efficiency and political stability.
</P>
<P>
   Still, how deeply rooted is this cultural transformation? Will
Israel's increased Americanization also lead to a more democratic,
pluralistic and tolerant society? And what values are young
Israelis digesting with their MTV and Big Macs?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, many of the cultural messages aren't the most
positive ones _ and often the media or corporate outlets themselves
portray only a part of what America is supposed to represent.
</P>
<P>
   Take MTV. For many young Israelis, this is the ultimate symbol
of America today, a youthful, free and sexually daring society.
America's MTV society is also multicultural and multiracial. Since
the multicultural images portrayed on the channel today are
generally African, Hispanic and Asian, MTV-style tolerance doesn't
have much impact on its young Israeli viewers, for whom the issue
is Jewish-Arab relations, says Sam Lehman-Wilzig, an
American-Israeli media expert from Bar Ilan University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israelis have a tendency to distinguish between
multiculturalism around the world, which they understand in
abstract terms, and the Arab-Israeli conflict, which they see as a
security conflict _ a different kettle of fish,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Lehman-Wilzig adds, there is growing evidence that young
Israelis _ exposed to heavy doses of American films, sitcoms and
videos _ are more self-centered, more prone to alcohol or drug use
and more likely to resort to violence than previous generations of
Israelis _ even though the strength of the Israeli family tends to
mitigate the negative impacts.
</P>
<P>
   Or take another American issue, environmentalism. In the United
States, even corporations like McDonald's, which symbolizes the
throwaway culture, have been belatedly pressed into the campaign to
preserve the planet, creating extensive recycling and environmental
awareness campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, however, while a whopping 56 restaurants have opened
here in just five years, the chain is mum on such topics. It's not
surprising. The introduction of American fast-food chains has
helped spur the transformation of Israel from a conservationist
society _ where everyone went grocery shopping with reusable bags _
into a throwaway culture of plastic and disposables. Israelis today
generate more household waste per capita than any other country
except the United States and Canada _ and they recycle almost
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Most worrisome for Americans, scarce water supplies are being
poisoned with waste from dumps built using technologies from the
1950s _ a factor that is sure to exacerbate tensions between Israel
and its Arab neighbors over control of the region's water sources.
</P>
<P>
   Against this cultural Americanization of Israel, there is the
countervailing influence of the Orthodox and ultra-Orthodox groups,
who today represent 20 to 30 percent of Israel's population _ and
whose numbers are growing. They are the Israelis who often don't
even own a television, and who may not be able to afford to
purchase American-style hamburgers _ or who refuse to do so,
because they may not be kosher.
</P>
<P>
   Many study in yeshivas, and ape the dress styles of Jews of the
18th century. Their kids sing folk songs, Middle Eastern music or
Klezmer tunes _ and know nothing of MTV. Increasingly, in Israel's
westward-looking culture, these Orthodox groups are seen as the
country's last repositories of cultural authenticity and social
solidarity _ even if the culture they represent is intolerant,
insular and increasingly anti-democratic. Americans who are deeply
concerned about making peace between Jews and Palestinians, and
promoting democracy in countries like Israel, need to ask what kind
of values they are exporting to a rapidly changing Israeli society.
</P>
<P>
   Israel, like its Arab neighbors, is in the throes of a cultural
struggle between traditionalism and modernity. It is a struggle
between religious fundamentalism and intellectual liberalism, a
struggle between a Western emphasis on individualism and a more
Eastern sense of social solidarity. The outcome of the cultural
struggle will have a profound impact on the direction of Israeli
society _ and ultimately on the regional peace process.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Western, i.e. American, culture is represented
overwhelmingly in terms of its gross commercialism and
media-sponsored hedonism, then the moral high ground in Israeli
terms will reside with the ultra-Orthodox and the religious
nationalists. Western culture, meanwhile, will increasingly be
reduced to the slogans and easy icons of the food, clothes and
music products that youths here so readily consume. Neither
prospect seems to bode well for the future of a country in which so
much American prestige and political clout are invested.
</P>
<P>
   American corporations that are becoming increasingly active in
Israel should do more to promote values on which everyone can agree
_ cultural tolerance, environmentalism and democracy, or even
employee exercise and health.
</P>
<P>
   Such corporate initiatives are still so rare here that they are
sure to generate broad publicity for any company involved. One good
example is the photo campaign conducted last year by the Italian
housewares and apparel company, United Colors of Benetton. Benetton
sent internationally renowned photographer Oliviero Toscani to
Israel, the West Bank and Gaza to photograph examples of
cooperation, communication and fellowship between Israelis and
Palestinians. The campaign's attempt to portray moments of positive
contact between Jews and Arabs was followed here with great
interest, debate and curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that when American companies move into a
country like Israel, they are not just marketing their products,
but American culture as a whole. When corporations promote, even in
a cautious way, values like tolerance, democracy or environmental
awareness, they have done a great deal.
</P>
<P>
   If MTV, which plans to sponsor an hour a day of local
MTV-Israel, opts to air video clips of Arab singers, or mixed
Jewish-Arab performing groups, it'll have a major long-term impact
on the prospects for peace in the region _ more so than any
presidential peace initiative, or Middle East shuttle mission.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask any Israeli teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Elaine Ruth Fletcher is the Jerusalem correspondent for the San
Francisco Examiner).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
