<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3993 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN16-COX     09-14 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOW I SPENT MY BALTIC VACATION: A little bit of home half a
world away
 &HT;    Eds: Last in a series of reports from Russia and the Baltics.
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If you suffer from spinal column and joint, peripheral nervous
and digestive systems, coronary heart and gynecological diseases,
you will be successfully treated here.'' _ Brochure promoting the
healing mineral waters and mud baths of Druskininkai, Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
   DRUSKININKAI _ It's been that way for more than 200 years, so
who am I to say otherwise?
</P>
<P>
   Heaven knows I feel better just being here. For a fact I feel
right at home.
</P>
<P>
   Druskininkai, located 75 miles southwest of Lithuania's capital
city of Vilnius, is a community surrounded by pine forests, lakes
and rivers, same as my little hometown of Lufkin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   They even barbecue, though with birch instead of hickory or
mesquite.
</P>
<P>
   Big improvement over Lufkin: No traffic is allowed for blocks in
every direction at the center of the town.
</P>
<P>
   My kind of place. My kind of folks.
</P>
<P>
   Not that we can understand a word the other is saying.
</P>
<P>
   English isn't spoken here, other than ``yes'' or ``no.'' Mostly
no.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to check into the hotel, I asked if they took Visa.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' the desk clerk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Express?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How about 100 dollar bills?'' I said with a wink and a grin.
</P>
<P>
   He winked back. ``No,'' he said, grinning.
</P>
<P>
   That's when I knew I was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But not for long. I managed to find a bank that would accept
American money in exchange for their two-bit Lithuanian litas,
valued at four to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not complaining. Prices are cheap. In the Baltic's major
cities, I'd been paying at least $100 a night for a hotel room.
Here it's half of that for a suite with full kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when I tried to tip a waitress five litas, she refused.
Too much, she indicated.
</P>
<P>
   That's mainly how we communicate, by indicating.
</P>
<P>
   I even have trouble ordering a meal. What I do is take whatever
they offer. Maybe it's better that way, not knowing. I know for a
fact that a favorite dish is fried pig's ear.
</P>
<P>
   On this particular day I stopped at a grocery store for a loaf
of bread, a hunk of cheese and a bottle containing some of their
healing water. This particular brand, Alus Darykla, has been brewed
hereabouts since 1902. ``5.4 percent alk.,'' the label said. Just
about right, I'd say.
</P>
<P>
   The bread was black and of sufficient density to anchor a small
rowboat. The yellow cheese was tasty enough. At least I thought so.
</P>
<P>
   I offered a piece to a passing dog. The dog passed on it.
</P>
<P>
   I further studied the label on the cheese. I wondered what the
Lithuanian word for ``cheese'' is. I wondered what the Lithuanian
word for ``candlewax'' is.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. The sun was warm, the air was cool. I'd parked myself
on a park bench next to Druskininkai's Orthodox church, a wooden
structure built in 1865, painted a bright blue and trimmed in
white, and glorious with its crown of onion domes.
</P>
<P>
   A believer stopped outside the door to make the sign of the
cross three times, each time bowing from the waist and touching the
earth with her fingers. It touched my heart.
</P>
<P>
   The older ladies passed. I smiled and tipped my cap. They
returned my smile.
</P>
<P>
   The younger ladies passed. I smiled and tipped my cap. They
quickened their pace.
</P>
<P>
   When I left, I left the remaining food and drink behind, a gift
for man or bird or beast.
</P>
<P>
   My kind of place. My kind of folks.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
