<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4004 &Cx1f; sci-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-     09-14 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-TIMES-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service plans the following
 &UR; ScienceTimes &LR;  stories for papers of Tuesday, Sept. 15:
</P>
<P>
   Photos, where indicated, are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphics, to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   Some ScienceTimes stories are available to international clients
only by special arrangement, and are so marked. Asian and European
points: contact Karl Horwitz in Paris for details and prices
(Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX: 47-42-80-44). Latin American points:
contact Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX:
310-996-0089).
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MULLIS-DNA (Undated) _ Kary Mullis won the Nobel Prize for
his inventions known as the polymerase chain reaction or PCR, used
for amplifying chosen sections of DNA. It has quickly become an
essential tool for biologists, DNA forensics labs, and almost
anyone else who needs to study the genetic material. But science
has been just one of the keen interests in Mullis's life, competing
with psychedelic drugs and women. Nowadays he is pursuing his
writing and venting his contempt for corrupt science in his highly
unorthodox ways. By Nicholas Wade. (2200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NURSE-STUDY (Undated) _ More than 20 years ago, a doctor
curious about the effects of long-term oral contraceptive use sent
questionnaires to 370,000 registered nurses. The answers he and
colleagues have since received have turned into the largest and
longest study ever of a group of women. This massive scientific
effort has only begun to pay dividends. With many of the original
participants now entering their 60s and 70s, the study promises to
bequeath an even greater wealth of knowledge, much of it otherwise
unattainable, about how a lifetime of choices in food, drink,
exercise and medications can translate into protection from or
increased risk of deadly and debilitating diseases. By Carol Kaesuk
Yoon. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NASA-SMALL (Undated) _ NASA has been shifting focus away
from costly, large satellites and space probes, touting a number of
successes with smaller, less expensive craft that exemplify its new
``faster, better, cheaper'' philosophy of doing business. From its
highly successful Pathfinder mission, which left a small robot
rover crawling about Mars, to new probes heading for asteroids and
comets, and small satellites measuring tropical rainfall or
atmospheric gases on Earth, the space agency says it has ample
evidence the streamlined approach is working. By Warren E. Leary.
(1735 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-CHALLENGE (Undated) _ In response to the free-market
challenge of Bruce Venter, government scientists on the Human
Genome Project say they will finish mapping the human blueprint in
2003, two years earlier than planned. That would still be two years
behind Venter's target date of 2001, but the government scientists
say that by that time they will have, more accurately than their
rival, sequenced the gene-rich portions of the human genome. By
Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WEDDING-BUTTERFLIES (Undated) _ Basking in their first
moment of nuptial bliss, brides and grooms around the country are
exiting churches, showered not with rice or confetti, but
surrounded instead by the fluttering gossamer wings of hundreds of
butterflies. The releases are the latest fashion at weddings, and
are now even taking flight at memorial services, grand openings,
divorces and prison releases. But while some view the release of
butterflies as an uplifting celebration of natural beauty, many
others _ including conservationists, scientists and amateur
butterfly enthusiasts _ see it as a misguided practice that poses
serious risks to the wild butterfly population and compromises
scientists' ability to study phenomena like the annual migration of
the monarch butterfly. By Carol Kaesuk Yoon. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-THUNDERCLOUDS (Undated) _ A new Earth satellite, launched
last fall, captured a series of radar images of skyscraper-like
thunderclouds rising more than 11 miles into the atmosphere from
the center of Hurricane Bonnie on Aug. 22. So powerful were the
forces producing the clouds that they actually punched through the
upper boundary of the troposphere, the dense lower layer of the
atmosphere, by one to three miles. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STANDARD FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ On Studio 400, a $200 peripheral
from Pinnacle Systems of Sunnyvale, Calif., that enables people
with Pentium-class computers running Windows 95 or 98 to edit home
videos into movies that are actually worth watching. By Rob Fixmer.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ Short takes on science.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Science questions answered.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-WATCH (Undated) _ Short itmes on health.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEALTH PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ALTERNATIVE-MEDICINE-HEALTH (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ A conference
last month in Albuquerque highlighted the intersection of
traditional and alternative forms of treatment. In addition, more
than half the nation's medical schools now offer courses in
alternative medical practices, and patients are looking for
physicians familiar with complementary as well as mainstream
medicine. In the Southwest, the movement is especially strong. By
Catherine C. Robbins.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ While politicians and the media focus
on the sex scandal in the White House, the American public and its
leaders all but ignore a far more serious sex scandal _ the young
ages at which boys and girls now engage in sexual intercourse, more
often than not risking pregnancy and sexually transmitted diseases,
including infection with the virus that causes AIDS. By Jane E.
Brody. (1130 words) (``l'' code)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
</TEXT>
