<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LATAM-0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMPARED TO SCANDALS IN LATIN AMERICA, CLINTON'S SEEMS TAME
 &HT;    (EDs: With optional add beginning at 550 words.)
 &HT;    With CLINTON-0915.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Sure, lurid details of President Bill Clinton's alleged
sexual exploits have riveted the world this past week. But few can
amuse _ or bemuse _ the masses like Latin American presidents when
it comes to affairs of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Argentine President Carlos Menem once locked his wife out of the
presidential palace. Peru's President Alberto Fujimori once locked
his in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Presidents in Latin America have certainly had their share of
affairs,'' said Eduardo Gamarra, who heads the Latin American and
Caribbean Center at Florida International University. ``This kind
of thing is considered to be a badge of honor, not dishonor.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Latin American presidents like to be pictured with
wives and children, just like their U.S. counterparts, political
mistresses are part of the accepted political landscape.
</P>
<P>
   And first ladies are, in general, expected to be like children:
seen, and not heard.
</P>
<P>
   Latin presidents have faced scandals so lascivious that they
make the case involving former White House intern Monica Lewinsky
look like Clinton was merely late for a formal dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Take Fujimori, who separated from his wife of 20 years, Susana
Higuchi, in August 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Their bitter arguments became public in a most sensational
manner during the campaign leading up to the presidential election
of 1995, with Higuchi publicly accusing Fujimori of being corrupt
and of overlooking the needs of Peru's poor.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Fujimori even locked his charismatic wife into the
presidential palace for four days, during which time Higuchi leaned
out of a fourth-story window and shouted allegations against her
husband to tickled journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually she launched her own opposition party and sued her
husband for ``psychological violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Their divorce became final in 1995, but not before she told
reporters that he was lousy in bed.
</P>
<P>
   But afterwards, Fujimori's became even more popular with voters,
both men and women.
</P>
<P>
   In Argentina, a similar soap opera unfolded in 1990 when Menem _
often called the region's master of machismo _ ordered soldiers to
remove his wife of 30 years, Zulema, from the presidential palace
just a year after he was first elected.
</P>
<P>
   She was ejected from their residence after staunchly criticizing
her husband's social policies to anybody who'd listen.
</P>
<P>
   Argentine television later showed his wife and children being
turned away from the doors of the palace by security officers.
</P>
<P>
   Menem _ who's called himself ``a seducer, not a womanizer'' _
has not only been accused of chronic infidelity, but of corruption,
wife abuse, and of having ties to drug smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   During one particularly titillating press conference, Menem
declared that, contrary to Madonna's claims in Vanity Fair
magazine, he had not leered at her breasts during a dinner party.
</P>
<P>
   But he's su ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
