<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4069 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARBAGE-CAN-DESIGN-AR     09-14 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARBAGE-CAN-DESIGN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LITTLE CAN THAT COULD 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By PHIL PATTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the garbage can that got glamour. Since its introduction
two years ago, the Umbra company's Garbo can, in black, white and
translucent colors, has moved from a best seller at such humble
retailers as Linens and Things and Bed, Bath and Beyond to become a
celebrity of the design world. It has been celebrated in the
Italian design press from Domus to Interni, the Milan-based
magazine on whose current cover it appears, and this fall it will
get its own ads in Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a heady trip for a humble object of high-impact virgin
polypropylene that retails for $10 or $12. With nearly a million
copies of Garbo and its smaller sister Garbino sold, Umbra is
offering the cans in 17 new colors this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The name was important to the can's appeal. It was born in a
brainstorming session, said Paul Rowan, who founded and runs the
Buffalo, N.Y.-based Umbra with Les Mandelbaum. The name Toss was
tossed about. The ideas of romantic curves and Hollywood were
raised. Then a salesman, whose name no one remembers, pronounced
the word Garbo.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Karim Rashid, 38, who was born in Cairo, grew up in
Britain and the United States, studied in Italy and worked in
Canada, Garbo has an international following. Rashid calls his
style ``sensuous minimalism,'' and the lines of, say, the metal
salt and pepper shakers and candlesticks he designs for Nambe
suggest a similar fluidity.
</P>
<P>
   But Garbo's shape also grew from Rashid's scrupulous study of
the markets and methods of the waste-container business. When he
travels, he visits malls and grocery stores to see competing
products _ the less expensive, the more closely he looks. He visits
factories to makes himself an expert on the molding methods that
create Garbo.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Garbo's sensual shapes come less from any natural model
than from the methods of the factory floor. The shape began with
Pilot Fineliner drawings in Rashid's sketchbooks and progressed
through images rotated, spun and varied on the computer, where
Rashid does most of his work. The shapes are deceptively simple. A
circle is pulled up and out to form the walls. At the top, ``the
saddle, or butterfly cut, makes it look elliptical,'' Rashid said,
and provides a natural place for the ``negative space'' of handles.
``It's a play on geometry,'' he added. The rounded interior bottom
also makes for easier cleaning, a detail Rashid is proud of.
</P>
<P>
   Garbo is almost a cartoon of how to make an easy-to-mold shape.
It's a model of the means of its own manufacture _ of little
interest to the buyer who sees simply graceful forms but of much
interest to the guys at the factory _ and to Rowan. When he speaks
of Garbo, he exudes pride in its sales, but there was even more
satisfaction in his voice when he said, ``the productivity of the
tool is very high.''
</P>
<P>
   Rashid has one worry about Garbo: that its success will
overshadow his work in furniture (at Totem, a store in Manhattan's
Tribeca) and lighting. ``I'd hate to think it might be like a hit
song that ends up on VH1 15 years later,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Garbo was joined by the smaller Garbino after Umbra found that
Japanese and some European buyers considered the five-quart-plus
version too big. Now, Garbino outsells Garbo. Just arrived are
Garbanzo, a swing-top kitchen garbage can, and Garbowl, a fruit
bowl with lines similar to the original.
</P>
<P>
   But people like Garbo so much they use it for other purposes.
Umbra now describes it as an alternative storage medium. A worker
at Umbras Buffalo factory uses Garbos as horse feeders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen it used in Soho galleries as an umbrella stand,''
Rashid said. People put flowers in it. And customers find that
Garbino, with its round bottom full of ice, functions well as a
Champagne bucket.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
