<SLUG> BC-ZIP-CODES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTAL BOUNDARY CREATES GREAT DIVIDE BETWEEN NEARBY HAMLETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRYDEN, Texas _ As the crow flies, the eight people who live in
this West Texas hamlet are just 20 miles east of Sanderson, the
seat of Terrell County.
</P>
<P>
   But to mail a letter from Sanderson to Dryden, the letter would
travel 1,200 miles.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for this postal oddity lies in ZIP code boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Sanderson, population 1,012, is in the El Paso ZIP code zone, so
all mail dropped there goes west for processing.
</P>
<P>
   And because Dryden is in the San Antonio postal zone, all mail
from there heads east.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, a letter mailed from Sanderson _ ZIP code 79848 _ to
Dryden _ 78851 _ passes through El Paso, San Antonio and Del Rio
before it's delivered 20 miles from where it was posted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago, we could put something in the mail in Sanderson,
and it would reach Del Rio the next day. Now it takes five to seven
days for mail to get from Sanderson to Del Rio,'' said Marsha
Monroe, the Terrell County attorney.
</P>
<P>
   For locals, this postal equivalent to the Continental Divide is
overcome by ingenuity and persistence.
</P>
<P>
   Fax machines and Federal Express service are very popular in
Sanderson. And there also is the daily mail shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband ranches in that area. He doesn't leave town without
taking mail to Dryden,'' Monroe said. ``The lady who drives the
school bus also carries mail for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if nothing else is available, we call the courthouse or
the wool house looking for a rancher going east.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone from my office is going to Dryden, we call the bank
and the title company to see if they have any mail to take over,
and they do the same for us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the old Dryden Mercantile, which sells fossils, ram's heads,
beer and snacks and also houses the post office, a steady stream of
motorists arrives each morning, bearing mail heading east.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent day, Mike Hill and his 3-year-old cowpuncher son,
Hayden Claude Hill, rolled in shortly before noon with a land
payment bound for Houston, more than 350 miles east of Dryden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes six or eight days from Sanderson. From here it takes
two or three days,'' Hill said as he finished his paperwork on the
steering wheel of his truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mail issue is part of life here,'' Hill said. ``I've got a
ranch north of here. I come by five times a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Dudley Harrison, the executive of Terrell County, said he fought
for years to get postal authorities to restore the connection with
Dryden. But postal officials in El Paso and San Antonio said the
issue is beyond appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much mail are you talking about? Who in Sanderson writes
to Dryden?'' asked Manny Martinez, the network transportation
manager in El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be an 18-wheeler that went from San Antonio to
Sanderson when Sanderson was a booming town, but now that it's died
down to almost nothing _ a ghost town _ they discontinued that
route,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Gossage, a postal network specialist in San Antonio, said
he ultimately gave up the struggle to connect the two towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really bad for them. It's the county seat, and it's a
unique situation,'' he said. ``I did everything I could, but it was
not to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Gossage said, ZIP code boundaries have to fall
somewhere, and it was just Sanderson's bad luck that the West Texas
divide fell where it does.
</P>
<P>
   To make a special accommodation, he said, would require changing
routes and ZIP codes and wouldn't be cost-effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you gave me the power to fix it, I could do it, but it
would cost $20,000 a year and someone would gripe spending that on
14 letters a week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, it used to be worse. Until a couple of years
ago, all mail from Sanderson east was routed from El Paso to Dallas
to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Even under the current system, he said, a letter mailed from
Sanderson to Dryden should take only two days to arrive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
