<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-MANIA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NILE'S STYLES: EGYPT'S IMAGES PROVE ENDURING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - It has been 2,000 years since Egypt ceased to exist as
a world power, yet Egypt is all around us.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Mighty Isis.
</P>
<P>
   It is in our culture, in our movies, in our TV shows, in our
literature, in our pockets.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, take out a dollar bill and look at the back. What
do you see?
</P>
<P>
   A pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   Go to the nation's capital and what do you see? The Washington
Monument, which is modeled on an Egyptian obelisk.
</P>
<P>
   Watch Michael Jackson's 1992 video for ``Remember the Time'' and
you see the singer dressed up in the striped ``nemes'' headdress of
a Pharaoh sharing his first screen kiss with supermodel Iman.
</P>
<P>
   The Bangles told us to ``Walk Like an Egyptian.'' When we were
old enough to walk into a drugstore for protection, it was Ramses
that offered it to us. And when women want to get rid of unwanted
hair, they can use a depilatory product called Cleopatra's Secret.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's the Luxor hotel in Las Vegas or the pack of Camel
cigarettes, the images of ancient Egypt are all around us.
</P>
<P>
   There are DeMille-sized visions of slaves piling stone on stone
to make the pyramids; there is the autocrat Pharaoh, looking a lot
like Yul Brynner, his life slathered in gold; there is the
bandage-wrapped mummy, later a baleful Boris Karloff, a
pre-Christian version of the Resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   You hardly can have a big-budget futuristic sci-fi movie without
its Egyptian component. There is ``Stargate,'' ``The Fifth
Element,'' ``Raiders of the Lost Ark.'' They all have their ancient
priests and hidden tombs.
</P>
<P>
   It might be said that ancient Egypt holds the same place in
popular culture that ancient Greece holds in high culture.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, you've never seen a Three Stooges short that takes on
pre-Socratic philosophers. But every male in America can remember
1939's ``We Want Our Mummy,'' in which the three search for the
tomb of the midget King Rootin-Tootin.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, 1939 was a great year for cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Egypt has held its place in the popular imagination of the West
for 2,000 years. It began with ancient Rome, which built temples to
Egyptian gods.
</P>
<P>
   In the Middle Ages, they told stories about Israel and the
Pharaoh; in the Renaissance, they painted many canvases on the
theme of the ``flight into Egypt'' of the holy family fleeing the
wrath of Herod.
</P>
<P>
   The 19th century used Egypt _ as they used much of the ancient
world _ as an excuse to paint seductive dancing girls.
</P>
<P>
   And our own century is in some ways the ``century of Tut.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of our obsession with ancient Egypt rests on four ancient
personalities, four Egyptian symbols and two major discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest Egyptian craze began with Cleopatra, who had a
famous love affair _ or political alliance _ with Julius Caesar,
followed by a famous love affair _ or political alliance _ with
Mark Antony. There is so much fable in the stories that it is
impossible to extract simple fact from them.
</P>
<P>
   Cleopatra remained the center of Europe's Egypt of the
imagination for a very long time.
</P>
<P>
   In Geoffrey Chaucer's ``Legend of Good Women,'' Cleopatra has
the first place as the woman who sacrifices her life for love.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare has her in ``Antony and Cleopatra.'' Later writers
saw her less as victim and more as temptress. More recent writers
have her as feminist hero and savvy politician.
</P>
<P>
   There are literally hundreds of novels about Cleopatra written
in European languages, hundreds more paintings and dozens of films.
From Theda Bara to Rhonda Fleming to Liz Taylor, these vamps and
tramps have given us Cleos dressed up in their best Hollywood camp
and kitsch.
</P>
<P>
   The second important pillar of Egypt in the West is the Pharaoh
of Exodus. We cannot be sure which Pharaoh this might be, nor just
how much of the story in the Bible can be verified historically.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the part of Egypt that most fascinated Europe during
medieval times. Old Testament stories frequently are depicted in
the stained-glass windows of cathedrals.
</P>
<P>
   In the early part of the 19th century, painters loved the vast
sublimity of the seven plagues of Egypt, and there are paintings by
such luminaries as William Turner and such subluminaries as John
Martin, who actually makes Cecil B. DeMille look like a
miniaturist.
</P>
<P>
   There has always been a Hollywood-like underbelly in pop
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Turn to Cecil B. DeMille's ``Ten Commandments'' _ either the
silent of 1923 or the bloated Charlton Heston epic of 1956 _ to
make hash of history and chowder of the Bible. Look for Heston
wearing a wristwatch while standing on a rock.
</P>
<P>
   The third major figure is Tutankhamen, whose grave was
discovered in 1923. Tutmania swept America and Western Europe from
then until the Depression hit six years later. There were scarab
rings, Tut nickel cigars, hieroglyphic dresses and dining chairs
designed to look like Egyptian thrones. Babies were named Tutter
for boys and Tuttie for girls.
</P>
<P>
   Tutmania picked up again in 1976 after the blockbuster art
museum show called ``The Treasures of Tutankhamen'' toured the
country, leaving lines of people down the street outside every
museum it hit.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Martin performed his ``funky'' Tut parody on ``Saturday
Night Live'' and had a hit novelty number. ``Now if I'd known/
They'd line up just to see him,/ I'd taken all my money/ And bought
me a museum. King Tut.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth personality is that of the enigmatic king who
immediately preceded Tut, who is most widely known as Akhenaten.
Born Amenhotep IV _ or Amenophis _ the Pharaoh broke 1,500 years of
artistic and religious tradition and attempted to institute a
version of monotheism as state religion. He also changed his name.
</P>
<P>
   Akhenaten worshiped the solar disc instead of the dozens of
local and state deities of the past. As soon as he died, the old
gods were reinstated by Tutankhamen.
</P>
<P>
   Sigmund Freud wrote a book trying to prove that Moses influenced
the king. Michael Curtiz, director of ``Casablanca,'' in 1954 made
a film called ``The Egyptian,'' which glamorized that period in
Egyptian history.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, minimalist composer Philip Glass wrote an opera
titled ``Akhenaten,'' which is sung entirely in a synthetic
language imitating ancient Egyptian. Some would say it also was
written in a synthetic style imitating music, but that's beside the
point.
</P>
<P>
   The symbols that we have include:
</P>
<P>
   1. The pyramids and sphinx _ They survive everywhere in pop
culture. Arizona's Gov. George W. P. Hunt is buried under a pyramid
in Phoenix's Papago Park. You also can rent a room in the Luxor
hotel, the laser-tipped kitsch pyramid in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, there were people who believed that pyramids could
sharpen razor blades. It was called pyramid power, and some people
thought that home-appliance pyramids could replace refrigerators
for the preservation of meat.
</P>
<P>
   2. Mummies _ From Karloff to Abbott and Costello, mummies
inhabit our fright-flick subconscious, like zombies, only older and
well wrapped. When mummy shows turn up at museums, the line forms
to the right.
</P>
<P>
   Mummies also captivate us for being an ancient attempt at
understanding life after death.
</P>
<P>
   3. Hieroglyphs _ Ancient Egypt remains a noisy culture. There is
chatter written around almost every painted or carved figure in
Egyptian art. They tell us who we are looking at and even how we
are supposed to feel about them. The wiggle of a line of water, the
stare of a hieroglyphic eye and the stroke of a feather. They all
have meaning that we now can read and understand, making for the
feeling of a direct line of communication between us and 3,000
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   4. The Ankh _ The looping symbol of life was taken by the Coptic
Christians as their cross and it has survived down to our time as a
popular amulet. There are still many people who wear them around
their necks.
</P>
<P>
   As for the discoveries that fueled our obsession with Egypt, we
already have mentioned Howard Carter's opening of King Tut's tomb
in 1923.
</P>
<P>
   But even more important than that was expansion of Napoleon into
Egypt in 1798. He ultimately was defeated by the British navy, but
his expedition also took with him 167 scholars who got a serious
look at the antiquities of the Nile for the first time. They were
dumbfounded by what they saw.
</P>
<P>
   The most influential of these academics was the artist Domenique
Vivant Denon, who made sketches of the ruins, statues and
hieroglyphs that he saw. The book of his drawings is still in
print.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was treading the soil of a land covered since immemorial
times with a veil of mystery,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   When the drawings hit Europe, it set off the first great modern
Egyptian craze. English poet Robert Southey wrote, ``Everything
must now be Egyptian; the ladies wear crocodile ornaments, and one
must sit on sphinxes in a room hung with mummies and the long-nosed
hieroglyphical men who are enough to make children afraid to go to
bed.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the French finally opened the Suez Canal in 1869, it
was Giuseppe Verdi who provided the music, with his Grand Opera and
Kitschfest ``Aida.'' It provided the standard for Egyptian music at
least until the exotic dancer Little Egypt shook her booty in the
coochie-coochie dance at Chicago's World's Columbian Exposition in
1893.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure you all can remember her tune, often sung to the words
``Oh, they don't wear pants in the southern part of France.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Richard Nilsen is online. Send e-mail to him at
richard.nilsen(at)pni.com on the Web. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
