<SLUG> BC-HOYE-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOT IDEA: PCS THAT FIT OUR LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - You want the next ``killer app''?
</P>
<P>
   I got the next killer app . . . right here.
</P>
<P>
   It's an idea that's bumped around in my head for a few years.
But I think it's time has come.
</P>
<P>
   Killer app, as you may or may not know, refers to ``killer
application.'' Computer industry people use the phrase to refer to
something that helps drive the market.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if someone came out with a piece of software that
cleaned house and cooked dinner while you were at work, and
required a Pentium II-450 running Windows NT 5.0 and 128 megabytes
of RAM, that would be a killer app.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because millions of people would want the software, and, to
make it run, they'd have to upgrade their machines accordingly,
thus driving the market.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not my idea.
</P>
<P>
   My idea resurfaced the other day as I sat in a small room with
my 4-year-old son, Patrick, waiting for the World's Greatest
Pediatrician (a k a Dr. Schwartz) to examine Patrick's sore foot,
the latter a result of an ill-advised climb up a pantry shelf in
search of a Fruit Roll-Up.
</P>
<P>
   As I gazed around the examining room, and tried to interest
Patrick in the cowboy motif so he'd stop spinning around on the
doctor's stool, I couldn't help but notice a full-sized desktop
computer perched, somewhat precariously, on one end of the Formica
counter.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why doctors need access to computers. Everybody
does these days. Clearly, though, that machine was not built for
that spot.
</P>
<P>
   Now, this doesn't reflect badly on the doctor's office. You see
the same thing everywhere. There's basically one computer design in
this world, and we're stuck with it, no matter where, or under what
conditions, we need such a machine.
</P>
<P>
   Look around. Ever watch an automobile mechanic, his hands all
greasy, try to type in your credit card number on the repair shop's
computer? Ever try to fit a PC on a child's desk in his bedroom?
Ever wish you could fit a computer on the kitchen counter so you
could watch the kids do their homework or so you could use one of
those recipe programs?
</P>
<P>
   Why can't somebody make computers that fit?
</P>
<P>
   OK. So here's my idea: It's called the home server. You sell
people a powerful PC. They plunk it down in the den. Then, they use
it to run an assortment of computer appliances spread all over the
house.
</P>
<P>
   In the kitchen, you could have a small countertop terminal built
with washable plastic, like toasters and blenders. In the kid's
room, you could have a terminal that not only fits on a desk, but
looks like an elephant or a space ship. In the garage, you could
have a touch-screen terminal so your dirty hands don't gunk up a
keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   You could take the idea and use it in small offices, giving
professionals the access to the computing power they need without
the trouble of dealing with the computer itself.
</P>
<P>
   The examples could go on and on.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, all this is possible today. And I think it would
make a heck of a killer app.
</P>
<P>
   Now don't go writing me nasty e-mails, telling me this is just a
rehash of somebody's ``house of the future'' concept. I've heard
all that. And I've seen the software that allows people to automate
their homes using computers.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not really talking about that.
</P>
<P>
   My idea is, simply, to give people computers that fit into their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it: Desktop PCs now have more power than any of us
really need. Why not put them to work running a small network in
your home?
</P>
<P>
   All we need is for some computermaker to get on the stick, as it
were.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it's time for a non-computer company to get into the
game. Black &AMP; Decker? Hamilton Beach? Whirlpool? Hello? You guys
listening?
</P>
<P>
   Make us some computer appliances that can hook up to a PC (or a
Macintosh) in the home! Sell them at Target or Kmart. Include two
or three, along with cables and software, in a ``home server kit.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago at the COMDEX computer trade show, I asked
Eckhard Pfeiffer about all this. He's the CEO at Compaq, one of the
world's largest computer manufacturing companies.
</P>
<P>
   It was a pleasant interview, conducted in midtrot, as Pfeiffer
and his support staff ran between buildings at the Las Vegas
Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   I don't remember exactly how I phrased it, but I asked Pfeiffer
why companies like Compaq couldn't make computers that better fit
our lives.
</P>
<P>
   He looked over his shoulder at me and said, ``We're working on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   At least I think that's what he said. He speaks with an accent,
you know. He might actually have said, ``I'd like a bratwurst.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I think the home server/computer appliance idea is a
concept whose time has come. Maybe not next week, but certainly
before that big desktop machine falls and gives Dr. Schwartz a sore
foot. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye is an online editor and covers computer- and
Internet-related issues for Arizona Central, the Web site of The
Arizona Republic. He can be reached at dhoye(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
