<SLUG> BC-SILICON-VALLEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY PREDICTS TOUGH TIMES FOR SILICON VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Silicon Valley's economy could crash like a
burned-out computer system, falling into recession by next year
from the effects of the 14-month-old Asian fiscal crisis, according
to a study by the Santa Monica-based Milken Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The study, ``The Asian Crisis Tsunami,'' says that San Jose will
be hit hardest of any metropolitan area in California. ``Real
personal income growth in the San Jose metropolitan area will be
zero next year. In a pessimistic scenario, it will decline by 1.5
percent in 1999 and 1.7 percent in 2000,'' said a consensus
scenario sketched out in the report, which was released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the slump, according to the study by the
7-year-old nonprofit think-tank headed by former junk-bond king
Michael Milken, is Silicon Valley's reliance on high-technology
exports to Asia. Cash-strapped Asian economies, battered by
currency devaluations, do not have the money to buy the high-tech
gear, according to the 48-page report.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Milken report, about 75 percent of California's
total exports to Asia in 1997 were high-tech, including a
breathtaking 95.7 percent of exports from San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   The report draws on statistics and studies by sources such as
the California Trade and Commerce Agency, the International
Monetary Fund, the World Bank and the U.S. Department of Commerce.
It was written by Ross C. DeVol, the Milken Institute's director of
regional studies.
</P>
<P>
   DeVol, who joined the Milken Institute in January, is former
senior vice president of regional economics for Wharton
Econometrics Forecasting Associates in Philadelphia, where he
covered the California economy.
</P>
<P>
   DeVol said in a telephone interview that he was surprised by the
extent of the state's reliance on exports to Asia. ``When I started
it, I didn't realize how important Asia is, particularly to the Bay
Area,'' he said, ``especially San Jose, where 25 percent of
personal income is linked to exports to Asia, the highest
percentage in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The Milken report encompasses three possible scenarios _
``optimistic,'' ``consensus'' and ``pessimistic'' _ outlining
intensifying degrees of pain to California's economy. DeVol said
the consensus or pessimistic scenarios were most likely. In the
pessimistic scenario, China devalues its currency, the yuan, and
471,000 California jobs could be lost.
</P>
<P>
   The report notes that in the second quarter of this year,
exports of California manufactured goods to Japan fell 18 percent
from the same period in 1997, with exports to South Korea falling
38.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment, tourism, real estate and foreign investment are
all being hurt, according to the report, but the most vulnerable is
high-tech: electronic and electrical supplies, industrial machinery
and computers, transportation equipment, and instruments and
related projects.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Selfridge, senior vice president for international banking
at the Santa Clara-based Silicon Valley Bank, said the broad
outlines of the report conformed to what his bank was seeing with
its clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan and South Korea particularly are major markets for this
area,'' Selfridge said. Fallout from the crisis in Asia, he added,
``is already working its way into the semiconductor industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Although California's trade with North American Free Trade
Association partners Canada and Mexico is robust, DeVol cautioned
that it might not be that way for long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada is a major exporter of commodities,'' he said, ``and
commodity prices are falling because of the Asia crisis. Mexico is
the object of attention from speculators, driving down the value of
the peso vis-a-vis the U.S. dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   DeVol said that increased trade with Europe could provide a
partial answer to troubles in Asia and Latin America. ``They are
far behind us in high-tech,'' DeVol said of Europe, ``and they want
to acquire our technology. Europe is the largest major market
that's growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Selfridge agreed, observing that ``Europe has been a vital trade
partner for technology. High-tech exports to Europe grew 16 percent
_ by $1.2 billion _ in the first six months of 1998. But Asia
slumped 12 percent _ $3.7 billion _ at the same time. So it doesn't
quite offset the drop we've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   DeVol said state and local governments could be hurt by
declining trade, too, since tax revenue forecasts are drawn from
expectations of bullish growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to take a close look at those tax revenues,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
