(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Jimmy
Johnson at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
CARMEN-OPERA (Los Angeles) _ In L.A. Opera's new production of
``Carmen,'' mezzo-soprano Jennifer Larmore proves she has the
deep-burgundy vocal coloring and the acting chops required of
Bizet's beloved tragic heroine. By Reed Johnson. 
. 
BARRYMORE-STAGE (Los Angeles) _ There's a touch of sheer,
anachronistic pleasure in watching actor Christopher Plummer's
marvelously reckless bad-boy portrayal of fellow actor and
legendary lush John ``Jack'' Barrymore at the Ahmanson Theatre. By
Reed Johnson. 
. 
THREE-PENNY (Los Angeles) _ When one of his henchmen says to
Macheath in ``The Threepenny Opera'' that something was nice, Mack
the Knife corrects him. ``That wasn't nice, clown. That was art,''
Mackie says turning to the audience with a leer to deliver the
punch line. By Rob Lowman. 
. 
YOYO-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ Imagine you're a music student and
somebody tells you your assignment is to create an orchestral piece
about, oh, the Mother of God. Yo-Yo Ma laughs when he thinks about
the challenge that faced composer John Taverner when he sat down to
write ``The Protecting Veil,'' a richly spiritual work for
orchestra and cello that Ma will perform Tuesday at the Hollywood
Bowl. By Reed Johnson. 
. 
ROSEANNE-TV (Los Angeles) _ Forty pounds lighter, in tailored suits
with a chi chi hairdo, Roseanne, the Domestic Goddess, is giving
the syndicated daytime talk genre a try, and possibly Rosie a run
for her money. Among her first guests in the hourlong show (KNBC,
10 a.m.) is supposed to be Whoopi Goldberg. By Keith Marder. 
. 
. 
The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``l'' lifestyle news file. For questions, contact Jimmy Johnson
at the Daily News, (818) 713-3695. 
. 
ZAX-SAX (Los Angeles) _ It was the lead story on local television
stations that evening. Parents leave children alone for days.
Details at 11. Zachary Alessandro of Studio City was all of 2 years
old but old enough to comprehend the distraught faces that flashed
back at him from the tube. He walked into his bedroom, peeled a
pillowcase off a pillow and began filling the bag with his toys.
Thus, the idea for ``Zax Sax'' was born. By Heesun Wee. 
. 
