<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARRYMORE-STAGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUMMER POURS HIMSELF INTO `BARRYMORE' ROLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Like the proverbial ``office flirt'' and the
``honest politician,'' the ``debonair drunk'' has fallen on hard
times lately.
</P>
<P>
   For every Dean Martin suavely knocking back cocktails while
crooning ``Amore,'' there's a thousand obnoxious barroom bores who
never know when to shut up. Stylish inebriation is no longer
fashionable _ if indeed it ever was.
</P>
<P>
   So there's a touch of sheer, anachronistic pleasure in watching
actor Christopher Plummer's marvelously reckless bad-boy portrayal
of fellow actor and legendary lush John ``Jack'' Barrymore at the
Ahmanson Theatre. In fact, Plummer's Tony Award-winning performance
is so intoxicating, it drowns out the slightly stale, predictable
taste of William Luce's high-spirited play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barrymore'' is set in the last month of the actor's life,
which fizzled out prematurely in 1942 when he was 60. Luce's
premise is that the booze-addled yet still waspish Barrymore has
rented a New York theater, where he's making a halfhearted stab at
rehearsing ``Richard III'' with the help of an unseen prompter,
Frank (John Plumpis).
</P>
<P>
   By the 1940s, Jack was a broken parody of his handsome, majestic
younger self. But as Plummer inhabits him, he's also a brilliantly
engaging raconteur with a trunkful of lewd limericks and wittily
self-mocking ``thea-tuh'' anecdotes sandwiched between spot-on
impersonations of everyone from W.C. Fields and a foul-mouthed
parrot to Barrymore's famous siblings Ethel and Lionel.
</P>
<P>
   Boisterously orchestrated by director Gene Saks, the party
starts from the moment Jack lets out a devilish backstage cackle
and staggers out singing ``I Got a Gal in Kalamazoo.'' Naturally,
he's brought his trusty black bag of libations (to help him
``loosen up,'' you understand), which he dips deeper into as the
evening wears on and the emotional cracks bubble up in his
party-hearty facade.
</P>
<P>
   To Frank's mounting frustration, it's quickly obvious that Jack
is far more interested in reliving old pranks and settling old
scores with colleagues and ex-wives than in learning his lines.
Sure enough, for the next 1{ hours there's virtually no letup of
bawdy asides, painful reveries and the occasional tortured insights
that hit Jack like a sucker punch to the jaw.
</P>
<P>
   We've seen this structure many times before, in plays about
Truman Capote, Maria Callas, Ty Cobb and others: layers of juicy
gossip alternating with thick slabs of agonized confession. What's
more distracting is that several of Luce's narrative jump-cuts are
remarkably slipshod, and he pads the evening with too many cheap
laughs about New York cabdrivers and the like.
</P>
<P>
   But Plummer, like the seasoned pro he is, skates over these
bumps with unerring comic timing and hilarious vaudevillian
showmanship. He also demonstrates why he's one of the continent's
top classical actors: Despite all the blatant gag-dropping here,
Plummer's reactions are hauntingly subtle: a quaver that slithers
like a garden snake across his magnificent baritone, a look of
panic that freezes his features like a man glimpsing his own ghost.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Frank feeding him lines from the wings, Plummer's
Barrymore is his own best straight man. ``I don't have to tell you
that divorces cost more than marriages _ but, goddamit, they're
worth it!'' he bellows at one point.
</P>
<P>
   If Luce's structure were as brilliant as his one-liners,
``Barrymore'' might be a small masterpiece. As it is, it's a
uniquely memorable evening with an unforgettable drinking buddy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1641EDT &QL; 
