A4294 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZAX-SAX-LADN     09-14 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZAX-SAX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODDLER PHILANTHROPIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEESUN WEE 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; It was the lead story on local television
stations that evening. Parents leave children alone for days.
Details at 11.
</P>
<P>
   Zachary Alessandro of Studio City was all of 2 years old. But he
was old enough to comprehend the distraught faces that flashed back
at him from the tube. Sadness, he concluded.
</P>
<P>
   He walked into his bedroom, peeled a pillowcase off a pillow and
began filling the bag with his toys.
</P>
<P>
   His parents smiled. How cute, they thought. They let the
situation pass. Zachary would forget about the troubled children,
they thought. He was, after all, only 2.
</P>
<P>
   But Zachary didn't forget. He wanted to give small sacks filled
with goodies to children like those on television. ``When are we
going to make the sacks?'' he asked occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Zachary's parents, who donate to various charities, are
compassionate. But they hesitated about pursuing their son's idea.
They worried his good deed might expose him at too early an age to
such real-world issues as delinquent parents.
</P>
<P>
   But Zachary kept pushing. And his parents finally relented.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for ``Zax Sax'' was born.
</P>
<P>
   A year after that fateful television news program, Zachary
opened a lemonade stand strategically located near neighborhood
garage sales to raise money to stock his Zax Sax.
</P>
<P>
   A relative pitched in $50, and soon he had raised about $120 to
buy fabric that his mom sewed into small bags, complete with
drawstrings and stuffing on one side of each bag for a makeshift
pillow. ``So they can take a nap,'' Zachary explained.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two years since he learned about the less-fortunate fates
of other children, he occasionally fills the homemade sacks himself
with toys Mom orders in bulk from catalogs. At the family's kitchen
table, he walks down his assembly line of crayons, trolls, rubber
snakes and sunglasses, dutifully depositing one of each in his
bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you stuff it up,'' he said, pulling the drawstring and
closing the bag. ``And put it in the box. Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past month, Zachary and his mom have delivered some
60 bags to the North Hollywood and Van Nuys divisions of the Los
Angeles Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I have ever had anyone this young be
involved in volunteer work,'' said Detective Harold Rhudy of the
Van Nuys Division, an officer for 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   Before Zax Sax came along, a visit to a local police division
went something like this for a child: Just saw Dad beat Mom. Police
came and handcuffed Dad. Now sitting in police station amid strange
adults who are busy processing paperwork. Tired. Scared. Nothing to
do.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Zax Sax are a welcome relief for officers and the
children who receive them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't get gifts quite often, and to be handed something,
especially when they're nervous and fearful, it breaks down many
barriers,'' said Detective Thomas Culotta of the North Hollywood
division.
</P>
<P>
   Zachary originally wanted to meet and hand his sacks in person
to children at police stations. But detectives said laws require
them to keep children's identities private.
</P>
<P>
   It still didn't dissuade Zachary from wanting to reach out and
help.
</P>
<P>
   His parents don't regret giving in to their young
philanthropist's wishes. The project has helped Zachary appreciate
how lucky he is compared to some other children, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows there are bad mommies and daddies that get
arrested,'' said Lorraine Alessandro, Zachary's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, who could say no to a child with such good intentions?
</P>
<P>
   ``I took out my toys, and I wanted to give them away, so we came
up with the idea,'' Zachary explained. The reason was simple:
``Because I've got a lot of toys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
