<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-THUNDERCLOUDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HURRICANE'S THUNDERCLOUDS GIVES RISE TO SKYSCRAPER IMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By WILLIAM K. STEVENS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new earth satellite, launched last fall, captured radar images
of skyscraper-like thunderclouds rising more than 11 miles into the
atmosphere from the center of Hurricane Bonnie on Aug. 22.
</P>
<P>
   So powerful were the forces producing the clouds that they
punched through the upper boundary of the troposphere, the dense
lower layer of the atmosphere, by one to three miles.
</P>
<P>
   The radar images, which are themselves invisible, were
artificially colored. In one image of Hurricane Bonnie, red was
used to indicate higher amounts of moisture. A circular white patch
under the spiky image of the thunderclouds described the surface
cloud layer of the hurricane as it moved northwestward over the
Atlantic Ocean toward the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The tallest spike of clouds reached 59,000 feet, about twice as
high as Mount Everest. Normally, tropical thunderstorms reach
30,000 to 40,000 feet, and 40,000 to 50,000 feet is not out of the
ordinary in the center of a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   But clouds as tall as those recorded here are rarely seen in
Atlantic hurricanes, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   When these images were captured, say scientists at the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration, Hurricane Bonnie was moving
very slowly, allowing it to suck up more moisture and energy from
the sea surface. Warm, moist air kept funneling upward, driving the
cloud tops ever higher.
</P>
<P>
   When the air reached higher altitudes, where it was colder, the
moisture condensed into raindrops, releasing latent heat into the
atmosphere. This infusion of energy, meteorologists believe,
strengthens a hurricane. And indeed, Hurricane Bonnie intensified
during the 24 hours after the images were obtained.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak, the hurricane was a moderately severe storm, rating
as a category 3 (with category 5 the strongest) on the
Saffir-Simpson scale of hurricane intensity.
</P>
<P>
   The radar images were made by instruments aboard the Tropical
Rainfall Measuring Mission, the world's first space-borne rainfall
observatory. A joint Japanese-American project, the satellite was
launched Nov. 27 from Japan as one of the first of a planned series
of new satellites to be launched over the next several years, aimed
at obtaining vast amounts of information about the earth-atmosphere
system.
</P>
<P>
   The mission satellite has flown over some 100 tropical cyclones,
giving scientists views unobtainable with instruments on the ground
or on airplanes, and possibly giving them new insights into
hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   But the greater value, experts say, may come from the
information it provides about tropical precipitation, which in turn
could help experts improve computerized weather predictions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1643EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
