A4299 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THREE-PENNY-LADN     09-14 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THREE-PENNY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THREEPENNY OPERA' HAS ITS CHARM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When one of his henchmen says to Macheath in ``The
Threepenny Opera'' that something was nice, Mack the Knife corrects
him. ``That wasn't nice, clown. That was art,'' Mackie says turning
to the audience with a leer to deliver the punch line. ``And art
isn't nice.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's the problem with the Bertolt Brecht-Kurt Weill
classic at UCLA's Freud Playhouse, part of the latest offering in
the Reprise! series of concert musicals, which is a counterpart to
the Encore! series in New York City. It's a little too nice.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that the production doesn't offer its
pleasures. In fact, that's what it does best. There are solid
renditions of Weill's familiar cabaret-style songs, some very good
performances and witty staging.
</P>
<P>
   So it may seem unfair to carp, considering that the series is
meant to be a showcase of neglected musicals and in essence bills
itself as a ``concert'' (actors often carry around notebooks to
refer to lines since there is usually only about a week of
rehearsals). But the play is staged, and the actors do more than
read their parts.
</P>
<P>
   This stripped-down approach has worked well with other shows in
the series, such as ``Promises, Promises'' or Finian's Rainbow,''
but ``The Threepenny Opera'' is a different beast than those
Broadway lambs.
</P>
<P>
   First produced in 1928 in Berlin, the musical was meant as a
commentary on the decadence, cynicism and corruption rife in an
economically unstable Germany under the shadow of Nazism. Brecht
was a communist, but the subversive ideology he put forth in
``Threepenny'' was more theatrical than Marxist. His intention was
to ``alienate'' audiences, wanting to wake them from their
comfortable roles as passive observers of entertainment, remind
them that they are watching a play and implicate them in crimes of
society.
</P>
<P>
   Based on John Gay's ``The Beggar's Opera,'' the musical is
filled with lowlifes of every sort. There are cutthroats, cheats,
con artists and corrupted officials, and Brecht wanted the audience
to know they were responsible. He even creates an artificial upbeat
ending, reminding people that they may like things neatly tied up
with a happy conclusion, but that rarely happens for most people.
</P>
<P>
   The Reprise! production of ``The Three Penny Opera'' is the 1953
translation by Marc Blitzstein that played on Broadway, and it's
this version that we are most familiar with. But it's probably time
to go beyond this, and there have been recent and only moderately
successful attempts to reinterpret the musical.
</P>
<P>
   This doesn't mean it has to go the Baz Luhrmann ``William
Shakespeare's Romeo and Juliet'' route, but the musical begs not to
be put in a time capsule. Perhaps an odd choice for the series,
nonetheless this bare-bones version almost presented an opportunity
to be subversive, to invoke the Brecht-Weill spirit.
</P>
<P>
   What was presented, though, was very professional. Those who are
fans of Weill's dark, almost atonal music won't be disappointed.
From Ken Page's (the Street Singer) wonderfully forceful opening
``The Ballad of Mack the Knife'' through Jonelle Allen's (Jenny)
dynamic ``Pirate Jenny'' to Carrie Hamilton and Marguerite
MacIntye's (Lucy and Polly) lively ``Jealousy Duet,'' the show's
singing is always engaging.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Cassidy is a live wire as Macheath, and his energy on
stage is infectious. The rest of the cast, including stage veteran
Theodore Bikel (Mr. J.J. Peachum) are quite good. And if you have
never seen ``The Threepenny Opera,'' you won't go wrong if you buy
a ticket. It may not be Brechtian, but it is entertaining.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1643EDT &QL; 
