<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-G7-0915-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    G7 MEMBERS TO REVIEW SUPPORT OF RUSSIA, BASED ON MARKET REFORMS
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox New Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ World economic leaders will review their approach to
the Russian economy in the wake of the nation's near financial
collapse, the British government said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Group of Seven industrial nations spent
several hours being briefed in London on the country's economic
situation by Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Georgy Mamedov.
</P>
<P>
   The former world superpower, in recent weeks, has seen its
currency -- the ruble -- plummet in value, most of its banks
struggle with insolvency and heard consumers' complaints of empty
store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Before the end of the month, the heads of the G-7 member
governments -- which include the United States, Britain, Canada,
France, Germany, Italy and Japan -- are expected to receive a
report with recommendations based on the meetings with Mamedov.
British Prime Minister Tony Blair is considering whether to call
for a G-7 summit to discuss the Russian situation within the next
few months.
</P>
<P>
   The report would be used at such a summit, a senior financial
official with the Blair government said in a briefing afterwards
with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   While refusing to reveal specifics of the meeting, the official,
who asked not to be named, said it was clear that the G-7 is
considering a new approach to Russia. ``The program we had
supported has suffered some serious setbacks,'' he said. ``We need
to study the situation and come to some conclusions.''
</P>
<P>
   No definitive actions were taken at the meeting, but the G-7
delegates said continued financial aid from the West would be
linked to continued reforms in Russia toward a free market economy.
``The international community is ready to be supportive in Russia
provided the economy is headed in the right direction,'' the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians asked to be judged on their performance in the
coming months, but did not offer an specifics, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not expect any programs as the government was only
three days old,'' the official said. ``It was a very open,
friendly, candid discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov promised Monday to
continue market reforms but said he would also work to protect
Russians from the painful effects of the country's economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot conduct reforms that affect the people adversely,''
Primakov said at a Cabinet meeting. ``If therapy drags out for
decades . . . it is certainly not in the interests of the country,
not in the interests of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov was accepted Friday by the Russian Parliament, which
had repeatedly rejected President Boris Yeltsin's earlier
nomination of Viktor Chernomyrdin. The ruble, which had lost
two-thirds of its value over the past month, rallied.
</P>
<P>
   Mamedov said the G-7 meeting went well. ``There was a lot of
enthusiasm for the fact that we have a new prime minister and that
the period of uncertainty is over,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He said his government was inviting International Monetary Fund
representatives to visit his country soon. Russia is eager to
receive another installment from the $22.6 billion rescue program
the IMF approved in July. The first $4.8 billion was consumed in a
vain attempt to prop up the slumping ruble.
</P>
<P>
   Mamedov said the G-7 officials welcomed signs of more stability
in Russia. ``They all have an economic interest in that because the
Dow Jones index does not fall by chance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
