<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4339 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN-N     09-14 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESKTOP STUDIO FOR HOME VIDEO BUFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By ROB FIXMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a few notable exceptions like the stuff that ends up on
``America's Funniest Home Videos,'' most family movies and tapes
are destined to the oblivion of those dresser drawers that collect
the pressed flowers and love beads of our youth.
</P>
<P>
   There is no mystery to this. Home videos are typically painfully
packed with jiggled-camera shots and endless feet of boring images.
Yet, most contain a few gems within their 120 minutes of raw
footage that are worth savoring from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the market for Studio 400, a $200 peripheral from
Pinnacle Systems of Sunnyvale, Calif., that enables people with
Pentium-class computers running Windows 95 or 98 to edit home
videos into movies that are actually worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   No one who has used a professional Macintosh-based video editing
system like the Avid would ever be satisfied with the Studio 400.
Yet, with enough patience and just a touch of creativity, this
product can help you fashion a first-rate production from the
visual chaos of your home videos.
</P>
<P>
   And if your objective is to produce videos for a Web site, the
Studio 400 is probably a wiser investment than a professional
system. Its lack of sophistication is not a drawback for making
short clips, and the quality of its output far exceeds the current
state of the art in online movies.
</P>
<P>
   That said, do not rush out and buy this device unless you are
absolutely sure you have the required equipment to make it work _
and that you are willing to suffer through the extreme hassles of
setting it up and disassembling it.
</P>
<P>
   The most important requirement is the right kind of camcorder.
It basically has to be a Sony or one of the very few camcorders
from other companies that use the Sony LANC system. LANC, commonly
referred to as ``Control L,'' is a set of communications rules that
Sony cameras use to send and receive instructions like start, stop,
record and pause. Unless you already own such a camcorder or are
willing to buy one, the Studio 400 will be useless.
</P>
<P>
   (Pinnacle Systems also claims to support a few camcorders that
can be controlled with an infrared remote or a Panasonic 5-pin
jack, only used abroad. For this review, only a Sony camcorder was
used.)
</P>
<P>
   "You will also need a VCR that can be controlled by a standard
infrared remote. That covers virtually all VCR's, but unless your
computer just happens to be sitting right next to your television,
you will have to unplug the VCR and move it.
</P>
<P>
   Before doing this, consider that when unplugged, most VCR's lose
anything stored in their memory, which will have be reset. And if
your VCR requires using an on-screen menu to switch it from cable
or antenna reception to accepting input from a camcorder, you will
also have to attach a television to the VCR during the setup
process.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will you be able to use your VCR or camcorder when it is
connected to the system.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, installing Studio 400 leaves you with a jumble of
eight cables, at least two of which are not supplied and will have
to be hunted down. The unit itself _ a box about 6.5 inches by 4.5
inches and 2 inches called the studio mixer _ must be plugged into
a computer's parallel and serial ports and into a parallel printer
unless you have more than one printer port.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you are willing to go through the expense of making the
Studio 400 a semi-permanent installation by dedicating a VCR and
camcorder to the system, setting up for each editing session will
take about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, you can do without the VCR and save your finished
movies directly on your hard drive _ but only if you have about a
gigabyte of space for a half-hour movie that plays on the PC
screen.
</P>
<P>
   There are other drawbacks. The connection to your parallel port
is supposed to let you run your printer at the same time, but when
either of two popular ink-jet printers _ a Canon BJC 4000 or an
Epson 600 _ was attached to Studio 400, neither worked properly.
Nor could the computer find a Xip drive that had been attached via
the parallel port. Two hours of playing with the port settings,
rebooting and re-initializing printers never fixed the problems.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, once set up, Studio 400 turned out to be a useful tool
that enables you to control both your camcorder and VCR from your
computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   The first step is to capture the images from a tape on the
camcorder and save them on your hard drive. At this step, the
system employs heavy compression so that the images use little disk
space _ about 150 megabytes for every hour of video. These images
only have to be good enough to let you see what you will be editing
and can be discarded after the movie is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, it is easiest to capture the video from an entire
tape, but you can monitor the action on screen as the tape plays
and start and stop the camcorder to select only portions you want
to use. As the video is captured, Studio 400 recognizes scene
changes and pops the first frame of each scene into an ``album'' on
your computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   Next you choose the scenes you want and arrange them in order by
dragging the first frame of a scene from the album into a cell on a
``story board.'' You then choose fades, cuts and other ways that
one scene blends into another from a respectable selection of
effects and drag them to their desired spot on the story board.
</P>
<P>
   Studio 400 also enables you to create titles and subtitles.
While title animation is limited, the text can be moved in and out
of scenes nicely using the transition effects.
</P>
<P>
   The editing is completed by switching from the story board to a
timeline view of the movie. At this point you can shorten or
rearrange scenes, add sound effects, narration and background music
and fine-tune transitions. Music can be cued to the exact length of
the movie or of individual scenes.
</P>
<P>
   When editing is finished, Studio 400 completes the movie by
reading its instructions from your timeline. For each scene, it
cues the camcorder to the first frame, copies the scene to the VCR,
then pauses the VCR, finds the first frame of the next scene and
repeats the process until the entire movie is assembled on the
videotape in your VCR. At each step, it adds the titles, transition
effects and sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on your creativity and patience and the quality of the
videos, the result can be surprisingly professional _ or just
another, very expensive artifact for your dresser drawer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
