<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4353 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      09-14 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNHAPPY MARRIAGE OF PLANTS  
 NOT ALL CLOCKS ARE IN SYNC  
 EVEN BIRDS NEED PRACTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KAREN FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Genetic engineering may be enough to push a plant to
promiscuity. And that's bad news for the scientists who have been
counting on crop plants' propensity to keep themselves to
themselves when it comes to reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   When genetic engineers slip a gene for herbicide resistance into
a crop, they hope that the domesticated plants won't pass it
around. If the wild plants can't get the gene for resistance, they
can be wiped out with the herbicide.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to see a generation of untamed interlopers with a
gene that lets them thumb their metaphorical noses at the
weedkiller.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't thought to be much of a danger because most crop
plants are self-fertilizing. But when Dr. Joy Bergelson of the
University of Chicago and two colleagues looked at genetically
engineered Arabidopsis _ a self-fertilizing mustard plant _ they
saw inhibitions against mating with wild relatives melting away.
</P>
<P>
   And it seems to be gene splicing, not just the herbicide
resistance, that is the cause, the researchers reported in the
Sept. 3 issue of the journal Nature. Non-engineered plants with a
mutant gene for herbicide resistance showed nowhere near the level
of erosion of family values.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Plant behavior is also causing trouble for scientists working on
ways to store nuclear waste.
</P>
<P>
   When a small amount of radioactive material from the Three Mile
Island accident was buried in an experiment at Oak Ridge National
Laboratory in Tennessee, scientists expected to see some
radioactivity leaching out _ but down, not up. When radioactivity
turned up on the surface, they had to figure out why.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers led by Dr. William Sanford of Colorado State
University reported in the Journal of Environmental Radioactivity
that plant roots probably drank in radioactive molecules in water
and ferried them to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Whether plant or animal, slowpoke or speedster, organisms across
a wide swath of biology may use the same basic mechanism for timing
daily cycles. But that doesn't mean that all biological clocks
evolved from the same ancestral clock, and a study in the Sept. 4
issue of the journal Science indicates that they probably didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The circadian clock, that self-winding marvel, appears to tick
away with swings of a molecular pendulum. The level of a molecule
builds until a braking mechanism is triggered, then the level falls
as the pendulum swings back.
</P>
<P>
   But researchers from Nagoya University have reported that the
circadian molecules used by blue-green algae are different from
those used by mammals and fruit flies, indicating a separate
evolutionary origin.
</P>
<P>
   The clocks all do a remarkable job for their disparate masters.
As Alexander Pope said, `` 'Tis with our judgments as our watches,
none go just alike, yet each believes his own.''
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Timing is just one of the problems of a young zebra finch trying
to learn to sound like one. A study in the Sept. 3 issue of Nature
says the syrinx, the source of birdsong, is a more complicated
instrument than it appears.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Bell Laboratories and the California Institute of
Technology looked at the acoustic properties of the isolated syrinx
and found the organ is capable of producing a variety of sounds all
on its own, free of muscle control and neural input.
</P>
<P>
   So a young finch yearning to sound like an adult one day has a
tough instrument to master _ more like taking up the French horn
than fooling around with a harmonica.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1700EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
