<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-REPORT-OUTRAGE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOLEN KISSES IN THE MOONLIGHT? GET REAL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Central time zone, call CONNIE WHITE at
1-800-444-0267. Or fax her at (816) 822-1444.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Pacific or Mountain time zones or in Latin
America, call OLIVIA VASQUEZ at (310) 996-0075. Or fax her at (310)
996-0089.
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Most of the talking heads on TV and a good number of senators
and congressmen seem to be in a state of collective shock over the
more lurid elements of the Starr Report. They're stunned, they tell
us. Stunned!
</P>
<P>
   ``How can this president ever walk in front of another audience
again, again in his life, political or private, without their first
thought in the front row being the thought bubble, the mental image
of the acts described in this report we're reading today?'' fretted
Brian Williams of MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worse than I thought it would be!'' said Rep. Thomas
Davis (R.-Virginia).
</P>
<P>
   Give me a break. What did these people expect when they scrolled
through the Starr Report? Did they really think they'd read stories
of romantic dinners, declarations of deep love, stolen kisses under
the moonlight and soft-focus movie-sex with orchestral music in the
background?
</P>
<P>
   Affairs are rarely if ever like that in real life. Affairs are
awkward and messy and occasionally ridiculous _ especially the
sexual stuff. Zippers are unzipped, bras are unhooked,
undergarments are pushed aside in a rushed frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Was the Clinton-Lewinsky liaison really so different from
millions of other flings? I don't think so. Joke all you want about
the cigar, the Altoid mints, the stained dress _ but would you want
every little quirk of your sex life to be detailed in a report
posted on the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   Forget for a moment that Bill Clinton is the leader of the free
world, and you realize this relationship was almost mundane.
Clinton's fling with Lewinsky follows the pattern of so many
assignations between older, married men and starstruck young women.
It wasn't shocking _ it was depressingly predictable, from its
groping start to its inevitable finish.
</P>
<P>
   She was an intern who flirted with the boss, who should have
known better than to pursue it. Instead, he encouraged her as she
playfully showed him a flash of her underwear, and told him she had
a big crush on him.
</P>
<P>
   He asked if he could kiss her. She said yes. Moments later, she
was engaging in a sex act.
</P>
<P>
   Thus began what Lewinsky thought was a grand love affair, and
Clinton knew to be something less. A month into it, Lewinsky
starting asking the questions young women almost always ask when
mired in such relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him why doesn't he ask any questions about myself, and
... is this just about sex?'' she testified.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton gave the kind of answer married older men almost
always give in that situation. He assured Lewinsky he ``cherished''
their time together.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he gave her just enough encouragement to keep it
going.
</P>
<P>
   Did Clinton consider leaving his wife for Monica? Hey, it
happens. The world is filled with trophy second wives. In this
case, though, it's doubtful the man considered such a move for even
one second.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Monica thought they were in love, and she convinced herself
the feeling was mutual, according to the Starr Report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just knew he was in love with me,'' she told prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   While it's true that Clinton foolishly, recklessly gave Lewinsky
trinkets and would wear the neckties she presented to him, it was
Monica who acted as if she was a high school senior in love with a
teacher who really just wanted sex but tolerated her fantasies of a
substantial relationship.
</P>
<P>
   _ For Valentine's Day, she placed a personals ad in the
Washington Post. It was addressed to ``Handsome,'' and quoted from
``Romeo and Juliet.''
</P>
<P>
   _ She blabbed to at least 11 people about the affair, reportedly
telling one friend Clinton might marry her after he left the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   _ She sent him gushing love notes, riddled with grammatical
errors, and spent hours on the phone with him.
</P>
<P>
   _ As Clinton tried to distance himself from her, she crashed
parties and even tried to grope him in public, and she threw
tantrums and began referring to him as the ``creep.''
</P>
<P>
   _ After a gap of nearly a year, there were two more cheap
trysts. This too sounds like an awful lot of affairs in which the
married man calls it off, only to have a brief relapse before
ending it for good.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finally, in December of 1997, Lewinsky was outside the gates
of the White House, in tears and screaming at Secret Service agents
who refused to let her see the president one last time. Only then
did she realize it was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want me out of your life,'' she wrote to Clinton. ``I
guess the signs have been made clear for a while _ not wanting to
see me and rarely calling ... You let me down, but I shouldn't have
trusted you in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Shocking? Stunning? Hardly. This was a most ordinary affair,
doomed from the start. The most obscene thing about the whole
sordid episode is that people are seriously talking about
impeaching the president over this nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) can be heard on the
``Media Creatures'' show, which airs daily in Chicago from 10 a.m.
to 2 p.m. on WMVP-AM (1000) and appears Tuesday and Thursday at
7:55 a.m. on WFLD-TV's ``Fox Thing in the Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (A daily columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, Roeper has also
written for TV Guide, Spy, Playboy, Chicago magazine and many other
publications, and has appeared as a guest on ``Nightline'' and
``Oprah.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
