<HEADER>
A4366 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILIPPINE-BELLS-HNS &LR;      09-14 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINE-BELLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILIPINOS CONTINUE QUEST FOR RETURN OF CHURCH BELLS FROM WYOMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At an Air Force base in Cheyenne, Wyo., sit two
bronze church bells at the center of a trans-Pacific dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Taken by American soldiers as a war trophy in 1901 from a
Philippine island, the bells symbolize a period of history few
Americans understand well _ the violent and bloody rebellion
against U.S. rule.
</P>
<P>
   The Bells of Balangiga, as they are called, had been forgotten
for decades in their isolated Wyoming home. They suddenly came to
international prominence last year when the Philippines asked for
them back in time for the centennial of the Philippines'
independence from Spain.
</P>
<P>
   But asking has not been enough, nor has a year of high-level
negotiations or pleas to the spirit of a century of
Filipino-American friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Pitting American war veterans against Filipino-American
activists, the question of where the bells belong has stirred up
issues of patriotism, justice and interpretations of history.
</P>
<P>
   The story of how the church bells ended up in Cheyenne stems
from two grisly battles in the coastal village of Balangiga in
1901. In the first, nationalist rebels launched a surprise attack
on American soldiers as they were quietly eating breakfast. The
bells of the small Catholic church were sounded as the assault
began. Only 22 of 74 soldiers survived.
</P>
<P>
   Retaliation was brutal. American Brig. Gen. Jacob Smith
essentially ordered his troops to kill everyone on the island of
Samar over the age of 10. Villages were set on fire, crops were
destroyed and thousands are believed to have died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish you to kill and burn. The more you kill and burn, the
better you will please me,'' Smith told his officers, according to
testimony at his court-martial in 1902.
</P>
<P>
   Although Smith was found guilty of misconduct, he got off with
admonishment.
</P>
<P>
   American troops took the two bells back to their home base, what
is now F.E. Warren Air Force Base in Cheyenne, as war trophies.
Nearly a century later, Wyoming veterans view the bells as a
commemoration to lost American lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't believe in dismantling war memorials,'' said
Robert Nab, an adjutant of the American Legion in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Any notion that the bells are religious objects, as Bishop
Joseph Hart of the Cheyenne diocese has argued, doesn't wash with
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is, the church became part of the conflict because it
was used to alert the local people to attack the American army,''
Nab said. ``We feel strongly that the bells and the church itself
were part of the massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Filipino Americans have strongly advocated the return of
the bells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us take the act of acquiring these bells as a total
insult,'' said Terry Bautista, a co-founder of Filipinos for
Affirmative Action in Oakland, Calif. ``It's like you already
killed the women and children, you already took it upon yourselves
to mess up the land, then you have the gall to take something from
a church.''
</P>
<P>
   The significance of the Balangiga battles went beyond the lives
lost on both sides, says Professor Daniel Phil Gonzales,
coordinator of Filipino-American studies at San Francisco State
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The retaliatory attack did not stop with Balangiga,'' he said.
``It was the spark for even more insidious slaughter of tens of
thousands of people. It made the wholesale slaughter of Filipinos a
rational act in the minds of Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the June centennial celebration of the Philippines'
independence from Spain has come and gone, the goal is to get the
bells back by 2001, the centennial of the confiscation, said Rodel
Rodis, a San Francisco attorney who has written several articles
about the bells.
</P>
<P>
   The Philippine government has even proposed a compromise _ make
replicas of the bells and allow each country to keep one replica
and one genuine bell. But the Wyoming veterans were not receptive
to the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``All it takes is a small group of narrow-minded, jingoistic
veterans,'' Rodis said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The group has some powerful allies. Sen. Craig Thomas, R-Wyo.,
introduced a bill in April requiring congressional approval before
any part of a veterans memorial could be sent to a foreign country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think most people (in Wyoming) agree that this is a memorial
to the soldiers who died,'' said Dan Kunsman, a spokesman for the
senator. ``History brought them to Cheyenne, and that memorial
should stay there.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the conflict in the Philippines lasted four years _
from 1898, when the United States acquired the archipelago
following the Spanish-American War, until 1902, when President
Theodore Roosevelt declared victory.
</P>
<P>
   Some estimates say that as many as 250,000 Filipinos were killed
in the insurrection. The Philippines gained independence from the
United States after World War II.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
