<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4384 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-WATCH-NYT &LR;      09-14 0322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ANN M. KENNEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Lead in Breast Milk &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Mother's milk is generally best, but not always.
</P>
<P>
   A study in the October issue of Environmental Health
Perspectives, the journal of the National Institute of
Environmental Health Sciences, shows that lead accumulated in a
woman's bones can be released during pregnancy and transferred to
breast milk during lactation. This can mean increased lead exposure
for breast-fed infants, a risk if the mothers have been previously
exposed to high concentrations of lead.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted by Australian and American scientists,
looked at samples of blood, urine and breast milk of 21 mothers
during pregnancy and six months after delivery and compared these
samples with blood and urine specimens from their 24 infants, said
Dr. Brian Gulson, a toxicologist at Macquarie University in Sydney,
Australia, and lead investigator of the project. The researchers
found a significant link between the amount of lead in the mothers'
milk samples and the corresponding lead levels in the infants'
blood. They also noted that 40 percent to 70 percent of the lead in
pregnant women's blood came from lead accumulated in the bones.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul Mushak, who was an adviser to the study, believes the
research has relevance for health and regulatory policy. ``One of
its critical implications is that lead is a transgenerational
problem,'' Mushak said. High lead levels in the blood of infants
and children can result in brain damage, behavioral problems and
liver and kidney disorders. The Centers for Disease Control
recommends testing for high-risk infants beginning at the age of 6
months.
</P>
<P>
   As for breastfeeding, Gulson says, ``It is still an important
option for healthy mothers. Breast-fed infants are only at risk if
their mothers have been previously exposed to high concentrations
of lead.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1708EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
