<HEADER>
A4392 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOSA-SURPRISE-62-NYTS     09-14 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOSA-SURPRISE-62-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMMY'S RECORD SURPRISED THE CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Central time zone, call CONNIE WHITE at
1-800-444-0267. Or fax her at (816) 822-1444.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Pacific or Mountain time zones or in Latin
America, call OLIVIA VASQUEZ at (310) 996-0075. Or fax her at (310)
996-0089.
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ``You think there might be a little scratching and clawing,
maybe some kicking or biting, as they fight to gain possession of
that million-dollar prize?'' _ From a column I wrote last month,
speculating on what would happen when Mark McGwire and/or Sammy
Sosa hit their 62nd home run.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Biting! There really was biting outside Wrigley Field
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Thank heavens, because I thought I'd lost my touch on the
popular pulse. Human beings were behaving with class and dignity,
and it was confusing me. I watched in amazement as fan after fan
returned coveted home run balls to Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa,
brushing away the memorabilia dealers and the home shopping
channels, asking the superstars for only a few autographed trinkets
in return.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the youngsters who scrambled across the tarp in the
outfield bleachers at Pro Player Park in Miami to retrieve a couple
of McGwire's home run balls? One was 17, the other just 11. Each
said it wouldn't be right to keep the ball and handed it over to
McGwire in exchange for balls, bats, jerseys and the chance to
shake hands with the big lug.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the woman who made that one-handed catch of a
Sosa home run at Wrigley Field. She too said the ball belonged to
the slugger _ though to Sammy's credit, he signed the ball and
handed it right back to her.
</P>
<P>
   Similar stories of bleacherite benevolence were told after
several other homers. Apparently a lot of fans were buying
McGwire's theory that anyone who tried to sell a special home run
ball was holding it ``hostage.'' These purists were killing me!
Where was the greed, where was the selfishness, where were the
stories about fans fighting? Heck, where were the lawyers? All
these nice people were ruining my perception of the American way of
life _ but that was before Bloody Sunday on Waveland Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone seemed under-prepared for the possibility of Sammy Sosa
reaching the 62 mark over the weekend. They didn't use balls marked
with infra-red labels for Sosa's at-bats (as they did when McGwire
was closing in on Maris); the commissioner wasn't in attendance;
there was no special ceremony planned to honor No. 62 _ and while
there were plenty of cops stationed outside Wrigley, they were
greatly outnumbered by the ball-hawkers.
</P>
<P>
   When Sammy hit No. 60 on Saturday, the fan who grabbed the ball
was doused with beer by rooftop revelers. That should have been
taken as a sign.
</P>
<P>
   It got weirder, rougher and greedier on Sunday. The unemployed
fan who caught No. 61 said there was no way he was giving the ball
to Sammy; instead, a $10,000 price tag sounded about right.
</P>
<P>
   When home run No. 62 sailed out of the park, hundreds of fans
dashed for it. Longtime ballhawker Gary ``Moe'' Mullins, 47, said
he had possession of the ball, but lost it in a massive pileup to
one Brendan Cunningham, 33. Cunningham emerged from the pack,
reportedly shoved the ball down his pants and ran down Sheffield
Avenue until he found police protection from the mob.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like a VIP or a criminal!'' Cunningham told NBC-5's Amy
Jacobson, as he described his ride in a police car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tripped and mugged and knocked to the ground,'' Mullins
told Jacobson in a separately taped interview. ``I held on as long
as I could but they piled up so high, they finally got it from me.
I was being bit, scratched, everything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't bite anybody!'' Cunningham retorted.
</P>
<P>
   Mullins filed a police report. (Never having dealt with a claim
of a stolen home run ball, the cops classified it as an alleged
strong arm robbery.) As of this writing, ownership of the ball is
still in dispute, and there's talk that _ surprise, surprise _ the
whole mess might wind up in court.
</P>
<P>
   All right, NOW we're talking, sports fans. Now we've got the
material of which columns are made. Just a few points to ponder:
</P>
<P>
   A. You can buy official National League baseballs for about $9
at area sporting goods stores. Without the infra-red markings,
who's to say any of these guys really have the balls Sammy hit? In
fact, I'VE got the 62nd homer! Yeah, that's my story, it bounced
over to me!
</P>
<P>
   B. Which baseball is really going to be worth $1 million _
McGwire's 62nd, or the last record-setting homer of the season? If
Sosa finishes with 67 and McGwire closes with 65, isn't Sammy's
67th the real treasure?
</P>
<P>
   C. Do you think Chicago police will consider closing off
Waveland Avenue for next Sunday's game, the regular season home
finale for the Cubs?
</P>
<P>
   D. In an effort to gain a strength advantage, will some
ballhawkers start ingesting androstenedione?
</P>
<P>
   E. When the oversized McGwire took that victory lap in that
little red '62 Corvette, did he look like a GI Joe doll in a Hot
Wheels car or what?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) can be heard on the
``Media Creatures'' show, which airs daily in Chicago from 10 a.m.
to 2 p.m. on WMVP-AM (1000) and appears Tuesday and Thursday at
7:55 a.m. on WFLD-TV's ``Fox Thing in the Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (A daily columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, Roeper has also
written for TV Guide, Spy, Playboy, Chicago magazine and many other
publications, and has appeared as a guest on ``Nightline'' and
``Oprah.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
