<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4419 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX     09-14 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECORD-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE RETURNED TO US SOMETHING THAT WAS MISSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PHIL RECORD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thank you, Mark McGwire, for giving back _ if even for a little
while _ what many lovers of baseball feel has been taken away from
us.
</P>
<P>
   You gave us, in your successful effort to become the new
home-run king, the enthusiasm for the sport that was once properly
described as the national pastime.
</P>
<P>
   I, and many others, have lost much of our loyalty for baseball _
and many other professional sports _ because we no longer feel that
the owners and players have loyalty for us.
</P>
<P>
   That is sad.
</P>
<P>
   For the owners and the players, the name of the game is money,
and that spells G-R-E-E-D. That hasn't left much room for the fans.
</P>
<P>
   But for one brief moment, you, Mark McGwire, gave back to many
us that joy of watching the game as you battled the pressure to
smash home run No. 62.
</P>
<P>
   Here was what has been described as a very decent guy who seemed
more interested in sharing with others the thrill of the conquest
than in how much he was going to deposit in his bank account.
</P>
<P>
   We began to identify with this man of class and power.
</P>
<P>
   We pulled for him. We let him tug at our hearts.
</P>
<P>
   We wanted him to reach a plateau no other man had reached in the
major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't bear him resentment.
</P>
<P>
   We forgot, for one brief moment, how professional sports has
forgotten many of us.
</P>
<P>
   We rejoiced when that baseball barely cleared the left-field
fence in Busch Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   I'm thrilled I was watching live TV when McGwire reached the
mountaintop. I thank him for the mental snapshots that will remain
with us for many years:
</P>
<P>
   _An elated McGwire being congratulated warmly by the opposing
Chicago Cub infielders as he circled the bases.
</P>
<P>
   _A display of a father's love as Big Mac lifted on high his
10-year-old son, Matt, after circling the bases. And the joy
reflected in the faces of McGwire's parents, who were in the
stands.
</P>
<P>
   _The unselfish sportsmanship of Sammy Sosa, Big Mac's chief
competitor in the race for the home-run kingship. I was deeply
moved by the sight of the two embracing after Sosa left his
position in right field to congratulate from the heart the new
King.
</P>
<P>
   _The fans in St. Louis standing for Sosa the next time he came
to bat and pulling for him to put one out of the park. McGwire has
called them the best fans in baseball. They certainly were on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   _McGwire not hesitating to give recognition before and after his
achievement to the source of his talent. Prior to Tuesday night, he
said the record-breaking homer would come in the Lord's time, which
proved to be perfect (in McGwire's words, ``It was a great script
written by the Man Upstairs''). After breaking the record, he did
not forget to give credit to the Lord.
</P>
<P>
   _McGwire hurdling a railing to embrace the family of Roger
Maris, the man whose record he broke Tuesday night. He enabled them
to share in some of the joy and enthusiasm that was denied to their
father when he broke Babe Ruth's home-run record.
</P>
<P>
   _Tim Forneris, who described himself as ``just a regular Joe,''
not hesitating to return the record-breaking ball to McGwire. It
was Forneris, a member of the Busch groundskeeping crew, who chased
down the ball after it cleared the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Thank God the ball did not fall into the hands of those
memorabilia groups that would perpetuate the greed of the game by
offering $1 million for it.
</P>
<P>
   So thank you, Big Mac, for giving back what many of us thought
was gone forever: a great zest for the game and a true joy in
watching one accomplish the seemingly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief period you put on the back burner the Bill
Clinton-Monica Lewinsky scandal. For a brief period you showed that
the talents of a good guy could triumph over the greed that has
soiled a wonderful game.
</P>
<P>
   May your days be long and blessed by the Lord you did not forget
in your hour of triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I fear, it is back to business as usual. We will again be
overwhelmed by what one syndicated columnist aptly called the
Monica Mess; owners and players in professional sports will resume
haggling over outrageous salaries, and owners of the some teams
will be ready to desert the fans in one city for those in another
if they feel there are more bucks to be made.
</P>
<P>
   Sports can get an unreasonable hold on us. I certainly used to
be in that grasp on those Saturday afternoons when Notre Dame was
in a tough game.
</P>
<P>
   It's OK to be amused by sports, to use them as a diversion from
the trials and pressures of life. The trouble is, too many of us
abuse sports.
</P>
<P>
   Too many of us spend our time chasing a small white ball on
Sunday mornings when we should be in church worshiping Jesus. Too
often we feel it necessary to skip some ``pew time'' in order to
get an early start to the stadium to watch a bunch of grown men
smash their bodies together.
</P>
<P>
   St. Paul undoubtedly was a sports fan. He used references to
sports in some of his epistles. But I doubt if he was ever a fool
for sports.
</P>
<P>
   As I watched the enthusiasm of the crowd in Busch Stadium on
Tuesday night, I wondered how many put that much enthusiasm into
making their marriages work, into their work, into their church.
</P>
<P>
   Too few, I fear.
</P>
<P>
   It seems it is OK to get tremendously excited in a sports
stadium, but many label us as fools if we show real excitement
about God.
</P>
<P>
   Don't let that stop you. Paul assures us in the fourth chapter
of 1 Corinthians that those who appear to the world to be fools on
Christ's account will also appear to be wise in the eyes of God.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that the next time you go to the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   (Retired ombudsman Phil Record is a consultant to the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at precord(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
