s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-SAFRICA-$ADV20     09-14 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SAFRICA-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA LEARNS THAT TOURISM IS FRAGILE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ The bomb that went off in the
Planet Hollywood restaurant in Cape Town on Aug. 25, killing two
people, has hurt tourism in South Africa's prettiest city, but no
one agrees how much. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One restaurateur says that business fell off for only the first
couple of days; another says reservations dropped sharply. One
tourism official says she can prove that the city lost at least
$800,000 in business, another estimates the nation lost $55
million. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This much is not debated: South Africa is new at international
tourism, and still floundering in figuring out how to respond to a
crisis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Cape Town dozens were hurt in the blast, in addition to the
two who were killed. Who left the bomb in the crowded bar, and why,
is still unknown. An anonymous caller to a radio reporter said it
was left by a group called Muslims Against Global Oppression.
</P>
<P>
   That got wide currency because the blast followed American
cruise missile attacks on the Sudan and Afghanistan, which were
themselves in retaliation for truck bombs that exploded outside
United States embassies in Kenya and Tanzania. A day later, the
group condemned the bombing and called it a ploy to discredit
them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since then there have been no arrests. Videotapes from cameras
inside the bar proved to be weeks old. The one lead the police
admit having is that the bomb had a timer like those on bombs left
at two Cape Town police stations. Those bombs are believed to be
the work of People Against Gangsterism and Drugs, a militant
anti-crime group founded by Muslim clerics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Planet Hollywood is part of the Victoria and Alfred Waterfront,
a collection of shops and restaurants that resembles Fisherman's
Wharf in San Francisco and the South Street Seaport in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism officials estimate that 40 percent of all foreign
visitors and 56 percent of American tourists visit it. Although the
Waterfront usually feels like a safe place, its reputation has
suffered because of the blast and because of a fatal shootout
between two drug gangs outside the entrance several months ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since the blast, the Waterfront has hired a new firm to oversee
its security guards, started mounted armed patrols and added 30
cameras to the 116 already in place. Some theaters and clubs search
customers' bags. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gauging the blast's effect on tourism is tricky. ``There was
definitely an impact that first week,'' said Maureen Thompson, a
spokeswoman for the Waterfront. ``As time plods by, things look as
if they're getting back to normal again.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rens Ratcliffe, manager of St. Elmo's Pizza, and Andre Swart,
the manager of Mitchell's Waterfront Brewery, a popular tavern,
said that their walk-in crowds were back to normal. The
reservations clerk at the Quay 4 restaurant said she had some
cancellations from tour groups: ``A Dr. Pepper group from the U.S.
that booked over a year ago canceled, and it said on the fax that
it was because of the bombing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Americans are seen as especially desirable tourists. More
Britons and Germans visit, but Americans stay longer _ 20 days on
average, versus 10 for Europeans _ and spend more _ $140 a day, not
counting air fare, versus $94 for Britons and $73 for Germans. (The
bombing got more publicity in Britain than in the United States. No
Americans were hurt, but three generations of one British family
were injured.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Americans are also seen as extremely cautious. ``They tend to be
more nervous than Europeans,'' said Gillian Saunders, a tourism
consultant. ``We had cancellations here because of a bomb in
Nairobi. We don't get that with Europeans.'' Nairobi is 2,400 miles
from Cape Town, about the distance from New York to Los Angeles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Saunders' consultancy, Grant Thornton, came up with the $55
million loss estimate. She admits it was a bit of a guess _ ``a
discussion amongst ourselves'' _ based on the assumption that a
third of the 60,000 Americans who come for pleasure would cancel
this year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Ozinsky, manager of Cape Town Tourism, a joint
city-industry group, found $55 million ``a bit over the top.'' Her
$800,000 figure, however, is based strictly on actual cancellations
received by the 60 of her 1,400 members who bothered to answer her
snap survey. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both women and Ms. Thompson said that South Africa is ill
prepared to mount a big campaign to win tourists back. Local
government has promised $160,000 and hoteliers have agreed to
donate rooms and meals if foreign travel writers can be rounded up
to write what they hope are glowing articles.
</P>
<P>
   But that amount seems a pittance considering that South Africa
earns over $3 billion a year from foreign tourism, an industry that
employs more than 600,000 South Africans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Australia's spend on this is 10 times ours,'' said Ms.
Ozinsky. ``It's unbelievable.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
