<HEADLINE>
THE CLINTONS AT BAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The customary picture of President Clinton and his
wife Hillary leaving church holding hands was missing this Sunday;
they did not leave the White House to worship, despite the
president's recent appeals for forgiveness and redemption.
</P>
<P>
   They have not, in fact, been seen holding hands in public since
a few days before Clinton's Aug. 17 grand jury testimony, when he
reportedly confessed to her at last about his sexual encounters
with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   But Hillary Clinton recently stood at her husband's side at
several public events, introduced him at a fund-raiser by saying
she is ``proud'' of his progressive policies and even patted him on
the back on one occasion. She has not deserted him politically,
although she gives every sign of having done so emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   Their joint appearances now lack the cozy intimacy, the loving
glances and affectionate touching that used to characterize their
public performances. When they are seen together, there is not much
physical distance between them but the psychic distance is
enormous.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestions from the president's advisers last week that she
would make a speech reaffirming her love and forgiveness were
quickly countered by reports from her friends that she will do no
such thing. At least not for a while. Not until the political
process of punishing her husband is further along.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, she may not be able to rescue him this time, as she
did six years ago when she defended him on television against
Gennifer Flower's allegations of an affair.
</P>
<P>
   A USA Today poll conducted Sunday indicated that while 14
percent of those surveyed said her forgiveness would influence
their view of the president ``a great deal,'' 52 percent said it
would affect their opinion ``not at all.'' A Newsweek poll reported
that only 30 percent of those surveyed would be more likely to
support the president if she made a show of forgiving him.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's credibility has sometimes been questioned and
she is in no mood to test it over her cheating husband's adultery.
</P>
<P>
   She has been accused of lying about such unresolved
controversies as missing law firm records and cattle futures
investments. Her toughest critics even contend she knew all about
his lewd conduct when she blamed the initial stories about Monica
Lewinsky in January on a ``vast right wing conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The first question everyone asks these days is what political
price Bill Clinton should pay. But the second is: How can she stay
with a selfish, unfaithful cad who has publicly humiliated her?
</P>
<P>
   There have always been two theories, equally unproven, about the
Clinton marriage. One is that she has known all along about his
marital infidelities but ignores them because they share a
passionless business partnership that advances her own political
ambitions as well as his.
</P>
<P>
   The other theory is that they really do love each other and she
naively fooled herself about his womanizing because she was in
romantic denial.
</P>
<P>
   If Lewinsky can be believed, the president himself indicated
that he and his wife were not enjoying perfect wedded bliss even
before the scandal erupted. She says he bragged about ``hundreds''
of affairs throughout his marriage, although he claimed to be
trying harder to be faithful since he turned 40.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky told a friend that Clinton had mused he did not know
whether he would remain married after he left the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky testified that during what she characterized as a
``very emotional'' meeting she told him she hoped he might have
more time for her when he was out of office.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Lewinsky stated, ``And he said, well, l don't know, I
might be alone in three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Did the president really mean to suggest he was thinking of a
divorce? Or that Hillary was? Or was he merely trying to placate a
demanding sexpot who was feeling neglected and had become not just
an inconvenient nuisance but a looming threat to his presidency?
</P>
<P>
   The nation's capital has been awash in gossip for years that the
Clintons were unlikely to remain together once their public life is
over. The feeling, among many women at least, was that she will be
better off with an independent career and a life without him. But
the gossip has always been just that, unconfirmed and
unconfirmable.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton herself remains inscrutable, doing her best to
behave with dignity in a very undignified situation. She is loyally
maintaining a full schedule of public appearances, some in tandem
with the president's own activities.
</P>
<P>
   As the wronged wife bearing up silently under great pain, she
has won the public's sympathy. A Newsweek poll in Monday's issue
shows that 59 percent of those surveyed have a favorable opinion of
her, up from 52 percent pre-Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   Despite everything, Clinton himself retains more support among
women than among men, as he did in both his 1992 and 1996
presidential campaigns. The USA Today poll indicates that roughly
33 percent of men surveyed think Clinton should be impeached and
removed from office, but only 26 percent of the women do.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how much Hillary's steadfastness and popularity
has to do with that. But it can't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone would go along with the solution proposed by Donald
Trump, the flamboyant real estate developer. The president's only
option, Trump told the New York Times, is to ``leave his wife
(before she leaves him), resign from office and go out and have a
good time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
