<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTIFUL LAKES SHOULD BE OPENED TO THE PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You can see this one coming from a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   Future opportunities to go hiking, biking, fishing, canoeing or
horseback riding at the Peninsula's Crystal Springs watershed are
being quietly destroyed in a series of maneuvers by the San
Francisco Planning Department.
</P>
<P>
   Four alternatives are proposed for the Draft Management Plan for
the Crystal Springs Watershed, the extraordinary swath of land
along California Highway 280 on the Peninsula. The preferred
alternative allows for a short connector trail on an existing fire
road for the Bay Ridge Trail, and consideration of a new golf
course, and that's pretty much it.
</P>
<P>
   The other three alternatives attempt to make the preferred
alternative look like a compromise: The ``No Action Alternative,''
where you get zilch (which is what you get now), ``Alternative A,''
where they throw you a golf course near Woodside, but no hiking,
biking, fishing, boating or horseback riding or public access, and
``Alternative C,'' which would allow some public access, perhaps
even hiking or fishing, by gosh, only by permit.
</P>
<P>
   For years, I've called the Peninsula Watershed ``The Forbidden
Paradise,'' because all you have to do is drive down Highway 280,
take in the view of Crystal Springs Reservoir, and ask, ``Why can't
I go there?''
</P>
<P>
   It covers 23,000 acres with four fish-filled lakes, all of which
adjoin another 100,000 acres of wildlands, and all with a network
of dirt roads ideal for hiking and biking.
</P>
<P>
   A formal long-term planning process by the San Francisco
Planning Department is now under way to develop a Watershed
Management Plan. I believe the entire premise is to come up with a
legal document, once and for always, that will keep the public out
forever.
</P>
<P>
   The Peninsula has seven beautiful lakes: Upper and Lower Crystal
Springs, San Andreas, Pilarcitos, Felt, Searsville, and Boronda
(for Palo Alto residents only), and get this: Public access is not
permitted at any of them. That is just plain wrong.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two new books that hit the mark: ``In the Slick of the Cricket,
A Shark Odyssey,'' by Russell Drumm, which portrays 40 years of
shark chasing by Frank Mundus, whose character was portrayed in the
first ``Jaws'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``California Dog Lover's Companion,'' by Maria Goodavage,
featuring an area-by-area guide across the state for lodging where
dogs are permitted, is perfect for people who travel with their
pets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
