<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4508 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX     09-14 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS AWARE OF THEIR LEADERS' FLAWED NATURES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is among ordinary Americans a strong strain of decency and
fairness. It is an essential part of our nation's character. Once
again, as often before in this country's history, the public is
reacting with reasoned restraint to the shock, shame and sorrow of
events in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Bombarded incessantly by a withering fusillade of news media
overkill during the whole four weeks since President Clinton's
confession of Aug. 17, mainstream Americans have rejected hysteria.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't that they don't have opinions. To persistent pollsters,
they've said repeatedly that they (1) think Bill Clinton has been a
good president, (2) disapprove of his conduct with Monica Lewinsky
and (3) are seriously disappointed in him.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a majority insist they (4) do not want the president
impeached, (5) believe that the investigation has gone on too long
and (6) want to get the public focus back on America's unfinished
business that affects their lives.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing actually inconsistent between these conclusions
and the people's historic reaction to their public figures.
</P>
<P>
   Folks traditionally have tolerated moral frailties and forgiven
behavioral transgressions in elected officialdom, so long as
they're convinced that the public servant is actively fighting for
them.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans probably would rather have a well-meaning rogue
who loves and serves them than a moral purist who's indifferent to
their problems or sanctimonious and ineffectual.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine presidents elected in the past 50 years (Dwight D.
Eisenhower through Clinton), there were only three (Richard Nixon,
Gerald Ford and Jimmy Carter) about whose marital fidelity I never
heard ugly Washington rumors. This doesn't mean that rumors
involving others were true. But Ford and Carter were rejected for
re-election, and Nixon left for other reasons. The public just
isn't fixated on the president's bedroom, and doesn't want to be.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should we infer from this that Americans don't value a high
moral standard in public office. I'm convinced that they do. They
want decent role models for their children. Yet they know that
elected officials are human and prone to err. They tend to judge
each as a whole person and don't condemn altogether for one
character flaw.
</P>
<P>
   Texans understand this. Our state's political patron saint, Sam
Houston, offended almost all the conventional moralists at one time
or another.
</P>
<P>
   Houston swore profanely, so much so that the Mexicans named him
``Senor God Damn.'' He drank excessively, seeming at one point
ready to drown his future in alcohol. The Cherokees named him ``Big
Drunk.'' Mentioned in his 30s as a presidential prospect, Houston
forfeited his political career and resigned the governorship of
Tennessee under a cloud of suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   He was married three times _ once without the benefit of clergy,
unless we count Cherokee tribal customs. He fought duels in
violation of the law. On one occasion, he was censured by the U.S.
House for thrashing a congressman who had publicly insulted his
honor.
</P>
<P>
   Baptized by immersion in an icy stream at age 61, Houston was
told, ``All your sins are washed away.'' He replied, ``God help the
poor fish.''
</P>
<P>
   But Houston had enormous redeeming virtues. If his faults were
bigger than life-size, so was his faith. If his crudeness was
colossal, so was his basic integrity. For 50 years, he wore a ring
given him by his mother. Engraved on the underside, next to his
skin, was one word: ``Honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston left the governorship of Texas rather than swear
allegiance to the Confederacy. He believed secession to be treason.
Twice governor, of two different states, he twice vacated the
office rather than compromise his convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Reprimanded by the House in 1832, Houston described himself as
``a man of broken fortune and blasted reputation.'' He contritely
took the blame for his misdeeds. He quoted Lord Byron: ``The thorns
which I have reaped are of the tree I planted; they have torn me
and I bleed.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, he was president of the Republic of Texas and
on his way to immortality.
</P>
<P>
   To ask forgiveness is harder for a public man than for most
others. But asking it is the act of a big person. So is giving it.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps history's greatest story of sin, forgiveness and
redemption is that of David, Old Testament hero and most honored of
Israel's kings. If you haven't read it lately, revisit it in
Chapters 11 and 12 of 2 Samuel.
</P>
<P>
   David, so capable of nobility and grace and yet so human, had an
affair with another's wife, who became pregnant. In an attempt to
cover his misdeed, David ordered the husband, Uriah, sent home from
the battlefront. A few days with his wife, the king reasoned, and
Uriah would suppose later when the child came that it was his own.
</P>
<P>
   But Uriah, intent on serving his king and country, refused to go
home. Frustrated, David ordered his general to abandon Uriah to the
enemy. Uriah died a soldier's death.
</P>
<P>
   King David's crime of adultery and official betrayal, compounded
by murder, was greater than any attributed to any American
president. Its enormity, impressed upon the king by a prophet named
Nathan, drew from David the self-judgment that he deserved to die.
Yet he was forgiven and became, with all his flaws, a role model
for his progeny through 26 centuries.
</P>
<P>
   This is no excuse for Bill Clinton. What he did was wrong. He
knows that. But if the American people want to forgive their
president, as they seem to, who will deny them that right?
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth, a Democrat, is a former speaker of
the U.S. House of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box
1413, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1759EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0269 </DOCNO>
