</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOENBERG-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOENBERG ANNIVERSARY: WHIRLWIND OF ENERGY FOR A DISSONANT
MASTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I am not sure I have ever seen a group of musicians
stride onto a concert platform so joyful and eager as were the 15
players who burst through the stage entrance door at Merkin Hall on
Saturday night. And what were they to perform? Schoenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Only in New York, asserted the cellist Fred Sherry, who was
responsible for putting together a whole weekend of programs at
this venue to celebrate the 124th anniversary of Schoenberg's
birth. Maybe he was right. The city is home to scores of musicians
who are devoted, heart and soul, to the music not only of
Schoenberg but also of his most challenging successors. It is also
home to a large and willing audience that wants to hear this music.
</P>
<P>
   Our major musical institutions rarely want to recognize that
fact _ with the conspicuous exception now of the Metropolitan
Opera, which this season is presenting both Schoenberg's ``Moses
und Aron'' and Berg's ``Wozzeck'' and whose maestro, James Levine,
was at Merkin on Saturday to take part in the postperformance
discussion. Others should note that the hall was full for the work
the happy band of 15 was to play: Schoenberg's Chamber Symphony No.
1.
</P>
<P>
   The musicians' enthusiasm by no means stopped when they got
going. Rather, they thrust their phrases with maximum care and
effort into the Chamber Symphony's maelstrom of activity.
</P>
<P>
   There were incisive, battling strokes from the first violinist,
Rolf Schulte. Sherry himself showed that warmth can coexist with
speed. The clarinetist Alan R. Kay and the oboist Stephen Taylor
blended perfectly together. Donald Palma, on bass, produced some
beautiful harmonics.
</P>
<P>
   Tara Helen O'Connor, on piccolo in the closing pages, put the
sparkle on the mounting exhilaration. And finally the two horn
players, William Purvis and Christopher Komer, seemed to lift the
whole work into their hands and lob it over the finishing line.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the ensemble wobbled, as wobble it will when so much
is going on. And sometimes one might have wanted more dynamic
variation. Robert Craft, who had conducted, admitted this in the
postperformance discussion, remarking that it had been difficult to
get the players to hold back when they had been so overjoyed by
what they were doing. Everyone there, surely, was overjoyed too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
