<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDITORIUM-CLASH-2TAKES(1160)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR INTRAMURALS IN CHICAGO, THE PRIZE IS A THEATER
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO, Sept. 14 _ It is a conflict that has evoked pride and
betrayal, pettiness and high-mindedness, calling up a fair bit of
history and not a little money. Though neither side is evil, each
claims to be wronged. As a drama it might be stageworthy if it
didn't involve so much litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Gross, president of Roosevelt University, one of the
combatants, sized it up by invoking King Lear. ``Shakespeare said
it better than I ever could,'' he said. ``It's a case of filial
ingratitude.'' That would be one spin. The other is that Roosevelt
is greedily overstepping its bounds.
</P>
<P>
   The battle is over control of the 109-year-old Auditorium
Theater, one of this city's most prominent cultural venues. It is
owned by Roosevelt but has been managed for 38 years by the
Auditorium Theater Council, a community-based group that was formed
with the aid and encouragement of the university and then more or
less left alone to do its job.
</P>
<P>
   The council's sole functions have been the restoration and
operation of the theater, and it views the university's recent
attempts to assert the power of ownership by using theater funds
for nontheater purposes as anathema. ``The theater is a cash cow to
them,'' said Fred Eychaner, the council board member who is leading
the fight. ``The art and the architecture is clearly in second
place.''
</P>
<P>
   A magnificent 4,200-seat performance hall, designed by Louis
Sullivan and Dankmar Adler, the theater occupies some 40 percent of
the mammoth Auditorium Building downtown. It is a venue for
traveling Broadway shows and a growing variety of performances by
both internationally known and local arts groups. The Joffrey
Ballet, the Chicago Youth Symphony and dance troupes from Zimbabwe
and Japan are all on the schedule this season, and the
Broadway-bound revival of ``Oliver!'' is slated for next fall. But
the nature of its management and the future of its programming both
depend on the outcome of litigation that has gone on for four
years.
</P>
<P>
   Though the council has put $9 million worth of restoration work
into the theater and has $5.5 million in the bank, Roosevelt says
the council is not maximizing its earning potential or thinking big
enough. Gross hopes to turn the theater into a centerpiece for a
music and performance conservatory and to hire new management that
will make it a nationally important venue, perhaps a launching site
for extravagant touring shows, perhaps, like the Brooklyn Academy
of Music, an arts emporium with an idiosyncratic agenda that itself
becomes an attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it will be,'' Gross said. ``That will depend
on the vision of the people we put in charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the council decries those plans as
pie-in-the-sky and fears that a parade of high-grossing popular
shows will deprive local audiences of diverse programming and local
arts groups of their access to the space. The council also says
that such a programming plan is a questionable financial strategy
because three other large theaters are being built in the city and
Chicago's appetite for big musicals is unproven. In any case, the
issue is control, and it dates to 1960, when the council was
formed.
</P>
<P>
   Although the legal argument has grown grotesquely arcane, the
fundamental dispute is over the nature of the relationship forged
then between the university and the council. Namely, the question
is whether the initial agreement established the theater as a
public trust with the council as trustee. The council says yes,
that although the agreement does not specifically say so, it
created an implied trust and that other documents and letters
confirm that a trust is what the university intended.
</P>
<P>
   The university says this is simply ludicrous, that the council
is and always has been simply a committee of the university. ``When
people raise money for a place and operate it, they have an
understandable tendency towards proprietorship,'' Gross said.
``They think they own it. But they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt, founded in 1945 as an alternative to local colleges
that used racial quotas, struggled financially for many years but
is now an expanding university with an enrollment that has grown to
nearly 7,000. It has owned the Auditorium Building and used it as a
campus since shortly after the university's inception but did not,
in its early days, make use of the theater, and indeed allowed it
to fall into disrepair. In the late 50s, it invited proposals from
the public to take over the theater portion of the building.
</P>
<P>
   That resulted in the formation of the council, a group of
private citizens that included Roosevelt trustees. It raised $3
million, enough to reopen the theater in 1967, and has operated it
in the black through much though not all of the last three decades.
Still, it does not pay rent to Roosevelt, and in the deficit years,
during the 1980s, Roosevelt lent its support, helping to keep the
theater open.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between the two groups has been rocky from the
start, but until Gross' arrival in 1987 the university maintained a
largely hands-off policy, leaving the council to run the theater
without interference. But Gross made it known that he wanted
circumstances to change because, he said, the theater was not
serving the university to full advantage. ``The theater was left
alone for too long,'' he acknowledged last week. ``But why should
Roosevelt give up control of an asset that it owns? I don't think
any self-respecting university would make such a sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue boiled over in December 1994 when Gross tried to
appropriate $1.5 million in theater funds to help secure a loan for
Roosevelt's new campus in Schaumburg, a suburb northwest of the
city. The council, claiming that its cash assets reflect donations
by the public specifically meant for the theater, saw the move as a
power grab. ``You don't give money for breast cancer in order for
it to go to prostate cancer,'' said Jan Kallish, the council's
executive director. ``You don't give money for the theater and
expect it to be shipped out to a university in Schaumburg.''
</P>
<P>
   The council filed suit to stop the appropriation and, with
rising acrimony, the matter has been in the courts ever since. In
1995 a county court judge made a summary judgment in favor of
Roosevelt; in April 1997 the Illinois Appellate Court returned the
matter to the court for trial. This summer there were 10 weeks of
testimony. A ruling is expected on Sept. 28, but both sides say
that if they lose, they will appeal.
</P>
<P>
   An exasperated Gross said the $1.5 million was to be taken from
accumulated ticket revenues, not from public donations. And he
remains appalled by what he calls the ingratitude of the council
board. ``During the 1980s when the Auditorium Theater was in
deficit mode, Roosevelt stood by them,'' he said. ``We could easily
have shut the doors. We were there when they needed us. They
weren't there when we needed them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Both sides say their primary concern is the continued health of
the theater, with Roosevelt asserting that the theater can only
benefit if the university is as strong as it can be, and the
council saying that the university will never make the theater
enough of a priority to restore and manage it properly.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides say they want to settle, but on the issue of
controlling the theater's board and assets, the parties appear
intractable. ``We've talked settlement for four years,'' said
Stanley Eisenhammer, a lawyer for Gross. ``Every time we reach an
agreement, they pull back and ask for more.''
</P>
<P>
   The council's point of view? ``At one point we agreed to pay
more than we thought we should in exchange for a stipulation that a
certain amount of the theater's money would always be used for
restoration,'' Eychaner said. ``It was turned down unilaterally.
They said we weren't going to tell them what to do with the
building.''
</P>
</TEXT>
