<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Sept. 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vestiges of moisture from the ghost of Tropical Storm Frances
will join with a cool front Tuesday, setting the stage for
scattered showers and thunderstorms from the lower Great Lakes to
northwest New England. A few of the storms could produce brief
downpours and gusty winds, but the risk of severe weather will be
almost nil. Showers and isolated thunder will develop farther east
near the northern New England coast as a warm front presses slowly
toward the Canadian Maritimes.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly sunny, unseasonably hot, and humid weather will continue
across much of the Middle Atlantic and Southeast States as
sprawling high pressure holds steady over the region. Warm air
aloft associated with the high will suppress the vertical growth of
cumulus clouds, so that any afternoon thunderstorms that develop
will be solitary. However, on the high's weak western flank,
clusters of thundershowers will bubble up from the western Gulf of
Mexico coast to the middle Mississippi Valley within a narrow
corridor where humid air flows northward. The heaviest rain will
likely occur in Texas and Oklahoma, where low pressure near 18,000
feet incites currents of rapidly rising air.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered heavy thunderstorms will douse parts of southwest
Florida as a disturbance teams with local sea-breeze fronts to lift
tropical moisture. Rainfalls in excess of an inch are possible.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the West will be sunny to partly cloudy and tranquil.
Isolated thunder will develop in New Mexico, while patches of
morning fog begin the day along the Pacific Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Wet Desert
</P>
<P>
   In a typical September, rainfall at Las Vegas averages 0.28
inches, a meager total consistent with the city's desert climate.
With California's Sierra Nevada Mountains far to the west and the
lofty Spring Mountains just to the west effectively blocking
Pacific moisture, September rains are supported by a sporadic flow
of moisture from the south. This month, a persistent flow of
moisture from the tropics at high altitudes has fueled measurable
rain on seven of the first 13 days. The total of 1.29 inches of
rain already ranks this month as the city's fourth wettest
September on record.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
