<HEADLINE>
`ANNE FRANK: THE MISSING PAGES': A LOOK AT ANNE'S MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes at end of review. Time, channel are for New
York area. Check local listings.) 
(mk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a work that is treasured around the world for its glow of
youthful honesty, Anne Frank's diary has turned out to have more
than its share of contention, exploitation and evasion. Tuesday
night's documentary, ``Anne Frank: The Missing Pages,'' based on a
new biography by Melissa Mueller, draws attention to five censored
pages that Otto Frank, Anne's father and the keeper of her flame,
entrusted privately to a friend because they cast an uncomfortable
light on his relations with his wife, Edith.
</P>
<P>
   In what Ms. Mueller calls ``a stunning analysis of her
parents,'' Anne wrote that there was little sexual love between
them. Missing, Anne wrote, was ``the kind of love that I envisage
for a marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mueller, who has been denied permission to quote from the
new material in her book (``Anne Frank: The Biography,'' published
by Metropolitan Books, a division of Henry Holt), reports that
Frank had a ``first love'' whom his wife was never able to replace.
Tuesday night's program suggests that Otto may have married Edith,
who was from a well-to-do German family, for her money.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the facts of the case, the cheerful Edith glimpsed
Tuesday night in youthful photographs is virtually absent from the
diary known to so many millions of readers. Ms. Mueller says, ``By
leaving these pages out, Otto Frank actually betrayed his wife and
daughter, because this is the only passage in the diary where Anne
shows sympathy and understanding for her mother.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Missing Pages'' speculates on Anne's intentions in writing
and rewriting what the diary's custodians found to be an
``extremely unkind and unfair picture'' of her parents. Did she
come to think of her diary, composed as letters to a make-believe
friend, as a sketch for a novel? Did some of her reworkings reflect
the imagination of a developing writer as well as the changing
attitudes of a teen-ager whose feelings about her parents were
still unresolved?
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the abiding mystery of who betrayed the Frank family
to the Germans, Ms. Mueller directs suspicion at a cleaning woman
who was worried about her husband's being arrested and also may
have been seeking revenge for a son who was lost in the German
Navy.
</P>
<P>
   But as one researcher says Tuesday night, nothing in the new
material can much enhance or diminish the impact of the diary.
</P>
<P>
   The Franks were among many Jews betrayed to the Nazis, and the
details of their betrayal, like those of their domestic relations,
are easily overshadowed by Anne Frank's legacy. For that, see
Saturday night's episode of ``Biography,'' titled ``Anne Frank: The
Life of a Young Girl,'' at 8 o'clock on A&AMP;E.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `Investigative Reports: Anne Frank: The Missing Pages'
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday on A&AMP;E at 9 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   For Dateline Productions: Bernard Hammelburg, executive producer
and director; David Hammelburg, producer; Kim Celentano, associate
producer. For TV Matters: Daniel Hart and Jan Willem Bosman Jansen,
executive producers; Bruce Mundt, producer. For ID Cultuur: Piet
Erkelens and Harry de Winter, executive producers; Jean Marc van
Sambeek, associate producer. For A&AMP;E: Laura Fleur, coordinating
producer; Gayle Gilman, supervising producer; Michael Cascio,
executive producer. Produced by TV Matters BV, Dateline Productions
Inc., IDTV Cultuur and ORF Broadcasting in association with A&AMP;E
Network/USA, EO/Holland and ORF/Austria. For Investigative Reports:
Bill Kurtis, host and executive producer.
</P>
</TEXT>
