<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISCUITS AND OTHER REASONS TO RISE AND SHINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My daughters are my biggest fans, so I was a little more than
skeptical when Asha told me recently that I should quit my job and
just sell my biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   It's sort of like my sisters telling me I should just write
books. You have to wonder if their biscuits have been baked enough.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing I know for sure is that they love me an awful
lot, and for that I'm eternally grateful. Besides, not only do they
often provide substance for this column, they teach me things like,
well, how to make biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   It was a Saturday morning when I decided I could no longer wait
to go to Mississippi to have them. Biscuits, I mean.
</P>
<P>
   I called Nancy, whom I consider the best cook among my five
sisters (after myself, of course), and asked her how to make
biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get you some self-rising flour and milk and oil, and you
stir it and stir it and stir it,'' she told me.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, but, how much flour and oil and milk, and after I'm done
stirring it and stirring it, how long do I bake it?'' I asked.
``What do I put the oven on?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, about 350,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Did I tell you that, out of all of my sisters, Nancy is the
sweetest? Who else would offer instructions like that but a
sweetheart?
</P>
<P>
   I did make biscuits that day. They rose, they were golden brown,
a little crusty on the outside, but edible. I was determined to
master this rather sketchy recipe, so every Saturday for the next
several months, I made Jimmy, Jamila and Asha my guinea pigs.
</P>
<P>
   They were gracious. They ate them. They offered compliments, but
I knew these were not Nancy's biscuits. These weren't even the
biscuits my sister Dianne could bake.
</P>
<P>
   I retreated and started to offer my family the uncanned version
from the grocer's freezer. I felt like a failure. Even my baby
brother, Ronald, was making biscuits for his family. In fact, he'd
become rather well-known for making one really big one for each
member of his family.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate, it occurred to me that although Dianne didn't always
get them right, she was the sister who got a certain pleasure out
of giving instructions. Whatever she told me, I knew I could make
this recipe mine. Just like I had with the poundcake recipe, the
turkey stuffing and banana pudding.
</P>
<P>
   Now Dianne would teach me to make mouth-watering biscuits. At 7
a.m. on a Saturday morning about a month ago, I got her on the
phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing up so early?'' she asked in amazement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want biscuits,'' I said, my ingredients and daughters
already in position.
</P>
<P>
   In about 15 minutes, she had talked me through a perfect pan of
biscuits. It was on! For the next month, every Saturday morning, I
was up at 7 making biscuits. Two weeks ago, my biscuits had their
coming-out. It was time to test them on my sister Jo.
</P>
<P>
   My biscuits? They're the bomb!
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't it the Duke of Edinburgh who said, ``I never see any home
cooking. All I get is fancy stuff''?
</P>
<P>
   The poor duke. Obviously, he never had sisters or daughters, and
I happen to have the best. They believe I can do anything. Sell my
biscuits? Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   But I could never put a price on being in the kitchen with my
daughters and flour, or on sharing recipes with my sisters. Jo and
I still laugh about Nancy's instructions: ``Stir it and stir it and
stir it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments like these do not happen often enough.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gbs(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
