<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Tuesday, Sept. 15. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ECON (New York) _ President Clinton on Monday called for
a meeting of the finance ministers and central bankers from the G7
and key emerging economies to discuss the spreading global economic
crisis. Urging top economies to boost growth, Clinton also
instructed Treasury Secretary Rubin and Fed Chairman Greenspan to
convene a meeting within 30 days on global financial institutions.
By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PASTORS (Undated) _ At least two clergymen will become
advisers to Clinton on moral issues.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCHOOLS (New York) _ For teachers of literature and
social studies _ at Bronx Science, as well as at schools around the
region and across the rest of the country _ the tawdry details
contained in the Starr report and their Constitutional import
presented any number of dilemmas yesterday: whether to discuss the
rapidly unfolding events in Washington at all, if so how much and
what to do if some student decided to ask about the particulars of
oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CLINTON (New York) _ Clinton gets a warm reception in New
York, where he came to appeal for funds while still grappling with
the findings of the Starr report. Besides attending midday
fund-raiser at East Side apartment, the president gave a speech at
the Council of Foreign Relations and was to attend an evening
performance of the Lion King. By N.R. Kleinfield.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ Developments on Prime Minister Primakov's
economic team and policies. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ELECT (New York) _ The last full day of campaigning for
Senate, governor and attorney general in New York state,
complicated by President Clinton's visit here for a speech and for
a fundraiser. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   WALLACE-ALABAMA (Dateline tk, Ala.) _ On the end of an era in
Alabama with the death of George Wallace. We talk to politicians
and historians, but also to the sort of ordinary people who once
put him in office to see how they feel now. Just as Wallace himself
had changed, so has the state of Alabama. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-HISPANICS (New York) _ While white and black single
mothers have left the welfare rolls in droves over the last three
years, the number of Hispanic women on public assistance has held
almost stubbornly steady. And the disparity highlights a widening
ethnic divide among New York City's poorest families.
</P>
