<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: KEVIN SPACEY JOINS THEATER BOARD; AWARDS AT VENICE
FILM FESTIVAL; MASUR ANNIVERSARY CONCERT; MEMORIAL TO KUROSAWA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people leave their hearts in San Francisco, but Kevin
Spacey has a warm spot in his for London. The actor, who triumphed
as Hickey in O'Neill's ``The Iceman Cometh'' at the little Almeida
Theater in the city's Islington section and then moved with the
drama to the 1,000-seat Old Vic near Waterloo Station, is joining
the board of the historic Old Vic. One of the world's most famous
stages, the Old Vic was spared its final curtain this summer by a
charitable trust created to preserve it.
</P>
<P>
   Closing Credits
</P>
<P>
   The Venice Film Festival, whose top award is the Golden Lion,
wound up in something of an uproar on Sunday. The festival's
director, Felice Laudadio, called the competition ``stupid and
arrogant'' and resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Beatty, whose political satire ``Bulworth'' was in the
competition, got a surprise when he was chosen for a lifetime
achievement award.
</P>
<P>
   The Gold Lion went to ``The Way We Laughed,'' directed by Gianni
Amelio. The bittersweet story of two brothers from Sicily who move
to Italy's industrial north was the first Italian film in a decade
to win the festival's top prize.
</P>
<P>
   Other honors went to Sean Penn, named best actor for
``Hurlyburly''; Catherine Deneuve, best actress for ``Place
Vendome''; Emir Kusturica, best director for ``Black Cat, White
Cat,'' and Eric Rohmer, cited for best original screenplay, for
``Conte d'Automne.''
</P>
<P>
   Marking Time
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fifty years ago, in September 1948, a 21-year-old
conductor made his debut leading the Landestheater Halle in
Germany. His name was Kurt Masur, and on Wednesday night he will
honor that occasion by leading the New York Philharmonic at Avery
Fisher Hall in the opening concert of its 157th season.
</P>
<P>
   The all-Beethoven program, including the Symphony No. 1, begins
a complete traversal of Beethoven's nine symphonies in five
programs over three weeks, ending on Oct. 3. The cycle is the
orchestra's first since its 100th anniversary in 1941, when it was
led by Arturo Toscanini.
</P>
<P>
   The concert is also a salute to the violinist Isaac Stern.
Stern, who first performed with the Philharmonic in 1944, has since
made more than 100 solo appearances with the orchestra. In a
program that also includes the ``Fidelio'' Overture, he will
perform two Romances for violin and orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Homage
</P>
<P>
   Some 35,000 fans and guests bade an emotional farewell to the
director Akira Kurosawa at a memorial service on Sunday at his
studio in Yokohama, Japan. About 4,000 guests inside the studio
heard an eulogy delivered from the gold-room set used for one of
the director's greatest films, ``Ran.'' Kurosawa, whose works
include ``Seven Samurai,'' ``Kagemusha,'' ``Rashomon'' and
``Yojimbo,'' died on Sept. 6 at 88.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
