<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4546 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUTCHESON-COLUMN-TEX     09-14 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUTCHESON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS ARE THE MAIN THERMOMETER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If you're trying to gauge how much trouble
President Clinton is in, don't pay any attention to the
Republicans. Listen to the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hard facts of life in Washington is that your enemies
can't hurt you nearly as much as your friends. No one resigns from
office because they are under attack from their political
opponents. They resign when their allies go AWOL.
</P>
<P>
   It happened to Richard Nixon. It happened to Jim Wright. Now
it's happening to Clinton. Democrats are not in full-scale retreat
yet, but the troops are getting skittish.
</P>
<P>
   The lurid details and explosive allegations in the report
submitted to Congress by independent counsel Kenneth Starr will
only add to the panic attack. If the polls show that the public is
turning against Clinton and his party, presidential apologies are
likely to fall on deaf ears as Democrats try to avoid an Election
Day meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   The grumbling in the ranks started long before Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn., denounced Clinton's behavior in a blistering
Senate speech. But Lieberman's decision to go public proved that
Democrats have nothing to lose and plenty to gain by distancing
themselves from the president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged as much by agreeing with Lieberman that the
White House sex scandal resulted from immoral, wrong and
unacceptable behavior. The president also uttered the words ``I'm
sorry'' for the first time since he acknowledged his relationship
with former intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's comments are mild compared to some of the more
recent criticism directed at Clinton by members of his own party.
</P>
<P>
   Although most Democrats are not ready to toss Clinton overboard,
they clearly have no intention of going down with the ship.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's experience is instructive. At the start of 1974, only 37
percent of Americans favored Nixon's impeachment. Most
congressional Republicans embraced Nixon's view that the Democrats
were out to get him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't confuse me with the facts,'' Rep. Earl Landgrebe,
R-Ind., one of the president's die-hard fans, told reporters as the
Watergate scandal reached a climax. ``I've got a closed mind. I
will not vote for impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first issues that Congress had to resolve was
establishing the grounds for Nixon's removal. What, exactly, does
the Constitution mean when it says that a president can be
impeached for ``treason, bribery, high crimes and misdemeanors''?
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Nixon's lawyers argued that impeachment should
be used only in cases involving criminal conduct. Others concluded
that the Constitution's framers wanted to include conduct that
might not violate any law but that does violate the standards that
Americans expect of their president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Underlying all the constitutional relationships we talk about
is the necessity for standards of honesty, truth and integrity,''
said Paul Sarbanes, a Maryland Democrat who was then a member of
the House and now is a senator. ``Our own system of free government
cannot operate if those standards are not honored.''
</P>
<P>
   With time, most lawmakers concluded that Nixon's conduct fit
either definition of an impeachable offense. Nixon's determination
to fight evaporated as his stalwart defenders abandoned him in the
face of mounting evidence of presidential wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 5 p.m. Aug. 7, 1974, three prominent Republicans _
Sen. Barry Goldwater of Arizona, Senate Minority Leader Hugh Scott
of Pennsylvania and House Minority Leader John Rhodes of Arizona _
met with Nixon in the White House and told him that he could not
longer count on Republican support. The next day, Nixon announced
that he would resign.
</P>
<P>
   (Ron Hutcheson is Washington bureau chief for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at rhutcheson(at)krwashington.com
or call him at (202) 383-6000. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1813EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
