<P>
   &UR; THE STARR REPORT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-REPORT (Washington) -- Democrats warn President Clinton
his defense strategy in the Monica Lewinsky case may be crumbling.
By Brian McGrory. 1500 words. (w coding)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRIVACY (Undated) -- Washington is wondering what names,
accusations, and sordid details lurk in the 2,000 pages of
unreleased ``supporting documents.'' By Peter Canellos 1200 words.
(a)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ECONOMIC (New York) -- President Clinton projects an
image of business as usual, speaking to the Council on Foreign
Relations and headlining fundraisers designed to replenish
Democratic Party coffers. By Ann Scales. 1200 words. (a)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LEWINSKY (Washington) -- Women, young and old, will
assign Monica Lewinsky her place in history, deciding whether she,
too, owes the country an apology. By By Ellen O'Brien. 1000 words.
(a)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-NEXT (Washington) -- A few key sentences in the Starr
report may provide clues about the prosecutor's next steps,
including a focus on President Clinton's relationship with former
White House volunteer Kathleen Willey. By Michael Kranish. 1200
words. (w)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SWISSAIR-VALUABLES (Halifax, N.S.) -- A Picasso painting,
diamonds and possibly millions of dollars in currency and gold are
resting in the twisted wreckage of Swissair Flight 111. By Tatsha
Robertson. (i and a coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOCTORS-MANAGED (Undated) -- US doctors overwhelmingly dislike
managed care, mainly because of restrictions on their income and
autonomy, not because of limits on care and policies that hamper
quality of care. By Richard A. Knox. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-PRIMARY (Boston) -- The primary campaign comes to a close
with candidates crisscrossing the state rallying supporters.
Secretary of State predicts a 30 percent turnout, but even that low
figure could prove optimistic. By Adrian Walker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS-RISE (New York) -- Stock market around the world rise
sharply, bouyed by weekend polls that showed a majority of
Americans want President Clinton to finish his term despite the
Monica Lewinsky scandal. By Peter B. Gosselin. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
