<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4554 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREEP-INTERVIEW-COX     09-14 2383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREEP-INTERVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Streep just acts, doesn't care for all the fuss
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_How do you start to write about the best actress in the
world?
</P>
<P>
   It helps to take a tip from the woman herself, Meryl Streep.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband has taught me a great thing,'' she says, talking
about the jitters she gets when she's about to play a new role.
``He's an artist, and he goes into his studio every day and
confronts that space, with nothing in it. And he just says, `Start
by starting.' Now I always say that to myself: `Just start.'''
</P>
<P>
   Okay then, let's start with the resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine this: Moviegoers here have just wet a few hankies (and
shirtsleeves) watching Streep battle cancer in an early screening
of ``One True Thing,'' opening Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes later, she strolls down the theater aisle, smiling
and very much alive. Then for a half-hour she answers questions
about the movie, based on Anna Quindlen's book and co-starring
Renee Zellweger and William Hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing Streep in public isn't a typical Meryl moment. Famously
private, she doesn't often feed the Hollywood PR machine. She
prefers staying in Connecticut with her sculptor husband, Don
Gummer, and their four kids.
</P>
<P>
   Even while promoting her new movie, she'd rather not slow things
down by posing for photographers. ``I've had more pictures taken of
me than President Clinton,'' she sighs.
</P>
<P>
   You can tell she doesn't care for all the fuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's first and foremost an actor and secondly a star,'' says
Pat O'Connor, who directed her in ``Dancing at Lughnasa,'' opening
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was totally intimidated,'' says ``One True Thing'' director
Carl Franklin in describing how he felt when he knew he would be
working with Streep. ``There are certain people who have a big
reputation, but when you meet them you're disappointed. They come
down to size. Meryl doesn't do that. She's a formidable presence.
... She's sweet, and she's down to earth. But she's somebody who
doesn't make mistakes. She measures up to her reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Streep never plays Streep in her movies. She disappears: a
country factory worker (``Silkwood''), Danish writer (``Out of
Africa''), Australian mother (``A Cry in the Dark''), Polish
survivor (``Sophie's Choice'') or Italian-American housewife (``The
Bridges of Madison County'').
</P>
<P>
   When the film's producer asked Quindlen what she thought about
Streep, ``I said, `Is there more than one answer to that
question?''' the novelist recalls. ``What can you say? Each time
you look up at the screen, she was a totally different human being.
When she signed on, I told my family, and my oldest son said,
`That's so great, but do you think she can do an American
accent?''' He was convinced she was British. Quindlen had to tell
him, no, honey, she grew up in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Today, without her fabled accents or a wig, Streep almost seems
adrift just being herself. She sits for an interview here wearing a
light plum-colored suit, grayish glass beads around her neck. She
stands up again and smooths the back of her jacket, a slight
nervous adjustment. At 49, her age shows only in a few laugh lines
around her eyes. A blue vein pulses dimly in her cheek, visible
through that translucent skin. It's the sort of skin that lets
thoughts and emotions drift across it, like wind on water.
</P>
<P>
   As Streep speaks, her hands carve graceful arcs in the air.
Because she doesn't give many interviews, her replies are fresh;
there's a sense that she's discovering her own answers as they
come. None of the tired soundbites.
</P>
<P>
   And she's funny. Sometimes when she knows better.
</P>
<P>
   Like the night before. At the Q&AMP;A, she quipped that she liked
how haggard she looks in the tear-jerking finale of ``One True
Thing'' because she looks so thin.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she hides her face. ``That was so sick, I regretted that
so much. I really did.'' A pause, a smile: ``But it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing the role of someone with cancer is something she knows
about. In the '70s, she nursed her lover, actor John Cazale, as he
died from bone cancer. She's seen it up close. She knows it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's holy,'' she says. ``It's really what life is about. It's
where it goes. I respect it, and I wanted to make sure they got it
right.''
</P>
<P>
   She's a little tired and anxious to get through the morning's
interviews. Flying into Atlanta the day before, her plane bumped
down through a sudden storm. Today, Hurricane Earl is creeping up
from the Gulf, and Streep wants to head out of the city as early as
she can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a bad flyer,'' she admits. ``That's because I have four
children and I really want to be here tomorrow. Here, in the world,
alive. It's a meat-and-potatoes issue for me.''
</P>
<P>
   You may not think meat and potatoes when it comes to Streep, but
that's one of her contradictions. She can play champagne; she can
play beer. She's racked up 10 Oscar nominations (only two shy of
Katharine Hepburn's record) while raising a family (yes, she does
laundry).
</P>
<P>
   And she's a mother first, actress second. She flew home to
northwest Connecticut by helicopter after every day's shooting on
``One True Thing,'' committed to making it home for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   When visiting the set, Quindlen says, ``I talked to Renee about
the scene they were shooting. Meryl and I talked about where our
kids were going to high school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Her main consideration was always what was needed at home,''
Franklin says. ``That's one of the things you have to take into
account, working with her. Part of what makes her a bit of an
enigma is that she is a very private person and she's not one to go
play the studio game and be glib.''
</P>
<P>
   Meryl the Mom
</P>
<P>
   Ask her about her kids, and she's a mix of pride and precaution.
Family is family. It's separate. That's why she's never let
magazines like Architectural Digest do a spread on her home. She
suddenly seems to whiff something rank. ``Oh what a nightmare! Why
would anybody want to have all these people come into their
house?''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard enough finding privacy in a house with four kids,
``For a long time, the toilet was the only place I could get by
myself. If I remembered to lock the door. I also have a little
window seat my husband built me on the back of my office. I love to
sit there.''
</P>
<P>
   People sometimes marvel at Streep's ability to combine family
life and career. She shrugs it off. ``I live the only way I can
live and stay sane. Relatively,'' she adds. ``You know?''
</P>
<P>
   So would she be glad if one of her kids decided to be an actor?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' she says, leaning in conspiratorially, ``my son was in
`Death of a Salesman' his senior year. He was Biff.'' She cuts her
voice to a whisper: ``I have to keep my voice down, because he's in
there,'' she says, pointing to the adjoining door. (Henry, 18,
accompanied her on the tour.) ``Although, you know,'' she adds,
``it's gonna be in a newspaper, (so) what am I whispering for?''
</P>
<P>
   Straightening up, she clears her throat and makes a decision.
``I'm not gonna talk about this, because he would not appreciate
it. But ...'' And here she simply mouths the words: ``He's a
wonderful actor.''
</P>
<P>
   With a mock melodramatic moan, she adds, ``I thought, `Oh, I'm a
failure as a mother.' I've been pointing them in all sorts of
interesting directions. The natural history museum: `Think about
being an anthropologist.' Or financial planning. Accounting.''
</P>
<P>
   Momdom has kept Streep off the theater stage for 16 years,
except for a two-week workshop in Seattle for friend Wendy
Wasserstein's play ``An American Daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Streep was afraid of performing live after so long, but ``I
loved it! Oh my God, oh my God, I loved it. And I realized how much
I'd given up for my children.'' The last words come out again in a
mock-grand, wounded voice. Her youngest is only 8, so it may be 10
more years until she can try the stage again. ``I can't even say
it, but it seems to mean that, yeah,'' she says. ``They don't care
what I'm doing during the day. They just want me home at night.''
</P>
<P>
   She may be a great parent, but her own mom makes fun of her.
``My mother says, `You have raised four only children.' I have
three girls. Everything is a big drama. But it's great. They're so
interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   The two youngest girls' fave movie lately: ``Dance With Me,'' a
love story, starring Vanessa L. Williams, set in the world of
ballroom dancing. ``We're all in love with (co-star) Chayanne
now,'' Streep says. ``Big, major.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most, her kids have the don't-embarrass-me-Mom syndrome.
They hate it if Streep, a trained singer who was once slated to
play ``Evita'' on-screen, sings around the house or in the car.
</P>
<P>
   But during the interview comes the unmistakable warble of a
young man in the room next door. Her son. So the kids can sing; she
can't.
</P>
<P>
   Streep smiles ruefully. ``Therein lies the dreadful irony,
because the world is about them. Your world (as a kid) is not about
your parents, it's about you. And that's the way it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Some years back, Streep punched a photographer who was trying to
shoot one of her kids. ``I'm a public figure,'' she says. ``You can
write anything you want about me. But they are not. They should be
able to make their own mistakes, and if somebody writes about them
I will sue their pants off.''
</P>
<P>
   Okay then. Next subject:
</P>
<P>
   Meryl the Actress
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason you hire Meryl is if you want to get the best
actress in the world,'' says director O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   But good luck asking Streep the secret to her success. ``There's
not a lot of mystical conversation about the way she works,''
Franklin says. ``Her process goes on in private. There's only so
much you can explain about what she does. There's something else at
work there that may be more in the category of `gift.' It defies
explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   So nobody knows what makes Streep so good. ``Neither do I,'' she
says with a hint of bewilderment. ``I don't know how it really
works. I don't know how other people do it. I see de Niro writing
lots of things in the margins of his script, but I don't know what
he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   She read a book by writer-director David Mamet about acting.
``But I couldn't locate myself in one page of it,'' Streep says.
``To me, it felt like surgery on the outside of your body. I
couldn't incorporate it into what I understand. It's sort of
inchoate, my process.''
</P>
<P>
   With a self-mocking grand diva voice, she repeats, ``My
process.'' And laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's magic, how actors do this,'' she continues.
``There's a little bit of craziness in it. There's a little bit of
what goes out of control ... with multiple-personality people. The
brain, the emotional, imaginative connection is very inscrutable to
me. I don't question it. But I do always feel completely daunted at
the beginning by the fact that I don't have a method.''
</P>
<P>
   So despite the Oscars and accolades, Streep can still be
surprisingly vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Making Meryl cry
</P>
<P>
   Take the shoot of ``Dancing at Lughnasa.'' Of the five actors
playing Irish sisters, three were British, only one was Irish, and
Streep was the sole American. A dialect coach was hired to monitor
their accents. And Streep remembers seeing him shake his head in
dismay while listening as she acted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a complete breakdown,'' she says. ``I cried for two
weeks _ ask Roy, my makeup man. I really had like a complete
dismantling. And it's because I don't have a method that I've
articulated for myself. So I understood how fragile my process is,
how ephemeral, that it can be stolen away by basically a lack of
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   It makes sense to O'Connor. ``The reason Meryl is at the top of
her game (as an actor) is that great talent like that is very
sensitive.'' Even when she's not acting.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Streep felt ambushed watching ``The Truman Show,''
when she learned that the sunny actress/wife played by Laura Linney
is named ``Meryl Burbank.'' (Her own name is a combo of her first
names, Mary and Louise.)
</P>
<P>
   ``That hurt my feelings _ I mean, if I'm gonna admit things,''
she says. ``It did. It was a weird choice of a name.''
</P>
<P>
   But certainly the choice was meant as a sort of tribute to her
status. ``Meryl'' is now synonymous with ``Actress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, but what was it supposed to represent in that movie?'' she
asks. ``I guess it represents'' _ she switches into a saccharine,
cheerful voice _ ``perky perfection in some horrible way, which is
really not the way I feel in my skin.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the emotional dangers of being an actor _ and
getting jibed at in somebody else's movie _ performing a scene
right, nailing it, makes it worthwhile. And Streep knows when that
happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yes, yes!'' she leans back in her chair as if reliving the
experience. ``It's just the sweetest feeling, and you feel it all
over your little self, head to toe. You know you're all done. You
can go have a doughnut now. It's why people keep going back to
acting, even if they are not making any money, the play fails, or
the movie doesn't get distributed. You do it for that hit. It's
just irresistible.''
</P>
<P>
   So how do you sum up Streep, 20 years into her career?
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a wonderful person to work with,'' O'Connor says. Then
he adds, apologetically, ``That's the guff you journalists always
have to listen to. But in this case, it's absolutely meant.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's Quindlen's take: ``What must it be like to be absolutely
the best at what you do in the whole world? You'd think she'd be a
terrible human being, but in fact she's just the best.''
</P>
<P>
   But there will always be a certain unknowability of Streep. Even
one of her brothers (she has two) has said that the Streep family
is hard to get to know.
</P>
<P>
   So here comes the stare-into-her-eyes, Barbara Walters style
question: Who is Meryl Streep?
</P>
<P>
   The actress takes a pause, and you can tell she doesn't know
whether to laugh the question off _ or be embarrassed that people
want to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm me,'' she says simply. ``People who know me don't have to
ask that. And people who don't know me are not gonna find out in a
three-minute answer.''
</P>
<P>
   And here it comes again, that what's-the-fuss, get-over-it,
I'm-just-Meryl laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
