<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-ESSAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WILD, THE SUBLIME, THE REAL AND THE ARTIFICIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. _ By now, summertime adventures
are being put aside for more urbane cultural concerns, but for me
that may be difficult. In my mind, I am still trudging up a jagged
mountain path, sidestepping mule dung and negotiating slick rocks
in the late summer heat. With every turn come vistas I doubt will
be displaced in my mind by any music heard or art seen in coming
months: massive granite contusions carved by ancient glaciers;
sheer, glistening slopes of stone shining with cascades of water;
glimpses of earth's supple musculature upon which one walks
tentatively, humbly, struck dumb by its powers.
</P>
<P>
   I am more cautious than John Muir was more than a century ago
when he climbed these mountains without the benefit of marked paths
and chiseled stone steps. Muir, who founded the Sierra Club, wrote
eloquent paeans to the American wilderness, particularly to
Yosemite, where he found ``majestic operations of nature''
appearing alongside ``the frailest, most gentle and peaceful
things.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested strapping one's mountain shoes tight and bounding
ecstatically from boulder to boulder down the slopes: ``You will
then find your feet playing a tune, and quickly discover the music
and poetry of rock-piles.''
</P>
<P>
   But I am afraid of that Siren music, and walk gingerly to a
rock's edge at the peak of Nevada Falls, vertiginously gazing down
at the rushing waters and up again at the looming rock faces,
unable to encompass in my imagination the scale of things, admiring
the beauty, shaken by the immensity. The scene's timelessness turns
time into trivia; intimations of immortality inspire hints of the
opposite.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteenth- and 19th-century philosophers called this effect the
``sublime,'' and at one time artists and musicians yearned to
imitate its powers in painting and sound. The sublime overwhelms,
bewilders, frightens, chastises and elevates. It courts one's
understanding, yet defies one's imagination.
</P>
<P>
   The sublime may not be in artistic fashion these days _ what
role can it have in a world of postmodern tastes? _ but judging
from Yosemite there is a gargantuan appetite for it. An estimated
4.5 million people are expected to visit the park this year. I
encountered several thousand when descending from the falls to
lower, more accessible terrain. Sublime it is. Solitary it isn't.
We are all migrating here for a purpose, not necessarily seeking
solitude, but yearning for something _ the wilderness sublime _
that inspires a peculiar feeling about one's humanity and its
fragile grandeur in the face of greater things.
</P>
<P>
   Religions have tapped that desire. Some of these mountains here
are even called cathedrals. In recent decades, popular culture has
begun filling the gap that art promised to fill, creating man-made
substitutes for those who can't get their dose of canyons and
cataracts. Like the natural version of the wilderness sublime,
these cultural creations _ Imax films and special-effects cinematic
spectaculars _ present images that confound the human imagination
and seem beyond human control. They alter the scale on which we
judge ourselves. They exhilarate and frighten us, amaze and humble
us and invoke great forces that we cannot fully anticipate or
control. Forget profundity and beauty; such matters are stripped
away for the sake of raw effect. So many people line up for this
artificial sensation, it might be called the commercial sublime.
</P>
<P>
   But the commercial sublime is present not only in films like
``Titanic'' and ``Armaggedon.'' It can also be found in even more
mundane incarnations, one of which I stumbled on during the same
trip that brought me to this mountain: Disneyland.
</P>
<P>
   This might seem, at first, absurd. After all, Disneyland, a
six-hour drive away, seems to be the opposite of these mountains,
not their counterpart. Instead of offering a landscape that dwarfs
the human, it offers a townscape that is dwarfed by the human. The
buildings in Disneyland are smaller than full size, compressed to
create a sense of the viewer's fairy-tale superiority.
</P>
<P>
   The medieval castle of Fantasyland is no Bavarian structure
towering over a ravine, but a scaled toy model. The amusement
park's vast ``lands'' are remarkably contained and navigable: no
immensity here.
</P>
<P>
   But this makes the impact of the attractions themselves, hidden
behind the facades, all the more powerful. I am lured onto the Big
Thunder Mountain Railroad, which looks neither big nor thunderous
nor mountainous. The cart I am in veers into the plastic landscape,
but, instead of seeing grand vistas, I twist off balance, drop
precipitously into a miniature free fall and lurch like some
drunken John Muir attempting a boulder dance. There is a moment
when it seems too much for the human system _ my bearings are lost,
I am subject to some greater force, fear sends an electric shock
through my body _ and then, just as suddenly, the moment passes
into laughter and I am ready to pay homage to those big, thunderous
and mountainous effects.
</P>
<P>
   It is an artificial version of the sense I have laboriously
climbing to the top of Nevada Falls in Yosemite, every turn
yielding gasps at the changing shapes of rock and water, fear mixed
with fascination, not just at beauty but at the wildness of it all.
In comparison, human desires are puny things. Maybe Disneyland
aspires, in part, to such a sentiment (as long as it leaves those
commercial desires intact).
</P>
<P>
   This may be why its various ``lands'' so self-consciously invoke
the wild and untamed _ Adventureland, Frontierland, Tomorrowland. A
spaceship is out of control; an explorer is lost in a cavern; a
raft crashes down a roaring waterfall. Natural forces are invoked
and imitated, and the viewer is artificially dwarfed by their
seeming immensity. It is no accident that one of the more
astonishing ``rides'' is a three-dimensional virtual-reality show
called ``Honey, I Shrunk the Audience,'' in which the viewers
actually begin to feel as if they are being carried around in a
box.
</P>
<P>
   But once these experiences end, the sublime perspectives are
inverted, and riders stumble warily into a comforting world in
which everything is even more manageable and more controlled than
in ordinary life.
</P>
<P>
   The thrill is, of course, less lasting and far less resonant
that that of Yosemite's vistas, but there are times I wonder even
about even that wilderness. We camp in a tent, 100 yards from flush
toilets and 10 yards from another store-bought domicile or
recreational van; we store our toothpaste and trail mix in metal
lockers at the campsite to protect them from the imperial appetites
of swaggering bears. And we walk on laboriously constructed paths
that permit no fatal missteps.
</P>
<P>
   Even this is perhaps an artificial wilderness, a stage set with
appropriate crowd control. One almost begins to envy Muir's
solitude, his strolls through the meadows and sequoia groves, his
easy acquaintance with nature's creatures and forces. But partly
because of his efforts on behalf of wilderness, we are at least
given this managed piece of it.
</P>
<P>
   Which is just enough to spur the appetite for more. For on the
trails, above the shuttle buses and cafeterias, again and again
comes that aching vision in which space and time become tactile
immensities. And human culture, with all its high- and low-minded
enterprise, is temporarily put in its place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
