<HEADER>
A4561 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TURANDOT-500&AMP;AD     09-14 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TURANDOT-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TURANDOT' BIDS FAREWELL TO BEIJING, THE `HOME' IT AWED AND
PERPLEXED
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ After eight performances _ actually seven and
two-thirds, because one was halted by rain _ the much-anticipated
production of ``Turandot'' in an ancient temple of the Forbidden
City here closed on Sunday night to a lengthy standing ovation from
a nearly full house approaching 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   If the sumptuous costumes, lavish set and kinetic staging by the
Chinese movie director Zhang Yimou sometimes seemed to upstage the
music _ conducted by Zubin Mehta with singing by major stars _ the
thousands of opera fanatics who traveled here from Europe, the
United States and neighboring Asian countries still got what they
paid for: a grand theatrical spectacle that will be hard to match.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beautiful,'' sighed Dr. Abdul Allam, a surgeon who came
from Switzerland with his wife, Almut Allam, president of the
Connecticut Opera in Hartford. ``The grandiosity of the temple, the
costumes _ it's just unbelievable,'' Allam said. ``And the sound is
excellent, with no echo.''
</P>
<P>
   Although few Chinese are steeped in Western opera, Zhang's
interest in the project and his goal of making the opera more
authentically Chinese was widely noted here. ``Chinese feel proud
that on their own land the Chinese culture is playing a major role
on the international stage,'' said one typical article in the
Beijing Youth Daily newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the $15 million production had gone, Michael Ecker,
the Austrian impresario who pulled it together, said that
``artistically, it was a great success.''
</P>
<P>
   The financial story is less clear. Ecker said that 87 percent of
the seats had been sold but that corporate sponsorships, high-end
sales and donations had been lower than expected, which he blamed
on the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Ecker said that until he received an accounting from the China
Performing Arts Agency, which was a co-sponsor of the production
and controlled many tickets, he could not assess the financial
situation, which would include revenues from television and
recording rights as well as ticket sales. ``I hope we'll break
even,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The official video and compact disc of the performance will be
released on Oct. 11 by BMG Classics, Ecker said, and a film of the
production is to be shown in the United States on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   On the last night, a few scalpers were selling what they said
were $350 tickets for $50, and they had some takers among some
Westerners. The scalped tickets presumably came from the hundreds
distributed free to people in the government.
</P>
<P>
   The crowds included many Chinese who obtained free tickets and
who came out of curiosity. Many shared the view of one businessman
who attended on Sunday and said, ``I just don't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the scenery seemed to dazzle everyone. ``Zhang
Yimou is a genius,'' said one young Chinese office manager, who
professed to not understand a single word.
</P>
<P>
   Opera fans or not, some of Beijing's more affluent inhabitants
saw ``Turandot'' as a social event not to be missed, and many
celebrities from the literary and art worlds turned out, especially
for one of the earlier shows that was reserved for Beijing
residents at reduced rates.
</P>
<P>
   In the sort of biting article rarely seen here, a popular
newspaper, Southern Weekend, wrote, ``The only ones who pretended
any interest in hearing the performance were those media types who
were mingling with the foreigners between acts.''
</P>
<P>
   The article added: ``The tickets for `Turandot' were expensive
and hard to get. And for this very reason some people just had to
go and see it, and what's more were certainly not going to buy
their own tickets. Otherwise you wouldn't be flaunting your status
and influence.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the few Chinese reviews of the production, in the
English-language China Daily, Li Xing wrote that the performance
offered ``a busy feast for the eye,'' and that ``opera lovers had
the luxury of basking in Puccini's splendid choruses and the
resounding accompaniment of the orchestra under the brilliant
conducting of Zubin Mehta.''
</P>
<P>
   ``However, the production has not gone beyond creating a
theatrical spectacle,'' Ms. Li added, saying that the audience was
too busy watching all the scene changes and extras moving about to
``sink deep into the arias.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
