<HEADER>
A4564 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOYO-MUSIC-LADN     09-14 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOYO-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MA TACKLES MOTHER OF GOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Having recently tackled tango and bluegrass,
Yo-Yo Ma certainly wasn't resting on his laurels when he decided to
take on yet another new genre: music written for the Mother of God.
</P>
<P>
   A formidable assignment, to be sure. But that hadn't stopped
British composer John Tavener. In his 1987 piece ``The Protecting
Veil,'' Tavener had sought to explore the mysteries of the Russian
Orthodox faith while creating what he termed ``a lyrical icon in
sound rather than in wood, using the music of the cello rather than
a brush.''
</P>
<P>
   As the most iconic cellist of the jet age, Ma was the natural
choice to attempt Tavener's wrenchingly ecstatic work. The result
was a Sony Classical recording with the Baltimore Symphony
Orchestra, released this year.
</P>
<P>
   But playing the work live was a different matter, says Ma,
who'll perform ``The Protecting Veil'' with the Los Angeles Chamber
Orchestra in concert tonight at the Hollywood Bowl. Jeffrey Kahane,
the orchestra's music director, will conduct a program that also
will include Schumann's Symphony No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was actually a little scared of it at first, because it's a
brilliant piece,'' says Ma, speaking by phone from his home in
Boston. ``What I say to myself is, `Imagine you're in music class
and your teacher comes to you and says, ``OK Yo-Yo, next week I
want you to write about the Mother of God!'' &UR;  &LR; ' And I'm like, `OK!
What's wrong with him, right?!' &UR;  &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   The spiritualistic and meditative qualities that define ``The
Protecting Veil'' have long characterized Tavener's work. Born in
1944, he first commanded attention with the dramatic cantata ``The
Whale'' followed in the late 1960s and early '70s with a number of
works influenced by Roman Catholic theology.
</P>
<P>
   Tavener's interest in metaphysical issues heated up with his
conversion to Russian Orthodoxy in 1977 at 33. ``The Protecting
Veil'' was inspired by an Orthodox feast day commemorating the
Virgin's appearance in A.D. 902 to the Greeks defending
Constantinople against the Saracen army. In the piece, the solo
cellist represents the voice of the Mother of God, a constant
reassuring presence over human affairs.
</P>
<P>
   As the liner notes to the ``The Protecting Veil'' observe,
Tavener's music has strong harmonic as well as mystical properties
_ an unusual combination for a contemporary composer. Perhaps it's
because of his ability to channel powerful, accessible, unambiguous
emotions that an excerpt of Tavener's ``Innocence'' was performed
last year at Princess Diana's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   When Ma first began exploring ``The Protecting Veil,'' he
wondered if it was going to be ``one of those New Age-y pieces'' _
more sizzle than steak.
</P>
<P>
   While so much 20th-century music has expressed itself through
``complexity and abstraction,'' Ma says, Tavener leans toward
elegant simplification that is able to evoke loss and grief,
resurrection and joy.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, simplification won Ma over.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really makes sense of it,'' Ma says of the piece. ``It's a
construction that is totally clear.'' &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
