<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOMCAT-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     09-14 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOMCAT-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``TOMCAT IN LOVE'': SHELL SHOCK ON THE BATTLEFIELDS OF A MESSY LOVE
LIFE  
 (PUBLICATION NOTES AT END)  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHIKO KAKUTANI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hero of Tim O'Brien's suffocating new novel is not only a
boor, he's also a big bore.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Tomcat in Love,'' O'Brien has left behind the battlefields
of Southeast Asia, which provided a backdrop for his earlier books
``Going After Cacciato'' (1978) and ``The Things They Carried''
(1990), two of the most powerfully imagined works to emerge from
the Vietnam War. He has instead moved to the domestic front and the
war between the sexes.
</P>
<P>
   His narrator, Thomas H. Chippering, the novel's ``tomcat in
love,'' is a Vietnam veteran who has become a professor of
linguistics at a small college. He's also an obnoxious
megalomaniac: a smug, pompous womanizer who keeps a running
tabulation of women he's been involved with. (``Names. Dates. Body
types. Complexion. Hair color. Other such vital statistical
data.'')
</P>
<P>
   Tom boasts that he's as ``virile as Secretariat,'' that he's got
an I.Q. ``well over 175'' and that women find him ``attractive
beyond words.'' He describes his latest paramour, a Mrs. Robert
Kooshof, as ``an improbable blend of Great Plains housewife and
sturdy strumpet'' who is ``busty as Nepal.'' He calls Toni, his
favorite co-ed of the moment, a ``little marshmallow.'' And he
refers to Thuy Ninh, a Vietnamese girl he had an affair with during
the war, as ``a crocodile in heat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like any gambling junkie, the female animal wants it all,''
Tom declares in one of his many misogynistic rants, ``your purse
strings, your heart, your spirit, the very breath of your lungs.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, Tom seems like such a ridiculous parody of a male
chauvinist pig that the reader suspects that O'Brien is trying to
write a sendup of the gender wars, a sort of Fay Weldonesque satire
from the male point of view. Certainly many of the novel's central
episodes are farcical in tone: a ludicrous scene in which Tom is
spanked in front of his class by his ex-wife's brother and her new
husband; another in which he is bound and gagged by two women he
has picked up at a bar. And certainly most of the novel's
characters are cartoonish, too: bullying, macho men and catty,
calculating women; clownish figures, meant perhaps to underscore
the comic similarities between ``wartime combat and peacetime
romance,'' in Tom's words. ``Blood lust. Mortal fear. Shell shock.
Despair. Hopelessness. Entrapment. Betrayal.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is ``Tomcat in Love'' isn't the least bit funny or
insightful, and Tom is a tedious, long-winded narrator, reminiscent
of the tedious, long-winded hero of O'Brien's lugubrious 1985 novel
``The Nuclear Age.'' Forced to listen to Tom go on (and on and on
and on) about his messy love life, his feelings of paranoia and his
belief in revenge, readers gloomily realize they are trapped, for
the duration of the novel, inside Tom's overheated brain.
</P>
<P>
   It's a claustrophobic place to be. The reader quickly suspects
that Tom is as crazy as he is self-absorbed. When he's not
scribbling down the vital statistics of his most recent female
conquests, he's obsessing about his ex-wife, the former Lorna Sue
Zylstra, whom he claims is the love of his life and whom he insists
has been having an incestuous affair with her brother, Herbie.
</P>
<P>
   Tom believes that Herbie deliberately sabotaged his marriage,
and he has vowed to exact revenge on Herbie and on Lorna Sue's new
husband, a wealthy tycoon from Tampa, Fla. His plans for revenge
swiftly escalate from practical jokes designed to sow the seeds of
mistrust between Lorna Sue and her husband _ like planting purple
underwear and leg irons under the front seat of the tycoon's car _
to a declaration of all-out war. Tom starts building homemade
bombs, seven of them, in his garage. He has a ``single
thermonuclear motive,'' he says, ``to strike back at the Zylstra
clan with every kilowatt of energy I could muster.''
</P>
<P>
   What this means for the reader is lots of portentous talk about
revenge. Like: ``The word  &UR; glee &LR;  may be taking it too far, yet I
have come to discover that acts of vengeance are often accompanied
by a swollen bladder, an airy tickle at the tip of the urethra.''
And equally trying mumbo jumbo about Tom's state of mind: ``Without
up, I asked, where is down? Without hereness, how does one locate
thereness?''
</P>
<P>
   Tom explains that his ``sensitivity to people leaving'' him, his
``terror of betrayal'' and his ``lifelong propensity for exacting
vengeance'' are the result of a traumatic war experience that
involved being the butt of a monstrous practical joke: it seems his
comrades left him in the jungle to fend for himself while they went
off on a secret mission. Like most of Tom's explanations, this one
remains highly suspect. Given his avowed penchant for lying, it's
hard to tell when he's telling the truth, embroidering the truth or
simply stitching his paranoid fantasies into a tall tale.
</P>
<P>
   As Tom's madness accelerates, he dons military fatigues, darkens
his face with charcoal and starts whistling ``an old Vietnam
marching ditty'' as he heads off to exact ``payback, as in Nam.''
This behavior not only reads like a cruel parody of post-traumatic
stress syndrome, but also mocks the wonderfully nuanced delineation
of the Vietnam experience set down in ``Going After Cacciato'' and
``The Things They Carried.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the reader can only wonder at the disparity between the
power of those earlier books by O'Brien _ distinguished by their
inventive storytelling and their evocative depiction of the
visceral and emotional realities of war _ and the mangled mess that
is ``Tomcat in Love.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   TOMCAT IN LOVE
</P>
<P>
   By Tim O'Brien
</P>
<P>
   347 pages. Broadway Books. $26.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
