r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSMETIC-SURGERY-HNS &LR;      09-14 1374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSMETIC-SURGERY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECENT CASES HIGHLIGHT RISKS OF COSMETIC SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ and LANCE WILLIAMS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A fashion executive hired a San Francisco
cosmetic surgeon to have permanent eye-liner applied. During the
procedure, her eye was punctured by a syringe.
</P>
<P>
   A California woman, consulting a doctor about a scar on her leg,
said she was persuaded to try calf implants that would ``make her
legs look like Marilyn Monroe's.'' Three weeks later, feverish and
unable to walk, she needed emergency surgery to save her leg.
</P>
<P>
   A housewife had liposuction in the office of a doctor who was
already on state Medical Board probation for surgical negligence.
Five days later, she was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmetic surgery has become the medical growth industry of the
1990s, with hundreds of thousands of baby boomers undergoing face
lifts, breast implants, liposuction and other procedures in hopes
of fending off the wrinkles and sags of aging.
</P>
<P>
   Many get what they want: a trimmer body, a refreshed appearance
_ the way they remember themselves 10 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But an investigation of cosmetic surgery in California, where it
is heavily marketed and especially popular, shows a growing number
of patients suffer disappointment and disfigurement from what often
are billed as simple, low-risk procedures.
</P>
<P>
   No government agency or professional association keeps data on
accidents involving cosmetic surgery, which can be performed by any
doctor with a medical license, regardless of specialty or training.
</P>
<P>
   But after more than 150 interviews and a review of thousands of
pages of legal records, the scope of a growing problem emerges.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, four people have died following cosmetic
surgery since 1994, three of them after liposuction, the surgical
removal of fat using a suction device.
</P>
<P>
   The Medical Board of California was so alarmed by increasing
complications from cosmetic surgery that it appointed a special
committee to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   According to the chairman of the committee, Dr. Robert del
Junco, 60 to 100 deaths occurred last year in the United States
from liposuction complications out of an estimated 110,000
procedures performed.
</P>
<P>
   ``To put this number in perspective, childbirth, once a major
killer of young women, now yields about seven maternal deaths in
about 100,000 births,'' he said during a June committee meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This comparison illustrates how one procedure _ a cosmetic
procedure, not a lifesaving one _ appears to have an unacceptable
and, I think, certainly preventable, high mortality rate. In my 20
years in medicine, I have never seen any cosmetic procedure that
has had such a high rate of risk.''
</P>
<P>
   For every liposuction death ``I've heard ... there could
possibly be 20 near deaths,'' del Junco said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet what is the medical community doing about this? If it were
a drug, it would have been pulled from the market,'' he said.
``Cosmetic surgery is not like heart surgery. These are healthy
people, and some are getting incredibly bad outcomes.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the outcomes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Jennifer Ha, 38, a Santa Rosa mother of four, was stricken on
the operating table during 1996 surgery in the clinic of Dr. Leslie
Moglen, a San Francisco physician already on Medical Board
probation for gross negligence in previous cosmetic surgeries.
Moglen said he was deeply saddened by the death, which he said
resulted from ``an idiosyncratic drug reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Paul Falaschi was 25, handsome, healthy, but overweight, a
personal trainer in a gym environment that stressed good looks.
Last November, he had liposuction at St. Francis Memorial Hospital:
fat removed from his abdomen, thighs, flanks, buttocks. Four days
later, he died of strep infection.
</P>
<P>
   _ Audrey Penn Rodgers, 71, of San Francisco, died of heart
failure in 1994, two days after bladder surgery by a gynecologist
and liposuction by a doctor who advertised, ``When you consider
cosmetic surgery, have it performed by a specialist.'' Three
doctors and the California-Pacific Medical Center paid a $50,000
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   _ San Francisco psychotherapist Myra Breen Ruskin, 56, underwent
a $20,000 face lift and other cosmetic procedures in August 1997,
then died in a recovery room at her doctor's Union Street clinic,
law enforcement records show.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year later, no one has been held responsible,'' said
Ruskin's son, Joshua Breen. ``Doctors are pushing beyond the
boundaries of what is medically prudent. You have a formula for
disaster. The bigger question is who is responsible for putting in
place medical standards? How many more people will have to die
before something is done?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Lisa Santoro, a former fashion consultant, went to Dr. Alan
Gaynor, a San Francisco cosmetic surgeon who has promoted his
skills by performing live procedures on television talk shows, once
doing a fat transplant from Geraldo Rivera's buttocks to his face.
</P>
<P>
   Santoro wanted permanent eyeliner tattooed into her upper and
lower lids, a procedure Gaynor had spoken of on the Geraldo show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's perfect,'' Gaynor boasted. ``And it doesn't look like
make-up.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't Santoro's outcome. She said in a lawsuit that Gaynor
punctured her eye with a syringe.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor said he was innocent of wrongdoing and settled Santoro's
lawsuit out of court. ``I am a person of conscience,'' he said,
``and I was profoundly worried for her.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In June 1992, Carmen Sandino went to cosmetic surgeon Jeffrey
Friedman to discuss having a scar removed. While there, she said, a
medical assistant said Friedman could make her legs ``look like
Marilyn Monroe's'' with calf implants. Sandino agreed to the
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit, Sandino contends that Friedman had never done a
calf implant procedure before and boned up on the procedure by
watching a medical video and reviewing a textbook.
</P>
<P>
   Within days of the operation, Sandino said, she was suffering
excruciating pain. Her legs were swollen and blistered; fluid
drained from her wounds. She was hospitalized for nine days after
surgery to save the leg and off work for five months.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman denied malpractice. He said he had received seminar
training in the calf-implant procedure and had arranged for an
experienced surgeon to proctor the operation.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was settled out of court.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients undergo cosmetic surgery assuming a high degree of
success,'' said New York cosmetic surgery consultant Wendy Lewis.
``In cosmetic surgery, the margin of error is zero. You can accept
the risk of death in a gall bladder or liver surgery, but who wants
to die from liposuction?''
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by a society fixated on youth and beauty, cosmetic
surgery is seeing unprecedented growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beyond a boom; it's an explosion,'' San Francisco plastic
surgeon Andrew Barnett said. ``It's an amazing growth.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, the nip-and-tuck industry has
flourished, with some procedures, such as liposuction and breast
augmentation, tripling from 1992 to 1997, according to the American
Society of Plastic and Reconstructive Surgeons. The number of
cosmetic surgery procedures rose 68 percent between 1992 and 1996,
the organization said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3.3 million cosmetic treatments were performed in
1996, according to the American Academy of Cosmetic Surgery. Men
accounted for 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But in the largely unregulated cosmetic business, some
physicians are performing plastic or cosmetic surgery who received
their formal training in another specialty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of hucksterism in this business,'' said Dr. John
Renner, president of the National Council for Reliable Health
Information. ``I know doctors who've given fanny tucks away as part
of a raffle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it a travesty that pediatricians and ER physicians and
other doctors who could not get operating privileges anywhere are
opening up offices and doing cosmetic surgery,'' said Dr. Aaron
Stone, a plastic surgeon in Los Angeles. ``This isn't the Wild West
anymore. If you don't have hospital admitting privileges, you
shouldn't be doing surgery. Period.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
