<HEADER>
A4582 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKTV-TEX     09-14 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKTV-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH BOOK-TV, C-SPAN2 DEVOTES WEEKENDS TO LITERARY PURSUITS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by BC-BOOKTV-CHRONOLOGY) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first glance, TV shows about books seem like an oxymoron. But
the low-tech, intellectual book programs on C-SPAN2 have grown so
popular that the cable channel launched ``Book TV,'' devoting every
weekend to shows about books and the book industry.
</P>
<P>
   It could make for an interesting audience demographic. ``One
group will be the same people who already watch C-SPAN and
C-SPAN2,'' said Connie Brod, executive producer of ``Book TV.''
``They are already used to coming to us for subjects covered in
depth. The second group, I'm hoping, is book lovers who may not be
watching a lot of TV because they'd rather read.''
</P>
<P>
   Each weekend from 7 a.m. Saturday until 7 a.m. Monday, C-SPAN2
will air unedited interviews with authors, panel discussions,
bookstore signings, trade meetings, book conventions and
interactive chats between viewers and authors, book editors and
book publishers. (No current C-SPAN2 programming is being replaced;
there will simply be fewer repeats of previous telecasts.)
</P>
<P>
   The timing for ``Book TV'' seems right; various publishing
industry surveys suggest total book sales in 1998 may increase as
much as 8 percent to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   C-SPAN's foray into book programming began 10 years ago with
``Booknotes,'' its venerable author interview show. ``We know from
feedback that our current book programming is popular with our
viewers, though all our information is anecdotal since we've never
taken formal ratings,'' said C-SPAN spokesman Richard Fahle. ``But
everything C-SPAN and C-SPAN2 covers are issues that influence
public opinion, and books are part of that realm. Where books (on
TV) are concerned, we're a playing field of one.''
</P>
<P>
   No other network can or would devote full weekends to books,
Fahle said. ``They have to fulfill their advertisers' wishes, which
is to get the maximum number of eyes glued to their commercials.''
C-SPAN and C-SPAN2 don't face the same pressure because they are
privately funded by the cable industry; about 5 cents a month from
each TV cable customer's bill goes toward their costs.
</P>
<P>
   Initial ``Book TV'' programming leaves lots of room for
experimentation. Saturday kicked off with a one-hour rerun of
``Booknotes,'' followed by a two-hour ``Business of Books''
segment. The rest of the day's viewing included features on
children's books, historical works, another ``Booknotes'' encore
and several generic ``More Books'' slots allowing the network and
its viewers to travel between book-signings, trade shows and panel
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday included three ``Biography'' segments and one
``Children's Books'' slot, with the rest of the day's programming
reserved for the ubiquitous ``More Books.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Book TV'' viewers, though, will have to be interested in the
nonfiction side of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``On C-SPAN and C-SPAN2, we always deal with real information,
things that have been and can be researched,'' Fahle said. ``So at
this point we have no plans to go into fiction. Larry McMurtry, for
instance, is best-known as a writer of fiction, so from that
perspective we wouldn't have him on. But as someone who is a
scholar concerning books, someone who has rare bookstores, those
are subjects with him we would definitely like to try.''
</P>
<P>
   Even programs about children's books will stick to nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to focus on children's books that can be learning
tools for them,'' Brod said. ``Our first program will be about
Peter and Cheryl Barnes, a couple who write children's books
together. Their titles that we'll look at are `House Mouse, Senate
Mouse' and `Woodrow, the White House Mouse.' The books are so cute
that you just can't imagine, but they use the stories to teach
children about how the government works. `Cinderella,' now, you
won't see that on `Book TV.' ''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that doesn't concern C-SPAN2, Fahle said, is how to
fill entire weekends with book programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing we had to decide when we began looking at
`Book TV' was, Is there enough stuff out there?'' he said. ``This
isn't going to be a problem. In fact, we now think we could have
enough to fill an entire network week. Perhaps some day we'll look
at that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeff Guinn is associate books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
