<HEADLINE>
BOOKS ON TV: A TIME LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: CORRECTS day in final graph) 
(EDS: Accompanies BC-BOOKTV-TEX) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   C-SPAN's first book programming aired 10 years ago:
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 14, 1988: An interview with Neil Sheehan, author of ``A
Bright Shining Lie: John Paul Vann and America in Vietnam,''
inspires the idea for a show about books.
</P>
<P>
   April 2, 1989: First ``Booknotes'' airs with Zbigniew
Brzezinski, author of ``Grand Failure: The Birth and Death of
Communism in the Twentieth Century.''
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 23, 1992: Richard Nixon, author of ``Seize the Moment:
America's Challenge in a One Superpower World,'' appears on
``Booknotes.''
</P>
<P>
   April 3, 1994: For ``Booknotes' '' fifth anniversary, C-SPAN
offers bookmarks to the first 500 viewers who request one. More
than 10,000 respond.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 19, 1995: Jimmy Carter, author of ``Always a Reckoning and
Other Poems,'' appears on ``Booknotes.''
</P>
<P>
   May 9, 1996: ``About Books'' launches on C-SPAN2, offering
another five hours of book-industry TV.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 15, 1996: President Bill Clinton, author of ``Between Hope
and History: Meeting America's Challenges for the 21st Century,''
appears on ``Booknotes.''
</P>
<P>
   May 9, 1997: The Alexis de Tocqueville Tour spends nine months
retracing the famous Frenchman's 1831-32 trip to America, detailed
in ``Democracy in America.'' A companion book, ``Traveling
Tocqueville's America,'' is released later by Johns Hopkins
University Press.
</P>
<P>
   June 16, 1997: ``Booknotes: America's Finest Authors on Reading,
Writing and the Power of Ideas'' by Brian Lamb (Times Books) is
released.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 7, 1998: C-SPAN2 devotes the first Saturday of every month
to 24 hours of ``About Books.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday: C-SPAN2 launches ``Book TV,'' devoting entire weekends
to shows about books.
</P>
