r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POSTHUMOUS-BOOKS-TEX     09-14 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSTHUMOUS-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAD MAN WRITING: HEMINGWAY IS PATRIARCH OF POSTHUMOUS PUBLISHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Ernest Hemingway took his own life in 1961, he left behind
papers weighing half a ton, including several unpublished
manuscripts. Soon after his death, ``A Moveable Feast'' was issued,
and Papa's recollection of Paris in the 1920s was a posthumous
triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequently, however, publication of the novel ``Islands in the
Stream'' compromised Papa's reputation. Still later, in 1986, the
arrival of another novel _ ``The Garden of Eden'' _ seriously
wounded it.
</P>
<P>
   We supposed we had heard the last from Ernest Hemingway. But no.
Now we're told that Scribner will publish ``Truth at First Light,''
a novel believed to contain more comedy than Papa's usual quotient,
in the summer of 1999, as part of a Hemingway centennial
celebration. The factual/fictional account follows a writer and his
wife on an African safari.
</P>
<P>
   Posthumously published novels are nothing unusual. Most authors
of high rank have a book in press when they advance to that great
literary cocktail party in the sky. Perhaps there's another in
manuscript, possibly an even older unpublished work in the trunk.
These usually see publication in the early aftermath of the
author's life, when former friends and colleagues are still saying
nice things about the deceased, however guardedly.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't often that readers wait 38 years after an author's
passing to absorb his final literary testament. And Patrick
Hemingway, the fabled author's 70-year-old son and editor of the
200,000-word manuscript, assures us that ``Truth at First Light''
will be absolutely the final published work in the Hemingway canon.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-eight years. Is that a record? Probably not, but in the
concern of high-profile authors, it surely is.
</P>
<P>
   When Herman Melville died in 1891, aged 72, he had published no
prose works after his 40th year. Disillusioned by critical
response, the author of ``Moby Dick'' abandoned fiction in favor of
poetry. But in his last few years, Melville worked intermittently
on the maritime novel ``Billy Budd, Foretopman.''
</P>
<P>
   For many years afterward, the completed ``Billy Budd''
manuscript languished undisturbed among the late author's papers.
</P>
<P>
   During the early 20th century, there was little interest in
Melville. However, a literary revolution was trumpeted in the years
immediately after World War I by a new wave of critics _ H.L.
Mencken, Lewis Mumford, Charles Baldwin, Edmund Wilson, Thomas Beer
_ who discovered Sinclair Lewis, Scott Fitzgerald and yes, Ernest
Hemingway; and who rediscovered Stephen Crane, Frank Norris and
yes, Herman Melville.
</P>
<P>
   Published in 1924, all of 33 years after its author's death,
``Billy Budd'' is today regarded as one of Herman Melville's major
works.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, is ``The Mysterious Stranger'' considered an important
entry in the Mark Twain ledger. When Sam Clemens died in 1910,
``The Mysterious Stranger'' existed as a story in several
manuscript drafts that were markedly different from one another. As
a philosophical parable showing the pessimism of Clemens'/Twain's
later years, it incited curiosity and mild interest upon finally
seeing print in 1916.
</P>
<P>
   Later, it was determined that Albert Bigelow Paine, executor of
the Clemens estate as well as Sam's official biographer, had
fashioned ``The Mysterious Stranger'' from three drafts, taking
parts from each, with the result that the published version was
more Paine than Twain. The original ``final'' draft as Sam Clemens
wrote it appeared at last in 1969, and has passed every test of
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   So in a way of thinking, Sam Clemens still has Hemingway beaten
by 21 years in the game of posthumous publishing.
</P>
<P>
   What remains is to find a lost Poe or Hawthorne manuscript;
better yet, a complete novel by Charles Dickens, about which no one
knew anything. The divine quest is to find a literary equivalent to
Schubert's Unfinished Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   Might it be Ernest Hemingway's ``Truth at First Light?'' That
would be a stretch, because Papa, living or dead, has ever been too
much with us. In any event, we must wait and see, as we anticipate
the literary event of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
