<SLUG> BC-MALDEN-MILLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALDEN MILLS TO CLOSE MAINE PLANT, MOVING 200 JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Malden Mills Industries Inc. says it must close a plant in
Bridgton, Maine, and move its operations and 200 jobs to Malden's
facility in Lawrence, Mass., to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very difficult decision, one I didn't expect to
have to make,'' said Malden Mills chief executive Aaron Feuerstein,
who added, ``We would not make this move unless we felt it
absolutely necessary to ensure the long-term health of our
business.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bridgton knitting mill is one of the largest employers in a
town about 40 miles northwest of Portland. The move to close the
mill by December stunned a community with about 4,500 residents,
said Town Manager Ronnie Belanger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a total surprise,'' Belanger said.
</P>
<P>
   Malden Mills ``repeatedly gave assurances to our local paper
that the plant wouldn't be shutting down,'' said Brenda Ridlon,
president of the Bridgton Lakes Region Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three years ago, the Lawrence headquarters facilities for
Malden Mills were devastated by fire. As part of heroic rebuilding
efforts, Malden Mills has shifted gears, focusing more on selling
fabrics to apparel makers and away from making fabrics that
furniture companies use for upholstery.
</P>
<P>
   That shift is one reason why the Bridgton plant must be closed
after being part of the Malden Mills family for about 35 years _
and one reason why the total work force for Malden Mills has
dropped from about 3,000 workers before the fire to about 2,000
today, said Malden Mills spokesman Jeff Bowman.
</P>
<P>
   As it focuses more on apparel, Malden Mills must be able to
react quickly to fashion trends, and a need to be nimble led to the
decision to consolidate operations in Lawrence, Bowman said.
</P>
<P>
   Thread is brought to Lawrence, then trucked 130 miles to
Bridgton, a town far from major highways, for one step of a process
that turns thread into fabric, he said. Later steps, including
dyeing and finishing, take place in Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   By bringing all steps of the process to Lawrence, Malden Mills
can cut costs and be more efficient, Bowman said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the distance, few Bridgton workers are likely to move
to Lawrence; workers on the job for more than three years will get
a week's worth of severance pay for each year of service. Workers
make an average of about $13 to $14 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Because last year's mild winter reduced the demand for warm
clothing, the apparel division of Malden Mills sold about $250
million worth of fabric last year, somewhat below expectations.
</P>
<P>
   A private company, Malden Mills does not disclose revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to shut the Bridgton mill is another blow for
Maine's rural towns. Once these towns thrived, thanks to tanneries,
paper mills, and shoe factories, said Charles Colgan, a professor
at the University of Southern Maine's Muskie School of Public
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Now Maine's rural manufacturing sector ``is the most vulnerable
part of the economy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While rural areas are losing manufacturing jobs, southern and
coastal counties are gaining service jobs, said Dana Evans, an
analyst for the Maine Labor Department. In July, the state's
seasonally adjusted unemployment rate was 4.5 percent, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
