<HEADER>
A4598 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAVID-HYDE-PIERCE-IN-     09-14 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVID-HYDE-PIERCE-IN-FRASIER-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID HYDE PIERCE ENJOYS `FRASIER'S' DAY IN THE SUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of David Hyde Pierce in a scene from
``Frasier.'' 
 By CHRISTOPHER LOUDON  
 c.1998 Canadian TV Guide  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arriving for a late-night interview at Montreal's trendy
L'Express bistro in chinos, creased button-down shirt and
wire-rimmed glasses, David Hyde Pierce _ winner of a 1998 Emmy
Award as Best Supporting Actor in a comedy _ looks every inch the
well-bred, well-educated, slightly rumpled preppie.
</P>
<P>
   Which actually isn't surprising, because that's exactly what the
39-year-old Yale graduate is.
</P>
<P>
   Don't confuse him with his television alter-ego, natty, neurotic
Niles Crane, though. Told that there will be a 15-minute wait for
his reserved table, Pierce doesn't fly into a Nilesian priggish
snit. Instead, he's content to stand patiently by the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually settling into a corner table, Pierce seems remarkably
unperturbed by the fact that the entire restaurant is trying hard
not to stare at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get used to it,'' he says with a good-natured shrug. ``It
happens enough that you don't really notice it any more, unless
it's really obvious or silly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at my hotel eating breakfast the other day, sitting by
myself at a little table,'' he recalls. ``Right next to me was a
group of about 16 kids, and I could hear them loudly whispering to
one another, `Is that him? It looks like him. Could it be him? It
might be him.' Finally I turned to them and said, `Yes, it's him.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Another time I was chased through a chateau in the Loire
Valley by a bunch of American high-school girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am, by nature, a fairly shy person,'' the Canadian-born
actor continues, ``and one of the things I had to learn was, when
you're on a popular show and people feel they know you, what used
to pass for shyness can be perceived as rude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel more vulnerable, but people are always nice,'' he
admits. ``Nobody ever comes up and throws food on me and says the
show is crap.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's strange, though,'' he adds after a moment, ``is that
there's a whole genre of people who come up to you and say, `Hey,
are you that guy on ``Frasier?''' I say, `Yes,' and they say, `I
never watch it.' I've never understood the psychology of that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a busy off-season for Pierce, who spent most of his
hiatus in Quebec, Canada, filming the feature film ``Isn't She
Great.'' The loosely-based-on-fact movie stars comedy heavyweights
Bette Midler and Nathan Lane as ``Valley of the Dolls'' author
Jacqueline Susann and her husband, Irving Mansfield.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce appears as Susann's editor, a rather Niles-like
character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing a kind of WASPy, fairly well-off Connecticut guy,
which is not that far from Niles,'' he admits. ``But it was such a
good part and such a good script that it was never a question.
</P>
<P>
   ``The curse of being on `Frasier' is the challenge of finding
writing that's that good in any other medium,'' the actor adds.
``I've been looking at scripts for two years, then this came along.
It's a terrific script, written by Paul Rudnick (author of 1996's
`Jeffrey' and 1997's `In &AMP; Out'). It's like an incredible marriage
of his obvious comic ability and a very serious side that I think
he handles tremendously well.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with larger-than-life performers such as Midler and Lane
was a memorable experience, Pierce reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just funereal,'' he says with his trademark deadpan. ``No,
really, it's great. And the thing that makes it great is that
they're both so good. People can be a hoot on the set, but if
they're not good to work with, that tires really quickly. These two
are both such pros ... They're really very different people, but
they work off each other beautifully.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't She Great'' also offered Pierce the chance to act with
one of his comic heroes, John Cleese, who plays his boss in the
film.
</P>
<P>
   ``That tipped it for me,'' he says. ``When people ask who
influenced me, I always say John Cleese. Also, Bob Newhart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only realized this recently,'' Pierce adds. ``I had a
flashback of when I was growing up, and remembered watching `Monty
Python' and `The Bob Newhart Show' and laughing hysterically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alec Guinness was also a role model of mine, because he has
that quality of doing the most with the least, with the smallest
gesture,'' he says. ``That's my taste in acting, and both John
Cleese and Bob Newhart are masters of that.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, ``Frasier'' shifts into the coveted Thursdays-at-9:00
time slot previous occupied by ``Seinfeld.'' Star Kelsey Grammer
reportedly lobbied hard for the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelsey had personal reasons for wanting it,'' Pierce says,
``because of all those years that `Cheers' was on Thursday night,
and it felt like home to him. The rest of us said, `We have a good
show. It will be a good show on Tuesday night, it will be a good
show on Thursday night.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, it's nice to be acknowledged,'' he admits. ``You feel
like NBC is saying, ```Seinfeld'' was our prime show, and now this
is our prime show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Frasier,'' which recently was awarded its fifth straight Emmy
as Best Comedy, ended the 1997/98 season with a bang, as Frasier
and his colleagues were fired from their radio jobs. The new season
will find them seeking new jobs, Pierce says, offering fertile
comic ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in the show, I think it's a really smart and
organic way to throw something new into the mix,'' he says. ``It
certainly didn't feel like a gimmick, and I think people will love
watching Kelsey try other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The might-be relationship between Niles and Daphne will be
developed further, Pierce notes, but that doesn't mean that we've
heard the last of Niles' never-seen ex, Maris.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be a Maris,'' he says, ``because she is such
a great character. In fact, I think NBC should give her a spin-off
show _ in which she never appears.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce's closest friendship among the cast is with Grammer, his
brother on the show. On the surface, the zany, bigger-than-life
Grammer and the calmer, more reactive Pierce could hardly be
different, but Pierce says there's more to both men than meets the
eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprisingly, we're a lot alike,'' he says. ``We don't tend to
do the same things, and if we weren't on the same show it's
unlikely that we'd run into each other socially. The show is the
thing that brought us together, and there's a very strange
transference that happens in playing brothers. We just respond to
one another in a very deep way.''
</P>
<P>
   The cast of ``Frasier'' is, on the whole, a warm, friendly
bunch, Pierce says. But he cautions that a friendly on-the-set
atmosphere, while pleasant, is not a prerequisite for a successful
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have to choose between working with nice people or
talented people,'' he explains, ``you have to choose the talented
people, because that's what makes the show good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've fallen into a situation where everyone on the show is so
generous and so good at what they do. That's when you know you've
won the lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Christopher Loudon is the editor of Canadian TV Guide, based
in North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
