<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENNIS-FARINA-IN-BUDDY-FARO-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENNIS FARINA'S `BUDDY' SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Dennis Farina in a scene from ``Buddy
Faro.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The face rings a bell.
 &HT;    Let Dennis Farina walk down the street and, inevitably, people
stop to chat with the actor or nod a silent hello. They can't all
place the name, but that craggy, tough-guy mug is hard to forget.
 &HT;    ``Some people see me and say, `How's the nose?,' meaning they
saw `Get Shorty' (1995),'' Farina says, laughing. ``Some people who
know their TV recognize me for `Crime Story,' but a lot of people
just think they recognize me from something they think I did,
because I have played a lot of tough guys.
 &HT;    ``I don't know what it is,'' he concludes. ``I have that look,
that persona, I guess.''
 &HT;    The latest vehicle for that persona is ``Buddy Faro,'' an
offbeat series debuting Sept. 25 on CBS. The actor plays the title
character, a legendary private eye _ he had a way with a quip as
well as with the ladies _ who disappeared without a trace in the
1970s.
 &HT;    After by-the-book gumshoe Bob Jones (Frank Whaley) tracks him
down, the drunken, grubby Faro spiffs himself up and teams with
Jones to crack tough cases.
 &HT;    ``Buddy lived his life a certain way in the 1970s, and now he
has a chance to do it all over again,'' the soft-spoken, modest
Farina says by telephone from Los Angeles during a break from
taping ``Faro.'' ``So what if the times have changed?''
 &HT;    It's a little bit ``Austin Powers,'' a little bit
``Moonlighting,'' a little bit ``Maltese Falcon.'' And a whole lot
unusual.
 &HT;    ``It's a different show from anything else out there, and that's
what interested me,'' Farina says. ``I really didn't care to do
just another TV show.
 &HT;    ``The quirkiness of it and the quirkiness of the characters
appealed to me,'' he adds, ``and I liked that it wasn't a straight
drama or a straight comedy. It's a little bit like life in that
way, in that you're not always in a dramatic situation or a funny
situation.
 &HT;    ``In our everyday experiences, most of us experience a little
bit of both.''
 &HT;    The show's quirkiness manifests itself in several ways. Jumpy
cameras and nifty editing supply a sleek veneer, while zippy music
enhances the mood.
 &HT;    Then there's the often-bohemian banter, the distinctive
character eccentricities. In an unexpected sort of way, it's all
pretty much what you'd expect from ``Faro'' head honcho Mark Frost,
who co-created the peerlessly odd ``Twin Peaks,'' and co-executive
producer Charles Haid, who directed the pilot.
 &HT;    ``I was aware of Frank Whaley and Allison Smith (who plays a
neophyte private eye) and Charlie, but knowing that Mark would be
around to talk to, to work with on the scripts, made all the
difference,'' says Farina, who also serves as co-executive producer
of the show. ``Mark listens to everyone, cuts through the minutiae
and says, `OK, this is what I think we should do.' His involvement
was actually what convinced me to do the show.''
 &HT;    That ``Buddy Faro'' would be a television series was by no means
carved in stone.
 &HT;    ``When the whole thing started, I asked that we do `Faro' as a
movie,'' the actor recalls, ``but Mark didn't want to and his deal
with CBS didn't allow him to do that.
 &HT;    ``Then I suggested we do it as a `Columbo'-like series of TV
movies, but TV people aren't interested in that anymore,'' he adds.
``So we're at the pilot and 12 episodes. Hopefully, the American
public will think Buddy's as interesting as I do.
 &HT;    ``I love fish-out-of-water stories, and Buddy's a very big fish
out of water.''
 &HT;    Farina debated long and hard before committing to ``Faro.''
After all, his movie career has been blooming of late. He starred
with Bette Midler in Carl Reiner's ``That Old Feeling,'' and also
logged supporting roles in this summer's ``Out of Sight'' and
``Saving Private Ryan.''
 &HT;    ``I weighed everything, believe me,'' Farina says. ``After a lot
of thinking and a lot of business meetings it came down to me
asking myself, `Do I want to do this or do I want to see someone
else doing it?'
 &HT;    ``If I said no, I might have wound up saying, `Gee, I wish I'd
done that,''' the actor says. ``Now we'll see what happens. If it
all falls apart, fine _ at least I won't feel I missed an
opportunity.''
 &HT;    Farina has always made the most of his opportunities. ``Thief''
(1981) marked the former policeman's big-screen debut, and he first
generated serious buzz with the acclaimed but short-lived series
``Crime Story.''
 &HT;    Subsequent credits include several plays in his native Chicago,
among them the Steppenwolf Theatre production of ``A Prayer for My
Daughter,'' directed by John Malkovich, and such films as
``Manhunter'' (1986), ``Midnight Run'' (1988), ``Another Stakeout''
(1993) and ``Eddie'' (1996).
 &HT;    ``I act because I enjoy doing it, but I also like to
entertain,'' says Farina, a 55-year-old, divorced father of three.
``I don't seek to convey a message to anyone.
 &HT;    ``The work I've done I did because I liked the role, the work,
the people,'' he says. ``I love `Thief' because it's the first
thing I ever did, and `That Old Feeling' because I got to do a
comedy and work with Bette Midler and Carl Reiner.''
 &HT;    His small role as an officer in Steven Spielberg's summer hit
was a great personal satisfaction, Farina says.
 &HT;    ``I was proud to be even the tiniest part of `Saving Private
Ryan,''' he explains. ``That is an important film, and it will be
watched for a long time.''
 &HT;    Farina laughs.
 &HT;    ```Buddy Faro' won't change the world for anybody, but it may
entertain you for an hour every Friday night,'' he says. ``That's
the reason, I think, that they started making TV shows and movies.
 &HT;    ``I know it's important to inform and educate, but entertaining
is important, too.''
 &HT;    Between finishing the ``Faro'' pilot and launching into
production on the first dozen episodes, Farina squeezed in ``The
Mod Squad,'' an upcoming film version of the hip 1960s television
series. He plays the police captain who assembles a trio of young
delinquents _ among them Claire Danes _ to operate as undercover
cops for the LAPD.
 &HT;    ``I'd never watched the show, but the script for the movie was
good,'' Farina says. ``They've got the squad going into the clubs
these kids today like. You need a kid to go into these places
undercover, because I'd certainly be too old to do it.
 &HT;    ``It's a nice-size role, and it kind of sets up everything else
that happens.''
 &HT;    Though he's shared the screen with some of Hollywood's biggest
names, Farina doesn't pine for the upper reaches of stardom. He'd
rather share the screen with Travolta, De Niro, Clooney or Hanks
than be any one of them.
 &HT;    ``I accept being considered a character actor,'' Farina says.
``I have no problem at all being known as that.
 &HT;    ``I'm pretty happy where I'm at,'' he concludes. ``I never had a
grand scheme about where I wanted to be. I never said, `If I'm not
doing this or that by the time I'm 55, I'm out of here.'
 &HT;    ``I've just taken things as they've come my way and,
fortunately, they keep coming.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
