<HEADER>
A4600 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSICIAN-GARY-BROOKER     09-14 1477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSICIAN-GARY-BROOKER-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROCOL HARUM'S GARY BROOKER ROCKS ON
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of musician Gary Brooker 
 By TITO DAVILA  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    They'd just buried the Czar, and Gary Brooker was in Russia
looking for bones.
 &HT;    No, he wasn't grave-robbing. The singer and pianist, who
``skipped the light fandango'' in the 1960s gothic-rock anthem ``A
Whiter Shade of Pale,'' was taking the occasion of a Russian tour
with Beatles legend Ringo Starr to look for old bootleg records,
made on old, glued-together X-rays and known, with typical Soviet
black humor, as ``bones.''
 &HT;    ``I was trying to get ahold of some `bones,' but I didn't find
any,'' Brooker says. ``They would use it as if it was vinyl and
made a pirate recording, but you could usually see the X-ray
picture through it, somebody's chest or something.''
 &HT;    It was through ``bones,'' the musician adds, that many fans in
the old Soviet Union first heard such forbidden, ``imperialist''
tunes as ``Conquistador,'' ``Whiskey Train'' and ``A Salty Dog,''
all originally recorded by Procol Harum, Brooker's band in the
1960s and 1970s.
 &HT;    Brooker visited Russia in late August as a member of Starr's
latest incarnation of his All-Starr Band, featuring former Cream
member Jack Bruce on bass and Peter Frampton on guitar. The tour's
stops included Finland, Switzerland, Denmark, Germany, Belgium,
England, Ireland, Luxembourg and Portugal, as well as Monte Carlo,
where Brooker agreed to a telephone interview from his hotel room.
 &HT;    Looking back on Russia, which the band left just as its
financial crisis crystallized, the musician most recalls runaway
prices and a bad experience with Russian trains.
 &HT;    ``We were on the Red Arrow from Moscow to St. Petersburg, a
long-distance train,'' he says. ``I should think it was last
cleaned in 1947.''
 &HT;    Trains matter to Brooker, who patterned his autobiographical
``Last Train to Niagara'' on an imaginary long-distance rail
journey. Even his sea epic ``A Salty Dog,'' was surprisingly
inspired by train travel.
 &HT;    But ``Whiter Shade,'' his biggest hit, was inspired by something
even more unlikely _ Bach's ``Air on the G String,'' which Brooker
heard played on a Hamlet Cigars television commercial.
 &HT;    The 1967 song, which combined classical and rock music, double
keyboards, Keith Reid's far-out lyrics and Brooker's soulful voice,
was Procol Harum's first recording. It immediately climbed to the
top of the charts, and has remained one of rock's most enduring and
memorable songs, featured in movies such as ``The Big Chill''
(1983) and ``The Commitments'' (1991), and covered by artists
ranging from Sammy Hagar to Annie Lennox.
 &HT;    Brooker, however, has reservations about the song's appeal to
other artists.
 &HT;    ``Normally a song like that would have been covered a million
times by everybody from Liza Minnelli to Julio Iglesias,'' he says.
``It's not that simple in its content. I think you've got to put it
across with a bit of conviction, otherwise you'll sound silly.
 &HT;    ``Annie Lennox sang it like she meant it,'' he adds. ``You
believed her. If you don't put those words across just right,
people won't believe it.''
 &HT;    Now in his 50s, Brooker enjoys a private life that is in sharp
contrast to his hard-rocking onstage career. He and his wife,
Franky, celebrated their 30th anniversary in July _ no small
accomplishment for one in Brooker's line of work.
 &HT;    The musician has a simple formula for a successful marriage, he
says: ``Pick the right woman. Pick the right man.''
 &HT;    After the Starr tour, he's scheduled for an October trip through
Europe with ex-Rolling Stone Bill Wyman's band, the Rhythm Kings.
The ensemble will include Georgie Fame, Albert Lee and Frampton,
and they'll make stops in Germany, Denmark, Sweden and Norway.
 &HT;    Brooker's friendships with Starr and Wyman date back to the
1960s _ he played at Wyman's wedding _ and he insists that the
veteran stars are still capable of putting on a dynamic show.
 &HT;    ``This is not like a revival show _ we are going over old ground
in a new way,'' he says. ``They play my songs really well and it's
good playing Cream songs, Frampton and Bad Company and a couple of
Beatles tunes,''
 &HT;    Brooker, who traces his R&AMP;B roots to Ray Charles and Jerry Lee
Lewis, isn't afraid to team with rock icons: Since Procol Harum
disbanded in 1977 _ since 1991, the group has reformed periodically
to produce two CDs and several tours _ he's also played with George
Harrison and Eric Clapton, providing backup vocals and piano for
Clapton's music for Martin Scorsese's ``The Color of Money'' (1986)
and touring extensively with his band.
 &HT;    He even helped the legendary guitarist master a new set of
strings.
 &HT;    ``I said, `Come out with me one day when I go fly fishing,'''
says Brooker, himself a European Open fly-fishing champion. ``He
liked it and I showed him how to do it _ he is a very quick
learner, and he became proficient pretty quickly and had a natural
feel for it.''
 &HT;    Brooker's main offstage focus, of late, has been a crusade to
save his neighborhood church in England. It's a surprising twist
for the singer, whose songs have often had an anti-clerical tone:
One denounced ``religious leaders teaching hate,'' while another
scorned preachers who ``don't know what they're teaching.''
 &HT;    Nevertheless, in 1996 Brooker came to the aid of the
13th-century St. Mary &AMP; All Saints Church, located in Surrey, a
bucolic suburb south of London. It was scheduled to close, he
learned, because of a budget crunch on the national level.
 &HT;    ``The main reason was that the Church of England invested
heavily in the stock market, and their coffers were emptied because
of losses on the market,'' he says, ``and they were going to take
away our local vicar.
 &HT;    ``So I said perhaps we could do a little concert in the village
hall,'' he recalls. ``They held me to my word, and we ended up
doing it in the church.''
 &HT;    The performance featured Brooker's vocals and piano leading a
rock band, backed by a chorus and string quartet. ``A Whiter Shade
of Pale'' came into its own when played on the church's organ. The
performance was recorded and issued on a CD as ``Within Our
House,'' and the hastily assembled recording has generated a steady
stream of funds to help keep the church open.
 &HT;    It was another spur-of-the-moment recording, on a chilly
Canadian November evening, which yielded Procol Harum's greatest
success. Brooker recorded the band's performance with the Edmonton
Symphony Orchestra, producing its only gold album. The biggest hit
was a remake of an earlier tune, ``Conquistador,'' which tells the
tale of a historical figure who came to conquer but only died.
 &HT;    The song, originally a forgettable track on Procol Harum's debut
album in 1967, was rearranged for orchestra at the last minute
because, Brooker says, ``we needed another fast one.''
 &HT;    Procol Harum continued to produce critically praised albums, and
even hit the European charts with a single called ``Pandora's Box''
in 1975. But it was never quite to break through as a top-rank
band.
 &HT;    Brooker can't help wondering if the band may have sealed its
fate in 1969, when it passed on a chance to play at the Woodstock
Music Festival.
 &HT;    ``They really wanted us at Woodstock, they pleaded with us,''
Brooker recalls. ``But we were just coming to the end of a long
tour, and one of the reasons we were going back to England was that
the wife of (guitarist) Robin Trower was going to have a baby, and
we were going to be there in time for that birth. So we said, `No
thanks, we are going home.'
 &HT;    ``The baby, of course, was two weeks late,'' he adds with a
chuckle. ``It would have helped us a lot if we had been at
Woodstock, but that's the way the dice fall.''
 c.1998 Tito Davila  
<TEXT>
