<HEADER>
A4601 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONICA-POTTER-IN-WITH     09-14 1438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONICA-POTTER-IN-WITHOUT-LIMITS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UNLIMITED POTENTIAL OF MONICA POTTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Monica Potter in a scene from ``Without
Limits.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    They tell Monica Potter she looks like Julia Roberts, but so
what?
 &HT;    ``Not that I would mind that a bit,'' Potter says. ``They do
tell me I look like Julia Roberts' blonde sister. I get Juliette
Lewis, too.''
 &HT;    Someday soon, though, people may be telling Lewis _ or even
Roberts _ that she looks like Monica Potter, because as she settles
in for an interview at the Los Angeles Hilton, wearing a simple
blue dress with her long blonde hair loose and tumbling across her
shoulders, the 26-year-old Potter is enjoying her status as one of
Hollywood's current rising stars.
 &HT;    Her appeal will be tested on Sept. 25, when she hits screens in
``Without Limits,'' a biopic of the late Olympic runner Steve
Prefontaine (Billy Crudup).
 &HT;    ``I play his girlfriend, Mary,'' Potter says. ``She's a real
person, which was a unique way for me to explore a role. I got to
spend a lot of time with the real Mary. She told me a lot of
stories about Steve and his drive to win. That helped me flesh out
the character.''
 &HT;    Produced by Tom Cruise and directed by Robert Towne, director of
``Personal Best'' (1982), ``Without Limits'' was filmed two years
ago, but delayed to distance it from Disney's ``Pre,'' a
Prefontaine biography which flopped in 1997.
 &HT;    In the meantime, Potter had made another film, gaining good
notices as Nicolas Cage's wife in 1997's ``Con Air.''
 &HT;    ``I saw `Con Air' with an audience,'' she recalls. ``It was an
out-of-body experience for me, because you really don't believe
you're up there. Afterwards someone recognized me and said, `Really
nice job.' That meant so much to me.''
 &HT;    So ``Without Limits'' is technically Potter's second film,
though it was made first. There's more to come, though: She plays
Robin Williams' love interest in ``Patch Adams,'' due in December,
and then will star in ``Martha Meet Frank, Daniel and Lawrence,'' a
romantic comedy with equally hot newcomers Joseph Fiennes _ Ralph's
brother _ and Rufus Sewell.
 &HT;    Add it all up, and Potter just might be the ingenue du jour.
 &HT;    ``This stardom idea is just starting to hit me,'' she says.
``I'd be thrilled to sign an autograph.''
 &HT;    She'd expected ``Without Limits'' to be her big break, but as it
turned out it was ``Con Air'' that got her bandwagon rolling.
 &HT;    ``I didn't think that movie would be a huge career boost,'' the
actress recalls. ``I just thought I would have a few weeks on the
film, and I would make my SAG rate and be able to pay off some
insurance.''
 &HT;    Instead, she says, she benefited from producer Jerry
Bruckheimer's eye for a hit. The film was an unexpected smash, and
suddenly Potter's agent started getting calls.
 &HT;    ``The thing about my agent is that she believed in me from day
one. She would send me to audition for things that Cameron Diaz was
getting or Gwyneth Paltrow might do,'' she recalls. ``She always
treated me like one of the girls who was doing very well. I never
felt like I couldn't do the big movies. I was told, `It's just a
matter of time.'''
 &HT;    Most actors have Hollywood horror stories, but not Potter.
 &HT;    ``I might be completely naive _ I'm from Cleveland,'' she says.
``But the truth of the matter is that people have been very nice to
me.''
 &HT;    Not that she hasn't had to work for her success. Potter has been
acting since age 5, in fact, having made her not-so-professional
debut in her parent's bedroom.
 &HT;    ``My Dad would tell me, `Pretend to be a sandwich,''' she
recalls, giggling. ``My three sisters and I would make ourselves
into human sandwiches with the pillows in my parents room.''
 &HT;    She laughs.
 &HT;    ``I know this is so bizarre _ just stick with me here,'' she
begs. ``My dad would put me between the pillows and I would act out
being peanut butter. I guess I was good at it, because my dad would
say, `You're going to be a movie star.'
 &HT;    ``I would always imagine that I was an actress,'' Potter adds.
``As a little girl, when I would wave to people, I would do it like
I was at the Oscars.''
 &HT;    Her destiny became manifest when she started acting in
Cleveland, doing commercials at age 12. She studied at the
prestigious Cleveland Playhouse, and then after high school logged
time in Chicago, Miami and Los Angeles trying to break into the
business.
 &HT;    ``I would take any job,'' Potter says. ``I did a children's
pilot for a game show. I hope nobody ever sees it.
 &HT;    ``I can see `Hard Copy' bringing it out,'' she adds, wincing.
 &HT;    Potter settled in Los Angeles in 1994 during a stint on the soap
opera ``The Young and the Restless.'' She was on the verge of
giving up show business, she admits, thinking that her real break
would never come.
 &HT;    ``I always thought I would like to study psychology, because I
think it's needed in this town,'' she says, laughing. ``I've always
been interested in why people are so weird, and there are a lot of
case studies in Hollywood.''
 &HT;    The idea of quitting at 22 would seem impossible to many
career-obsessed performers, but Potter's life has never revolved
exclusively around acting.
 &HT;    Currently, her highest priority is her two young children. She
and her husband, who is in the construction business, live in Los
Angeles _ though she is reluctant to say anything more about her
family, including the children's names or ages.
 &HT;    ``I don't want to say because I'm worried about security,'' she
says.
 &HT;    Some warned her that marriage and kids weren't compatible with a
Hollywood career, and urged her to keep it quiet.
 &HT;    ``At first,'' she recalls, ``everyone said, `Don't say anything
about being married. You're an ingenue!'''
 &HT;    She shrugs.
 &HT;    ``You know what? This is who I am,'' she says defiantly. ``If
people don't like it, they can lump it. Then they can take it down
the street and dump it. I don't care.
 &HT;    ``I learned that little line from my dad,'' she adds with a
chuckle, ``and it comes in really handy.''
 &HT;    Stardom may place further stress on her family life. Potter
isn't sure, but she's ready for the test.
 &HT;    ``Journalists ask me how this work will affect my personal
life,'' the actress says. ``My response is that you can only take
one day at a time, as they say.
 &HT;    ``I've been married for seven years,'' she adds, ``and my
husband is the most supportive person in the world next to my
father, so I'm not worried.
 &HT;    ``Anyway, who knows what will happen in a lifetime? Only God
knows. I think, as a couple, you just have to work together.
 &HT;    ``My family is what keeps me grounded,'' Potter concludes. ``A
lot of people in this business lose their personal life, and I hope
I never do.''
 &HT;    Even if it means giving up her shot at being the next Julia
Roberts.
 &HT;    ``It's not a bad thing to be compared to Julia,'' she says,
flashing a Julia-esque smile. ``I think she's fantastic. The
comparison might even help at this stage of my career, but once
people get to know me they'll see that I'm different.
 &HT;    ``I would love to play her little sister in a movie,'' Potter
adds. ``I could dye my hair brown or she could dye her hair blonde.
Either way, it would work.''
 &HT;    The truth is, Potter would rather be the next Carole Lombard.
 &HT;    ``I love the older actresses,'' she says. ``I love old-time
Hollywood. Those women were so beautiful and classy.
 &HT;    ``I would die if they said, `She's the next Grace Kelly.'''
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
