<P>
   &UR; The Fortune Teller &LR;
</P>
<P>
   During a recent publicity outing, Hillary sneaked off to visit a
fortune teller of some local repute. In a dark and hazy room,
peering into a crystal ball, the mystic delivered grave news.
</P>
<P>
   `There's no easy way to say this, so I'll just be blunt: Prepare
yourself to be a widow. Your husband will die a violent and
horrible death this year.`
</P>
<P>
   Visibly shaken, Hillary stared at the woman's lined face, then
at the single flickering candle, then down at her hands. She took a
few deep breaths to compose herself. She simply had to know. She
met the fortune teller's gaze, steadied her voice, and asked her
question.
</P>
<P>
   `Will I be acquitted?`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Gift Giver &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A young couple got married and went away on their honeymoon.
After 2 weeks they came back and finally put away all of the
presents they received from friends and family. Since this was a
new home, the process took sometime. The silver went into the
closet, items were put on the walls for display and some of the
more intimate apparel was put in the bedroom drawers.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, they received in the mail two tickets for a
popular show where tickets were impossible to get. They were very
excited and warmed by the gesture of the person who sent this.
Inside the envelope, however, was only a small piece of paper with
a single line.
</P>
<P>
   `Guess who sent them.`
</P>
<P>
   The pair had much fun trying to identify the donor, but failed
in the effort.
</P>
<P>
   They went to the theater, and had a wonderful time. On their
return home late at night, still trying to guess the identity of
the unknown host, they found the house stripped of every article of
value. And on the bare table in the dining-room was a piece of
paper on which was writtenin the same hand as the enclosure with
the tickets:
</P>
<P>
   `Now you know!`
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   My friend Ivy Podolski was driving home to New Jersey via Harlem
River Drive when her car began to overheat. She left the highway
and stopped at a service station. When her car was repaired, she
asked for directions back to the highway and was told to look for
Broadway and follow it until she saw the signs for Harlem River
Drive.
</P>
<P>
   After driving a few blocks, she realized she was hopelessly
lost. She stopped and asked a dreadlocked fellow on the street,
``Can you tell me how I can get to Broadway?'' He didn't miss a
beat. ``Well, it all depends,'' he replied. ``Can you sing, can you
dance?''
</P>
<P>
   _ DEBBIE GOLDSCHMIDT
</P>
<P>
   The hazards of parking in Manhattan are many and well known, but
Jamie Moog has another to add to the list. His car was parked on
the Upper West Side and when he went to pick it up, it looked, in
his own words, ``like a rancid tossed salad.'' A sanitation pickup
had obviously taken place and one of the bags had somehow come
undone over his car. Moog had no choice. He needed his car, so he
got in and started off, trailing lettuce, shredded carrots,
cucumber peels and other mutilated vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Stopped for a red light at 65th and Madison, he noticed a man
hosing down the sidewalk. He rolled down his window and yelled,
``Think I could have a blast?'' indicating the mess. The stranger
took one look, aimed a stream at the car and voila, almost as good
as a car wash. Moog directed a thumbs-up signal through the watery
window and headed to his appointment, his faith in humanity
restored.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Amesse is the deputy superintendent of a large wastewater
treatment plant on Wards Island. His duties include reviewing the
log sheets listing visitors. The truck drivers for one of the
contractors who remove the plant's waste usually sign in by writing
their company name and their own first name. Amesse was amused as
he looked over the sheets for one week this summer. There were only
two entries on the final shift. That night, the plant was visited
by Mohammed and Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   The scene: The J. Peterman outlet at Woodbury Common
</P>
<P>
   The observer: Carol Alexander
</P>
<P>
   Short, roundish woman, perhaps mid-40s, gesturing appropriately
to saleswoman: ``I'm a size 6 up here, but then I branch out.''
</P>
<P>
   The sign on the Chinese restaurant read: ``To serve you better,
Excellent Dumpling will be closed on Sundays.'' Which led Bonnie
Seegmiller to ponder how better service is achieved by closing.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Plotkin was annoyed with Sydney, her 4-year-old daughter.
``How many times do I have to tell you not to play with my good
camera?'' she asked. ``Don't worry, Mommy,'' Sydney replied. ``I
won't press the Cheese button.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Yaeger, breaking his drive back from East Hampton with
a snack stop, noticed a woman eating at one of the picnic benches
near the restaurant. As she set a plate of food down before her
apparently ravenous dog, she issued her instructions: ``Eat
slower,'' she commanded. ``Chew!''
</P>
<P>
   Ivy Berchuck was at Chautauqua this summer racing from concerts
to lectures. At one particularly crowded event, she edged onto a
bench, squeezing an elderly couple even closer together. After
apologizing, she began talking to them and the woman eventually
asked where she was from. ``New York City,'' Ms. Berchuck said. The
woman was thrilled. ``We're from Nashville,'' she said. ``We would
just love to visit New York some day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Please come soon,'' Ms. Berchuck replied. ``I know you'll have
a great time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes,'' the woman said. ``And I know what we'll do first.
We love music, so we'll drop our bags at a hotel and get ourselves
right over to the Metropolitan Opry.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Steuer and a friend were going through the security check
at Kennedy International Airport recently when the friend was
stopped. A mysterious-looking item in his suitcase showed up on the
X-ray. He opened his bag _ the item was a long shoehorn.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's that?'' the inspector asked. Told what it was, the
inspector said: ``Really? How do you play it?''
</P>
<P>
   The friend picked up the shoehorn, put it to his mouth and began
blowing through the hole at the end. Smiles all around. The couple
and the shoehorn were given a pass.
</P>
<P>
   Overheard on a Madison Avenue bus by Marilyn Baker:
</P>
<P>
   First chic woman: ``I just love your pedicure.''
</P>
<P>
   Second chic woman: ``I'll give you a card to my beauty salon but
ask for Monique. She really understands my toes.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Alden was sitting on a bench at the entrance to the Museum
of the City of New York when he heard this exchange between a young
