<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4629 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEATTLE-SYMPHONY-HALL     09-14 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATTLE-SYMPHONY-HALL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEATTLE, CIVIC PRIDE BUILDS MUSIC A HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Symphony orchestras in the United States begin as
civic gestures. While the Berlin or the Czech Philharmonic defends
a national culture (and is paid by a national government to do so),
their American counterparts identify individual cities and report
on their aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Cities like this one, for example, maintain their orchestras in
the same spirit in which they pave streets, plant trees or open
schools. European cities are old and work to keep their identities.
American cities are young and are usually looking for an identity.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Symphony, for all the local pride it represents, has
known the downside of urban life, including its longstanding and
seemingly intractable housing problem. Crowded with the city's
opera and ballet companies into a drably functional theater left
over from the 1973 World's Fair, it has regularly suffered the
indignities of restricted rehearsal opportunities, compromised
schedules, cramped quarters or, in some cases, no quarters at all.
</P>
<P>
   All this makes the opening of Benaroya Hall over the weekend an
important event. The 2,500-seat space, with a 540-seat recital hall
attached, sits between a pair of the steeply sloping side streets
that characterize Seattle's downtown. Like the art museum just
below it and the proliferating apartment buildings all around, it
is a component of urban renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle residents, festively dressed for the weekend's concerts,
seemed very pleased with what their city is doing.
</P>
<P>
   The new hall, costing $118 million, has been financed in the
usual American way, through a pool of local government funds,
corporate donations and private giving. The several names attached
to it are displays of gratitude, also typically American.
</P>
<P>
   The building itself is named for Jack Benaroya, a Seattle
developer who gave $15 million. The larger of the auditoriums bears
the name Taper, after the savings-and-loan family known for its
cultural generosity in California. The smaller space is Nordstrom
Hall, for the national retailers. The Boeing Arcade Gallery recalls
the airplane maker's significant help with management for the
project.
</P>
<P>
   Benaroya Hall is also important for how it works. Fiscally
minded builders have been leaning toward layouts adaptable to
several kinds of performance, but the multipurpose design has been
rejected here. No adjustable walls and ceilings. No orchestra pit
or wing space for musical theater. Every element is fixed in place.
It is a symphony hall. The city owns Benaroya Hall, but the Seattle
Symphony runs it.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, Benaroya's physical attractions are mostly hidden.
The big theater sits in a kind of cocoon: a sound-insulated
shoe-box shape encased on the outside by thick concrete, set on a
rubber undercarriage and further separated from the outside world
by an air pocket on every side.
</P>
<P>
   It has a darkly handsome interior, though it was made less so by
Saturday night's heightened television lights. Boxes are angled
toward the stage. The surfaces are plaster, and the walls, made of
African makore wood, bulge intermittently in the form of converging
triangles.
</P>
<P>
   The acoustics designed by Cyril Harris seem exceptionally good.
One hears the different orchestra sections with clarity, and
already the stage floorboards resonate nicely. Having been witness
at the inauguration of several dry, dead halls in recent years, I
find this one a pleasant surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller hall is equally alive if not more so. Chamber
orchestras and new-music ensembles, at least judging from the
rehearsal I heard on Friday, are going to be severely tested on
matters of restraint and fineness. The recital hall has an explicit
sound; it promises to reward the virtuous while punishing the
smallest musical miscalculation.
</P>
<P>
   Benaroya Hall's exteriors make little impression; this amateur's
eye, at least, found little to engage it. What one sees from the
street or experiences in the inner public spaces appears functional
to a fault, despite Robert Rauschenberg's large panels above the
main staircase and the pair of oddly wriggling glass chandeliers by
Dale Chihuly.
</P>
<P>
   It is as if the designer Mark Reddington and his employers
really didn't want to be noticed at all. Seattle, for all its
openness to the arts, is a conservative town and may not have been
in the mood for a beacon or a challenge. What it has got is a
well-behaved neighbor. The performance spaces, properly lighted,
are striking. What is around them reassures more than it excites.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Saturday's symphony concert, conducted by Gerard Schwarz, began
with speeches and then went through a potpourri of pieces. ``A Gala
Celebration'' by David Diamond was busy and businesslike in its
first performance. Webern's hyper-romantic ``Langsamer Satz,'' an
attractive sin of the composer's youth, profited from Schwarz's
preference for slow tempos. So did most of Stravinsky's
``Firebird'' Suite and the excerpts from Wagner's
``Goetterdaemmerung'' after intermission.
</P>
<P>
   The first bizarre moment of the evening was Henri Lazarof's
``Celebration for Four Brass Choirs.'' Such anguished and
gloom-ridden music seemed a strange way to greet Seattle's
citizenry as it filed into its new hall for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The other episode of strangeness was Jessye Norman in Wagner's
final scene. One forgave the lapses in pitch and the episodes of
strain; the part is probably high for her voice. Less acceptable
were the hooting vowels, the spit-out consonants and the popeyed
exaggeration of gesture. Ms. Norman has within her a great artist.
I hope she will look at what she did here on television and do some
reconsidering.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra itself is decent, reliable and at times quite
good. With Schwarz, its future is in excellent hands. Perhaps the
real challenge Benaroya Hall offers is to these musicians. The
place is a world-class establishment, a significant success. The
Seattle Symphony is going to have to work hard to keep up with it.
</P>
</TEXT>
