<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WOMEN SUPPORTERS CONFLICTED OVER CLINTON
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For many women who have been among President
Clinton's most loyal fans, these are uncomfortable and conflicting
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts my heart,'' said Susan Lundy, looking visibly
distressed as she went from exasperation to admiration to
disillusionment in discussing the man she had twice voted for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than being a womanizing jerk, he's a good leader,'' said
Lundy, a 40-year-old registered nurse from Bondurant, Wyo. But she
quickly added of his sexual liaison with a White House intern and
his efforts to cover it up: ``It's unforgiveable, the abuse of
office.''
</P>
<P>
   But should he be impeached? ``I think the humiliation is
punishment enough,'' she said. ``I feel like he's leading us in the
right direction.'' Asked what that has meant for her family, she
offered, ``He seems to have cared'' about people and added: ``It's
all 'seems to have' now.''
</P>
<P>
   Turning to her 3-year-old son Jason, along for a family tour of
the capital, she said, ``I'm not telling him'' about the president.
</P>
<P>
   Women, especially the so-called ``soccer moms'' who were widely
credited with providing Clinton's victory margins in 1992 and in
1996, are being tested by the Starr report and its graphic
depictions of Clinton's sexual escapades with then 21-year-old
Monica Lewinsky. Although their support has drooped a bit, women
continue to support the president in far greater numbers than men,
most recent polls indicate. A Washington Post poll, for example,
showed that 25 percent of women favor impeachment, compared with 35
percent of men.
</P>
<P>
   Many of his staunchest supporters are still holding on, but with
caveats.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could get him by the collar and shake him and say, 'Grow
up!' and have it work, I would have done it a long time ago,''
Patricia Ireland, president of the National Organization for Women,
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Her feminist group has pulled back from solid backing and even
discussed calling for Clinton's resignation. ``I've been talking to
a lot of people who think it would help to have Al Gore an an
incumbent,'' Ireland said.
</P>
<P>
   She blamed Clinton for ``the kind of disrepect for women in the
workplace that may be harmful to literally millions of us out in
the work place.'' And that's in addition to the scandal's expected
impact on the coming elections, in which Republicans and
conservatives unsympathetic to NOW's views are expected to extend
their majority in Congress
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   For all of that, Ireland still applauds Clinton's policies,
which included pro-choice on abortion, and for picking women for
high cabinet posts such as Attorney General Janet Reno and
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, both firsts for their
gender.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't come in perfect packages,'' Ireland said.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   At the National Women's Political Caucus, president Anita Perez
Ferguson said she leans toward censure for Clinton, whom she faults
for ``setting a bad example'' but credits for numerous small
changes throughout the government, especially the signing of the
family medical leave act.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is obviously a real split between the person and the
policies,'' Ferguson said. ``I feel that I can trust him with the
public policies, the leadership of the economy, and in
international relations. With other things, I'm going to be
cautious and watch where we go.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson readily conceded her position was not totally
consistent on Clinton. ``Life is contradictory,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of Clinton's female supporters have been so
understanding. Mary Jones, a retiree from the Chicago suburb of
Naporville who was visiting Washington voted for the president but
now regrets it. She believes he should resign or be impeached..
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me,'' she added, ``he's supposed to be an
inspiration to the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
