<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 REPORTS, ONE GLOBAL, ONE REGIONAL, DRIVE BONDS UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The price of the 30-year Treasury bond rose late
Monday as stocks declined from their intraday highs.
</P>
<P>
   Two reports were also major factors in bond market activity. A
statement from the Group of Seven nations led to speculation of
global interest rate cuts to spur growth, and a regional report by
the Federal Reserve Bank of Atlanta showed that manufacturing in
the southern part of the country was slowing, which could suggest
the Fed might lower interest rates soon.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Schaja, an economist with Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette,
said Monday's Atlanta Fed report on regional business activity was
not as weak as it appeared. The index of business activity fell to
a reading of minus 12.1 in August from a plus 1.2 reading in July,
which had originally been reported as a reading of plus 3.4.
</P>
<P>
   ``The details of the report suggest that caution should be used
in interpreting the decline as a reliable gauge of a sharp drop in
economic activity,'' Ms. Schaja said.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year bond was up 4/32, to 104 4/32. Its yield, which
moves in the opposite direction from the price, fell to 5.22
percent, from 5.23 percent on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Market participants were also awaiting Wednesday's testimony to
the House Banking Committee by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, who will report on
the global economic turmoil and may offer some insight about rate
cuts. Few investors, however, expect a cut in interest rates before
the Sept. 29 meeting of the Federal Open Market Committee, the
Fed's policy-making group.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the bond market already bracing for a very weak economy
before actual business conditions seriously deteriorate,'' said
Maury Harris, chief economist at Paine Webber, ``the accompanying
pre-emptive interest rate reductions should prevent realization of
the stock market's worst fears about a weak U.S. economy.''
</P>
<P>
   And he added that since the Fed might start temporarily basing
its rate decisions more on world financial market and economic
turbulence than on just this nation's economic conditions, even a
temporarily very weak domestic economy might no longer be required
before the central bank trimmed the federal funds rate that banks
charge one another for overnight loans. That rate is currently 5.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
