<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BASEBAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME RUN CHASE A HAPPY DISTRACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The thrill of the chase is back!
</P>
<P>
   The quest to become Major League Baseball's all-time home run
leader seemed to lose some of its spark when Mark McGwire of the
St. Louis Cardinals, with a nation watching last Tuesday, drilled
No. 62 on a line just inside the left field foul pole at Busch
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs, at 58 and holding, was lost in
the McGwiremania. For all the excitement that the McGwire-Sosa home
run chase had generated through the summer, there was a sense that
once McGwire surpassed Roger Maris' tremendous feat of 61 home runs
in 1961, the home run derby, for all intents and purposes, was
over.
</P>
<P>
   A gap of four round-trippers with two weeks to go seemed
insurmountable. Time for fans to turn their attention to the
upcoming playoffs, and maybe pay more attention to the start of the
football season.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Bill Clinton and Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast. In the friendly confines of Wrigley Field last
weekend, Sosa did not disappoint the fans who love to chant
Sam-meeee; Sam-meeee. On Friday he hit No. 59. On Saturday No. 60
flew out onto Waveland Avenue. And on Sunday he again hit two
tremendous shots over the left field wall _ all unanswered by
McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa _ whose grace and heartfelt joy at seeing McGwire smash the
record redefined humility in professional athletics _ had tied
McGwire for perhaps the most glamorous record in all of sport.
</P>
<P>
   It was an amazing display of power in a series with the
Milwaukee Brewers, who left Chicago not knowing what hit them. The
advance hype and postgame hoopla sadly paled by comparison to that
which surrounded McGwire's feat earlier in the week. Sosa's
incredible accomplishments of the weekend were overshadowed by a
nation trying to come to grips with a president fighting for his
political survival.
</P>
<P>
   These two men have been great for baseball, helping to erase the
image of overpaid athletes who sulk better than they play, of a
sport with labor problems that never seem to end, and of a league
that has a long way to go to recapture the respect that it once
had.
</P>
<P>
   Records are made to be broken, and by season's end the home run
king will be the player with the most. Regardless of who will wear
the new crown, the skills of both men in putting the sweet part of
the bat on a pitch traveling in excess of 90 mph from a distance of
60 feet, 6 inches, are truly remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   They have been a tonic for the country and for baseball, and for
that we are thankful. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1848EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
