<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4650 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SURGERY-GAYNOR-HNS &LR;      09-14 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURGERY-GAYNOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVVY COSMETIC SURGEON LEAVES TRAIL OF DISSATISFIED PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LANCY WILLIAMS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Charming, glib and media savvy, Dr. Alan Gaynor
is San Francisco's most televised cosmetic surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   The state Medical Board accuses him of incompetence, gross
negligence and dishonesty. But on talk TV, Gaynor has become an
emblem for the idea that, with little pain or risk, modern medicine
can reverse the aging process.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Gaynor gave Geraldo Rivera a live-on-camera ``instant
face lift,'' using a syringe to suck fat from the talk-show host's
buttocks and injecting it into a crease in Geraldo's craggy face.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, as the studio audience laughed and cheered, Gaynor gave
Geraldo an on-air eyelid lift.
</P>
<P>
   On his Web site, www.lookyoung.com, Gaynor say he is ``the best
known cosmetic surgeon in the United States,'' with appearances on
more than 400 TV shows.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes dressed in aquamarine surgical scrubs, he has
cheerfully flogged such procedures as the ``Lipo-Sculption'' (a
$10,000-per-session surgical suctioning of fat from the belly,
bottom and thighs), the ``Sushi Hair Transplant'' ($3,000 per
cluster of mini-grafts) and the laser-fired ``Alternative
Facelift'' ($5,000 per blast.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We travel the world to find new surgical procedures that are
safe and work well!'' his commercial says.
</P>
<P>
   But don't tell that to the Medical Board, which in 1996 moved to
suspend Gaynor's medical license, or to four women who have claimed
in court papers that they were disfigured during visits to his
office.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor denied wrongdoing. He said he was a caring, skilled
doctor, wrongly targeted by the state, perhaps for writing a
consumer-oriented book on cosmetic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had great sympathy for patients who have complained
about him, but said the vast majority of his patients had happy
outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in practice 21 years. During that period, I've done
20,000 procedures,'' he said in an interview. ``I will leave it to
you: Are the number of cases I had too many for ... a doctor who
has been in practice that long?''
</P>
<P>
   One woman said Gaynor's fat transfer procedure had left her with
leg scars and nerve damage.
</P>
<P>
   Another said she had needed a tracheotomy after her neck
liposuction went awry. A third said she had suffered ``horrendous
facial scarring'' and lost part of her nose.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth said that while having permanent eyeliner applied, she
had been stabbed in the eye with a syringe and partially blinded.
</P>
<P>
   For them, Gaynor has come to symbolize a lamentable aspect of
the surgical quest for youthful good looks, one seldom mentioned on
happy-talk TV or in glossy ads. Cosmetic surgery is serious
business _ and when it goes wrong, the down side is very steep
indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The injury Dr. Gaynor inflicted on me has shattered my life,''
former fashion consultant Lisa Santoro wrote to a San Francisco
judge in 1993, more than a year after she said Gaynor had punctured
her eye with a syringe. ``The episodes of pain that I have endured
... have been beyond comprehension.''
</P>
<P>
   According to his Web site biography, Gaynor is a onetime child
piano prodigy from New York who became a dermatologist in San
Francisco in 1980, after completing Yale Medical School and a
residency at the University of California at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few years, he was showing up in gossip columns as ``the
best skin doctor in the world'' and ``the Sassoon or Gucci of
skin.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, Gaynor focused on collagen injections, surgical face
lifts, chemical skin peels. But he became interested in
liposuction.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he has recalled in TV interviews, he met Brazilian
physician Luis Toledo, who was saving fat from liposuction and
injecting it into the faces of patients to smooth wrinkles. Gaynor
seized on the procedure and promoted it heavily. Eventually, the
supermarket tabloid Globe featured him in its ``medical marvels''
column.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor's first breakthrough celebrity client was Eddie Fisher:
in 1989, he got his name in USA Today for performing liposuction on
the 1950s crooner.
</P>
<P>
   But that was nothing compared to the public relations bonanza he
reaped from his 1992 appearance on ``Geraldo.''
</P>
<P>
   While comedian Joan Rivers made wisecracks and the studio
audience whooped and yelled, Gaynor gave Rivera a local anesthetic,
then extracted fat from his bottom and injected it into his
forehead to smooth a wrinkle. The physician kept a running patter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Geraldo's going to get the point now!'' Gaynor quipped as he
shot Rivera's backside with Novocain.
</P>
<P>
   The show had monster ratings. The after-broadcast buzz continued
for months, as the Johnny Carson, Arsenio Hall shows and ``Saturday
Night Live'' took turns mocking Rivera for undergoing what came to
be known as the ``butt-head'' procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor parlayed that appearance into three other ``Geraldo''
stints, plus appearances on ``20/20'' and other national shows.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor's media-propelled medical practice brought him wealth: a
mansion on Telegraph Hill and two Mercedes Benzes, one with the
personalized license plate, ``LIPODOC.'' His donations to Steve
Young's Forever Young Foundation caused the San Francisco 49ers
quarterback to praise Gaynor as ``a man with a golden heart.''
</P>
<P>
   But a different portrait of Gaynor emerges from a review of the
lawsuits in which he has been involved. In them, he is sometimes
portrayed as confrontational and litigious.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1990 he sued a prospective patient after she balked at going
through with an operation.
</P>
<P>
   And last year, after a patient sued him over a fat transfer that
went awry, Gaynor counter-sued for invasion of privacy, because the
patient had tape-recorded some of her phone calls to him
complaining about post-operative problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``My civil rights have been violated,'' Gaynor told the court.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor's worst problem with a patient occurred in 1992, only
three months after his first appearance on ``Geraldo.''
</P>
<P>
   Santoro, 37, a glamorous, $250,000-per-year saleswoman in New
York's Garment District, said she had read an article in Allure
magazine that described how Gaynor had given his own wife permanent
eyeliner by tattooing her upper and lower eyelids. Santoro wanted
the procedure to highlight her own striking brown eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Reassured by literature describing Gaynor's ``100 percent
positive track record with our clients,'' her lawsuit said, Santoro
flew to San Francisco. At Gaynor's office, she said, she watched a
video of a Gaynor appearance on the Phil Donahue show, then was
given Valium.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Gaynor injected Santoro's eyelids with lidocaine,
then turned her over to a tattoo artist, Linda Swan, to apply the
eyeliner.
</P>
<P>
   But within minutes it became clear something was terribly wrong.
Santoro told Swan her eye hurt. After that, according to the
Medical Board, Gaynor told Swan to drive his patient to the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In the car, the pain was so intense, Santoro began throwing up.
</P>
<P>
   In her lawsuit, Santoro said Gaynor had plunged the needle of
lidocaine directly into her cornea. The injuries destroyed the lens
of her eye and all but wrecked her life, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Beset by pain and confined for years to a darkened room because
of light sensitivity, she lost her job and her fiance.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor initially said the accident had occurred because Santoro
had thrashed about in the chair as he injected her. Later, in a
counter-lawsuit, he blamed Swan, claiming that the tattoo artist
had re-injected Santoro's eye with anesthetic after he'd left the
room.
</P>
<P>
   Swan denied it. She sued Gaynor, claiming he had tried to induce
her to back up his false testimony in a pretrial hearing; Gaynor
countered with a slander suit, accusing Swan of telling potential
patients that he had blinded Santoro.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the lawsuits were settled. But the Medical Board has
charged Gaynor with gross negligence, dishonesty and repeated
negligent acts in the affair.
</P>
<P>
   Gaynor said terms of the settlements limit what he can say, but
he said that once the injury occurred, he sent Santoro to ``the
best ophthalmologist in the city. ... I was profoundly worried for
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gaynor said he put his medical practice ``in
hibernation'' to spend more time with his family and to promote his
book, ``Everything You Ever Wanted to Know About Cosmetic Surgery
But Couldn't Afford to Ask.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a ``definite guide to finding the fountain of youth in the
doctor's office,'' the publisher said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
