<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4673 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-REPORT-SCENE-     09-14 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REPORT-SCENE-755&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS AND LAWMAKERS SIFT THROUGH STARR REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ark., Calif.)  (See also CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-CONSTITUENTS, CLINTON-DEFENSE,
CLINTON-STARR, CLINTON-POLICY, CLINTON-PERJURY) 
(lb) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The room, H2-186 in the Ford House Office Building,
has the crash-course ambiance of a law-school study hall on the eve
of the nation's ultimate examination on constitutional law.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the 27 lawyers and 35 House lawmakers who are the only
ones permitted the entry code to the guarded room are cramming on
the biggest legal case of their careers _ the impeachment grounds
crafted against President Clinton by Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are highly trained lawyers, so I assume they have some
special talent for rummaging through the 17 boxes of stuff in
there,'' one House staff member said with a smile of doubt at the
daunting task going on inside as the lawyers quietly, whisperingly
race through the Starr report's supporting evidence for impeachment
charges.
</P>
<P>
   The staff lawyers _ 18 Republicans and nine Democrats _
sometimes find themselves sharing a big study table in the
45-by-15-foot common conference room. They sit as rival scholastics
silently searching through various chunks of the Starr boxes for
something damning or promising, exculpatory or explosive. Time is
short; the task is huge, with the room open only from 8 a.m. until
midnight each day for intense lawyers who might prefer
all-nighters.
</P>
<P>
   Two separate side rooms have been set aside for the minority and
majority members, stocked with locked storage cabinets and video
and audiotape players to sample electronic evidence ranging from
Linda Tripp's furtive recordings of Monica Lewinsky to Clinton's
controversial pleadings of his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   No one can leave with any documents, which marks H2-186 as the
latest challenging arena in the endless media-leaking contest that
has marked the sex-and-mendacity investigation of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, here I am just skating around the Ford building,'' Rep.
John Conyers of Michigan, the ranking Democrat on the Judiciary
Committee, declared rather fatalistically as he wandered the halls
in search of H2-186. ``I just want to see the premises,'' he said
before finding the Starr cache and sampling the contents for an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Conyers emerged chewing jelly beans and offering no fresh
epiphanies. ``It goes on and on and on and on.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the weekend and on Monday, the Judiciary staff lawyers
and the first trickle of committee members began the rush to vet
for public consumption some or all of the boxfuls of supporting
evidence. From explicit tapes to anecdotal hearsay, through 2,600
pages of offerings beyond the boxes, they have less than two weeks
to fashion the next big impetus in the scandal inquiry _ another
document-big dump on the far-from-finished task of judging the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people do not want, do not see the need for such
detail,'' said Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Fla., a member of the
Judiciary committee who faulted the lurid detail found in the Starr
report and anticipated more in the boxfuls of material inside
H2-186.
</P>
<P>
   The loudest outburst in the common room over the weekend,
according to participants who wanted their identities protected,
was not about the overturning of another promising rock of
illicitness; it was over Sammy Sosa's hitting his 62nd home run to
pull even with Mark McGwire. Quietude soon resumed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of like being in a library _ you don't talk a lot,''
said Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., a former U.S. attorney who spent
10 hours in the document room over the weekend and went back for
more Monday. He finds the offerings important because they are, in
effect, the specific citations on which Starr is making the case
against the president. ``We have to put it in context but also see
what material there may be of an exculpatory nature.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere in there is intense but rather collegial,''
Hutchinson said. ``We're trying to get a job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Between the two private offices of the separate sides there is
the inner-sanctum storeroom of Starr materials, divided within by a
partition, with each side having a full set of documents for
authorized parties to peruse. A copying machine is in the common
area, but it is for use only within the H2-186 operation.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately the Judiciary committee and not Starr's report will
be the agent of any impeachment decision, and not all committee
members are rushing to sample Starr's secret offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't looked at it yet,'' said Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif.,
a member of the Judiciary committee. ``Mr. Starr sent over a bunch
of accusations and we could spend a lot of time running around.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the congresswoman said she preferred a different initial
approach. As a lawyer, she stayed here last weekend to study not
the Starr appendices but the Watergate articles of impeachment from
24 years ago, when she served as a staffer in the thick of that
ordeal. ``The first thing is to know what matters
constitutionally,'' she explained, ``And not so much what matters
to us emotionally or morally.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lofgren said she was enlightened by a phrase she had
forgotten from the impeachment articles against President Richard
Nixon, a standard she finds relevant once more, whether
presidential misbehavior is ``subversive of constitutional
government to the great prejudice of the cause of law and justice
and to the manifest injury of the people of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what matters,'' Ms. Lofgren said, promising to consider
in due course whatever H2-186 might have to offer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
