<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIOR-CARE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CRIMINAL BACKGROUND CHECKS URGED FOR NURSING HOME EMPLOYEES
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Convicted criminals continue to find employment in
U.S. nursing homes, and the homes should be required to use a
national registry to perform background checks on many applicants,
advocates for the elderly urged Congress on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In a hearing of the Senate Special Committee on Aging, Sen. John
Breaux, D-La., presented a report by government auditors showing
that about 5 percent of nursing home employees in Maryland and
Illinois had records of crimes including assault and armed robbery.
</P>
<P>
   The panel heard testimony from a man whose 92-year-old mother
was raped by a nursing home worker later identified as a convicted
child molester.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there are places where convicted criminals who have
paid their debt to society should be able to work,'' said Sen.
Chuck Grassley, R-Iowa. ``But if the crime was one of violence or
deception, my view is that nursing homes are not one of the places
these criminals should work. In these settings, seniors are just
too vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Abuse in nursing homes has become a growing concern as the
population grows older and long-term care facilities suffer from
tightening budgets, low staffing levels and declining Medicare
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   In July, President Clinton ordered a crackdown on nursing homes
in light of a report that showed two-thirds of American nursing
homes are abusing patients or repeatedly violating health and
safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, support has grown for a law to create a national
registry and require all nursing homes to check the background of
people applying for jobs that bring them into frequent contact with
residents. Although at least 33 states have their own background
check laws, they don't have access to each others' records.
</P>
<P>
   The Service Employees International Union, which represents many
nursing home employees, said it would supports such a law, but
added that there should be a provision allowing recourse for
applicants who are denied employment resulting from an inaccurate
background check. The group also said employees should not be made
to pay for the background checks.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1904EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4676 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLICY-2TAKES     09-14 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLICY-2TAKES(840)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS LOOK TO PUSH AGENDA AND KEEP HEAT IN CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-ECON, CLINTON-REPORT-SCENE, CLINTON-SCHOOLS,
CLINTON-PERJURY, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-PASTORS, NY-CLINTON.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Eager to appear focused on the people's business
and not President Clinton's, Republicans plan to push ahead with
their ambitious agenda of economic and social issues, while hoping
to avoid outright battles that would allow Clinton to shift the
focus away from his own woes.
</P>
<P>
   As the pressure on Clinton mounted, Republican Congressional
leaders insisted in the past several days that they were
concentrating on the issues of most concern to their constituents,
from tax cuts and the budget to abortion, drug use and national
security.
</P>
<P>
   In part, they said, they were motivated by a desire to avoid
appearing overly partisan as the House considers impeachment
hearings. But they also said voters want them to have a positive
message heading into this fall's elections and not just to
capitalize on Clinton's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to expand our majority is to do the business of
the people, not to expect the problems of the Democratic side to
carry us forward,'' said Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo. ``Their
liabilities are not necessarily our assets.''
</P>
<P>
   The way the Republicans handle their legislative agenda in the
final few weeks before Congress adjourns will go a long way toward
determining how much opportunity Clinton will have to change the
subject or put Republicans on the defensive. Most obviously,
Republicans will have to decide whether to risk a showdown over
their spending priorities and a repeat of the government shutdown
in 1995 and early 1996 that played out to Clinton's tremendous
political benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said there is a division within the party about how
hard to push in coming weeks not just over the spending bills
making their way through Congress, but over tax cuts and social
issues like abortion.
</P>
<P>
   While some Republicans in Congress want to press as hard as
possible on those issues at a time when the White House is
struggling to stay politically relevant, other Republicans are
counseling restraint, saying the party should compromise and avoid
ideological battles that Clinton could use to rally his core
Democratic base.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the view that says that from a political standpoint
things seem to be breaking in the direction of the Republicans and
we should not engage in efforts to pursue our policy agenda that
are not consensual and should let the election be about the
president and his conduct,'' said Rep. David McIntosh, R-Ind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there's the argument that the American people want us to
do our job on the Starr report, but they really want us to do our
job on cutting taxes, balancing the budget and maintaining a strong
national defense,'' McIntosh said. ``People are evenly split
between those two views.''
</P>
<P>
   McIntosh said he came down on the side of pursuing an ambitious
agenda, although not to the point of shutting down the government
over differences with Clinton about spending priorities for the new
fiscal year that starts Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   A memo circulating among Republican members of Congress last
week from Frank Luntz, a consultant who is influential with many
conservatives, said Clinton is much weaker than during battles over
changing the health care system in 1994 and balancing the budget in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``By a healthy 14-point margin, Americans believe President
Clinton is likely to try to distract the nation from his ethical
problems by forcing a confrontation with Congress'' over policy
issues, Luntz's memo said.
</P>
<P>
   But Luntz said shutting down the government over spending bills
would be going too far, with voters saying they would blame
Republicans rather than Clinton, by 42 percent to 32 percent, if
such a showdown occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Republicans said, Clinton's troubles have created new
opportunities for legislative victories. Republicans said they now
have a realistic hope of passing a substantial tax cut this year,
believing that Clinton has lost some of his ability to convince
voters that a tax cut, by dipping into projected federal budget
surpluses, will endanger the future of the ailing Social Security
system.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said the assumption that the president's
power and influence were in terminal decline vastly overstated his
loss of ability to shape the outcomes of many policy disputes. And
with the country still likely to face crises having nothing to do
with Clinton's sex life, they said Clinton will play as central a
role as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still has the veto pen,'' said a senior administration
official who spoke on the condition of anonymity. ``He still has
the microphone.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said it would play to their strengths if
Republicans decide to push a conservative agenda, especially on
such issues as education and the environment where the House has
often had to back down when confronted by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's win-win,'' said the White House official. ``If the
Republicans cave, it shows we're still winning our policy agenda.
And if they fight us on an issue like education it will only remind
the public why they like Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Along with taxes, the biggest policy fights in coming weeks will
be over the spending bills that Congress must pass to finance the
government's operation in the new fiscal year that starts Oct. 1.
Clinton issued veto threats against many of the bills during the
summer, objecting both to the spending levels for many programs and
to language dictating the way some programs are run.
</P>
<P>
   But although they said they will almost certainly not allow the
government to be shut down _ Congress can pass temporary spending
measures if Clinton should veto any of the appropriations bills _
Republicans said they may prove less willing to compromise than if
the president was not fighting for his survival.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Democrats said Clinton's limited ability to
twist arms on Capitol Hill and rally public support could thwart
any chance of them getting their legislative initiatives through
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Without considerable help from the president, Democrats said,
the party's already difficult struggle to push new regulations on
health maintenance organizations through the Senate will become a
long shot at best.
</P>
<P>
   A hobbled and distracted president will also make it
considerably more difficult for Democrats to build pressure on
Republicans to go along with a proposed increase in the minimum
wage, a key goal of liberals in the final weeks of this Congress.
The wage increase faces a key test on Tuesday, when Senate
Democrats will attempt to attach it to legislation overhauling the
nation's bankruptcy system.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's problems also raise questions about a variety of other
issues, including how much time he will have to devote to foreign
policy. And his troubles have in some ways demoralized Republicans
as well as Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   After the campaign finance overhaul bill that he co-sponsored
suffered another procedural defeat last week, Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., was asked if he would continue bringing up the bill in the
hopes of creating more pressure for its passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not as long as the president has got the problems he has,''
McCain said. ``We don't talk about HMO's anymore, we don't talk
about taxes anymore, we don't talk about Social Security anymore.
There's only one thing on everybody's mind and everybody knows it.
That's the great tragedy of the whole thing we are going through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1905EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
