<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4680 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CEO-PAY-MARKETPLACE-A     09-14 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEO-PAY-MARKETPLACE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: FOR CHIEF EXECUTIVES, HOME RUN SEASON ENDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic on CEO compensations is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ADAM BRYANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until the recent market slump, chief executives had been hitting
financial home runs like Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa. With
compensation tied increasingly to the rising stock market, outfield
walls were moving in every year _ so much so that many executives
started betting they could hit the ball far beyond the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Since July, however, stocks have been broadly lower. Even with
Monday's strong gains, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, for
example, is down 14 percent from its high on July 17. With the
slump _ and uncertainty about the market's future _ the challenge
chief executives face to make their stock options pay off looks
very different. Executive compensation experts say that if the
market goes into a prolonged slump, the mix and structure of
executive pay packages may change in ways both small and large.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the system works correctly, and if corporations and boards
are serious about pay for performance, there should not be an
alteration in how compensation is delivered,'' said Judith Fischer,
publisher of Executive Compensation Reports, a newsletter. ``But I
think totally new mechanisms will start springing up if the market
does not rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the recent slide, for example, some companies were
backing away from signing onto compensation plans that require
above-average performance before paying off, partly out of fear
that the market was overheated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen some people getting cold feet,'' said Robin
Ferracone, president of SCA Consulting in Los Angeles, whose firm
has designed many recent executive compensation plans that set
tougher hurdles for executives.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ferracone and others said that in the event of a prolonged
slump, executives might start requesting that part of their pay be
tied to measures other than the stock price, such as long-term
earnings growth. That is what happened in the flat stock market of
the 1970s, only to be abandoned increasingly for pay tied more to
stock performance.
</P>
<P>
   Such a strategy has paid off handsomely in recent years. The
average salary and bonus of 279 chief executives of large companies
was $2.1 million last year, according to Graef Crystal, editor of
the Crystal Report newsletter on executive compensation. However,
the present value of stock options they received, which give them
the right to buy stock at a set price for a set period of time,
helped push the value of the average pay package to $8.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the drop in the stock market has knocked tens of
millions of dollars worth of paper profits off the value of many
executives' stock options. For others who have signed up for more
challenging compensation packages, the likelihood that those plans
will pay out has also dropped significantly.
</P>
<P>
   Consider John Reed, chairman of Citicorp. Earlier this year,
Reed received 300,000 stock options at about $120. But there was an
important catch. For those options to vest, Citicorp stock had to
reach $200 within five years, and stay at or above that mark for 10
trading days within a 30-day period.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, on the day the proposed merger of Citicorp and
Travelers Group was announced, Reed was well on his way to reaching
his mark _ Citicorp's stock hit its high for the year of $182 on
April 6. But Citicorp's stock closed Monday at $101.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is looking at the price barrier through the wrong end of a
telescope, and he is doing that perched under five feet of water,''
Crystal said. ``It's very hard to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed has plenty of company. When Richard Nanula left his post as
Disney's chief financial officer to become chief executive of
Starwood Hotels and Resorts Worldwide Inc., he signed up for a pay
package that included 3 million stock options with exercise prices
ranging from $53.2875 to $76.125. When his move was announced April
15, Starwood's stock reached a high that day of $53, just shy of
the strike price of his first million options. Since then, Starwood
shares have fallen to $32.0625.
</P>
<P>
   At Circuit City Stores Inc., Richard Sharp, its chief executive,
was closing in this summer on a stock price of $59, the exercise
price of 1 million options he was granted in the 1997 fiscal year,
when the stock was just under $30. But after reaching a high of
$54.50 on July 14, Circuit City's stock has since dropped to
$33.5625.
</P>
<P>
   Other executives received enormous grants of stock options in a
single year, agreeing not to receive any more for several years.
Depending on how the market performs over the next few years, they
may wish they had stuck with smaller annual option grants.
</P>
<P>
   Reuben Mark, chairman of Colgate Palmolive Co., received a grant
last year of 2.6 million stock options to last him through 2003.
The exercise price of the options was set at levels between 10
percent and 70 percent over the market price of $62.563 on Nov. 7
when they were granted. Although the stock ran up to a high of
$98.875 on July 24, it has since sunk to Monday's close of
$72.9375.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, a bear market would certainly test chief
executives' commitment to sticking to the letter of their
employment contract.
</P>
<P>
   For example, more than 20 percent of the country's 1,000 largest
companies have adopted guidelines in the last five years that
require top officers to own stock equal in value to several times
their annual salaries. The goal of such guidelines was to create
the perception that executives were in the same boat as outside
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   But in a falling market, top executives face potentially two
doses of bad news. Not only would the value of their personal
holdings in company stock be falling, but if companies are vigilant
about enforcing the guidelines, they will also make the chief
executive buy even more stock to remain within the guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Because such guidelines are a relatively recent phenomenon,
``I'm not completely sure how many teeth there are in them,'' said
Steven Hall, managing director of Pearl Meyer &AMP; Partners, a
compensation consulting firm in New York.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, many companies may be tempted to reprice their stock
options, a practice used by many concerns in recent years that have
not joined in the bull market. Repricing, which effectively lowers
the bar over which employees must jump for the options to pay off,
has come under growing scrutiny by institutional investors and the
media, and a number of consultants said they expected many
companies would resist the temptation to reprice.
</P>
<P>
   One alternative, of course, is to simply grant new stock options
at a lower price, using the argument that executives need such
incentives to keep them from jumping ship to a competitor. Such a
move, however, could also anger shareholders by further diluting
the value of their stock.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Edelstein, a principal with Todd Organization, an
executive benefits consulting firm, said that many companies whose
performance faltered before the broader market dip are now
considering increasing the interest rate paid on deferred executive
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are exploring alternatives to stock options,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Todd, a principal with the Towers Perrin consulting firm,
said many executives may also be exercising stock options this year
to cash in the gains of recent years. That could create enormous
public relations problems next year if the market is still in a
slump, she said, when proxies show chief executives pocketing
enormous wealth for the year, despite poor performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gains may be based on seven or eight years of good
returns,'' she said. ``But that big number hits you whenever they
exercise, and the shareholders at that moment may not be feeling so
warmly towards the CEO.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
