<SLUG> BC-TELLABS-CIENA-ART-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELLABS CALLS OFF CIENA ACQUISITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tellabs Inc. called off its planned acquisition of Ciena Corp.
on Monday, after diminished financial prospects, scuttled sales and
a steep drop in the share prices of both companies made the deal
untenable.
</P>
<P>
   The already depressed shares of both companies hit new lows
after the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   When Tellabs announced in June that it would acquire Ciena in a
stock swap then valued at $7.3 billion, it was billed as the merger
of two rising stars in the fast-growing market for
telecommunications equipment. But Ciena, an early leader in a
technology for expanding the capacity of fiber optic networks, has
seen its star dim as larger, more diverse competitors like Lucent
Technologies Inc. have undercut its pricing to grab sales and gain
market share. Tellabs' growth has slowed as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really killed this deal was not the pretext of a
strategic fit, but that management and Wall Street's estimates of
Ciena's prospects were unreasonably high,'' said Greg Mesniaeff, an
analyst with Robinson Humphrey in Atlanta. ``It happened that all
the planets were misaligned.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed merger survived Ciena's loss last month of an AT&AMP;T
sale estimated at more than $100 million. But the deal unraveled
after the company last week lost a sale to Digital Teleport Inc.,
estimated to be worth about $25 million, to Pirelli S.p.A. Ciena
then had to announce that results for its third fiscal quarter,
which ended Aug. 1, would fall far below analysts' estimates and
that revenues and profit margins for the fourth quarter and next
year would also be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Decimated by the string of negative events, Ciena shares closed
Monday at $13.19, down $2.75, a fraction of their 52-week high of
$92.37. Tellabs shares, after initially trading up on the
announcement, dropped after management disclosed in a conference
call with securities analysts that its third-quarter results would
fall below estimates. Tellabs closed at $37.69, down $7.31, down 40
percent from its 52-week high of $93.12.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tea leaves were just not right for us to proceed,''
Michael Birck, Tellabs' president and chief executive, said in the
conference call. The companies had revised the deal's share
exchange rate once to reflect Ciena's diminished growth prospects
and were not likely to find a new rate again that would satisfy
shareholders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just looked at the revised Ciena prospects and factored in
the sentiment of the market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Birck held out the possibility that Tellabs and Ciena might
collaborate in the future, but he noted that strategic alliances
that did not involve an equity stake were often more difficult than
mergers. He said Tellabs still regarded the technology pioneered by
Ciena _ dense wavelength division multiplexing, or DWDM _ as
strategic, but he added that its availability now from a number of
competitors had rapidly turned DWDM into something of a commodity.
</P>
<P>
   Ciena managers said they were disappointed that the deal fell
through but would proceed as an independent entity.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, our business fundamentals are strong,'' Patrick
Nettles, Ciena's president and chief executive, said in a telephone
interview. ``We've indicated we are going to be competitive on
price by reducing the expectations for profit margins going
forward.'' Though he would not rule out other mergers, he said,
``We're getting back to the business of running our business
first.''
</P>
<P>
   But analysts predicted that Ciena would have a tough time
competing as an independent company. Although most said that the
company retained a lead in technology, its competitors could not
only undercut its pricing, but could also offer a broader and
deeper array of products and services. It made sense for Ciena to
become a part of a larger company, but that will be difficult to do
now, they said, because the expectations created by the terms of
the Tellabs deal were not realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be another acquirer, but I don't think anybody
else is going to show up until the dust settles,'' said Steven
Levy, a managing director at Lehman Brothers. ``You've got a
falling star that has not stopped falling yet.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ciena reported third-quarter earnings of $2.1 million Monday, or
2 cents a share fully diluted, down from $35.7 million, or 36 cents
a share, in the comparable period a year ago. Sales rose 6 percent,
to $129.1 million, from $121.8 million in the third quarter of the
1997 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Exclusive of one-time charges associated with the settlement of
litigation with Pirelli and merger-related costs, Ciena earned
$16.1 million, or 15 cents a share, in the quarter. Prior to the
company's warning, analysts had expected Ciena to earn 32 cents a
share, according to First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Nettles said that the shortfall reflected not only the loss of
the sale to Digital Teleport but also delays of a number of smaller
sales that are now expected to close in the fourth quarter. As the
company's number of customers has grown, management's ability to
forecast sales and the timing of sales has been stressed, he said,
adding, ``We've got to learn to manage that better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
