A4691 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     09-14 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S HARD TO CONVINCE BOSSES WHEN THEY'RE WRONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken LLoyd, Ph.D., is a specialist in organizational behavior.
Questions can be sent by electronic mail to lloydonjob(at)aol.com,
or they can be mailed to P.O. Box 260057, Encino, CA 91426. Names
will be withheld upon request.) 
BY LEN LLOYD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: When I was hired as a manager, my manager and I agreed upon
goals and what I needed to do to meet them. Now she has completely
changed her thoughts about those goals and put new ones in their
place. Her ideas make no sense for the staff, the company or
anybody. How do I convince her that she is wrong? L.W.
</P>
<P>
   A: It is very difficult to convince people that they are wrong,
and it is arguably wrong to presume that your objective. After all,
even when shown a clear, measurable, irrefutable error in their
thinking, many people still have a hard time admitting they made a
mistake. If you take something as debatable as goals and try to
convince your manager that she is mistaken in this area, you are
trying to squeeze water out of a brick.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than focusing on her being wrong, there are some other
strategies that may work better. Obviously, the first step is for
you to honestly review and assess her approach. Remember, she
thinks that you are absolutely wrong.
</P>
<P>
   If you still find that her approach is strictly in the slow
lane, then you should discuss your suggestions with her. However,
your objective is not to prove her wrong; rather, it is to jointly
develop a more effective strategy.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, present your points in a professional, factual and
nonjudgmental style. Try to use words that have a strong positive
emotional charge for her and try to include phrases with which she
can only agree. In fact, throughout the discussion, she should have
numerous opportunities to agree with you and say yes. Remember that
each little yes helps lead to the big one.
</P>
<P>
   If she still insists that you charge down the wrong path, you
may want to opt for the path that leads to her manager.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our company just completed a very expensive refurbishment of
our offices. The quality of the workmanship is high, but the
problem is with functionality. Several of us are now having
problems accessing the people we need to deal with. What should we
do? S.E.
</P>
<P>
   A: Employees often have excellent ideas regarding physical
improvements in the work environment, and making changes without
them is simply playing corporate roulette. In this case, the gamble
did not pay off.
</P>
<P>
   Employee satisfaction and productivity clearly are impacted by
working conditions. While wonderful surroundings do not
automatically improve performance, problems with working conditions
can definitely undermine it. And, more importantly, employee ideas,
input and suggestions on issues that affect their work not only
lead to better decisions and increased acceptance of change, such
participation also contributes to employee motivation.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, you and your associates should discuss the
problematic physical barriers among yourselves and try to devise
some adjustments. Ideally, your suggestions will deal less with
moving walls and more with moving people.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to meet with management to discuss your ideas.
If you meet an immovable wall, it will be a clear sign that there
are more than just physical barriers in this company.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been a manager here for several months, and although
things were chaotic when I joined, I figured that they would settle
down in time. But nothing has changed. It is always one crisis or
another, systems mean nothing and everyone is running around. I'm
ready to quit. Is there anything that can be done in this
situation? D.C.
</P>
<P>
   A: There is something to be said for a match between an
employee's style, standards and objectives, and those of the
organization in which he or she works. A good match sets the
foundation for personal satisfaction, productivity, commitment and
growth. In your situation, it sounds like the match is ready to
ignite.
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean that you are in a bad company or, conversely,
that there is anything wrong with you. It simply means that this
company is not right for you.
</P>
<P>
   You can meet with management to discuss specific aspects of your
job that need more formalization, organization and structure, but
the prognosis is not very good. The chaos probably emanates from
the top of the company, and may arguably be serving it very well.
In fact, there is a school of thought that contends that chaos in
an organization is a source of creativity, spontaneity and energy.
</P>
<P>
   However, chaos can be stifling when pushed to its limit. In your
case, it sounds like you and the company have been pushed to the
limit. Take a look at your industry and see if this chaotic
environment is typical of it, and then take a look at yourself and
what you really want in a job. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 1916EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4692 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MINORITIES15-     09-14 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MINORITIES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MINORITIES, SUSPICIOUS OF GOVERNMENT, STILL BACKING CLINTON
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ African Americans, long suspicious of the nation's
law enforcement establishment, have become President Clinton's most
ardent defenders in his bid to withstand impeachment, while among
Latinos, another key constituency, leaders say there is growing
uneasiness over investigating the personal lives of politicians.
</P>
<P>
   For many African Americans, independent counsel Kenneth Starr's
investigation of Clinton's sexual affair with Monica Lewinsky is
not unlike J. Edgar Hoover's infamous investigation of the Rev.
Martin Luther King Jr.'s sex life in the early 1960s, said David
Bositis, a senior policy analyst at the Joint Center for Political
and Economic Studies, the nation's leading African American think
tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word 'prosecutor' has an entirely different meaning in the
African American community than in the white community,'' said
Bositis. ``Hoover probably spent millions of dollars investigating
King, and Hoover didn't even have the excuse of an independent
counsel law.''
</P>
<P>
   A history of police brutality and persecution of blacks by the
nation's law enforcement system has prompted many African American
officials to rally behind the president, not in approval of his
conduct but to ensure that the president gets a fair hearing as
Congress proceeds on Starr's report, said Rep. Sheila Jackson
(D-Texas).
</P>
<P>
   ``For those of us with a history in the civil rights movement,
this is an issue of fundamental fairness,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine of the 35 members of the House Congressional Black
Caucus voted last week against public release of Starr's report to
Congress. Rep. Maxine Waters (D-Calif.), who heads the caucus,
vowed that her organization intends to be ``the fairness cop'' as
Congress decides what to do about Starr's report of possible
impeachable offenses by the president.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the fairness issue, however, many African Americans view
Clinton as their most important political ally since Lyndon
Johnson, standing up to Republican-led efforts to do away with
affirmative action, programs designed in the late 1960s to correct
past discrimination and ensure equal opportunity for minorities,
and conducting a year-long ``national conversation'' to mend racial
divisions in the country.
</P>
<P>
   A poll by the Pew Research Center for the People and the Press
just before Starr's report was released showed Clinton with an 88
percent job approval rating among African Americans, considerably
higher than the 61 percent approval rating among whites.
</P>
<P>
   The poll did not provide such a breakdown among Hispanics, but
Hispanic leaders at the grassroots level suggested Monday that
Hispanic support for Clinton mirrors the national trend, with
roughly two out of three approving of the job he is doing but
disapproving of his personal conduct.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1996 election, Clinton received 88 percent of African
Americans votes and slightly more than 70 percent of Hispanic
votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latinos are pretty much mainstream,'' said Guillermo Galindo,
incoming chairman of the Hispanic Chamber of Commerce in Dallas.
``They don't like what the president did, but they think he's been
a pretty good president overall.''
</P>
<P>
   The political fall of former HUD Secretary Henry Cisneros,
accused of lying to the FBI about a mistress, has contributed to
Hispanic concerns about investigating the personal lives of public
officials, Galindo added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether we should be looking into such
matters,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa Orenstein, a lawyer, said a meeting of Democratic and
Republican Hispanic leaders in Dallas Saturday concluded with ``the
overwhelming feeling `` that Starr's investigation had gone too far
into Clinton's personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it really our business to be peeping into windows?'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Congressional Hispanic Caucus, in contrast to the
black caucus, has not asserted any caucus role if Congress proceeds
with impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that the Hispanic leadership is stuck in a political
fix,'' said Rodolpho O. de la Garza, a professor of government at
the University of Texas in Austin and vice president of the Thomas
Rivera Policy Institute, a Latino-oriented think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic leaders are promoting Energy Secretary Bill Richardson
as a possible vice presidential running mate for the Democratic
nominee in 2000, de la Garza noted: ``And if the nominee is (Vice
President Al), Gore, (Hispanics) criticizing Clinton now could hurt
Richardson's chances.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
