<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGEMENT OFFENDS ALLISON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Bruins president/general manager Harry Sinden says he
is prepared to let Jason Allison, Anson Carter, and Kyle McLaren
sit home all season rather than meet the free agents' salary
demands. The sides are no closer to a resolution than they were
July 1 when the players became Group 2 (restricted) free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all intents and purposes, we've quit negotiating with any
of them,'' said Sinden Monday. ``We'll have three Nedveds on our
hands and we're ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Petr Nedved opted to sit out the entire 1997-98 season because
he couldn't get the salary he wanted from the Pittsburgh Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   Allison, who is in London, Ontario, said he was offended by the
Nedved reference and by the notion that the Bruins were done
negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   ``He quit negotiating?'' said Allison. ``I just want to know
when he started. I don't want to hit a home run. I just want to get
on base and they're trying to strike me out. I just want to hear
how they're justifying not trying to sign me. They haven't tried
seriously to get a deal done or even negotiated with us. That's a
bad attitude to take. It's not going to help me, it's not going to
help the team, and it's not going to help the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison said he would be willing to discuss a one-year contract
or a three-year contract. The Bruins have said they don't want to
talk about a two-year deal. Allison said the Bruins told his agent
three times that if he wants a one-year deal, he has to take his
qualifier (a 10 percent raise over last year's salary of $600,000).
Allison, who was the ninth-leading scorer in the league, said he'd
be happy to talk about an incentive-laden deal with a reasonable
raise in base salary. He feels the Bruins aren't being fair.
</P>
<P>
   Allison has seen management's quotes about being fearful he
won't be able to repeat his success of last season. If that's the
case, he'll agree to bonuses and would get big money based only on
performance. He said so far the Bruins won't talk about that.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that his salary demands for a three-year deal
are high but he believes the Bruins' offer of $750,000 a year is
outrageously low.
</P>
<P>
   If there is no break in the stalemate, Allison said he will sit
out the year. He said he would begin looking into job opportunities
in the International League and in Europe, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could've gotten everyone signed before camp,'' said
Allison. ``But they never tried. It's sad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't given up on them. How could I give up on them? We
haven't even started yet. There's so much opportunity here. We have
a good, young team. The last thing I want to do is sit out the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prospect of being in Boston is exciting. I think we could
win the Stanley Cup in three or four years. It's a great hockey
city and it's a shame. It's a shame that they punish people for
playing well. It's like you don't want to do too well or you get
punished.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' fourth free agent, Ted Donato, would like either to
be assured of an opportunity here or traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teddy doesn't seem to be able to come to grips with what he
wants to do,'' said Sinden. ``I don't know where that's going to
go. That really is in his hands right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden intimated that the NHL Players' Association might be the
reason there are vast numbers of Group 2's out of camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no evidence of this but it seems to be somewhat
organized across the league,'' said Sinden. ``I think there were at
least 100 players in this position. If it's organized in this
manner, chances are it's not going to be resolved until they change
as a group, as opposed to Boston dealing with their players or some
other team dealing with their players. If I'm right about that, it
could be a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison said that theory was patently false and that he and his
agent, Bob Gerow, will not even talk to the Players' Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NHLPA called me and I won't even go,'' said Allison. ``I
don't believe they should have anything to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   As days and weeks go by, Sinden said, it will be more difficult
for the missing players to acclimate once they're back in the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much like what we have to face with an injury,'' he said.
``If a player is out for a period of time, there's another period
of time before he can really help you on the ice. It's probably the
same with these players. They're probably doing some skating.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get them back, they'll probably have to go through a
training camp period for a couple of weeks. If you go really deep
in the season, you might as well forget it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to sign all three. It would be very easy to sign them,
just give them what they want. That's the case all across the
league and it happens way too much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
