<SLUG> BC-MA-INSURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTORNEY GENERAL WANTS DETAILS OF AUTO RATES SESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Attorney General Scott Harshbarger Monday called on
Insurance Commissioner Linda Ruthardt to fully disclose what was
discussed at a private meeting on automobile insurance rates she
held in March with key figures from the insurance industry.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Ruthardt, Harshbarger's office said the March 23
meeting could undermine the integrity of the rate-setting process,
in which Ruthardt is supposed to act much like an impartial judge
ruling on arguments made by the insurance industry, the attorney
general and the state rating bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``The occurrence of such meetings may introduce a nonpublic
aspect to the setting of rates which is not in the public interest
and/or not in accordance with the law,'' said the letter, which was
signed by Assistant Attorney General Peter Leight.
</P>
<P>
   The March meeting first came to light last week when a former
official in Ruthardt's office wrote a letter to Acting Governor
Paul Cellucci stating that Ruthardt ``is too closely aligned with
the insurers to protect the public adequately.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter was written by Stephen J. D'Amato, former director of
the state rating bureau, a unit within the Division of Insurance
that advocates on behalf of consumers. D'Amato said Ruthardt met
with Daniel Johnston, president of the Automobile Insurers Bureau,
to discuss ``settlement of the profit portion of the 1999 rate
hearing, presumably on terms favorable to the insurance industry.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato acknowledged the meeting occurred before the start of
the official hearing to set rates for next year, but he said the
meeting ``violated the spirit of the law and was inappropriate.
Consumers have a right to expect that the commissioner of insurance
and the auto insurers are not meeting behind closed doors to
`simplify' the profit-rate issues of an upcoming hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Klein, a spokesman for the Division of Insurance, said
Johnston sought the meeting with Ruthardt to simplify the process
of setting rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to see if the commissioner would object,'' Klein
said. He said Ruthardt told the insurance industry officials that
she had no problem with trying to simplify the rate-setting
process, but that the other parties in the process would have to
agree.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said no profit numbers were discussed at the meeting and
added that D'Amato has ``turned it into something sinister and it
really isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato said Monday that a legal adviser to Johnston told him
that resolution of the profit portion of the case, including
specific numbers, were discussed at the meeting. He said the profit
portion of the case is likely to be a key element in next year's
rates. The industry is seeking a 15 percent rate hike for next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston did not return phone calls Monday and Klein was
interviewed prior to the release of the letter from Harshbarger's
office.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato also said in his letter to Cellucci that Ruthardt
threatened one of his staff members for being ``too proconsumer.''
D'Amato did not mention the name of the staff member, but one
source said it was Burt Feinberg, a mathematical analyst who two
years ago uncovered a $176 million mistake in the way rates had
been calculated for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Klein said Feinberg did not want to talk to the press, but he
quoted him as saying, ``He doesn't think anyone tried to have him
fired at any point.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci has largely ignored the many serious charges raised in
the letter from D'Amato, with a spokeswoman calling it
``self-promotional'' when its existence was first reported by The
Globe last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
