<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4708 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-COX15     09-14 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-COX15 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IN NEW YORK, CLINTON STRESSES LEADERSHIP OF WORLD AND HIS PARTY
 &HT;    560&AMP;add.
 &HT;    Eds: Please watch wires for insert after 10 p.m. EDT with
Clinton addressing 'Lion King' gala. But if Clinton makes major
news with these remarks, Deans will file a new top to story.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ President Clinton shed the cloak of contrition and
donned the mantle of leadership Monday, using the bully pulpit to
try to talk interest rates downward and proving to Democrats that
he remains their most effective money-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when Clinton raised about $4 million for Democrats in a
series of exclusive political events, including a private evening
performance of the Broadway musical ``The Lion King,'' major U.S.
allies lined up behind his call to take steps to stimulate the
ailing global economy.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the Council on Foreign Relations, an influential
New York policy group, Clinton called for the Group of Seven
industrialized democracies to develop a coordinated plan to get
world markets moving again.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal was quickly endorsed in a statement by the deputy
finance chiefs of the group's other member nations _ Canada,
Britain, France, Italy, Germany and Japan _ who met this weekend in
London on the global financial troubles.
</P>
<P>
   This international support ``is a big deal,'' Clinton later told
60 wealthy Democratic supporters who had shelled out $50,000 per
couple to nibble on a crabmeat salad lunch and listen to the
president. ''This is what politics in America ought to be about.''
</P>
<P>
   Warning that the world economy was facing its toughest challenge
since World War II, Clinton said the risks of a deepening global
downturn now outweigh those of inflation _ a carefully crafted
endorsement of interest rate cuts.
</P>
<P>
   After a generation of tailoring interest rates to combat
inflation, ''clearly the balance of risk has now shifted,'' Clinton
told the Council on Foreign Relations. ''The industrial world's
chief priority today plainly is to spur growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House does not control interest rates, which are the
domain of market forces and the Federal Reserve Board, an
independent agency with a mandate to act strictly on economic, not
political, forces. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin stressed that
Clinton was not explicitly calling for interest rate reductions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, coming on the heels of Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan's
recent suggestions that interest rates might be headed downward,
the president's remarks were plainly meant to support that
approach.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not directly refer to his legal and political
troubles over the Monica Lewinsky scandal in his remarks at the
luncheon or a later dinner where 400 people paid $10,000 a plate
for a tuna and pasta buffet. But he did predict that Democrats are
''going to do just fine'' in midterm elections Nov. 3 ''if we talk
about these big things and we remember, these elections are never
about us, they're always about the people out on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton, ''Our problem is not adversity, we will rise in
adversity. Our problem is complacency.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing to dampen expectations, however, Clinton stressed that
the party of second-term presidents has lost seats in Congress in
every midterm election since the Civil War. Still, he added, ''I
think we're going to beat history.''
</P>
<P>
   Trumpeting one of the signal successes of his administration,
Clinton said that he was looking forward to Oct. 1, which will
conclude the first fiscal year since 1969 that the federal budget
hasn't run a deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't felt like this,'' Clinton said, ''since the week
before Chelsea was born.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's first day of public appearances outside the
Washington area since Friday's public release of Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr's report to Congress on the Lewinsky scandal,
Democratic leaders worked hard to help Clinton change the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the fund-raising luncheon, Democrats scrupulously
avoided mentioning the matter and enthusiastically praised
Clinton's record on the economy and his efforts to advance the
party's agenda in areas ranging from Social Security and health
care reform to education, the environment and crime.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are talking with the American people about the issues that
they care about,'' said House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo..
Gephardt has been sharply critical of Clinton in the Lewinsky
matter, but predicted Monday that his fellow Democrats would regain
control of the House from Republicans in the coming elections. ''In
November,'' Gephardt said, ''we will win the House back.''
</P>
<P>
   However, both Gephardt and Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle,
D-S.D., issued statement in Washington urging Clinton to tell his
lawyers to stop arguing that his misstatements under oath to
investigators did not legally amount to perjury.
</P>
<P>
   ``The considered judgment of the American people is not going to
rise or fall on the fine distinctions of a legal argument, but on
straight talk and the truth,'' said Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly agree with those who have grown impatient with
hairsplitting over legal technicalities,'' said Daschle.
</P>
<P>
   But party officials in New York said that polls were wrong in
suggesting that the Lewinsky scandal had so disgusted Democrats
that many would stay home on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our turnout will be there on November 3 to fight for values
and principles and priorities,'' Steve Grossman, national chairman
of the Democratic National Committee predicted at the luncheon,
held at a private penthouse residence. ''We will be able to bring
this victory home.''
</P>
<P>
   White House aides were heartened by the turnout at the
fund-raisers, saying it signaled the party's continuing support for
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are a lot of strong supporters of the Democratic Party
who believe very much in what the president and Democrats are
trying to accomplish for the country,'' said White House spokesman
Barry Toiv. ''Their support enables candidates to communicate their
message to the American people. The president certainly is going to
continue his efforts on behalf of the party, and we appreciate the
support.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
