</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MSKUBE-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: The sadness lies in what `might have been'
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I last saw him at a basketball game with Bill and Hillary
Clinton. Everyone was happy, enjoying life. We weren't at the game
ourselves. We were somewhere in Kentucky, en route to Illinois, and
had bivouacked at a motel next to a Mexican restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``That looks like Barlow!'' my wife suddenly said.
</P>
<P>
   I looked up from my enchiladas and frijoles at the television
mounted overhead. The camera had cut away from play on the court,
where Arkansas was playing Arizona, and there he was on national
TV, out of his seat along with the president of the United States,
the two of them cheering a Razorback run in the Final Four in
Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   We knew they were friends from way back, the one from Hope, the
other from Paragould. He didn't have the kind of spare cash it took
to be a Friend of Bill, but he was a believer in Bill. Many were.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both came from small towns in Arkansas,'' Barlow Herget was
saying Friday afternoon as the Internet was fanning the Starr
report to the prurient everywhere. ``We were of the generation that
fought against Orval Faubus. I'm 56 and Clinton was coming up just
behind me. Mac McLarty (former White House chief of staff) and
David Watkins (who got caught up in the inquiry into the affairs of
the White House travel office) were fraternity brothers of mine.''
</P>
<P>
   The years passed and Barlow Herget, a journalist turned local
politician in Raleigh, N.C., became one of those Arkansans whose
belief in Bill Clinton was personal as much as political. Clinton's
promise was messianic, a deliverance from the South's backward,
segregationist past. He was someone to be proud of, someone who,
you were certain, would not only lift his little state but the
South with it.
</P>
<P>
   No one speaks of him anymore with great pride, except his wife.
Those who once did struggle to hold on to what remains of the pride
they had. He was never exactly an altar boy _ that was part of his
charm. Now, the unseemliness of what has engulfed the president is
the kind of thing that shatters personal and political faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the classic American tragedy _ a man of great promise and
talent brought low by the oldest sin in the Bible,'' Herget said.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the time he picked candidate Clinton up at
Raleigh-Durham International Airport. It was 1992. ``I drove out in
my 1988 Ford station wagon. At the last minute I had to get it
cleaned _ I thought, `I can't pick him up in a car looking like
that. This could be the future president of the United States.'''
</P>
<P>
   He met Clinton again the next time he flew into Raleigh-Durham,
this time on Air Force One, and they rode together in the
presidential limousine. He and his wife, Millie, attended Clinton's
inaugural ball in 1993 and again in 1997. In the fall of 1993,
Herget lost a mayoral election to a Jesse Helms protege, and that
night Clinton called him at home to offer consolation. ``We
commiserated, and he told me not to lose heart,'' Herget says.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't completely. But he's lost something he doesn't expect
to recover. At 56, you understand that these things happen. Friends
divorce when you had no clue of trouble; families disintegrate;
good kids turn out bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm old enough, I've been around long enough to know that
everybody's got human failings,'' he said. But still ...
</P>
<P>
   He was hardly the only person who believed, once, that Bill
Clinton's star could only rise, higher and higher. It was like
someone telling you to keep an eye on a young baseball prospect who
was the real thing, the next Joe DiMaggio. Now, in retrospect, you
recall Paul Simon's lyric as lamentation: ``Where have you gone,
Joe DiMaggio, a nation turns its lonely eyes to you.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the next DiMaggio; he wasn't even very good. But he
could have been.
</P>
<P>
   ```Disappointed' is not strong enough a word,'' Herget said.
``I've wrestled with this. It's as if your younger brother came
home from college and did that which he ought not have done. I feel
like he has betrayed his own promise.''
</P>
<P>
   It goes without saying that he has betrayed others as well,
beginning with his wife and daughter. But for many who've known him
most of their lives, who knew long before others that he could be
reckless in his personal habits, his undoing has a particular
sadness. The Greek dramatists understood tragedy in this way, the
fatal flaw, there from the start, that brings a man down.
Shakespeare understood it.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is that tragedy, in their hands, was never as
tawdry as this. The fallen hero retains something of his nobility,
even in ruin. In Clinton's case, friends and believers alike can
only contemplate a greatness that never was _ or, at best, might
have been. But it is no less painful for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's distasteful, it's embarrassing, and nobody likes
being lied to,'' Herget said in a heavy voice. ``But I honestly
appreciate so much that this kid's done. I'm just sorry about what
he's done to himself.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
