<HEADLINE>
PRIMARIES EXPECTED TO DRAW 1 MILLION VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After well over a year of debating the issues and
taking the measure of the candidates, an estimated 1 million
Massachusetts voters are expected to go to the polls Tuesday in
Republican and Democratic primaries that will determine the general
election candidates in November for governor and a host of other
statewide races.
</P>
<P>
   A hotly-contested Republican primary pitting Acting Governor
Paul Cellucci against Treasurer Joseph D. Malone will finally reach
its judgment day, while three Democratic contenders _ former
congressman Brian Donnelly, Attorney General Scott Harshbarger and
former state senator Patricia McGovern _ will vie for the right to
carry the Democratic banner in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most interesting races on the ballot are the attorney
general's race, in which State Senator Lois G. Pines of Newton and
Middlesex District Attorney Thomas F.Reilly have waged the slugfest
of the political season, and in the 8th Congressional District,
where 10 Democrats are battling to succeed retiring US
Representative Joseph P. Kennedy 2d.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State William M. Galvin estimated turnout at about
30 percent - higher then the turnout in the barely contested
primaries of 1994, but well below the voter participation in 1990,
the last gubernatorial election without an incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're projecting 300,00 voters in the (Republican) primary,
and about 700,000 on the Democratic side,'' Galvin said Monday. He
said absentee ballots, a prime indicator of turnout, indicated that
those estimates might be a tad inflated for the Democratic side.
``It's active where there are local contests and in the Eighth
District, and quiet elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, with fewer than 36 hours left before the polls close,
candidates crisscrossed the state thanking volunteers, appearing on
radio talk shows and preparing for massive rallies in Dorchester
and West Roxbury that traditionally mark a symbolic closing of the
fall political madness in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Under gray skies at Downtown Crossing, Democratic gubernatorial
candidate Patricia McGovern attempted to way-lay voters as they
hurried out to lunch Monday. The crowd was sparse, but the media
presence thick, as McGovern hammed it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the Sammy Sosa of Massachusetts politics,'' she said,
referring to the Chicago Cubs slugger who has been chasing Mark
McGwire for baseball's home run title. ``I've always been behind
the other guy, but I hope I can catch him and pass him.''
</P>
<P>
   McGovern said she has spent the final days of the campaign
travelling the state and receiving warm and supportive words from
the voters. On Election Day, she said, ``I'm going to vote and then
I'm going to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger began the day touring a Quincy housing development
with US Representative William Delahunt, who was an early
supporter. He later toured Uphams Corner in Dorchester with state
Representative Charlotte Golar Richie,and visited businesses and an
elderly housing development in Jamaica Plain before heading for the
rally in Adams Village in Dorchester.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're going into the hard-core homestretch of getting
voters to the polls,'' said Harshbarger spokesman Edward Cafasso.
``It's about executing the last two days of the game plan and
getting ready for the general election.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci campaigned in the North End in the morning and greeted
voters at the Back Bay MBTA station. He was planning a tour of four
Boston taverns last night squeezed around appearances at various
rallies.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he was concerned that the attention on President
Clinton's woes in Washington could drive down turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big story down in Washington pushed the campaign here off
the front page,'' he noted. ``That kind of froze the race over the
weekend. But we've been focusing on getting out our vote. It
doesn't have much to do with what's on the front page or what's on
the news.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he was going into the final relaxed and confident.
He spent the last weekend of the campaign greeting voters at Boston
College and New England Patriots and was making the rounds of radio
and television shows Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on the phone talking to a lot of our key volunteers
and they're energized and positive and I'm looking for a good day
(Tuesday),'' Malone said. ``I think those Reagan republicans will
turn out and vote for me and carry the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Galvin, the state's top election official, reminded voters that
if they have pledged a party affiliation they can vote only in
their party's primary. Unenrolled voters can take a take a ballot
for either party but can only cast votes for either Democratic or
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Donnelly, the former ambassador, said he believed his
insurgent campaign had helped elevate the dialogue among the
Democratic candidates. Donnelly said he used the final debate
between the Democratic candidates last week in Springfield to put
quality of life and urban issues on the agenda this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the rank and file's decision,'' Donnelly said. ``They'll
make it, I'll live with it. I think my presence helped set the tone
of the debate and the substance of the debate. If you look back,
before I entered all anyone was talking about was who could give
the biggest tax cut. In Springfield, we were talking about
libraries, schools, and cities.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe staff writer Jill Zuckman contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
