</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Newsmagazines focus on Starr report
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As expected, all three newsmagazines this week are Starr-struck.
Newsweek ($2.95) devoted 29 pages to excerpts from the special
prosecutor's report and a six-page rebuttal from President
Clinton's lawyers. U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($2.95) had 10 pages of
excerpts and no rebuttal and Time ($2.95), apparently counting on
its Time.com Web site to handle serious browsers, included only
five pages of excerpts and a one-page rebuttal. All the pundits are
speculating about Clinton's fate, but former presidential aide
George Stephanopoulos describes the most likely scenario: ``Clinton
won't willingly go home _ and Hillary, who worked on the Watergate
impeachment, is even more reluctant to have her husband join Nixon
in the ranks of the resigned,'' he writes. ``My guess is that
Clinton will convince 34 senators that concealing an adulterous
affair doesn't merit removal from office.'' Meanwhile, Time's
Margaret Carlson says the first lady is coping with the scandal by
doing vigorous exercise workouts on state-of-the-art equipment.
</P>
<P>
   BEING MIKE: Forget about the pretentious article by an anonymous
contributor about ``My First Gulfstream.'' The must-read article in
October's Vanity Fair ($3.95) is the excerpt from Michael Jordan's
autobiography, ``For the Love of the Game: My Story.'' As the
superstar ponders his future beyond basketball, he reflects on the
forces that allowed him to succeed. Several times, Jordan recalls,
he had close brushes with death. He nearly suffocated as a baby,
barely escaped electrocution as a 2-year-old and almost drowned as
a college student. After that, Jordan says, ``How can you say there
isn't a plan for all of us?'' So what about retirement? When it
happens, he says, ``I am not going to mind being out of the
spotlight.'' Also in this issue, the magazine ranks the 50 most
powerful masters of the information age. The Top 5 are Bill Gates ,
Rupert Murdoch, Michael Eisner, Sumner Redstone and Ted Turner.
</P>
<P>
   A MATTER OF STYLE: With its focus on fashion and its
accompanying clothing and fragrance ads, this week's New Yorker
($3) looks more like Vanity Fair than it did when Tina Brown was
editor. But there is substance behind the style. In ``Letter From
Moscow,'' Masha Lipman questions the launching of the Russian
edition of Vogue at a time when the ruble is falling faster than
hemlines. Red is the ``in'' color for fashion, Lipman writes, and
possibly for politics as well. Other fashion coverage includes John
Updike on the men and mores of Coco Chanel and a profile of
designer Charles James, who numbered the Whitneys, Hearst and
Paleys among his clients. Elsewhere in the issue, North Carolina
native Tony Earley writes eloquently _ and sadly _ about the
disappearing dialect of the Appalachians, a form of speech that he
confesses seems ``quare'' to flatlanders.
</P>
<P>
   JANET REBOUNDS: Michael Jackson is not the only one in the
family with problems. In a Rolling Stone ($3) cover story, Janet
Jackson talks about her latest release, ``Velvet Rope,'' her
current tour, and the year of depression and self-doubt after her
last album flopped.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK READS: Stone Mountain Mayor Chuck Burris is in some
glamorous company in the October issue of Ebony ($2.50). The cover
story spotlights some of Hollywood's ``hottest new faces,''
including Lisa Nicole Carson of ``Ally McBeal.'' Featured inside in
a flattering profile, the first black mayor of the former Klan
stronghold in Georgia talks about how times have changed since he
found himself in Stone Mountain park the day of a Klan rally and
was warned to leave. Also of note: The magazine names Atlanta chief
of police Beverly Harvard as one of the ``Top Black Cops'' in the
nation. ...The October issue of Essence ($2.50) lists Oprah
Winfrey, Camille Cosby and Black Entertainment Television executive
Sheila Crump as three of the 20 wealthiest black women.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
