</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New album shows range of Hootie
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the release today of ``Musical Chairs,'' Hootie &AMP; the
Blowfish show off the band's flexibility, with tunes ranging from
country (``Desert Mountain Showdown'') to R&AMP;B (``What's Going on
Here'') and '80s rock (``Wishing''). Frontman Darius Rucker
explains the diversity by saying that tunes for previus releases
``would end up being a rock 'n' roll song, even if it was written
as a country song. With this record, we just really wanted the
songs to remain intact.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Paul Anka, ``A Body of Work'' (Epic). Thanks to high-tech
engineering, '60s star duets with Frank Sinatra, Patti LaBelle,
Tevin Campbell, Celine Dion, others.
</P>
<P>
   -- Digital Underground, ``Who Got the Gravy?'' (Jake Records).
Bay Area crew gets help from Big Punisher, KRS-One and Biz Markie.
</P>
<P>
   -- Flipmode Squad, ``The Imperial'' (Elektra). Busta Rhymes'
Squad makes collective debut.
</P>
<P>
   -- Vern Gosdin, ``The Voice'' (BTM Records). All-new material
from country stylist.
</P>
<P>
   -- Patti LaBelle, ``Live _ One Night Only'' (MCA). Mariah Carey,
Gerald &AMP; Eddie Levert guest on album from PBS special earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   -- Local H, ``Pack Up the Cats'' (Island). Duo chronicles
youth's life as little fish in big pond.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Saturday Night: A Stephen Sondheim World Premiere'' ((RCA
Victor). Music from updated piece features London cast.
</P>
<P>
   -- The Tannahill Weavers, ``Epona'' (Green Linnet). Scottish
band will spotlight new release Wednesday night in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   -- Doc &AMP; Merle Watson, ``Home Sweet Home'' (Sugar Hill). Doc
turns loose tapes recorded at home in Deep Gap, N.C., in 1967 with
son, who died in 1985 tractor accident.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
