</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-GODOT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones, Griffin team for `Godot'
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The late Samuel Beckett wanted to see black actors
play his most famous characters: Vladimir and Estragon, the
ever-waiting, ever-befuddled clowns marooned in the bare-stage
universe of 1953's ``Waiting for Godot.''
</P>
<P>
   Joy Zinoman, founding artistic director of Studio Theatre,
didn't know this when she asked Thomas W. Jones and Donald Griffin,
Atlanta-based actors who've enjoyed stage successes in her city, to
play the classic roles. Nor did those stalwarts of Atlanta's
Jomandi Productions ever imagine they'd be invited to star in the
most mystifying but influential play of the postwar era, which
opened last week (to a rave in The Washington Post) and runs
through Oct. 4. Zinoman thought of Jones and Griffin because of
``their friendship, which is so alive. There's a freedom that
carries into their performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The play scared me to death at first,'' continues the 50ish
Zinoman, ``until I began to approach it not as a cosmic work about
salvation, but a story in which redemption and meaning are found in
the friendship of two valiant vagrants. It's not a political
statement about race.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Zinoman tried to cast a white woman as the slavelike
Lucky, a lesser role, and Beckett's estate turned her down
(``They're monsters _ controlling to the nth degree,'' she adds
hotly). But it was from the estate that Zinoman learned that
Beckett, always obsessive about his plays, once expressed his
desire to see a black Didi and Gogo (as the characters call
themselves). The only such production to date had been in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 42, is co-artistic director of Jomandi Productions and
author of two hits that played the Studio (``Bessie's Blues,''
``Birth of the Boom''). Griffin, 40, is an actor with Jomandi and
Alliance Theatre (``The Amen Corner''), an outstanding clown in the
tradition of two well-known Estragons: Bert Lahr and Robin
Williams. Friends for 20 years, Jones and Griffin spoke after a
rehearsal at a restaurant near the Studio.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did this production concept strike you?
</P>
<P>
   Jones: I was stunned. It hit me from left field.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin: I was surprised. Joy told me that when she saw me in
``Seven Guitars'' wearing a bowler (the standard ``Godot''
headware) it started her wheels turning.
</P>
<P>
   Jones: Oh, she came to you first?
</P>
<P>
   Griffin: Right. (Pause. Jones pretends to be put out; Griffin
guffaws).
</P>
<P>
   Griffin: I read this play in college and my reaction was,
``Ohhhhhhhh-kay! Whatever. It ain't `Purlie.''' I mean, I know all
about the play's significance. ... What exactly the brother is
saying, I couldn't tell you.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a special resonance when the characters are black?
</P>
<P>
   Jones: Every generation of black folks has been told that
something big was coming. I think that's why we bought so heavily
into the Christian ethic. Someone was coming to deliver us. First
we moved to the north but nothing got getter. Then it was
education: We got educated but nothing really changed. So waiting
became our historical motif, like, ``Where's my 40 acres and a
mule?'' When we accept that nobody's coming, we take our destiny
into our hands.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does this ``Godot'' happen in a black world?
</P>
<P>
   Jones: Oh yeah! Joy said to explore it all.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin: It's like vaudeville _ we take it right back to the old
days of black vaudeville.
</P>
<P>
   Jones: There are certain moments with different voices. For
instance, I start out doing Martin Luther King and end up as Jesse
Jackson. (He performs a few lines from the play as if he were
Jackson on a public affairs program.) We push some boundaries. Old
Sam just might climb out of the grave and come after us!
</P>
<P>
   Griffin: Nah, he can't mess with us now.
</P>
<P>
   Jones: I don't know, he might say, ``I wanted to see it black,
but not this bad!'' (They laugh).
</P>
<P>
   Q: The Studio is one of the few small theaters in America that's
thriving (5,000 subscribers) with a balanced racial mix in its
audience. Do you think black audiences will come and connect with
this production?
</P>
<P>
   Jones: I wish I knew. Connecting with this play shouldn't be a
big leap for anyone, though. It has tons of humor. It deals with
issues of power and class that resonate with Jews, resonate with
women, resonate with the Irish. This isn't a production about race
but man's inhumanity to man.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will you bring this production back to Jomandi in Atlanta?
</P>
<P>
   Jones: Sure, if it works _ why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``Waiting for Godot''
</P>
<P>
   Through Oct. 4. $19.50-$36.50. Studio Theatre, Washington.
</P>
<P>
   202-332-3300.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
