<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Filmamker tries to trace his roots
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A hit at film festivals around the country (including Sundance
where it won the Freedom of Expression Award), Macky Alston's
``Family Name'' (PBS-check local listings) is a personal
exploration of family matters with a universal significance.
</P>
<P>
   Alston, a white North Carolinian, grew up wondering why some of
the African-American kids at his school had the same last name as
he did. As an adult, he decided to find out. For a start, he
attended separate but equal family reunions. He discovered that,
not only did neither family know about the other family's reunion
but that both families weren't especially eager to have their
mutual history examined. Undeterred, the now New York-based
filmmaker embarked on a geneological quest. In doing so, he used
the Alston history of family secrets as a mirror for his own
once-closeted homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family Name'' is of particular interest to Southerners (Alston
has kin in Atlanta). Without finger-pointing or rancor, it explores
the peculiar dual legacy fostered by de facto segregation. Part
family album, part detective story, it's a thought-provoking,
touching and ultimately uplifting film.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   (``Family Name'' has an odd Atlanta footnote. Alston, who was
born in Durham, N.C., always knew he had family in Atlanta. So
while researching his film he came here to investigate the Alston
House, which was once owned by his family. When he showed up to
talk to the current residents, he was greeted by a man who agreed
to let the filmmaker return the next day with his camera and crew.
When Alston showed up, however, the house was empty. It turned out
that the man was not the owner and when the director found the real
owner, he learned that the imposter had cleaned the house out and
left without a trace).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
