<SLUG> BC-RATINGS-CLINTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet, Cable, and networks see ratings rise for Starr's
report
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris and Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report may have been bad
news for President Clinton, but it's been good _ if not great news
_ for the cable TV networks and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours after the release of Kenneth Starr's report Friday,
the Nielsen ratings for the four major cable news networks
increased substantially as news junkies and casual viewers tuned
in. No viewership records were set, though.
</P>
<P>
   Computer users logged on to the Internet in what could amount to
be record-breaking numbers to read the report.
</P>
<P>
   On cable TV, CNN saw the greatest uptick in viewers, nearly
doubling its average ratings for a 24-hour period.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based network drew a 1.4 average rating for the day,
or about 1 million households, said network spokesman Howard
Polskin. The network typically averages a 0.8 rating, or roughly
552,000 households for that time period, he said.
</P>
<P>
   CNN viewership spiked to a 3 rating at 5 p.m., when the
president's lawyers held a news conference to dispute the
allegations in Starr's report, Polskin said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox News also doubled its ratings average for the day after the
report was released, jumping to a 0.4 rating or 131,000 housholds.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC got a 0.8 average rating or about 354,000 households,
compared with its latest weekday average of 0.3 rating or 139,000
viewers. The network's highest rating was a 1.7, or about 730,000
viewers for ``White House in Crisis: The Starr Report,'' an
hourlong special at 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Its sister network, CNBC, which programs financial news in the
morning and political talk shows at night, saw only a slight
increase in viewership Friday, a spokesman said. Its biggest
performer, ``Geraldo Riviera Live,'' got a 1.5 rating, which means
it was seen in about 1,038,000 homes said spokesman John Brine.
</P>
<P>
   Ratings for the broadcast networks were not immediately
available.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, Atlanta-based Web measurement firm Relevant
Knowledge reported that Friday's posting of the Starr report
ignited ``a surfing frenzy'' of major proportions. The company
estimates that 24.7 million ``unique visitors'' logged on, Friday
and over the weekend, presumably to read the report.
</P>
<P>
   The sites that published the report and the rebuttal saw their
traffic increase nearly tenfold. Regional and national news sites
got the most traffic, with a 95 percent increase in traffic and 7
million unique visitors combined.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy traffic was not not good news for Clinton: More than
10 times more users visited sites posting the report than the
president's rebuttal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
