<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODAY'S LESSON: THE PRESIDENT'S CONDUCT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: the complete version is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET) 
(See also: CLINTON-ECON, CLINTON-REPORT-SCENE, CLINTON-POLICY,
CLINTON-PERJURY, CLINTON-CONGRESS, CLINTON-PASTORS, NY-CLINTON,) 
(JT) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the Starr report very much on the minds and lips
of her seniors at the Bronx High School of Science Monday morning,
Marilyn Reinhardt opened her fourth-period literature class by
scribbling three one-word questions on the blackboard: ``Psycho?
Devil? Victim?''
</P>
<P>
   She then asked her students whether President Clinton's behavior
with Monica Lewinsky, as well as his apparent attempts to cover it
up, was most like that of the mentally unstable Reverend Dimsdale
of ``The Scarlet Letter,'' the unrepentant killer Mersault of
Albert Camus' ``The Stranger'' or Jay Gatsby, whom she
characterized as a victim of the prevailing ethos of the Roaring
Twenties, which she defined as ``get rich quick by any means, but
then no one comes to your funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   From the back of the room, one 17-year-old girl raised her hand.
``I don't think he's any of the three,'' she said. ``He's just a
man. All men cheat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's biological destiny,'' Ms. Reinhardt replied, `` `Stand
by Your Man,' as Tammy Wynette said in that song.''
</P>
<P>
   If this had been any other September, Ms. Reinhardt would have
spent the third day of the school year Monday introducing her
students to Wordsworth, Keats and Jane Austen. But after reading
the report by the Whitewater independent counsel, Kenneth Starr,
over the weekend, she _ like so many other teachers across the
country _ concluded that her original lesson plan just could not
compete.
</P>
<P>
   And so, imploring their classes to cast aside any nervous
snickers, teachers at middle schools, high schools _ and even in
the older grades of some elementary schools, based on visits to
more than a dozen schools throughout the metropolitan New York
region Monday _ wove the scandal engulfing the president into their
lesson plans, often as a way to get their students to think about
larger issues like morality or impeachment that might otherwise
have put them to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers' only dilemma, it seemed, was not whether to
discuss Clinton's troubles, but in how much detail. And even then
there was surprising latitude.
</P>
<P>
   In Kitty Rooney's 12th-grade class at Bishop Loughlin Memorial
High School in Brooklyn, the words ``sex'' and ``sexual
intercourse'' flew around the room, with little giggling. Never
mind that the subject was government and the setting was a Catholic
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the Constitution class can be formulaic and dry,'' Ms.
Rooney said afterward, ``but now the students are very interested.
It's living history.''
</P>
<P>
   As the students struggled to form opinions, many found
themselves as conflicted as their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Bascio, a social studies teacher at Public School 111 in
midtown Manhattan, asked her seventh graders to write a paragraph
about whether the president should be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, because he shouldn't of cheated on his wife,'' one girl
wrote. ``No, because it is his personal business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some,'' the student concluded, ``think he should be punished
in a different way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
