<SLUG> BC-STOCKS-RISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS RISE AFTER CLINTON NEWS DEEMED NOT CRITICAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It may take Congress months to decide President
Clinton's fate, but not the financial markets; they have decided
he's staying.
</P>
<P>
   The stock market climbed Monday, with the Dow Jones industrial
average rising almost 150 points, as investors concluded that the
president's troubles, although serious, are not enough to produce a
full-blown political upheaval. Coming atop a 180-point gain last
Friday in the wake of Independent Counsel Kenneth W. Starr's report
about Clinton's affair with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky, the latest market performance signals that investors
think Clinton can ride out the storm, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The markets are saying `This is not a crisis,' '' according to
Richard Schmaltz, investment director with J&AMP;W Seligman in New
York. ``They may be disgusted with the guy, but they are figuring
he will finish his term,'' Schmaltz said.
</P>
<P>
   The president played to the markets Monday in a New York speech
in which he warned that the current global crisis is ``the biggest
financial challenge facing the world in a half century'' and called
on the major economies to adopt a coordinated strategy to boost
growth, a move that investors would dearly like to see.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were also comforted by word out of a London meeting of
finance ministers and central bank leaders of the Group of Seven
industrial nations Monday that a coordinated interest rate
reduction might be in the works. Such a move would help nations
like Russia and Brazil by spurring growth and therefore world
consumption of their products.
</P>
<P>
   In concluding that Clinton will likely remain in office, the
markets tracked weekend poll results that show most Americans
believe that, whatever his personal failings, the president is
still doing a good job in office and should be censured rather than
impeached.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-stock Dow rose 149.85 points, or 1.9 percent, to 7945.35.
That brings its two-day gain to 330 points. The broader Standard &AMP;
Poor 500 Index climbed 20.66 points, or 2.1 percent to 1029.72,
while the technology-laden Nasdaq Composite Index rose 24.05
points, or 1.5 percent, to 1665.75.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were not alone in rising in value Monday; the dollar also
rose, regaining more than half of the two percent it lost last week
against the Japanese yen and squeezing out small gains as well
against the German mark. Analysts traced most of the gain to
currency traders' conclusion that the Starr report contains no new
surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a relief bounce as much as anything else,'' said David
Solin, a partner with Foreign Exchange Analytics in Essex, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Relief could be short-lived if, as many expect, companies in
growing numbers warn of profit disappointments on the way. The
financial world is entering the dreaded ``pre-announcement''
period, the weeks leading up to the end of a fiscal quarter when
firms try to get ahead of bad news by disclosing they will not do
as well as had been expected.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that such disclosures could prove a particular
problem this month because the global crisis has cut overseas sales
and made it hard to raise prices at home, and because any profit
figures will be compared with year-ago numbers, which were
spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in for a long confessional period not only about the
quarter, but also the year as a whole,'' said Ned Riley, chief
investment officer for BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   Investment professionals cautioned Monday that the conclusion by
financial markets that Clinton will be able to hang onto the
presidency does not mean he is out of the woods. ``Even if he
stays, he's going to be a lame duck,'' said Scott Black of
Boston-based Delphi Management, a former Clinton supporter.
``Basically you're going to have a bigger Republican majority in
Congress and two years of gridlock.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All the market is saying is it doesn't like catastrophic
change,'' said Schmaltz. ``That doesn't mean it likes the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, although Clinton Monday hit most of the notes investors
wanted to hear about US readiness to tackle the global financial
crisis, most analysts said that there is little he can do to help
in his politically weakened state.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to the New York-based Council on Foreign
Relations, the president said ``the leading economic nations must
act together to spur global growth.'' He warned that the principal
problem that policymakers must tackle has changed from inflation to
economic weakness. ``The balance of risks has now shifted with a
full quarter of the world's populations now living in countries
with negative economic growth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that he had asked Treasury Secretary Robert E.
Rubin and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan to convene a
meeting of the G-7 nations to cope with the crisis within 30 days,
a timetable that some observers wryly noted happens to coincide
with an already scheduled session of the International Monetary
Fund and World Bank next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton's call for a meeting makes it a little more likely it
will happen quickly,'' said Gary C. Hufbauer, the just-departed
research director for the Council on Foreign Relations where
Clinton spoke. But ``there is not a lot more he can do,'' Hufbauer
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
