A4755 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMMER-COX     09-14 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMMER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Openly gay candidates in numerous primaries
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democratic voters in Washington state and
Massachusetts today have the chance to add to the largest line-up
ever of openly gay candidates for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Grethe Cammermeyer, a retired Army colonel, and Susan Tracy, a
former state legislator, are seeking the Democratic congressional
nomination in districts north of Seattle and in the Boston area,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   If they win, seven gay and lesbian candidates, including two
congressional incumbents, will be on the ballot in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving toward a place where sexual orientation won't
play a part,'' said Winnie Stachelberg, political director of the
Human Rights Campaign Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Charles Cook has said the November election
``is a breakthrough election'' because so many of the gay
candidates are running competitive races.
</P>
<P>
   The incumbents are Republican Jim Kolbe of Arizona and Democrat
Barney Frank of Massachusetts. The other candidates who have won
party primaries are Wisconsin state Rep. Tammy Baldwin; San Diego
City Council member Christine Kehoe and Paul Barby, trying for the
second time to capture a western Oklahoma seat.
</P>
<P>
   If any of these candidates win, it would mark the first time an
openly gay American won election to Congress. Kolbe and Frank
revealed their homosexuality only after they had been in Congress
for some time.
</P>
<P>
   None of the contests is expected to be easy. Baldwin is running
in a Madison-area district that is represented by Rep. Scott Klug,
a Republican who is retiring. She will face Josephine Musser, a
former Wisconsin insurance commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Musser narrowly defeated Ron Greer, a Christian fundamentalist
and former firefighter, who made his opposition to homosexuality a
major part of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Kehoe is trying to unseat Rep. Brian Bilbray, a moderate
Republican whom national analysts say has been helped by a strong
pro-incumbent mood nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Barby is up against Rep. Frank Lucas (R-Okla.), who took 64
percent of the vote two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Democratic primary in Massachusetts will be
the favorite to win in November because the district is staunchly
Democratic. It is currently held by Rep. Joseph Kennedy, who is
retiring.
</P>
<P>
   But Tracy is one of 10 Democrats in the race, several with
personal fortunes to draw on and with strong records on gay issues.
</P>
<P>
   Cammermeyer's campaign also faces an uphill road, but it may be
the most intriguing because of her life story. She is campaigning
as a career military officer, a nurse, mother and grandmother,
generally leaving her sexual orientation out of her campaign pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other gay candidates, Cammermeyer, 56, said she is
running for Congress because of her concerns about health care,
Social Security and the environment: ``I cannot reiterate enough
that what may have brought some national interest is not of local
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cammermeyer also is the only candidate running this year who
can say that the actress Glenn Close portrayed her in a television
movie.
</P>
<P>
   Cammermeyer drew national attention when she lost her position
in the Washington Army National Guard after acknowledging that she
is gay. She sued for and won reinstatement, then retired in 1997.
Close starred in ``Serving in Silence,'' a movie about
Cammermeyer's ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Cammermeyer, who is divorced, lives with her partner, Dianne
Divelbess, in a small village on Whidbey Island that also is home
to the probable Republican nominee, Rep. Jack Metcalf.
</P>
<P>
   The 70-year-old Metcalf, a retired teacher, began the campaign
in the spring by focusing attention on Cammermeyer's personal life.
He referred to her in a mailing as a ``controversial lesbian.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate fund-raising letter, Metcalf wrote, ``We are in a
life-and-death struggle for the spiritual and cultural heritage _
and future _ of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a recent interview, he said, ``I don't intend to talk
about it unless she brings it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Candidates who wish to wage a ``family values'' campaign may now
plausibly focus their attention on a bigger story, President
Clinton's sexual indiscretions, without making an issue of their
opponents' private lives.
</P>
<P>
   And Metcalf has one other way of drawing a contrast with
Cammermeyer in this area. He will celebrate his 50th wedding
anniversary in early October, an event his campaign intends not to
let pass unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
