<HEADER>
A4756 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MILLER-COX     09-14 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MILLER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Governor denounces Clinton's actions as `wrong, shameful'
 &HT;    By Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- In a move that may help distance Georgia Democrats
from the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal, Georgia Gov. Zell Miller on
Tuesday harshly condemned the president's behavior as deplorable
and said his longtime political ally has destroyed his own
credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't deny what he did was wrong, shameful,'' Miller said.
``I feel sorry that a good friend has betrayed his family and his
staff, debased himself, embarrassed himself and diminished the
presidency. He has shattered his credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who soon will leave office as perhaps Georgia's most
popular governor, is expected to be the mainstay of Democratic
campaigns across the state this fall as candidates try to tap into
his broad support base. Miller's strong links to the president may
be the best way for Republicans to undercut his appeals for support
for other Georgia Democrats on the ballot, or to keep him from
weighing into the contests at all.
</P>
<P>
   But by speaking out on Clinton's woes, Miller may be trying to
inoculate himself and the candidates he supports from being further
tarnished by the president's troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Miller stressed that he is not trying to distance himself from
the president, who he still gives high job approval ratings. And he
wouldn't say whether he thinks Clinton should resign, saying that
is a decision the president must make for himself. ``I still love
him like a brother... but I can remain his friend without excusing
his behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Miller's friendship, and his political support, that
helped catapult Clinton from governor to the White House. Miller is
credited with reviving Clinton's foundering presidential bid in
1992 after allegations of an affair with Gennifer Flowers sent his
campaign into a tailspin in the New Hampshire primary. By moving up
the date of Georgia's presidential primary, Miller provided Clinton
with the platform to rebound and much-needed momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The consultants for Miller's 1989 bid for governor, Paul Begala
and James Carville, crafted Clinton's presidential campaign, and
Miller's chief of staff left the Georgia Capitol to become a White
House staffer.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Miller was rewarded with a position as a keynote
speaker at the 1992 Democratic National Convention, and has
remained a close friend of the president.
</P>
<P>
   But Miller said he couldn't excuse Clinton's handling of
allegations about his relationship with former intern Monica
Lewinsky. ``I'm not talking about what he did to Monica. I'm
talking about what he did after he knew he'd been found out,'' he
said. ``I'm talking about January to August, sending aides who
served him so loyally out to lie unbeknownst to themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, House Speaker Newt Gingrich continued to adopt a
cautious wait-and-see approach Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At Hayes Elementary School in Kennesaw, Gingrich was asked by a
third-grader if the president is ``going to get fired.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know yet,'' Gingrich said. ``We have to see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich said a weekend in his Cobb County district confirmed
that his Republican supporters agree with the cautious approach:
``I found even the most partisan Republican wants this to be done
in a fair and constitutional manner with a real opportunity for
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
