<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4757 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALLACE-BAXTER-COLUMN     09-14 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLACE-BAXTER-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Charisma, endurance shaped a tragic Southern story
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- I finally met George Wallace, after a lifetime of
hearing about him, when I was working one summer for the Montgomery
Advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, his wife Lurleen was governor, and whatever he was
sounding off about that day wasn't very newsy, so the city desk
sent another intern and me out to his office. Wallace spotted us
among the other local reporters, and when his official business was
over he kept us behind and inquired our names.
</P>
<P>
   I was only mildly surprised when in a couple of quick questions
he was able to identify me as the nephew of the girl who'd tutored
him in 7th grade algebra. My family came from near Clio, the little
railhead town, named after the muse of history, where he was born.
</P>
<P>
   But then he turned to the other intern and, on hearing his name,
offered condolences for his mother's death in the Orly plane crash
several years before, along with myriad details of that young man's
family, which was from another part of the state. And as I watched
those dark, burning eyes search our faces, imprinting the memory of
us into some unimaginably deep mental card file, I began to grasp
that mixture of awe and terror with which other politicians
regarded him.
</P>
<P>
   He was a force, an almost startling combination of restless
ambition, charismatic resentment and unsleeping memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``If George had parachuted into the Albanian countryside in the
spring of 1962,'' former adviser John Kohn told Wallace's
biographer, Dan T. Carter, ``he would have been head of a
collective farm by the fall, a member of the Communist Party by
mid-winter, on his way to the district party meeting as a delegate
by the following year and a member of the Comintern in two or three
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace traced a fiery arc across the nation's history as the
segregationist Southern governor who tapped into a much wider pool
of white working-class anger in the 1960s, but it was in Alabama
where the fullest range of his shape-shifting political talents
were played out. Over three decades, even after Arthur Bremer's
bullets left him wheel chair-ridden and in constant pain, he
dominated his state in a way no other American politician has in
this era.
</P>
<P>
   It was sheer endurance, as much as anything, that enabled
Wallace to hang on long enough to write his name not only in
history but in myth, the modern embodiment of an old Southern story
of pride, disaster and redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``That part of the state, you had to grow up tough and rugged,
with stick-to-it-iveness and faith,'' said Rep. John Lewis. The
farm near Brundidge where Lewis grew up is about 15 or 20 miles
from Clio, but it was long after the young civil rights worker was
beaten at Selma's Edmund Pettus Bridge that he met his former
nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on one side, he was on the other. He grew. For me, he's
the personification of a person's ability and capacity to change,''
Lewis said from a phone in a Los Angeles hotel room Monday. The
overwhelming support that black voters in Alabama gave Wallace in
his last election, after his repentance for his '60s demagoguery,
should be a relevant lesson for today, said Lewis, who has been a
staunch supporter of Bill Clinton in his darkest hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can forgive this man, then I think America should be
able to forgive the president,'' Lewis said, giving that tragic old
Southern story one more twist.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
