u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALLACE-Q&AMP;A15-COX     09-14 0423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLACE-Q&AMP;A15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wallace's philosophy `never got in the way'
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dan T. Carter, Andrew Mellon professor of history at Atlanta's
Emory University, is the author of ``The Politics of Rage: George
Wallace, the Origins of the New Conservatism and the Transformation
of American Politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Former Montgomery Advertiser-Journal editor and Carter White
House official Ray Jenkins has said that George Wallace's ``most
enduring legacy'' is ``Richard Nixon's `Southern strategy' and the
fulfillment of it in Ronald Reagan.'' Do you agree? It seems to
leave out credit for the 1964 Barry Goldwater campaign for
president as being the criticial event swinging the South to the
GOP.
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Goldwater's legacy is relevant, but keep in mind that to
many Republicans (including Richard Nixon), Goldwater's strategy
had backfired. (Goldwater lost to Lyndon B. Johnson in a landslide,
carrying only Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, Mississippi, South
Carolina and his home state of Arizona.)The real shift for the
center of the Republican Party toward the Southern strategy came
under the leadership of Nixon, particularly after the '68 election
when he saw how much he had been threatened by George Wallace.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Wallace told The Associated Press in 1992 that he ``should
have been vice president in 1972.'' Do you agree? Would a
doctrinaire liberal like George McGovern, in the bitter Vietnam-era
climate, have named archconservative Wallace his running mate?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``Ray Jenkins has the final word on this, I think, since he
talked to both Hubert Humphrey (about the 1968 race) and McGovern
(about '72). Neither would have run with Wallace. That kind of
ticket was a pig that would not fly. Despite his crushing defeat in
'72, McGovern wasn't stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you feel regarding Wallace's sea of change to
moderatism on the race issue? Was it a genuine spiritual conversion
or political expediency?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``The late Bob Vance (Alabama Democratic Party chairman and
later an 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals judge) had the best
response to that question. When asked it by an Alabama public
television director for a two-hour documentary on Wallace, he
paused and said, `His philosophy never got in the way.' I don't
think he was a visceral racist in the sense that it overshadowed
his thinking, so it wasn't that hard to change his public views
once the political terrain shifted.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
