<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ECON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OUTLINES PLAN FOR DEALING WITH WORLD ECONOMIC TURMOIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (also moving in `a' category; with: CLINTON-REPORT-SCENE,
CLINTON-SCHOOLS, CLINTON-PERJURY, CLINTON-CONGRESS,
CLINTON-PASTORS, NY-CLINTON, CLINTON-LEWINSKY,
CLINTON-LEWIS-COLUMN) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ President Clinton declared on Monday that the
economic turmoil on three continents constitutes ``the biggest
financial challenge facing the world in a half-century.'' Without
once discussing the calls for his censure or impeachment, he laid
out for the first time a strategy to quell the trouble before it
hits American shores.
</P>
<P>
   In a half-hour address to a friendly, carefully selected
audience at the Council on Foreign Relations in Manhattan, Clinton
said that the economic turmoil, if allowed to fester, would pose a
threat to American security and ``put our own prosperity at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's biggest initiative _ though one he couched carefully
to avoid appearing to interfere in interest rate policy _ was a
call for the world's leading economies to abandon their fear of
inflation and instead ``spur growth.'' He also urged the World Bank
to double its aid in Asia, where millions of people are suddenly
unemployed or sinking back into poverty, and he called for a
meeting of finance ministers from the world's largest economies and
from the hard-hit emerging markets ``within 30 days'' to develop
broader strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``For most of the last 30 years, the United States and the rest
of the world has been preoccupied by inflation,'' he said. ``But
clearly the balance of risks has now shifted.''
</P>
<P>
   In a move coordinated by the Treasury Department over the
weekend to come within minutes of Clinton's speech, the finance
ministers and central bank governors of the world's seven largest
economies issued a parallel statment that was clearly intended to
open the door to coordinated interest-rate cuts _ a step that, if
skillfully executed, could help spur economic activity around the
globe. It was the first time that the Group Of Seven had vowed to
make a coordinated effort to reign in the economic disorder that
officials clearly fear is spinning out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a general truth,'' one senior administration official
said after Clinton spoke, `that the magnitude of the
deterioration'' in recent week has been ``much greater than anyone
anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   The finance ministers also endorsed another initiative announced
by Clinton: Support for the use of an emergency fund within the
IMF, now down to its last $15 billion, to combat the latest
economic turmoil in Latin America.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
