</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-PRISONS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Move to make private prison public is delayed
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Georgia's attempt to integrate privately run prisons
into its system faces another delay today as the company running
the prison misses another moving-in day for medium-security
inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Cornell Corrections Inc. had planned to start taking
inmates at a prison it built in Charlton County in the southeast
corner of the state early last month. That was delayed because
construction was not complete, so the next deadline was set for
today, Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Corrections spokesman Scott Stallings said Monday
the plan now was to have the first state inmates in the Cornell
prison by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't have a firm date,'' Stallings said. ``They had
told us by the latter part of this month. They're just not ready.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to ease the expensive crush on the state prison
system, which now holds more than 38,000 convicts, Georgia
contracted with two companies _ Cornell of Houston and Corrections
Corp. of American of Nashville _ to build three 750-bed
medium-security prisons. The Cornell prison was to be the first to
open while CCA is set to finish building similar prisons in Coffee
and Wheeler counties late this year or early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell officials say the opening delay can be blamed on
weather-related construction problems that are no different from
those that routinely occur with any large building project.
</P>
<P>
   State officials argue that turning to corporate America will
save taxpayers because the private sector can build prisons faster
and it is not hamstrung by a costly governmental bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the addition of the three private prisons, meanwhile,
DOC still plans to ask the 1999 Legislature for $148 million to
build about 4,500 beds that would be in the system within two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delay is bad because we need the space,'' said Rep. Denny
Dobbs (D-Covington), who has been holding hearings on sentencing
reform.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
