<SLUG> BC-KAZAKHSTAN-OIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEALS SIGNED FOR OIL AND GAS EXPLORATION IN KAZAKHSTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By STEVE LeVINE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALMATY, Kazakhstan_ U.S. and Japanese companies signed oil- and
gas-exploration deals on Monday that could be worth several billion
dollars to this former Soviet republic in Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips Petroleum of the United States and the Japanese-owned
Indonesian Petroleum Company agreed to pay a total of $500 million
in cash for stakes in a 2,000-square-mile oilfield, called
Kashagan. The Kazakhs are also to receive a $1 billion,
low-interest loan from Japan, and investment in several hydrocarbon
and metals enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Phillips agreed to build a $500 million liquefied
natural gas plant, and the Japanese pledged $2 billion in
investments including an oil refinery, a plastics plant and an
aluminum smelter.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's sale of Kazakhstan's one-seventh stake in the Kashagan
field came at a critical time, less than a week after the
government revised its budget estimates and announced a prospective
$750 million deficit.
</P>
<P>
   At the signing ceremony in Astana, 600 miles north of here,
Prime Minister Nurlan Balgimbayev said the $500 million would be
injected directly into the budget.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement caught industry analysts off guard. While the
Kashagan field is thought by some experts to contain the largest
reserves on the Caspian Sea _ seismic studies have disclosed
gigantic, domed undersea structures _ the field has yet to undergo
drilling tests that would prove what is actually there.
</P>
<P>
   But ``this is big,'' said a Western official here, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. Referring to the $500 million signing bonus
from the two companies to Kazakhstan, the official added, ``That's
a lot of money'' for something sight unseen.
</P>
<P>
   With the deal, the two companies join a consortium that includes
Mobil, Royal Dutch/Shell, Total of France, Agip of Italy, British
Gas and British Petroleum.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly $50 billion in U.S.-led private energy investment has
been pledged over the last few years to the three regional
republics richest in oil and natural gas _ Kazakhstan, Turkmenistan
and Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time horizon that oil companies have is pretty long,''
said Otbert de Jong, head of the ABN-Amro Bank branch here.
``You'll see that events, such as the low oil prices at present,
won't influence decisions now. My feeling in general is that they
will remain very enthusiastic and keep things ticking over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
