A4777 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NKOREA-ROCKET-NYT &LR;      09-14 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NKOREA-ROCKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA TRIED TO LAUNCH SATELLITE, U.S. SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States now believes that North Korea
tried, but failed, to launch a small satellite into orbit when it
fired a multistage rocket in an arc over Japan two weeks ago,
administration and defense officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The rocket, however, was significantly more powerful than
American defense and intelligence officials first reported. The
officials now say that the rocket had three stages, not two, and
that the final stage used solid fuel, a significant technological
leap for North Korea's missile program.
</P>
<P>
   The third stage of the rocket, which carried a small satellite,
broke up somewhere over the Pacific Ocean before reaching orbit,
said the officials, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the satellite indicated that North Korea has not
yet mastered solid-fuel technology, but the officials said the
effort alone suggested that North Korea's program might be more
ambitious and advanced than was widely believed. One government
official said Monday that if North Korea perfected a third stage in
future tests, its missiles would have a range of some 3,500 miles,
enough to reach parts of Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has strongly condemned North Korea's launching
of the rocket on Aug. 31, calling it a provocation that needlessly
stoked tensions in the region. In the two weeks since then,
however, the administration has had to retreat from its initial
assessment of the firing, which intelligence agencies monitored
closely and declared to be a test of a two-stage rocket called the
Taepodong-1.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has claimed it successfully placed a satellite into
an oval orbit around the earth for peaceful scientific purposes,
including the broadcast of ``immortal revolutionary hymns'' in
honor of its paramount ruler, Kim Jong Il, and his father, Kim Il
Sung, who died in 1994. The launch came only days before North
Korea celebrated its 50th anniversary and consolidated Kim Jong
Il's power as chairman of the National Defense Commission.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. Space Command at Peterson Air Force Base in
Colorado, which tracks objects in orbit, has been unable to verify
North Korea's claims, nor has anyone at the Pentagon or the
intelligence agencies been able to tune in to the hymns, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have concluded that North Korea did attempt to orbit a very
small satellite,'' the State Department's spokesman, James Rubin,
said Monday. ``We also have concluded the satellite failed to
achieve orbit.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin went on to say the launch itself confirmed North Korea's
``inherent capability to threaten its neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the State Department announced that a North Korean
delegation had agreed to resume talks about its missile program in
October in New York City. Those talks, which never advanced very
far, were suspended a year ago after two of North Korea's diplomats
defected to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Milhollin, director of the Wisconsin Project on Nuclear
Arms Control, a research organization in Washington, said the
disclosures suggested North Korea was intent on building
intercontinental ballistic missiles. ``I don't want to sound
alarmist,'' he said, ``but that's where we are heading.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
