<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SUPPORT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORKERS OFFER CLINTON A SUBDUED CHEER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - There was no strolling or shopping this time around.
</P>
<P>
   On his past trips to Manhattan, President Clinton has stepped
out of his limo to mingle with the people and buy some trinkets in
a mall.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, though, as he was shuttled from one Manhattan fundraiser
to the next, the president stayed securely behind the armored
plating and the tinted glass.
</P>
<P>
   New York has long been a hospitable stop for Clinton, and New
Yorkers remain as supportive as any, even amid his current
troubles. The Daily News' editorial Monday blared, ``City to Bubba:
Hang in there.''
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, hundreds of people waved and cheered as his
motorcade zoomed down Park Avenue in the morning, Fifth Avenue in
the afternoon, and Broadway in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the applause was far from feverish _ or unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a unionist, I'm for the president 100 percent,'' said Jose
Rosado. ``But I will never vote for him again, even if he runs for
something. I have a family. I have morals.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean Piersol, a teacher visiting the city from San Francisco,
said, ``I'm disappointed in him. He's a brilliant man, but he's so
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she stood on the sidewalk for nearly an hour,
waiting for a glimpse of Clinton, as he left a $50,000-a-seat
luncheon in the Fifth Avenue penthouse of Denise Rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited,'' Piersol admitted. ``It's the President. It's
bigger than him. I want to get a picture of him for my class _
though maybe I'll wait a while to show it to them, 'till after this
has blown over.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate over Clinton's behavior and the Kenneth Starr report
carried into the streets, as the crowds waited for the president to
pass and the barricades to be lifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should resign and I think the people who are up there with
him,'' said Walker Dean, a commercial real-estate consultant, ``are
a bunch of hypocrites.''
</P>
<P>
   A schoolteacher who identified herself only as Barbara replied,
``What, you think this hasn't been going on since George
Washington's day? Look at Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about Washington or Kennedy,'' Dean replied.
``We're talking about this president in 1998. Our times have
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Three women from Trenton, N.J., who had come into Manhattan on
the train to shop, were all for the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Ken Starr investigation is the most phenomenal waste of
money,'' said Ellen Glover. ``I don't condone Clinton's behavior,
but really, it's his personal life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We already knew he was a cheat,'' added her friend, Sherry
Bailey. ``The only person he should have to answer to is Hillary.
When someone asks you a question that's none of their business, you
don't have an obligation to answer it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, as Clinton headed toward Times Square _ first
for a dinner at The Supper Club, then a special performance of
``The Lion King'' at Disney's New Amsterdam Theater, with tickets
priced from $125 to $100,000 a seat _ the argument raged on.
</P>
<P>
   George Cruikshank held a sign reading ``Clinton Is the Real
Lyin' King,'' and shouted, ``Where's the outrage?''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Reedy, an office supervisor in the area, sneered back,
``He's no lying king. He's a good man. All these people in Congress
are doing the same thing. The only difference is they didn't get
caught.''
</P>
<P>
   The most widespread criticism of Clinton Monday concerned how
badly his trip here _ with its attendant security and roadblocks
and pedestrian barricades _ was tying up traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell him to stay the hell out of New York,'' said an Upper
East Sider who was blocked from getting to work by barricades
around the Council on Foreign Relations, where Clinton delivered a
policy address on international economics in the morning. ``He
messes up the whole town every month, it seems.''
</P>
<P>
   Tempers flared hotter still in Times Square, where security
measures went into effect during the evening rush hour. ``Is the
president going to pay my parking bill?'' asked one man who was
blocked from getting to the garage where he parks his car. Other
office workers pleaded with police to let them through so they
could get home to sick children, angry spouses, or starving pets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
