<SLUG> BC-BOMBINGS-FREEH-320&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI CHIEF CITES CIA HELP IN AFRICAN BOMBING INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST, Hungary, _ The director of the Federal Bureau of
Investigation, Louis Freeh, said Monday that much of the progress
made in the investigation of the bombings of two U.S. embassies in
East Africa had been a result of close cooperation between two
usually rival agencies: the FBI and the Central Intelligence
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh, who was visiting an FBI-financed international training
center here, said in an interview that it ``doesn't make sense''
for past antagonisms to hamper collaboration between two
organizations that can help each other fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the work in the East Africa bombings is the product
of close cooperation of the agency and the FBI in terms of locating
suspects and obtaining lawful evidence that FBI agents can
introduce in court,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA has long fought to preserve its overseas authority
exclusively for itself, but it does not have law-enforcement
powers. The FBI has begun to expand outside the United States to
investigate crimes against Americans overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh has made expanding the reach of the bureau a hallmark of
his tenure. He has sent agents to Tbilisi, Georgia, to help in the
investigation of the assassination attempt against President Eduard
Shevardnadze and here to Budapest, where Russian organized crime
has become a threat to economic stability.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau now has 32 offices overseas, including one in Moscow,
and negotiations are under way for the opening of an office in
China.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh said there were still about 100 FBI agents in Kenya and
Tanzania working on aspects of the embassy bombings in August. The
bureau is getting help from the authorities in a number of
countries, including the Comoros, a remote republic of islands off
the coast of East Africa, where agents raided several homes this
month seeking a suspect.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the International Law Enforcement Academy that opened here
with FBI financing in 1995, Freeh addressed a class of more than 40
Russian, Polish and Estonian police officers selected to take part
in an eight-week course with U.S. law enforcement instructors.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 700 police officers from Central and Eastern Europe and
the former Soviet Union have taken part in the courses, which
relate to crimes like money laundering and weapons- and
people-smuggling as well as terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh also announced the formation of a U.S.-Hungarian organized
crime force to assist the Hungarian police in new techniques of
discovering computer-driven money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. ambassador to Hungary, Peter Tufo, said more than one
Russian-speaking organized crime group with involvement in the
United States now had headquarters in Budapest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
