<HEADLINE>
ONLY EIGHT FLIGHT 111 VICTIMS IDENTIFIED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Budgeted as Swissair-Valuables; i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ Although Navy divers have spent nearly
two weeks combing the ocean floor for remains from Swissair Flight
111, officials as of Monday had identified the bodies of only eight
of the 229 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The process is being slowed by the need to gather DNA and
medical records, said John Butt, chief medical examiner of Nova
Scotia. Some of the records also have to be translated.
</P>
<P>
   The mammoth diving and recovery process is still under way but
Butt said he believes there are no human remains scattered outside
the debris area, which leads officials to think they will probably
be found inside several large pieces of the fuselage.
</P>
<P>
   If the recovery process becomes too dangerous, said Butt, the
remains might have to be pulled up with the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't come to that point, yet,'' said Cmdr. Kevin Carle,
spokesman for the Canadian Navy. ``The navy's priority hasn't
shifted. It is still collecting the victim's remains.''
</P>
<P>
   But Carle said the recovery process is extremely dangerous and
slow. ``You have to understand that being down there is like
walking among a hedge of razor blades,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The USS Grapple, a salvage ship, is moored to large concrete
blocks, preparing to raise sections of the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Navy divers found the second ``black box'' or
cockpit voice recorder. Officials are hoping conversations from the
tape, which records in 30-minute continuous loops, will help
explain the cause of the MD-11 crash on Sept. 2. However, Canadian
law prohibits disclosure of transcripts of the tape to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Swissair officials confirmed Monday, in a statement,
that the flight was carrying valuables on board, including an
original Picasso called ``Le Peintre,'' or ``the painter.'' The art
piece was worth $1.5 million. The plane was also carrying bank
notes, watches and jewelry, as well as another unknown art piece.
</P>
<P>
   The statement said Swissair carries some 200,000 valuable
consignments a year. Officials have also confirmed that a large sum
of money, maybe in the millions, was on the plane, secured in a
container. None of the valuables has been retrieved, said
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Police said poachers ``will not be tolerated and will be dealt
with swiftly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4786 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      09-14 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP CONGRESSIONAL DEMOCRATS CALL ON CLINTON TO STOP LEGAL
`HAIR-SPLITTING' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: story will be updated and expanded.) 
(See also: CLINTON-ECON, CLINTON-REPORT-SCENE, CLINTON-SCHOOLS,
CLINTON-PERJURY, CLINTON-PASTORS, NY-CLINTON, CLINTON-LEWINSKY,
CLINTON-LEWIS-COLUMN) 
(nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The two Democratic leaders of Congress sharply
admonished the White House Monday to stop trying to make legal
justifications for President Clinton's misleading testimony about
his relationship with Monica Lewinsky. But buoyed by polls showing
the nation still reluctant to embark on impeachment, they also
called for quick decisions to resolve the nation's constitutional
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The similar statements by House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt
and Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle positioned them squarely in
synch with the perceived public mood. Their remarks were designed,
aides said, to head off any Republican efforts to have protracted
impeachment hearings lasting well into next year.
</P>
<P>
   But while Republicans pledged to move in timely fashion, they
appeared to be looking at precisely the kind of broad-reaching and
time-consuming inquiry that Democrats want to avoid. Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., the Judiciary Committee chairman and therefore the
person who oversees the impeachment process, said he would not rule
out expanding any inquiry beyond the president's affair with Ms.
Lewinsky and efforts to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is certainly a possibility,'' he said, explaining that
Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth Starr could still send
Congress information on other matters he has investigated and that
``we would be duty bound to consider whatever he sends us.'' He
also did not rule out an extensive inquiry even if Starr did not
make another report, called a referral. ``It's possible,'' said
Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   The positioning in Congress came as members of the House and
Senate returned to Washington after a weekend of sampling
constituent opinion to the flood of sordid details about Clinton's
relationship with a White House intern. Sentiment varied from
district to district, with Republicans generally seeking punishment
of Clinton but Democrats saying both impeachment and resignation
are too harsh, and finding conflicting feelings from a nation that
wants Clinton rebuked but fears the trauma of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a way to salvage the situation for the White House,
both Gephardt and Daschle _ in their first reactions since Starr's
report was made public on Friday _ warned President Clinton against
the kind of defense his lawyers put forth on weekend talk shows
when they continued to argue that he had not lied in legal
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly agree with those who have grown impatient with
hair-splitting over legal technicalities,'' Daschle said. ``There
is a basic understanding of the truthfulness that the president
failed to meet.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The president and his advisers must accept that
continued legal jousting serves no constructive purpose. It simply
stands in the way of what we need to do: move forward and let
common sense guide us in doing what is best for the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2009EDT &QL; 
