<HEADER>
A4788 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-CAUCUS-HNS &LR;      09-14 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-CAUCUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK CAUCUS SUPPORTS EMBATTLED CLINTON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Members of the Congressional Black Caucus, seeing
parallels between President Clinton's plight and the persecution of
African Americans, continue to support the embattled chief
executive despite allegations that he lied under oath, obstructed
justice and abused his power.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than expressing anger at the president, the group of 38
congressional Democrats have focused their wrath on independent
counsel Kenneth Starr. The special prosecutor last week issued a
report alleging 11 impeachable offenses by Clinton and containing
salacious details of the president's extramarital affair with
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black people have known what it's like to be hounded and
prosecuted and to be selectively investigated,'' Rep. Charles
Rangel, D-N.Y., said Monday. ``The ability to pursue somebody is
subjective. Prosecution ... can turn to persecution.''
</P>
<P>
   Other caucus members said many black Americans feel kinship with
Clinton _ a powerful white man _ based on their belief he is a
victim of a justice system that has singled him out for punishment
on questionable grounds and evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many African Americans ... feel that he has been railroaded,''
said Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr., D-Ill., the son of the civil rights
leader. Black Americans need to be assured that Clinton will
receive ``due process of law, a sense of fairness and equal
protection under the law,'' Jackson added.
</P>
<P>
   ``That process must be fair,'' the congressman said of the House
Judiciary Committee's consideration of whether to launch an
impeachment inquiry. ``When the facts emerge, let the chips fall
where they may.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Danny Davis, D-Ill., said the president's efforts to reach
out to the African-American community have played a larger part in
the good will he is receiving than any parallels to black
persecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton has demonstrated awareness and some positive
movement toward issues that affect African-American life,'' Davis
said, referring to the president's efforts to protect low-income
assistance programs. ``They recognize that President Clinton has
stood between the low-income community and disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Elijah Cummings, D-Md., echoed Rangel and Jackson,
saying black men have been unfairly targeted by police and
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``African-American people have felt so much pain,'' Cummings
said. ``Anything that smacks of abuse they can understand.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Cummings said, blacks will have an open mind as the
House weighs whether to proceed with the impeachment process.
``African Americans can handle results as long as the process is
fair,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The black caucus has no official position on the Clinton scandal
and has held no formal discussions on the president's situation.
Nevertheless, the panel's overwhelming support for Clinton mirrors
polling data that show widespread support among blacks for the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton enjoys a 90 percent overall favorable rating among black
Americans, according to a poll last week from the independent Pew
Research Center for the People &AMP; the Press. In addition, 91 percent
of blacks said Clinton should stay in office while 6 percent said
he should resign; in contrast, 76 percent of whites said the
president should remain while 20 percent called on him to quit.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 63 House members who voted Friday against the immediate
public release of independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report, 29
belong to the black caucus, including Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee,
D-Houston. Members who voted against the rule, which cleared the
way for the report to be put on the Internet, said it was unfair to
allow the public to see the document before the accused president
could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the general public will not be deceived by this
Hollywood-type production and promotion of this issue by
independent counsel Ken Starr and the Republican-controlled
Congress,'' said Rep. William Clay, D-Mo. ``I saw nothing new in
the charges against President Clinton. The so-called 11 impeachable
items are a real legal stretch by a highly partisan prosecutor who
seemingly spent $40 million of taxpayer funds to produce a
government document to rival Hustler magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Eva Clayton, D-N.C., said the American ideal of equal
justice demanded that Clinton should have had a chance to respond
to the report before it was made public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president should not have any more rights than any other
accused person, but he should not have any less,'' Clayton said in
voting against release of the Starr report without first allowing
the president to see it. ``Any citizen, similarly situated would be
entitled to know what the accusations are and who are the accusers.
It is a sad and dangerous day in the history of this nation when
the principles upon which this nation was founded bow to the
pressures of what is politic and what is fashionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangel, however, voted for the immediate release of the report
despite his misgivings. ``I didn't think I should be unfair and
deny the American people a chance to review it,'' Rangel said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's private attorney David Kendall did provide a rebuttal
to the report before it was released. But the response was based
solely on media accounts of what the report contained, Kendall
said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
