<HEADER>
A4798 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      09-14 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDALOUS LESSONS FOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - The gentleman on the telephone spoke loudly and
quickly and hung up before I could answer his question, which was:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, moron, what kind of sick lesson do YOU think this putrid
Clinton scandal is teaching our children?''
</P>
<P>
   Had he stayed on the line I would have told him that, near as I
can tell, there isn't one lesson to be taught, but many.
</P>
<P>
   For example, our children might learn that some of our most
opinionated citizens choose to speak anonymously.
</P>
<P>
   I received a number of such calls over the weekend. This one was
left on my answering machine by an unidentified woman:
</P>
<P>
   ``Reading your column in the paper, E.J., you are such a biased
(expletive). . .We just don't want Clinton to be president anymore.
Why can't you get that through your thick skull, you idiot!''
</P>
<P>
   This came from a brusk, confident-sounding but unnamed man:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, E-GAY. I feel your pain. You and that sick president,
E-GAY!''
</P>
<P>
   And this from another a self-assured fellow who, like the
others, chose not to identify himself:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Slick Willie's got the Democrat liberals looking like
roaches on their backs floating on a toilet seat. All kind of
twitchy. How's it feel, you little queer? How's it to see your boy
go down like this. Twisting. Agonizing. Does it hurt you, Montini?
You little queer. If this was a Republican, you'd be squealing like
the (expletive) little rat that you are. All right? But you just
want us to forget it and get on with life. Hey, Twitchy.
(Expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   From these people our children might learn is that, among
certain grown-ups, the most insulting thing you can say to someone
else involves an ugly variation on the word ``homosexual.''
</P>
<P>
   They'd also see that those who use such slurs rarely have the
guts to own up to it.
</P>
<P>
   That alone would be invaluable information to a child.
</P>
<P>
   And it's just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   A concerned, polite father from Scottsdale telephoned to ask,
``If Clinton isn't impeached and removed from office, wouldn't that
tell our kids that lying has no consequences?''
</P>
<P>
   It might, but only if the public humiliation Clinton is going
through is inconsequential.
</P>
<P>
   Only if embarrassing your wife and daughter and ruining your
reputation is not a consequence.
</P>
<P>
   Only if making yourself the butt of an international joke is not
a consequence.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, some of Clinton's biggest detractors in
government said there would be no need for impeachment if he would
own up to his relationship with Monica Lewinsky and apologize for
what he'd done.
</P>
<P>
   He's been apologizing daily for about a month, now, but the
politicians have changed their minds, saying Clinton's repentance
wasn't quick enough and hasn't been ``sincere'' enough.
</P>
<P>
   Children could learn a lot from that about self-righteousness.
</P>
<P>
   And promises.
</P>
<P>
   If we wanted to, we even could teach children about Kenneth
Starr, the special prosecutor. He has called Clinton a liar and
wants him kicked out of office for it.
</P>
<P>
   Starr once represented the Brown &AMP; Williamson tobacco company.
</P>
<P>
   When was the last time a responsible American adult told
children to believe cigarette makers or their representatives?
</P>
<P>
   What lesson can our children learn from someone like Starr
pointing the finger at someone like Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   That it's OK to side with liars _ for a fat retainer?
</P>
<P>
   That's it's OK to lie in business but not in one's personal
life?
</P>
<P>
   If the politicians holding the rocks ever tossed a few at the
big glass houses of Congress, our children would see that the most
scandalous information to be learned from the Clinton affair has
nothing to do with sex, but with power.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a lesson or two for us adults. The most valuable
being:
</P>
<P>
   Don't listen to your voice mail. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
