<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4802 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      09-14 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS POST STRONG GAINS FOR 2ND STRAIGHT SESSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic on the market's performance is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices posted strong, broadly based gains for
the second consecutive session Monday, buoyed at least in part by
wisps of optimism that a range of domestic and international
problems that seemed so destabilizing and insuperable a few weeks
ago may be ultimately resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 149.85 points, or 1.92
percent, to 7,945.35. Earlier in the session the blue-chip index
was up as much as 244 points.
</P>
<P>
   Broader market measures also posted strong gains. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index rose 20.66 points, or 2.05 percent, to
1,029.72. The Nasdaq composite index, which is heavily weighted in
technology issues, increased by 24.05 points, or 1.46 percent, to
1,665.69. The Russell 2000 index of small stocks rose 4.10 points,
or 1.16 percent, to 357.72. On the Big Board, advancing issues
outpaced stocks that fell in price by a ratio of two to one. Volume
was 714.4 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The gains followed a good day on foreign equity markets and a
rally by the dollar on foreign exchange markets.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and traders said investors in this country and
elsewhere were encouraged by a number of recent developments,
including a spate of public opinion polls conducted over the
weekend that showed little or no erosion in support for President
Clinton despite the allegations in Special Prosecutor Kenneth
Starr's report to Congress. Analysts said some expressed relief
that much of the substance in the report had been leaked to the
media before it was formally released.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, word that the International Monetary Fund is
prepared to provide a financial package for Brazil, if necessary,
was seen as a positive.
</P>
<P>
   So too was a speech the president gave in New York Monday in
which he highlighted the need to pursue policies that promote
growth around the world. That view was reiterated later in the day
by officials representing the Group of Seven industrial nations.
Clinton's remarks and those by the G-7 follow a Sept. 4 speech by
Alan Greenspan, in which the Federal Reserve Board chairman said
inflation was not a near-term concern for the central bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is now acknowledging what the risks are, which is
reassuring,'' said David Hale, chief economist for the Zurich
Group. ``And the good news for Clinton is that the Starr report had
nothing new in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Smith, chief investment strategist at Prudential
Securities, said that in addition to hopes that key international
economic problems may be addressed on a coordinated basis,
investors were encouraged by announcements last week from Intel
Corp. and General Electric Co. that third quarter results will be
better than previously expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were a couple of really important announcements,'' he
said, ``GE for leadership reasons and Intel because of its
bellwether status in the high-tech group.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Okesky, head of block trading at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, said the tone of Monday's session was much like last
Friday, when stock prices also staged a broad advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clients are definitely more relaxed'' than they were a few
weeks ago, he said. ``Not many are particularly bullish, but the
market has not fallen off a cliff, and that provides some relief.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of what might be a coordinated cut in interest
rates around the world, coupled with the promise of IMF help for
Brazil, helped to bolster bank and financial company stock prices,
whose shares have been battered in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Citicorp rose 5 a share Monday, to 101. American Express was up
3 5/16, to 81 11/16. Merrill Lynch gained 1 5/8, to 57 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks were also big gainers. Merck &AMP; Co. rose 4, to $132,
and Eli Lilly gained 1 5/16, to 76 3/16, after doctors at the
European Congress of Osteoporosis conference said their new drugs
offer new hope for treating the disease, which afflicts an
estimated 200 million women.
</P>
<P>
   And airline stocks were big gainers after the newspaper Barron's
reported over the weekend that these stocks represented very good
value at current price levels.
</P>
<P>
   AMR Corp., parent of American Airlines, gained 4 15/16, to 60
1/2; UAL Corp., holding company for United Airlines, rose 5 7/16,
to 69 3/16, and Delta Air Lines rose by 8 3/4, to 104 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Deere &AMP; Co. and Walt Disney &AMP; Co. were among the losers for the
session, as investors sold shares after the companies said
quarterly earnings will be lower than previously forecast. Deere
dropped 1 3/4, to 31 7/16, and Disney lost 1 3/8, to 24 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   The market's recent performance has encouraged some technicians
to predict that the steep slide in prices may be over for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is at least a short-term bottoming or stabilizing
reaction, and could be the start of a rally that lasts for a month
or so,'' said Richard McCabe, chief market analyst at Merrill Lynch
&AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Still, few are prepared to pronounce that the political and
financial problems facing policy-makers here and around the globe
have been solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Markets around the world seem to have concluded the president
will stay in office, and that we will have some leadership in the
United States at an extraordinarily tricky time,'' said Hugh
Johnson, chief investment officer at First Albany Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``But actions speak louder than words. Congress has to approve
the $17.9 billion requested for the IMF, not the $3.5 billion that
was voted out of the House Appropriations Committee last week. The
Fed has to cut interest rates. Japan has to reflate its economy and
reform its banking system. In short, we need to see things get
done. There is still a healthy level of skepticism.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
