u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTH-SPENDING-530&AMP;A     09-14 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-SPENDING-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOTAL SPENDING ON HEALTH CARE TO RISE STEEPLY IN NEXT DECADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After five years of relatively slow growth, total
spending on health care in the United States will climb briskly
over the next decade, doubling by 2007, federal officials said on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   And in a reversal of recent trends, they said, private spending
will grow faster than public outlays.
</P>
<P>
   In a new report, the Department of Health and Human Services
predicted that health spending would rise to $2.1 trillion in 2007,
from slightly more than $1 trillion last year.
</P>
<P>
   The department said health care would account for a growing
share of the nation's total output: 16.6 percent of the gross
domestic product in 2007, as against 13.4 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Smith, the main author of the report, published Monday in
the journal Health Affairs, said the growth in per capita health
spending, after adjusting for inflation, would ``be driven almost
entirely by rising expenditures in the private rather than the
public sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent actions by Congress, especially passage of the Balanced
Budget Act of 1997, are slowing the growth of Medicare and
Medicaid, the health programs for the elderly and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   But the authors of the new study foresee ``a rebound'' in
private health care spending, mainly because of ``increases in the
use and intensity of services'' rather than price increases.
</P>
<P>
   Government economists predict that private health insurance
premiums will rise an average of 7 percent to 8 percent a year in
the coming decade, much more than in the last few years. But the
Congressional Budget Office and some private experts on employee
benefits, like Jon Gabel of KPMG Peat Marwick, say the increases
will be more modest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1995, increases in premiums have been less than the
increase in the gross domestic product,'' Gabel said, and he
expects premiums to rise 4 percent to 5 percent a year in the
coming decade.
</P>
<P>
   The federal study says that increases in real per capita income
over the next decade will increase the demand for health care
services, because consumers will have more to spend on health care.
But it says that health maintenance organizations and other forms
of managed care ``will play a smaller role'' in controlling costs
than they have in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-five percent of the people with employer-sponsored health
insurance are already in some type of managed care. And the authors
say that HMOs do not save money for Medicare because the payment
rates are based on what is paid in Medicare's traditional
fee-for-service program.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people without health insurance has been
increasing by 1 million a year and now exceeds 41 million. In the
next few years, the report says, the number of uninsured may grow
more slowly, as more employers offer health benefits to attract
workers at a time of very low unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   But the authors said that the trend of recent years would
eventually resume, so that a larger proportion of Americans would
be uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   Population growth accounts for a relatively small share of the
increase in total health spending. The government predicts that
national health spending will average $7,100 for each American in
2007, up from $3,904 last year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the last five years, from 1992 to 1997, public spending on
health care rose twice as fast as private spending: 7.4 percent a
year, as against 3.7 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   But in the next five years, from 1997 to 2002, private health
spending will rise faster than public spending (7 percent a year,
as against 5.9 percent a year), the department predicts.
</P>
<P>
   The government foresees sharp increases in the growth of
spending for doctors' services and prescription drugs over the next
five years. But it predicts that spending for nursing homes and
home health care will grow more slowly than in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   From 1998 to 2000, the report said, ``Medicare spending for
inpatient hospital services is expected to grow at the lowest rate
in the program's history _ an average of 3 percent a year, compared
with 8.2 percent a year for 1993-1996.''
</P>
<P>
   Many doctors have harshly criticized HMOs, but the report says
that managed care will be responsible for much of the increase in
spending on doctors' services, since HMOs substitute outpatient
doctors' services for hospital care when possible.
</P>
<P>
   Spending for doctors' services increased an average of 3.6
percent a year from 1992 to 1997, but will rise an average of 7.3
percent a year in the coming decade, the government predicts.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith, the main author of the report, said that only some of
the new spending would show up as an increase in doctors' incomes.
Many doctors will, in effect, have to do more work. The total
volume of doctors' services will increase, as consumers demand more
access to medical specialists, free of the constraints imposed by
the most restrictive HMOs, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The report said increases in drug prices had been ``relatively
restrained'' since 1993. But the Department of Health and Human
Services said, ``Expenditures for drugs are expected to grow
rapidly through 2007 as more prescriptions are written and the mix
of prescriptions shifts to more expensive drugs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
