<HEADLINE>
NASA TO BUY MORE RUSSIAN HARDWARE TO HELP FUN SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASA has opened negotiations to purchase more Russian hardware
for the international space station in a bid to give that country
enough cash to keep up its end of the partnership.
</P>
<P>
   NASA hopes to begin assembly of the new orbital laboratory on
Nov. 20., the date it established late last May. But Russia,
suffering from an eroding economy, recently announced a new
three-month delay in completion of a crucial early component called
the service module.
</P>
<P>
   Denied most of its budget this year, the Russian Space Agency
needs the equivalent of $10 million to complete the service module,
said Joseph Rothenberg, NASA's associate administrator for space
flight.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of funding has forced the Russians to set back the launch
of the service module from April to July 1999. The 42,000 pound
module is required to house the new station's first occupants as
well as to keep the spacecraft circling at a safe altitude above
the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to assure funding and stop further delays of the
service module, NASA is negotiating for the purchase of two Russian
Soyuz crew capsules. The three-person Soyuz craft would be docked
to the new station in late 2002 to serve as life boats. The
capsules would allow the station's permanent population to grow
from three to six astronauts and cosmonauts.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the station's resident crew will grow to seven as
NASA replaces the Soyuz rescue craft with at least one seven-person
U.S. rescue ship that is permanently docked to the station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, that will give the up front cash to the Russians
and they will be able to pay off (their contractors for) the
remaining parts they need to get the service module on track,''
Rothenberg said from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He could not provide a cost estimate. The trade publication
Space News, however, citing Russian space officials, placed the
cost of a Soyuz capsule at about $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to Rothenberg, the service module lacks 10 relatively
small components for completion.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most vital of those are two of three star trackers,
optical devices that are needed for the guidance system to keep the
station correctly oriented in space.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are launch critical,'' said Rothenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Other components needed include sensors that relay pressure and
temperature readings to the ground as well as some communications
transmitters and a backup device for cleansing breathing air of
carbon dioxide.
</P>
<P>
   Previous funding problems with Russia's service module forced
NASA to delay its launching from April 1998 to April 1999. Each of
those in turn has prompted the United States to delay the start of
station assembly from November 1997 to November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   NASA seems determined to absorb the latest three-month slip in
the service module without new delays to the start of the station's
five-year construction.
</P>
<P>
   The new station's first module _ a U.S.-financed, Russian-built
guidance and propulsion device called the Zarya control module _ is
targeted for a Nov. 20 launching from central Asia.
</P>
<P>
   It is to be joined by the U. S.-financed and built Node 1 module
dubbed ``Unity'' in early December. Launched by the space shuttle
Endeavour on Dec. 3, Unity is equipped with six docking ports that
will link future U.S. and Russian modules.
</P>
<P>
   Those dates were agreed to by the station's U.S., Russian,
European, Japanese and Canadian partners late last May.
</P>
<P>
   The Nov. 20 and Dec. 3 launch dates can hold as long as the
launching of Russia's service module does not slip past September
of next year, Rothenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The control module has enough propellant and electrical power to
keep itself and the Unity node safely orbiting the Earth for 500
days before it must be joined by the service module.
</P>
<P>
   NASA plans to re-evaluate its decision to stick with the
November and December launching dates for the first of the stations
components during a series of meetings in Moscow to begin next
week. The last of the meetings should wrap up in mid-October.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rothenberg said Monday the United States is taking
measures to safeguard it from future reliance on the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's financial problems make it increasingly unlikely the
country can keep a commitment to periodically launch unmanned
Progress cargo capsules to the new station. The Progress capsules
help re-boost the station and furnish the propellant needed by the
service module to boost.
</P>
<P>
   NASA plans to take measures to replace the need for Progress
capsules, including:
</P>
<P>
   Modifying its space shuttles so that steering thrusters on the
ships can boost the station while docked to the orbiting laboratory
as early as late in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Urging the White House for the funds needed for an American
propulsion module that could be launched to the station in early
2002.
</P>
<P>
   Launching an already developed U.S. ``interim control module''
to the new station sometime after the Russian service module
arrives. It was designed to meet propulsion requirements for at
least one year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
