<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-ASSEMBLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER ASSEMBLY STARTS, WITH DEBATES ON FLAGS AND LANGUAGES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ The new Northern Ireland Assembly
held its first working session Monday. But instead of dealing with
how to enact the provisions of the peace settlement reached in the
spring, the Protestant and Roman Catholic members plunged into
debates about flags, party labels, the use of Gaelic and Ulster
Scots as official languages and whether it was proper to have a bar
in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   In effect the hostilities between Protestants and Catholics were
removed from the field of sectarian violence that has plagued the
province for 30 years and taken more than 3,200 lives. With all
major paramilitary groups, including the Irish Republican Army,
observing a cease-fire, the 108 Assembly members instead jumped to
traditional and predictable arguments over cultural and political
issues that have divided the province for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Absent was debate over the serious issues of how to effect the
drastic political changes envisaged in the peace accord,
principally changes that would give the minority Catholics added
power in this predominantly Protestant British province.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Adams, president of Sinn Fein, the political wing of the
IRA, and a member of the Assembly, had said he would not sit in the
Stormont government complex because of the memories of Protestant
repression it represented for Catholics. But there he was, in a
white shirt and tie, facing political foes like the Rev. Ian
Paisley, who had vowed never to sit in a room with Adams, whom he
says is the representative of the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make friends with Dr. Paisley,'' Adams said. The
flamboyant clergyman did not reply, but neither did he perform a
dramatic walkout, as he has in the past when under fire.
</P>
<P>
   The day began with the flag-waving issue. Outside the Stormont
gates a small group of people, including children, waved signs
reading, ``Protestant Parliament for Protestant People,'' and
complained that no Union Jack was on the building.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said that the flag of the Irish Republic should be flown
along with the Union Jack and that Gaelic should be an official
language. To the consternation of some Protestant unionist
deputies, a Sinn Fein leader, Bairbre de Brun, spoke in Gaelic and
called for simultaneous translations of all Assembly speeches. A
small minority of Catholics and virtually no Protestants are fluent
in Gaelic.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who like many other republicans studied Gaelic while in a
British prison, said that in addition to voting aye or nay, members
should be allowed to vote in Gaelic, ta or nil. Protestants
responded by saying that Ulster Scots, also rarely spoken here,
should be an official language.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is similar to the Tower of Babel,'' Ian Paisley Jr. said.
``People are going to be utterly confused.''
</P>
<P>
   Paisley's father, a fundamentalist preacher and the hardline
leader of the Democratic Unionist Party, questioned the need for a
basement bar. It would be, he said, ``a bar to heaven and a door to
hell.''
</P>
<P>
   After 90 minutes of debate the temporary Assembly speaker, Lord
Alderdice, adjourned the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Feeney, a political consultant and former Belfast City
councilman, said: ``It's depressing. It doesn't take us any further
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   John Taylor, a Protestant unionist leader whom Republican
machine gunners shot in the face in 1972, made a joke about the
illegal arms being held by the IRA. He noted that a British
shooting team had won a medal at an international competition,
adding: ``I'm glad to see Mr. Adams laughing. Those were legal
firearms.''
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon of war enemies' chuckling together over old
wounds may have begun in Northern Ireland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4813 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ECON-2NDTAKE-     09-14 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ECON-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: Latin America. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The president also called for a global effort to help businesses
in Asia to emerge from ``crippling debt burdens,`` but Treasury
officials were unspecific about what kind of plan they had in mind,
saying they were not yet ready to attempt the kind of massive
restructuring of debt that the United States coordinated in Latin
America more than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech on Monday was a long time in coming: For months
now, during visits to China and then Russia, he has discussed the
impact of the financial crisis that began in Asia 14 months ago but
offered few new, major initiatives. His aides defended the seeming
slowness of his response, saying that until the economic turmoil
spread to Russia and now to Brazil _ an economy far larger than
Russia's and more directly linked to the United States _ it would
have been difficult to develop an international consensus for
action.
</P>
<P>
   It may also be difficult to develop much domestic enthusiasm in
the midst of the most perilous political moment of Clinton's
presidency. The president's plan was an attempt to return to his
old campaign theme _ ``It's the economy, stupid,'' _ with a global
twist. Implicitly, he was making the case that while Congress was
reviewing the report about his liaison with a former White House
inter, the House of Representatives was, by refusing $18 billion in
funds to the IMF, endangering the welfare of ``our workers, our
businesses, our farmers.''
</P>
<P>
   As the economic storm has moved from Asia to Russia to Latin
America, he said, ``the clouds are closer, and you can hear the
thunder.''
</P>
<P>
   But the House majority leader, Rep. Dick Armey, immediately shot
back that ``instead of repairing his credibility, the president
today dug himself into a deeper hole'' by supporting the IMF. The
Fund, he said, is ``a destabilizing force that has helped cause the
financial crises in Asia and elsewhere.'' But the Republican head
of the House Banking Committee, Rep. Jim Leach, urged the passage
of the IMF funding and even stronger action by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a dangerous time, requiring firm, bipartisan American
leadership,'' he said. ``The honor, prosperity and security of the
United States are at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech in the quiet confines of the Council on Foreign
Relations was the first major public appearance by Clinton since
the publication of the Whitewater independent counsel's explicit
recounting of the president's liaison with Monica Lewinsky, and it
was the unspoken subtext of the session.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, it was a carefully controlled event. The
invitees were members of the council, including network anchors,
Wall Street financiers, columnists and editors, and a cross-section
of foreign policy professionals. The scandal in Washington was
never far from their minds: Several members of the audience scanned
accounts of the Lewinsky affair as they waited for Clinton to
arrive. Just before he entered the room, they folded up their
papers and tucked them under their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, sat beside him, and the
president periodically placed his hand on her arm as they worked
the room. Later, she accompanied him through an afternoon of
fund-raising events and an evening at the Broadway hit, ``The Lion
King.'' Clinton did not repeat last week's string of apologies for
his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, and when a network television
reporter raised questions about the possibility of striking a deal
for censure, instead of impeachment, in Congress, the reporter was
hissed down by the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the greeting he received was somewhat cool. His
speech was never interrupted by applause, though there was
sustained applause for his Treasury secretary, Robert Rubin, when
he was introduced before the speech.
</P>
<P>
   Some in Clinton's audience, which included some former officials
in his administration, said they feared his speech may have come
too late _ both because the economic turmoil has grown so fierce,
and because Clinton's own powers appear greatly diminished.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Briefing reporters after Clinton's speech, Rubin denied that the
president was trying to pressure Alan Greenspan, the chairman of
the Federal Reserve, to cut interest rates in the United States.
``The answer to that is absolutely not,'' he said, arguing that
Clinton would not interfere with the independence of the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   What Clinton may have been doing, however, was jumping on _ and
accelerating _ a train that Greenspan got rolling 10 days ago in
San Francisco. In a speech there, Greenspan signaled that the Fed
was now less worried about inflation, and increasingly worried
about the risks of economic slowdown. Clinton invoked Greenspan's
earlier speech, declaring, as Greenspan did, that the United States
cannot consider itself ``an oasis'' from global economic forces.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Clinton and Rubin have both shied away from
characterizing the current economic turmoil as the worst since the
end of World War II _ in part for fear of jarring the markets. But
in recent weeks, the damage has become so widespread that failure
to acknowledge the scope of the problem looked increasingly
strange.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton compared the American role in stabilizing the world
economy to what ``the World War II generation did'' fifty years
ago, and said that ``the United States is called upon once again to
lead.'' But at the same time, Clinton is clearly not yet prepared
to announce the equivalent of a Marshall Plan for a global economy.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's speech, for example, he made no mention of the
possibility of dipping into U.S. funds to aid countries if the
IMF's resources are depleted, or in restructuring the World Bank
and the Fund _ created in 1946 _ to meet the challenges of a very
different world economy.
</P>
<P>
   In private, however, administration officials have begun
discussing whether it would be politically feasible to once again
use an emergency fund, under the Treasury's control, that was used
to aid Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   It is a difficult calculation. Such a step would undoubtedly
raise an uproar in Congress, at a time Clinton has no political
capital left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
