<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA GROWTH SLOWS, BUT STATE STILL NO. 2 IN NEW JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CATHERINE REAGOR  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - After several booming years, job growth is slowing as
expected in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise is that it's putting on the brakes just slightly,
and less than economists forecast it would a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona ranked No. 2, behind South Carolina and ahead of Nevada,
in the number of jobs created in June, according to the Blue Chip
Economic Forecast.
</P>
<P>
   And among large metro areas, Phoenix led the nation in creating
employment in June, posting a 5.6 percent jump in new jobs. From
June 1997 to June 1998, about 76,200 new jobs were added here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little surprising, the rate that Arizona continues to
grow,'' said Tracy Clark, senior economist of Arizona State
University's Bank One Economic Outlook Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Department of Economic Security recently reported
that the state will add 4.8 percent more payroll jobs this year
than it did last year, according to research administrator Dan
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because the Valley's real estate industry has continued to
boom, creating more jobs, and people have continued to pour into
Arizona to fill those new positions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada has outpaced Arizona in new employment during the past
few years, but Arizona and Texas are the only Western states to
beat analysts' projections for new employment this year.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the West is at the other end of the spectrum,
creating jobs at an even slower rate than projected earlier this
year by the economists who put together the monthly Blue Chip
Economic Forecast. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Catherine Reagor can be reached at catherine.reagor(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
