<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4818 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALLACE-ALABAMA-575&AMP;A     09-14 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLACE-ALABAMA-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING A LOVED _ AND HATED _ GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ For 65-year-old James Harper, sitting on his
tiny front porch in West Anniston with the day still brand-new, the
news that George Wallace was dead caused him to lower his eyes and
catch his breath for a second, as if some last, dying chorus of
``Dixie'' had lodged in his throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know,'' he said. ``You here to talk about him? Sit
down. I voted for him. Every time. I liked him standing up there in
that school door, by God,'' he said, referring to Wallace's stand
in the doorway to prevent integration at the University of Alabama
on June 11, 1963.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the federals had to move him,'' said Harper, and then he
grinned. ``He was a man, by God. He wasn't no boy.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he was asked if he still respected the former governor
after a would-be-assassin's bullet crippled him in 1972, after old
age and history mellowed him and even made him say he was sorry,
Harper seemed not to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved that man,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To many in Alabama _ the people who hated, feared or loved him _
that frail, apologetic old man who died Sunday night in Montgomery
failed to register in their memories as vividly as the young, fiery
one with slicked-back hair and rigid finger stabbing the air, the
one who promised ``segregation forever.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people said they could forgive him, and would even pray
for him, but many of them said they just wish he could have learned
he was wrong a lot sooner, and led his state out of racial hatred,
instead of into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can have my forgiveness if they ask the Lord to
forgive them,'' said 87-year-old John Lilley, making his way slowly
down Birmingham's 20th Street with the help of a cane.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did what he did to stay on the good side of the white
people. He did it to keep his job. But I forgive him.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled a little when he was asked if the pain-racked,
paralyzed man had found peace in death. ``I don't know if George
Wallace is in heaven,'' said Lilley, walking away. ``The only thing
I know is he's been in hell long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Young people, whites and blacks, know only the historical
Wallace, and spoke of him the way they would have spoken of a
Confederate statue on the courthouse lawn. But across the state,
people who are old enough to remember a time before his wheelchair
and who heard his voice before it was slurred, talk as if he was
not some distant politician in Montgomery but someone who protected
them, or threatened them. They take him personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember being at ball games and having my parents come and
get us because they had heard the Klan was coming,'' said Ernestine
Abraham, who grew up in Birmingham in the 1960s. ``He could have
changed that. He had the power, and could have turned that tide. He
didn't,'' said Ms. Abraham, now 44 and an office manager at a
Birmingham bank.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had not been hurt, he never would have changed,'' she
said. And by then, it was too late, she said, because too many
people had been hurt in the era of racism that he had prospered in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man in the chair didn't matter,'' she said. ``The young
man who stood in the schoolhouse door mattered.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess,'' she said, ``he didn't have the courage to do it,
then.''
</P>
<P>
   As she talked, the first of the rush-hour traffic was beginning
to creep through downtown Birmingham, past Kelly Ingram Park where
marchers were once torn by police dogs and blown along sidewalks
like leaves by powerful fire hoses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wallace is very personal, here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up here when you couldn't sit here, and you couldn't
eat there, and you had to sit in the last row,'' said Rita
Kendrick, 50, who works for Alabama Power in downtown Birmingham.
``He tried to keep it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   But she believes he was sorry, that it was not just politics
when he begged for forgiveness later in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a big heart to forgive him,'' she said. ``I
can, but it's hard.''
</P>
<P>
   But the people who gave him his power, families who always voted
for him and who wept when he lay bleeding on the asphalt of a
Maryland shopping center, loved him then and now.
</P>
<P>
   They loved him when he was unrepentant, because he told them to
stand up and be proud. For many of the people in his power base,
the poor farmers and factory workers who had always lived beneath
the disdain of the aristocrats, his message was stronger than
moonshine.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you'd hear him talk, you knew he was for you and for
Alabama,'' said Gary Heathcock, a 46-year-old steelworker who lives
in Alexandria. ``My daddy always voted for him,'' he said, and once
the family even voted for Wallace's wife, Lurleen. It was really a
vote for George.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them had never been told that they were even good enough
for their place in Southern society, let alone better than anyone,
and now there was this man moving from town to town on the campaign
trail preaching to the crowded auditoriums and county fairs that
they were superior to a whole race of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove trucks for 30 years, and I worked in the pipe shop,''
said James Harper of West Anniston. ``Every time I wrote him a
letter, he wrote me back. I worshipped the ground he walked on.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not, said some of his older white supporters, that they
always agreed with him. Sometimes, said 76-year-old Ed Mullinax of
Anniston, ``I had to vote for him because he was the only one
running.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a fairly good fellow who had his faults,'' said
Mullinax, a retired millwright. ``It was a different world.''
</P>
<P>
   Blacks voted for him, as early as 1958, because they saw him as
a lesser evil. Cicero Bynum, a retired steelworker from Gadsden,
remembers meeting Wallace during the 1958 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did vote for him in 1958 because I couldn't vote for John
Patterson,'' said Bynum, 69. ``He was more evil than Wallace at
that particular time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met with him when he was trying to drum up support. They
brought him in the back door of the building so the white folks
wouldn't see him coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace would repay them by claiming he lost because was
``out-niggered'' _ too soft on segregation _ and would vow never to
let it happen again.
</P>
<P>
   But in a way, said Bynum, Wallace's defiance served them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he hadn't made that stand in the schoolhouse door, we
wouldn't have come as far as we've come,'' he said. ``Our problems
wouldn't have been shown around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, aging warriors in that struggle for civil
rights graciously spoke of Wallace as a changed man, as a sort of
tragic figure who was swallowed in a whirlwind of his own creation.
Historians said he was the perfect enemy, who gave the people who
believed in change someone to hate.
</P>
<P>
   If that is true, then they needed each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``All throughout history, if you have an ugly enemy, if your
enemy is cruel and monstrous or you can paint him as a monster,''
the battle over people's conscience can be won, said the Rev.
Joseph Lowery, the past president of the Southern Christian
Leadership Council and one of the Rev. Martin Luther King's chief
aides in the 1960s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
