<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0404 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4831 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCHOOLS-1STLD     09-14 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCHOOLS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODAY'S LESSON: THE PRESIDENT'S CONDUCT 
</HEADLINE>
  (expands with optional add at 14th graf, `For any teacher...'; adds
700 words) 
(also moving in `a' category; with: CLINTON-ECON,
CLINTON-REPORT-SCENE, CLINTON-PERJURY, CLINTON-CONGRESS,
CLINTON-PASTORS, NY-CLINTON, CLINTON-LEWINSKY,
CLINTON-LEWIS-COLUMN) 
(JT) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With the Starr report very much on the minds and lips
of her seniors at the Bronx High School of Science Monday morning,
Marilyn Reinhardt opened her fourth-period literature class by
scribbling three one-word questions on the blackboard: ``Psycho?
Devil? Victim?''
</P>
<P>
   She then asked her students whether President Clinton's behavior
with Monica Lewinsky, as well as his apparent attempts to cover it
up, was most like that of the mentally unstable Reverend Dimsdale
of ``The Scarlet Letter,'' the unrepentant killer Mersault of
Albert Camus' ``The Stranger'' or Jay Gatsby, whom she
characterized as a victim of the prevailing ethos of the Roaring
Twenties, which she defined as ``get rich quick by any means, but
then no one comes to your funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   From the back of the room, one 17-year-old girl raised her hand.
``I don't think he's any of the three,'' she said. ``He's just a
man. All men cheat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's biological destiny,'' Ms. Reinhardt replied, `` `Stand
by Your Man,' as Tammy Wynette said in that song.''
</P>
<P>
   If this had been any other September, Ms. Reinhardt would have
spent the third day of the school year Monday introducing her
students to Wordsworth, Keats and Jane Austen. But after reading
the report by the Whitewater independent counsel, Kenneth Starr,
over the weekend, she _ like so many other teachers across the
country _ concluded that her original lesson plan just could not
compete.
</P>
<P>
   And so, imploring their classes to cast aside any nervous
snickers, teachers at middle schools, high schools _ and even in
the older grades of some elementary schools, based on visits to
more than a dozen schools throughout the metropolitan New York
region Monday _ wove the scandal engulfing the president into their
lesson plans, often as a way to get their students to think about
larger issues like morality or impeachment that might otherwise
have put them to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers' only dilemma, it seemed, was not whether to
discuss Clinton's troubles, but in how much detail. And even then
there was surprising latitude.
</P>
<P>
   In Kitty Rooney's 12th-grade class at Bishop Loughlin Memorial
High School in Brooklyn, the words ``sex'' and ``sexual
intercourse'' flew around the room, with little giggling. Never
mind that the subject was government and the setting was a Catholic
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the Constitution class can be formulaic and dry,'' Ms.
Rooney said afterward, ``but now the students are very interested.
It's living history.''
</P>
<P>
   As the students struggled to form opinions, many found
themselves as conflicted as their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Bascio, a social studies teacher at Public School 111 in
midtown Manhattan, asked her seventh graders to write a paragraph
about whether the president should be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, because he shouldn't of cheated on his wife,'' one girl
wrote. ``No, because it is his personal business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some,'' the student concluded, ``think he should be punished
in a different way.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For any teacher who brought up currents events Monday, the
challenge was to keep the unvarnished language of the independent
counsel's report from spilling over into class and derailing any
meaningful conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Garvey, a social studies teacher at Intermediate School
195 in Harlem, navigated between the document's seamiest sections
likes a ship's captain steering clear of icebergs.
</P>
<P>
   In his seventh-grade class Monday, he described Monica Lewinsky
only as someone who ``wanted to be the president's girlfriend.'' He
said he was careful not to give his 12- and 13-year-old students
any more knowledge than they absolutely needed, because of the wide
range of their own experiences. Some have not yet reached puberty,
while one 12-year-old girl already has had a baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a sex education teacher,'' he said. ``I'm not about to
test the limits of what is allowed in the classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   In the social studies department office at Bronx Science Monday,
the talk among teachers between periods was of how far they should
go once behind the classroom door.
</P>
<P>
   Irene Blair, who teaches government and American history, said
that questions concerning the legalities of impeachment process
would be fair game in her class but that she would swat down any
questions that bumped up against ``sexual matters.'' She intended
to direct students to ``refer it to your families.''
</P>
<P>
   But as he prepared for his fifth-period American history class,
one in which he had decided to scratch his planned lecture on
post-Civil War reconstruction, Jim Uldrych said that he intended to
put no brakes on the discussion of Starr's findings among his
seniors. ``At a certain point, you gotta discuss that, too,'' he
said, speaking of some of the president's most lewd behavior. ``You
can't run from it.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, it was his students who reined in the
discussion to keep it G-rated.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Uldrych's initial question asking for general
reaction to the report, one girl in the front row scrunched her
face in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes way too far,'' she said. ``It's like a porn novel.
It's not necessary to the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in what went on,'' she added, ``and I'm
certainly not interested in what I know now.''
</P>
<P>
   The students in Eric Plak's third grade class at Public School
192 in West Harlem never raised the names Lewinsky and Clinton. But
that's not to say they were oblivious to the names of another
couple joined in the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're more interested in McGwire and Sammy Sosa,'' Plaks
said, invoking the hallowed names of the combatants in baseball's
record-shattering home run derby. ``They're all on Sammy's side.''
</P>
<P>
   To sate them, Plaks devised a line-up card's worth of word
problems _ all about calculating home runs _ to engage them Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In other schools, the students were eager to talk but found
their teachers were unprepared to.
</P>
<P>
   After school at Hackensack (N.J.) High School Monday afternoon,
four teachers who had gathered in the English and social studies
department office said that they were horrified to learn that their
students were better versed in the report's findings than they.
While several pledged to go home and study it, Bette Parslow would
have none of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my students I did not want to read it,'' said Ms.
Parslow, who teaches U.S. history. ``I know the gist of what it is
going to say. I'm a grownup. I know what goes on. I just don't need
to wallow in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Conflicted over what exactly to say to her students, Ms. Parslow
thought she might relate her own disillusionment with Clinton by
likening it to her father's reaction upon learning, years after
Franklin D. Roosevelt's death, that he had had an affair in and
around the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents idolized him,'' she said. ``My father didn't want
to believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, for all the talking they may have done in
schools, some children left far more confused than they had arrived
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the level of knowledge of her 10-year-old son Emil,
who is in the fifth grade at R.J. Bailey School in Greenburgh,
N.Y., Geraldine Wiles said: ``He's got Tara Lipinsky and Monica
Lewinsky's names mixed up.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
