A4836 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     09-14 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A POLITICIAN'S PERSONAL BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Norbert Michael Lindner &LR; , who is married and has four
daughters, was elected in 1996 to a seven-year term as mayor of
Quellendorf, Germany. He announced this summer that he planned to
start wearing women's clothes and going by the name Michaela, in
preparation for a sex-change operation.
</P>
<P>
   A petition calling for Lindner's impeachment was signed by 175
citizens (out of a total population of 1,048), including Deputy
Mayor  &UR; Uwe Pforte &LR; , who said _ is this starting to sound familiar?
_ that the politician had lost the people's trust. ``We voted for a
man, not a woman,'' said resident  &UR; Otto Schibelius &LR;  at a city
council meeting last week. ``He should have told us beforehand.''
</P>
<P>
   Six out of eight city council members approved a November 29
referendum on the mayor's impeachment. Dissenting board member
 &UR; Erich Fosshauer &LR;  said he was ``shocked and disappointed. ... This
shows a lack of tolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONEY MAKES THE WORLD GO ROUND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Bill Gates &LR;  had $60 billion when the October issue of Vanity
Fair went to press, before the current stock market roller coaster.
That amount made him rich enough to:
</P>
<P>
   Pay the ``entire cost of the Gulf War for the U.S. and all its
allies''; buy a four-year college education for every 18-year-old
in the country; pay Habitat for Humanity to build a house for every
homeless person in the country; or use half of his money to buy
``every sports team in major league baseball, the National
Basketball Association, National Football League and National
Hockey League.''
</P>
<P>
   _ New weaponry is being used in a war created by entrepreneurial
wizards. &UR; Marsha Cohen &LR; 's Pacific Bell bill contained notice of an
option explicable only after considering history:
</P>
<P>
   Caller ID, established by the phone company, allows Jane Doe to
pay an extra amount to be aware (if she is familiar with the
number), &LR;  that the regular 6:45 p.m. call she receives is from the
Acme Metal Siding Company &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   When this extra service was established, Uncle Sam insisted that
the caller have the right to protect its privacy by giving Acme the
right to keep its number anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   Now, &LR;  the phone company says it's protecting the privacy of Jane
Doe by offering an extra $2-a-month service that will automatically
reject calls from anonymous phone numbers. ``Anonymous call
protection'' protects callees (by not letting the phone ring) from
callers protecting themselves from Caller ID, a service requested
by callees protecting themselves from unwanted callers.
</P>
<P>
   Coming next month: Anonymous callers get the option of water gun
attacks on caller ID users, $3 a month. The month after: The Caller
ID crowd gets to throw pies at the anonymous callers, $4 a month.
</P>
<P>
   _ A sign was posted in the Powell Street Muni Metro station by
an electronic panhandler: The grant-seeker identifies himself, then
says, ``I need a way to earn money to live on. Please page me at
... if you can help. I am hungry and homeless.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The official Web site of the state of Pennsylvania,
www.state.pa.us, on Wednesday started broadcasting live camera
images, shot every half hour, of the fall foliage. This could be
slow going.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Barnaby Conrad III &LR; , author of ``The Martini'' (Chronicle
Books; $24.95), sends word that Plymouth gin is once again coming
to the New World. Specified in the original recipe for the dry
martini, this ingredient has been unavailable here for more than 20
years.  &UR; Charles Rolls &LR; , head of the British company that makes
Plymouth gin, wrote Conrad that it was being reintroduced in  &LR; to
America ``in light of the almost Orwellian adulteration of martinis
with vodka, chocolate syrups and strange garnishes''; also,
although he didn't say, to make a buck in the Generation X martini
craze.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wasn't the stereotypical Yankee. I was short and
stubby, and with my catcher's mask on, I looked like Hannibal
Lecter. When I started with the Yankees, a reporter said that I
didn't even look like I was a Yankee. That comment still hurts
today. ... I'm kind of glad that reporters are not always accurate.
I really have not said everything I've said. Back to my appearance:
Lucky for me, you don't hit with your face.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The great Yankee catcher Yogi Berra in P.O.V. magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
