<HEADER>
A4842 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PASTORS-NYT &LR;      09-14 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PASTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CHOOSES TEAM OF SPIRITUAL ADVISERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Mass.)  (See also: CLINTON-ECON, CLINTON-REPORT-SCENE, CLINTON-SCHOOLS,
CLINTON-PERJURY, CLINTON-CONGRESS, NY-CLINTON, CLINTON-LEWINSKY,
CLINTON-LEWIS-COLUMN) 
(mk) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton has chosen two or perhaps three ministers to
serve as a team of personal spiritual advisers that will meet and
pray with him weekly, and help him resist what one of the ministers
called ``the temptations that have conquered'' the president in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   The president phoned the ministers and asked them for their help
on Labor Day evening, just as he and the nation were expecting
Special Prosecutor Kenneth Starr to release a report detailing the
president's affair with White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the clergymen, both formidable evangelical preachers, are
the Rev. Tony Campolo, an outspoken liberal Baptist from
Pennsylvania known for his ministry to urban youth and for
controversial books advocating Christian acceptance of
homosexuality; and the Rev. Gordon MacDonald, senior pastor of the
nondenominational Christian church, Grace Chapel, in Lexington,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   By his own account, MacDonald has faced his sin and sought
redemption. Twelve years ago, while he was president of a major
mission agency, MacDonald admitted to an extramarital affair,
resigned his position and left the ministry for almost two years.
He later wrote a book, ``Rebuilding Your Broken World,'' about his
experience.
</P>
<P>
   That book, which the president told MacDonald he has has read
twice, is one of the reasons the president selected MacDonald for
spiritual guidance, MacDonald said in a sermon to his congregation
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Since admitting to his affair with a White House intern, Clinton
has been struggling to persuade the American people that he
seriously regrets his actions and is taking steps to repent and
reform. Both ministers were defensive about the possible appearance
that Clinton had selected them as part of political damage control.
</P>
<P>
   According to Campolo, ``There are those who will say that Gordon
and I are being used and manipulated. Should this be true,it would
not be the first time that Christians have been taken in. But we
would rather be men of faith who believe that God is working in the
life of the president, than to join that army of cynics, many of
whom are religious leaders who cannot accept a plea for forgiveness
at face value.''
</P>
<P>
   Any publicity about Clinton's arrangement with the ministers is
also likely to suit the White House's need to persuade the public
that president Clinton has come to grips with the gravity of his
wrongdoing and is taking steps to repent and reform.
</P>
<P>
   Such informal ``accountability circles,'' usually held in utmost
privacy, are not uncommon among Christian evangelicals, and
particularly among leaders of large churches and organizations. Men
_ and it is most often men _ meet regularly with a small group of
peers to pray and provide support. Such a circle of three men,
named by the elders of Grace Chapel, met with MacDonald weekly
after he confessed his adulterous relationship, and eventually
helped restore him to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bring an understanding of what it is like to face the public
scrutiny when one has sinned,'' MacDonald said in his sermon. ``I
have gone through, and continue to go through, the breaking
process. I have known both the remarkable grace of forgiving,
restorative people and the lash of those who choose other options.
I am in a position to talk the language of repentance and what it
takes to find a deeper and more purposeful walk with God in the
midst of a personal tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
