<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAN-AFGHANISTAN-590&AMP;     09-14 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-AFGHANISTAN-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAN HINTS AT READINESS TO USE MILITARY FORCE AGAINST AFGHANISTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ Iran on Monday issued its strongest threat yet
that it might use military force against Afghanistan unless the
militant Taliban movement in power there makes amends for ``past
errors'' and adopts a more conciliatory course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have so far prevented the lighting of a fire in this region
which would be hard to extinguish,'' the country's supreme leader,
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, said in a statement read in stern and
solemn tones on Iranian television. ``But all should know that a
very great and wide danger is quite near.''
</P>
<P>
   Iran's army command quickly followed with a statement announcing
that its 500,000 troops were at ``full preparedness to implement
the leader's orders and to conduct any mission anywhere and under
any conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   After more than a month of tension inflamed by the killing of
nine Iranian diplomats in Afghanistan, the warnings appeared
intended to send a message that Iran's patience was wearing thin.
</P>
<P>
   Iran has built up its military forces along the Afghan border,
and has appealed in vain for international help in reining in the
Taliban's military advances.
</P>
<P>
   Iran's harsh public words were moderated somewhat by private
signals suggesting that no action is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Resident diplomats from Britain, France, Russia and China were
summoned to Iran's Foreign Ministry on Monday to hear what one
participant described as a pledge that Iran is determined to
exhaust all diplomatic alternatives before resorting to force in
what is emerging as a showdown with the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, Iranian officials made clear Monday
their view that the crisis has assumed a new urgency with the
capture by the Taliban on Sunday of Bamiyan, the last major city
held by an opposition force Iran had provided with clandestine
military support.
</P>
<P>
   International human rights groups have said that Taliban forces
may have killed thousands of civilians, most of them Shiite
Muslims, after taking control last month of Mazar-i-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
   And though Taliban officials have pledged that civilians in
Bamiyan would not be harmed, U.N. officials said they were
``extremely concerned'' about the situation, and Iranian media
reports suggested that a wave of Taliban reprisals may have already
begun.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Iran's representative at the United Nations, Mohammad
Hadi Nejad-Hosseinian, met with Secretary-General Kofi Annan to
urge that the United Nations ``promptly and resolutely react'' to
avert what the Iranian warned could be killings on an even broader
scale.
</P>
<P>
   And in his statement Monday, Ayatollah Khamenei delivered a
fervent appeal that he addressed in particular to other Muslim
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not let thousands of Afghanistan's disinherited people
become victims of the Taliban's mischief,'' he said. ``Do not allow
the religious war and blood-letting carried out by this ignorant,
backward and cruel group in Afghanistan to spread _ God forbid _ to
other parts of the Islamic world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Afghan Islamic Press, an independent news agency, quoted
Taliban spokesmen as saying Monday that the people of Bamiyan were
``voluntarily surrendering their weapons'' to the militia in
house-to-house searches aimed at confiscating guns.
</P>
<P>
   Iran, with its Shiite Muslim majority, has long looked askance
at the Taliban, extremist followers of a purist version of Islam's
dominant Sunni faith. Neither group regards the other as true
Muslims, and that suspicion has long spilled over into rivalry,
with Iran an important backer of the Taliban's opponents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But it has only been in the last month, with the deaths of the
Iranian diplomats and with Taliban gains that have put the movement
in control of nearly all of Afghanistan, that Iran's opposition has
hardened into a military buildup and explicit threats.
</P>
<P>
   Some 70,000 Iranian Revolutionary Guards have been deployed near
the Afghan border since they carried out military exercises that
ended last week, and an additional 200,000 army troops are to take
part in a second round of war games in the border area later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a month of saying that they had no information
about 11 Iranian diplomats missing in Afghanistan, Taliban
officials admitted last week that ``either intentionally or
unintentionally'' Taliban forces had killed at least nine of the
diplomats when the Iranian consulate in Mazar-i-Sharif was overrun.
</P>
<P>
   Iranian officials have said that a crisis with Afghanistan could
be averted, but only if the Taliban responded favorably to a series
of Iranian demands.
</P>
<P>
   Some progress apparently was made Monday on one of the demands,
that the bodies of the dead diplomats be returned. Iranian
officials and representatives of the International Committee for
the Red Cross were permitted by the Taliban to land in
Mazar-i-Sharif on Monday, and Iranian television said they carried
the bodies of at least seven Iranian diplomats back to Teheran
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The television report said that Taliban officials had presented
the delegation with nine bodies, the number they claimed to have
recovered last week, but that only seven of them had been
identified as Iranian.
</P>
<P>
   In other areas, however, the two sides appear perilously far
apart. The Taliban leader, Mullah Mohammed Omar, has been quoted by
the Afghan press as saying that he was not sorry that the diplomats
had been killed, rebuffing Iranian demands for an apology. Taliban
officials have refused an Iranian demand that those who killed the
diplomats be surrendered to Iran for trial here.
</P>
<P>
   They have said that as many as 45 Iranians now in Taliban
custody would not be returned outright, as Iran has demanded, but
only as part of an prisoner exchange with Iranian-backed militia
groups.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks Monday, Ayatollah Khamenei said that a wider
regional conflict could be prevented only ``by obliging the leaders
of the Taliban group to submit to logic, to abandon actions which
lead to a catastrophe and to make up for their past errors.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also upped the ante by calling for an end to Pakistani
military intervention in Afghanistan on behalf of the Taliban, a
role that Pakistan has steadfastly denied. Ayatollah Khamenei
warned that Iranians who have spent the last three days mourning
the deaths of the diplomats were ``impatiently waiting for
decisions by state officials with a heart full of pain and anger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
