<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4849 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRADA-STORE-FASHION-A     09-14 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRADA-STORE-FASHION-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE A PRIVATE CLUB, PRADA OPENS ITS DOOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(JT) 
 By CONSTANCE C.R. WHITE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patrizio Bertelli, the chairman of Prada, stood on
Fifth Avenue before the smooth stone facade of his new store. His
face was alight with the idea that the company he and his wife, the
designer Miuccia Prada, had steered into the loftiest realms of
fashion is reaching downward to one of the most populist venues _
Fifth Avenue _ where the dreams of a diamond Tiffany engagement
ring and the reality of a Bugs Bunny T-shirt meet.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could be more emblematic of Prada's grab for broad
acceptance than the opening of its large, four-level store on
Saturday at 724 Fifth Avenue (56th Street). ``When you're on
Madison Avenue you're in Manhattan; when you're on Fifth Avenue,
you're in America,'' Bertelli said. ``It's a special feeling. It's
a step in our history. It will help establish the brand more in the
American market.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan Bertelli and Ms. Prada have in mind is to reach a wider
audience than Prada is used to, while maintaining the brand's
considerable cachet. They seek to interest hoi polloi in a look
that has been the uniform of a strict, private club whose members
dress in expensive stark, black uniforms and whose insignia is a
discreet black and silver triangular badge adorning futuristic
nylon bags.
</P>
<P>
   It will not be an easy task. Expanding downward in fashion is
not unusual, and several companies like Calvin Klein, Giorgio
Armani and Ralph Lauren have done so successfully. But others _ the
Gucci of 10 years ago, Halston and Pierre Cardin _ have failed.
Cardin's fall 1998 men's show in Paris in July was an embarrassing
parade of accessory and clothing trinkets from a man who was once
an undisputed innovator.
</P>
<P>
   Bertelli and Ms. Prada think the time is right to push Prada
beyond cult status, because of strong sales, which are projected to
grow from $850 million worldwide this year to $950 million in 1999,
Bertelli said. The company is privately held, and last year,
profits reached approximately $100 million, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The new Fifth Avenue store, which has 16,000 square feet, is
only part of a broad expansion in the United States that includes a
smaller Prada Sport store at 116 Wooster St. in SoHo, Prada's
fourth in Manhattan; it is scheduled to open at the end of this
month. In July, the company opened a men's store on Rodeo Drive in
Beverly Hills, and there are plans for stores in the new Bellagio
casino-hotel in Las Vegas for October, and in Chicago for January
1999. The company's United States flagship, opened last year at 841
Madison Ave. (70th Street), is still the largest of its 98 stores
worldwide, with 18,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   To make Prada as accessible as Ralph Lauren, for instance,
Bertelli and Ms. Prada will put most of their emphasis on their
less expensive collections _ Prada Sport and Miu Miu, a youthful
line bearing Ms. Prada's nickname. Clothes in both collections cost
45 percent to 50 percent less than those of the top collection. Miu
Miu men's wear is to be introduced on the runway in February for
fall 1999, Bertelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Prada Sport is being positioned as a stand-alone collection. The
SoHo store, the first to sell Prada Sport exclusively, will appeal
on the basis of lower prices and a lower fashion bar than Ms. Prada
requires customers to hurl themselves over when buying her top
line. Easy-fitting anoraks, lightweight wind pants, simple tops in
colorful sports-inspired fabrics are meant to be accessible and
versatile.
</P>
<P>
   Some retail analysts questioned Prada's latest strategy. ``It's
easy volume to add these secondary lines and tertiary labels, but
let's not forget Gucci in the '80s,'' said Isaac Lagnado, president
of Tactical Retail Solutions, a market research company. ``When
your secretary starts wearing a derivative label of yours if you're
an executive at Morgan Stanley, do you really want that? Ralph can
get away with it, but I'm not sure it has been without cost.''
</P>
<P>
   And he added: ``It might be a touch late for them to be
expanding in the U.S. market. They have focused on international
expansion and they are very exposed in the Far East.''
</P>
<P>
   Bertelli revealed that Prada has suffered losses of up to 33
percent in some parts of Asia, but these have been offset by gains
in the Japanese market, as the Japanese travel less and buy more at
home.
</P>
<P>
   In Bertelli's and Ms. Prada's eyes, some of the risk inherent in
trying to appeal to a broader swath of customers can be nullified
by focusing on youth. ``A wider group of people, and even more
young people, are increasingly understanding design in clothing,''
Ms. Prada said.
</P>
<P>
   Young people today, Bertelli added, have a very different
attitude to dressing than they did in the '80s. ``It's not
necessary to wear sports things for a sports use,'' he said. The
Sport line, said Bertelli, who is entering a yacht in the America's
Cup competition, is not simply an active-wear line. ``It may become
a very popular or mass product, though that's not what it started
out as,'' he continued. ``It was for our customers to wear in their
leisure time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not elitist,'' he added, speaking of himself and his
wife. ``We like sophisticated things in fashion and in art, but
that's why we like young people, because they are the ones that
bring up new ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   As it expands, the company intends to keep tight control over
distribution of its clothes, which means owning nearly all of its
stores. Although franchising was popular with designer companies
seeking to expand in the late '70s and '80s, it fell from favor as
the designer business began to shrink, hot designers demanded
higher licensing fees and old names became less desirable. ``It's
so beautiful in the beginning,'' Bertelli said of the relationship
between franchiser and franchisee. ``Then it becomes a source of
conflict. All the major brands _ Armani, Versace, Gucci _ had to
buy back their franchised stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Bertelli's determination to keep a viselike grip on distribution
led to Prada's recent unceremonious exit from Bergdorf Goodman.
``It's their attitude that I didn't like,'' the Prada chairman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bergdorf executives would not comment on the situation directly.
They issued a statement pointing to the many boutiques like Chanel
and Gucci that exist a stone's throw from the store, yet enjoy good
business in Bergdorf's.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Selling its clothes and accessories in its own stores does allow
Prada to keep control of the message of understated luxury that it
seeks to telegraph to the customer. An in-house team of architects
and designers in Italy worked on the new store, which features
interior walls of pistachio green, a Prada signature, and huge
plate glass walls looking onto Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, cashmere sweaters and clean leather bags are displayed
gallery-like on glass shelves and in rectangular cubbies. The store
carries Prada women's and men's lines, accessories and Prada Sport.
</P>
<P>
   No one familiar with the trajectory that has rocketed Prada to
the forefront of fashion would have thought that expansion into the
mass market would be its ultimate fate. Prada fashion has
communicated membership in a cool, secretly knowing and affluent
society, however pretentious that may sound. Since reviving the
family leather-accessories business with her nylon backpack in the
late '80s, Ms. Prada has denoted a new, tacit badge of success in a
world used to the showiness of Chanel. And just when that idea was
settling in in the early '90s, she proposed an equally startling
concept _ trailer-trash prints as high fashion, which challenged
good taste.
</P>
<P>
   In many regards, her brand has more in common with respected
labels of limited appeal like Comme des Garcons, Jean Colonna and
Issey Miyake than with more commercial lines like Armani, Gucci and
Chanel. But in her black nylon backpack, Ms. Prada found the edge
that could cut through to every level of consumer. In a sense,
Prada's real challenge now is to find the sequel to black nylon,
which has acquired the stature of a commodity.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 percent of Prada's business is done in black nylon
clothes and accessories, Bertelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Prada said: ``Black nylon became a basic, so diffused in
real life that we do not distinguish ours from the rest anymore. It
was a moment in my work. I think that it is helpful because it
taught me something important: Good design in fashion has to be
real, influencing the real way of dressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost half of Prada's sales come from accessories, 16 percent
from shoes, and the remainder, about 27 percent, from
ready-to-wear, Bertelli said. The women's business is almost double
that of the men's.
</P>
<P>
   Prada is a third-generation company, but the seeds of its
present form were planted in 1978 when Ms. Prada, who was once a
member of the Italian Communist Party, met Bertelli as a client at
one of his factories. They married in 1987 and went into business
together with Prada and its subsidiary, IPI _ I Pellettieri
d'Italia.
</P>
<P>
   The same factories still make Prada bags, but now both the
factories and the product are owned by the couple.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding beyond Prada itself, Bertelli shook the fashion world
earlier this year by acquiring 9.5 percent of the stock of an
archrival, Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   The current Asian crisis and Gucci's subsequent stock slide
would seem to give him cause to question his move, but Bertelli
remains cool on the surface. ``I have no particular feeling about
it,'' he said. ``The drop in stock is no big deal. It's not
necessarily a total picture of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Although speculation about his motives was furious at the time
of the stock purchases, he has not moved since then to increase his
holdings. In an interview last week, he said, ``Because it's a
publicly traded company, whatever we think or say may have an
effect on its market performance.'' At the very least, the move may
go down as a brilliant strategy to rock the psychic calm of a major
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   But with their current Prada expansion, Bertelli and Ms. Prada
have other concerns closer to home to worry about as they attempt
the high-wire act of staying aloft even as they swoop down to
capture the attention of a wider fashion audience.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
