<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIAN DEMONSTRATORS OPPOSE MILITARY'S ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Pressing the government to take important
powers away from the military, nearly 200 students staged a sit-in
at one of the Indonesian capital's busiest thoroughfares.
</P>
<P>
   In their second week of demonstrations, the protesters called
for an end to the armed forces' role in the nation's political
affairs. The issue has galvanized students from around the country.
</P>
<P>
   In a scene that would have been unimaginable several months ago,
heavily armed soldiers stood by and listened as a group of
university students lashed out at a tenet held sacred by the
military: its dual function, which gives the military legal powers
to take part in politics as well as in defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The involvement of the military in civilian matters has done
nothing but cause damage to the people and is in conflict with
democracy,'' the student group said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian military has come under increasing scrutiny since
the resignation in May of former President Suharto, whose absolute
control over the armed forces helped him to maintain power for 32
years.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging evidence of the military's kidnapping and torture of
political dissidents during the Suharto years has outraged the
public. Human rights groups have called for investigations into the
atrocities that they believe claimed thousands of lives.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty International announced Monday that it had been invited
last week to meet with the Indonesian government and military in a
gesture not seen in five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually do believe that there is an openness here that has
never been here before,'' Kerry Brogan, of Amnesty International,
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   President B.J. Habibie has vowed to review the role of the
military and to investigate the rights abuses alleged to have taken
place under his predecessor and longtime associate, Suharto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
