<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4862 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLITZ-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-14 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLITZ-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET READY, CONSUMERS: HERE COME THOSE ANNUAL AD BLITZES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The week after Labor Day always brings a torrent of
advertising intended to stimulate consumers to step up their
shopping during the important fourth quarter. True to form, several
big advertisers in categories from retailing to media to packaged
goods are beginning multimillion-dollar marketing blitzes.
</P>
<P>
   Banana Republic, the upscale retail chain owned by Gap Inc., is
undertaking what it calls its first television campaign ever. The
commercials, which will appear in Chicago, Los Angeles, New York
and San Francisco, promote new suede merchandise and a 98-page fall
catalog of apparel and home furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television as a medium is a very powerful way to evoke how
people feel about the Banana brand,'' Amy Schoening, vice president
for marketing at Banana Republic in San Francisco, said in a
telephone interview Monday. ``This felt like the right time to go
out and do it big.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no coincidence that the campaign, created in-house, comes
after Gap Inc. spent heavily on splashy television commercials for
its two other chains, Gap and Old Navy. Sales at both have
increased since those spots began running.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being in the same company, it's hard for that not to be
contagious,'' Ms. Schoening said.
</P>
<P>
   Banana Republic's five eclectic, fast-paced commercials all
feature soundtracks with Nina Simone warbling a jazzy version of
``Feeling Good.''
</P>
<P>
   Interspersed with shots of stylish consumers cavorting in suede
outfits are unconventional images that range from a map of the
Ponderosa as seen in the opening credits of the old television
series ``Bonanza'' to a black-and-white clip of a saxophone player
to glimpses of the Manhattan skyline.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're trying to say is there's a sensuality and yet
there's fun,'' Ms. Schoening said. ``We don't take ourselves too
seriously, which fashion can tend to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the commercials and the catalog, there will be
print advertisements in national magazines, billboards and posters.
Ms. Schoening declined to specify spending other than to say that
the budget would be 350 percent more than what was spent last fall;
according to the Competitive Media Reporting unit of VNU N.V.,
Banana Republic spent $2.6 million from September through December
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to another campaign, the Discover Card is changing ads
for the first time in two and a half years as DDB Needham Chicago,
a unit of Omnicom Group, introduces a comprehensive campaign
carrying the theme ``Discover the feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, which starts with television commercials on
Thursday night, is meant to imbue the credit card with a warmer,
more emotional image than had been imparted in recent ads centered
on such celebrities as John Lithgow, Trisha Yearwood and Gregory
Hines.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do like to buy things,'' said Lisa Lampert, senior vice
president for marketing at the Discover Card unit of Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter &AMP; Co. in Riverwoods, Ill. ``The goal is to capture the
positive feeling about making special purchases.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lampert discussed the company's plans in an interview after
a news conference Monday morning in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The category is obviously very cluttered and competitive,''
she said, alluding to Discover Card rivals like American Express,
Mastercard and Visa, which have all intensified their marketing
efforts. ``This cuts through the sea of confusion to provide
logical and emotional reasons for using Discover.''
</P>
<P>
   Each spot depicts an average consumer making a typical purchase
with a Discover Card, which transforms the transaction into an
extraordinary event.
</P>
<P>
   In one spot, there is a star-spangled parade at an FAO Schwarz
toy store; in another, a clerk turns into an angel.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign also includes magazine and Internet ads,
billboards, radio commercials and unusual vehicles like ads on gas
pump handles. Promotional tie-ins include agreements with the
Universal Studios unit of the Seagram Co., the Anheuser-Busch
Adventure Parks and the Times Square 2000 organization coordinating
the celebration of New Year's Eve on Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Spending will be increased from last year, Ms. Lampert said, but
she declined to discuss details. Discover Card spent $77.4 million
on advertising in 1997, according to Competitive Media Reporting.
</P>
<P>
   A third big campaign in the works is for the ABC television
network, which is owned by the Walt Disney Co. A series of
promotional commercials that will feature stars of ABC series will
be presented at a news conference Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The commercials will start appearing next week as the network
introduces its 1998-99 prime-time schedule. The spots offer photo
montages of such ABC personalities as Tim Allen, Drew Carey, Jenna
Elfman, Michael J. Fox and Dylan McDermott.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the commercials are not being created by the TBWA
Chiat/Day unit of Omnicom in Playa del Rey, Calif., which is
responsible for the familiar promotional campaigns for ABC that are
centered on the color yellow and carry such fanciful themes as ``TV
is good'' and ``We love TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather, they are being created by Pittard Sullivan in Culver
City, Calif., which specializes in media and entertainment brand
campaigns, credits for television series and promotional spots for
networks including CBS and the Nickelodeon unit of Viacom Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Sewell, a spokeswoman for ABC in New York, confirmed a
report about the Pittard Sullivan campaign that appeared in The
Daily News. The star-oriented spots are meant to complement the
TBWA Chiat/Day campaign, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Two other big campaigns began on Sunday during the NBC broadcast
of the 50th annual Emmy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   One was a brand image campaign for the Kraft Foods unit of the
Philip Morris Co. by the J. Walter Thompson Chicago unit of WPP
Group PLC. The $50 million campaign, intended to show how families
are brought together by cooking and eating at home, carries the
theme ``Let's make something good.''
</P>
<P>
   The other was a revamped version of a long-running campaign for
Sears, Roebuck by Young &AMP; Rubicam Advertising in New York. The
commercials retain the theme ``Come see the softer side of Sears,''
but add humorous elements like footage of long-ago fashions to urge
women to ``take another look'' because ``surprise, surprise,
there's so much more'' than they may expect from apparel sold at
Sears stores.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
