A4867 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS &LR;      09-14 1151
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE COULD VOTE NEXT WEEK ON RESOLUTION FOR IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
and BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House could vote as early as this week on a
resolution laying out the scope of an impeachment inquiry against
President Clinton, Republican sources said Monday. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The resolution would cover the kind of subpoena authority and
other powers the Judiciary Committee would have if lawmakers decide
to hold hearings on independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report
about the president's relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   It appears inevitable that before leaving on Oct. 9 for fall
campaigning, the House will vote to conduct an impeachment
investigation on 11 charges suggested by Starr, ranging from
perjury to obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see a vote very shortly that will determine
what powers the judiciary committee and the chairman will have to
compel witnesses to testify,'' said panel member Lamar Smith, R-San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and other members of the committee spent Monday afternoon
in a heavily guarded room in the Ford House annex building
reviewing some of the 2,000 pages of supporting documents and
evidence supplied by Starr, including a videotape of Clinton's Aug.
17 testimony to a federal grand jury in which he acknowledged for
the first time an ``inappropriate'' relationship with the former
White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The House is expected to release more of Starr's material on
Sept. 28.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Republican and Democratic members of the
judiciary committee are jousting behind the scenes over how to
handle the inquiry and what kind of powers will be granted to
committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., and ranking Democrat John
Conyers of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde has promised a bipartisan process, and has hinted at
sharing responsibilities with Conyers. But the two are reportedly
already at odds over whether they should have joint subpoena powers
or whether the chairman should have sole authority to force
testimony from uncooperative witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans indicated Hyde will meet with Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., and other members of the leadership team on
Wednesday to iron out the details.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats are also scrapping over whether the
committee should have the authority to raise other issues in the
hearings, including the Whitewater land deal, which was the basis
for Starr's original investigation of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes no sense to me that we would even think of giving
singular or unilateral powers to any chairman without the
cooperative and co-sharing power of the ranking member,'' said Rep.
Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Houston, who also serves on the Judiciary
Committee. ``This has to be a process above reproach.''
</P>
<P>
   There appeared to be a consensus among lawmakers that
impeachment hearings would not begin until after the Nov. 3
election.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional aides were already at work Monday on language to
be placed in the resolution ending the session next month that
would allow the Judiciary Committee to continue meeting through the
fall. It will also provide for the recall of Congress if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country wants this over with,'' said Hyde spokesman Sam,
Strathman. ``It is not fair to the president that it be stretched
out any longer than necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic congressional leaders agreed on the need for speedy
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sooner this crisis can be resolved the sooner we can turn
our full energies to the promise of our policy agenda,'' House
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt said in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Democrat also warned the White House that the legal
strategy of trying to convince members the president did not commit
perjury when he denied having sex with Lewinsky may not be the
wisest approach to impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The considered judgement of the American people is not going
to rise and fall on the fine distinctions of a legal argument, but
on straight talk and the truth,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., issued a
strong rebuke to the White House for trying to argue that
technically the president didn't not lie in his original court
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a basic understanding of the standard of truthfulness
that the president failed to meet,'' Daschle said. ``The president
and his advisers must accept that continued legal jousting serves
no constructive purpose. It simply stands in the way of what we
need to do: move forward and let common sense guide us in doing
what is best for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt and Daschle joined the president and first lady in New
York Monday for a series of party fund-raising events.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., and a Clinton critic, left a
luncheon event before Clinton spoke. Kerrey chairs a committee of
senators trying to elect more Democrats to the upper chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons and Vice President Al Gore later attended a
fund-raising dinner and a special theatrical presentation of ``The
Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton thanked the Democrats who gave him a warm welcome. ``For
Hillary and for me just your presence here, your enthusiasm and
personal support mean more than you will ever know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Polls continue to indicate that most Americans oppose removing
the president from office, despite increasing calls by media
outlets and lawmakers for his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   A USA Today/CNN Gallup poll released Monday found that two out
of three people surveyed say the president should not be impeached.
The poll, conducted over the weekend, found that 64 percent of
respondents approved of the job the president is doing, slightly
higher than before the Starr report was released.
</P>
<P>
   However, the survey also indicated that the public holds an
increasingly dim view of the president personally. For example, a
majority of those surveyed said they did not respect Clinton and
disapprove of the way he has handled the current controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Polls taken by the Washington Post, Los Angeles Times and the
major networks found similar sentiments. But those who want Clinton
to resign or be impeached are loudly making their views known.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said that his office has logged more than 1,000 phone
calls from constituents in San Antonio about the Starr report, with
90 percent demanding the president's resignation or impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the concern of their constituents, two more
Republicans joined in the calls for Clinton's resignation Monday.
Rep. Greg Ganske, a moderate Republican from Iowa, and House Budget
Committee Chairman John Kasich, R-Ohio, who is considering a run
for the presidency in 2000, both joined the resignation chorus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has brought dishonor on himself, the office of
the presidency, and our country,'' Ganske said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
