u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     09-14 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
So does this mean that Sammy gets a '62 Corvette, all shiny and
blue? Or do the Cubs wait to make it a '63, '64, '65 or even a '70,
figuring they'll get a better deal on a later model along with
accuracy?
</P>
<P>
   And just what were Buzz Aldrin's words when he stepped off that
ladder and became the second man on the moon?
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa took two not-so-small (480-foot) steps on Sunday at
Wrigley Field and one giant leap back into the home-run race.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just when we thought it was safe to put away all the
flowery language that is often used to describe any big event in
baseball, here we go again, reaching for the poetry books.
</P>
<P>
   Roses are red, violets are blue. Watch out Big Mac, mon, Ah'm a
comin' after you.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it's chasing history with a calypso beat as the
smiling slugger from San Pedro de Macoris in the Dominican Republic
swings for the fences and his own Juanny-come-lately spot in the
Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Babe Ruth's record lasted 34 years. Roger Maris' record stood
for 37. Mark McGwire had the pedestal to himself for, oh, five
days.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not the geniuses of Major League Baseball who
apparently declared the race over when McGwire slugged No. 62 on
Sept. 8, with nearly three full weeks left in the season.
</P>
<P>
   As Sosa launched homers 61 and 62 onto Waveland Avenue,
commissioner-lite Bud Selig was conspicuously absent from the box
seats along the first-base line. So, too, was barnacle Bobby
Costas, TV's self-proclaimed keeper of the sacred baseball flame.
</P>
<P>
   No high-fives from opponents as he rounded the bases. No media
flock.
</P>
<P>
   There were no infrared markings on the baseballs, and No. 62 was
reportedly caught by a guy named Moe, who was promptly bitten on
the hand and beaten in a mad scramble and had it wrested away.
</P>
<P>
   How fitting.
</P>
<P>
   While McGwire's pursuit of Ruth and Maris was held in reverence
and awe, Sosa has spent the summer joyously dancing behind him, a
conga line in the shadows.
</P>
<P>
   And it seems that is the way most baseball fans outside of the
Dominican Republic wanted it. Remember, in polls taken two weeks
ago, 79 percent of Americans said they were rooting for Big Mac to
break the record compared to only 16 percent for Sosa.
</P>
<P>
   Is there the slightest tinge of a racial element there? One can
only wonder if Sosa would have been perceived differently all
season long if he were white and spoke flawless English.
</P>
<P>
   It is also possible that McGwire was the challenger of
preference to break the greatest of all American sports records
simply because he has the track record and looks more like a
home-run hitter. If somebody was going to pass Babe Ruth _ and to
many, Ruth's 60 was still the benchmark _ then it would certainly
help if that man seemed Ruthian in stature. And there is Big Mac,
Bunyanesque, like he just rode into town on the blue ox.
</P>
<P>
   But we can ponder whether McGwire would have been able to reach
the historic level without Sosa always there nipping at his heels.
Was it purely a coincidence that every time Slammin' Sammy would
sneak up into a tie or even take the lead, Big Mac came right back
with a couple of homers?
</P>
<P>
   And wasn't it Sosa, with his carefree, let's-enjoy-the-moment
attitude, who finally got McGwire to loosen up over the past month
of the record chase and who made last Tuesday night at Busch
Stadium so special with his happy hug and display of sportsmanship?
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the horse-track announcer says, down the stretch they
come, looking like Affirmed and Alydar in any one of the Triple
Crown races. This is Bird and Magic going one-on-one. It is Ali and
Frazier fighting for survival.
</P>
<P>
   Who gets the edge?
</P>
<P>
   Well, McGwire hasn't hit one out since breaking the record. He
left the Astrodome bothered by back spasms but may also be
suffering from an expected mental letdown following the big event.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire seems sapped. Sosa looks enervated. He and the Cubs also
have the electricity of the wild-card race to provide a charge.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to crank up the circus again. The Dominican Destroyer
is still hitting jonrons.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to put the special markings on the baseballs. And just
to make things right, as with the Maris sons on hand for Big Mac's
historic night, couldn't somebody at least ask the chubby little
McGwire kid to sit in the front row and watch Slammin' Sammy break
his dad's record?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2051EDT &QL; 
