<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-MCBRIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICAN OFFICIAL FREED FROM PRISON IN MOZAMBIQUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ A South African Foreign Ministry
official was released from a prison in Mozambique on Monday, six
months after he was arrested at a border town there and said to be
carrying thousands of dollars and trying to buy a cache of assault
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But what exactly he was doing remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Robert McBride, a famous anti-apartheid guerrilla, left the
prison with his wife, Paula, and returned to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   After landing at Johannesburg Airport, McBride said he had been
falsely implicated on charges of gun-running in Mozambique and that
he knew who had set him up. He said he was ready to reveal their
names ``to the relevant people.''
</P>
<P>
   McBride, who was involved in blowing up a crowded bar in Durban
in 1986 as a member of the armed wing of South Africa's ANC party,
was a high-level Foreign Ministry official last March when he went
to Maputo, Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
   McBride said he was investigating arms trafficking, trying to
track down who had been involved in supplying high-powered weapons
used in attacks on cash-carrying armored vehicles in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   But the government has repeatedly distanced itself from him,
saying that he was not on official business and that the law must
take its course.
</P>
<P>
   McBride has been suspended from his job and on Sunday night a
spokesman for the Foreign Ministry, Marco Boni, said he could not
comment on McBride's release.
</P>
<P>
   Theories on what McBride was really doing have varied widely.
Some people have suggested that he was buying arms for the East
Timorese guerrilla movement. Others believe he may have been
stocking up on weapons for former anti-apartheid guerrillas now
involved in illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters believe he was set up by right-wing elements in
the security forces. Soon after McBride's arrest, President Nelson
Mandela disclosed that he had received a report from the chief of
the army, Georg Meiring, linking McBride, several army generals and
the president's former wife, Winnie Madikizela-Mandela, to a plot
to overthrow the government.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela said he believed the report was a hoax and a hastily
formed commission of inquiry soon agreed, though it said that
certain elements of the report needed further checking. Meiring
eventually retired early because of the incident. But relations
between government officials and McBride did not seem to warm.
</P>
<P>
   McBride has been charged in Mozambique with gun-running and
spying and a lower court judge has ruled there is enough evidence
to go to trial. Monday's ruling by a higher court allows McBride
bail while he appeals the lower court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   During the struggle against apartheid McBride was sentenced to
death, later commuted to life imprisonment, for a bomb attack on a
bar in which three women were killed in June 1986. He was released
by former President F.W. de Klerk, along with many other political
prisoners during the last days of apartheid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4880 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECON-NYT &LR;      09-14 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORBACHEV'S ADVISERS MAKE COMEBACK IN TIME OF CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Summoned back from a decade of obscurity, a group of
Gorbachev-era economists on Monday stood outside the gates of the
Russian government building, awaiting their turn to give advice on
how to rescue a floundering economy.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, these men were the talking heads of
`Perestroika,' the name given to reforms launched by then-Soviet
President Mikhail Gorbachev _ which in due course, led to the
collapse of communism and the end of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, they joined the alumni of Gorbachev's varsity squad
who find themselves back at the center of Russia's economic policy
debate. Russia's new prime minister, a top economic aide and the
new head of the central bank all served under Gorbachev.
</P>
<P>
   That the Russian government sought the help on Monday of so many
Gorbachev economists was a sign of the dearth of new ideas to save
Russia's economy. It was also a telling symbol of how last week's
political showdown has humbled President Boris Yeltsin.
Paradoxically, Yeltsin won the affections of Russian voters in 1991
by attacking Gorbachev's feeble efforts at economic reform, and by
extension the economists behind perestroika.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it is Yeltsin's team of young liberal economists who
are under attack for having shortchanged the Russian people by
clinging to free-market theories that have yet to take root here.
</P>
<P>
   Looking reinvigorated, if a bit rumpled, in the bright autumn
sunshine, the reassembled team measured their words carefully as
they waited for an escort to take them into a meeting with Prime
Minister Yevgeni Primakov's top deputy for economic affairs, Yuri
Maslyukov, a Communist.
</P>
<P>
   Among them were three top advisers to Gorbachev, Leonid Abalkin,
Nikolai Petrakov and Oleg Bogomolov.
</P>
<P>
   Their glee at having survived to see their services back in
demand was evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there is hope for a more realistic policy,'' said
Bogomolov, director of the Institute for Internal Economic and
Political Studies. ``Now it is not just one side that can express
their ideas, like our liberal radical economists. We are all in
favor of reforms, but not reforms for their own sake, but reforms
which serve people.''
</P>
<P>
   Primakov's government has yet to fix a clear economic policy to
pull Russia out of its crisis, but his choice of advisers has sent
strong signals that his approach will be a throwback to another
era, when economists tried to introduce some free market ideas
within a Soviet system.
</P>
<P>
   To Primakov's predecessors who favored free markets and tight
fiscal discipline, the return of the Soviet cast of characters is
eerie, even alarming: Not only is Maslyukov a member of the
Communist Party, he was also once director of Gosplan, the giant
bureaucracy that was the epicenter of the Soviet command economy
and the headquarters of its detailed five-year-plans.
</P>
<P>
   At a thinly-attended rally in Moscow Sunday, former Prime
Minister Yegor Gaidar issued dark warnings about the return of the
Communists to power, and the impending collapse of Russia's fragile
market economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main task today is to unite democratic forces to prevent
the downfall of Russia,'' said former Deputy Prime Minister Boris
Nemtsov, another young liberal reformer, speaking on television on
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also a more benign view of the return of a breed of
Soviet economists that many had assumed had become extinct. ``I
swear, I didn't even know he was still around,'' said one economic
researcher after reading a public appeal issued last week by
Abalkin, who is still director of the Institute of Economics.
</P>
<P>
   In his public comments, Primakov has indicated that his
government will put its emphasis on meeting the needs of the
Russian population, and Russian industry, without explaining where
the money to do so will come from.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a message with broad appeal that reaches beyond the
political debate, deep into a poor and exhausted society.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must not carry out reforms that have a bad effect on the
people,'' Primakov said on Monday at a government meeting. ``If
therapy drags on for decades, and there is no light at the end of
the tunnel, of course, this is not in the interest of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   This was in many ways the language of perestroika, when
Gorbachev, during communism's waning days, tried to give the
economy a more human dimension, allowing room for personal
ambition, ability, freedom and a limited dose of capitalist greed.
Yeltsin, in his early days, also was able to connect with his
voters but in recent years, both he and his governments have seemed
distant, and unfeeling.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the Gorbachev-era economists _ most of them
heads of academic institutes _ have adapted to Russia's changing
reality and their views, too have changed.
</P>
<P>
   Their opinions also differ. Bogomolov, for instance, proposes to
increase the country's money supply by printing rubles, and issuing
new bank credits, while at the same time asking the West for a
postponement on debt payments. Abalkin, on the other hand, would
use the increased sales tax revenues to compensate those income
groups that have been hardest hit by rising prices.
</P>
<P>
   Abalkin, whose views were considered liberal in the Soviet
context, remembered the time when he and his colleagues were first
called together. ``It was under Andropov,'' he said, referring to
the former KGB chief, who as Soviet leader in the mid 1980s, first
opened the door to non-doctrinaire economic theory.
</P>
<P>
   Their heyday came during perestroika, even though they, like
Yeltsin's young liberal economists, complained that their ideas
were never carried out in full. ``The country's economy is now
going through a very difficult time,'' wrote Abalkin in 1988 in the
newspaper Argumenti I Fakti. ``The situation has not been this bad
in many years.``
</P>
<P>
   Like Gorbachev before him, Yeltsin has seen his political
authority and popularity shrink with the withering of the Russian
economy. And like Gorbachev, Yeltsin has been compelled by
political reality to shift his government's economic course.
</P>
<P>
   With his once favored liberal economic reformers now out of
government, and his Communist opponents now in their place,
Yeltsin's about-face promises to be as abrupt as Gorbachev's
decision to abandon a famous 500-day plan for economic reform in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   In another twist of Russia's recent history, a co-author of that
plan, Grigori Yavlinsky, head of a liberal opposition party, on
Monday said he could never join an economic team headed by s man of
Maslyukov's convictions. He has a different opinion on financial
and economic policy, said Yavlinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a different vision on ways to overcome the crisis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
