<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PRIVACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE DOCUMENTS AWAITED IN CLINTON CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER S. CANELLOS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With 445 pages of salacious material heating up
computer drives across town, Washington is turning its attention to
the 2,000 pages of Kenneth W. Starr's report that remain unreleased
_ and wondering what names, accusations, and sordid details lurk in
the ``supporting documents.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue are the reputations of scores of people interviewed by
Starr's prosecutors in a grand jury bound by rules of secrecy _
rules that suddenly have been superseded by the unique requirements
of an impeachment case.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee is moving quickly to review the
supporting documents, and could release more papers within days,
according to a GOP committee source.
</P>
<P>
   The documents are expected to shed further light on glancing
references in Starr's report to President Clinton's friendships
with other women, the actions of his mid-level aides, and what
Secret Service agents did or did not see.
</P>
<P>
   But legal specialists, some of whom found the sexual
explicitness of Starr's narrative to be excessive, worried about
the extent to which officials involved in the impeachment process
are ignoring the usual rights of witnesses who appear before grand
juries.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal rules, grand jury testimony can only be unsealed
if the same witnesses are scheduled to appear at trial, and
only &UR;  &LR; to allow defense attorneys to investigate any discrepancies.
With a few additional exceptions, grand-jury materials remain top
secret.
</P>
<P>
   But not in this case.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a criminal case is brought, that doesn't mean the whole
grand-jury file is opened up,'' explained Gerard Lynch, a professor
at Columbia Law School and a former head of the criminal division
of the US attorney's office in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel approved the release of Starr's report plus
the supporting documents to Congress last Thursday. The House voted
to make the main report public on Friday. Now, the 37-member
Judiciary Committee, which has until Sept. 28 to review the
supporting documents, is moving quickly, and should release more
information soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee is working expeditiously to review the documents
and will vote as soon as possible,'' the GOP source said. ``It
could be this week.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee's mandate from the full House obliges it to err on
the side of making more material public, the source said. Some
legal specialists, however, urged the committee to show greater
restraint.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Congress's decision and I think they should balance the
public's right to know against, dare I say it, decency and fairness
to people not accused of wrongdoing,'' Lynch said. ``But my guess
is they'll release everything, because that's the way things are
going these days.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a huge trove of testimony coursing out over the
Internet alarms many observers, because the documents elaborate on
claims made in Starr's report _ some of which seemed hurtful to
innocent people without shedding light on claims of perjury or
obstruction of justice by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's narrative, for instance, quoted a friend of Monica S.
Lewinsky recalling a conversation in which Lewinsky said the
president was unsure whether he'd be married after his term ends.
It quoted Lewinsky recalling an insulting comment Clinton allegedly
made about White House volunteer Kathleen Willey.
</P>
<P>
   It also quoted Lewinsky, speaking on a tape made by Linda R.
Tripp, as saying she thought Clinton might be sexually involved
with a prominent Washington woman, who was named in the report. The
supporting documents would likely include both the full transcript
of the tape and copies of the woman's testimony to Starr's
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole way in which everything's been disclosed so quickly
and so broadly is troubling,'' said Fred Lawrence, associate dean
of Boston University Law School. ``More was made available than had
to be. Instead of stemming the rush to judgment, it's accelerated
the rush to judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence, a former federal prosecutor, believes none of the
supporting documents should be made public: ``Further disclosure
would make things worse, not better.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Rules of Criminal Procedure, disclosure of grand-jury
material occurs only when a judge approves a defendant's request
for the testimony of witnesses who will appear against him at
trial; when a defendant makes a preliminary showing of abuses in
the grand jury; when one grand jury takes over an investigation
midstream; or when state police make a showing that the testimony
relates to a violation of state law.
</P>
<P>
   Secrecy is maintained for many reasons, including a need to
protect innocent people, legal specialists said. There are few
limits on what can be asked in a grand-jury session, and many
questions range far into the realm of speculation and would never
be admissible at a trial.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, grand-jury witnesses are not subject to cross
examination, raising concerns about fairness to the target of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grand-jury process is entirely one-sided,'' said Robert
Ullmann, a former assistant US attorney in Boston and a current
partner at Nutter, McClennen &AMP; Fish. ``Starr's report makes no
effort to show the public flaws in the evidence he's selected. For
example, Monica Lewinsky has some obvious credibility problems, but
you don't see those in Starr's report.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, both Ullmann and Lawrence believe the fault is less with
Starr than with Congress, which made no effort to shield innocent
people in Starr's main report, and which is now moving to release
at least some of the supporting documents. Starr himself has urged
Congress to keep private material that could invade the privacy of
innocent parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of wide disclosure is very dangerous,'' said BU's
Lawrence. ``If you're making a report to a deliberative body,
Congress, it's probably right to err on the side of inclusion, but
that doesn't mean Congress is obliged to make it public.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
