<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0427 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4885 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-REPORT-BOS &LR;      09-14 1466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REPORT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE BUILDS FOR SWIFT ACTION ON CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House inched closer Monday to a formal
impeachment inquiry of President Clinton, amid fears among
Republican leaders about a potential backlash and the harshest
rebuke yet by Democratic leaders of Clinton's ``hair-splitting''
legal defense.
</P>
<P>
   As pressure built for swift congressional action on Clinton's
sex scandal, Republican leaders said they expected the
GOP-controlled House to approve a formal impeachment investigation
as soon as the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign the investigation could be scaled back to avoid
turning the proceedings into a tawdry spectacle, Republican leaders
expressed concern about the potentially devastating consequences of
full-scale hearings, which could be rife with lurid testimony from
witnesses such as Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody around here believes there is going to be a formal
inquiry,'' said Representative John A. Boehner, an Ohio Republican
who is chairman of the House Republican Conference. ``But it's
going to be a very difficult job for Congress to go through with,
and we've got some big decisions to make before we begin.''
</P>
<P>
   Concern spread among many House members as they returned from a
weekend of absorbing the salacious, 445-report from the independent
counsel, Kenneth W. Starr, and listening to constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, sources on the House Judiciary Committee, which is
conducting a preliminary review of 11 impeachable allegations, said
the panel may begin releasing additional material from Starr's
grand jury investigation as early as the end of this week. A
special team of 23 lawyers and investigators assigned to the
preliminary review spent the weekend scouring 17 boxes of the
closely guarded material, including Clinton's videotaped
deposition.
</P>
<P>
   The panel must decide by Sept. 28 how much of the material to
release.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Henry Hyde, an Illinois Republican who is
chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, said the panel has just
``begun the beginning'' of the process and has yet to consider how
much material to release or how much to narrow the scope of a
formal inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said he would consider proposals from GOP colleagues to
expand an impeachment inquiry to examine additional
Whitewater-related matters. But he expressed concern about
completing the process as swiftly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   If the House approves a formal inquiry, Hyde's staff said, the
Judiciary Committee would be permitted to conduct the proceedings
after Congress recesses for the year in early October. Members of
both parties want the issue resolved before a new Congress is
seated next January, if not sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a cloud hanging over Capitol Hill and the White
House, and the sooner it can be dissipated constitutionally, the
better,'' Hyde said. ``I don't know of anybody in either party who
wants to stretch this out.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Judiciary Committee already is split over a pivotal
issue: How much investigative authority the panel will receive, and
how much will be granted to the Democratic minority.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders, unable to reach an agreement acceptable to
committee Democrats, Monday abruptly abandoned plans to seek power
for the Judiciary Committee to interview witnesses and issue
subpoenas in its preliminary review.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat who
serves on the panel, said opposition to the initial GOP plan
centered on the fact, while it gave the committee broad
investigatory powers it did not afford the president a chance to
review the material before its release. Democrats on the committee
also chafed at the idea that only the committee majority could
issue subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan said the plan would give Democrats and Clinton fewer
rights than were afforded to committee Republicans and President
Nixon when Democrats controlled the House during Watergate
impeachment proceedings in 1974. ``I don't think the American
people want this president or any president to be railroaded,''
Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   As for expanding the hearing to examine Whitewater-related
matters, Representative Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat who
sits on the committee, said the exercise would be ``ludicrous,''
considering Starr has investigated for four years and has not filed
allegations against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an increasing number of lawmakers and news outlets
called on Clinton to resign, even as some congressional Democrats
expressed support for punishing the president with a formal censure
rather than possible impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders in the House and Senate, facing the
possibility of Clinton's scandal destroying their strategy to pick
up seats in the November elections, also issued terse statements
denouncing the White House legal defense strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly agree with those who have grown impatient with
hair-splitting over legal technicalities,'' said Senator Tom
Daschle of South Dakota, the Senate minority leader. ``The
president and his advisers must accept that continued legal
jousting serves no constructive purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   The House minority leader, Representative Richard A. Gephardt,
of Missouri, said: ``The considered judgment of the American people
is not going to rise or fall on the fine distinctions of a legal
argument but on straight talk and the truth. It is time for the
president and the Congress to follow that common sense for the good
of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials acknowledged the pointed complaints of
Democratic and Republican lawmakers. But in that acknowledgement
there was sign of a plan to change the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a legal definition that he doesn't believe and his
lawyers don't believe fits,'' said Paul Begala, Clinton's White
House counselor, of the perjury allegation. ``But I hope nobody
thinks he is relying on the technical legal definition of
perjury...as an excuse for having an affair and misleading people
about it. People may be worried that he is using the legal niceties
to obscure the fundamental realities. I don't think he is.''
</P>
<P>
   White House aides also said they had no more plans for Clinton
to continue apologizing. In New York, Clinton launched into what
aides called a post-report phase, in which he tried to appear
presidential with a speech on the economy that was void of any
references to the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week it was the contrition mission,'' Begala said. ``It
was enormously, personally painful. He got through it. He had to do
it. He owed it to the Cabinet, the clergy, the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was part one,'' Begala continued. ``There are two parts,
to try to make right what you've done wrong. The second is to get
back to doing the work that the people want him to do. You can't
spend all your time apologizing.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials, led by deputy chief of staff John
Podesta, continued to push to bring new lawyers with political
savvy into Clinton's campaign for redemption, with the idea being
to hire new conduits of significant stature between the White House
and Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Former Senate majority leader George Mitchell of Maine remained
in the running, officials said. Podesta has also held discussions
with Greg Craig, a state aide and a former foreign policy adviser
to Senator Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts. Craig, a lawyer by
trade, was described by former colleagues as an amiable presence
deeply familiar with the ways of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the White House is continuing with plans to have
Clinton appear in Boston at a pair of fund-raisers Thursday night
that are expected to bring in $1 million to the party.
</P>
<P>
   One senior Clinton strategist described Boston Monday as `` a
good place for Clinton right now'' with ``many friendly faces.''
During the stopover, Clinton is expected to attend a reception at
the Back Bay townhouse of Jack Manning, the president of Boston
Capital, then dine at a fund-raising dinner at the Park Plaza Hotel
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The fund-raising stops are part of what Democrats are describing
as ``unity'' events, in which the Democratic National Committee,
the Democratic Senate Campaign Committee, and the Democratic
Congresional Campaign Committee split the proceeds for the November
election.
</P>
<P>
   The pricetag on the fundraisers is hefty: $25,000 to attend the
private reception; $1,000 to attend the dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of anyone who has said I'm staying away,'' said
Steven Grossman, the chairman of the Democratic National Committee,
in a telephone interview Monday. ``I really trust the voters, and
they want to get beyond this. They don't want to put it aside
forever, but they want to get back to issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
