<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DELIVERS POLICY SPEECH ON WORLD ECONOMICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Traveling outside Washington for the first time since
the release of Kenneth W. Starr's impeachment report, President
Clinton Monday dispensed with apologies and tried to turn the focus
from the biggest scandal of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   As Congress weighed whether to proceed with impeachment
hearings, Clinton projected a business-as-usual image, speaking to
the Council on Foreign Relations on the global financial crisis and
headlining a series of Democratic fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest financial challenge facing the world in a
half-century,'' Clinton said of the turmoil in international
financial markets. ``And the United States has an absolutely
inescapable obligation to lead.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Clinton's first major policy speech since the lurid
details of Starr's report to Congress became known, and the first
chance for New Yorkers to see the president since learning of his
exploits with former White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Before Clinton spoke, Pete Peterson, chair of the Council on
Foreign Relations, said, ``Mr. President, we've always admired your
ability to focus when a lot is going on around you, and we need
that focus today.''
</P>
<P>
   Untypically, Clinton's speech was not once interrupted by
applause. The only noticeable response from the audience came when
Peterson told the president, ``From Main Street to Wall Street,
people sleep better because Bob Rubin is the secretary of the
treasury.'' Rubin accompanied the president.
</P>
<P>
   The crowds that stopped to watch the Clinton motorcade as it
moved through Manhattan were also noticeably subdued. People
stared, but few waved. When the motorcade arrived at the Council on
Foreign Relations, a small group chanted, ``Free Clinton, Jail
Starr.'' Later, as the motorcade left the council, two people stood
with their thumbs pointed down and holding a sign that said
``Resign.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to the council, Clinton said that a quarter of the
world's population now lives in countries with declining economic
growth. ``All of us in this room know that our future prosperity
depends upon whether we can work with others to restore confidence,
manage change, stabilize the financial system and spur robust
global growth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, Wall Street was posting strong gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growth at home depends upon growth abroad,'' Clinton said,
pointing out that 30 percent of America's growth since he took
office has come from international trade. ``That's why ordinary
Americans should care if Asia or Russia or South America is on
solid economic footing. These people are our customers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After he spoke, finance ministers and central bank presidents of
the world's seven richest countries issued a joint statement
pledging to cooperate in dealing with the spreading economic crisis
and endorsing Clinton's view that the greatest risk now is
recession not inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Clinton attended a Democratic fund-raising luncheon at a
posh, two-story 5th Avenue penthouse owned by Denise Rich, a New
York socialite and philanthropist. Some 60 couples paid $50,000
each to dine on grilled sea bass, crabmeat salad, and lemon cake.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Grossman, a Massachusetts native and chairman of the
Democratic National Committee, offered Clinton a ringing
endorsement at the luncheon. He told the president: ``You have
demonstrated ... a higher commtiment to the kind of moral
leadership that I value in public service and public policy than
any person I have ever met.'' Grossman said he prayed that Clinton
``will continue to provide the kind of moral leadership to this
country that has enriched the life of virtually every citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   Also at the fund-raiser were House Majority Leader Richard A.
Gephardt, Senate Majority Leader Thomas A. Daschle and Senator Bob
Kerrey, Democrat of Nebraska, who heads the Democratic Senatorial
Campaign Campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Guests were seated in three rooms. Gephardt and Daschle emerged
from other rooms to deliver their speeches. Neither one approached
the president nor looked at him when he spoke, though Daschle at
times pointed toward Clinton. Kerrey was spotted leaving before the
program began and Gephardt excused himself before Clinton spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was joined by Vice President Al Gore and his wife,
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last week's tour of contrition, during which Clinton
seemed to apologize for lying about his relationship with Lewinsky
at every turn to Democratic supporters, he barely alluded to his
problems Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that I speak for Hillary when I say we thank you for
your personal friendship and your support. It means more now than
ever, and we'll never forget it,'' he said in one of the few
references to his troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton suggested that Democrats might be able to turn ``the
adversity of the moment'' into their advantage, saying it had
spurred a higher turnout for Monday's fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest enemy for Democrats in the election, he said, is the
good economy that might create complacency among voters. Noting
that the party of the incumbent president has lost seats in midterm
elections since the Civil War, he said, ``I think we're going to
beat history.''
</P>
<P>
   DNC officials said that Monday's fund-raisers, which included
the luncheon, a dinner at The Supper Club, and an exclusive
performance of the Lion King at the Amsterdam Theatre netted more
than $4 million, $1 million more than had been projected.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
