<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NEXT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR MAY BE PURSUING ANOTHER WOMAN'S CLAIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While the report by the independent counsel,
Kenneth W. Starr, focuses mostly on President Clinton's
relationship with Monica S. Lewinsky, legal analysts said it also
provides clues that the prosecutor may still be examining Clinton's
encounter with Kathleen Willey.
</P>
<P>
   Willey, unlike Lewinsky, has said she rebuffed the president's
advances. But Willey, a former White House volunteer, also said
Clinton committed perjury in a deposition when he denied touching
certain parts of her body.
</P>
<P>
   Legal analysts said Starr seemed to indicate in his report to
Congress that he is continuing to investigate the Willey case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Additional events arising from the Lewinsky matter have also
come under scrutiny, including possible perjury and obstruction of
justice related to former White House volunteer Kathleen Willey,''
the report said. Yet the report does not detail the Willey case,
which some legal analysts interpreted as a signal that Starr is
continuing to collect evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Willey has alleged that Clinton made an inappropriate sexual
advance toward her in 1993. Lewinsky, the former White House
intern, gave her one-time friend, Linda R. Tripp, a document of
``talking points'' in which Tripp was supposed to say that she knew
nothing about an inappropriate meeting between Clinton and Willey.
</P>
<P>
   A former federal prosecutor, Bruce Yannett, said, ``I read the
report to say that the Kathleen Willey event is still under
investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the report makes clear that Starr wants more
information from White House deputy counsel Bruce Lindsey. The
report notes phone logs indicate that Lindsey had many
conversations with the president at key times, but Lindsey has
cited attorney-client privilege and has refused to answer certain
questions for the grand jury. The issue is pending before the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   A number of news organizations have raised questions about
whether Lindsey was involved in writing the talking points,
suggesting that the memo was written evidence that the White House
was involved in obstruction of justice, with perhaps even Clinton
involved.
</P>
<P>
   But as White House officials have pointed out, the Starr report
makes no reference to Lindsey or anyone else at the White House
being involved in the talking points.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no `talking points' smoking gun,'' according to the
White House rebuttal of the report.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky reportedly testified that she wrote the talking points
herself. Tripp has denied having written or suggested any of the
points.
</P>
<P>
   Given all the attention earlier this year to talking points,
legal specialists said they received suprisingly little notice in
the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The absence of a discussion of the talking points was a
mystery to me,'' said former federal prosecutor Dennis Saylor of
Boston, noting that Starr did not conclude who was the author or
whether someone at the White House participated in writing them.
</P>
<P>
   Saylor also found it noteworthy that Starr had not made any
judgments about the Willey-Clinton story. In an interview on CBS'
``60 Minutes'' this year, Willey said the president ``had his arms,
they were tight around me, and he touched me. ... He touched my
breasts ... and I was just startled.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his January deposition in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment case, was asked about Willey.
</P>
<P>
   Q. ``Did you ever attempt to touch her breasts?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton: ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Willey said on ``60 Minutes'' that she believed Clinton
committed perjury in the Jones deposition. But the Starr report,
which alleges that Clinton perjured himself in denying sexual
relations with Lewinsky, does not come to a conclusion regarding
Willey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that means Starr concluded Clinton told the
truth about Willey, or he thought he lied about it and he couldn't
prove it,'' Saylor said.
</P>
<P>
   The Starr report does not detail Willey's meeting with Clinton,
but it does say that Lewinsky told the president that an article
about Willey might be published. ``I was concerned that the
president had no idea this was going on and that this woman was
going to be another Paula Jones and he didn't really need that,''
Lewinsky testified.
</P>
<P>
   The report said Lewinsky thought Clinton might be able to ``make
this go away'' by finding Willey a job. But, the report said, ``The
president responded that the harassment allegation was ludicrous''
because he would never be attracted to someone like Willey.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, who is still presenting evidence to a grand jury,
recently set off a round of speculation by filing a motion in a
separate civil case that indicated he might soon seek indictments.
But Starr did not indicate whether the indictments would be related
to the Whitewater land deal, which he was originally appointed to
investigate, or other matters such as the firing of the White House
travel office or the misuse of government personnel files.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
