<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CLINTON-1STLD-WRIT     09-14 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S DAY IN NEW YORK: BOOS, CHEERS AND ``THE LION KING'' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Additional material including names of attendees at the
president's dinner and tightened editing throughout.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(JT) 
 By N.R. KLEINFIELD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a day of respite from the intense debate going on
in Washington, President Clinton came to New York Monday in pursuit
of money and perhaps solace, and found some of both.
</P>
<P>
   Making his first trip since the release of the Starr report and
accompanied by his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, Clinton gave a
speech on the global economy before a foreign policy group and
circulated at three crowded Democratic fund-raisers, including an
evening performance of ``The Lion King.'' Among a populace long
supportive of him, he was largely greeted with encouragement to
proceed with his job, though he also encountered his share of
dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   In a city in which presidential visits are humdrum and often
disdained for the gridlock they add to already car-choked streets,
there was keener interest than usual in Clinton's itinerary in the
wake of the scathing report of the Whitewater independent counsel,
Kenneth Starr. Here was a chance to glimpse the man of the moment
at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like what he did, but I'm not angry at him,'' said
Mary Kane, a medical administrator trying to catch a view of the
president as he arrived for his speech Monday morning on East 68th
Street, down the block from where she works. ``I'd love to see him.
I'd tell him, `Good luck and I wish you well.'''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout a day that the Democratic Party said raised more than
$4 million, there seemed to be more affirmation than antipathy
among hundreds who lined the avenues as Clinton's motorcade wound
its way from a speech at the Council on Foreign Relations on 68th
Street and Park Avenue to the trio of fund-raisers, before a
late-night return to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   People pressed against police sawhorses along Park Avenue
clapped and waved as he proceeded to lunch on 60th Street. There
were only a handful of picketers. One man, who acknowledged being a
veteran Clinton foe, displayed a white banner with ``RESIGN''
inscribed in red, while two women held up their own sign saying,
``RESIGN NOW.'' In the back seat, Clinton waved and smiled to the
onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think what he did was necessarily awful,'' said Adam
Gana, a freshman at Hunter College, which is situated just across
from where the president was speaking. ``I think maybe he should
have been a little more considerate and not lied. But I like the
president. I don't think he's a bad guy. If I could get a word with
him, I'd ask him about the universal health coverage rather than
the stupid affairs he's had.''
</P>
<P>
   Later on, as Clinton passed down Fifth Avenue on the way to the
Waldorf-Astoria Hotel, people were lined 7 and 8 deep for 10
blocks, craning for a look at him, and some of them waited
patiently for more than an hour. When he approached the hotel,
about half of the crowd there cheered and the other half booed.
</P>
<P>
   Some called for his resignation. ``I feel he should resign,''
said Ivan Richards, 30, a Manhattan therapist. ``It's put a stop on
our country. We can't get anything done.''
</P>
<P>
   Others wanted him to fight on. ``I'm out here because it's still
exciting to see the president,'' said Andrea DeMaso, 25, a
marketing executive from Dix Hills, N.Y. ``I think he's doing a
good job and has only done what all the presidents before him have
done.''
</P>
<P>
   At his various stops, Clinton sidestepped any discussion of the
Lewinsky matter. His morning speech was before about 150 people,
who were politely warm but not especially enthusiastic or all that
friendly. Some council members who had been invited stayed away,
council members said, because they did not want to shake the
president's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who did come were reading newspaper coverage of
the Lewinsky matter and then hastily tucked the papers away when
word came that the president had arrived. Theodore Sorensen, who
attended the speech, summed up the feelings of many by saying that
if Clinton lied under oath, it was ``inexcusable.'' But, he said,
``it does not amount to high crimes and misdemeanors.'' Some
others, who insisted on anonymity, were more critical and said that
Clinton's conduct had diminished the presidency and they hoped that
he would resign.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton took no questions, and when a reporter twice shouted to
him whether he would accept censure from Congress, Clinton ignored
him.
</P>
<P>
   At a $50,000-a-couple fund-raising luncheon on Fifth Avenue,
Clinton did allude to the latest events when he said, ``The
adversity of the moment, I think, has led us to this record
turnout. Why? Because people made a decision and they thought they
were needed and they stood up.''
</P>
<P>
   The luncheon was held in the two-story penthouse of Denise Rich,
a socialite, philanthropist and lyricist, whose ex-husband, Marc
Rich, is a fugitive commodities trader who fled the country rather
than face prosecution in a tax case. Sixty couples filled tables
arranged in three rooms, and others were turned away because of
lack of space. Clinton had his grilled sea bass in a different room
from his wife. Vice President Al Gore and Rep. Dick Gephardt of
Missouri, the minority leader, attended, though Rep. Charles Rangel
of Manhattan was the solitary New York politician to show up.
</P>
<P>
   John Catsimatidis, chief executive of the Red Apple Group, said
donors made their positions clear to party leaders at a recent
luncheon in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the point was made very clearly to the senators and
the congressmen there that New Yorkers feel very strongly about the
president, and support him, and any congressman who won't support
him, don't come back to New York for money,'' Catsimatidis said.
``If you can't stand up next to your friend, who you've called a
friend for the last few years, then you don't deserve our
support.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In his introduction, Steve Grossman, the chairman of the
Democratic National Committee, said, ``Mr. President, it seems to
me that you have demonstrated, at least in my adult lifetime, a
higher commitment to the kind of moral leadership that I value in
public service and public policy than any other person I've ever
met.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his brief remarks, said, ``I know that I speak for
Hillary when I say we thank you for your personal friendship and
support. It means more now than ever, and we'll never forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, Clinton stopped at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel,
on Park Avenue, the lodging choice of presidents since the days of
Hoover, where he had a rest break before his evening appearances.
He called Sammy Sosa and congratulated the Chicago Cubs outfielder
on matching Mark McGwire's record 62 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the dignitary-hardened hotel staff said there was
more excitement than customary given recent news developments. ``I
have no problem with him being here,'' said Geraldine Grays, a
lobby attendant polishing the brass banisters. ``Just leave him
alone. Let him do the job. I know some of the guests said he should
be seen today. He needs all the support he can get.''
</P>
<P>
   James Dowd, a doorman on the Park Avenue entrance, said this
time he was hearing more presidential jokes than usual, most of
them risque.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, Clinton and his wife dined with 400 people who
had paid $10,000 a plate at the Supper Club, a dinner and dancing
establishment on West 47th Street. The president's arrival
interrupted guests trying to reach their rooms at the Hotel Edison
next door to the club. Police officers lined them up and admitted
them two at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Several New York politicians put in appearances at the dinner,
including Mark Green, Geraldine Ferraro and Charles Schumer, the
three Democratic candidates for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   People began arriving for the dinner at 4:30, though the
Clintons, accompanied by the Gores, did not get there until about
6:45. By then, most of the crowd had finished their buffet meals.
The donors, including an infusion of celebrities like Christie
Brinkley, Roberta Flack and Kevin Spacey, applauded Mrs. Clinton
for a full 25 seconds. Clinton received a briefer, though equally
hearty, welcome. In addressing the audience, the Clintons spoke of
each other in glowing terms. Mrs. Clinton said of the president,
``He wakes up and worries about what he can do to help the American
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the Clintons watched the ``The Lion King'' at the New
Amsterdam Theater on Times Square in the company of 1,700 people
who had bought tickets at prices ranging from $350 to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
