<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-TIGER-COURSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tiger helps open new Atlanta course
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- To have a golf course bear your name is honor enough,
85-year-old Charlie Yates decided Monday as the afternoon shadows
lengthened behind him, overlooking the first tee. To have it happen
for the benefit of junior golf on a piece of ground once more
crime-ravaged than any in the city _ the failed public housing
project known as East Lake Meadows _ took the dream to near-fantasy
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see all denominations and all races coming together in this
marvelous spot ... I wish you all could feel the depth of my
emotions,'' said Yates, the former British Amateur champion and
current president of East Lake Golf Club. ``Bob Jones would have
been so happy to be here standing with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's official opening of the first nine holes of the Charlie
Yates Golf Course, a Rees Jones layout that will serve as the home
site of the East Lake Junior Golf Academy, brought politicians,
leaders of the Atlanta golf community and even Tiger Woods to the
revitalized area.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' entrance was detached _ three security guards in red
shirts and black pants flanking him in rock-concert style _ but his
words and commitment were truly warm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say I want golf to look like America,'' Woods, 22,
said, ``and you know what? We're here. Look at us. This is what
it's all about. I'm honored to be here and to be a part of it. I
love seeing the smiles on the kids' faces and I'm proud of what
they stand for and what they will do in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The official kickoff was the presentation of a bronze plaque to
Yates from Joe Rogers, who lifted the drape along with two of the
honoree's grandchildren and said, ``Charlie, here's your golf
course.'' Following that, 10 children from the East Lake Junior
Golf Academy and Woods simultaneously hit ceremonial shots down the
first fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, accompanied by his father Earl, told the audience that
the course, which will be operated by the East Lake Community
Foundation as yet another step of developer Tom Cousins' amazing
project, ``is a perfect example of how dreams can come true.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled to open for public play in mid-October, the course,
according to architect Jones, was designed as a sort of miniature
East Lake. Nine more holes will be added later on the property that
once was the site of East Lake's other course, along Glenwood
Avenue. The youth course, with a first nine of 2,000 yards, has par
3s ranging from 110 to 207 yards and three par-4s, the longest at
340 from the back tees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted it to be a challenge, but we also wanted to
encourage youngsters to play it, so we didn't want it to be too
hard,'' said architect Jones, who took no design fee for the
project.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
