<SLUG> BC-TX-MINORITY-ENROLLMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE MINORITIES ENROLL AS FRESHMEN AT UT DESPITE AFFIRMATIVE ACTION
BAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LYDIA LUM 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   More of the state's top black and Hispanic students enrolled as
freshmen at the University of Texas this fall, despite an
affirmative action ban.
</P>
<P>
   But the total number of black and Hispanic freshmen dropped this
year at UT. The actual number of Hispanic freshmen at UT dropped
from 807 to 762 this fall, while black freshmen rose from 163 to
165.
</P>
<P>
   This freshman class is about 10 percent smaller than last year's
because of efforts by the administration to limit overall
enrollment at UT, one of the nation's largest universities with
48,857.
</P>
<P>
   UT officials, however, focused their attention on the higher
numbers of minority students who graduated in the top 10 percent of
their high school classes. Texas passed a law last year
guaranteeing admission to state-supported colleges to all high
school seniors in the top 10 percent of their classes, regardless
of race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was gratifying to see the increase,'' said Bruce Walker, UT
admissions director. ``The top 10 percent admissions law has
allowed the university to focus our recruitment activities, and to
attract a highly qualified, diverse freshman class.''
</P>
<P>
   Among black UT freshmen this year, 38 percent were top 10
percent graduates, compared with 31 percent last year. And 54
percent of UT's Hispanic freshmen graduated in the top 10 percent
of their classes this year, vs. only 44 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   The top 10 percent legislation was in response to public, and
even some private, colleges in Texas dropping affirmative action in
admissions and scholarships. Lawmakers had hoped the admissions
guarantee for high-achieving students would make Texas colleges
more appealing than those outside the state.
</P>
<P>
   National attention has focused on Texas colleges since an
appeals court found unconstitutional UT law school's former
admissions policy, which had considered Hispanics and blacks
separately from white applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Attorney General Dan Morales subsequently decided the
court ruling applied not only to UT, but to other Texas colleges,
and applied to scholarships as well. So, many Texas colleges have
dropped race-based admissions and scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, black and Hispanic enrollment at many Texas colleges,
including UT, declined. Educators largely blamed the many
universities outside this state still offering minority
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   However, privately administered minority scholarships in this
state may have helped boost enrollment at some schools, including
UT law, officials said. Private groups and foundations are not
affected by the affirmative action ban.
</P>
<P>
   At UT law, at least eight black and 39 Hispanic first-year
students enrolled this year, compared with four blacks and 28
Hispanics last year. UT officials said 35 of their 482 first-year
students did not disclose their ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rice University in Houston has drawn 40 black
freshmen this year, compared with 30 last year. And 73 Hispanic
freshmen enrolled at Rice, vs. 59 a year ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
