<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ONDECK15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On Deck: Philadelphia Phillies
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: 7:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   TV/radio: TBS; 750-AM.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: RHP Kevin Millwood (15-8, 4.34 ERA;
3-0, 2.06 lifetime vs. Phillies) vs. RHP Tyler Green (6-10, 4.79;
3-1, 3.24 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The Braves did something July 23 they'd never done
before: They beat Tyler Green. It took seven tries, but Atlanta
defeated the right-hander 3-2 at Veterans Stadium, thanks to
back-to-back solo homers by Javy Lopez and Curtis Pride in the
sixth inning. Inexplicably to the Braves, Green remains 3-1 against
them with a 3.24 ERA during his career. He's 15-22 with a 5.30 ERA
against everybody else. In addition to Atlanta, his only other
winning records in the NL are 1-0 each against Chicago, San Diego
and Arizona. He is effective against the Braves primarily because
they are a free-swinging team, and Green's menu of sliders,
off-speed curves and change-ups is hard for Atlanta to pass up. He
faced Atlanta twice in the first two weeks of the season, allowing
two runs in 10 innings with a victory and a no-decision. Millwood,
who has four victories in his last six decisions, continues to give
up a load of hits, but he has a devastating strikeout rate. In his
last 49 innings, he has yielded 54 hits and struck out 55 batters.
His strikeouts per nine innings rate of 8.4 is tied for sixth in
the NL and in the Braves' rotation is second only to John Smoltz
(9.2).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
