u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MOORE-COLUMN-COX     09-14 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MOORE-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HR drama has become Sosa's stage
 &HT;    By Terrence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- What we're seeing here with Mark McGwire and Sammy
Sosa is another manifestation of Biblical prophesy. Indeed, the
first shall be last, and the last shall be first. That means there
shall be much weeping and moaning among the masses when Sosa is
crowned king of kings in regard to slamming home runs during a
season.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa isn't the people's choice. Well, not unless those people
live in his native Dominican Republic or know that McGwire isn't
the only person in this wonderful saga who is a treasure on and off
the field.
</P>
<P>
   As a youth, Sosa was so poor that he sold oranges when he wasn't
shining shoes on the streets of San Pedro de Macoris. As for now,
he donates much of the $10 million per year he makes with the
Chicago Cubs to charities in the United States and the Dominican
Republic. He spent last December distributing thousands of gifts to
children in schools and hospitals in both countries as somebody
called ``Sammy Claus.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's another thing: The man can hit. He joined McGwire over
the weekend in making Babe Ruth and Roger Maris just footnotes.
Sosa also is performing well enough as a complete player to push
the Cubs toward a playoff date that McGwire's Cardinals only can
dream about until next season.
</P>
<P>
   Little of this matters to the masses. In a USA Today poll last
month, 5,800 readers were asked to choose whom they wished to pass
Ruth and Maris in this cozy chase. Sosa received 16 percent to
McGwire's 79.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, for the masses, McGwire is becoming the other guy
to the other guy. We're not surprised. It's been a week since
McGwire slammed No. 62 in St. Louis against the Cubs, but two
memories remain for a columnist who visited both clubhouses that
night after much of the media had dwindled to three.
</P>
<P>
   Memory 1: It was near midnight, when McGwire and his son, Matt,
returned from a back room to a virtually empty home clubhouse.
McGwire spoke again of hitting Nos. 60, 61 and 62 within a four-day
period that featured more drama than you could stuff into a novel,
and then he hinted that Superman would become Clark Kent for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just took a couple of Advils to get rid of a headache,'' he
said with a deep sigh. He resembled somebody who had climbed the
highest mountain and wished to return slowly to the ground in an
overstuffed chair on an elevator.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I finally did it'' _ hit No. 62 in the fourth inning _
``it was sort of like, 'Oh, my God. I've got five more innings
left.' I mean, what else can you do after something like that?''
</P>
<P>
   You can go into a slump, which McGwire did, especially with his
team just playing out the season.
</P>
<P>
   Memory 2: Soon after the third or fourth wave of reporters left
Sosa's locker after McGwire's No. 62, Sosa lost the sloppy smile
he'd owned during most of the two-game series. Was he thinking
about going oh-for-the-moment while McGwire prospered or about the
Cubs dropping both games during a pennant race?
</P>
<P>
   Neither. Sosa told a columnist, ``I have to wait for my time.
And my time will come.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa's time is now. Whether the masses like it or not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2110EDT &QL; 
