<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BEAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bean fights lightweight reputation
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Those who count ticket sales and sell cable TV
subscriptions have gone to great lengths to tell you that Evander
Holyfield's next opponent is the world's No. 1-ranked heavyweight
contender, even if that's in the blurred vision of the IBF. They
point to the 31-1 record and shout, as his manager Butch Lewis did,
``This will be a September to remember!''
</P>
<P>
   Except that, even listening for nearly two months to circus
barking, many fight observers still view Vaughn Bean to be as
intimidating as Jello.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not paying attention to anybody's opinions,'' said Bean,
the heavyweight division's 25-year-old obscurity, who meets
Holyfield in the Georgia Dome and on the Showtime cable network
Saturday night. ``I'm here to fight. I'm here to do a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Turner, Holyfield's trainer, said Bean ``isn't nearly as bad
as people make him out to be.'' And the notion that the credentials
of a boxer with such a high success rate would be questioned does
seem strange, especially when Bean's only loss was a narrow
decision last year to then-IBF champion Michael Moorer.
</P>
<P>
   But in boxing, contenders are judged by the quality of wins. And
when Bean's resume is slipped under a microscope, it bears a strong
resemblance to that of Peter McNeeley, who was 36-1 against
convenience-store clerks until being floored by Mike Tyson in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Bean, who is unranked by the sport's other two major governing
bodies, claimed wins against boxers with a composite record of
152-294-14 at the time of the bouts. It gets worse. Those opponents
went on to a current combined mark of 181-511-19. Only three have
winning records _ not that Warren Williams (10-8-1), Maurice Harris
(11-9-2) or Issac Brown (12-10) have cracked any rankings.
</P>
<P>
   The one fact that separates Bean from McNeeley is that Bean has
faced a champion. The loss to Moorer was a narrow decision
(116-113, 115-113, 114-114), but those scores were more a
reflection on the lack of punches thrown than on fierce
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Even Bean admitted, ``I was worried about his southpaw style
instead of just fighting him. I was waiting for him to make a wrong
move, and he was waiting for me to make a wrong move. So we were
just standing there, taking pictures of each other.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Bean was ranked fifth by the IBF, despite having
never fought a top-10 opponent. IBF president Bob Lee constantly
has had to answer criticism about the rankings. His standard
response: ``He's been one of the most active heavyweights, and he
was undefeated going into the Moorer fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee said he was somewhat vindicated by the closeness of the
Moorer fight, although others might point to Moorer's lack of
enthusiasm and his trainer, Teddy Atlas, telling him before the
fight that he was quitting.
</P>
<P>
   Bean's 15 minutes of fame soon turned into a half-hour. Lewis,
who once maneuvered Leon Spinks into a title fight against Muhammad
Ali after only seven bouts, argued with Lee that Bean lost the
decision because the judges were influenced by prefight negative
media attention. Lee bought it and made Bean a mandatory challenger
for Moorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Butch, `I want to kiss your feet,' '' Bean recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The rematch with Moorer never took place. Bean received a
$350,000 ``step-aside'' payment to allow Moorer to fight Holyfield
first, with the promise that he would fight the winner; Holyfield
and Moorer split the payoff. Holyfield knocked down Moorer five
times, and Bean now has his second title shot in 18 months, along
with a nearly $2 million payday.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said, ``He used to come to me and say, `Butch, let me
fight somebody. They're laughing at me in the gym.' I said, `Just
wait until you're fighting for the championship.' Now where are the
wisecracks?''
</P>
<P>
   He has come a long way from his childhood on the south side of
Chicago. When Vaughn was 13, Brenda Bean, a single mother of two,
was killed on Valentine's Day after her car slid across an icy
highway and was hit head-on by another vehicle. Bean lived with an
aunt until moving out on his own when he was 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``The criticism doesn't bother me, because I've dealt with a lot
of obstacles in my life,'' Bean said. ``This fight is just one more
hurdle.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
