<SLUG> BC-FBC-TENN-FLA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A Gator jinx on Vols
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Over the past five years Tennessee has won 50
games, and 10 wins a year isn't bad in anybody's league. The Vols
have won an SEC championship. They've been in the Top 10 for 38 of
the last 39 polls. They've watched Peyton Manning come, create a
legend, and go on to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Tennessee's football team and fans have been able to
celebrate just about everything you could name in that five-year
span. Everything, that is, but a win over Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Not since 1992, when Phillip Fulmer was an interim coach for the
ailing Johnny Majors, has Tennessee tasted victory over the Gators.
Except for 1994's 31-0 loss in Knoxville, Tennessee has had chances
to win each game. But invariably Florida would make the key play,
force the big turnover, and find a way to come out on top.
</P>
<P>
   For Fulmer, there is nothing mysterious about Tennessee's
five-game losing streak to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida is a very talented, well-coached team and if you don't
play well ... if you don't block and tackle well and take care of
the football, chances are you are not going to win,'' said Fulmer,
pointing to the fact that Tennessee has committed significantly
more turnovers (18-8) in the five losses.
</P>
<P>
   But fans keep looking for something beyond the physical to
explain why Tennessee has been unable to get over this Gator-made
hump. On talk shows and in other media has come the strong
suggestion that after five straight years, the hump has become more
mental than physical.
</P>
<P>
   They point to last season, when Fulmer took his team down to
Florida a day early, camping out in nearby Ocala in hopes of
getting the players better acclimated to the heat. But when the
Vols turned it over three times and lost 33-20, Fulmer's critics
said the move served to further tighten what was already a tight
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't buy that at all,'' said wide receiver Jeremaine
Copeland. ``We might have gotten a little uptight but I don't think
it's been the difference in the game. The difference is they made
the plays and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   But sophomore running back Jamal Lewis believes the hurdle
Tennessee must overcome to finally beat the Gators is found in the
mind, not the body.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way those guys have more talent than we do,'' said
Lewis, who played sparingly in last year's game as a freshman. ``I
think part of it is mental. And you overcome that by keeping your
cool and playing your game. That's what we have to do on
Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer does not believe he or his staff is doing anything to
make his team uptight before it plays the Gators.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they've tightened up it's because of the maturity level of
the football team,'' said Fulmer. ``We were able to come back
against Auburn in the SEC championship game because by that time,
our team had matured.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer believes a coach must be careful about buying into
psychological explanations for winning and losing. He witnessed the
same situation as an assistant to Johnny Majors, whose stumbling
block was Alabama. Every year Majors would tighten up the week of
the Alabama game and try different things to get his team ready to
play. Not many of them worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you try to do something that's not your nature it doesn't
come across as genuine,'' said Fulmer. ``Ultimately, it comes back
to whether or not you blocked and tackled them the way you were
supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he concedes that until Tennessee beats Florida, this will
be a yearly question. He and the Vols would like to put it to rest
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bothers me that we haven't won, particularly in a couple of
games where I thought we were as good or maybe better,'' said
Fulmer. ``As well as we've played here, we should have won our
share. As a competitor, that digs at you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
