u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-COX     09-14 0308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hallen, German to be used more
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Falcons are going to take the next step in coach Dan
Reeves' grand plan, they will have to beat the San Francisco 49ers.
And to do so, they will need more help from some of the team's high
draft choices.
</P>
<P>
   That opportunity is coming. After this Sunday's bye, the Falcons
play at San Francisco on Sept. 27, and some players who haven't
dressed for a game yet might get a chance to help.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said Monday that second-round draft choice Bob Hallen, a
guard/center, and third-round draft choice Jammi German, a
receiver, stand good chances of being active for the 49ers game.
</P>
<P>
   No changes are imminent on the offensive line, Reeves said, but
they could happen in the future. Left guard Calvin Collins and
right guard Gene Williams have not been impressive. The way Hallen
is used in practice today might offer some clues. He has been
working at backup left guard for about five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way Bob Hallen is going to be ready ... is to get ...
some playing time,'' Reeves said. ``We've got guys playing there
now making mistakes, and there's no difference in a rookie making
those mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hallen) has got speed and quickness. He's very good pulling,
has quick hands, quick feet, great athletic ability. Probably the
thing he needs to improve on is ... assignments, which comes from
being in there.''
</P>
<P>
   German, Reeves said, would get a look as a return man, as an
outside coverage man on punts and ``maybe as the third or fourth
receiver,'' spots currently held by Todd Kinchen and rookie Tim
Dwight. Reeves also said seventh-round draft choice Ken Oxendine, a
running back, could dress for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
