<SLUG> BC-TEN-NOTEBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brat Pack making Davenport more marketable
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Lindsay Davenport says it never bothered her that the
most marketable players on the WTA Tour lately have been four
self-assured, if not cocky, teenagers _ Martina Hingis, Anna
Kournikova and Venus and Serena Williams _ even though without
Hingis the whole group has won exactly one singles' title.
</P>
<P>
   Now, following her first U.S. Open women's championship and 17th
title overall, Davenport could credit the four indirectly for
shaping her suddenly marketable image into that of the
anti-brat-packer, the one who wasn't glamorous, didn't boast, never
complained. She just got to work and did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's American, and she's normal,'' said Tony Godsick,
Davenport's IMG agent. ``I'm not saying the other women aren't
normal, but Lindsay is American as apple pie. ... She likes to
spend time with her mother and her friends. She really tries to
stay out of the spotlight.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport won the U.S. Open on the birthday of her mother, Ann.
The two are roommates in Davenport's home in Newport Beach, Calif.
Davenport invited her in after she and Davenport's father, Wink,
divorced four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the one that used to drive me hours and hours to
practice since I was 6,'' Davenport said. ``It's a great story.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport is still close to her father, although he didn't
attend her final.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport went to work Monday as a new celebrity, doing an
interview with CNN and appearing on ``CBS This Morning.'' Later,
she did photo shoots for People and New York Times magazines, then
a taping for the ``Rosie O'Donnell Show,'' which will air
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Remaking Kournikova
</P>
<P>
   Advantage International will announce this week the signing of
former IMG clients Kournikova and her pal Sergei Fedorov of the
Detroit Red Wings. One of the goals of Advantage will be to tone
down Kournikova's racy image. Advantage president Phil de Picciotto
told Sports Illustrated he wants to ensure that ``her tennis
excellence is what makes her attractive.'' Her tennis excellence
somehow was underplayed in a recent Rolling Stone story, in which
she was pictured in high heels and a miniskirt that bared her
underwear. Kournikova has beaten Hingis, Davenport, Monica Seles
and Steffi Graf this year but has not won a WTA Tour title.
</P>
<P>
   An Australian revolution
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Open men's final was the first involving two
Australians since 1970, when Ken Rosewell beat Tony Roche, and
Patrick Rafter is the first Australian to win back-to-back titles
since Neale Fraser in 1959-60. ``You know, it was quite normal to
expect two Australians to get through to a Grand Slam final, but it
hasn't happened in 25 years, which means that anyone under 25 has
no idea what I'm talking about,'' said Geoff Pollard, the president
of the Australian tennis federation. Pollard also noted that Rafter
did it ``the Australian way,'' a serve-and-volley, net-attacking
style. Pollard said Australians were beginning to wonder ``whether
the Australian game was passe; whether we should teach our players
the continental game. Others said, 'Don't copy; you'll never catch
them. Don't replicate Europe.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Nuveen field announced
</P>
<P>
   The field for the Atlanta stop on the Nuveen Tour, to be played
Sept. 30-Oct. 4 at Atlanta Athletic Club, has been set. It includes
Jimmy Connors, Mats Wilander, Andres Gomez, John Lloyd, Mikael
Pernfors, Mel Purcell, Johan Kriek, Gene Mayer, Mansour Bahrami,
Tim Wilkison, Jose-Luis Clerc and Eddie Dibbs. For ticket
information, call 877-836-6477.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
