<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BOOKS-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTANTS CALL   FOR ACTION OVER   STUDIO BOOKKEEPING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hollywood executives face a nightmare soon from
something far more frightening than Freddie Krueger _ the nation's
accountants.
</P>
<P>
   Proposed changes in how movie studios report the finances of
their blockbusters and bombs are causing as much consternation as
the prospect of $25 million star salaries. One analyst has
estimated studios will have to take a collective hit topping $2
billion if the rules are altered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposals are being contested rather heatedly,'' said
Steven Cesinger, an investment banker with Greif &AMP; Co. ``They have
not been well-received.''
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Accounting Standards Board of the American
Institute of Certified Public Accountants will meet Friday in
Norwalk, Conn., to discuss staff proposals to change FASB Statement
53, which concerns rules covering how Hollywood reports movie
results.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, studios have considerable latitude in how they report
earnings, making it legal to pretty up results by declaring most
film revenues up front while holding off on disclosing expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's currently some diversity in practice,'' said Dan Noll,
a technical manager for the AICPA who helped write the proposals.
``That means investors and analysts can't adequately compare one
movie company to another.''
</P>
<P>
   Noll stresses AICPA and FASB aren't trying to bury Hollywood.
``This started because analysts, preparers and accountants were
asking for more guidance and we're trying to be responsive to their
cries for help,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   FASB 53 hasn't been changed since 1981. Frank Scheuerell, FASB's
project manager, said, ``At the time, there were mainly two markets
_ theaters and free TV _ so it doesn't have the specific details
for home video, pay TV and cable.''
</P>
<P>
   How is it that Hollywood is able to operate under such oddball
rules in the first place? Cesinger points out that the accounting
practices reflect the essentially speculative nature of the
business of making films.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue with movies is that you're dealing with
intangible assets and how you exploit those over time,'' he said.
``That gives you huge latitude over how you report. So the film
industry is definitely an animal unto itself that requires
different rules.''
</P>
<P>
   If the board agrees the rules need to be changed, it would then
open a 90-day public comment period next month, followed by a final
review next year and implementation as early as the year 2000.
Proposals would allow studios no longer to mask losses through
tactics such as deducting marketing costs over several years while
booking projected TV revenues up front.
</P>
<P>
   The rules would also halve the period over which costs must be
written off from 20 years and bar profits from promotional
merchandise in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're proposing will make the balance sheet tighter,''
said Scheuerell. ``If it's an unprofitable movie, you'll be able to
tell a lot faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles-area resident Steven D. Sills, an auditor-attorney
specializing in studio contracts, says the changes reflect the need
for studio accounting to better match costs of doing business with
revenue streams. ``Ten years is still a pretty long time but it
does make Judgment Day come a lot faster,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Studios have not commented much officially _ ``We prefer not to
comment'' was a Walt Disney Co. spokesman's response _ but
executives have claimed the new rules will lead to incorrect
presumptions about movie successes and failures.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the proposed restrictions could force publicly
traded Hollywood companies to take a one-time charge of more than
$2 billion, according to analyst David Londoner of Schroder &AMP; Co.,
who helped write the proposed rules.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS.)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
