u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-1STL     09-14 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-950&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP CONGRESSIONAL DEMOCRATS CALL ON CLINTON TO STOP LEGAL
`HAIR-SPLITTING' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: UPDATES with quote from Lott in new 5th graf, Senate
Majority ...; ADDS 13 grafs after 8th graf pvs, He added: ..., with
quotes, background.) 
 (See also: CLINTON-ECON, CLINTON-REPORT-SCENE, CLINTON-SCHOOLS,
CLINTON-PERJURY, CLINTON-PASTORS, NY-CLINTON, CLINTON-LEWINSKY,
CLINTON-LEWIS-COLUMN) 
(nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The two Democratic leaders of Congress sharply
admonished the White House Monday to stop trying to make legal
justifications for President Clinton's misleading testimony about
his relationship with Monica Lewinsky. But buoyed by polls showing
the nation still reluctant to embark on impeachment, they also
called for quick decisions to resolve the nation's constitutional
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The similar statements by House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt
and Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle positioned them squarely in
synch with the perceived public mood. Their remarks were designed,
aides said, to head off any Republican efforts to have protracted
impeachment hearings lasting well into next year.
</P>
<P>
   But while Republicans pledged to move in timely fashion, they
appeared to be looking at precisely the kind of broad-reaching and
time-consuming inquiry that Democrats want to avoid. Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., the Judiciary Committee chairman and therefore the
person who oversees the impeachment process, said he would not rule
out expanding any inquiry beyond the president's affair with Ms.
Lewinsky and efforts to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is certainly a possibility,'' he said, explaining that
Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth Starr could still send
Congress information on other matters he has investigated and that
``we would be duty bound to consider whatever he sends us.'' He
also did not rule out an extensive inquiry even if Starr did not
make another report, called a referral. ``It's possible,'' said
Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said that he did not believe
the House would be able to do anything more than vote on whether to
open an impeachment inquiry before Congress recesses in early
October for the November elections. He said of a full-fledged
impeachment process: ``How you get that done before Christmas would
be a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   The positioning in Congress came as members of the House and
Senate returned to Washington after a weekend of sampling
constituent opinion to the flood of sordid details about Clinton's
relationship with a White House intern. Sentiment varied from
district to district, with Republicans generally seeking punishment
of Clinton but Democrats saying both impeachment and resignation
are too harsh, and finding conflicting feelings from a nation that
wants Clinton rebuked but fears the trauma of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a way to salvage the situation for the White House,
both Gephardt and Daschle _ in their first reactions since Starr's
report was made public on Friday _ warned Clinton against the kind
of defense his lawyers put forth on weekend talk shows when they
continued to argue that he had not lied in legal proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly agree with those who have grown impatient with
hair-splitting over legal technicalities,'' Daschle said. ``There
is a basic understanding of the truthfulness that the president
failed to meet.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The president and his advisers must accept that
continued legal jousting serves no constructive purpose. It simply
stands in the way of what we need to do: move forward and let
common sense guide us in doing what is best for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt said, ``The considered judgment of the American people
is not going to rise or fall on the fine distinctions of a legal
argument but on straight talk and the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's legal team has consistently argued that Clinton did
not commit perjury in his appearance before a grand jury on Aug. 17
and in an earlier deposition in a sexual misconduct lawsuit brought
by Paula Jones. Perjury, however, was one of the offense cited by
Starr as possible cause for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, White House spokesman Jim Kennedy said, ``The
president has made it clear that he does not want the work of his
lawyers to get in the way of his admission that he had an improper
relationship and he misled people to keep it private. No legalisms
should obscure the fact that it was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle also opened the door to censure of the president,
mentioning the possibility of ``other means to address the
president's conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gephardt did not. And several key Republicans _ including
Lott _ showed resistance to such a route for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our responsibility under the law and under the Constitution is
to examine whether there's sufficient basis for an impeachment
inquiry,'' said Rep. W. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., who is on the
Judiciary Committee. ``It would be premature to look at censure.''
</P>
<P>
   With members of the Judiciary Committee poring through the 17
boxes of backup materials Starr sent along with his report,
Republicans said they were considering making public more of the
materials within the next few days, including Clinton's testimony
to the grand jury. That would answer any questions about whether
Starr quoted the president out of context in his report.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a grand jury though closed circuit television,
Clinton testified about his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky and
defended his statements that and he and Ms. Lewinsky did not have a
sexual relationship in a deposition in the sexual harrassment case
brought by Mrs. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans also put off, for now, any further votes on the
procedures to be followed by the Judiciary Committee, in an effort
to avoid a bruising partisan confrontation until it can no longer
be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and Democrats are battling over issues crucial to
the course of an investigation, such as subpoena powers and the
authority to take depositions, grant immunity for witnesses and
cite witnesses for contempt. ``I expect some contentious issues to
surface, and some decibels to be raised,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As the deliberations went on, the rank-and-file in Congress
seemed divided along party lines about what course their
constituents wanted them to take, with some just uncertain what
they should do next.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., who is on the Judiciary Committee,
said, ``People are saying you want to impeach the president over a
private sexual affair,'' Nadler said. ``They think it's a vendetta.
They are very angry at Starr for putting this salacious material
out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Denny Hastert, R-Ill., said he went out of his way to
visit a county fair over the weekend and that 95 percent of the
people who walked up and talked with him argued for impeachment or
resignation. ``They were saying kick the guy out,'' Hastert said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Forbes, R-N.Y., who represents a Long Island
district that can swing in its party allegiance, said, ``There's a
lot of frustration among people who believed in Bill Clinton. But
people are truly in a quandary. They're not saying, 'Go impeach
him.' But they're also not saying, `Don't impeach him.' The biggest
question they're asking me is, 'What are you going to do?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
