<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0446 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4915 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-BOOKS-2ndTake-L     09-14 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BOOKS-2ndTake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES:   the proposed rules. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Londoner has projected write-offs will include $400 million at
Viacom Inc., parent of Paramount; $375 million at News Corp.,
parent of 20th Century Fox; and $475 million at Time Warner, parent
of Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   The changes, Scheuerell says, are aimed at preventing unfair
interpretations of the rules such as those that occurred at Cannon
Films and Orion Pictures in the late 1980s. Sills, who co-wrote
``Movie Making: Understanding Hollywood's (Creative) Accounting
Practices,'' points to Cannon as the prime abuser of FASB 53.
</P>
<P>
   Cannon, an action-film specialist, overestimated revenues and
slowed down amortization of production costs, leading to an
artificially high stock price. Cannon ran afoul with the Securities
and Exchange Commission, agreed to change accounting methods, saw
profits become huge losses and closed up shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changes may be about 10 years too late,'' said Sills.
``Major studios are part of conglomerates more interested in cash
flow than manipulating profits.''
</P>
<P>
   David Davis, a vice president at investment banker Houlihan
Lokey Howard &AMP; Zukin, notes that since studio parents will all take
the hit at the same time, the long-term impact may not be
particularly severe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the majors are already using very conservative
methods,'' he said. He added it makes sense for FASB to institute
new rules so that investors can better understand the values of the
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to have companies on an even footing,'' said
Davis, noting that one difference in current accounting practices
is that smaller studios often spread marketing costs over a
seven-year schedule rather than as the money is spent. ``It makes
sense to clarify and eliminate confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Cesinger notes that final rules may be significantly different
than proposed. ``Ideally, the FASB wants to set out something that
everyone agrees to,'' he said. ``They don't like controversy. They
want something that's implementable.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood already has a notorious reputation for murky
accounting practices for profit participation, although the new
FASB rules won't cover that area. In the most famous case, filed a
decade ago by humorist Art Buchwald, Paramount declared that the
Eddie Murphy feature ``Coming to America'' didn't show a net profit
even though it generated over $340 million at the box officer
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   A judge found Paramount had used ``unconscionable'' accounting
practices to deny the humorist and producer Alain Bernheim their
share of profits. Paramount appealed and the case was settled in
1995 and that led to further suits over concealed profits.
Screenwriter Ron Shelton won $9.8 million last year over the
profits from the 1992 hit ``White Men Can't Jump.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's reputation received another black eye a month ago
when the SEC fined Sony $1 million for misleading investors on the
value of its movie studios prior to a $2.7 billion write-off. The
fine was equal to the highest ever in a securities case that did
not involve fraud; the SEC also ordered, in the first such move in
its history, that auditors examine details of Sony's 1994 annual
report.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, books like ``Movie Money'' represent a further
assault on studio power by disclosing Hollywood's methods in
limiting net profits for actors who sign profit-participation
deals. Under it, studios can subtract a wide range of questionable
expenses from revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Will all this mean reduced power for studios? Sills doesn't
think so, saying, ``The reality is that the studios still write the
contract.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
