<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOOKED BY GHOST STORIES FROM '78 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What makes them the Red Sox is their insistence that
the past has nothing to do with the present, followed by
performances that appear infinitely predestined.
</P>
<P>
   And so they came to Yankee Stadium Monday night, losers of 8 of
10, a woeful 3-8 in September, looking at their onetime wild card
lead of nine games (on Aug. 27) shriveled to three with 15 to play.
</P>
<P>
   There were ghosts in the eyes of those who were here 20 years
ago, the older men who wore the Red Sox uniform for the collapse
against which all others are measured.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Eckersley today is a 43-year-old middle reliever who won
20 games for the 1978 Red Sox. Jim Rice is a 45-year-old batting
coach who had his MVP season for the '78 Sox. Sox broadcaster Jerry
Remy, 45, was an All-Star second baseman for the '78 Sox and hit
the ninth-inning playoff single that somehow found its way into the
glove of a sun-blinded Lou Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, and then there is Don Zimmer. The inimitable Zim,
target of Bill Lee and his bleacher minions in '78, today is a
bench coach with the muscle-flexing New York Yankees. Twenty years
ago, Zim steered the pro sports equivalent of the Exxon Valdez,
running it aground and unleashing a toxic spill from which New
England has never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Before Monday night's Red Sox-Yankees joust at The House That
Ruth Built, the ghosts of '78 were asked about flashbacks and the
panic mentality that has taken hold of Greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand,'' said Eckersley. ``It's the nature of the
tradition. That's profound, huh? Actually, I don't remember '78
that well. I know we won the last eight in a row and 14 of our last
16 to tie. I remember winning a big game here in September. It was
a big game just like this is a big game tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer said, ``Because of the way things have happened there
over the years, I can understand how people are feeling.
Personally, I'm rooting for the Red Sox and the Cubs _ two teams
that fired me. But as a manager you just have to make sure you keep
your club playing hard. Boston's still got the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a stretch to compare '98 to '78. Twenty years ago, the Red
Sox were one of the dominant teams in baseball, an All-Star cast of
home run thunder. They roared to a 62-28 record and led the
defending champion Yankees by 14 games on July 20. Then came the
free fall, lowlighted by the Boston Massacre, and a humiliating
stretch of sloppy baseball that put them 3 1/2 games behind the
hated Yanks.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Boston rallied to win its last eight games and force
a playoff, but no one remembers the '78 Sox as a clutch bunch. They
are etched in hardball history as the Manila Folders _ a team that
won 99 games but is remembered only for blowing a big lead, then
losing the one-game playoff because of Bucky Dent's homer.
</P>
<P>
   Remy stood in the clubhouse Monday night, chatting with Rice,
another soldier in the war of '78.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah, we hardly get asked about '78 at all,'' Remy said
sarcastically. ``Just every time the Sox lose five in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice rolled his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Even the veteran writers had flashbacks. New York Times baseball
sage Murray Chass, who covered the Yanks for the Globe in '78 (the
Times was on strike), said, ``They'e doing a pretty good imitation
of that year.''
</P>
<P>
   Could it happen again? Sox fans are trained to fear the worst, a
trait that's become painfully obvious to Boston manager Jimy
Williams. After Sunday's loss Williams answered a pessimistic
question with, ``Only in Boston ...''
</P>
<P>
   Only in Boston? What about Toronto in 1987, when Williams's Blue
Jays led the Tigers by 4 1/2 games with a week to play, then saw it
dissolve in a hail or close losses to Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the first time I've been through this,'' said
Williams, citing his days as a coach with the Braves and some minor
league pennant races. ``It's the nature of the game. You never get
too high or too low.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams believes the negativity is media-driven. He chuckled
and said, ``I've got tinted windows in my car. And I turn the sound
way up.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidding some more, he said, ``Do they have talk shows in
Boston?'' Then he said he might make a call to the other clubhouse
and invite Zimmer to come visit.
</P>
<P>
   Zim would be able to tell him some stories _ such as the time he
got booed carrying the lineup card to home plate for the Fenway
opener, six months after winning 99 games and finishing tied for
first. Zim could tell Jim about driving home over the Tobin Bridge
and hearing his daughter weep in the back seat because of the
treatment her dad got from the Boston fans.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Williams needs no reminders. He went through
pennant-race hell as a major league manager in 1987 and no doubt
the scars are deep.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way it is for Red Sox fans. This is why they worry
as the games dwindle to a precious few. Fourteen to play, starting
tonight, against the Yankees. Again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   y
</P>
</TEXT>
