A4918 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGRICH-FINE-NYT &LR;      09-14 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-FINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GINGRICH TO PAY ALL OF FINE WITHOUT DOLE LOAN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Speaker Newt Gingrich said Monday that he did not
need to borrow any money from former Sen. Bob Dole after all to
help pay the fine levied on him last year by the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker's office offered no explanation for why Gingrich
would not take Dole up on his offer, extended soon after the fine
had been imposed, but one Republican suggested that Gingrich had
earned more money from sales of his book this year than he had
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, who was fined and reprimanded by the House in January
1997 for misleading the House ethics committee about his use of
tax-exempt groups for political purposes, has already paid $100,000
of the $300,000 penalty. The House panel, formally the Committee on
Standards of Official Conduct, said Monday that he would pay the
rest in two installments, one in November and one in January, and
confirmed that Dole was now released from restrictions, to which he
had agreed, against speaking to Gingrich on behalf of clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was glad to do it,'' Dole was quoted by a spokesman as
saying of his offer. ``That's what friends are for.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who had joined the Washington law firm of Verner Liipfert
Bernhard McPherson &AMP; Hand after losing the 1996 presidential
election, initially offered to lend Gingrich the entire $300,000.
But that early arrangement raised questions of a sweetheart deal:
The accord did not require Gingrich to begin repaying Dole until
2005, by which time Gingrich might well have left Congress, and
critics, including the public-interest lobby Common Cause,
suggested that Dole was trying to buy influence for his firm, which
represented tobacco interests among other powerful groups.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was renegotiated. Under the new arrangement, the
amount that Dole could lend was scaled back to no more than
$150,000. He proclaimed his intention not to register as a lobbyist
during the life of the loan and promised that if he did, the loan
would be transferred to a commercial lender. He also promised not
to ``directly or indirectly contact Speaker Gingrich on behalf of
any clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich initially anticipated using revenue from the book,
``Lessons Learned the Hard Way,'' along with his house in Marietta,
Ga., to secure the loan from Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Lessons Learned the Hard Way'' was never expected to
generate the kind of revenue earned by his first book, ``To Renew
America,'' and, sure enough, had to be heavily discounted.
HarperCollins, the publisher of both books, printed only 150,000
copies of ``Lessons Learned,'' in contrast to its run of 450,000
copies of ``To Renew America,'' published in 1995 at the dawn of
the Gingrich-led Republican revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Renew America'' earned Gingrich $1.2 million in royalties
that first year and was on The New York Times best-seller list for
12 weeks, compared with one week for ``Lessons Learned.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, publishing officials said Gingrich had aggressively
promoted ``Lessons Learned,'' with two dozen autograph sessions,
and the book is still moving. HarperCollins, however, would not
disclose sales figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
