<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASSPORTS TO DIGNITY FOR THE OPEN WINNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When it came to the grand finales of this year's U.S.
Open, anticlimactic was the word _ for all but two players, that
is.
</P>
<P>
   For Patrick Rafter of Australia and the homegrown heroine
Lindsay Davenport, whose 1998 Open titles not only conveyed
million-dollar benefits but also conjured the distinct prospect of
gaining No. 1 rankings, the Open was a passport to self-respect. By
defending his title, Rafter proved that he was not, as John McEnroe
had fretted this June, going to fall into the trap of whiling away
the rest of his tennis life as a one-Grand-Slam wonder. By winning
her first Grand Slam title, Davenport proved to herself, and to the
legion of skeptics who questioned her passion for competition, that
hers is a major talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't a gem to start with; it just took some polishing by a
lot of patient people, me included,'' the 22-year-old Davenport
said after dethroning Martina Hingis in the women's final, which
again took a back seat to football in the minds of CBS and was
sandwiched between the men's semifinals on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Open was finally over, despite the dubious
entertainment value of the first all-Australian men's final in 28
years, history had not been made.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Rafter's diligence in his semifinal against the
four-time champion Pete Sampras, Roy Emerson's dozen Grand Slam
crowns still stand alone as the career benchmark. Sampras, whose
Wimbledon title this year brought his own collection to 11, went
home wounded in spirit and quadriceps. He refused to answer a query
about when, or whether, he would stay healthy and hungry long
enough at a Grand Slam event to match Emerson's record, or perhaps
eclipse it.
</P>
<P>
   Like the top-ranked Sampras, the top-ranked Hingis went away
mad: not even a generous runner-up check for $400,000 could assuage
her disgust at leaving the Open without becoming, at 17, the
youngest champion to mount a successful defense. Also like Sampras,
Hingis' inability to grab a title here at the year's final Grand
Slam event had a doubly depressing significance: it left her with
only a single Grand Slam championship to remember 1998 by, and left
her in imminent danger of losing her No. 1 ranking to the player
who defeated her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to get a final again,'' said Hingis, who settled
for semifinal finishes at the French Open and Wimbledon, ``but it's
always a better feeling to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams, after falling a round short of reprising her
surge to the final in her controversial Open debut last year, vowed
to purchase a coffin and bury the red, white and blue tennis outfit
she would not be unveiling in the final round. Not one to defer to
her rivals, Williams, whose tennis philosophy has evolved along the
lines of bigger is better, found herself in the uncomfortable
position of having to admit that the Davenport who gave her a
straight-set semifinal tuning is bigger and better than her.
</P>
<P>
   Better late than never for Davenport, said Williams, who also
warned that 22 is perilously close to over the hill in women's
tennis. But the birth certificates of the eight different players
who surfaced as 1998 Grand Slam champions defied that teen-age
logic: the four female champions ranged from Hingis at 17 to
Wimbledon's queen for a day, Jana Novotna, at 29. And on the men's
side, the winners ranged from 22-year-old Carlos Moya at the French
Open to 29-year-old Petr Korda at the Australian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's starting to happen more and more,'' said Rafter,
25, of the trend toward Grand Slam-sharing instead of the Grand
Slam-hoarding represented by Hingis' three 1997 titles. ``The most
amazing thing is that it happened on the women's side. The men's
side is no big shock, but it's starting to become a bit more
competitive on the women's side as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's what prompted Sampras to rethink his strategy for
the Grand Slam he has never won, Roland Garros, where he may have a
chance next year to break Emerson's record _ if he can tie it first
at the 1999 Australian Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to enter the ladies' event next year,'' Sampras
said. ``Maybe I'll get lucky and win that.'' According to sages
like Emerson, Rod Laver and Don Budge, Sampras needs a French Open
crown on his resume. The alternative, they have said, would be
anticlimactic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
