</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PARTY'S NOT OVER, BY A LONG SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is probably the best time to send out the first national
sports memo. It could be faxed to the country. It could be sent via
overnight mail. It could be e-mailed. We could even call up a Starr
investigator, have him prepare a special report, and reveal the
details in newspapers. But no matter how we sent our baseball memo,
the message in all subject headings would be the same: You can't
determine when historic parties are supposed to stop; they fade
themselves out.
</P>
<P>
   We all should have known better, right?
</P>
<P>
   Only a week ago, Mark McGwire was being called the king of home
runs. The Cardinals first baseman flicked aside previously magical
numbers by Hack Wilson, Babe Ruth, and Roger Maris. He appeared on
the front pages of nearly every paper in the country. Television
programming was rearranged and interrupted to watch him scale
Maris's magical 61-homer mountain (Maris's family was at Busch
Stadium to watch). Bud Selig, baseball's commissioner, was in St.
Louis when McGwire made history. And when the slugger hit No. 62
last Tuesday, the Hall of Fame came looking for his bat and jersey.
All angles were covered. All except the Sammy Sosa angle.
</P>
<P>
   People in Chicago celebrated when Sosa, the Cubs right fielder,
hit his 61st and 62d home runs of the season Sunday. But the nation
did not pause and throw a party. The nation had already
(itals)stopped(unitals) the party, having given all the verbal
gifts to McGwire. Selig? He was nowhere near Wrigley Field. And a
media crew that once numbered 700 had shrunk to its normal size. So
Sosa was not the sports story of the day, instead blending in with
an NFL Sunday, the US Open, and baseball's playoff pushes.
</P>
<P>
   I say again: We should have known better. Baseball players
always recite cliches, saying that the long season should be played
day by day by day. Maybe everyone got tired of the boring remarks,
because not many people listened during McGwire Week. In a season
when McGwire and Sosa have gone on home run binges, why anoint
McGwire as a history-maker when there was plenty of baseball to be
played? Now he is bothered by back spasms, while Sosa seems to be
getting hot again. Sixty-one has lost its aura. The new standard
will be near 70. And it could be held by Sosa. Or McGwire. Or both.
We won't know until the end of this month. Until such time, both
men should be seen as Co-Home Run Kings. In Waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning, the phones were buzzing in the Globe's sports
department. Several angry callers wanted to know why McGwire got
pages to himself as well as his own special section while Sosa got
a comparative slap on the back. Many said that what they perceived
to be a slight was racist and that they were canceling their
subscriptions.
</P>
<P>
   I don't agree with them, but I don't blame them. I also do not
think their rage is overblown, nor reactionary, nor foolish. There
is a strong element that doesn't want a dark-skinned man to set the
home run record. Anyone who doesn't believe that should step
outside and smell the fumes of America. And a legitimate argument
can certainly be made that one man got more publicity than the
other even though they accomplished the same thing. But I also
believe that if the order were reversed _ if Sosa had hit 62 first
_ Sosa would have received all the attention that McGwire got,
while McGwire would have been the secondary newsmaker.
</P>
<P>
   While in Pittsburgh, Sosa was asked about a national poll. It
indicated that most Americans wanted McGwire to set the sacred
record, not him. He was asked if he thought the fact that he is a
black man from the Dominican Republic had anything to do with it.
He said no. He said he expects Americans to root for McGwire
because McGwire is American. Good analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The rush to crown an all-time home run champion is truly a
modern American tale. Which is to say that the hype of the moment
came to a crescendo and erased reason. Judgment, too. We all
approached the story wrong, didn't we? This year, the person
reaching 60 or 61 or 62 (itals)first(unitals) was irrelevant. It
was definitely worth the coverage it received, since the record
stood for 37 years. But no one should have been talking about the
mark and asking, as I heard some people asking, how long the mark
would stand. (itals)How long will it stand?(unitals) Well, try five
days. And when someone hits 63, that may not stand for 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that many of us have missed the beauty of the
history we are now witnessing. The current record that is being set
and reset has very little to do with the one Maris set in 1961,
save for the number: 61. That's what makes this home run race so
intriguing. In the end, Maris did not have someone chasing down the
record with him. Maybe his hair wouldn't have fallen out and he
wouldn't have become sullen if he had ESPN, endorsement
opportunities, and a microphone pointing in his direction into
which he says, ``I'm going to Disney World.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a season-long pursuit. We do not know what the number to
beat is; we have to wait. We do not know what number Ken Griffey,
McGwire, and Sosa will be asked about at the beginning of Spring
Training '99; we have to wait. And since both men are having great
seasons in the same league, we even have to wait to say who will be
the National League MVP (I would give it to Sosa).
</P>
<P>
   We should have known better. The party's music never stopped.
People just left early. If Selig was going to be in St. Louis, he
should have been in Chicago, too. Even Bill Clinton took time away
from his very, um, busy office schedule to call McGwire
(itals)and(unitals) Sosa after they hit their 62d. We are watching
the pursuit of a great record. We won't know how great it is and
who is the greatest until the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Michael Holley is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
