<HEADER>
A4940 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUCHWALD-PROFILE-ART-     09-14 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHWALD-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART BUCHWALD: FUNNY GUY WITH A MELANCHOLY BENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(JT) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The front desk of the Regency Hotel, home of the Park
Avenue power breakfast, is in full-throated warble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, Mr. Buchwald!''
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you, Mr. Buchwald?''
</P>
<P>
   Art Buchwald, the humor columnist and Washington institution who
last week made the Regency _ and New York _ his official home,
loves the fuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``See?'' he said. ``I told you they take care of me.'' Or, as he
said over breakfast: ``I think if I did it again, I'm not sure, but
I'd marry a concierge.''
</P>
<P>
   This is obviously a story about a famous columnist forever
associated with Washington who surprises everyone and moves to New
York, his childhood home. A lot of it is funny. Buchwald, for
example, addressed the question of what it's like going out with
women when you're 72: ``The definition of dating now is very weird.
If you say you're dating, does that mean you're going to bed with
someone? If it means you're going to the movies with someone, then,
yes, I'm dating.''
</P>
<P>
   This is also a story about a victim of depression who left his
wife of 40 years, Ann, but went back to her as she was dying of
cancer, in 1994. A lot of it is not so funny. ``There are some
mornings when I say I wish I could have a woman who could pack for
me,'' Buchwald said. ``Or a woman who says, `We're going to Bedford
today,' and I say, `Oh, is that where we're going?' When you're not
married, no one tells you where to go. There's no center.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Buchwald is marrying the funny and not-so-funny
in a book-in-progress, ``Stella in Heaven: Almost a Novel,'' about
a dead wife who is running her husband's life from the clouds.
</P>
<P>
   And what is Stella telling Buchwald now?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, there's some discussion about finding another wife,''
Buchwald said. ``The problem is, the ones she selects for me are
not too good, because she doesn't want them to be better than she
is.'' Stella's search committee did find one good prospect,
Buchwald said, but she turned out to be a kleptomaniac. ``They also
selected a motorcycle policewoman for me,'' Buchwald said. ``And
she's pretty nice, except she's got herpes.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchwald joked last week in the Regency's dining room, quiet
after the departure of the dry-toast executive crowd. ``This room
we're sitting in now, this is the power room,'' Buchwald said. ``I
would like some of it to rub off on me.'' Buchwald said the place
reminded him of the Sans Souci, the original Washington power
restaurant, long closed, that was his second home.
</P>
<P>
   Here are his reasons for leaving Washington: ``After a certain
amount of time, there's nothing new. Restaurants are the same,
stores are the same, your buddies are the same. And some of them
disappear on you.'' His close friend Edward Bennett Williams, the
Washington lawyer, has died. Another close friend, Ben Bradlee, the
former editor of The Washington Post, has a family. ``The circle
was getting smaller,'' Buchwald said. ``Maybe it's me, maybe it's
them. But I'm a bachelor.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that his column, syndicated in 350 newspapers,
was moved off the front of The Washington Post's Style section in
the spring. ``They were very nice about it,'' Buchwald said. ``They
didn't have to be.'' Friends say Buchwald has always known when
it's time to move on. ``I do think one of the purposes of my move
was to keep going,'' Buchwald said. He'll continue his 400-word,
twice-weekly column of political satire from New York, even though
one of the biggest political sex scandals in history is unfolding
in his old home. ``I can sit up here and know as much as people in
Washington,'' Buchwald said, crediting CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Buchwald has good friends here _ Mike Wallace, the ``60
Minutes'' correspondent, and the author William Styron, who lives
in Connecticut. All three men have suffered from depression; Styron
wrote a successful book about his. ``He and I had depressions at
the same time,'' Buchwald said. ``And the only difference is, he
made a million on his, and I didn't make a dime on mine. We argue
about who had the worst depression. He says his was 9.9 on the
Richter scale, and mine was a rainy day at Disneyland.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchwald's childhood was not funny at all. To know that, all you
have to do is read the first paragraph of his 1993 memoir,
``Leaving Home:''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shortly after I was born, my mother was taken away from me or
I was taken away from my mother. This was done because she was
mentally ill. She suffered from severe chronic depression, which
required that she be committed to a private sanitarium. She never
recovered and, eventually, when my father ran out of money, she was
placed in a state hospital in upper New York for 35 years _ the
rest of her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchwald's father couldn't take care of him, so Buchwald spent
his childhood in foster homes. He joined the Marines, became a
columnist in Paris, fell in love with Ann, adopted three children,
became a columnist in Washington and won the Pulitzer Prize for
commentary in 1982. In ``Leaving Home,'' he wrote: ``People ask
what I am really trying to do with humor. The answer is, `I'm
getting even.'''
</P>
<P>
   Buchwald now works in his two-room suite at the Regency, and has
an office at Newsweek magazine. He said he needs a new secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know anybody?'' he asked. ``I need somebody to take
over my life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
