<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4946 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GIANTS-RAIDERS-NY     09-14 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-RAIDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS: OUTPLAYED ON THE FIELD AND ON THE SIDELINES AS WELL  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The Oakland Raiders say the Giants arrived and
expected the Raiders to fall flat on Sunday. After six straight
losses, including this season's opener, the Raiders were a basket
case. And not a good football team.
</P>
<P>
   It was not that simple.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders are not a Super Bowl-caliber team, but they have
plenty of good players, especially on offense. They certainly have
more speed than the Giants, and in their 20-17 victory, the Oakland
defense outplayed the Giants' strength _ their defense.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have plenty to ponder. Three areas require tough
scrutiny. Finding answers will save the Giants heartburn over their
next 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE RUNNING GAME &LR;  _ This team is built on the run. It seemingly
has always been that way with this franchise. But when the running
game goes kaput, frequently the Giants do, too. On seven of their
13 possessions on Sunday, they offered three plays and a punt.
There were 23 carries for 71 yards, an average of 3.1 yards a gain.
</P>
<P>
   When Napoleon Kaufman dashed through the middle of the Giants'
defense for a sensational 80-yard touchdown run to open the game,
he reminded the Giants of something they don't have _ pure speed in
the backfield. Tiki Barber gives them something, but he looks
heavier and a step slower this season than last year as a rookie.
Sometimes younger players between their first and second seasons
put on weight thinking they must be bigger to play in the National
Football League. Whether this is the case with Barber, he and none
of the other Giants backs hit the holes with gusto on Sunday. They
were laboring.
</P>
<P>
   This brings us to Tyrone Wheatley, who has not played in the
first two games. He has to get a shot now. In the long run, he
boosts the Giants' rushing game.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THIRD-DOWN PLAYS &LR;  _ The Giants were 1 of 14 on third-down
conversions. They made only three rushing first downs. They gained
more first downs via Raiders penalties (four).
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, the Raiders converted 8 of 18 third-down
situations and had 5 first downs rushing and 15 more passing. They
kept finding holes in the Giants' defense, especially the
secondary, for big plays on third downs. It was as if the Giants
fell asleep after big sacks that put the Raiders in third-and-long
situations. More attention is required.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COACHING &LR;  _ The players weren't ready for the Raiders and the
coaching staff wasn't, either. The calls on offense, especially
when the Giants attempted to run wide, were widely anticipated. It
was no accident that on Kaufman's run, the Raiders recognized the
defensive set and exploited it. The Giants gave a strong rush look
and backed off. The Raiders slammed the Giants up the middle before
they could recover.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Fassel, the Giants' head coach, and John Fox, the defensive
coordinator, used to be Raiders coaches. The Raiders attacked both
of them in play-calling as if they knew them well. Obviously, they
did. And the Giants' Fassel and Fox didn't respond adequately.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Raiders' safeties kept cheating toward the line
to offer run support, and all the Giants needed to do to make them
pay was run the ball up the middle, toss it back to the quarterback
and then throw deep. That would have burned the safeties. Also, the
Giants' speediest player, receiver David Patten, didn't touch the
ball enough to stretch the defense. Receiver Amani Toomer could
have provided more answers. And receiver Chris Calloway caught a
20-yard touchdown pass but had only 3 other catches for 23 yards.
Not enough balls were thrown his way.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' defense seemed so concerned with giving up a big
play to the speedy James Jett that it left Tim Brown alone too
often in single coverage. He made a touchdown grab of 22 yards in
man-to-man coverage provided by Conrad Hamilton. In the fourth
quarter, Brown made a 29-yard catch on third-and-8 with Carlton
Gray covering him alone down the sideline. Gray joined the Giants
only last Wednesday. Brown burned the Giants with 6 catches for 127
yards.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, the Giants will do their homework and prepare for
Dallas on Monday night with a rebound in mind. Heads might not
roll. It's early. But attention to these details is essential.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
