<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4948 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALLACE-ALABAMA-1STLD     09-14 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLACE-ALABAMA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING A LOVED _ AND HATED _ GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Adds 12 grafs at end. Inserts ``who is white'' in 3rd graf
and in graf that begins ``He was a fairly.'' No other changes.)   (lb) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ For 65-year-old James Harper, sitting on his
tiny front porch in West Anniston with the day still brand-new, the
news that George Wallace was dead caused him to lower his eyes and
catch his breath for a second, as if some last, dying chorus of
``Dixie'' had lodged in his throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know,'' he said. ``You here to talk about him? Sit
down. I voted for him. Every time. I liked him standing up there in
that school door, by God,'' he said, referring to Wallace's stand
in the doorway to prevent integration at the University of Alabama
on June 11, 1963.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the federals had to move him,'' said Harper, who is white,
and then he grinned. ``He was a man, by God. He wasn't no boy.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he was asked if he still respected the former governor
after a would-be-assassin's bullet crippled him in 1972, after old
age and history mellowed him and even made him say he was sorry,
Harper seemed not to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved that man,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To many in Alabama _ the people who hated, feared or loved him _
that frail, apologetic old man who died Sunday night in Montgomery
failed to register in their memories as vividly as the young, fiery
one with slicked-back hair and rigid finger stabbing the air, the
one who promised ``segregation forever.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people said they could forgive him, and would even pray
for him, but many of them said they just wish he could have learned
he was wrong a lot sooner, and led his state out of racial hatred,
instead of into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody can have my forgiveness if they ask the Lord to
forgive them,'' said 87-year-old John Lilley, making his way slowly
down Birmingham's 20th Street with the help of a cane.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did what he did to stay on the good side of the white
people. He did it to keep his job. But I forgive him.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled a little when he was asked if the pain-racked,
paralyzed man had found peace in death. ``I don't know if George
Wallace is in heaven,'' said Lilley, walking away. ``The only thing
I know is he's been in hell long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Young people, whites and blacks, know only the historical
Wallace, and spoke of him the way they would have spoken of a
Confederate statue on the courthouse lawn. But across the state,
people who are old enough to remember a time before his wheelchair
and who heard his voice before it was slurred, talk as if he was
not some distant politician in Montgomery but someone who protected
them, or threatened them. They take him personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember being at ball games and having my parents come and
get us because they had heard the Klan was coming,'' said Ernestine
Abraham, who grew up in Birmingham in the 1960s. ``He could have
changed that. He had the power, and could have turned that tide. He
didn't,'' said Ms. Abraham, now 44 and an office manager at a
Birmingham bank.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had not been hurt, he never would have changed,'' she
said. And by then, it was too late, she said, because too many
people had been hurt in the era of racism that he had prospered in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man in the chair didn't matter,'' she said. ``The young
man who stood in the schoolhouse door mattered.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess,'' she said, ``he didn't have the courage to do it,
then.''
</P>
<P>
   As she talked, the first of the rush-hour traffic was beginning
to creep through downtown Birmingham, past Kelly Ingram Park where
marchers were once torn by police dogs and blown along sidewalks
like leaves by powerful fire hoses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
</TEXT>
