</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIMINATE-CLINTON-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
Monday, Sept. 14, 1998
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Editors: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CLINTON-ECONOMY (New York) _ The CLINTON-ECONOMY story will not
move tonight on the Hearst News wire service. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0469 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4951 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALLACE-ALABAMA-1STLD     09-14 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLACE-ALABAMA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BIRMINGHAM, Ala.: fire hoses.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wallace is very personal, here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up here when you couldn't sit here, and you couldn't
eat there, and you had to sit in the last row,'' said Rita
Kendrick, 50, who works for Alabama Power in downtown Birmingham.
``He tried to keep it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   But she believes he was sorry, that it was not just politics
when he begged for forgiveness later in his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a big heart to forgive him,'' she said. ``I
can, but it's hard.''
</P>
<P>
   But the people who gave him his power, families who always voted
for him and who wept when he lay bleeding on the asphalt of a
Maryland shopping center, loved him then and now.
</P>
<P>
   They loved him when he was unrepentant, because he told them to
stand up and be proud. For many of the people in his power base,
the poor farmers and factory workers who had always lived beneath
the disdain of the aristocrats, his message was stronger than
moonshine.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you'd hear him talk, you knew he was for you and for
Alabama,'' said Gary Heathcock, a 46-year-old steelworker who lives
in Alexandria. ``My daddy always voted for him,'' he said, and once
the family even voted for Wallace's wife, Lurleen. It was really a
vote for George.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them had never been told that they were even good enough
for their place in Southern society, let alone better than anyone,
and now there was this man moving from town to town on the campaign
trail preaching to the crowded auditoriums and county fairs that
they were superior to a whole race of people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove trucks for 30 years, and I worked in the pipe shop,''
said James Harper of West Anniston. ``Every time I wrote him a
letter, he wrote me back. I worshipped the ground he walked on.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not, said some of his older white supporters, that they
always agreed with him. Sometimes, said 76-year-old Ed Mullinax of
Anniston, ``I had to vote for him because he was the only one
running.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a fairly good fellow who had his faults,'' said
Mullinax, who is white, a retired millwright. ``It was a different
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Blacks voted for him, as early as 1958, because they saw him as
a lesser evil. Cicero Bynum, a retired steelworker from Gadsden,
remembers meeting Wallace during the 1958 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did vote for him in 1958 because I couldn't vote for John
Patterson,'' said Bynum, 69. ``He was more evil than Wallace at
that particular time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met with him when he was trying to drum up support. They
brought him in the back door of the building so the white folks
wouldn't see him coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace would repay them by claiming he lost because was
``out-niggered'' _ too soft on segregation _ and would vow never to
let it happen again.
</P>
<P>
   But in a way, said Bynum, Wallace's defiance served them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he hadn't made that stand in the schoolhouse door, we
wouldn't have come as far as we've come,'' he said. ``Our problems
wouldn't have been shown around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, aging warriors in that struggle for civil
rights graciously spoke of Wallace as a changed man, as a sort of
tragic figure who was swallowed in a whirlwind of his own creation.
Historians said he was the perfect enemy, who gave the people who
believed in change someone to hate.
</P>
<P>
   If that is true, then they needed each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``All throughout history, if you have an ugly enemy, if your
enemy is cruel and monstrous or you can paint him as a monster,''
the battle over people's conscience can be won, said the Rev.
Joseph Lowery, the past president of the Southern Christian
Leadership Council and one of the Rev. Martin Luther King's chief
aides in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't need to do that. We just had to reveal him,'' he
said. ``He did reveal himself, for that matter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So he will wear that,'' said Lowery. ``Although I'm sure that
there are some people who will remember that like the prodigal son,
he came to himself.''
</P>
<P>
   He points out that Wallace had once been a politician in the
mold of Jim Folsom, the more moderate former governor. And as he
became older and admitted his mistakes, he seemed to try to return
to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beginning was like the end,'' Lowery said.
</P>
<P>
   Many, especially young people, will remember only the one in the
middle, the demagogue.
</P>
<P>
   Cedrick Rembert, a black junior at the University of Alabama,
knows only that legacy of division. ``I don't hate him,'' he said,
but ``I have never heard anything positive about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Some will not remember him at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think he's going to have a legacy,'' said
Angela Davis, a black sophomore at the University of South Alabama
in Mobile. ``There are a lot of people on campus who don't even
know who he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper knows.
</P>
<P>
   His Wallace never got old, never capitulated. His Wallace was
almost president.
</P>
<P>
   And while Wallace may have apologized for what he did, Harper
will not apologize for the pride he once felt at being part of his
climb, his legend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worshipped the ground he walked on,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
