<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maddux injury traced to triceps
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- It's not Greg Maddux's armpit. It's the top of his
right tricep. And it's much better, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fine. I'll be there,'' Maddux said whan asked if he'll
make his next start.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux came out of Sunday's game after 83 pitches, 30 fewer than
his previous start in Montreal, when he first developed some
soreness where the triceps tapers into the armpit area. He reported
Monday feeling much better than he did after the Montreal game and
expects to be ready for his next scheduled start Friday in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should always be concerned,'' said manager Bobby Cox.
``But where it's located, it's not life-threatening.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux will under go a week of therapy _ ultrasound,
eletro-stimulation, stretching _ and reiterated his premature
departure from Sunday's game after six innings was nothing more
than precautionary. The fact that he had put together a string of
10 scoreless innings before leaving Sunday's game implies he has
regained his form. Maddux (17-8) is winless in his last four starts
and is 5-6 in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a thing where it's that time of the year and you
have to think what's in front of us,'' he said. ``You're better
safe than sorry. I know we're fighting to have the best record.''
</P>
<P>
   Rotating the rotation
</P>
<P>
   Cox's pitching plans are about to change by week's end. Kevin
Millwood will move to the bullpen to prepare for the postseason and
the club will look for an opportunity to skip John Smoltz, as the
schedule allows, to give his elbow a break. That will give rookie
left-hander Bruce Chen at least one and probably two more starts
before the regular season ends.
</P>
<P>
   While Smoltz will make his next scheduled start Wednesday and
then wait to see how the final 11 days of the season break down, as
well as how the postseason rotation sets up, before his plans are
set, Millwood becomes a reliever after his start tonight. He has
thrown just two relief innings all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, it's not much of a change. You still have to go
out and pitch,'' Millwood said. ``Mentally, it's a little
different. As a starter, you have to think about setting up
hitters. In the bullpen, you go hard all the time and you don't
have to pace yourself at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The case for Norm
</P>
<P>
   After yielding a run in his Braves debut Aug. 12, reliever Norm
Charlton has strung together six scoreless appearances entering
Monday night. His candidacy for the postseason roster is best
stated in his 1.35 ERA, the lowest on the team. If Kerry
Lightenberg, Rudy Seanez and Millwood have October reservations
wrapped up, has Charlton earned one of the remaining three spots?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any idea,'' he said. ``It's up to me and it's not
up to me. It's up to me, based on the way I go out there and pitch.
It's not up to me because it's not my decision.''
</P>
<P>
   With one single and three walks yielded in his last 5 2/3
innings, Charlton has just one strikeout as a Brave but the league
is only hitting .190 against him. This has been his best stretch of
work all season. He never went more than five innings with
Baltimore without yielding a run and had a 6.94 ERA when the
Orioles released him. Charlton still is not satisfied with this
work here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really haven't thrown breaking balls at all,'' he said.
``They've all been situtations where we need to gets guys out and
they're swinging at the first or second pitch and making an out, or
I'm behind 1-0 and I'm not in a situation where I'm going to throw
a breaking ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Crunch time
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Keith Lockhart could not play Monday night
because of continued right hamstring problem. He has started in
just three of 13 games this month and with the postseason set to
begin two weeks from today, there is a growing concern that the
second baseman who started 83 games this year may not be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fun,'' Lockhart said. ``It's different from the
shoulder, where you can play with what pain you can tolerate. A
hamstring you really have no control over. That's one where the
body will tell you when you can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
