<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Byrd turns into a find for Phillies
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- He has a new job, a new nickname and, best of all, a
future. Yet of all the goodness that has come Paul Byrd's way
recently, the best of all was the bike ride.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 18, Byrd was riding an exercise bicycle in the Phillies'
weight room in Veterans Stadium. Suddenly, he had company on the
bike beside him. A 6-foot-10 left-hander sat down and starting
pedaling. ``Man,'' Randy Johnson asked, ``where have you been?''
</P>
<P>
   The night before, Byrd was on the mound, making his first start
since being waived by Atlanta while at Class AAA Richmond and
claimed by Philadelphia Aug. 14. ``They said, `Go out there and
just enjoy yourself,' '' Bird recalled. ``I wanted to win. It was
the opportunity of a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Some opportunity: Paul Byrd, ex-Met, ex-Brave, waived at
Richmond to make room for Norm Charlton, vs. Randy Johnson, the
1995 AL Cy Young winner who'd gone 3-0 since being traded from
Seattle and was fresh off consecutive shutouts. Yet on the exercise
bike, all Johnson could do was gush about Byrd. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the Big Unit sitting next to me and saying he's really
impressed with my stuff,'' said Byrd, who'd beaten Johnson and the
Astros 4-0 on a four-hitter. ``That really did a lot for my
confidence, even more than how I pitched against the Astros.''
</P>
<P>
   That was merely the new beginning. In his next start, Byrd threw
another complete game, holding the potent Rockies to five hits and
just one run. For all that, Byrd was named the National League
player of the week.
</P>
<P>
   This from a guy the Phillies claimed because they needed another
arm to give them some innings to finish out the season. Yet in six
starts with Philadelphia, Byrd has five quality starts, a 4-2
record, a 2.84 ERA and a nickname: ``Frasier,'' for his resemblance
to actor Kelsey Grammer. He knows he has stunned people. After his
only bad outing (Aug. 27, when the Padres rocked him for nine hits
and seven runs in 5 2/3 innings), Byrd approached his next start as
a proverbial big game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know everybody's waiting for the wheels to fall off,'' he
said after limiting the Dodgers to two hits and a run in six
innings. Byrd has won his last two starts, going seven innings
Sunday (three hits, one run) to beat Pittsburgh 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got him off the waiver wire and I don't think you expect to
get a 20-game winner there,'' manager Terry Francona said. ``But
he's certainly pitched his way into our plans. ... My feeling right
now is that he isn't a fluke.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are shocked but I've never had a shot in the big
leagues where I got the ball every five days,'' said Byrd, who was
4-4 with a 5.26 ERA last season while with Atlanta, then 0-0, 13.50
in one appearance this year before going 5-5, 3.69 in 17 starts in
Richmond. ``I was really pleased (Philadelphia) wanted to give me a
shot as a starter. I felt I could start in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I didn't like about the Braves was there was no
opportunity for me. I enjoyed Bobby (Cox) and the coaches, the
front office, the players, but middle relief in Atlanta is no job
at all. But everybody here's happy for me. Makes me feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
