<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-ANDRO-BAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BILL TO BAN MCGWIRE DRUG  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ New Jersey would become the first state to ban
sales to minors of androstenedione, the testosterone-boosting
hormone used by Mark McGwire, under a bipartisan bill introduced
Monday in the State Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Herbert Conaway, a Democrat from Delran who
co-sponsored the bill, said that children might be tempted to
imitate the record-breaking home run hitter. Conaway, a doctor,
said that there have not been adequate safety studies of the drug,
which has been banned by the International Olympic Committee and
the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark McGwire is a grown man and is free to decide what legal
substance he puts into his body,'' Conaway said in a statement.
``But as a highly respected role model to millions of kids, his
actions could send the wrong message: that improved performance on
the field is worth the health risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, people who sold or offered androstenedione to
minors would be fined $250 for a first offense, $500 for a second
offense and $1,000 thereafter. The bill would not make it illegal
for children to possess or use the drug, however. The measure now
goes to the Assembly Health Committee for consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Courtney, a spokesman for Major League Baseball, declined to
comment on the bill. He noted that last month league doctors began
a review of unregulated nutritional supplements.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
