<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGRY FASSEL LOWERS THE BOOM ON BOTH OFFENSE AND DEFENSE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The head coach was red-faced and angry,
the offensive linemen were under siege again, jobs were being lost
in the defensive secondary and the linebackers were all limping.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was having a very good day inside the Giants' locker room
on the day after the team's 20-17 loss to the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   Weary from their overnight flight from the West Coast, players
and coaches Monday afternoon trudged into the videotape rooms,
where they studied their Sunday mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Fassel promised it would be a long, censorious
viewing. No one expected to be home in time for dinner _ if they
had the stomach to eat after watching a performance filled with 15
Giants penalties, just 71 yards rushing and no pass play longer
than 20 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be smiling around this group for quite a
while,'' Fassel said. ``And I'm not talking about just this week.
They got my dander up, and it's going to stay up for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel has many complaints, but most of all he singled out the
offensive line. ``Poor execution, poor everything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the coach said that the playing time of the rookie safety
Shaun Williams would be reduced. Carlton Gray, a new cornerback,
will take Williams' place in the nickel defense packages beginning
with Monday's game against the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel then went on to criticize just about everyone on the
team, except quarterback Danny Kanell, running back Tiki Barber,
tackle Roman Oben and three defensive players _ ends Michael
Strahan and Chad Bratzke and cornerback Phillippi Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Of the rest of the team, Fassel said, ``They were asleep at the
wheel.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel put the blame for the Giants' running-game woes on the
line, which he said routinely missed its assignments. He suggested
that there would be changes on the line if play did not improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll play somebody else,'' he said. ``I don't care who they
are.''
</P>
<P>
   But the possibilities at any of the line positions have been
tried before: the reserve Jerry Reynolds at tackle for Scott Gragg
or center Derek Engler for the starter Lance Scott. Beyond the
threats, the real consensus is that the starting five on the line,
a group that worked together effectively last season, will have to
find a way to come together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running the football and blocking for it is an attitude,'' the
Giants' offensive line coach, John Matsko, said. ``We have to have
more determination to get that job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel played down his comments after Sunday's game about using
running back Tyrone Wheatley this week against Dallas. Fassel
reaffirmed that it was a possibility, but his praise of Barber made
it plain that Wheatley was not likely to step into the starting
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, Wheatley will take the place of the backup running
back Gary Brown. Brown has 21 yards on 10 carries in two games this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel said little about the injuries to linebackers Jessie
Armstead (sprained ankle), Scott Galyon (Achilles' tendon soreness
and calf-muscle strain), Corey Widmer (strained knee) and Marcus
Buckley (bruised hip).
</P>
<P>
   But it appears that Galyon may not be ready for the Cowboys and
that is a significant loss because Galyon is the team's most
dependable linebacker in pass coverage.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he is Armstead's backup, and Armstead could have
used a backup Sunday. Armstead was not himself against the Raiders
and would have sat out much of the game had Galyon been able to
play.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries to Widmer and Buckley are not considered serious.
</P>
<P>
   In so many ways, the Giants were a team licking its wounds
Monday, wondering what went wrong and wondering whether they were
better prepared for early season adversity than the 1997 Giants,
who won their opener and then slid to 1-3.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel said he was confident that this year's team was
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel confident in how they will react,'' he said. ``Last
year, I didn't know how they would react.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, heading to Oakland knowing it would take discipline to
defeat the unpredictable and generally undisciplined Raiders, the
Giants jumped offside six times. They converted on just 1 of 14
third-down plays.
</P>
<P>
   The defense forced just one turnover. There was no downfield
threat in the passing game and barely time in the pocket for Kanell
to consider the slower developing, long pass plays.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, the Giants gave up an 80-yard touchdown run on the
first play from scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``No less than five guys made mental mistakes on that play,''
Fassel said.
</P>
<P>
   Responsibilities were ignored, rotations missed based on the
formation and motion, and assignments botched once the play began.
Seventeen seconds later, the Giants trailed by 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   If only it had been the lone lapse for the Giants' vaunted
defense. But the Raiders had 414 total yards and were successful on
8 of 18 third-down plays _ some of them very long third-down plays.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel would not say whether he was contemplating any other
lineup changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't make decisions when I'm angry and I'm tired,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
