<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-BUSINESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIECES OF HISTORY, OR JUST RUINING IT?  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the baseball Hall of Fame preserves history by stocking up on
bats, balls, jerseys and other artifacts connected to Mark McGwire
and Sammy Sosa, one company is chopping history into tiny bits.
</P>
<P>
   The Upper Deck Co. is carving a bat Babe Ruth used in games into
200 pieces for eventual mounting on trading cards, which will be
inserted into hundreds of thousands of 1999 card packs.
</P>
<P>
   Can collectors possibly covet one two-hundredth of a bat? Will
the richest collectors try to corner the slivers to try to
reconstruct the bat?
</P>
<P>
   It would seem that any piece of memorabilia connected to Ruth _
no matter how small _ deserves to be kept intact. That's the way it
is with history. You want to guard it, not carve it into
1{-by-1{-inch pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a Ruth bat should not be mistaken for an artistic
masterpiece, it deserves preservation, not a fate determined by a
woodcutter. ``It goes against everything we would do, to grind up
something, rather than preserve it,'' said John Ralph, a spokesman
for the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   How does Upper Deck justify its repugnant merchandising? On two
grounds. First, according to its documentation, Ruth did nothing
momentous with the bat. Second, such rare memorabilia is expensive
_ Upper Deck paid $23,000 for the bat _ so chopping it up lets the
poor folk own a tiny part of a legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our way to spread the wealth,'' said Mary Mancera, an
Upper Deck spokeswoman. Ah, desecration for the public benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Mancera called the company's chopping-block mode of marketing
``product innovation.'' She offered a splendid assurance that if
this were the last game-used Ruth bat left, the company would not
cut it up. The company's research found that 50 to 100 Ruth bats
are still around.
</P>
<P>
   So, chop the company must, as long as there is a remaining
supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how it works sometimes,'' Mancera said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't matter if there were 5 or 50 Ruth bats left,''
Ralph said. ``They all need to be preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   Upper Deck purchased a Michael Jordan jersey last month for
$26,400 and will cut it into 138 swaths to be inserted into card
packs. But Jordan is alive and, unless he retires, still playing
and creating new game-worn memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth, deceased, hasn't swung a bat in a real game in 63 years.
Now, one bat with which he might have got a hit _ or maybe taken a
mighty whiff on a third strike _ is being desecrated, not
preserved.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in Upper Deck's parlance, it is ``pieces of history.''
</P>
<P>
   Pieces of shame.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The TV Home Run Derby &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Once Mark McGwire hit his 62d home run last Tuesday, the rush
for Fox and ESPN to add more games involving McGwire and Sammy Sosa
abated.
</P>
<P>
   But when Sosa hit No. 62, the frenzy returned. ESPN will carry
the Pittsburgh-St. Louis game at 8 p.m. Wednesday on ESPN2 and the
Chicago Cubs-San Diego game at 10:30 p.m. on ESPN, and is looking
for any opening it can find. Fox is looking to add Cubs or
Cardinals games to its Saturday afternoon slots, to Fox Sports Net
on Thursday nights and to FX on Saturday nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to see the games, whether it's home run 64 or
67,'' said Dick Glover, an ESPN executive vice president. ``You
want to take advantage of these opportunities. Maybe the 63d home
run will last for another 37 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our initial interest was in who would break the record,'' said
Vince Wladika, a Fox spokesman. ``Now, it's who will hold the
record.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, ESPN cut into its programming to carry live each of
Sosa's at-bats and Sosa's news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Fox Sports Net _ which asked, ``Where would you
turn for the best sports news?'' in newspaper ads Monday _ showed
taped cut-ins of the home runs. It showed none of the news
conference on its cable affiliates like the MSG Network (which
showed soccer) and Fox Sports New York (which carried motorcycle
racing) until its Fox Sports News came on hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gray area whether more people will see a press
conference in our news or in the middle of a soccer game,'' said
Arthur Smith, executive vice president of Fox Sports Net. ``The
home runs are the news, the press conference is reaction to the
news. His reaction is just as valid two hours later.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Fox Sports Net and Fox Sports News, its news operation,
are to be taken seriously, they must carry news as it happens, not
when it's convenient.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
