<HEADER>
A4962 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXASQUARTERBACK-     09-14 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASQUARTERBACK-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
AUSTIN _ There were no kind words for Major Applewhite around the
University of Texas campus Monday. No one stopped him to offer best
wishes _ or condolences. No one stopped him at all.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not that Applewhite's fellow students don't care about such
things as who starts at quarterback. Applewhite, however, is about
as anonymous as a Texas quarterback can be. And at a glance, there
is no chance they would guess that the slender, freckled redhead in
front of them is a football player.
</P>
<P>
   When he was in high school, Applewhite was called ``Opie,''
apparently not looking quite tough enough to be Richie. On his
recruiting visit to Texas, he said, linebacker Cedric Mitchell
``thought I was a fraternity guy hanging around the hotel to see
what recruits were in.'' His role model at quarterback is not quite
Brett Favre or John Elway. It's former Alabama role player Jay
Barker.
</P>
<P>
   But Richard Walton, who in two weeks had given Texas the Big
12's top passing offense, is out for four to six weeks with a
fractured right hand. And Applewhite, a redshirt freshman with no
career starts and seven career passes, will take over when the
Longhorns face No. 5 Kansas State and the nation's top-rated
defense Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Friends have peppered Applewhite with questions about his state
of mind, now that he finds himself a starting quarterback awaiting
such a difficult baptism.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody else has seemed to notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know who I am,'' Applewhite said. ``They just see a
6-foot-tall, redheaded kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas coaches, however, see a player who adjusted to a new
offense remarkably quickly. And though he is not as strong-armed or
experienced as Walton, Applewhite has had his moments in the
Longhorns' two games.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite's appearances were just cameos, but in two games he
has completed five of seven passes for 59 yards. He led a pair of
scoring drives against UCLA on Saturday and even had the presence
of mind to notice the Bruins' starters were still in the game and
still blitzing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very intense about his football,'' Texas coach Mack Brown
said. ``He takes great pride in knowing what to do, where to go. He
watches football all the time. It's not like he hasn't prepared for
this time. He studied film every day in spring practices like he
had a game that night. He's very competitive. I think he's very
confident. I've never walked around him where I didn't think he
felt good about himself, which is a great trait for a college
football player, especially a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity for him. There's pressure on all of
us. But the opportunity is great if he plays well and helps us win
the football game. Maybe you got this great opportunity before you
were ready for it. But you'd better go take advantage of it. That's
what we need Major to do.''
</P>
<P>
   His position as the Texas starter is unexpected for reasons
beyond the injury to Walton or Applewhite's physical appearance.
</P>
<P>
   He was a lifelong Alabama fan, named after former Crimson Tide
running back Major Ogilvie. Making the 5{-hour ride from his home
in Baton Rouge, La., to Tuscaloosa _ or the 6{-hour drive to
Birmingham _ was a family ritual. After one game when he was an
eighth-grader, Applewhite slipped into the Alabama locker room to
beg for a few sweaty gloves and wristbands. He posed for a
photograph with Barker and celebrated when Barker led 'Bama to the
1993 national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite prayed for a chance to play for the Tide. But when
Applewhite was a popular recruit, pursued by Texas, LSU, Texas A&AMP;M
and Mississippi State, Alabama was in the middle of a coaching
change after Gene Stallings' retirement and told him it would not
sign a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite promptly changed his plans and committed to Texas
A&AMP;M. But when Steve Ensminger was fired as the Aggies' offensive
coordinator after the 1996 season, Applewhite changed his mind
again and committed to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, unanswered prayers work out best,'' he said. ``This
is my love now. I love Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   But his love had gone unrequited on the depth chart. He and Greg
Cicero were running even for the backup position until Cicero tore
knee ligaments in a scrimmage. Recruit Adam Dunn, who will now be
Applewhite's backup, was considered the Texas quarterback of the
future.
</P>
<P>
   But Applewhite will start Saturday and likely for a month to
come. And the Longhorns seem comfortable with the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's smart, and he knows football,'' UT defensive tackle Casey
Hampton said. ``Nothing he does surprises me, because I know he
knows the game.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows enough to understand how difficult his charge will be.
But a player who became a quarterback only because an eighth-grade
teammate fell and fractured a bone in his right hand looks at
facing the nation's top defense as a boon rather than a burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a tough spot to be in,'' Applewhite said.
``But I enjoy it. I wouldn't want to play football if we played a
softy every week and beat teams 66-0. I'll enjoy playing a team
like this. It's going to be a great experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
