<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLEY HAS TRYING WEEK AS JET STARTER  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Glenn Foley's numbers as a starter aren't
pretty _ 1-6 in his career _ and the Jets have begun this season
0-2. Foley will start his third consecutive game on Sunday for the
first time as a pro. This week will be a big test for Foley.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those things where your quarterback has to be a
fighter,'' Coach Bill Parcells said. ``One of the lead fighters. He
has to demonstrate to the team that he is going to respond. And I
think he will.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has been unhappy with many of Foley's passing decisions
over the two games _ especially throwing into double coverage in
the end zone in Sunday's 24-10 loss to the Baltimore Ravens. ``His
performance was excellent the first half, no question,'' Parcells
said. ``You couldn't throw the ball too much better.'' Foley,
without a running game from Curtis Martin, was 13 for 18 for 177
yards and a touchdown in the opening half.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second half, you couldn't throw it that much worse,''
Parcells added. Foley was 9 for 15 with 3 interceptions, 3 sacks,
and a total of 70 yards passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't go by one bad half and judge him,'' Parcells
said. ``The sacks belonged to the quarterback, three of them. These
are the kinds of things quarterbacks have to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells believed Foley had some lucky breaks in his brilliant
415-yard performance in the opener against the San Francisco 49ers,
a game the Jets lost in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Foley continued his alliance with Keyshawn Johnson, who remains
the American Football Conference's leading receiver with 15
catches. Wayne Chrebet has also expanded his role from being merely
a good-hands third-down receiver to an every-down player who is
actually averaging more yards a reception (18) than Johnson (13.8).
</P>
<P>
   Now Foley will lead the Jets as a favored team for a second
straight week as they play the Indianapolis Colts at the
Meadowlands. Foley's counterpart this time will be the most
acclaimed college quarterback to go into the draft in the 1990s:
Peyton Manning of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, out of Boston College, was the last pick of the draft for
the 1994 Jets. No matter. He is in charge now and the players will
be watching.
</P>
<P>
   He was unavailable to reporters Monday because he was having his
battered body tended by the Jets' trainers. Foley has never had to
go through this sort of pounding, and losing, for weeks at a time.
This week can answer questions that not only Parcells has, but
Foley's teammates as well.
</P>
<P>
   Without a running game, there is greater pressure on Foley. In
his fourth year, Martin has never been so unproductive in
consecutive games in which he had at least 20 carries. He agreed
that he should be running more aggressively. Parcells is reluctant
to criticize Martin, who signed a $36 million contract and has
amassed 116 yards, averaging 2.6 yards, in two games. Nevertheless,
the coach suggested that Martin might be running with a little
higher stride and not as forcefully.
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied at 7-7 in the second quarter against the
Ravens, Martin was halted four times in one series that began at
the Baltimore 3-yard line, the final three times from only a yard
out. ``There was one time I was undecided and started to cut to the
outside,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Martin is fifth in total yardage in the AFC with 217,
including 101 yards receiving.
</P>
<P>
   Vinny Testaverde, who has started 129 times as a pro
quarterback, can relate to Foley's woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to a quarterback to be in charge,'' said Testaverde,
who has not had to put on his helmet this season. ``Now you're
beaten up. Now you have to show by example.''
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde was in the locker room at lunchtime, while Foley, who
was sacked four times by the Ravens on Sunday, was receiving
treatment. So far, Foley's body has stood up and he has not missed
a snap.
</P>
<P>
   And Testaverde? The 34-year-old has been listed as third string.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
