<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE MacNEILLE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; New Year's in Paris &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I will be in Paris during the New Year's
holiday, and we would like suggestions on how to celebrate. _ Susan
Reynolds Baime, Essex County, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. You won't find a French version of the Times Square
experience, but there are plenty of entertaining ways to spend New
Year's Eve _ or Reveillon, as it's called in Paris _ particularly
if it involves eating.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the city's well-known restaurants plan New Year's menus
and events, although representatives for the following
establishments said details won't be complete until later in the
fall. They also said that they expect to be booked by the end of
October, so make reservations soon. Prices for six-course meals
will probably range from about $170 to $340 a person, including
wine. Among the restaurants planning special menus are the
three-Michelin-star Taillevent, 15 Rue Lamennais, telephone (33-1)
44.95.15.01; the three-star Arpege, 84 Rue Varenne, (33-1)
45.51.47.33; and the two-star Ledoyen, Carre Champs-Elysees, (33-1)
45.41.47.33. At Les Ambassadeurs restaurant in the Crillon Hotel,
(33-1) 44.71.15.00, there will be an orchestra and dancing. Les
Muses at the Hotel Scribe, (33-1) 44.71.24.24, will have an
Egyptian theme for its menu presentation and decor, and there will
be fireworks in the gardens for diners and hotel guests at Plaza
Athenee, 25 Avenue Montaigne, (33-1) 53.67.66.65.
</P>
<P>
   For a less expensive evening you might consider a Left Bank
institution like La Coupole on the Boulevard de Montparnasse,
(33-1) 43.20.14.20. For about $70 it offers a la carte dining and
dancing until dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Several dance halls just east of the city, along the Marne
River, are pretty venues in which to spend New Year's Eve, with
dinner, music and dancing for about $100. The Guinguette du Moulin
Vert in Champigny-sur-Marne is a 20-minute drive east of Paris on
the A4 highway, (33-1) 47.06.00.91. The Guinguette de L'Ile du
Martin Pecheur is in the same suburb, (33-1) 49.83.03.02.
</P>
<P>
   Boat companies with tours along the Seine will be operating at
full capacity on New Year's Eve. Among those offering a five-course
dinner, including Champagne, and dancing, are Bateaux Parisiens
(the cost is $300; access beside the Eiffel Tower), (33-1)
44.11.33. 44, and Bateaux Vedettes du Pont Neuf ($200; access under
the Pont Neuf), (33-1) 53.00.98.98.
</P>
<P>
   The Ballet Company of the Paris Opera offers another New Year's
Eve option, with its staging of ``Don Quixote'' at the Palais
Garnier at 7:30, choreographed by Rudolf Nureyev. Tickets range
from about $5.50 to $75. On the same day and time, the Bastille
Opera will present ``The Happy Widow,'' a three-act operetta by
Victor Leon and Leo Stein, directed by Jorge Lavelli and starring
Nancy Gustafson as Hanna Glawari. Tickets cost $10 to $110. Call
(33-1) 40.01.17.39 for reservations for both.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hudson Valley in the Fall &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you know of fall events at Hudson Valley sites, such as
Sunnyside, that would appeal to my 7-year-old? _ Miles Ellsbach,
New York, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. The Historic Hudson Valley, the organization in Tarrytown
that manages Sunnyside, Philipsburg Manor, Van Cortlandt Manor,
Union Church of Pocantico Hills, Montgomery Place and Kykuit, has
information on a number of good possibilities. The number is (914)
631-0089. Here are a few options:
</P>
<P>
   At Sunnyside, the 17th-century cottage that belonged to the
writer Washington Irving, there will be a daylong festival on Oct.
4 celebrating children's literature. Authors like Jean Craighead
George (``Julie of the Wolves''); Lloyd Moss (``Zin! Zin! A
Violin''), who will lead musical activities, and Richard Devins and
Norman Sandler, who will demonstrate some moves from their book
``Martial Arts for Kids,'' will be on hand, as will costumed
characters from the Magic School Bus book and TV series (including
Ms. Frizzle). A variety of hands-on workshops and nature walks will
also be offered. Admission is $8, $7 for seniors and $4 for
children 5 to 17; children under five are free. Information: (914)
591-8763.
</P>
<P>
   Also at Sunnyside, on Oct. 25, there will be ``An Evening of
Scary Tales With Robert Klein.'' The actor and comedian will read
some spooky stories, and visitors can take candlelight tours of the
cottage beginning at 6 p.m. The reading will be from 7:30 to 8:30
p.m. Admission is $15. Reservations are necessary. Call (914)
631-8200, extension 618.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvest Fair at Montgomery Place on Columbus Day weekend
(Oct. 10 and 11) is another good bet. Your child can gather apples
from the estate's orchards, press cider, square dance, take a
hayride or pony ride and help make a scarecrow. The setting is the
434-acre grounds of a grand early-19th-century mansion, former home
of the horticulturist Janet Livingston Montgomery (the widow of the
Revolutionary War hero, Gen. Richard Montgomery). Hours for the
fair are 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. on both days. Admission is $5; $3 for
children. Mansion tours are an additional $2, as are the pony
rides. Information: (914) 758-5461.
</P>
<P>
   The Historic Hudson Valley sites are also open throughout the
week (closed in January and February; Kykuit, the Rockefeller
estate, is closed from Nov. 1 until May). Hours and prices vary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Newsletter for Diabetics &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I've heard there is a travel newsletter for diabetics, but I
have not been able to find it. Can you help? Mary T. Haker, San
Francisco
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, there is such a publication. The Diabetic Traveler, a
six-page quarterly newsletter is designed to encourage people with
diabetes to travel and to do so safely. It is edited and published
by Maury E. Rosenbaum, an insulin-dependent diabetic.
</P>
<P>
   The newsletter focuses on specific locations _ Vancouver,
Acapulco and Paris are among the cities covered in past issues _
and types of travel, like spa vacations and rail or air travel.
Travel tips, including all-night pharmacies in particular cities,
insulin adjustment for air travel, generic and
foreign-manufacturer's drug names, are also included.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbaum also has some free publications, including a list of
diabetes associations in 84 countries and an insulin-adjustment
guide for travelers crossing multiple time zones. To receive them,
send a self-addressed, stamped business envelope to The Diabetic
Traveler, Post Office Box 8223-RW, Stamford, Conn. 06905. A year's
subscription to The Diabetic Traveler costs $18.95, and can be
ordered through the above address, or the newsletter's Web site:
www.ishops.com/diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
