<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-RDP-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISSAIR JET IN CRASH HELD A PICASSO PAINTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ The cargo hold of the Swissair jet that
crashed off the coast here Sept. 2 held currency, diamonds and
jewelry, along with a painting by Pablo Picasso that is believed to
have been destroyed when the jet slammed into the water, Swissair
officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually those kind of paintings are sent in some kind of
wooden construction that is really not a shockproof container,''
said Urs Peter Naef, a spokesman for Swissair's cargo-handling unit
in Zurich, Switzerland. ``We don't know for sure, but we assume
that because of the heavy impact it was probably destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Swissair declined to identify the owner of the painting, or say
to whom it was being shipped. The painting was identified as ``Le
Peintre'' (The Painter) and was shipped as general cargo, not
valuable cargo, which would have entailed extra care, the airline
said.
</P>
<P>
   Swissair officials said the shipping company, which it refused
to identify, estimated the painting to be worth $1.5 million.
Because that figure is based on the shipper's estimate, not the
owner's, it could vary widely from the painting's true value.
</P>
<P>
   A painting called ``Le Peintre'' was sold at auction at
Sotheby's London in December 1996 for the equivalent of $867,000.
The 36-inch-high oil canvas was painted in 1963 in tones of blue,
black and white. It depicts a bearded artist holding a palette.
</P>
<P>
   But Matthew Weigman, a spokesman for Sotheby's New York, said
that records indicated that Picasso did at least six paintings with
that title in 1963. ``Without seeing a photograph, there is no way
of telling if the painting sold by Sotheby's was the one that was
on the plane that crashed,'' Weigman said.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation of the jet's valuable cargo adds another
dimension to the crash that cost the lives of all 229 passengers
and crew. Although electrical problems are suspected, investigators
have not reached any conclusions about the cause of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   As news spread of the jetliner's valuable cargo, the Canadian
authorities warned away any would-be treasure hunters. ``The crash
site is still a protected zone and any attempt by anyone to
infiltrate or pilfer the site will not be tolerated,'' said Cpl.
Carl Hubley of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police in Halifax.
</P>
<P>
   Divers searching the wreckage have not reported coming across
any of the valuables from the Swissair cargo hold. Searchers found
some currency on the surface, but that is believed to have been
money held by passengers, not part of the shipment.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for a commercial jet like the McDonnell
Douglas used by Swissair to carry commercial cargo along with
baggage, company officials said. The jet that crashed was carrying
16 tons of cargo, which Swissair said was well within usual
operating limits.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the cargo consisted of textiles, machine parts and
computer equipment, as well as 530 pounds of express mail and 440
pounds of regular mail. The valuables and their packaging totaled
132 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Swissair handles about 200,000 consignments of valuables each
year, the company said. Shippers are charged by weight, not
content. All cargo shipments are insured for less than $10 a pound,
but shippers usually add their own insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Naef of Swissair would say little about the valuables that were
shipped on Flight 111 beyond what was on the jet's manifest. Each
item is listed by weight, including the packaging. The plane held
more than 100 pounds of currency that an American bank was shipping
to one of its branches in Switzerland, about 10 pounds of jewelry,
4 pounds of watches and 2 pounds of diamonds and their packaging.
</P>
<P>
   The airline would not give the value of the money or the
jewelry, or identify the owners.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the paintings, the money and jewelry were shipped
in a protective container provided by Swissair. It had a locked
aluminum door and metal seal.
</P>
<P>
   But this type of container is not shockproof or fireproof,
according to the company, and may not have been strong enough to
withstand the crash.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Canadian divers continued Monday to search through the tangled
wreckage of the Swissair MD-11 jet for human remains. So far, the
remains of only eight of the 229 victims have been positively
identified.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Butt, the Nova Scotia medical examiner, said Monday
that nearly all of the human remains had been retrieved from the
ocean floor in the area where the debris from the jet was found. He
said the head of Navy diving operations told him that it might be
too dangerous to enter the large, jagged sections of fuselage lying
on the ocean floor to recover remains still inside.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the fuselage fragments may have to be raised while they
hold the shattered bodies, Butt said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
