<HEADER>
A4978 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-STOCK-LADN     09-14 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-STOCK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOUSE BUCKS BULL; MARKET   BUFFETS   DISNEY   AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On a day when the bulls ruled Wall Street,
investors hammered Walt Disney Co. stock following a bleak earnings
forecast and knocked shares down to their lowest point in almost a
year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Shares fell $1.375 to $24.4375, completing a decline of 42
percent since Disney stock hit its all-time high in early May.
Monday's sell-off, accelerated by eight analysts downgrading the
stock, saw 23.7 million shares change hands in the largest volume
during a single session since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Disney was also by far the biggest loser among the 30 components
of the Dow Jones industrial average, which rose 149.85 to 7945.35.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's punishment reflects a growing perception among
investors that the global recession has become a flat tire on what
had been the entertainment industry's fastest vehicle over the past
decade. Even with Monday's decline, shares have doubled in value
over the past four years and are worth five times as much as they
were a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's downgrades and sell-off stemmed from Disney's
announcement late Friday that its fourth quarter, ending Sept. 30,
would come in at 15 cents or 16 cents a share, well below Wall
Street's consensus estimate of 21 cents. It blamed a variety of
problems: Asia's economic turmoil, slack demand for consumer
products and home videos overseas, and rising costs for films and
its ABC network.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts, many who issued downgrades and cut estimates earlier
in the summer, admitted Disney's problems aren't limited to this
quarter and may not go away quickly. ``This is a more significant
speed bump than we expected,'' said ING Barings Furman Selz analyst
Stewart Halpern, a longtime Disney bull who downgraded the stock
from ``buy'' to ``hold'' and lowered his year-end price target to
$35 from $42.
</P>
<P>
   Halpern said new revenue sources _ such as a cruise line, ESPN
magazine, stores and restaurants, new theme parks, international
expansion _ will take longer than expected to overcome current
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Jill Krutick of Salomon Smith Barney, who noted she had
sliced estimates June 30 and since has seen the stock fall 35
percent, agreed. ``While some of the issues are quarter specific,
we believe the announcement underscores longer-term challenges as
well,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the ongoing problems include poor ratings at ABC, the
soaring costs of TV programming such as pro football and the
cannibalization of attendance at its Florida theme parks by its own
Animal Kingdom and by Universal's planned Islands of Adventure
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Krutick, who downgraded her rating to ``neutral'' from
``outperform,'' warned that Chairman Michael Eisner's goal of 20
percent gains in earnings has become more difficult to achieve now
that Disney pulls in annual revenues of more than $20 billion. ``We
believe the bar is raised for Disney going forward,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The downbeat forecast means that for the fiscal year ending
Sept. 30, Disney will eke out a slight gain in profit of 88 cents
to 89 cents a share, up from 86 cents a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Disney is in the process of cutting back its live-action films _
one of its least profitable sectors _ to about 15 films a year
while ramping up its cornerstone animated film operation. Analysts
believe its strongest prospects are in the latter category, led by
``A Bug's Life,'' due out in November in partnership with Steven
Jobs' Pixar Animation. ``Tarzan'' and ``Toy Story 2'' are potential
animated blockbusters due in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Still, analysts believe the outlook will eventually brighten.
They cite Eisner's willingness to invest aggressively to expand
Disney's lucrative franchise. Krutick said the cruise line, new
animated films and gaining control of Web search specialist
Infoseek are particularly attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to believe in the long-term investment merits of
Walt Disney,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Bannister of Edward Jones &AMP; Co. reiterated her ``strong
buy'' rating while cautioning that Disney may need several quarters
to begin posting significant profit growth again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think Disney has been investing very wisely for the long
term with the cruise line, the new park in Anaheim and Animal
Kingdom,'' she said. ``Longer term, shareholders are going to be
fine. It's had these kind of problems before with the recession in
1991 and Euro Disney in 1993.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
