<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLIED-AMP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIED SIGNAL TAKEOVER BID FOR AMP GAINING SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.J.)  (lb) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Allied Signal Inc.'s hostile $9.8 billion takeover battle for
AMP Inc. escalated Monday as investors owning 72 percent of AMP
stock agreed to sell their shares to Allied Signal.
</P>
<P>
   Allied said it would buy as many as 40 million shares of AMP, or
about 18 percent of its outstanding stock, for $1.8 billion. That
amount falls short of spurring an AMP anti-takeover provision,
which goes into effect if anyone buys more than 20 percent of the
shares. Previously, Allied said it would only buy shares if the
takeover provision was removed.
</P>
<P>
   The share purchases should make Allied Signal the largest
shareholder and could put the company one step closer to completing
its plan to buy AMP, a leading maker of electronic equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, when Allied Signal announced its hostile cash bid
for AMP, AMP dismissed the offer as too low. AMP's new chairman and
chief executive, Robert Ripp, said there were no synergies between
the two companies and AMP was not interested in a combination.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Signal is also trying to force a vote that would give
investors, rather than the Harrisburg, Pa., company's board, the
ability to rescind the anti-takeover provision, or poison pill.
</P>
<P>
   Investors holding more than 157 million AMP shares offered their
stock for sale, an Allied official said. As a result, the
Morristown, N.J., maker of aerospace and automotive products, plans
to prorate its offer, buying a percentage of shares from each
investor who wants to sell. The tender offer expires on Sept. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Signal plans to continue its offer to buy the remaining
shares for $44.50 each, if the poison pill is removed.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Bossidy, Allied Signal's chief executive, said the high
percentage of shares offered ``is a vote of no confidence in
management's restructuring plan and a mandate in favor of Allied
Signal's offer.''
</P>
<P>
   But AMP's chairman, Ripp, disagreed. The results indicate ``AMP
shareholders want value and that's what we'll deliver,'' he said.
Allied Signal knows, he added, ``the initial round of tenders does
not translate into support for its bid.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle between the two companies escalated Monday, as AMP
newspaper advertisements asked Allied Signal investors how Allied's
executives and board could manage both businesses at once if it
were to gain control of AMP.
</P>
<P>
   AMP has urged shareholders to reject Allied's advances, and
promised improved profits. As part of its revamping plan, AMP
expects to generate an operating margin of 13.5 percent in 1999,
with earnings per share of about $2.30 and about $3 per share in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of AMP rose $3.0625 Monday, to $42.0625. AMP has been
struggling recently because of weakness in Asia, which accounted
for 20 percent of 1997 sales. In July, AMP announced a plant
closing and elimination of 3,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe that Allied's persistence could prompt an
offer from a rival bidder, or force changes at AMP. ``Obviously
shareholders are looking to send a real message to this
management,'' said Steven Cohen, director of research at Kellner,
DiLeo &AMP; Co., a New York merger arbitrage firm. ``You have a
management saying, `Trust us, don't worry.' If shareholders are
skeptical about believing these kinds of things, no one can blame
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
