Protesters showing their support of President Clinton by deriding
Kenneth Starr and his actions. Clinton came to New York Monday in
pursuit of money and perhaps solace. Throughout a day that the
Democratic Party said raised more than $4 million, there seemed to
be more affirmation than antipathy among hundreds who lined the
avenues as the president's motorcade made its way through the
city's streets. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- NY-CLINTON-1, 9-14 --
While Lucy and Ricky pucker up behind him, a protester gives
President Clinton a piece of his mind as his motorcade passes by
Monday. Making his first trip since the release of the Starr report
and accompanied by his wife, Hillary Rodham, Clinton gave a speech
on the global economy before a foreign policy group and circulated
at three crowded Democratic fund-raisers, including an evening
performance of ``The Lion King.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) JERICHO, West Bank -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- WESTBANK-CASINO,
9-14 -- A Palestinian woman washes her terrace Monday in a refugee
camp next to the newly built Oasis casino. It is the first large,
for-profit international investment in Palestinian territory, a $50
million project intended to generate millions in tax revenues for
the cash-strapped Palestinian Authority. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- RIOJA-DANCE-REVIEW, 9-14
-- Pilar Rioja performing ``Cafe de Chinita'' at the Gramercy Arts
Theater. Rioja's programs of Spanish dance are solo concerts. Yet
she often created the illusion that she was not dancing alone when
she performed on Sunday night. By abruptly opening large fans in
``Cafe de Chinita,''she appeared to be making pronouncements to a
host of unseen people. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SEATTLE -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- SEATTLE-SYMPHONY-HALL, 9-14
-- The Seattle Symphony performing at the opening of Benaroya Hall.
The 2,500-seat space, with a 540-seat recital hall attached, sits
between a pair of the steeply sloping side streets that
characterize Seattle's downtown. Like the art museum just below it
and the proliferating apartment buildings all around, it is a
component of urban renewal. (Dan Lamont/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) TUSCALOOSA, Ala. -- Sept. 14, 1998 --
OBIT-WALLACE-3-B&AMP;W, 9-14 -- Then governor of Alabama, George
Wallace, on June 11, 1963, when he mounted his ``stand in the
schoolhouse door'' to block two black students, Vivian Malone and
James Hood, from enrolling at the University of Alabama in
Tuscaloosa. Wallace, who had been in declining health since being
shot in his 1972 presidential campaign, died Sunday night at
Jackson Hospital in Montgomery. He was 79. (Calvin
Hannah/Tuscaloosa News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- OBIT-WALLACE-2-B&AMP;W, 9-14 --
Former Alabama Gov. George Wallace ,right, with legendary Alabama
football coach Paul ``Bear'' Bryant. Wallace, who built his
political career on segregation and spent a tormented retirement
arguing that he was not a racist in his heart, died Sunday night at
Jackson Hospital in Montgomery. He was 79. (Calvin
Hannah/Tuscaloosa News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- OBIT-WALLACE-1, 9-14 --
Former Alabama Gov. George Wallace in 1996. Wallace, who had been
humbled by the pain and paralysis of a 1972 assassination attempt,
died Sunday night in a Montgomery hospital. He was 79. (Neil
Brake/Tuscaloosa News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- SCI-NURSE-STUDY,
9-14 -- Dr. Frank Speizer, who started the Harvard Nurses' Health
Study in 1976 in order to gauge the effects of long-term oral
contraceptive use, and Dr. Sue Hankinson in the archive at the
Channing Laboratory, where the nurses' blood samples are kept.
Speizer originally sent questionnaires to 370,000 registered
nurses. The answers since received have turned into the largest and
longest study ever of a group of women. (Rick Friedman/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LA JOLLA, Calif. -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- SCI-MULLIS-DNA-2,
9-14 -- Dr. Kary Mullis, a Nobel Prize winner in chemistry, walking
the beach in La Jolla with his fourth wife, Nancy Cosgrove. Science
has been just one of the keen interests in Mullis' life, competing
with psychedelic drugs and women, although he is now happily
married. His newest interest is writing. A book of essays,
``Dancing Naked in the Mind Field,'' was published last month.
(Robert Burroughs/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) LA JOLLA, Calif. -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- SCI-MULLIS-DNA-1,
9-14 -- ``I'm on my vacation life here,'' says Dr. Kary Mullis, a
Nobel Prize winner in chemistry who has, for the most part, left
the world of science. ``I like writing about biology, not doing
it.'' His invention, known as the polymerase chain reaction or PCR,
is used for amplifying chosen sections of DNA and has quickly
become an essential tool for biologists, DNA forensics labs, and
almost anyone who needs to study the genetic material. (Robert
Burroughs/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LOS GATOS, Calif. -- Sept. 14, 1998 --
SCI-WEDDING-BUTTERFLIES-3, 9-14 -- Butterfly breeders Michael
Talesfore and Chris Hundley of Magical Beginnings in Los Gatos.
Butterfly releases are the latest fashion at weddings, and are now
even taking flight at memorial services, grand openings, divorces
and prison releases. ``The thing I like best is the emotions,
reactions and how much a butterfly can touch somebody,'' says
Hundley. ``Butterflies are just so happy.'' (Susan Span/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LEWISBURG, W. Va. -- Sept. 14, 1998 --
SCI-WEDDING-BUTTERFLIES-2, 9-14 -- A painted lady being freed in
Lewisburg. Basking in their first moment of nuptial bliss, brides
and grooms around the country are exiting churches, showered not
with rice or confetti, but surrounded instead by the fluttering
gossamer wings of hundreds of butterflies. The releases are the
latest fashion at weddings, and are now even taking flight at
memorial services, grand openings, divorces and prison releases.
(Susan Span/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SONOMA, Calif. -- Sept. 14, 1998 --
SCI-WEDDING-BUTTERFLIES-1, 9-14 -- Butterflies being released at a
wedding in Sonoma. While some view this popular trend as an
uplifting celebration of natural beauty, many others - including
conservationists, scientists and amateur butterfly enthusiasts -
see it as a misguided practice that poses serious risks to the wild
butterfly population and compromises scientists' ability to study
phenomena like the annual migration of the monarch butterfly.
(Susan Span/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. -- Sept. 14, 1998 --
ALTERNATIVE-MEDICINE-HEALTH, 9-14 -- Elena Avila is equally at home
among doctors and those using ancient healing methods. ``I practice
medicine and spiritual healing simultaneously,'' says Ms. Avila, a
psychiatric nurse and a ``curandera,'' or healer. (Cary Herz/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BOSTON -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- AUTHOR-PATTERSON-BOS, 9-14 --
Richard North Patterson during an interview in Boston. Patterson's
most recent novel, ``No Safe Place'' is his ninth novel, but a
departure from his trademark legal thrillers. Published by Knopf
barely two weeks ago, it landed in the No.10 spot on Sunday's New
York Times bestseller list and is expected to climb to No.5 on next
Sunday's list, with 400,000 copies already in print. (Tom
Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PEPPERELL, Mass. -- Sept. 14, 1998 --
SCI-UNLOVED-SPECIES-BOS, 9-14 -- Pat Huckery, up to her neck in the
waters of the Nissitissit River, pulls out a two-inch-long clam
that tells her she is in unspoiled water. ``Certain freshwater
mussels seem to be much more sensitive to water quality, and they
are the ones to end up'' on the endangered species lists, says Ms.
Huckery, the mussel specialist at Massachusetts Natural Heritage
and Endangered Species Program. (Mark Wilson/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
