<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 9/14/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) CHICAGO -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- BBO-CUBS-SOSA, 9-14 --
Sammy Sosa has a high profile at the ball park but a quiet life at
home. He and his wife, Sonia, play with three of their four
children in their 55th-floor condominium. The Sosas moved in to
their million-dollar home in June from a smaller one a few blocks
away. It appears almost unlived in, with little of the debris of
life scattered about. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- WELFARE-HISPANICS-2, 9-14
-- When Ramona Rosario left her husband, she had no job skills, no
English language skills and no way to survive without a welfare
check. ``I feel stuck,'' Ms. Rosario, 42, says in Spanish as she
wearily lists the supermarkets, hospitals and clothing stores that
have refused to hire her. ``Sometimes, I think we're all stuck.''
(Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- WELFARE-HISPANICS-1, 9-14
-- Spanish-speaking women on welfare, struggling to break into the
work force, studying English at Bronx Community College. The number
of Hispanic single mothers on public assistance has held almost
steady. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- BUCHWALD-PROFILE, 9-14 --
Art Buchwald has left his Washington base and moved back to New
York, where it all began. At the moment, Buchwald is marrying the
funny and not-so-funny in a book-in-progress, ``Stella in Heaven:
Almost a Novel,'' about a dead wife who is running her husband's
life from the clouds. (Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- CLINTON-SCHOOLS, 9-14 --
``Are we more fair-minded now?'' Mary Robinson asks her American
literature class at Bronx High School of Science on Monday as
students consider how Puritans would have viewed President
Clinton's behavior. ``He's just a man,'' a 17-year-old girl says
later in a more modern segment of the discussion. ``All men
cheat.'' (Richard L. Harbus/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- NY-CLINTON-3, 9-14 --
Hillary Rodham Clinton confers with Sen. Robert Torricelli of New
Jersey at a fund-raiser at the Supper Club on Monday night. Making
his first trip since the release of the Starr report and
accompanied by his wife, Clinton gave a speech on the global
economy before a foreign policy group and circulated at three
crowded Democratic fund-raisers, including an evening performance
of ``The Lion King.'' (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- PRADA-STORE-FASHION-2, 9-14
-- In an effort to reach a broader audience, Prada has opened a
four-level store on Fifth Avenue. Prada's top line will continue to
be exclusive, left; the more accessible Prada Sport. (Dan and
Corinna Lecca/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) UNDATED -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- PRADA-STORE-FASHION-1, 9-14
-- Designer Miuccia Prada. In an effort to reach a broader
audience, Prada has opened a four-level store on Fifth Avenue. They
seek to interest hoi polloi in a look that has been the uniform of
a strict, private club whose members dress in expensive stark,
black uniforms and whose insignia is a discreet black and silver
triangular badge adorning futuristic nylon bags. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- CLINTON-CONGRESS-2, 9-14
-- Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., faces the media Monday. The Judiciary
Committee chairman says he will not rule out expanding any inquiry
beyond President Clinton's affair with Monica Lewinsky and efforts
to cover it up, adding that Kenneth Starr could still send Congress
information on other matters he has investigated and that ``we
would be duty bound to consider whatever he sends us.'' (Shana
Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- OBIT-WALLACE-4-B&AMP;W, 9-14 --
Alabama Gov. George Wallace campaigning in 1972. Wallace, who had
been in declining health since being shot during his 1972
presidential bid, died Sunday night at Jackson Hospital in
Montgomery. He was 79. (Gary Settle/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- CLINTON-CONGRESS-1, 9-14
-- Rep. Zoe Lofgren, a California Democrat on the Judiciary
Committee, has looked to the articles of impeachment in Watergate
for guidance in the Clinton scandal. She meets with her staff
members Monday. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Sept. 14, 1998 -- NY-CLINTON-2, 9-14 --
