<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clinton Details His Policy for Economic Growth
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ President Clinton declared that the economic turmoil
roiling three continents constituted ``the biggest financial
challenge facing the world in a half-century.'' In a half-hour
address to a friendly audience at the Council on Foreign Relations
in Manhattan on Monday, he detailed a strategy to quell the trouble
before it puts ``our own prosperity at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called on the world's leading economies to abandon their
fear of inflation and instead ``spur growth.'' The finance
ministers and central bank governors of the world's seven largest
economies issued a parallel statement intended to open the door to
coordinated interest-rate cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond rose 4/32, to 104 4/32 in
response to the Group of Seven and to an Atlanta Fed report that
Southern manufacturing growth was slowing.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Smith Jr., chairman of General Motors, urged the Federal
Reserve to reduce interest rates to avert a recession.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Murdoch Leaves News Board
</P>
<P>
   Anna Murdoch, the estranged wife of News Corp. Chairman Rupert
Murdoch, has left the company's board. Murdoch has always said she
made a major contribution as a director and, should he die, she
could easily serve as chairman, until his adult children, whom he
is grooming to run the company, were ready. Wall Street had little
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Russia Turns to Economic Veterans
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen alumni of President Mikhail Gorbachev's varsity
economic squad are again at the center of Russia's economic policy
debate, commandeered by Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov to
recommend a reconstruction of the Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect Russia to default on up to $200 billion in
foreign debt next year, unless it can raise fresh funds or delay
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips in Big Kazakhstan Oil Deal
</P>
<P>
   Phillips Petroleum and the Japanese-owned Indonesian Petroleum
Co. signed oil- and gas-exploration deals with Kazakhstan in
Central Asia that could be worth several billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Economic Blows in Vigorous Mexico
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's once robust economy has been hit in recent weeks by an
18 percent drop in the peso's value, a 40 percent surge in interest
rates and a 50 percent slide in stock prices, but has not caved in.
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian Market Regaining Footing
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's stock market appeared to regain equilibrium after
dizzying losses last week, shored up by higher interest rates,
government stock purchases and suggestions that the IMF would lend
a hand.
</P>
<P>
   Allied Signal Bid for AMP Advances
</P>
<P>
   Allied Signal's hostile $9.8 billion takeover battle for AMP, a
maker of electronic equipment, escalated, as investors owning 72
percent of AMP stock agreed to sell their shares to Allied Signal,
which said it would buy 40 million, or 18 percent. That would make
it the largest shareholder without setting off AMP's anti-takeover
provision.
</P>
<P>
   American Phones for the Taliban
</P>
<P>
   Telephone Systems International, a privately owned company in
Parsippany, N.J., has signed a $240 million contract to build a
cellular telephone system for the Taliban, the Islamic
fundamentalists who control most of Afghanistan and whom the White
House has accused of harboring Osama bin Laden, the suspected
terrorist leader.
</P>
<P>
   October Trial for Microsoft Case
</P>
<P>
   The government's antitrust case against Microsoft will go to
trial Oct. 15, a federal judge decided. He denied the company's
request to throw out the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
