<SLUG> BC-LAPD-DAUGHTER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUGHTER OF LAPD CHIEF HELD IN COCAINE STING
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attention Las Vegas editors.) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
BY PATRICK McGREEVY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The 37-year-old daughter of Los Angeles Police
Chief Bernard C. Parks has been booked in Las Vegas on suspicion of
felony sale of cocaine after she allegedly drove a car containing a
man who tried to sell drugs to an undercover police detective,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Parks was released on her own recognizance after her
booking Monday by a judge pending a Sept. 29 arraignment on charges
of conspiracy to sell cocaine and trafficking in the drug,
according to Scott Mitchell, chief deputy district attorney for the
Clark County District Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   A clerk typist at the Los Angeles Police Department's Pacific
Division, Michelle Parks appeared in court after an arrest warrant
was issued stemming from an incident in Las Vegas on the evening of
June 24, 1998, court records indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell said Michelle Parks allegedly drove a car containing
Reginald Gathwright, 21, to a movie theater parking lot at 9 p.m.,
where Gathwright allegedly tried to sell 20 grams of cocaine to an
undercover Las Vegas police detective.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor said his office will try to prove in court that
Parks knew that her passenger intended to sell cocaine and
therefore was a co-conspirator.
</P>
<P>
   The drug-trafficking charge carries two to 15 years in prison
and a fine of up to $100,000, said Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Although those charged with the mid-level offense are not
eligible for probation, Mitchell said such cases are commonly
plea-bargained down to a charge where probation is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Gathwright and Parks were allowed to leave the scene after
meeting with an undercover detective but were stopped later by a
traffic officer who obtained their identification for the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Parks allegedly told the Las Vegas police officer
that she was the daughter of the chief and an employee of the LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Steve Meriweather, a spokesman for the Las Vegas Metro
Police Department, refused to provide additional details.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an ongoing investigation being conducted by our narcotics
unit,'' said Meriweather, adding that providing details ``would
either prejudice her rights or jeopardize the case.''
</P>
<P>
   He denied that the refusal to provide details had anything to do
with the defendant's stature as daughter of the Los Angeles Police
Department chief.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Parks declined comment through a spokesman, saying the
case is not within the LAPD's jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Parks joined the LAPD as a civilian clerk typist in
August 1996, went out on medical leave after surgery in November
1997 and remains on medical leave, according to LAPD Cmdr. Dave
Kalish.
</P>
<P>
   Kalish said there is an internal administrative investigation
into the actions of the chief's daughter. The LAPD has a
zero-tolerance policy when it comes to drug crimes, so officials
said Parks could lose her job if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Parks is the fourth relative of the chief to face controversy
involving the law.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Chief Parks' other daughter, Trudy Jackson, admitted to
filing a false theft report with the LAPD after her estranged
husband took her car and did not return it.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, Parks' nephew Winston Parks was three days
from graduating from the Police Academy when he resigned after
being told he would be dismissed for failing to disclose being
arrested but not charged as a juvenile for theft.
</P>
<P>
   In July of this year, Parks' 32-year-old niece, Darcelle M.
Parks, was arrested on suspicion of credit card fraud and forgery
after she allegedly submitted a false application for a credit card
in the Los Angeles area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
