<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN LEAVING U.N. DEVELOPMENT POST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The highest-ranking American in the U.N.
system, James Gustave Speth, administrator of the U.N. Development
Program, said Monday that he would be leaving the organization next
summer.
</P>
<P>
   European Union nations are expected to campaign for the job,
which has traditionally been held by an American. Among Europeans,
there is growing resentment against the United States, which owes
about $1.5 billion in unpaid assessments, while Europe shoulders
nearly half the organization's budget.
</P>
<P>
   The position is one of several that will open to international
competition in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Speth, a founder of the World Resources Institute in Washington
and its president when he was appointed to the development agency
in 1993, will join Yale University as dean of the School of
Forestry and Environmental Studies.
</P>
<P>
   Under Speth's tenure, the agency expanded its work
significantly, from basic development projects to broad involvement
in fostering better government.
</P>
</TEXT>
