<HEADLINE>
GM CHAIRMAN URGES RATE CUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The chairman of General Motors Corp. publicly urged
the Federal Reserve Board on Monday to reduce interest rates _ part
of what is likely to be a series of such statements by top
Midwestern manufacturing executives.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Smith Jr., GM's chairman, said that spreading economic
troubles overseas could cause a recession in the United States if
the Fed did not lower rates soon. Lower short-term rates, which the
Fed controls, would stimulate the domestic economy and make it
easier for other countries to lower their rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is whether the Fed will wait until the recession
is imported and then act, or act now,'' Smith said at a meeting of
the Detroit Economic Club. ``GM believes it should act now.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate news conference, Smith said that while he did not
have a specific rate cut in mind, ``about a half percent would be a
good move.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's rate-setting Federal Open Market Committee will meet
on Sept. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, has always closely watched the
sales and other statistics of the steel and auto industries as a
gauge of the overall economy's health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
