<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0496 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-WALLACE-NYT &LR;      09-14 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WALLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE WALLACE PARADOX 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Sept. 15:
</P>
<P>
   George Wallace's was a fate not to be wished on any man. He
lived long enough to be a relic.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, his passing invites our thoughts to stray to the
Gothic era in Southern politics, a time when it was sometimes hard
to draw a line between fact and fiction. The larger-than-life Huey
Long begets the fictional Willie Stark, and then suddenly out of
the Alabama outback springs this truculent little gamecock who
seemed concocted of their best and worst parts.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Kingfish, Wallace believed in books and schools, but he
had a dictator's heart that regarded his state's police and
treasury as personal assets. Like the hero of ``All the King's
Men,'' he believed that because he stood up for the downtrodden,
the rules of political morality and personal loyalty did not apply
to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an awful lot of mythology in Wallace's makeup, and
the best of it was that he identified with `the little man,'''
recalled Ray Jenkins, the former editor of The Alabama Journal and
a perceptive Wallace critic. But he added, ``The one thing that
ruled Wallace's life more than anything was political pragmatism.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have the tragedy of George Wallace in a nutshell. For
the sake of expediency, this progressive New Dealer of the '40s and
'50s transformed himself in the watershed year of 1963 into
America's foremost racist. He demonized the little people with
black skins in order to win the loyalty of those with white skins.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's excuse was that race-baiting was the only way to win
in Alabama at that time, and that once in office he had installed
programs like free textbooks that helped poor whites and poor
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   He died in denial about the fact that the ``pragmatic'' step he
took to win the statehouse triggered a murder epidemic that took
the lives of 10 people who were either demonstrating for civil
rights or simply breathing in Alabama while being black.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on the day he surrendered the governorship for the last of
four times, old and broken, he told his son that he worried about
who would take care of the little people now. For all the manifest
failures and betrayals of his career, he still saw himself as a
person with a caring heart.
</P>
<P>
   This aspect of Wallace's life defined, in its most extreme form,
the dilemma that has haunted Southern populists throughout this
century. As the region's candidates shed the burden of racism and
moved into the national arena, this tension between means and
results, between noble motivations and seedy tactics, has become a
part of the national debate as well.
</P>
<P>
   Even when you take race out of the picture, where does a
candidate draw the line between pandering and leadership? If a
candidate intends to do good in office, what corners can be cut to
get there? Once elected, if an officeholder is serving the people,
how much should the public care about his finances, personal
behavior, the dispensation of patronage or legislative deal-making?
</P>
<P>
   Among Southern populists, this often destructive dichotomy
between elevated goals and personal weakness surfaced in the failed
career of the movement's founder, the Georgia congressman Tom
Watson.
</P>
<P>
   It shoots through the bifurcated career of Lyndon Johnson, the
first of the modern era's Southern populist presidents. The author
of the Great Society was also a stealer of elections known as
``Landslide Lyndon.'' To the end of his days, he thought his good
intentions on civil rights and the alleviation of poverty ought to
earn him forgiveness for the folly of the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   The next Dixie populist, Jimmy Carter, to earn the White House
avoided the corruption associated with Johnson and came closer than
any to maintaining the humanitarian purity of his vision. But even
he touched the dark side in his 1970 gubernatorial campaign, when
his supporters circulated racist pictures of a rich rival ridiculed
as ``Cufflinks Carl,'' and Carter sent a racial signal by promising
to have Wallace address the Georgia legislature.
</P>
<P>
   This regional political tradition is important in understanding
both the campaign style and the psychology of aggrievement that
drives our current president.
</P>
<P>
   Like Wallace, Lyndon Johnson and even Carter, Bill Clinton
believed that doing good in office may require getting gamy in the
campaign. Hence the use of private detectives to vilify hapless
women who made the mistake of doing sexual favors for the
candidate. Hence the psychology that casts health-care opponents as
right-wing conspirators and insists that the blame for the
president's lying under oath and his sexual indiscretions rests
with those who exposed the behavior rather than with the man who
committed it.
</P>
<P>
   None of this argues for screening the populist strain from
national politics. Shorn of its racial aberration, it represents,
along with Northeastern social-welfare progressivism, the nation's
most humane impulses toward the afflicted and the powerless. With
its emphasis on the little people and its agrarian roots, Southern
populism also serves as a healthy antidote to the money-driven
influence of corporations and Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   In Wallace's career, of course, all these high-minded elements
got overpowered by the twisting power of hate. His wrecked body
became a metaphor for what he had done to his soul in 1962 and
1970, his most famously racist campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Later this week, his self-harmed and ever-restless spirit will
go at last into the flat prairie country he loved. In a
demonstration of the healing efficacy of democracy, he will be
preached home by the black Alabamians he strove so mightily to harm
and the white citizens whose aspirations and angers he so
poignantly embodied.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace yearned to be remembered for paving the way for Southern
Democrats like Carter and Clinton and for Main Street Republicans
like Ronald Reagan. Even so, the unalterable verdict of history is
upon Wallace as a politician of inborn gifts whose career was
blighted by his opportunistic alignment with bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the larger lesson of his life for national politics may not
be one he would have imagined. He established Southern populism as
an important strain of the national political environment. He also
showed that while the populist mind-set is noble in its
aspirations, it tends toward paranoia and demagoguery in the hands
of those of variable character.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
