u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-PARLIAMENT-390&AMP;A     09-14 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-PARLIAMENT-390&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQ ASSEMBLY THREATENS END TO INSPECTION COOPERATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Iraqi Parliament, which diplomats often
consider an advance-warning system on Baghdad's policy, threatened
on Monday to stop all remaining cooperation with a U.N. arms
inspection system.
</P>
<P>
   In a vote after a long session, the 250-member National
Assembly, dominated by President Saddam Hussein's Baath Party,
demanded that the Security Council reverse its decision last week
to stop all reviews of sanctions until Iraq allows on-site
inspections to resume. Without sanctions reviews, Iraq can never
hope to escape from an embargo imposed in 1990 after its invasion
of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   If the council does not resume reviews, Parliament's speaker
said in a statement after the session, the assembly would ask the
government ``to cut all relations with the United Nations Special
Commission and not cooperate with it in any way.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the State Department spokesman, James Rubin, said
the United States would ask the Security Council to take further
steps against Iraq if it suspended the activities of all weapons
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would constitute yet another flagrant violation of U.N.
Security Council resolutions and a direct challenge to the
authority of the council,'' he said at a daily briefing. ``In that
event, the council would have to consider further action.''
</P>
<P>
   The special commission, known as UNSCOM, is in charge of
dismantling prohibited Iraqi weapons systems and ensuring that the
country does not have the means to rebuild them. Stopped by Iraq on
Aug. 5 from making on-site inspections, the commission's experts
based in Baghdad are able to monitor Iraqi activities with
sophisticated video cameras and air, water and soil sampling
devices.
</P>
<P>
   But the Iraqis have already barred some follow-up inspections by
monitors from both the special commission, which keeps track of
biological, chemical and missile systems, and the International
Atomic Energy Agency, which watches nuclear issues, despite the
requirement that long-term monitoring be allowed to continue, not
only now but also after sanctions are lifted in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq also said on Aug. 5 that what monitoring goes on will be
permitted only as an ``interim'' gesture, pending Security Council
action. The council's resolution last week was that action.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some experts have always assumed that Iraq would dismantle the
long-term monitoring system at some point, or render it minimally
useful to the inspectors over the long term. U.N. officials say
unannounced or short-notice inspections are really the heart of any
monitoring system, however. Without the ability to follow
suspicions, the value of the commission's work is very much
diminished.
</P>
<P>
   UNSCOM has about 125 experts in Iraq, including 40 Chilean
helicopter pilots and crews used for aerial inspections. No U.N.
staff are armed. Their security is provided entirely by the Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   In Baghdad on Monday the National Assembly also renewed threats
against British and U.S. inspectors, in what is apparently another
attempt to divide Security Council opinion by provoking Washington
and London.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago Iraq provoked a crisis by expelling all U.S.
inspectors, and the commission chairman, Richard Butler of
Australia, withdrew his team for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the U.S.-sponsored council resolution last week
suspending sanctions reviews, a decision by the United States to
begin broadcasting Radio Free Iraq into the country in Arabic from
Europe has upset the Iraqi leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Last week David Newton, U.S. ambassador to Iraq from 1984 to
1988, was named to head the new service, which hopes to broadcast
from Prague, pending agreement from the Czech government. Iraq has
asked the Czech government not to permit the broadcasts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
