<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLEN QUITS FOR TRACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA's young secondary got considerably younger
Monday when reserve cornerback Damian Allen quit the team to
concentrate on his track career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came in (and said), `Coach, my heart's not in it,''' Bruins
coach Bob Toledo said. ``There was no way I was going to talk (him)
out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen, a third-year sophomore, finished second in the 100 meters
and third in the 200 meters at the Pac-10 championships in May. But
he was better on the track than on the field. Heavily recruited at
Damien High School in LaVerne _ Nebraska offered a scholarship _
Allen never seemed comfortable with the defense and shied from
contact.
</P>
<P>
   His departure means junior Ryan Roques, a former tailback, is
the top reserve cornerback behind starters Marques Anderson and
Jason Bell. In addition, the Bruins probably will use true freshman
Julius Williams, who expected to redshirt, as the No. 4 cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Julius will have to play,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rookie update: The most impressive true freshman against
Texas wasn't tailback DeShaun Foster, who rushed for 44 yards and a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Linebacker) Robert Thomas played really well,'' Toledo said.
``Looking at the tape ... he's going to be a super player. He made
some instinctive plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a broken right hand and limited snaps, Thomas, a reserve
inside linebacker, made three tackles. Expect his playing time to
increase Saturday at Houston. The same goes for reserve nose guard
Ken Kocher, whose size and strength are desperately needed on the
young defensive line. If Kocher's tender ankle holds, he'll play
plenty.
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury update: Fullback Craig Walendy (allergic reaction to
bug bites) is questionable for Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Also, left guard Oscar Cabrera is out several weeks with a
sprained right ankle. Cabrera suffered the injury in the first
quarter Saturday and was replaced by Matt Phelan.
</P>
<P>
   With Phelan starting, junior college transfer James Ghezzi
becomes the top reserve at both tackle and guard. Josh Webb, who
switched from defense two weeks ago, is learning to play right
tackle. David Wilford (tackle), Ed Anderson (guard) and Troy Danoff
(center) are available if needed.
</P>
<P>
   __ It didn't matter, but ...: The Bruins appeared to have a
second-quarter touchdown, or safety, when linebacker Brendan
Ayanbadejo knocked the ball from Texas quarterback Richard Walton
near the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   It rolled into the end zone, where UCLA's Micah Webb and Texas'
Roger Roesler fought for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit the quarterback and out of the corner of my eye I saw
the ball roll into the end zone and a pile of guys jump on it,''
Ayanbadejo said. ``I thought, `Sweet, it's a safety or touchdown.'
''
</P>
<P>
   The officials saw differently, awarding Texas possession at its
1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the worst call I've ever seen,'' Ayanbadejo said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Same play, different result: Tailback Jermaine Lewis' 7-yard
touchdown run came on the same off-tackle play (called Power 2) as
his botched fourth-and-1 attempt last year at Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of turning upfield before the hole developed, Lewis
stayed behind his blockers and eventually found a huge opening over
right tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a difference a year makes and what a difference a play
makes,'' Lewis said. ``As soon as it went wrong (last year), the
coaches lodged it in my head not to do that again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
