<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-READERS-DIGEST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READER'S DIGEST TO SELL ART AT PUBLIC AUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT and CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The financially troubled Reader's Digest Association,
owner of an exceptional art collection, will be selling an
estimated $100 million worth of Impressionist and 20th-century
works by masters like Cezanne, Monet, Modigliani and Matisse at
public auction in New York in November, several experts close to
the negotiations said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   While both Sotheby's and Reader's Digest refused to comment, art
experts said that the York Avenue auction house had been chosen to
sell the works in a special evening sale during the height of the
fall art season. The auction is a big coup for Sotheby's, which
competed fiercely for it against archrival Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   But the choice, experts said, was an obvious one, since
Sotheby's has been working with Reader's Digest for years, doing
its appraisals and last May selling two paintings _ a Monet and a
van Gogh _ which totaled $6.2 million. Around the same time,
Reader's Digest also sold a Braque still life privately.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, the best of Reader's Digest art holdings _ works
carefully collected by the publisher's founders Lila Acheson
Wallace and her husband DeWitt Wallace since the 1940s _ will be up
for sale. The highlights of the collection include two Modigliani
portraits, a Matisse still life, a Cezanne landscape, two Monets _
a landscape the artist painted while he was at Vetheuil and one of
the artist's famous waterlilies _ and a Van Gogh, which the artist
painted in Auvers-sur-Oise in 1890.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to sell this season is partly timed to take
advantage of the strong prices realized at auctions of the last
several years. The company is hardly the first corporation to sell
its art at Sotheby's. In recent years both IBM and CBS, under
financial pressure, sold parts of their collections. IBM's most
valuable American paintings brought record prices when they were
offered three years ago. CBS also made money selling about 100
works of contemporary art two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Reader's Digest is under enormous pressure to improve its
performance because the company's results have been very
disappointing over the last several years.
</P>
<P>
   Today, under its new chairman and chief executive, Thomas Ryder,
its financial situation is somewhat better than several months ago,
when it had a negative net worth. Not only has it sold some art,
but it has laid off some staff and closed some operations. Still,
its $100 million in cash is a far cry from the flush days when the
Reader's Digest balance sheet carried $700 million in cash. At its
late 1992 high, the stock traded at $56.375 a share. It closed
Monday at $17.6875.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company can meet its debt obligations, but they need
capital to fund new ventures,'' said Mandana Hormozi, an analyst at
Lazard Freres and Co.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hormozi and other analysts greeted the news of the pending
sale of art as a positive for the company and noted that Ryder had
said a sale was likely and that nothing was any longer sacred at
the company. The previous chief executive, George Grune, had been
reluctant to sell the collection.
</P>
<P>
   Though analysts are impressed with Ryder's no-nonsense approach
_ not only has he already sold several pieces of art, he has also
sold the corporate jet _ Reader's Digest's problems are deep.
</P>
<P>
   The books and home entertainment products are still not getting
strong responses to mailings, Ms. Hormozi said. And the revenue for
the magazine is down, in large part due to currency fluctuations.
In addition, Reader's Digest failed to meet its rate base to
advertisers of 15 million readers in 1998, delivering 14.7 million.
Under these circumstances it is not unusual for publications to
give advertisers free space to compensate for the readers they paid
for but did not get.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hormozi said that she had scaled back her expectations for
fiscal 1999, which will end June 30, from strong growth to moderate
growth. However she and other analysts said they were waiting to
hear Ryder's extensive presentation to analysts scheduled for
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The company has a unique structure. About 71 percent of its
voting stock is held by two charitable foundations established by
the Wallaces. Underneath the big foundations are seven charitable
funds, each of which supports a major cultural institution. The
funds once owned a total of 42 percent of the nonvoting shares.
However, Reader's Digest cut its dividend last year, and with the
stock doing poorly, some foundations lobbied for, and received, the
right to sell some stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
