<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERG MIGHT SLIP AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Restricted free-agent defenseman Aki Berg
said Monday he's close to signing a new contract but not with the
Los Angeles Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Berg, the third player chosen in the 1995 NHL draft, said he is
close to a deal with TPS, his former team in his native Finland. He
is scheduled to fly Wednesday to Finland and also is believed to be
receiving interest from another Finnish team and one in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Berg added that he has not given up on playing for the Kings
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully,'' Berg, 21, said through a translator when reached
by telephone in Ottawa. ``I've always wanted to play for the Kings.
But right now, it seems like it's not in the cards at all.''
</P>
<P>
   A source close to Berg said that among the Kings' offers is a
one-year contract for $467,500, which represents a 10-percent raise
on last season's base salary of $425,000.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-percent raise is the minimum allowed by the NHL
collective-bargaining agreement for a player with his experience.
Berg, who had no goals and eight assists last year, has played 164
games in three seasons with the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   Berg and his agent, Larry Kelly, said he deserves to be paid in
excess of the $825,000 he earned last season when factoring in a
portion of the $1 million bonus he received for first signing with
the Kings in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``How we decided to structure the compensation is irrelevant,''
Kelly said of the original contract. ``There's no way in the world
he would accept less than $825,000.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kings general manager Dave Taylor said he views signing
bonuses and base salary as separate, and the 10-percent rule does
apply only to base salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll continue to try to work out a deal with him,'' Taylor
said.
</P>
<P>
   Berg said he is not sure he can get a contract in Europe that
would leave him an out if he eventually comes to terms with the
Kings but added he'd be willing to sign a deal lacking such a
clause. If Berg were to play even one game in Europe after the Oct.
9 start of the NHL season, then sign with the Kings, he would have
to clear waivers before rejoining them. And that almost certainly
would not happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he plays over there at any time after the start of the
(NHL) season,'' Taylor said, ``he won't be coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg insisted his goal is to play in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big disappointment,'' he said. ``I've been training
hard.... And it's the best league in the world. But I'm going to
play 80 or 90 games for TPS and the Finnish national team, 30
minutes a game, so I don't think this will ruin my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Movement has been minimal, as well, in negotiations with the
other unsigned Kings: defenseman Rob Blake, goalie Jamie Storr and
enforcer Matt Johnson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
