<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CONTRITION DOESN'T RIGHT ALL WRONGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CLYDE HABERMAN  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The First Supplicant was back in town Monday, and for
the usual reason. He needed money.
</P>
<P>
   Do you ever get the feeling that President Clinton looks upon
New York as nothing but an ATM, to be tapped when he or the
national Democratic Party needs a cash infusion, which is often? It
seems only fair for the city to take a cue from some banks and
charge a fee for the privilege, given all the police overtime and
other costs that it must cover whenever Clinton finds himself a few
dollars short.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it might not be a bad idea if City Hall toted up in
advance the extra expenses anticipated for a presidential visit,
and then sent Clinton a check for that amount, on the condition
that he stay home. Taxpayers would lose nothing, and there would be
some obvious benefits. Traffic in midtown would be less ferocious,
to name one.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving money out of it, the president could not have picked a
more congenial spot than New York for his first foray outside
Washington since Kenneth Starr sent his report on the Lewinsky
affair to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   One could perhaps accuse him of having a tin ear in staging a
fund-raiser Monday in the 42nd Street theater where ``The Lion
King'' is playing. Did it not dawn on anyone at the White House
that the tabloids could have a field day with headlines about ``The
Lyin' King''? But that glitch aside, New York provided as welcoming
a place as a confessed sinner could desire.
</P>
<P>
   This is, after all, a live-and-let-live town, where people don't
much care what their neighbors do as long as it doesn't scare the
horses, to borrow from Mrs. Patrick Campbell, the actress.
</P>
<P>
   What better time for a penitent to come than the week when the
liturgical focus in Roman Catholic churches is on the tale of the
prodigal son? Or when, in a city that still responds to the
imperatives of the Jewish calendar, the High Holy Days of
self-reflection and atonement are about to begin?
</P>
<P>
   Assuming that a quick poll in The Daily News over the weekend is
not crazy, 77 percent of New Yorkers are willing to forgive Clinton
and want him to finish his term. Wall Street certainly showed that
the Starr report was not making it flinch. In the last two trading
days, the Dow Jones industrial average has climbed 330 points.
</P>
<P>
   But while basking in a warm New York glow, the president would
have been well warned that here, as elsewhere, contrition has its
limits. Apologies do not absolve all sins, even when they are
offered right away and with apparent feeling, not on the
installment plan that Clinton has preferred.
</P>
<P>
   Despite vast differences in the circumstances, the president
might consider the case of a New York police officer, Joseph
Locurto. Along with two city firefighters, this officer has been
suspended for having been among the geniuses in Broad Channel,
Queens, who put on blackface and rode in a Labor Day float that
mocked the vicious killing of a black man in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Locurto was a study in contrition on Saturday. Pleading that he
was not a racist, he said: ``I made a mistake, and I apologize for
it.'' This was, mind you, a full-throated apology, not the
mealy-mouthed locution often favored by politicians, the one in
which they say they are sorry if they have offended anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did was wrong,'' Locurto said forthrightly. ``I admit
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani wants the policeman and the
firefighters to be dismissed, not just suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has praised Locurto for having apologized. He also
agrees that city employees have an ``absolute right'' to be
offensive while off duty. But Giuliani argued Monday that the
citizens of New York also have rights. One of them is to make sure
that ``the power of life and death'' is not put in the hands of
someone who shows he has no ``mature understanding of how to relate
to human beings of all sorts of different races and backgrounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Count on the New York Civil Liberties Union fighting the mayor
hard on this one, while waving the banner of the First Amendment.
The civil libertarians just might win. Giuliani strikes out in the
courts more often than not in cases of this type. That having been
said, many New Yorkers no doubt agree when he says that statements
of contrition from one who has seriously sinned should carry only
so much weight.
</P>
<P>
   It is a lesson that the supplicant president, too, might wish to
absorb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0503 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5171 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PASTORS-2NDLD     09-14 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PASTORS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CHOOSES TEAM OF SPIRITUAL ADVISERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert new 18th graf  (See also: CLINTON-ECON, CLINTON-REPORT-SCENE, CLINTON-SCHOOLS,
CLINTON-PERJURY, CLINTON-CONGRESS, NY-CLINTON, CLINTON-LEWINSKY,
CLINTON-LEWIS-COLUMN) 
(mk) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton has chosen two or perhaps three ministers to
serve as a team of personal spiritual advisers that will meet and
pray with him weekly and help him resist what one of the ministers
calls ``the temptations that have conquered'' the president in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton phoned the ministers and asked them for their help on
Labor Day evening, as he and the nation were preparing for the
report that Kenneth Starr delivered to Congress two days later
concerning the president's relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The ministers, the White House has confirmed, include two
formidable evangelical preachers: the Rev. Tony Campolo, an
outspoken liberal Baptist from Pennsylvania known for his ministry
to urban youth and for controversial books advocating Christian
acceptance of homosexuality, and the Rev. Gordon MacDonald, senior
pastor of a nondenominational Christian church, Grace Chapel, in
Lexington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Since admitting a month ago that he had had an inappropriate
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, Clinton has been struggling to
persuade the American people that he seriously regrets it and is
taking steps to repent and reform. Both Campolo and MacDonald were
defensive about the possible appearance that Clinton had selected
them as part of political damage control.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are those who will say that Gordon and I are being used
and manipulated,'' Campolo said in a statement. ``Should this be
true, it would not be the first time that Christians have been
taken in. But we would rather be men of faith who believe that God
is working in the life of the president than to join that army of
cynics, many of whom are religious leaders, who cannot accept a
plea for forgiveness at face value.''
</P>
<P>
   By his own account, MacDonald has faced his own sin and sought
redemption. Twelve years ago, while president of a major mission
agency, he admitted to an extramarital affair, resigned his
position and left the ministry. He returned to the ministry after
two years and later wrote a book, ``Rebuilding Your Broken World,''
about his experience.
</P>
<P>
   That book, which the president told MacDonald he had read twice,
is one reason Clinton selected him for spiritual guidance,
MacDonald said in a sermon to his congregation on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Such informal groups of spiritual advisers, sometimes called
``accountability circles,'' are not uncommon among Christian
evangelicals, particularly among leaders of large churches and
organizations. Men _ and it is more often men _ meet regularly with
a small group of peers to pray and provide support for those facing
personal crises. A circle of three men, named by the elders of
Grace Chapel, met with MacDonald weekly after he confessed his
adulterous relationship, and eventually helped restore him to the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bring an understanding of what it is like to face the public
scrutiny when one has sinned,'' MacDonald said in his sermon. ``I
have gone through, and continue to go through, the breaking
process. I have known both the remarkable grace of forgiving,
restorative people and the lash of those who choose other options.
I am in a position to talk the language of repentance and what it
takes to find a deeper and more purposeful walk with God in the
midst of a personal tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House did not announce, but has confirmed, the
president's arrangement with the ministers. MacDonald mentioned it
in his most recent Sunday sermon, and Campolo, after consulting
with the White House staff, made available a statement through
Eastern College in St. Davids, Pa., where he is a professor of
sociology. Both have said they will not grant interviews. A third
minister, alluded to in McDonald's sermon, has not publicly
identified himself.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the president seeks pastoral guidance, he is bringing in
new legal and political advisers in anticipation of possible
impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The White House plans to announce this week the hiring of
several lawyers and advisers to shore up relations with restive
Democrats on Capitol Hill and to devise a new legal strategy as the
investigation of the president moves from the courthouse to the
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Among those expected to be part of the White House defense team
are Gregory Craig, a senior State Department official with
extensive contacts in Congress, and Peter Kadzik, the private
lawyer for John Podesta, White House deputy chief of staff. Several
current and former members of Congress are also being enlisted to
assist in the White House damage-control effort, which will be
directed by Podesta and Lawrence Stein, the White House director of
legislative affairs.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Monday whether the new advisers would be on the
White House payroll or serve more informally as outside
consultants.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, Clinton's lead personal lawyer, has in essence
been demoted and will play a much less central role in formulating
the future response to the impeachment report of Starr, the White
House independent counsel. White House aides expressed deep
disappointment Monday in Kendall's defense of the president in a
press briefing on Friday and in a television appearance on Sunday.
They said that the time for legalistic hairsplitting was past and
that the president's case would now be made by advisers with more
sensitive political antennae.
</P>
<P>
   Also mentioned as possible additions to the White House
damage-control squad are two former aides with experience on
Capitol Hill, Steve Ricchetti and Susan Anne Brophy.
</P>
<P>
   Campolo and MacDonald, the president's new spiritual advisers,
say they are concerned only with his spiritual _ and not political
_ redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least one of us will meet with the president weekly,''
Campolo said in his statement. ``We will pray with him, study
Scripture together, and do our best to help him as he searches his
heart and soul. We want him to understand what went wrong with him
personally that led to the tragic sins that have so marred his life
and the office of the presidency. We want to provide all the help
that we can to spiritually strengthen him against yielding to the
temptations that have conquered him in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
