<HEADER>
A5172 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PASTORS-2NDLD     09-14 0234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PASTORS-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: the past.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Be assured,'' Campolo said, ``that we will not offer what the
German martyr Dietrich Bonhoeffer called `cheap grace''; cheap
grace takes sin lightly and does not call for repentance and
change. But neither do we come in a spirit of loveless
condemnation.''
</P>
<P>
   Campolo, a minister with the American Baptist Churches USA,
first met the president in 1993 at a meeting on inner-city poverty.
Several years ago he publicly criticized Rev. Jerry Falwell for
marketing a videotape accusing Clinton of murder and drug-dealing.
</P>
<P>
   MacDonald also became acquainted with the president in 1993,
through friends, and says he has spoken with him about the ways in
which he has estranged many evangelicals.
</P>
<P>
   David Neff, executive editor of Christianity Today, a national
evangelical monthly, said, ``I think both of those men can
challenge the president at points where he might otherwise be a
little easy on himself.''
</P>
<P>
   If spiritual counseling is not sufficient to help the president,
said James Dunn, executive director of the Baptist Joint Committee
for Public Affairs, neither of these men will hesitate to recommend
some type of additional psychological counseling or treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they thought he needed the kind of help that was more than
they could give,'' Dunn said, ``they would be the first to suggest
it.''
</P>
