<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECONOMY-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZILIAN STOCKS REBOUND, EASING PANIC SOMEWHAT
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ The Brazilian stock market on Monday
appeared to regain equilibrium after dizzying losses last week,
shored up by higher interest rates, government stock purchases and
suggestions that the International Monetary Fund would step in to
prevent disaster.
</P>
<P>
   But without a government program to reduce the swollen budget
deficit, the Brazilian economy appears caught in a race against
time, pitting investors' nervousness toward emerging markets
against the approach of national elections on Oct. 4.
</P>
<P>
   In Sao Paulo, the benchmark Bovespa index closed up 7.79 percent
Monday, after a rise of 13.39 percent on Friday. Given a loss of
15.82 percent Thursday and persistent, lesser losses earlier,
Friday's and Monday's bounces were encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   But the flow of dollars out of the country continued unabated,
with some $1.6 billion in cash reserves leaving on Friday. By
Monday, that had slowed, with market informants saying that $410
million had left foreign exchange coffers by 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly it's a reprieve, but a clear indication of turning
the corner would embody structural fiscal reforms as well as
stabilization in the international arena,'' said Lawrence Goodman,
chief economist at Santander Investment. Those, he said, were
unlikely before President Fernando Henrique Cardoso runs for
re-election next month. ``Don't hold your breath,'' Goodman
remarked.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, the central bank increased the ceiling on
interest rates to 49.75 percent from 29.75 percent, the second rise
in less than 10 days. The next day, IMF officials said that as much
as $15 billion could be made available for Brazil in an emergency.
While Brazilian officials had not formally requested such aid, the
offer was seen as insurance against a currency devaluation or
default, and recognition that Brazil's economy, with $27 billion in
loans from U.S. banks, was too important for Washington to do
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are reducing the probabilities of a default and a major
devaluation,'' said Edmar Bacha, president of BBA Securities.
``Foreign investors were taken by panic in Russia, and they don't
want to be taken by surprise again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that the economy has turned the corner, but there's a
reversal as people reassess the probability of failure versus the
probability of success,'' Bacha added.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, investment analysts said, the government-run
National Bank for Economic and Social Development buoyed stocks on
Friday by buying up a larger-than-average volume of shares.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the bank declined to provide figures, but said
the purchases were not intended to raise stock prices. ``We're
always buying and selling,'' she said. ``What happened was simply
that the price dropped so low that it was a good time to buy. When
the price goes up, we'll sell.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, the steps appeared to calm panic. On the
black market, dollars were selling for 1.35 reais Monday, down from
1.45 on Thursday. In currency market trading late Monday, the
dollar sold just under 1.18 reais.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some voices have risen here suggesting that Cardoso should match
the promises of help with word of specific fiscal changes that his
government will seek from Congress after the elections. Cardoso,
whose main opponent in the race, Luis Inacio Lula da Silva of the
leftist Workers Party, has tried to play down the extent of changes
that will be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Steinbruch, president of the Vicunha textile group, the
second largest in the country, said the president feared that
disclosing post-election austerity measures now would ``become
ammunition for the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, industry has supported the measures that Cardoso has
ventured to take, despite the difficulty that high interest rates
represent. Official unemployment is expected to reach 10 percent
next year, double last year's level, and expectations of growth
have slowed to 1 to 2 percent for this year and next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Preserving the victories gained through stability and the
transformations that flow from it have to be the priority of the
government and of society as a whole,'' Arthur Joao Donato, acting
president of the National Confederation of Industry.
</P>
<P>
   But Donato added that administrative, social security and tax
reform would have to come soon. If the higher interest rates
prevail through December, they will drive up public debt by $20
billion. Even before the increases, the deficit was expected to
reach 8 percent of the gross national product by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   The president does appear to have room for a more forceful
stance. According to polls, the economic turbulence has only
bolstered Cardoso's standing. Voters largely consider him the
candidate best equipped to confront economic uncertainty, and say
they would accept government cutbacks to support the currency.
</P>
<P>
   The Real Plan, named for the new currency it introduced, has
resulted in nominal inflation, compared with 2,400 percent at its
peak.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent survey last week, 47 percent of Brazilians
said they would vote for Cardoso, up from 44 percent two weeks ago.
da Silva's standing in the same period dropped to 23 percent from
25 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
