<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5180 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN15-COX     09-14 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MAIN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves clinch in comeback
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- A team restless over a second season still two weeks
away paused for a few moments Monday night to salute itself. The
Braves clinched the National League East and an unprecedented
seventh straight postseason berth.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Tucker and Chipper Jones each hit solo homers as the
Braves came from behind twice to beat Philadelphia 4-2, giving the
Braves four wins in five games but, with some relief, a title they
had been favored to win since around last Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine worked a 2-2 game through the sixth but was the
winning pitcher over Curt Schilling to become the league's first
19-game winner.
</P>
<P>
   If the Braves downplayed the moment, so did the crowd. Just
33,367 paid to witness this history at Turner Field, some 17,000
less than capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta took its first lead on Jones' homer in the sixth,
putting the Braves up 3-2. The home run was Jones' 33 of the year,
the most by a Braves third baseman since Darrell Evans hit 41 in
1973.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker, who had hit just one home run the entire second half,
drove a 1-1 pitch over the wall in right for his 13th homer of the
season to tie it 2-2 in the fifth. That left Tucker 3-for-9
lifetime versus Schilling, all three hits homers. The Phillies had
taken a 2-1 lead in the top of the inning when Wendall McGee's
two-out single drove in Scott Rolen.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta tied it 1-1 in the fourth and only Schilling kept it
from getting worse. Jones opened the inning with his 27th double
and after Andres Galarraga went down swinging for the second
straight at-bat, Ryan Klesko delivered an opposite field double to
left, scoring Jones. The double was Klesko second in three games,
giving him five RBIs in a span of 10 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   But Schilling left Klesko standing on second, ending the inning
by striking out Javy Lopez and getting a groundout from Andruw
Jones. Still, the single run was a moral victory. The Braves scored
as many earned runs off Schilling in the first four innings than
they had in two April starts (18 innings) early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies had Glavine figured early, racking up four hits,
including two doubles, in the first two innings, which matched
total he had yielded in his last start in Montreal. The Braves were
fortunate to trail just 1-0, Glavine stranding five men in the
first four innings, three of them in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies took the lead in the first, after Desi Relaford
singled and stole second without a throw, Lopez losing his grip on
the ball. Two batters later, Rico Brogna waited out a full count
before ripping a line drive over Andruw Jones' head to the wall in
center for a RBI double.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980914.0509 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5181 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURDOCH-ANNA-NYT &LR;      09-14 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDOCH-ANNA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANNA MURDOCH RETIRES FROM NEWS CORP. BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anna Murdoch, estranged wife of Rupert Murdoch, chairman of News
Corp., has retired from the board of the company, where she had
served as a director since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The news came in the company's annual report, in which Murdoch
reviewed the events of the year and thanked his wife for her
contribution as a board member. The report was released Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The couple are in the midst of a divorce, and although it was
originally said to be amicable, one associate of Murdoch said
Monday that it appeared to be less amicable than had been reported.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview several years ago, Murdoch had said that in the
case of his death, his wife could easily serve as chairman until
his children were old enough to take over.
</P>
<P>
   In her own right, Mrs. Murdoch is a novelist, who has published
``Family Business'' and ``In Her Own Image.'' She is 54 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch, 67, has three children: Lachlan, 27, Elizabeth, 30, and
James, 25. Murdoch is grooming all of them to run the company.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch owns 31 percent of News Corp.'s voting stock and has
made no secret about his hopes to have his children take over.
</P>
<P>
   According to one person close to Murdoch, he has said that the
stock is in a trust for the children, and not part of his own
assets. That has helped mitigate Wall Street's reaction to the
divorce, where it appears to have had relatively little impact so
far. News Corp. stock closed at $25.4375 a share, down from its
52-week high of $33.50 on July 21, but far above its 52-week low of
$17 a share in October.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman said the company could have a further announcement
this week about the divorce settlement, but declined to be
specific.
</P>
<P>
   However, Murdoch appears to be under some pressure to meet his
estranged wife's requirements in the settlement. He has put their
home on Angelo Drive in Los Angeles up for sale, with a price of
$19.5 million. He paid roughly $6 million for the house in 1991. At
that time, he sold his Fifth Avenue apartment in New York and
leased a smaller residence on Central Park South.
</P>
<P>
   Though he sold his home in Aspen, Colo., several years ago, he
still owns a ranch in Carmel, Calif., and a sailboat. However,
Murdoch has never been known as a man who poured millions into art
collections or other costly holdings. A workaholic, he travels to
his company's far-flung businesses frequently.
</P>
</TEXT>
