<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-14 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5185 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINIORITY-ENROLLMENT-     09-14 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINIORITY-ENROLLMENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hispanic, black freshmen gain ground at UT
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN -- The University of Texas, trying to build a diverse
student body without affirmative action, enrolled slightly more
black and Hispanic freshmen this fall, indicating that a law
requiring state colleges to admit freshmen in the top 10 percent of
their high school class could be helping.
</P>
<P>
   However, official head counts done on the 12th day of classes
were not available Monday from other state universities, and the UT
data are open to interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear at UT is that a higher percentage of black and
Hispanic freshmen came from the ranks of the top 10 percent than
those enrolled in the past two years. The 1997 Legislature passed
the law to combat declines in black and Hispanic enrollments at the
state's premier universities, the result of a 1996 federal court
ruling that effectively ended affirmative action in admissions,
scholarships and other student programs.
</P>
<P>
   UT's medical and dental schools, meanwhile, have made
significant gains in Hispanic and African American enrollments
since the so-called Hopwood ruling and admitted a first-year class
similar to what they had in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``By broadening the scope of who we invited in for interviews
and by looking at a number of different factors . . . we were able
to reach a level of diversity close to the pre-Hopwood years,''
said Budge Mabry, director of the medical and dental applications
center for the UT System.
</P>
<P>
   Among undergraduate freshmen, UT-Austin enrolled 198 blacks, or
2.9 percent, of the entering class of 6,744 students, and 891
Hispanics, or 13.2 percent of the class.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when the Hopwood ruling fully took effect, UT
enrolled 190 blacks, or 2.7 percent of 7,085 freshmen, and 892
Hispanics, or 12.6 percent. That compared with 266 blacks, or 4.1
percent, of 6,430 freshmen in 1996, and 932 Hispanics, or 14.5
percent, of the total.
</P>
<P>
   UT Admissions Director Bruce Walker attributed this year's
modest increases to the new top-10-percent law, along with stepped
up recruitment efforts and minority-targeted scholarships offered
for the first time by the private UT Ex-Students' Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can now walk into any high school in Texas and know,
without a doubt, there is a group of students who are qualified to
be in UT-Austin,'' Walker said. ``We're headed in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The top-10-percent law was seen as a way to boost African
American and Hispanic enrollments _ groups historically
underrepresented in Texas higher education _ because there are many
public high schools in Texas dominated by students in those two
groups. Only grades go into figuring a student's class rank;
college entrance exam scores are not considered.
</P>
<P>
   About 42 percent of the freshmen enrolled at UT-Austin were in
the top 10 percent of their high school class. Of the 198 black
freshmen, 73, or 36. 9 percent, were top-10-percent students. Among
891 Hispanic freshmen, 436, or 48.9 percent, were in that category.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 28.4 percent of the blacks were in the top 10 and
41.9 percent of the Hispanics were. That compares with 35 percent
of black freshmen in 1996 and 43.8 percent of Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   At UT's four medical schools, 40 blacks were in this fall's
entering class of 801, compared with 24 out of 800 last year and 41
out of 782 in 1996. Among Hispanics, 133 enrolled this fall,
compared with 100 last year and 134 in 1996. At the two dental
schools, there were two African Americans among 148 entering
students, compared with two among 144 last year and one out of 143
in 1996. Among Hispanics, there were 19 this fall, seven in 1997
and 12 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   There was virtually no difference in grades and medical school
test scores over the three years, according to UT data.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment figures also have been finalized at the law school.
In a class of 465, 29 are Mexican American, 13 are other Hispanics,
eight are black, 29 are Asian Americans, five are American Indian,
313 are Anglo and 68 did not identify their race. In 1997, UT
enrolled four blacks and 26 Mexican Americans, compared with 26
blacks and 42 Mexican Americans in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   UT System Regent Tony Sanchez of Laredo, the only minority on
the nine-member UT System Board of Regents, said that while he was
aware of efforts taken to boost minority enrollments, he was far
from satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely disappointed in the law school,'' he said.
``It's an elitist school, and a lot of the kids who apply are not
being given the same kind of overall scrutiny as the kids that
apply to medical schools. I don't know what it's going to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Law school officials interviewed several hundred applicants for
the first time this year and broadened criteria for judging
students to go beyond grades and test scores. The Ex-Students'
Association also provided minority-targeted scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
