<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUARK-ADOBE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUARK QUITS ITS QUEST FOR ADOBE SYSTEMS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The graphic software publisher Quark Inc. on
Monday dropped its quirky bid to acquire rival Adobe Systems Inc.,
saying Adobe had spurned its advances and that it did not want to
pursue a hostile deal. Quark had never stated a price or specified
how it intended to finance its unsolicited offer.
</P>
<P>
   Quark announced its offer last month, after an initial exchange
of letters in which it was rebuffed by Adobe's senior management.
Although Adobe's weak earnings in recent quarters have depressed
its shares and left it vulnerable to such unwanted overtures, few
analysts took the proposal seriously, because Quark is a far
smaller, privately held company, with no shares to use as currency.
</P>
<P>
   And though hostile offers such as Mentor Graphics' bid to
acquire Quickturn have lately proliferated, they rarely succeed in
the technology industry. Products and technologies rapidly become
obsolete, and the most valuable assets in any high-technology
company, the engineers, can walk out the door at any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing basically died of its own lack of credibility,''
said Peter Rogers, an analyst with Volpe Brown Whelan in San
Francisco. ``I think Quark perceived that with the recent earnings
disappointment and the departure of three senior executives, Adobe
was in a weakened and confused state and that this would provide an
opportunity to coerce management and shareholders to consider a
combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Adobe shares closed Monday at $28.50, up 50 cents in Nasdaq
trading. Quark made its announcement after the close of the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since last week, we have again tried to open a dialogue with
Adobe, but to no avail _ they have not returned our phone calls,''
Fred Ebrahimi, Quark's president and chief executive, said in a
statement. ``We wanted to engage in friendly discussions regarding
the specifics of our proposal, but Adobe is not even willing to do
that. Adobe has made it clear that it is not interested in pursuing
any type of friendly transaction, even if it would benefit the
Adobe stockholders.''
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, John E. Warnock, Adobe's co-chairman and
chief executive, and Charles M. Geschke, co-chairman and president,
said: ``Adobe is pleased that Quark decided not to further pursue
an acquisition of Adobe. We are very grateful for the tremendous
support we have received from our business partners, customers and
our employees. We continue to focus on the exciting opportunities
available to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Quark, which is based in Denver, makes Xpress, an industry rival
of Adobe's Pagemaker, a page layout program. Adobe, which is based
in San Jose, Calif., successfully developed the Postscript
language, which began a standard for the publishing industry and
was crucial to the early success of Apple's Macintosh computer.
Adobe's Photoshop and Illustrator are mainstays of professional
graphics producers.
</P>
<P>
   Although Adobe has developed a number of products for creating
Web pages, it has not achieved the same industry standard position
there that it enjoys in desktop publishing. Adobe reported a 33
percent drop in earnings on a 3 percent drop in revenue for the
third quarter, and a work force reduction of about 13 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
