<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL PORTENT  
 MILITARY SUPPORT  
 ALL IN THE FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lot has happened since DONNA RICE was photographed on Sen.
GARY HART's lap on the yacht Monkey Business.
</P>
<P>
   He dropped out of the 1988 presidential race. She modeled No
Excuses jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Now married and using the name DONNA RICE HUGHES, she is the
vice president for marketing and public relations of an
organization called Enough Is Enough. It is a nonprofit group whose
goal is making the Internet safe for children, a cause she took up
after her 14-year-old sister disappeared in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In her new book, ``Kids Online: Protecting Your Children in
Cyberspace,'' Mrs. Hughes writes that her sister vanished after
meeting with a man she had met in an Internet chat room; he, too,
disappeared. Mrs. Hughes writes that her sister was found and the
man was apprehended after the case was described on the Maury
Povich Show.
</P>
<P>
   So where was Mrs. Hughes on Friday, when the report from KENNETH
STARR was released? At her computer, reading the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to say, `Hey, if I didn't have to read it for my job, I
wouldn't read it,''' she said. ``The organization I work for has
been working for four years to make the Internet safe for children,
protecting them from pornography and sexual predators. This doesn't
fall in that category, but it does raise awareness about
information that would be inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   She had expected as much, she said. ``I believed, after I heard
the request by Ken Starr asking Congress to keep some of the more
graphic details of the report confidential, that it certainly had
material that would not be appropriate, even for the general
public,'' she said. ``I agreed with him, once I read it.''
</P>
<P>
   Does she see parallels between 1987 and the current scandal?
``The situation with me was entirely different from this
situation,'' she said without elaborating. A moment later she
steered the conversation back to her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sometimes stop myself,'' she said. ``I'm back in the
limelight, and I never wanted to have anything to do with politics
or the media again.''
</P>
<P>
   Military Support
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the 1970s ZACHARY FISHER championed the USS
Intrepid, the aircraft carrier that became a floating museum from a
war in which he was not allowed to serve. He failed his Marine
Corps physical in 1942. The reason was a knee that had been hurt in
a construction-site accident when he was a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher went back to constructing buildings, the cornerstone of
the Fisher brothers' fortune. Over the years Fisher, 86, has
lavished money on military and veterans projects, giving more than
$25 million to the Intrepid museum. He also set up a foundation
that sent $10,000 checks to the relatives of the 241 victims of the
bombing of a Marine barracks in Beirut, Lebanon, in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday PRESIDENT CLINTON presented Fisher with the Medal of
Freedom, the United States' highest award for a civilian. Secretary
of Defense WILLIAM COHEN, Mayor RUDOLPH GIULIANI and Police
Commissioner HOWARD SAFIR were also on hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president mentioned my caring about the military so much,
more than any civilian he knew,'' Fisher said. ``I told him I
appreciate the acknowledgment of me as a patriot.''
</P>
<P>
   There was not a word about the Starr report. ``This was a
graceful and a loving time,'' Fisher said. ``No mention of anything
like that.'' Of the president, he said, ``I love the guy.'' Then,
referring to HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON, who also attended the
ceremony, Fisher said: ``I like her very much. She's very caring.''
</P>
<P>
   All in the Family
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kiss, kiss, darling. SIRIO MACCIONI, the owner of the
restaurant Le Cirque 2000, gave a 25th-anniversary party Monday
night and invited a few friends. Well, more than a few. The guest
list stretched to 1,000 names or so, and the two-story restaurant
on Madison Avenue was filled with air kisses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family wanted to thank everyone,'' Maccioni said,
``because in New York, 25 years doesn't seem like the easiest
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   To celebrate his quarter-century, Maccioni, 64, hired clowns and
jugglers from the Ringling Bros. and Barnum &AMP; Bailey Circus. And he
said that his three sons, who already run Osteria del Circo on West
55th Street, would be doing some juggling of their own.
</P>
<P>
   His oldest son, MARIO MACCIONI, 33, has moved to Las Vegas to
oversee the new Le Cirque at the Bellagio Hotel, which is scheduled
to open next month. The others, MARCO MACCIONI, 30, and MAURO
MACCIONI, 26, will be involved in restaurants planned for Paris and
London.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted my three sons to do something respectable with their
lives,'' Sirio Maccioni said with a straight face, ``but they have
all come into the restaurant business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
