<SLUG> BC-FBC-GRAMBLING-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RETIRED ROBINSON REMAINS THE CENTER OF AFFECTION
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doug Williams sat quietly and listened as those speaking before
him praised his predecessor, Eddie Robinson, at Yankee Stadium on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He listened as Dennis Walcott, the chief executive officer of
the New York Urban League, told how Robinson taught, by example. He
listened as Joe Taylor, Hampton University's highly successful
coach, said he and nearly everyone else involved in football at
historically black colleges stand ``on the shoulders of the
legendary Eddie Robinson.'' And he listened as both men, speaking
at a news conference for the 28th annual New York Urban League
Annual Football Classic, sprinkled their speeches with Robinson
quotes and anecdotes.
</P>
<P>
   When they were through, and Williams was finally given the
microphone, he started by saying perhaps the only thing that
someone replacing the winningest coach in college football history
can say: ``First of all, I apologize for not being Coach
Robinson.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in his first season as head coach at Grambling State
University, Williams finds himself in the uncomfortable position of
replacing a living legend, a man who is to black college football
what Babe Ruth was to baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever footsteps Coach Robinson had, we need to bronze them,
pick them up and put them on a pedestal because I don't think Doug
Williams or anybody else would enjoy stepping in those footsteps,''
said Williams, whose Tigers will face Hampton in this year's game
on Sept. 26 at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson won 408 games in his 56 years at Grambling and sent
more than 200 players to the National Football League. One of them
was Williams, who played quarterback at Grambling from 1974-77 and
then went on to lead the Washington Redskins to victory in Super
Bowl XXII.
</P>
<P>
   But the transition from Robinson to Williams was not a
particularly smooth one. In a power struggle that was played out in
the national news media, Robinson, 79, resigned begrudgingly after
three straight losing seasons. And when talk of his being replaced
by Williams, who coached at Division II Morehouse College last
year, began before Robinson left, a wedge grew between the two
Grambling legends.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is still mutual respect between Williams and
Robinson, now working at Grambling as the special assistant to the
president for university relations, the two men are basically
nothing more than acquaintances these days and, Williams said,
haven't had a meaningful conversation in about two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't have a great rapport,'' Williams said. ``We
haven't gone to each other and said, `Let's mend this situation.'
But I still have the utmost respect for Eddie Robinson, for what
he's done for black college football and for the opportunity he
gave me to play at Grambling.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' first step toward returning Grambling to prominence
was to do away with Robinson's historic wing-T offense and insert a
multiple pro set. So far, the Tigers are 1-1. While Williams
understands the difficulty of the task before him, he wouldn't want
to be in any other situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided that I wanted to be a coach 25 years ago in 1973,''
said Williams, the only black quarterback to start in the Super
Bowl. ``It just so happened that my plan got interrupted for about
12 to 13 years when I went to play a little football. But I
couldn't wait until it was over with so I could get into
coaching.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
