<SLUG> BC-RIOJA-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PILAR RIOJA: PRECISE SPANISH STYLING BY AN ENSEMBLE OF ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Pilar Rioja's programs of Spanish dance are solo
concerts. Yet she often created the illusion that she was not
dancing alone when she performed on Sunday night at Repertorio
Espanol, at the Gramercy Arts Theater. By abruptly opening large
fans in ``Cafe de Chinita,'' she appeared to be making
pronouncements to a host of unseen people.
</P>
<P>
   Her castanets took on lives of their own in two solos to
18th-century music. After striking elegant poses in ``Grave Assai e
Fandango,'' to Boccherini, she moved as if bewitched by the
castanets' varied tones. And the castanets seemed to giggle in
``Sonata,'' to Soler.
</P>
<P>
   Like her castanet playing, Ms. Rioja's footwork was notable for
its precision. She brought exaltation to her ``Alegrias,''
suggested that her feet were summoning up supernatural forces in
``El Vito'' and became a wild spirit in ``Jaleo: Bulerias y Rumba
Flamenca.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Que Pena Negra la Mia (How Black Are My Sorrows!)'' evoked
melancholy and defiance. And by blending traditional steps with
movements of her own in ``Tres Danzas,'' a suite of changing moods,
Ms. Rioja created what could be called a personal form of Spanish
modern dance.
</P>
<P>
   The program honored the 100th anniversary of the birth of the
Spanish writer Federico Garcia Lorca. One of his stories inspired
``Tener la Esperanza Muerta,'' which Ms. Rioja choreographed in
collaboration with Manolo Vargas. In this portrait of a woman who
feels herself doomed to be a spinster, fluid movements for Ms.
Rioja's upper body suggested the heroine's gentleness, while
restless stamping symbolized inner turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Rivela, an actor, recited quotations from Garcia
Lorca's theories of poetic inspiration. Robert Weber Federico, the
presentation's lighting and production designer, spoke on the
history of Spanish dance. All these remarks were fascinating. But
Ms. Rioja should avoid burdening programs with verbiage. Her
dancing speaks for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Her fine musicians included Martin Soderberg, pianist; Enrique
Iglesias and Bernardo De Jaen, singers; and Jose Luis Negrete,
Antonio Munoz and Francisco Roldan, guitarists. Ms. Rioja continues
through Oct. 4 at the Gramercy Arts Theater, 138 East 27th St.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
