<SLUG> BC-NY-COUPLE-DEATHS-300&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY HAD EARLIER REMOVED GIRL WHO FOUND HER PARENTS DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 10-year-old girl who found both her parents dead
in their Manhattan apartment on Saturday had been removed from the
home last year by child welfare workers and then returned after the
city investigated accusations that her parents had not been taking
proper care of her, family members and city officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The girl, Kelsea Michaels, was taken away from her parents in
November after the city's Administration for Children's Services
received an accusation of ``inadequate guardianship'' in the home,
said an agency worker familiar with the girl's case who spoke on
the condition of anonymity. The girl was returned to the home in
February.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday evening, Kelsea discovered her parents, Melanie and
Lloyd Michaels, both 35, dead in their bed at the Beaux-Arts
Apartments, a faded landmark building at 307 East 44th St. in
Turtle Bay. There were no signs of foul play, and the initial
autopsy results were inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors and police officials said that Ms. Michaels apparently
had a drug problem and that Michaels had been awaiting a kidney
transplant. No evidence of narcotics was found near their bodies
and no suicide notes were left, the police said. It could be
several weeks before pathologists learn the results of toxicology
tests that were done as part of the autopsies to try to determine
whether any drugs were in their systems at the time of their
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Without casting blame, some of the couple's relatives questioned
Monday why the girl was returned to what they described as a
troubled home. ``We're just asking a lot of whys right now,'' said
Ava Seavey, Ms. Michaels' sister. ``We're just asking why _ how
could this have happened? This child will never be the same.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   City officials said Monday night that they would not be able to
tell who made the decision to return Kelsea to the home _ and how
the decision was made _ until they were able to study the family
court transcript. Leonora Wiener, a spokeswoman for the
Administration for Children's Services, would only say that the
child was now being cared for by a relative and that she would
probably go on to live with another relative.
</P>
<P>
   A city official who spoke on the condition of anonymity said
that Kelsea was first returned to the family in February on a trial
basis, with heavy supervision from child welfare workers.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the official said, her return home was formally
approved. Under the agreement, the official said, child welfare
workers were to monitor the family for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said that Kelsea often appeared unkempt and hungry,
and that she was sometimes seen wandering the halls as late as 2
a.m., eating junk food.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the police said, she went out to play and when she
went home found that she could not wake up her parents. She went
back out to play, they said, and returned later, but still could
not wake them.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the police said, she went downstairs to ask a doorman
for help. The doorman returned with her to apartment 1403 and found
the parents dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
