<SLUG> BC-NJ-GALLERY-ARSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART GALLERY FIRE IS RULED ARSON, BUT NO POLITICAL AGENDA IS SEEN
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 BY RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ The fire at a Jersey City art gallery before the
opening of a photography exhibition dealing with the effects of the
violence in Northern Ireland was arson, officials said Monday,
adding that they had not found any evidence of a political motive.
</P>
<P>
   Steven J. McGill, the assistant director of fire and emergency
services for Jersey City, said that despite suspicions expressed by
the gallery owner and the photographer, there had been no note or
telephone call claiming responsibility that would suggest a
political reason.
</P>
<P>
   FBI Agent Monica Patton, a spokeswoman for the agency's Newark
office, said that the FBI had met with local investigators after
being called by the owners with their suspicions. But she said that
so far, such suspicions were only speculative, and the FBI would
not enter the investigation at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Stephan Shedrowitz, an owner of the Cooper Gallery, and Michael
Schwartz, the photographer whose work is featured in the
exhibition, ``Faces of War: Children of Belfast,'' have said they
believe the subject matter antagonized some people. But they also
did not report receiving any calls or letters claiming
responsibility or citing politics.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have determined that the Cooper Gallery and its
next-door neighbor, Modern Electric Arts and Graphs, an arts supply
store, were both broken into. The supply store was entered by
forcing the lock on the front door, investigators said. The store
was ransacked and a copying machine was taken, McGill said.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the burglar or burglars forced the lock on the rear
door of the Cooper Gallery, McGill said.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was started in some papers piled in the middle of the
gallery. McGill said that although flammable substances, like
oil-based paints, were within easy reach, none were used. The fire
damaged some photographs and walls, but it was quickly
extinguished.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-14-98 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
