<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: HOME RUNS BY THE BUSHEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Sept. 15:
</P>
<P>
   During the recent series between the Cards and the Cubs, Mark
McGwire suggested to Sammy Sosa how nice it would be if the two of
them could both beat Roger Maris' record, and maybe end the season
tied with the same number of home runs. That seemed unlikely at the
time, with Sosa stuck at 58 home runs and McGwire on a tear. But
beginning last Friday night, and continuing over the weekend, the
hero of San Pedro de Macoris, in the Dominican Republic, pumped
four home runs out of Chicago's Wrigley Field to draw even with
McGwire at 62.
</P>
<P>
   This McGwire-Sosa business is amazing, and fun. In the space of
one week, two players have broken Maris' 37-year-old record of 61
home runs, and the season has almost two more weeks to run. Nobody
knows how this is going to turn out, but given Sosa's history as a
streak hitter, it is entirely possible that he could win the home
run title and McGwire could wind up in the second paragraph of the
best sports story in years.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Sosa so interesting is that nobody thought he could
summon the discipline to challenge the record. Until last year he
was one of the most impatient hitters in the game, a happy-go-lucky
guy who usually swung at the first pitch, wherever it was, until
one day he got smart and decided to wait for pitches he could hit.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is a hard-working player who has brought to baseball a
sense of joy that seems rare among today's professional athletes.
His season has been every bit as important to baseball as
McGwire's, drawing thousands of extra fans to the ball park and
keeping interest alive at a time of year when interest tends to
flag. We thought it was over, but what was once a home run chase is
now a home run race.
</P>
</TEXT>
